	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Winners & Losers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Winners & Losers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The frenetic pace of corporate mergers and acquisitions—the result of companies searching for new ways to grow in a slowing economy—has helped power the market to new highs. By mid-November, announced deals worldwide had already edged past 1995's record volume of $949 billion, according to Securities Data. Share prices for acquiring companies have soared, further fueling the frenzy.<p>
WINNER: Elizabeth Bramwell  <a name="FUND:BRGRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BRGRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bramwell Growth Fund</b></a>
Growth investor Bramwell was rewarded for her patience when J. C. Penney announced its $3.3 billion purchase of <a name="NYSE:ECK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16231"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eckerd</b></a>. The drug retailer has been her $135 million fund's largest holding for a year, and on November 4, her 225,000-share stake got a $1 million boost. "I'm happy when buying things at a discount to their growth rate really works," she says.<p>
WINNER: Henry Kravis  Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
In September, buyout king Kravis cut one of his greatest deals, agreeing to sell <a name="NYSE:DUR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Duracell</b></a> to <a name="NYSE:G"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10655"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gillette</b></a> for $7.3 billion. His firm, which bought the battery maker from Kraft for $350 million in 1988, had already sold part of its stake for more than $1 billion in previous public offerings. If the merger goes through, KKR's 6.8 percent piece of Gillette could be worth $2 billion.<p>
WINNER: Lawrence Lasser  Putnam Investments
Putnam CEO Lasser had to be smiling after <a name="NYSE:BTY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41763"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>British Telecom</b></a> announced its $21 billion acquisition of <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>. Last summer, his mutual-fund firm bought 14 million shares of the number-two U.S. long-distance company, making it the largest institutional investor. Putnam's stake jumped $113 million in value on November 1, when CNBC broke the merger story.<p>
WINNER: Roberto Mendoza  J. P. Morgan  
Vice chairman Mendoza helped his bank win the choice assignment of co-advising <a name="NYSE:NSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11084"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Norfolk Southern</b></a> in its hostile $10 billion bid for <a name="NYSE:CRR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10395"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Conrail</b></a>. Although his client may lose the deal to rival <a name="NYSE:CSX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10274"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CSX</b></a>, J. P. Morgan is assured of divvying up $22.8 million in fees with <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> and cementing its place among the elite of investment banks.
R. Michael Shanahan  Capital Research and Management   <p>
LOSER: R. Michael Shanahan  Capital Research and Management
This adviser to the American Funds Group, of which Shanahan is chairman, bought 1.7 million shares of <a name="NYSE:MRV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10665"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Marvel</b></a> last spring when the troubled comic-book company was trading around $10 a share, says research group CDA/Spectrum. In November, Marvel fell to $2.75 after majority owner Ron Perelman offered to pay off bondholders with 410 million new shares.<p>
LOSER: Phillip Frost  Ivax
Investors were aghast when chairman Frost accepted a merger offer from drug wholesaler <a name="NYSE:BBC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11761"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bergen Brunswig</b></a> in November for $2 a share below <a name="AMEX:IVX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12043"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ivax</b></a>Ivax's then market price of $15.875. Both stocks dropped, with Ivax falling as low as $11. Frost, who couldn't comment on a deal in SEC registration, has lost more than $70 million on his 15 million shares.<p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual fund, fund manager

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
