<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>
The number of banks offering Internet services will swell in 1997. A recent study conducted by Datapro Information Services Group found that, while only 7 percent of all banks currently offer Internet services, 36 percent have plans to offer them by the end of 1997. <p>
Is a financial adviser under obligation to disclose all investment opportunities to all clients? Not necessarily, according to a U.S. district court judge in Philadelphia, who dismissed a lawsuit against Glenmede Trust. A family had sued Glenmede, asserting that a trust and other family interests were worth $80 million less than they otherwise would have been had Glenmede included them in an investment offer made to other clients.<p>
The Securities and Exchange Commission is examining "soft dollar" practices between investment advisers and the brokerage houses with which they do business. Soft-dollar arrangements are a portion of the commission that investment advisers may receive from brokers to pay for research, goods, and services. Investors are only rarely aware of these arrangements. Though the arrangements are entirely legal, SEC chairman Arthur Levitt has spoken out against soft-dollar transactions that do not benefit shareholders and other customers. <p>
The regulatory arm of the National Association of Securities Dealers, NASD Regulation, has proposed limiting punitive damages in arbitration claims against brokers and their firms to $750,000 or twice compensatory damages, whichever is less, to pay for lost interest income or principal. The proposal must be reviewed by both the NASD board of governors and the Securities and Exchange Commission. A final decision is not expected until summer. <p>
British investment-management group Invesco and mutual-fund family AIM Management Group intend to merge in February 1997. While each company will continue to operate under its current name, the listed holding company will be called AMVESCO and will have approximately $150 billion in assets.<p>
Airlines, hoping to enhance the appeal of frequent-flier miles, have begun allowing customers to use accumulated miles as currency for bidding at special auctions. Offerings at these auctions include "fantasy" trips, such as a ride on a space-shuttle simulator, and admission to holiday festivities with the First Family. One United Airlines customer, for instance, used his frequent-flier miles to place the top bid for a walk-on role on the sitcom Seinfeld. <p>
Fifteen discount-brokerage firms have joined together to form a new trade group: the Discount Brokerage Association. The new trade group will focus on efforts to "promote public confidence in discount brokers and to educate consumers on how to use the services of discount firms." The use of discount brokers has increased from 28 percent ten years ago to 36 percent today, according to a survey by the American Association of Individual Investors.<p>
The Securities Industry Association reported that 76 percent of the 1,500 investors it polled felt that the industry does not do enough to educate the public about investing. The survey found that 19 percent of the respondents who have brokerage accounts have an "unfavorable" opinion of the industry because of such concerns as dishonesty, greed, and excessive compensation.<p>
Comptroller of the Currency Eugene Ludwig announced the adoption of a rule that would allow banks to offer financial products, such as securities and insurance, through subsidiaries rather than holding companies. The new rule, which will take effect on January 1, has already met with opposition from other financial-services companies and lawmakers.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

