<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Getting Defensive</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Getting Defensive</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The rising stock market is sowing the seeds of its own undoing<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
Even as the Dow Jones Industrial average bursts through the 6400 mark, the character of this market is shifting. "The stock market is behaving like it should if it is heading into a tougher year," observes Hugh Johnson, the chief investment officer at First Albany. "It is becoming more defensive."<p>
Tougher year? Defensive? Those words hardly seem to fit a market that recently has been taking the steps three at a time. Yet a closer look at how individual stock prices are being reordered with this rally suggests that the market may be sowing the seeds of its own undoing even as it gains 100 points a week.<p>
By way of example, let's examine the Dow's 51-point, or 0.8 percent, rise on November 19. The gain in the Dow was mirrored that day by the Nasdaq composite index, which increased a little more than eight points -- or 0.6 percent.<p>
At the same time, however, more stocks lost ground (2,075) on the Nasdaq than gained in price (1,894). And while 161 Nasdaq stocks hit new 12-month highs, 129 issues recorded lows. <p>
What's going on? In a healthy market, gains in one stock typically spread to similar issues. <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> goes up because investors who see growing demand for devices that store huge amounts of computer data buy shares. This enthusiasm spills over to shares of other data-storage companies, such as <a name="NYSE:EMC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10491"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>EMC</b></a>.<p>
But the current market seems driven, in part, by bad news. A Wall Street favorite, such as <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>, will report disappointing earnings. This, in turn, casts a cloud over not just other home-improvement stocks, such as <a name="NYSE:LOW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10920"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lowe</b></a>'s, but the entire retail sector. <p>
As investors sell retail stocks or other sagging issues, what do they do with their money? Put it into apparently rock-solid stocks like <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a>, which because of its huge backlog of orders seems certain not to disappoint, or <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, which still seems secure in its dominance of a growing industry. Therefore, Boeing, though it already trades at a price-to-earnings ratio of 31, continues to climb. And because it is 1 of the 30 Dow Jones Industrial Average stocks, it takes the Dow up with it. Microsoft takes the Nasdaq index higher, too. The rich get richer, while the rest tread water or slip beneath the surface. The averages investors watch so carefully don't tell the full story. <p>
We are still in the very early stages of this trend. Stock-market analysts (and Worth in the "Market Radar" feature of "Need to Know") use a measure called the advance/decline line -- which charts the change in the ratio of advancing to declining issues over time -- to take the temperature of a market. Right now, the advance/decline line for the stocks on the New York Stock Exchange looks relatively healthy. On an up day, such as November 19, more issues gain (1,442) than lose (1,046), which seems to confirm that the large-company stocks that dominate the NYSE index and the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index still have legs.<p>
The advance/decline line for the small-company-dominated Nasdaq market has looked less healthy. The divergence between the two markets isn't reassuring -- a decline in the Nasdaq ratio often precedes a similar deterioration in the large-company market by six to eight months.<p>
In the shorter term, the market will favor stocks and sectors that fit the growing defensive mood. Utilities, consumer products such as drugs, and financials are likely to be the best performers, says First Albany's Johnson. <p>
Small-company stocks will not find much favor. "Investors know that the economy is slowing, and they're buying big names," says Claudia Mott, director of small-company research at Prudential Securities. When investors become nervous, they look for liquid big-company stocks, which are easy to unload when the going gets tough.<p>
But for long-term investors, this will create opportunities in good small-company stocks selling cheap. Invest 10 percent of a portfolio in small-company stocks picked for the long haul, and put them away, suggests Mott. All the data show that small-company stocks outperform their large-company brethren in the long term, she notes. "But none of those long-term results are based on calling the tops and bottoms of the market."<p>
KEYWORDS: economy, invest, Street Wise

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
