	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Mutual Fund Laboratory</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Money markets soak up the cash...<p>
Disappointing third-quarter corporate earnings dampen enthusiasm for equity funds in October. The bulk of new money flows into money-market funds as investors seek short-term safe havens until the dust settles from the elections in November.<p>
...and managers add to their reserves<p>
The Dow Jones Industrials' push into the uncharted territory beyond 6000 causes cash levels in fund portfolios to edge up in October, according to our index. As stocks get more expensive, some managers wait for a pullback before putting new money to work.<p>
OUR FAVORITE EQUITY FUNDS<p>
This table tracks the progress of 20 stock mutual funds selected by Worth's editors. Each fund listed below has been a consistent top performer, achieving superior returns with relatively low risk. The first five categories in the table are those used in the Worth asset-allocation model. By choosing one fund from each, investors can create an efficient and balanced long-term investment portfolio (see the November 1996 issue). The sixth category -- "Miscellaneous" -- lists three funds in market sectors with especially strong long-range prospects.<p>
