	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Best Buys: Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The bond market has given investors an early Christmas present. The 30-year Treasury bond appreciated by 2.7 percent in the first three weeks of November, as the yield fell below 6.5 percent. With continued tame inflation, that yield could fall to 6 percent by early 1997. But investors shouldn't forget about the risks of bonds with long maturities. Grant's Interest Rate Observer notes that corporations are selling 100-year bonds again. That should have investors concerned because previous instances in which Wall Street sold these ultra-long bonds have marked temporary lows in interest rates. The buys below represent our best picks for (1) the investor who needs cash, (2) the investor who wants near-term yield, and (3) the investor who seeks long-term returns -- without excessive risk. <p>
As Safe and Liquid as Cash 
Our picks with an emphasis on safety and yield<p>
We had to shop hard to get any extra yield in our picks for the investor who needs cash soon. While long-term interest rates have fallen over three-quarters of 1 percent since mid-July, short-term rates have barely budged. Yet it still pays to compare returns: The highest-yielding taxable money funds (typically those that waive all or a portion of their fees) offer rates almost one percentage point higher than the 4.86 percent average. Our choices are the highest-yielding instruments that lock up money for three months, tops. Bank money-market accounts and CDs are federally insured, and in 20 years, only one non-bank money-market fund has lost principal.
<br>
