<br>
To Save for a Goal Two to Three Years Away<br>
<br>
Our picks with an emphasis on safety and yield<br>
<br>
This category remains the place to be for investors who don't want to try to predict the direction of interest rates. Investors in bonds that mature in one to three years have earned a total return of 4.2 percent for 1996 (through mid-November). That's far better than the almost 2 percent loss suffered by holders of long-term bonds. Our list is for investors who want high returns but who need protection from losses, since they anticipate needing their money in two to three years for tuition, a down payment, or the like. It combines safety (no loss of more than 3 percent over any three-month period since 1990), 12-month yield, and three-year total return. <p>
Data as of 11/19/96. 
Sources: IBC Financial Data (<a HREF="http://www.ibcdata.com">www.ibcdata.com</A>) and BanxQuote (<a HREF="http://www.banx.com">www.banx.com</A>).
