<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-10 Stocks to Avoid/Consider</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-10 Stocks to Avoid/Consider</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						10 to Avoid<p>
Cedd Moses of Los Angeles–based Portfolio Advisory Services is an aggressive trader of stocks who uses both fundamental data and technical analysis. His methods have earned a 14.8 percent annualized return at the Calvert Strategic Growth Fund since its May 1994 inception, but they have really shone in his Aggressive Enhancement Strategy hedge-fund portfolios, which have much more freedom to short potential losers than do mutual funds. Those portfolios -- now $40 million -- are up an average of 29 percent annually since March 1990. Moses scours 9,000 issues a week in search of those likely to fall over the next six months. His favorite signals of financial stress include big jumps in inventories or accounts receivable and "lawyer's language" in quarterly reports that is aimed at protecting management from lawsuits if earnings disappoint. Moses sees danger ahead for Lone Star Steakhouse & Saloon, where restaurants older than one year show flat sales. Insider selling at Sun Microsystems confirms his belief that the company is vulnerable to Microsoft's Windows NT and Intel's Pentium Pro chips, which help cheaper PCs perform like Sun's workstations. At McDonald's, same-store sales abroad are falling -- a bad omen, since the company is relying on expansion abroad to make up for flagging sales at home. <p>
<a name="NASD:ASTF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42224"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AccuStaff</b></a> (Nasdaq: ASTF) $9.75<br>
• Acquisitions becoming more expensive, penalizing earnings<br>
• Labor costs likely to rise<br>
<a name="NASD:ATML"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14420"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Atmel</b></a> (Nasdaq: ATML) $15<br>
• Competition in key markets<br>
• Slowing sales growth<br>
• Inferior flash-chip technology <br>
<a name="NYSE:BTH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42000"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Blyth Holdings</b></a> (NYSE: BTH) $27<br>
• Excessive valuation<br>
• Low barriers to entry<br>
• Slowing sales, rising inventory <br>
<a name="NYSE:HOLX"></a><b>Hologic</b> (Nasdaq: HOLX) $16<br>
• Slowing sales of key product<br>
• Competition from new products  <br>
• Well-financed competitors<br>
<a name="NYSE:JLG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13846"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JLG Industries</b></a> (NYSE: JLG) $13<br>
• Slowing revenue growth<br>
• Rising inventories<br>
• Heavy reliance on big customer<br>
<a name="NASD:STAR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10372"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lone Star Steakhouse & Saloon</b></a> (Nasdaq: STAR) $15<br>
• Slowing same-store sales <br>
• Falling margins<br>
• High management turnover<br>
<a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> (NYSE: MCD) $38<br>
• Same-store sales are declining in U.S. and abroad<br>
• Significant insider selling	<br>
<a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a> (NYSE: MU) $18<br>
• Weak prices of DRAM chips <br>
• Significant new competition <br>
• Very low cash position<br>
<a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a> (Nasdaq: SUNW) $41<br>
• Threatened by Windows NT <br>
• Deteriorating balance sheet <br>
• Significant insider selling <br>
<a name="NASD:ZRAN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47415"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Zoran</b></a> (Nasdaq: ZRAN) $8<br>
• Delay of digital videodiscs <br>
• Falling prices of key product <br>
• Rising accounts receivable <br><p>
10 to Consider<p>
Richard Weiss co-manages with Marina Carlson the $1.7 billion Strong Opportunity Fund, which received a top $$$$$ rating in Worth's November fund rankings. The duo looks for misunderstood companies selling at big discounts to their private market value, paying special attention to hidden assets in a company's business mix. Though the two follow a value approach in a growth-driven market and hedge their bets with a heavy cash stake, their fund was up 27 percent in 1995 and 15.7 percent through mid-November 1996. Weiss continues to look for neglected stocks with strong fundamental value that could appreciate in the next 12 to 18 months. Comcast, one stock he likes in the depressed cable industry, plans to roll out digital technology and more channels in 1997, while its stakes in Sprint PCS wireless services and QVC home shopping make the stock "even cheaper than it looks." Newly public Pfeiffer Vacuum is the leader in the industrial-vacuum technology used in semiconductor and electronic-component manufacturing and has a healthy balance sheet. Chip maker Cypress Semiconductor has worked through its inventory glut and is now shifting its product mix toward higher-profit-margin programmable chips; although Weiss doesn't look for a strong first half, he expects 1997 earnings to reach one dollar a share.<p>
<a name="NYSE:CS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10276"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cabletron Systems</b></a> (NYSE: CS) $70<br>
• Expanding product line <br>
• Gaining market share<br>
• Promising new acquisitions<br>
<a name="NASD:CMCSK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13034"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Comcast</b></a> (Nasdaq: CMCSK) $16<br>
• Strong new-product offerings<br>
• Potential spin-off businesses<br>
• Trading at historic low<br>
<a name="NYSE:CY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10428"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cypress Semiconductor</b></a> (NYSE: CY) $12<br>
• Improved product mix<br>
• Chip prices have bottomed <br>
• Low price-to-sales ratio<br>
<a name="NYSE:DGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10436"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Data General</b></a> (NYSE: DGN)  $15<br>
• Leading-edge technology<br>
• Benefits from Windows NT shift <br>
• Making open-systems products <br>
<a name="NYSE:EEX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10522"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Enserch Exploration</b></a> (NYSE: EEX) $11<br>
• Promising deepwater acreage<br>
• Impending spin-off<br>
• Potential takeover target<br>
<a name="NASD:PAGE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13689"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Paging Network Tech</b></a>. (Nasdaq: PAGE) $18<br>
• Low-cost industry leader<br>
• Offering new voice products<br>
• Trading at historic low<br>
<a name="NYSE:PV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51985"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pfeiffer Vacuum</b></a> (NYSE: PV) $17<br>
• Dominant market share<br>
• Excellent management<br>
• Gains expected from spin-off<br>
<a name="NYSE:PYX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16745"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Playtex Products</b></a> (NYSE: PYX) $9<br>
• Excellent brand name<br>
• Improved pricing <br>
• Growing personal-care division <br>
<a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a> (NYSE: SGI) $21<br>
• Strong revenue growth<br>
• Exciting new-product offerings<br>
• Historically low p/e ratio<br>
<a name="NYSE:UPR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44541"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Union Pacific Rsrcs. Grp</b></a>. (NYSE: UPR) <br>$27
• Spin-off temporarily hurt stock<br>
• Low-cost producer of gas<br>
• Gas-price spike boosts earnings <br><p>
The 1996 Investment Outlook issue did not include the "10 Stocks" column. The monthly "Update" will resume with the February issue. <p>

