<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which he considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after September 20, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these managers are meant to illustrate a range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy stock, Worth recommends they conduct their own due diligence.<p>
**Preston Athey--T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value**<p>
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.
<a name="NYSE:CRC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15596"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chromcraft Revington</b></a> (NYSE: CRC) Up to $27
Chromcraft Revington (Delphi, Indiana) manufactures furniture for commercial and residential use under the brand names Chromcraft and Peters-Revington. In an industry characterized by wildly cyclical earnings and subpar return on assets, Chromcraft Revington stands out. The company has one of the highest returns on equity (19 percent) in the furniture-manufacturing group and is debt free. Despite consistent earnings growth for the past six years, the stock sells for only 11 times my 1996 earnings estimates of $2.25 a share. With its shareholder-oriented management team, Chromcraft Revington should be a superior long-term investment. <p>
**James P. Craig -- Janus Fund**<p>
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.
<a name="NYSE:CYT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41906"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cytec Industries</b></a> (NYSE: CYT) Up to $36
Spun out of American Cyanamid at the end of 1993, Cytec (West Paterson, New Jersey) manufactures specialty chemicals and materials used in the paper, mining, water-treatment, and aerospace industries, among others. The company has made serious efforts to trim down its operations -- it has disposed of some business lines, for example. With the proceeds from these sales and strong cash flows, Cytec has bought back a significant amount of its own stock: 1.7 million shares, or 10 percent of all the shares in existence. I'm looking for the company to earn $1.95 a share in 1996 and $2.40 a share in 1997. My 12-month target for the stock is $45.<p>
**Shelby M.C. Davis--New York Venture Fund**<p>
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
<a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eastman Kodak</b></a> (NYSE: EK) Up to $75
Kodak (Rochester, New York) is a world-class franchise that is rapidly turning around from a down decade. Under CEO and chairman George Fisher, management has successfully reduced debt while buying back the company's stock. Fisher wisely sold Kodak's chemical and drug divisions and a large portion of its copier business. With the release of its new photo system, Advantix, and with photography booming in emerging nations, Kodak should see a boost in sales as we approach the holiday season. Kodak's technology and strong balance sheet should generate earnings of more than $5 a share in 1997. Buy at up to $75 with a 24-month target of $90.<p>
**Daniel B. Leonard--Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology**<p>
Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.
<a name="NASD:BXMNF"></a><b>Bre-X Minerals</b> (NASD: BXMNF) Up to $22.50
Investments in Bre-X Minerals (Alberta, Canada) may be as good as gold, literally. This 350-employee company, recently listed on the Nasdaq, explores and develops gold mines in Indonesia. Not long ago, Bre-X discovered a huge gold property that will likely become the largest gold mine in the world. By year's end, the company should be able to confirm that this mine has reserves of 50 million to 60 million ounces of gold. It takes a few years to completely open up a mine, but hopes are that even more gold -- perhaps as much as another 50 million ounces -- will be discovered in the process. With virtually no competition in the region, Bre-X is a pure asset play. <p>
**William J. Nasgovitz--Heartland Value Fund**<p>
Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued.
<a name="NASD:GIBG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13571"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gibson Greetings</b></a> (NASD: GIBG) Up to $14
Gibson Greetings (Cincinnati) is the third-largest producer of greeting cards, behind Hallmark and American Greetings. In addition, Gibson owns the Paper Factory, a chain of party-goods stores operating across the U.S. Last year, the stock hit a low of $8 a share, primarily because of mismanagement. Under new CEO Frank O'Connell, however, I believe things should start to look up. O'Con-nell is a successful turnaround artist who brought SkyBox back from the depths and sold it for a profit. Trading currently at a dollar less than its book value of $14 a share, Gibson is a cheap buy with a potential for tremendous growth. I believe the stock could go as high as $20.<p>
**Eric E. Rayback--Lindner Dividend Fund**<p>
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.
<a name="NYSE:HDL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10700"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Handleman</b></a> (NYSE: HDL) Up to $7.50
Handleman (Troy, Michigan) is a music, software, book, and video distributor that is coming off some very tough times. Kmart, one of its largest customers, came close to filing for bankruptcy. And Handleman was pulled out of the S&P 500. At the end of fiscal year 1996, in April, the company's earnings, including restructuring charges, came to negative 67 cents per share. Come fiscal year 1997, however, the company will be profitable again. It should get a boost when the digital video disc makes it to the market in the next few years, just as the company profited when music went from eight-track to cassette and from cassette to CD. My target price for the stock is $12. <p>
**Ralph Wanger and Chuck McQuaid--Acorn Fund**<p>
Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.
<a name="NYSE:WAK.B"></a><b>Wackenhut Class-B Shares</b> (NYSE: WAK.B) Up to $16
Wackenhut (Palm Beach Gardens, Florida) provides trained security guards to protect businesses and government facilities. But these class-B shares come with an extra pop because Wackenhut owns 55 percent of Wackenhut Corrections, the second-largest private prison-management company in the world. Privately managed prison cells currently hold 4 percent of all U.S. prisoners; private corrections companies operate 10 percent to 20 percent more cheaply than bureaucratic government correctional agencies. With the industry set to grow at least 20 percent a year well into the next decade, this is an opportunity to buy into two strong sectors on the cheap.<p>
**Donald A. Yacktman--Yacktman Fund**<p>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.
<a name="NYSE:FNQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FRANKLIN QUEST</b></a> (NYSE: FNQ) Up to $20
Franklin Quest (Salt Lake City) provides time-management products and seminars for corporations, government agencies, and the general public. The company markets its services primarily by selling its trademark product, the Franklin Day Planner. Franklin suffered a relatively flat 1995 because of heavy write-offs. However, management has made some potentially profitable purchases lately, including competitor Productivity Plus. Since I recommended Franklin Quest in May, the stock has come down from $22 to $17. So much the better. With a clean balance sheet and earnings of more than $2 a share projected for 1997, it’s an attractive buy.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
