	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which he considers the recommended stock attractive. The newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the September 20 publishing deadline.<p>
**Al Frank--The Prudent Speculator**<p>
Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation.
<a name="NASD:FTSP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15311"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Team Sports</b></a> (NASD: FTSP) Up to $10.40
First Team Sports (Anoka, Minnesota) makes and distributes in-line roller skates, street-hockey equipment, ice skates, and skating accessories. The company watched its share price skid more than 20 percent in August after it forecast disappointing earnings in the second quarter. This was because of the general retail slowdown and First Team's excess inventories. Nonetheless, in-line skating remains one of the fastest-growing participation sports, and First Team is expanding worldwide -- it now sells products in over 50 countries. Third-quarter bookings have improved. With a price-to-earnings ratio of seven, we think First Team is an inexpensive buy.<p>
**Jim McCamant--Medical Technology Stock Letter**<p>
Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.
<a name="NASD:AMLN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13328"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amylin Pharmaceuticals</b></a> (NASD: AMLN) Up to $12
Amylin Pharmaceuticals (San Diego) develops treatments for diabetes and other metabolic disorders. The company is in two phase-three trials for its drug Pramlintide, a synthetic analog of a hormone that works in conjunction with insulin to manage blood-glucose levels. An interim look at the trial data in August was positive and triggered a $22 million payment to Amylin by the company's partner, Johnson & Johnson. Pramlintide is a potential blockbuster; it should help cut health-care costs by reducing the many complications associated with diabetes, such as kidney disease, blindness, and leg amputation. My 18-month target for the stock is $20.<p>
**Michael Murphy--California Technology Stock Letter**<p>
Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.
<a name="NASD:AMAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12647"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Applied Materials</b></a> (NASD: AMAT) Up to $30
Applied Materials (Santa Clara, California) is the world's largest manufacturer of chip-fabrication systems used in the semiconductor industry. The stock was up around $60 in August 1995 before it started to fall, primarily because of "push-outs" -- customers placing orders but putting off deliveries while they waited to see if the PC business would pick up. An increase in PC demand, however, may turn these push-outs into "pull-ins" by next March. R&D at Applied Materials is currently 11 percent of sales, and sales should grow around 40 percent a year. This is a good, well-financed core holding. My 12-month target for the stock is $55.<p>
**Louis Navellier--MPT Review**<p>
Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.
<a name="NASD:DSPC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42853"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DSP Communications</b></a> (NASD: DSPC) Up to $60
DSP Communications (Cupertino, California) designs software and integrated-chip sets for mobile cellular phones and voice-recognition applications. DSP stands to benefit greatly from an increased demand for mobile cellular service in emerging countries, which generally don't have the wiring and hardware in place for conventional communications systems. In addition, DSP's products are highly adaptable: They work in a variety of formats and are designed to minimize power consumption. The stock is currently trading in the low $50s. I'm projecting earnings of $1 a share this year and $1.31 a share in 1997. My 12-month target for the stock is $75.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
