<html>
	<head>
		<title>96/11-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>
The Internal Revenue Service experienced the worst year-to-year decline in "customer satisfaction" among all the companies and institutions measured in a recent survey conducted by the National Quality Research Center at the University of Michigan Business School. <p>
**SEC investigates mutual-fund companies**<p>
The Securities and Exchange Commission has begun looking into practices at various mutual-fund companies to determine if there is an attempt to boost the performance of individual funds by giving them a disproportionate number of shares of hot initial-public-stock offerings, according to The Wall Street Journal. Although no specific rule prohibits a company from doing this, the SEC said it could bring an enforcement action if it found that this practice led to unfair or unequal treatment of investors.<p>
**New SEC regulations on Nasdaq trading**<p>
The SEC has also approved new rules governing trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. The measures, which follow the agency’s landmark disciplinary case against Nasdaq dealers, are intended to narrow the spreads on trades by individual investors. Among other things, the rules require dealers to notify investors of the best available price at which they will execute a trade and to display to the market all investor limit orders of at least 100 shares. A limit order is a request that a stock be traded at a specific price. <p>
**Clinton signs bill to repeal excise tax**<p>
President Clinton has signed a bill that temporarily repeals (until the year 2000) the 15 percent excise tax on annual distributions above $155,000 from pensions, 401(k)s, and other retirement programs. Individuals who take advantage of the new law, however, may find themselves giving up future tax-deferred growth. Consult a financial adviser or tax planner first.<p>
**Tudor Investment settles charges of violating trading rules**<p>
Tudor Investment, the company run by commodities trader Paul Tudor Jones, has agreed to pay $800,000 in fines to settle charges that it violated trading rules while implementing a complicated trading strategy that caused the Dow Jones Industrial Average to plunge 16.45 points in a four-minute span on March 16, 1994. The firm didn’t admit or deny wrongdoing in settling the civil case, which was brought by the SEC.<p>
**Congress passes health-insurance proposal**<p>
Congress has passed a proposal that requires insurance companies, HMOs, and employers to offer parity, in both lifetime and annual limits, for the treatment of health and mental illness. The bill also requires insurers to pay for two-day hospital stays for women who have just given birth. (Currently, some insurers cover only a single day.) Supporters of both issues see the move as a positive step toward improving the current health-care system; opponents object to the government’s intervention into areas where it lacks expertise. <p>
**Duracell profits frozen by the SEC**<p>
The SEC has filed civil complaints in federal court against "certain purchasers" of <a name="NYSE:DUR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Duracell International</b></a> options contracts and has frozen profits of $950,000 on the trades -- made just prior to a public announcement that Duracell would be purchased by <a name="NYSE:G"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10655"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gillette</b></a>Gillette. The SEC also asked the court to force the parties making the trades to identify themselves. The trades were carried out by two overseas institutions: a Swiss bank and a Bahamian holding company.<p>
KEYWORDS:regulation, government, legislation

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<b>
					
					</b>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
