<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Seeds of 1997</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Seeds of 1997</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Stop worrying about interest rates and start fretting about growth.<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
This market is obsessively focused on the short term: How much will the Federal Reserve raise interest rates? Will corporate profits tumble? Will <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> beat earnings forecasts? One day the market falls 10 points; the next day -- with no new information -- it climbs 21. Do these gyrations matter?<p>
Well, yes. For the long-term investor who can avoid getting caught up in the daily soap opera, today's market shows how a growth crisis could unfold in 1997.<p>
**For the short-term, the outlook is good for the economy.**<p>
In the short term, the September market rally is likely to roll on into November and perhaps a month or two longer -- basically because the monsters the market fears are toothless. Federal Reserve rate hikes? The market has already discounted a 50-basis-point interest-rate increase; anything less than 50 points by year-end is therefore good news.<p>
Terrible earnings? The market got most of the ugly surprises out of its system in July. Current earnings bellwethers Microsoft and <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> -- which led the market upward in September -- are unlikely to disappoint when they report in October. Also, executives at many companies have aggressively talked Wall Street analysts into lowering expectations for the quarter that ended on September 30. With expectations so low, this market could move up on lackluster earnings reports.<p>
**Long-term indicators play a different tune.**<p>
In a longer time frame, however, the issues that dominate today's market play out very differently. A 50-basis-point interest-rate increase by the end of 1996 would demonstrate the Fed's determination to fight inflation, but its size would raise fears of an economic slowdown. Anything smaller would tell investors the Fed was too worried about growth. Either course will change the focus of investors' concern. For 1997, the question will be: Where is growth going to come from?<p>
Investors asking that question at year-end could have lots of reason to worry. Preliminary reports showed August retail sales growing at a weak 0.2 percent, continuing a pattern that began in June. Weak Christmas retail sales would lend credibility to fears that consumers are tapped out.<p>
Softness in the housing sector -- a key indicator of economic activity -- would add to worries about slow growth. The number of new building permits fell nearly 2 percent in June, July, and August. If the decline continues, it could translate into a drop in construction.<p>
**While conditions may not be bad enough for a recession, there are other worries.**<p>
All these changes wouldn't add up to a shrinking economy -- a recession -- but they would be enough to get Wall Street's attention. Markets rest on fundamentals and emotion. In 1996, the market has climbed to levels far higher than the fundamentals alone justify. A perceived growth crisis could be enough to damage the emotional pillar that supports the market at this level.<p>
For example, against this background, investors would feel differently about corporate earnings. They would focus on the growing leadership vacuum that clearly emerged in September 1996. Instead of gleefully noting Intel's positive announcement about future earnings, for instance, investors would remember that <a name="NYSE:CCE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10360"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> warned analysts that sales growth would probably be one percentage point lower than expected.<p>
**The market will continue its series of wild rides.**<p>
As 1997 dawns, investors won't know with any certainty what's going to happen to growth. But there will be just enough worry to send the market on the kinds of wild rides that have characterized 1996. Instead of bobbing and weaving in response to the latest reading of the tea leaves on Fed policy, however, the market will swing from mania to depression with each economic indicator.<p>
Of course, any highflier that falters will be sent to the woodshed in 1997. But investors in the so-called quality stocks may be shocked to find out that they are just as vulnerable.<p>
Historically, investors worried about the economy seek out never-fail companies -- those with predictable, sustainable earnings. Which drives up the price of those stocks until they trade at valuations usually attached to the riskiest growth stocks. Investors are now doing exactly this to Intel. At nearly $100 a share, the stock is trading at about 25 times 1995 earnings, a mite heady for a stock that's traded at 10 to 15 times earnings the past nine years. On September 19, a prominent analyst raised his earnings estimate from $4.55 a share to $5. Guess what happens if Intel misses by ten cents?<p>
Styles of stocks rotate in and out of fashion. At the top of a style's popularity, it sells for inflated prices. Right now, the guaranteed earners (another misnomer) are selling for a premium. Expect this to continue as investors pay more and more for the best growth stocks even as that category claims fewer and fewer members.<p>
**To succeed, look to out-of-favor sectors and good stocks at bargain prices.**<p>
It's foolish for a long-term investor to chase any style or individual stock at the peak of its popularity. Instead, wait for the market to punish a stock you've always wanted to own for an insignificant transgression. Study out-of-favor sectors. Small-cap stocks are always oversold in this kind of environment by investors worried about liquidity. Long-term investors can pick up small companies with big futures at reasonable prices. Look for industry leaders -- such as steelmaker <a name="NYSE:NUE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11098"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nucor</b></a> or nickel producer <a name="NYSE:N"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41792"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Inco</b></a> -- that are well positioned to pick up market share in a troubled industry.<p>
And, just in case the economy does go sour in 1997, pay as much attention to the financial soundness of a company as to its earnings. Make sure any company you buy has the financial strength to weather a recession -- or better yet to come out stronger than it went in.<p>
KEYWORDS:strategy, forecast, economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:MSFT">Microsoft Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:INTC">Intel Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:CCE">Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:NUE">Nucor Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:N">Inco Limited</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
