<html>
	<head>
		<title>96/11-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Global Markets</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						By Todd G. Buccholz<p>
Because of the size of the U.S. economy, most of us tend not to get too worked up about the dollar. Sure, when traveling abroad we might bellyache about $20 cantaloupes in Tokyo, but for the most part Americans can pass through life without registering the dollar's value against other currencies. Not so for the folks in other countries. In Tokyo, for example, bank signs hanging over the streets display the dollar-yen exchange rate with the time and temperature; in the U.S., exchange rates are on tiny tote boards inside a bank's lobby -- if the bank even bothers to post them.<p>
**What does a strong currency mean for an economy?**<p>
Whether we pay attention or not, however, the exchange rate matters. But does that mean it's good to have a strong currency? Depends on who's asking. Exporters like a cheaper currency. When the U.S. dollar soared against other currencies in the early 1980s, exporters' manufactured goods were priced too high for the world's markets; the U.S. lost market share, and the Midwest started to rust. When the yen rose against the dollar from 1993 to the spring of 1995, you could hear Japanese exporters scream in pain as Toyotas and Nissans became more expensive than their American counterparts. To combat the squeeze, Japanese exporters moved factories to cheaper production spots in Asia. Commentators began referring to Japan's hollowed-out "doughnut economy."<p>
So who benefits from a strong currency? Consumers often do because imported products are cheaper; this, in turn, forces domestic companies to hold down prices. Nervous businesspeople call the phenomenon "price destruction." Importers benefit when the products or materials they purchase fall in price. Tourists obviously enjoy a strong currency.<p>
**A rising franc has squeezed the Swiss economy in the last few years.**<p>
Now that the dollar and the yen have settled into a fairly stable trading range, look to Switzerland for an overvalued currency. The Swiss franc has risen over 17 percent against the U.S. dollar since late 1993. Admittedly, 17 percent doesn't sound like much, but consider the recessionary climate in which Switzerland has stagnated during this period -- while the U.S. economy has been fairly strong. Also, the Swiss inflation rate has hovered between 0.8 and 1.8 percent since 1994, far below the U.S. rate of roughly 2.9 percent, making the Swiss franc even more expensive in real terms. According to the International Monetary Fund, the currency has appreciated over 50 percent since 1981. Ouch. The Swiss are feeling the pinch everywhere from the ski-lift lines, where high prices scare off foreign tourists, to the chocolate factories. In imitation of the Japanese doughnut, Switzerland is hollowing out its chocolate base, building factories in Greece and Spain to take advantage of cheap currencies, cheap labor, and generous European Union trade laws (Switzerland, where neutrality is practically a religion, does not belong to the EU).<p>
The Swiss franc is overvalued because many European investors are worried about the forthcoming European Monetary Union, when Germans will exchange their cherished D-marks for Euros. Because the Swiss aren't participating, many Europeans have switched their savings into Swiss francs as a safe haven. An aggravating factor has been the Swiss insistence on keeping monetary policy tight, even in recession. Now the Swiss have few alternatives but to cut interest rates again and talk down their currency. Doing nothing means fewer tourists and less chocolate. Hardly a sweet forecast.<p>
Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz is a managing director of a New York–based international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.<p>
KEYWORDS:global, worldwide, money, exchange rate, foreign

					</font>
					<p>
					<font size=4>
					<blockquote>
					</blockquote>
					</font>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

