	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Fixed Income</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						96/11-Fixed Income<p>
By Chip Norton<p>
In September, the fixed-income markets fought a tug-of-war that sent rates higher and then lower as bond investors reacted to on-again, off-again reports of economic strength. At one point in early September, investors expecting an interest-rate hike at the September 24 meeting of the Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee sent the yield on the long Treasury bond soaring close to 7.2 percent. Then reports of subdued economic activity in mid-month left investors convinced that the Fed would postpone increasing rates after all. Rates fell back below 7 percent.<p>
A cynical assessment of the political realities supported those optimists who believed the Fed wouldn't hike rates in September. September's meeting was the last committee meeting until after the November 5 election. The betting was that Alan Greenspan was unlikely to turn on President Clinton by hiking rates in the final weeks of the campaign. Cynics, of course, have been wrong.
All of this volatility has investors questioning whether this is the right time to dive back into the bond market. Recent data from the Investment Company Institute, the mutual-fund industry's trade group, show that money actually flowed out of bond funds over the summer.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
bond, election, interest rates

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

