	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-10 Stocks to Consider/Avoid</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-10 Stocks to Consider/Avoid</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Paul Wick considers himself a patient investor. In his seven years running Seligman Communications and Information Fund, he has pursued a strategy of "growth at a reasonable price, with some momentum and value investing mixed in." In the long term, that recipe has worked: The fund's five-year 27 percent annualized return is a full three percentage points higher than the return for Morningstar's universe of specialty technology funds for the same period. This year, however, the fund was down 4 percent as of September 13, while Morningstar's tech funds were up an average of 9.1 percent. "Frankly, we've been hurt because the market has been so momentum oriented," says Wick, who typically avoids highfliers with little or no revenue. Instead, he prefers underappreciated companies like Lexmark International, IBM's former printer operation, whose earnings should grow as its cartridge business expands. Sales at Compaq Computer should take off, too, he says, as businesses upgrade to Windows NT. Not afraid to bottom-fish, Wick sees some gems in the battered semiconductor industry among specialty-chip makers ESS Technology and Xilinx. He also likes the huge cash flow generated by hard-drive maker Seagate Technology.<p>
**Wick's Picks**<p>
Company (EXCH:TKR)  fair value<br> 
*Reasons<br>
<br>
<a name="NASD:CDCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17123"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cidco</b></a>  (Nasdaq: CDCO)  $25<br>
* Leader in caller-ID equipment<br>
* Underpenetrated markets<br>
* Potential acquisition target<br>
