<br><p>
**10 Stocks to Avoid**<br><p>
Howard Schilit, adjunct professor of accounting at American University, pores over financial reports and SEC corporate filings to spot companies he believes may be headed for trouble. The results end up in CFRA's Monthly Research Compendium, a research service for over 100 institutional subscribers put out by the Center for Financial Research and Analysis, based in Rockville, Maryland. Schilit's work focuses on uncovering inflated revenues involving questionable sales, accounts receivable, or other forms of aggressive accounting in company financial reports. His picks for Worth in October 1995 have fallen off 10.4 percent, while the stocks targeted by his service over the past three years have plunged an average of 30 percent. Medic Computer Systems currently worries Schilit: The company recently benefited from a sale to a related party, yet no cash actually changed hands. The warning signs at Genesis Health Ventures, an operator of care centers for the elderly, include a recent sale and purchase of health-care facilities that inflated the company's revenues and profit margins. At Orthodontic Centers of America, a specialty group medical practice, a negative cash flow does not jibe with reported revenue and earnings.<p>
**Schilit's Pans**<br>
<br>
Company (EXCH:TKR)  Fair Value<br>
*Reasone<br>
<br>
