	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which he considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after August 22, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends they conduct their own due diligence.<p>
PRESTON ATHEY
<a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</b></a>
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.
<a name="NASD:SRCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14679"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sealright</b></a> (NASDAQ: SRCO) Up to $15
Sealright (DeSoto, Kansas) makes packaging for food products and is the leading supplier of frozen-dessert packaging in the U.S. A growth company through the 1980s, Sealright saw its margins fall in 1995 because of competition and overexpansion. CEO Charles F. Marcy, who came on board in 1995, has reduced overhead, consolidated manufacturing, and revived R&D. New applications for McDonald's and growing success overseas should provide a kicker to Sealright's domestic turn-around. Despite an earnings estimate of just 21 cents a share in 1996, the stock is supported by a 4.2 percent yield. The company could easily earn $1.50 a share by 1998.<p>
JAMES P. CRAIG
Janus Fund
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.
<a name="NYSE:BCS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41754"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Barclays</b></a> (NYSE: BCS) Up to $62
London-based Barclays is one of the largest financial-services companies in the U.K. While Barclays has been burdened in the past by losses from bad loans, it is taking strides to increase shareholder value: Management just bought back 3.5 percent of the company's stock and is dedicated to controlling costs. In addition, Barclays is the largest issuer of credit cards in the U.K., where the card business is still in its infancy. Last year, Barclays acquired Wells Fargo Nikko Investment Advisors in an effort to expand into asset management. Barclays should earn $6.90 a share in 1996 and $7.50 a share in 1997, and in six months the stock could trade at ten times the 1997 estimate. <p>
SHELBY M.C. DAVIS
New York Venture Fund
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
<a name="NYSE:DWD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15970"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dean Witter, Discover</b></a> (NYSE: DWD) Up to $55
Dean Witter, Discover (New York) is an emerging-growth story. The company operates in two primary businesses: credit cards and securities. The two segments have different customer bases, but they're complementary: One offers credit, the other gathers assets. With 38 million accounts and 46 million customers, the credit-card division is the largest issuer of general-purpose credit cards in the U.S. (it issues Discover, Private Issue, and Bravo). The stock has been under pressure because of rising card delinquencies, but the company should still turn in record earnings of $5.20 a share in 1996 and at least $6.00 a share in 1997. The target price for the stock is $70.<p>
DANIEL B. LEONARD
Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology
Seeks growth in technology and related fields.
<a name="AMEX:KEA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13890"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Keane</b></a> (AMEX: KEA) Up to $45
Keane (Boston) designs custom computer software to help make existing systems at corporations and health-care facilities more cost efficient. On the health-care side, the company provides services for more than 400 hospitals and 600 long-term-care facilities. On the corporate side (which accounted for 93 percent of 1995 revenues), Keane works with such big names as <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:PG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11211"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Procter & Gamble</b></a>. Keane is growing rapidly and will soon open a development center in Nova Scotia. Earnings have grown steadily. I believe the company could earn $1.55 a share in 1996 and $1.95 in 1997. This stock, which has been trading in the high 30s, could go to $60 in 12 months. <p>
WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ
<a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a>
Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued.
<a name="NASD:GISH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13575"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gish Biomedical</b></a> (NASDAQ: GISH) Up to $7.50
Gish Biomedical (Irvine, California) manufactures fluid-delivery and blood-management systems used during surgical procedures. Currently, Gish produces all the elements for these systems except the oxygenator. On January 1, 1997, however, Gish will introduce its own, better oxygenator. With this alone, Gish could earn $10 million dollars in sales and improve its margins greatly. Jack Brown, president and CEO at Gish, is a great sales-man and owns 14 percent of the company. The company has no long-term debt, trades at a reasonable ten times 1996 earnings, and is priced around its book value of $6 a share. I'd call that a relatively cheap buy.  <p>
Eric E. Rayback
Lindner Dividend Fund
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.
8El Paso Electric (AMEX: EE) Up to $8
Since emerging from bankruptcy earlier this year, El Paso Electric (El Paso, Texas) has significantly improved its operational and financial performances. Under new CEO and president James Haines, the utility has strengthened its management team and cleaned up its balance sheet by buying back high-coupon bonds. With the company looking to renew its contract to sell power to Mexico and with a ten-year rate freeze in Texas, El Paso has a tre-mendous advantage over current and future competition. The company is a potential buyout or merger candidate sometime in the future at a substantial premium to its current price. The target price is $15. <p>
RALPH WAGNER & CHUCK McQUAID
<a name="FUND:AUSAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AUSAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a>
Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.
<a name="NASD:ABII"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15513"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Business Info. </b></a>(NASDAQ: ABII) Up to $16
American Business Information Inc. (Omaha) compiles and sells data on 11 million businesses in the U.S. and Canada. More than 100,000 customers use the company's data (sold increasingly on CD-ROM) to create mailing labels, generate sales leads, and develop direct-marketing strategies. ABII has expanded its database to include geographic coordinates and credit information and has opened new sales offices. Growth of 15 percent to 20 percent should continue, and the company may be able to use the substantial amount of cash it's been generating to make acquisitions. At 15 times our 1995 earnings estimate of 90 cents a share, this stock is cheap.<p>
DONALD A. YACKTMAN
<a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalizations of at least $1 billion.
<a name="NYSE:KWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10857"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>King World Productions </b></a>(NYSE: KWP) Up to $38
The answer: What is King World Productions? The question: The company Oprah, Merv, and I all think is a smart buy. Of course, it helps that King World (New York) distributes Oprah Winfrey's show and that Merv Griffin is executive producer of Wheel of Fortune and Jeopardy! These three shows plus Inside Edition generated 84 percent of King World's fiscal 1995 revenue, and increases in advertising during these signature programs should continue to bolster revenues. What's more, there's a good chance the company may be sold. With its stock currently selling at approximately ten times 1996 earnings, King World looks very attractive.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
