				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which he considers the recommended stock attractive. The newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the August 22 publishing deadline.<p>
AL FRANK
The Prudent Speculator
Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation. 
<a name="NASD:BELF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bel Fuse</b></a> (NASDAQ: BELF) Up to $11.20
Bel Fuse (Jersey City) designs and manufactures delay lines and fuses used in computer networking, tele-communications, business equipment, and consumer electronics. The stock price plummeted more than 40 percent in July after Bel reported earnings six cents shy of estimates, but that doesn't worry us: We expect the company to rebound and earn $1.20 a share in 1996. Bel has a strong balance sheet -- it's free of long-term debt and has $3.82 a share in cash and marketable securities. The stock now trades for just nine times our 1996 earnings estimate and several dollars below its book value of  $11.84 a share. The three- to five-year target price is $22.<p>
JIM McCAMANT
Medical Technology Stock Letter
Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies. 
<a name="NASD:ICOS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12419"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ICOS</b></a> (NASDAQ: ICOS) Up to $10
Biopharmaceutical company ICOS (Bothell, Washington) develops anti-inflammatory therapeutic drugs for chronic diseases, such as asthma and multiple sclerosis. Chairman and CEO George B. Rathmann -- also the founder of Amgen -- has attracted excellent scientists, who in turn have brought in sophisticated investors. Making the firm even more appealing is Bill Gates, an active board member and the company's largest shareholder. ICOS has de-veloped attractive partnerships with <a name="NYSE:GLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41781"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Glaxo Wellcome</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:ABT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10030"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Abbott Laboratories</b></a>. Over the next year, we expect the investment community to get excited in response to clinical-trial results. The 18-month target price is $20. <p>
MICHAEL MURPHY 
California Technology Stock Letter
Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.
<a name="NASD:EUPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44511"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Euphonix</b></a> (NASDAQ: EUPH) Up to $7
Euphonix (Palo Alto, California) makes digital systems for audio mixers used in recording studios -- in particular, a feature called SnapShot Recall, which allows a recording engineer to switch from one mix to another in real time, something the company's competitors' systems can't do. A late-summer announcement that Euphonix was going to miss analysts' earnings estimates for the third and fourth quarters cut the stock price nearly in half. At this price, Euphonix is highly attractive. We expect the company to earn 20 to 25 cents a share this year and 40 to 45 cents in 1997. We give the stock a 12-month target price of $11; if things go as well as they should, it could go as high as $15.<p>
LOUIS NAVELLIER
MPT Review
Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks. 
<a name="NASD:HOLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13907"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hologic</b></a> (NASDAQ: HOLX) Up to $43
Hologic (Waltham, Massachusetts) makes and distributes X-ray equipment that helps doctors examine bone density and diagnose osteoporosis. Half the company's sales take place outside the U.S. In 1995, Hologic's stock price rose rapidly following FDA approval of an osteoporosis drug that has already increased demand for the company's products domestically. Hologic had a phenomenal third quarter, earning 32 cents a share -- 400 percent growth over the same quarter a year ago. I expect the company to earn 97 cents a share in 1996 and $1.24 a share in 1997. Having recently split its stock and with no long-term debt, Hologic is an attractive buy. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
