<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-The Big Squeeze</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-The Big Squeeze</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The market doesn't want to know that the economy is slowing<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
For most of this year, investors have rooted for slow growth. Every time the economy has revved up, bond yields have climbed and stock prices have fallen.The fear, of course, has been that good economic news would leadthe Federal Reserve to raise interest rates in order to head off inflation.<p>
Well, the market is now about todiscover that growth can be too slow.In August, a consensus forecast of 52 economists compiled by Blue Chip Economic Indicators predicted that the economy will grow by just 2.1 percent next year. Investors could be facing a classic earnings squeeze.<p>
On the surface, an economy growing at 2.1 percent doesn't seem like that big a problem for the stock market. After all, growth in 1995 was just 2 percent. But the pattern of changes in the growth rate is troubling. The economy has been gradually slowing since 1994, when it grew at 3.5 percent. After a brief pickup in the first half of 1996, the economy is projectedto resume its downward course, with growth dipping quarter by quarter: from 2.6 percent in the third quarter of 1996, to 2.1 percent, to 1.9 percent, and then to just 1.8 percent.<p>
What is 1997 likely to mean for corporate earnings? The Blue Chip consensus calls for profits to grow just 3.3 percent. The optimists are calling for an 8.4 percent increase and the pessimistsfor a 3.1 percent decline.<p>
Unfortunately, there is reason tobelieve that the gloomy view is closer to the mark. Besides the slowdown in overall economic activity, other fundamental trends are conspiring to depress earnings in 1997.<p>
First is the increasing strength of the dollar. The dollar's weakness over the past couple of years has given a boost to the earnings of multinationals, such as <a name="NYSE:KOF"></a><b>Coca-Cola</b> and <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>. A stronger buck will have the opposite effect.<p>
Second, inflation is so weak that companies will not be able to raise prices, and intense competition will even lead to price cuts on products from cereals to personal computers.<p>
Third, although general consumer inflation remains low, wages are creeping up. This kind of split is fairly typical in the late stages of an economic cycle, says James Stack, president of InvesTech Research. "Ask a CEO in the Midwest how tight the labor market is," he suggests. Labor costs rose at a 3.8 percent annual rate in the second quarter of 1996, according to the Department of Labor.<p>
But none of this would matter much to investors if stocks were cheap. But equities are actually more expensive than they were a year ago.<p>
The price that investors pay fora stock -as measured by its price-to-earnings ratio -rises and falls during an economic cycle. Generally, it peaks when the market sees rising earnings ahead. At the end of 1992, for example, when actual earnings for the previous 12 months had been relatively low, the p/e on the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index stood at 22.8. As those earnings arrived over the next three years, the p/e gradually moved downward, bouncing around 16 for most of 1995.<p>
From this perspective, the climb in the p/e from 17 in late 1995 to 19 in August 1996 was perverse. Facing slowing earnings growth, stocks should have grown cheaper -not more expensive.<p>
How much cheaper would be reasonable? If the optimists among the Blue Chip economists are right -corporate profits increase 13 percent in 1996 and 8 percent in 1997, but the p/e falls to 17 to reflect the prospects for slow growth -then the S&P would finish 1997 at 704.48, a gain of 5.6 percent over the next 16 months. If the optimists are right this year, but the consensus is correct about 1997 -3 percent growth next year -then the S&P 500 would stand at 671.86 at the end of 1997, for a gain of 1 percent. If earnings fall in 1997, returns could be negative. A decline of 10 percent wouldn't be out of the question.<p>
Needless to say, a market in which the most reasonable scenario shows a 1 percent return over 16 months is a bad buy.<p>
Individual stocks won't track this market exactly. Investors who see growth slowing have already bid up companies that offer what they view as strong, predictable earnings. Investors are now willing to pay 40 times earnings for Coca-Cola, up from 32 in early 1996.<p>
The market will dump shares in any company that misses earnings estimates by even a hair. <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> received the treatment in July. Expect to see more of the same. That kind of rush for the exit is what passes for investor discipline in a market like this.<p>
But if economic growth is indeed slowing, investors would be wise to switch some attention from corporate income statements to corporate balance sheets. In a slow economy, some overextended companies will find themselves unable to pay their bills -instead of just missing earnings estimates, some may wind up in bankruptcy. And financially weak companies don't have to go broke to do investors harm. They'll be so busy just trying to hang on that they'll lose ground to better-run companies. Great companies draw on solid balance sheets to build market share in slow times. They invest in gaining customers and improving efficiency when their competitors are struggling just to make ends meet. Those financially sound companies are the stocks an investor will want to own when growth picks up again.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
