					</center>
					<font size=4>
						LATE PAYMENT
Credit-card delinquency rates increased in the first quarter of this year with quarterly charge-offs of bad credit-card debt topping 1.07 percent ($2.23 billion) for the first time in three years, according to Veribanc of Wakefield, Massachusetts. That's likely to mean bad news for profits at some banks. (See "<A href="/articles/Z9608I02.html">Banking's Next Big Mistake?</A>
" July/August 1996.) Traditionally, a 1 percent charge-off rate is considered bad for bank profits. But with most banks showing healthy earnings, says Warren Heller, Veribanc's research director, the pain is likely to be confined to a few banks. A little more than 8 percent of the 6,085 banks that issue credit cards hold 30 percent of the bad credit-card debt. At the same time, the banks with the majority of bad debt account for only 16 percent of overall outstanding credit-card balances.<p>
MORE OPTIONS
Options traders now have an Internet option. The Options Industry Council's World Wide Web page provides a database of more than 1,800 listed equity options. OptionsCentral (<A HREF="http:// www.optionscentral.com">http:// www.optionscentral.com</A>) provides options symbols and stock and options prices and charts, along with other news and information.<p>
