<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Northern Lights<p>
By Todd G. Buchholz<p>
The U.S. isn't the only country roiled by budget deficits and a government-debt time bomb that threatens to blow up the living standard of future generations. Some countries, however, are standing up to the challenge. Two that have come back from the brink of financial disaster, Canada and Sweden, are creating opportunities for investors as a result. In 1994, both were headed toward a creditors' strike and had ratios of debt to gross domestic product well over 75 percent (compared with 60 percent in the U.S.). By mid-1994, Canada had to offer interest rates 200 basis points higher than U.S. rates to attract bond buyers; Sweden had to pay 310 basis points more than the U.S. These higher rates drove up budget deficits, creating a spiral of debt. Then these nations stiffened, showing that left-wing governments can sometimes be as fiscally conservative as their counterparts on the right.<p>
In 1995, Canadian finance minister Paul Martin delivered a strikingly tough budget plan to bring the deficit down steadily from 5.3 percent of GDP in 1994 to 4 percent in 1995 and to an estimated 2.7 percent in 1996 and 1.2 percent in 1997. The markets were particularly impressed that Martin performed his fiscal magic with few tax increases, but rather by slicing and dicing programs. The reward for the government's fiscal courage has been a stronger and more stable Canadian dollar, giving equity investors confidence that their capital gains and dividends won't be chewed up by currency losses. After a losing year in 1994, the Toronto stock index has climbed about 27 percent since Martin's 1995 budget announcement, despite a sluggish economy. When the Canadian economy does get off its feet, the stock market won't be dragged down by extraordinarily high interest rates or a flimsy Canadian dollar.<p>
Of course, one risk will continue to dog the Canadian markets: Quebec separatism. After losing a razor-thin vote last year, the separatists will likely try to stage another referendum on separation in 1998. Still, the performance of Quebec leader Lucien Bouchard is impressive. Rather than fight for separatist ideas during this interim period, Bouchard, too, is tackling Quebec's provincial debt. If Bouchard can stanch the province's bleeding red ink, he can probably capture additional separatist votes. And while separatism is generally bad for Canadian markets, balanced budgets comfort investors.<p>
Sweden's path has resembled Canada's over the past year and a half. Finance Minister Erik Åsbrink plans to produce a 1997 budget that will reach a deficit-to-GDP ratio of 3 percent. This would qualify Sweden for the European Monetary Union should the Swedes opt for a single European currency.<p>
Because the government has tackled the deficit problem, the Swedish central bank has been able to cut interest rates without imperiling the Swedish krona. In fact, the krona jumped about 15 percent against the deutsche mark from August 1995 to August 1996, even as the central bank cut its deposit rate from 8 percent to 5.25 percent. Ordinarily such a rate cut weakens a currency; the krona's newfound strength demonstrates confidence in Sweden's finances. That has permitted the Swedish stock market to climb 12.3 percent this year (through August 8), compared with 7.6 percent for the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index. When a recovery comes to the Swedish economy in 1997, it won't be short-circuited by the foolish, profligate spending policies of the past.<p>
Contributing editor Todd Buchholz is a managing director of a New York–based international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
