	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Fixed Income</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Falling Expectations<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
Now that the august 20 meeting of the  Federal Reserve has come and gone without a hike in interest rates, the bond market has started to focus on November. Although the Fed meets in September, most bond analysts don't believe the central bank will risk charges of political meddling by raising rates so close to the presidential election. A move in November, after the votes have been cast, is far more likely.<p>
But financial markets aren't expecting the Fed to take a big step upward on rates even then. As of mid-August, prices of futures contracts, which rise and fall with expectations of future interest rates, indicate that traders are expecting the Federal Funds Rate to inch up to about 5.7 percent in March 1997 from its current mark of 5.25 percent. A few weeks earlier, on July 25, futures prices were predicting a 6 percent Federal Funds Rate by March.<p>
That downward revision seems to reflect an increasingly pessimistic view of growth in the U.S. economy. A Merrill Lynch/Gallup poll of money managers conducted in early August showed that only 28 percent expect the U.S. economy to improve over the next 12 months. That's down from a peak of 63 percent in March 1996. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
