	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-What They're Recommending</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE RECOMMENDING  <p> The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the author considers the recommended stock attractive.In some cases, the newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages. He may also have changed his opinion after the February 26 publishing deadline for this issue.  <p> JIM McCAMANT <p>Medical Technology Stock Letter <p>Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.  <p> <a name="NASD:SHMN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15954"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SHAMAN PHARMACEUTICALS </b></a> (Nasdaq: SHMN) Up to $8. Shaman (South San Francisco), a biotech company, has  a singular approach todrug discovery, which includes analyzing active compounds inplants that have been used for medicinal purposes in indigenouscultures in  South America and Africa. The concept seems so obviousthat at first I was skeptical, but the company is proving thatthis process turns up real candidates: Virend, its herpes drug,is about to begin pivotal trials; Provir, its drug for travelers'diarrhea, is in phase-two trials; and another major program --focusing on type 2 diabetes -- is under way. The company hasplenty of cash from its 1993 initial public offering and a coupleof big-name partnerships.  <p>  <p>MICHAEL MURPHY <p>California Technology Stock Letter <p>Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.   <p> <a name="NASD:CRUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> CIRRUS LOGIC </b></a> (Nasdaq: CRUS) Up to $22. A semiconductor companywith a broad product line, Cirrus (Fremont, California) is thelogical choice to benefit from the Pentium-driven 20 percentgrowth I'm expecting to see in the personal-computer market thisyear. Changes in the company's manufacturing should mean a muchimproved bottom line. Cirrus has always depended on outside fabricationservices, but it is now spending roughly $1 billion to developco-manufacturing relationships, the first of which is with <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>. Cirrus is expecting a loss in the quarter ending in March asa result of PC-inventory problems; after that, results will improve.I think the stock will reach $45 a share by year-end.  <p>  <p>LOUIS NAVELLIER <p>MPT Review <p>Uses modern portfolio theory tooidentify high-return, low-volatilitystocks.   <p> <a name="NASD:JMED"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13873"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> JONES MEDICAL INDUSTRIES</b></a> (Nasdaq: JMED) Up to $52. Jones Medical Industries (St. Louis), a maker of pharmaceuticals and vitamins,looks quite attractive on a risk-reward basis. The stock, whichis up more than 600 percent from its 12-month low of $7.38 ashare, has an extremely high alpha (a positive technical sign,showing that its returns are uncorrelated with the market's)and  a very low standard deviation (a statistical measure ofrisk). Jones has over 400 different products and an aggressiveacquisition strategy, so it's no surprise that the company'sfundamentals are in great shape, too. Earnings last quarter camein well above most analysts' estimates, and the company has verystrong earnings momentum.   <p>  <p>DAN SULLIVAN <p>The Chartist <p>Uses technical analysis to identify long-term equity investments.  <p> <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BOEING</b></a> (NYSE: BA) Up to92. After struggling through five leanyears, the airline industry appears ready for takeoff. As a group,airlines lost roughly $13 billion from 1990 to 1994 before returningto profitability in 1995. As the recovery strengthens and airlinesreplace their aging planes with more fuel-efficient models, Boeing's(Seattle) orders will expand. In fact, TWA recently placed anorder to buy ten Boeing 757-200s and lease ten more. Rising orderscombined with more cost-efficient production should drive earningshigher through the end of the decade. The trip will not be turbulencefree, however, as Boeing's success rests, as always, in the handsof a fickle airline industry.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
