<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE BUYING NOW  <p> Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after February 26, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these eight managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends that they conduct their own due diligence.  <p> PRESTON ATHEY <p><a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</b></a>  <p>Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.  <p> <a name="NASD:AMTL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16007"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AMTROL</b></a>  (Nasdaq: AMTL) Up to $18. Investors in Amtrol (West Warwick, Rhode Island), a water-tank maker, took a bath in 1995, but long-term prospects remain good. After peaking in 1994 at $1.61 a share, earnings fell last year to $1.51 (before 31 cents a share in write-offs). This outfit can earn $1.60 a share in 1996. Amtrol is debt free and well worth its current stock price on the fundamentals alone. If the company is acquired, investors could reap much more. How likely is a takeover? Very. Its founder recently died at age 79 and left no clear successor. Plus, most of the common shares are owned by restless institutions that have lost money in the stock and are squeezing directors to sell out.  <p>
JAMES P. CRAIG <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a><p>Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea ofpreserving capital over the long term.   <p> <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS MACHINES</b></a>  (NYSE: IBM) Up to $130. Take-no-prisoners CEO Louis Gerstner has mended this computer giant's Achilles' heel -- the mainframe business -- by balancing aggressive pricecuts with strong growth in computing power. If IBM (Armonk, New York) can maintain this division's progress, its other lines of business could propel the stock to new heights. The stock looks cheap to me right now. With huge cash flow  ($7 billion in 1996, $8 billion in 1997), the company is able to buy back tons of stock (it repurchased $4.2 billion worth last year).I expect IBM to earn $14 a share in 1996 and $16 a share in 1997. If the mainframe business continues to improve, the stock could go to $170 a share by year-end.  <p>
SHELBY M.C. DAVIS <p><a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> <p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.  <p> <a name="NYSE:DLJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44439"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DONALDSON, LUFKIN & JENRETTE </b></a> (NYSE: DLJ) Up to $31. Why chase high-priced new Internet issues when you can buy the firm that is underwriting a lot of these offerings? Spun off from Equitable last October at  $27 a share, DLJ (New York) stock is in a post-IPO consolidation stage, trading at around $30. DLJ is strong inmerchant banking, equity underwriting, and research. Return one quity in 1995 was 17 percent and should be even higher thisyear. Book value is $21 a share now and is increasing steadily. Earnings have been on a roll  and should be in the $3- to $4-a-share range in 1996. Essentially, then, this is an emerging growth company, trading at a low nine times 1996 earnings estimates. <p>
DANIEL B. LEONARD <p><a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a> <p>Seeks growth stocks in rechnology and related fields.  <p> <a name="NASD:CRRS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14479"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CROWN RESOURCES</b></a>(Nasdaq: CRRS) Up to $7.50. Crown Resources (Denver) doesn't think doing the dirty work is below its station. After identifying promising gold properties in the western United States and South America, Crown teams up with larger partners for the later-stage development. The company is very close to getting the final permit for the Crown Jewel project, its Washington State joint venture with Battle Mountain Gold. Crown has exploration projects in Peru and Argentina, as well as in Nevada, Utah, and Montana. Although most gold stocks have been doing well, Crown has remained relatively flat, so I think the stock could bounce to $10 or $12 a share by year-end.  <p>  <p>WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ <p><a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a> <p>Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued.  <p> <a name="NASD:TRKA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14936"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TRAK AUTO</b></a>(Nasdaq: TRKA) Up to $16. Trak Auto (Landover, Maryland)is motoring ahead with its expansion plans. This retailer inthe $100 billion  do-it-yourself market for auto parts is repairing its bottom line. How? By emphasizing growth in its much-higher-margin superstores and warehouse stores, which now account for roughly two-thirds of sales. Trak currently has 282 stores and offersover 25,000 products. The stock is trading at book value andonly 11 times 12-month trailing earnings. This is a low valuationfor a company with no debt and more than $5 a share in cash flow, especially when compared with competitors such as Auto Zone (28 times trailing earnings), <a name="NYSE:PBY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pep Boys</b></a> (22), and <a name="NYSE:DAP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11567"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Discount Auto</b></a> (18). <p>
ERIC E. RYBACK <p><a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a> <p>Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.  <p> <a name="NYSE:CQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10379"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>COMSAT</b></a> (NYSE: CQ) Up to $26. This satellite maker's stock price, which has been orbiting in the $21 range for over a year, should improve as global demand for data, TV transmission, direct satellite broadcast, and personal-communication capability explodes. After a weak 1995, Comsat (Bethesda, Maryland) has taken steps to highlight the value of its 30-year-old satellite-communications franchises, Inmarsat and Intelsat. That's why the company recently spun offits Ascent Entertainment Group. Planet 1, the world's first personal-satellite-communications system, should be available in July. This five-pound device is another step toward global personal-communication capability. <p>
RALPH WANGER/CHUCK McQUAID <p><a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a> <p>Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.   <p> <a name="NASD:VCELA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15058"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VANGUARD CELLULAR SYSTEMS </b></a>(Nasdaq: VCELA) Up to $28. This cellular provider, which we recommended last July, is now emitting strong "buy" signals. Last year, Vanguard (Greensboro, North Carolina) boosted subscribers by 56 percent, service revenue by 49 percent, and cash flow by 89 percent. Plus, cash-flow margins jumped to 31 percent from 24 percent in 1994. We expect these trends to continue. Concern about personal-communications-services competition has hurt the stock but is unfounded --  these vendors are not building in Vanguard's markets, where population density is low and hilly terrain would block signals. Vanguard will adopt low-cost digital technology later this year, boosting its competitive edge.  <p>  <p>DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p><a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a> <p>Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitaization of at least $1 billion.  <p> <a name="NASD:BARE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BAREFOOT </b></a> (Nasdaq: BARE) Up to $12. Barefoot (Worthington, Ohio) is starting to make a big imprint on the slowly consolidating lawn-care industry. The second-largest company of its kind, Barefoot has been buying mom-and-pop stores and now has 59 company locations and 44 franchise locations. It is also one of the cheapest stocks out there, selling at about ten times my 1996 earnings estimate of between $1 and $1.10 a share. The company generates a lot of excess cash flow, which it has been using to buy back stock. One caveat: Quarterly earnings are sensitive to weather. For example, fourth-quarter 1995 sales were $4 million less than expected because of the cold, snowy start to the winter.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

