<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Market Psychology</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Market Psychology</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Fundamentals don't seem to count for much now -- so watch them carefully  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> On Tuesday, February 20, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspantold Congress to expect moderate economic growth of about 2 percentand low inflation for 1996. Oh, no! said the financial markets.The Fed doesn't need to cut interest rates to stimulate the economy! The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell almost 45 points, and the30-year Treasury bond tumbled.  <p> In his testimony the next day, Greenspan told Congress to expect moderate growth and low inflation. Yea! the stock market responded.The Fed's going to cut interest rates soon! The Dow climbed more than 57 points that day, tacked on another 92 points on Thursday,and finished the week with a 22-point gain as it hit another record high at 5630.  <p> But the bond market didn't share the stock market's euphoria that week. After rallying along with the equity market on Wednesday,the bond market resumed its two-month slide. Bond prices felland yields roseÐthe volatile 30-year Treasury bond finished the week yielding 6.42

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
