	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> KEEPING UP  <p> By John Fried  <p> Expect a cautious, inflation-loathing Federal Reserve Board for years to come now that President Clinton has nominated Alan Greenspan for a third term as chairman of the Fed. Greenspan's nomination is virtually assured of confirmation by the Republican-controlled Senate. Clinton has also chosen Alice Rivlin, the White House budget director, and Laurence Meyer, an economist, to fill twovacancies on the Fed board. Both Rivlin and Meyer are considered proponents of price stability and aren't likely to push for economic growth at the risk of triggering inflation.   <p> The capital-gains tax cut doesn't look like the sure thing it did just a few months ago. The longer the impasse on the federal budget continues, the more likely it becomes that the president and top GOP leaders will wait, in essence, to let voters settle the issue in the November elections.   <p> Warren Buffett has unveiled a plan that would allow investors to buy a stake in <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway</b> on the cheap if $1,000 or so counts as cheap. Currently, a share of Buffett's investment company trades for more than $30,000. The plan would create anew class-B stock and designate existing shares as class A. Class-A holders will be able to convert a share into 30 class-B shares though conversions in the other direction won't be permitted.  <p> The Securities and Exchange Commission has chastised closed-end mutual funds for poor disclosure, saying fund literature is often unclear on how and when the funds will take action to prevent the discount on shares from becoming too great. In a letter to the Investment Company Institute, the SEC expressed concerns that investors were being misled by apparent promises in disclosure documents to eliminate these discounts by converting the closed-end funds into the more common open-end variety.   <p> Employers now have even more incentive to offer employees solid investment options in their 401(k) plans. A federal appeals court in Philadelphia ruled that employees of Unisys could sue the company after one of the options (a guaranteed investment contract) in their 401(k) plan turned out to be a poor choice. Meanwhile, employers who procrastinate when it comes to depositing employee contributions into 401(k) and other benefit plans may soon run afoul of the Labor Department. The federal agency has proposed new regulations that would require employers to make monthly deposits within a few days. Currently, deposits can be held byan employer for up to 90 days.  <p> Only 6 of 16 major brokerage houses beat the market with their stock recommendations in 1995, according to a study by Zacks Investment Research and The Wall Street Journal.   <p> VISA U.S.A. has said it will discontinue offering automatic purchase insurance for gold-card holders. The move, scheduled to become effective March 1, applies to insurance that covers the cost of merchandise that is broken or stolen after a customer uses a VISA gold card to buy it. MasterCard International and <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>said they plan to continue to offer automatic purchase protection. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Taxation, Government, Mutual Funds Investing, Banking Industry, Insurance Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
