<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> GLOBAL MARKETS  <p> By Todd G. Buchholz  <p> The Campaign Market <p>Presidential candidates do what they need to do to woo voters, so it's time to ask what the presidential campaign will do to financial markets.  <p> First off, the U.S. bond market could be in trouble. The budget deal of 1993 raised taxes and cut spending part of then National Economic Council chairman Robert Rubin's strategy to please the bond market and let lower interest rates jump-start the economy. But no one will propose jacking up gas or income taxes this year. <p> With the drive toward a balanced budget stalled, traders no longer expect high bond prices or the 5.5 percent yields of two months ago. Even with a slowing economy, yields could surpass 6.25 percent. In sum: yields up, prices down.  <p> Changes in our bond market also have a global impact. For example, between January 19 and February 20 (with a Federal Reserve rate cut on January 31), U.S. bond prices plummeted, sending yields on the ten-year bond from 5.53 percent to 6.01 percent, largely on uncertainty over how much more the Fed might lower rates. This caused German bond yields to soar and Germany's DAX stock index to briefly lose its momentum. The rest of Europe felt a similar wallop.  <p> Trade policy is already being affected by the campaign, as Pat Buchanan has tempered every candidate's public enthusiasm forfree trade. China is the first test of the nation's commitment. The U.S. is rattling retaliatory sabers because of piracy of U.S. software, human-rights violations, nuclear proliferation, and a ballooning trade deficit (approaching $50 billion, in China's favor). There's also the threat of a Chinese invasion of Taiwan if the March 23 Taiwanese elections are won by the Democratic Progressive Party, which would represent a step toward independence and a turn toward democracy. The situation has some traders nervous enough to stay out of both China markets until April. The question is whether we will deny China most-favored-nation status. Republicans will pounce on any softness from Clinton on this issue, but I expect China to remain an MFN.  <p> Mexico may be in for some trouble, too. In February, Senators Dianne Feinstein of California and Alphonse D'Amato of New York proposed withholding U.S. aid unless Mexico does more to check drug traffcking and illegal immigration. Formal sanctions are unlikely, but the Mexican markets may suffer as Mexico bashing becomes an easy way for candidates to appeal to some voters. Also, opposition from California wine producers to competing against good, cheap Chilean wine will squash hopes of extending NAFTA to Chile.  <p> The election won't exempt the commodities markets, either. In February, U.S. trade representative Mickey Kantor announced anagreement with Canada to restrict its lumber exports here, and the deal has helped push lumber prices to their highest level in a year. Edgy traders also wonder if the president, to avoida foreign-policy crisis and romance the farm vote, will boost President Boris Yeltsin's reelection campaign (the Russian electionis June 2) by helping Russia purchase U.S. wheat.  <p> Election season is a time for caution, but keep in mind that U.S. stock markets have been buoyed by huge flows of cash from individuals into stock mutual funds. A bitter campaign might spur people to put even more aside for a rainy day.  <p> Todd G. Buchholz, a contributing editor, is an international economic consultant and lecturer and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Government, International Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
