	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Fixed Income</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> FIXED INCOME  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> When the federal reserve cut the federal funds rate from 5.5 percent to 5.25 percent on January 31, the bond market barely twitched. "The cut just confirmed what the market expected," says John Burgess, managing director of Bankers Trust Global Investment Management.  <p> And when, on February 20 and 21, Alan Greenspan spooked the market -- sending bond prices down and yields on 30-year Treasurys up from 6 percent to 6.4 percent -- by merely suggesting that the economy was healthier than believed, many experts concluded that the market had already factored another 0.25 percent cut into bond prices. That means bonds won't rally significantly unless the Fed lowers rates by half a percentage point or more. <p> Yet the Fed may not lower rates. "They have to keep rates high enough to maintain the dollar's strength and attract foreign capital to fund the deficit," says James B. Stack, editor of Inves Tech Market Analyst in Whitefish, Montana. In short, the potential for gains in long-term bonds isn't nearly what it was17 months ago when 30-year Treasurys yielded 8 percent, and the risks are growing. Best advice: Mix short-term with intermediate-or long-term issues.   <p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Economy, Retirement Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
