	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-What's Next?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-What's Next?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Jubak<p>The market is flirting with the edge of the cliff. After falling 161 points on Monday, July 15, the Dow Jones Industrial Average began Tuesday by plunging another 167 points. But then, on the verge of full-fledged panic, the market rallied. The Dow finished that day up
9 points and then roared uphill by 87 points on Thursday. On Friday, the Dow gave back 37 points.<p>What is behind this extraordinary volatility? Earnings are the clear culprit. The previous week, blue-chip bellwether <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>  reported second-quarter earnings some 14 cents a share below analysts' estimates, and <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> signaled Wall Street that it would have trouble meeting expectations for its third quarter. When, on July 15, <a name="NASD:AMAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12647"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Applied Materials</b></a>, the biggest maker of manufacturing equipment for the semiconductor industry, announced that it expected earnings to fall short, too, the market had heard enough. Technology stocks went into free fall -- taking the broader indexes with them. Only surprisingly strong earnings from <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>  the next day -- the chip maker reported second-quarter earnings well above estimates -- stemmed the rout.<p>Why are a few bad numbers enough to send Wall Street into a panic? The announcements seemed to confirm a pattern. After seeing earnings growth of almost 15 percent in 1993, 40 percent in 1994, and 11 percent in 1995, analysts began 1996 hoping for growth of 10 to 15 percent for the year ahead. That prediction has been repeatedly revised downward. Now the optimists believe earnings on the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index are likely to grow by just 9 percent on the year, says Ben Zacks of Zacks Investment Research. At the low end, Kurt Walters, vice president of research at Safian Investment Research, is calling for growth of merely 1 to 3 percent.<p>Even a drop to 9 percent is enough to rattle investors. The stocks in the S&P 500 recently traded at a price-to-earnings ratio slightly below 19. That's not out of line if earnings are growing at 15 percent a year, but if earnings for 1996 come in at 9 percent -- or worse yet, at just 1 percent above 1995's level -- this market is ripe for a fall.<p>How much will earnings growth slow in 1996? No one knows -- 
and the major reason is uncertainty about the economy. As a whole, it grew at a weak 2.25 percent annual rate in the first quarter of 1996, but industrial production came in at a robust 5.5 percent in the second quarter. Economic growth "could be positive by a big number; it could be negative by a lot," says Zacks. "No one knows. Alan Greenspan doesn't know. Wall Street analysts don't know."<p>With the macroeconomic data giving so little indication of the direction of the economy, investors are forced to glean clues from every earnings report. And right now, these terse statements don't make for comforting reading.<p>For example, analysts saw Applied Materials' announcement of weak earnings as a strong indication that capital spending (the money spent on the machines that are used to make everything from computer chips to lug nuts) was slowing. A few days later, chip maker <a name="NYSE:LSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13932"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LSI Logic</b></a> announced that it was expecting second-quarter revenues to decline from last year's level and was therefore delaying the start-up of a new manufacturing plant for at least six months. Voil! The decline in capital spending was anecdotally confirmed.<p>Investors are also watching the news companies report after they announce earnings. In the wake of its disappointing earnings, Motorola reported that it had cut 145 jobs at its semiconductor plant in Austin, Texas -- the first layoffs at Motorola in more than a decade. Clearly the company believes that the problems it faces require painful and dramatic action. Hewlett-Packard sent investors a message, too, when it announced that it would take a $150 
million charge to exit the disk-drive business. Companies tend to take write-offs when they've already decided the quarter will be a disaster. So HP, too, was signaling more than a temporary dip in business. Analysts reacted predictably.<p>Owning shares while Wall Street is ratcheting down its expectations is always painful. Just as the herd drove prices for many stocks -- and perhaps the market as a whole -- to unsustainable levels, now it may be about to send solid stocks tumbling down.<p>But this isn't a time to buy just anything on a dip -- a lot of junk stocks are trading 50 percent below their 52-week highs. Look for companies you'd like to own five years from now and calculate a target price.<p>Since earnings growth is slowing, first take a whack out of analysts' projections -- cut Hewlett-Packard's earnings by another 20 cents, for example, to $2.30 a share. Figure the lowest p/e that investors have paid for the company's earnings in the past five years by checking a publication such as Value Line Investment Survey. Take that low annual p/e (13.4 for HP) and multiply it by the discounted earnings to get a rough price of $31 a share. The stock could well go lower if the market panics, but it will bounce back. HP isn't there yet -- its recent low is $38.25 -- but some other quality stocks are. And in a volatile market, a hungry investor should know what price makes him salivate.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
