	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-What They're Recommending</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which he considers the recommended stock attractive. The newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the July 18 publishing deadline.<p>
Al Frank, The Prudent Spectator
Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation.
<a name="AMEX:GNA"></a><b>Gainsco</b> (AMEX: GNA) Up to $10
I like financial stocks in general right now -- they have a low price-to-earnings ratio relative to their growth rate -- and this is one of my favorites. Gainsco (Fort Worth, Texas) is a property and casualty insurer specializing in what's called excess and surplus insurance, primarily for commercial vehicles and auto garages. The bulk of its business is in Texas, but the company is aggressively getting into California and Illinois. Gainsco has had a 20 percent return on equity for the past decade, and I think it can maintain that rate in the years ahead. At around $9.50 a share, the stock is trading at 12 times trailing earnings and only 11 times my estimated earnings for 1996.<p>
Jim McCamant, Medical Technology Stock Letter
Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.
<a name="NASD:CHIR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12972"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chiron</b></a> (Nasdaq: CHIR) Up to $120
Chiron (Emeryville, California) is our top pick among the larger biotech stocks. The company's excellent management team is using outstanding science to build a world-class pharmaceutical company (over half of Chiron's sales are generated overseas). Chiron has not only the best product pipeline in the biotech industry but also a number of exciting products nearing FDA approval. Over the longer term, the company's vaccine and gene-therapy programs have the potential to fundamentally change the pharmaceutical industry. With a number of new products expected to receive approval next year, Chiron should gain increasing momentum.<p>
Michael Murphy, California Technology Stock Letter
Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.
<a name="NASD:RZYM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51693"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ribozome Pharmaceuticals</b></a> (Nasdaq: RZYM) Up to $13
Ribozyme Pharmaceuticals (Boulder, Colorado) is one of the new generation of biotech companies working inside the cell. Ribozymes, the company's namesake products, are laboratory-altered forms of ribonucleic acid, or RNA, that have the ability to inhibit protein production by going through the cell wall and selectively destroying messenger RNA before it can create problems. The treatment has very few side effects. The company also has a big deal with Chiron to develop five drugs; the first product is HIV-related. After a big run-up in price earlier this year, the stock has fallen back to its IPO price, which, based on all the money invested in R&D, is cheap.<p>
Louis Navellier, MPT Review
Uses modern portfolio theory to identify theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks. 
<a name="NASD:ZTEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16255"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Zytec</b></a> (Nasdaq: ZTEC) Up to $18.50
Zytec (Eden Prairie, Minnesota), which manufactures and repairs electronic power supplies for computers and printers, has been highly charged all year. Analysts have been consistently making upward revisions of earnings over the past few months, and big institutions have been buying up the stock quickly. While the stock's high standard deviation indicates a broad range of volatility, we are encouraged by an extremely high alpha, which indicates a strong return for reasons uncorrelated to the market. Of the 7,200 stocks I follow, Zytec ranks at number 26. That, combined with a high risk/reward rating, makes Zytec highly attractive.<p><p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
