<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here--
the maximum at which he considers it attractive. The manager also 
may have sold the stock after July 18, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends they conduct their own due diligence.<p>
Preston Athey, <a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</b></a>
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million. 
<a name="NASD:DGTL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14341"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Digital Systems International</b></a> (Nasdaq: DGTL) Up to $16
One of the great values created by the recent tech correction is Digital Systems (Redmond, Washington), a supplier of computerized telephone systems for customer-service centers. The stock has fallen 50 percent from its 12-month high of $24 a share. A 1994 shift away from proprietary hardware toward specialized software solutions that increase efficiency and save money has helped the company's sales and earnings rebound and should result in 20 percent annual growth over the next two years. Despite the fact that the company has no debt and has $3.50 a share in cash, the stock sells for less than 14 times its 1996 earnings estimate of $1 a share.<p>
James P. Craig, <a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term. 
<a name="NYSE:EDS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41915"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>EDS</b></a> (NYSE: EDS) Up to $57
Computer-systems giant EDS (Plano, Texas) has seen its stock held back by the <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> pension fund's liquidation of 20 million shares of EDS stock (EDS was formerly owned by GM). But like rival Computer Sci-ences, EDS will benefit from a much larger rise in 
outsourcing than people expect. EDS's contracts, which tend to be with large companies, are sometimes worth billions of dollars apiece (this kind of outsourcing can save a company 20 to 25 percent on its information systems). With more than $60 billion of business in backlog and a listing in the S&P 500 Stock Index expected in the near future, EDS could easily reach $70 a share in a year.<p>
Shelby M.C. Davis, <a name="NYVTX"></a><b>New York Venture Fund</b>
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
<a name="NYSE:HAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10697"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Halliburton</b></a> (NYSE: HAL) Up to $56
Dick Cheney, still in his first year as CEO, is taking anything but a defensive approach at energy-services and construction concern Halliburton (Dallas). This truly global company (it operates in a hundred countries, and more than half its earnings are generated overseas) has cut costs and is focusing on production and fieldwork for the major oil companies; these outsourcing contracts increasingly include lucrative bonus incentives for Halliburton. Industry revenues are rising at a double-digit pace, and profit margins are expanding. The company is poised to earn $2.50 a share in 1996 and $3 a share in 1997. This could be a $75 stock in three years.<p>
Daniel B. Leonard, <a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a>
<a name="NYSE:NEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11050"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>National Education Corp.</b></a> (NYSE: NEC) Up to $18
I recommended National Education Corporation (Irvine, California) back in January, and it still gets straight A's in my book. NEC is the largest technical-training company in the U.S. and a leading publisher of educational software. The company had a few problems a couple of years ago with a narrow product base and a slow delivery system, but under new CEO Sam Yau, NEC has focused efforts on the growing market for computer-based training and educational systems. Earnings were down in 1994 and 1995, but I'm looking for them to reach 50 to 55 cents a share this year and 70 to 75 cents a share in 1997. My target for the stock is $25 within a year.<p>
William J. Nasgovitz, <a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a>
Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued. 
<a name="AMEX:SST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12319"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Shelter Components</b></a> (AMEX: SST) Up to $33
Shelter Components (Elkhart, Indiana) sells a wide array of roducts--carpeting, wallboard, bathroom fixtures--to the manufactured-housing and recreational-vehicle industries. Manufactured housing has become a partic-ularly strong growth area and now accounts for a third of all new housing starts. Shelter, whose national distribution capabilities give it a competitive advantage in the field, has been increasing its market share right along with its revenue per manufactured home: In 1990 it made $766 per home; in 1995 it made $1,365. At nine times estimated 1996 earnings of $1.45 a share, Shelter is an excellent value, and insiders have been buying.<p>
Eric E. Rayback, <a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a>
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.
<a name="NYSE:JOS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10828"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Jostens</b></a> (NYSE: JOS) Up to $23
Jostens (Minneapolis) makes and sells yearbooks and class rings. The company's stock, which fell recently in reaction to investors' concerns that near-term earnings would be below expectations, yields 5.1 percent at its recent price of $17.25 a share. Jostens's management is very oriented toward shareholders, as evidenced by its repurchase of seven million shares at $24 a share in September 1995. I'm looking for the company to earn $1.25 a share in fiscal 1996 and $1.50 the following year. In addition, management has indicated it will take further steps to enhance shareholder value should the stock continue to languish.<p>
Ralph Wagner/Chuck McQuaid, <a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a>
Hold stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.
<a name="NASD:IVCR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13827"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invacare</b></a> (Nasdaq: IVCR) Up to $25
Invacare (Elyria, Ohio) manufactures home health-care and rehabilitation equipment, such as wheelchairs, nursing beds, and oxygen concentrators. The combination of an aging population and astronomical hospital costs has been a boon to home health care, and Invacare is poised to prosper. This low-cost producer has a leading market share (20 percent) in a $3 billion worldwide industry. Led by hard-charging CEO Mal Mixon, who owns better than 5 percent of the company's common stock, Invacare is also making acquisitions to complement its product line and is expanding distribution, particularly in Europe. The com-pany should earn $1.30 a share in 1996 and $1.55 in 1997.<p>
Donald A. Yacktman, <a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.
<a name="NASD:BARE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Barefoot</b></a> (Nasdaq: BARE) Up to $12
Lawn-care concern Barefoot (Worthington, Ohio) has not bloomed since I recommended it last April. Blame it on the weather. Nevertheless, the company's strategy of acquiring mom-and-pop stores (it now has 59 company outlets and 44 franchise operations) should compensate for a tough second quarter and carry Barefoot to a successful finish in 1996. Selling at about ten times my 1996 earnings estimate of 95 cents a share, the stock still looks incredibly cheap, though bad weather always remains a threat. The company generates a lot of excess cash flow, which it uses to buy back stock--
invariably good news for investors.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

