<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>Twenty-four securities firms have settled a civil antitrust suit brought by the Justice Department regarding allegations of price-fixing on the Nasdaq stock market. The settlement, which still must be approved by a federal judge, follows a two-year government investigation into allegations that the firms conspired to cheat customers by creating artificially wide margins between the bid and asked price for Nasdaq stocks. Government officials said that this practice cost the investing public millions of dollars. The two dozen firms__including <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, Smith Barney, Dean Witter, Salomon Brothers, <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a>, and Goldman, Sachs__did not admit any wrongdoing as part of the settlement. The settlement prohibits the firms from engaging in further collusion and provides for greater oversight, including requiring firms to monitor and tape-record communications with their Nasdaq traders and submit quarterly compliance reports to the Justice Department. Separately, The Wall Street Journal reported that Justice Department documents demonstrate that the National Association of Securities Dealers, the self-regulatory organization that oversees the Nasdaq market, knew about the anticompetitive practices associated with trading spreads as early as 1990.<p>A study by Prophet Market Research & Consulting of San Francisco has found that stockbrokers often dispense specific investment advice with little or no basic knowledge of a customer's individual needs. Prophet used 93 "mystery shoppers" who presented themselves as first-time investors to 21 brokerage firms. Prophet said that many of the brokers who dealt with its shoppers failed to inquire about even such basic matters as the income level or tax bracket of the customer. More than a quarter of the brokers provided investment advice without asking about a customer's investment history or willingness to tolerate risk, the study reports.<p>The Securities and Exchange Commission may require mutual-fund companies to provide customers with graphics that illustrate the risks associated with investing in specific funds. The SEC said that it is currently reviewing comments from fund companies about the concept and will disclose further details in the coming months.<p>Prudential Insurance Co. of America has reached an agreement with state insurance regulators under which it will pay a $35 million fine, create a program to provide as much as $1.2 billion in restitution to millions of policyholders, and further reform its own sales practices. The agreement results from a lengthy investigation by 30 states that followed widespread complaints that Prudential agents had misled customers about the cost of 
insurance policies.<p>The National Association of Securities Dealers has said that it is investigating a number of stockbrokers after uncovering evidence of pervasive cheating on licensing exams. Among other things, the NASD reported that it has learned that dozens of brokers may have used proxies (in one case for a $2,500 fee) to take the exams on their behalf.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

