<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Money, Money, Money<p>By Todd G. Buchholz<p>"A specter is haunting Europe -- the specter of Communism." So Marx and Engels began The Communist Manifesto in 1848. Today a new specter looms before continental capitalists. Plans for a single European currency -- a major part of the European Monetary Union -- are moving forward, and the next few months may determine whether deutsche marks, francs, and lire disappear in favor of "Euros." <p>Those supporting union point to the time and money wasted on exchanging money and doing business in different currencies. If, for example, you visit Europe with $100 in cash, convert your currency, and cross, say, eight national borders, you'll exhaust half your $100 just on conversion commissions. Transcontinental companies incur additional costs from hedging against currency fluctuations.<p>Pro-unionists also argue that, by tying their monetary policies to a single European Central Bank dominated by the German Bundesbank, countries like Italy and Spain will no longer be able to unilaterally adopt inflationary measures, so investors will buy their bonds at lower interest rates. Yield spreads have already begun to narrow between Germany's bonds and those of its neighbors. From January 3 to June 20, the interest-rate differential between Spanish and German bonds narrowed from 3.57 percent to 2.4 percent; the squeeze in Italy was even more impressive, from 4.75 percent to 2.87. This suggests that the market is starting to take EMU seriously, though other factors were also at work, including the election of market-friendly prime ministers in Spain and Italy.<p>Still, most British and American economists think EMU is a mistake. A single currency managed by the ECB will make it almost impossible to deal with the varying economic and political pressures faced by each member country. For example, if bumper harvests depress farm incomes in southern Europe at the same time the ECB is running a tight monetary policy to control wage inflation in northern Europe, the result could be a depression in Club Med (Italy, Spain, and Greece). <p>Euro enthusiasts like to call EMU a "United States of Europe" and argue that if California doesn't have its own currency why should France? The difference is that U.S. workers are mobile, moving from region to region as job markets shift. Can you imagine Germans giving up their citizenship to go to Ireland? In fact, EMU could aid xenophobic (some would say fascist) politicians who oppose immigration.<p>All of this will come to a head this fall. The charter for EMU, called the Maastricht Treaty, requires that countries reduce their budget deficits to 3 percent of gross domestic product; so far only Denmark, Ireland, and Luxembourg pass this test. Most others fall somewhere between Germany (4.1 percent) and Italy (6.4 percent). France (at about 4.4 percent) must put on paper a program to cut the budget. Since its economy is stagnant and tax revenues are lagging government estimates, Prime Minister Alain Jupp may have a terrible time making ends meet if he still plans to hit the EMU target. <p>Will Germans surrender their monetary sovereignty if the French make only a halfhearted effort to meet the Maastricht Treaty? I doubt it. So Jupp's budget cuts may be severe. The French bond and stock markets will likely get hammered this fall. And if the French get hit, you can bet that the rest of non-German Europe will, too.
Contributing editor Todd Buchholz is a managing director of a New York based international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Economy<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
