	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Fixed Income</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Jubak<p>The bond market continues to put its faith in Alan Greenspan. With stronger than expected job growth raising fears of wage-driven inflation, interest rates inched upward from 6.91 percent on July 1 to 7.19 on July 8. But then the tide ebbed__rates fell back to 6.92 by July 18.<p>That day, in testimony to Congress, the Federal Reserve chairman stressed his pleasure at the current combination of moderate growth and quiescent inflation; at an annual rate of 2.8 percent for the first six months of the year, inflation was about a half point lower than in the first half of 1995. Greenspan seemed to indicate that the Fed would not raise rates before its August 20 meeting__and that any rise at that time was likely to be moderate. Or so the market concluded.<p>Which may be setting up an unpleasant surprise. The gap between the yields on three-month and two-year Treasury bills widens when inflation seems a danger, because investors demand to be compensated for the risk that inflation will erode their capital. But on July 18, the difference was a narrow 89 basis points. If investors even suspect that the Fed is relaxing in the fight against inflation, they'll demand a much bigger premium on the two-year bills. And that will send the price of those and longer bonds down.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
