<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-What They're Recommending</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their 
favorite domestic stocks. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which he considers the recommended stock attractive. The newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the May 24 publishing deadline.<p>AL FRANK
THE PRUDENT SPECULATOR
Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation.
<a name="NASD:COHU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11828"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>COHU</b></a>  UP TO $28  Nasdaq: COHU
Cohu (San Diego) is one of the world's largest makers of equipment for semiconductor testing, and it also manufactures closed-circuit-television, metal-detection, and microwave equipment. Earnings have increased every year for the past five years, from 32 cents a share in 1991 to $2.46 a share in 1995. Trading at less than nine times 1996 estimated earnings of $3 a share, this value-priced growth stock has a 33 percent return on equity and no long-term debt. The stock came down with the semiconductor group earlier this year and then didn't participate in the April rally, though earnings have stayed strong. I expect the stock to hit $55 a share in three to five years.<p>JIM McCAMANT
MEDICAL TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER
Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.
<a name="NASD:TCEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14866"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T CELL SCIENCES</b></a>  UP TO $5   Nasdaq: TCEL
T Cell Sciences (Needham, Massachusetts) is one of the few remaining biotech bargains. The company's lead therapeutic product, TP 10, prevents the complement system (part of the immune system) from triggering excessive inflammation in response to foreign material. Phase-two trials are underway for the use of TP 10 to treat adult-respiratory-distress syndrome and should begin soon for its use in treating cardiac reperfusion (a reaction that occurs when blood is reintroduced to the heart after the heart has been shut off). Announcements of trial results and a large corporate partnership later this year should help move the stock toward my target of $10 a share.<p>MICHAEL MURPHY
CALIFORNIA TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER
Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.
<a name="NASD:COCN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15964"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>COCENSYS</b></a>   UP TO $11   Nasdaq: COCN
Biopharmaceutical company CoCensys (Irvine, California) has recently patented two compounds for the treatment of neurological and psychiatric disorders of the central nervous system. The more promising of the two -- CCD 1042 -- is an anti-convulsant designed to prevent episodes of epilepsy. Phase-two trials in France, for children, have moved from the hospital to the home, a sign that they're going well. I anticipate that the full results, to be announced this fall, will be sufficiently positive to merit adult trials. Cash flow is good, and the company, which has already spent roughly $40 million in R&D, plans to devote at least $12 million annually in the future.<p>LOUIS NAVELLIER
MPT REVIEW
Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.
<a name="NASD:OLGC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15951"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ORTHOLOGIC</b></a>   UP TO $30   Nasdaq: OLGC
OrthoLogic (Phoenix) makes a lot of sense. This is a great niche company -- it develops non-invasive devices that use magnetic-field technology to help bones heal faster than with traditional methods -- and has a relatively small market capitalization of $480 million. The company's earnings are phenomenal, and the stock is taking off. 
In the first quarter of 1996, both sales and earnings were 170 percent higher than in the same period a year earlier. Over the past three months, analysts have raised their earnings estimates by 33 percent. The stock has a high alpha (15.38) and a low beta (0.67), signaling that it is not closely correlated with the overall market.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
