	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Keeping up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Keeping up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>>THE TREASURY DEPARTMENT plans to begin selling a new class of bonds that will offer returns indexed to inflation. These inflation-adjusted bonds, which could be sold as early as the end of this year, will offer holders lower up-front yields but also a guaranteed upward adjustment should inflation begin to rise over the life of the security. The Treasury said many details of the plan have yet to be resolved, including what measure of inflation to use. But the department said it expects that the new bonds will allow the government to raise money at a lower cost, while providing fixed-income investors protection against the biggest threat to their portfolios__the erosion associated with inflation.<p>><a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MERRILL LYNCH</b></a> has told the securities and Exchange Commission that it is reviewing its practice of paying hefty sign-on bonuses to brokers hired from rival firms. Regulators have raised questions about the bonuses, saying they could create conflicts for clients. Merrill Lynch told The Wall Street Journal that it doesn't agree with the SEC's concern but would nevertheless consider altering its policy to eliminate even the appearance of a conflict.<p>>SMITH BARNEY will soon allow its customers to take Smith Barney mutual funds with them when they switch to another brokerage. PaineWebber and Prudential Securities also plan to permit a form of portability__one that involves only these two firms. Currently, most full-service brokerages require customers to liquidate their mutual-fund accounts__often at a steep price__when they transfer their business to another firm.<p>>The American Medical Association has begun urging investors to sell shares of any mutual fund that invests in tobacco stocks. The group said it will publish an annual list of the funds that hold shares in tobacco companies. According to the AMA, 1,474 mutual funds currently hold the stocks or bonds of 13 tobacco companies. The AMA also said it would help draw public attention to funds that shed such stocks.<p>>A study prepared for the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation has found that banks often fail to tell their customers that mutual-fund investments aren't federally insured. The study reports that, when professional evaluators telephoned 1,200 banks asking for information about investing in mutual funds, only 45 percent of the callers were alerted about the lack of federal insurance__a warning required by government bank regulators. A separate survey, prepared by Prophet Market Research &Consulting of San Francisco, discovered that Union Bank of California was the best at complying with federal disclosure requirements, while Comerica was the worst.<p>>NASD Regulation, the new regulatory and enforcement unit of the National Association of Securities Dealers, has said that it will hire 131 employees this year, raising its total number of regulatory officials to approximately 1,600. The NASDR also said that it will be restructured into seven divisions, one of which will be a unit dedicated to national enforcement.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

