<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-From Vinik to Stansky</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-From Vinik to Stansky</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Will a new manager change Magellan, or will the fund change him?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Jeffrey Vinik's May 23 resignation from the helm of the <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Magellan Fund</b></a> gives rise to two questions: What's the outlook for Magellan, the world's largest mutual fund? And what's the outlook for mutual funds now that they've become such a mainstay for investors?<p>The answer to the first question is of obvious interest to the folks with $57 billion on the line at Magellan. The fund's new manager, Robert Stansky, comes aboard from the $8.5 billion <a name="FUND:FDGRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FDGRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Growth Company Fund</b></a>, where he built a solid track record__an annualized total return of 17.44 percent for the five years ended April 30, 1996, compared with 16.50 percent for Magellan. Stansky, 40, put in three years as a research associate at Magellan back when Peter Lynch ran the fund.<p>If Stansky's record is an accurate indicator of how he'll approach his new job, investors can expect a more cautious Magellan__one that behaves much more like a traditional large-cap growth fund. Stansky's former portfolio was full of traditional growth issues such as <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett- Packard</b></a>. Fidelity Growth Company has done well in years when growth investing has prospered: In 1995, for example, it beat the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index by 2.08 percentage points. It has lagged when the market has been hostile to growth stocks, such as in 1994, when the fund trailed the S&P by 3.54 percentage points.<p>It's also quite possible that investors will see a new, more freewheeling Bob Stansky at Magellan. Fidelity has always viewed its flagship as an aggressive fund, and there is no indication Fidelity has shifted its thinking even a bit.<p>Vinik's departure was his own idea. He was under no pressure from Fidelity to quit. Although there was concern within the company about the fund's recent performance, no one in a position of authority was calling for Vinik's scalp. "If there was any pressure on Jeff, it was either self-imposed or it came from places outside Fidelity, such as the media," says a top Fidelity executive.<p>To assume that Magellan will change now that Vinik has left is to ignore the fund's history__under Vinik and his predecessors. It is also to ignore the powerful incentive any new manager will feel to use the fund's market clout and its unique role at Fidelity to attempt to score hefty gains for investors.<p>Vinik's big bet on technology stocks in mid-1995 was widely misinterpreted as an admission that Magellan had grown too large to continue as a stock-picking fund. Vinik, the theory went, had decided the only way to make a big score was to take risky sector bets.
This view gained credence when Vinik reduced Magellan's technology holdings from about 44 percent of the portfolio to just 4 percent at the end of 1995 and put the cash he raised into bonds instead.<p>The problem with this line of reasoning is that Vinik hadn't really done anything new at all. Like other managers at Fidelity (including Lynch), he had always made big sector bets, relying in part on the strong research and analysis that Fidelity churns out for its portfolio bosses. That approach was in place from the day Vinik took over the fund from Morris Smith in July 1992. He immediately cut Magellan's exposure__radically__to the consumer-company stocks Lynch and Smith had emphasized. <p>Vinik's aggressive style frequently paid off. For example, he sold much of his position in <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> prior to the meltdown in tobacco stocks known as Marlboro Friday. He built his big position in technology stocks when they were out of favor. True, his latest move into bonds has been less successful. Then again, he hasn't been proved wrong, either.<p>It remains to be seen if Bob Stansky will stick with the style he has used at past funds or will run Magellan like it has always been run. There is pressure to become more conservative. In a world increasingly dominated by the administrators in charge of 401(k) plans, many of the big mutual-fund companies are moving away from a star system of managers, because they know that competing for 401(k) dollars means offering pre-dictable commodity funds__funds that fill a defined slot in a marketing plan and never deviate from their objective. <p>At the same time, a more cautious approach isn't likely to produce the sort of investment gains Magellan shareholders have come to expect over the years. In Magellan's case, predictability has always meant unpredictability__ at least in the short run. Magellan's zigs and zags (hardly the sign of the cumbersome portfolio some critics suggest the fund has become) have been the reason it has been able to beat the market.<p>A newly conservative Magellan might make the new forces dominating the fund industry more comfortable with the fund, but it wouldn't necessarily be the best thing for Magellan's shareholders. Magellan's character under its new manager will tell investors whether there's still room for strong individual managers with unique styles at the biggest fund families.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:CSCO">Cisco Systems, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:MSFT">Microsoft Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:HWP">Hewlett-Packard Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:MO">Philip Morris Companies Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:FMAGX">Fidelity Magellan Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:FDGRX">Fidelity Growth Company Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
