<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which he considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after May 24, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends they conduct their own due diligence.<p>PRESTON ATHEY
<a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE SMALL CAP VALUE</b></a>
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.
<a name="NASD:TBCC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14868"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TBC</b></a> UP TO $10 Nasdaq: TBCC
The wheels are turning at TBC (Memphis), the country's largest distributor of private-brand replacement tires for cars and light trucks. (The best-known name among the company's many brands is Cooper.) Since TBC's long string of sales and earnings increases ended in 1992, the stock has fallen from $18 a share to less than $7, despite the appointment of a new CEO and a company buyback of 20 percent of its stock. I expect a recently proposed acquisition and a rebound in tire demand to drive 1996 earnings up 15 percent, to 72 cents a share. TBC is poised for two years of above-average growth, and that makes the stock look cheap.<p>JAMES P. CRAIG
<a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JANUS FUND</b></a>
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.
<a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WELLS FARGO</b></a> UP TO $260 NYSE: WFC
Since I recommended it last month, banking giant Wells Fargo (San Francisco) has seen its stock come down on fears of higher interest rates. But higher rates can have a positive effect -- the profitability of Wells Fargo's basic business (lending) increases as the yield curve steepens. In addition, a strengthening economy makes credit delinquency less likely. Down roughly 10 percent from its 12-month high of $268 a share, the stock looks even cheaper now than before. The company has also begun its share-repurchase program, and everything else is in place for long-term growth. My target for the stock is still about $320, a gain from here of more than 30 percent.<p>SHELBY M. C. DAVIS
<a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NEW YORK VENTURE FUND</b></a>
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
<a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDONALD'S</b></a> UP TO $48 NYSE: MCD
McDonald's (Oak Brook, Illinois) stock is a value meal in itself. The company derives 54 percent of its earnings from overseas stores. As this trend increases, higher profit margins and return on equity abroad should drive up the stock's price-to-earnings multiple. At home, the company is opening satellite units in high-traffic areas like gas stations (Amoco and Chevron) and retail stores (<a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>). The growth story is pretty simple: McDonald's currently has almost 19,000 stores and could easily have 30,000 by the year 2000. I expect the stock price to mirror the 15 to 20 percent annual earnings growth of the company.<p>DANIEL B. LEONARD
<a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>INVESCO STRATEGIC PORTFOLIOS TECHNOLOGY</b></a>
Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.
<a name="NYSE:IGT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13812"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>INT'L GAME TECHNOLOGY</b></a> up to $18 NYSE: IGT
International Game Technology (Reno, Nevada) is a good bet. In addition to being the world's largest manufacturer of traditional slot machines and gaming software, IGT produces wide-area networks that allow slot players in several locations to compete for common jackpots (this setup is known as a progressive system). Though the U.S. gaming market is slowing, the rest of the world, especially South America and the former Soviet Union, will take up the slack and then some. Given IGT's projected annual earnings growth of 20 percent, the stock is a good value at about 15 times estimated fiscal 1997 earnings of $1.05 a share. My target for the stock is $22 a share within a year.<p>WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ
<a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>HEARTLAND VALUE FUND</b></a> 
Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued.
<a name="NASD:CWEI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16203"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CLAYTON WILLIAMS ENERGY</b></a> up to $8 Nasdaq: CWEI
Clayton Williams (Midland, Texas) is a leader in horizontal drilling for oil and gas. After two difficult years, the company has restructured, and the founder has taken back the reins. The first quarter of 1996 was profitable (versus a loss a year ago), and I estimate earnings will be 40 cents a share this year. The stock sells at only 1.7 times 1996 estimated cash flow of $4 a share and slightly less than its replacement value (the value of the reserves in the ground) of $8 a share. A great kicker: The company owns a lot of acreage in a hot new field in East Texas called the Cotton Valley Pinnacle Reef Play, where a competitor has made a substantial discovery.<p>ERIC E. RYBACK
<a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LINDNER DIVIDEND FUND</b></a>
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.
<a name="NYSE:JNC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41931"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JOHN NUVEEN</b></a> UP TO $30 NYSE: JNC
Nuveen (Chicago) is a large underwriter of closed-end municipal-bond funds and a manager of tax-free investments. It has more than $25 billion in closed-end funds (out of $32 billion under management), money that can't be withdrawn by redemption. In addition, roughly 80 percent of Nuveen's revenues come from investment-advisory fees. The company has a new CEO, who plans to broaden Nuveen's offerings to include equity and non-municipal bond funds, and to look for ways to enhance shareholder value, including stock buybacks. I believe the stock, which has lagged on the fear that tax reform will hurt muni bonds, is worth over $40 a share.<p>RALPH WANGER
CHUCK McQUAID
<a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ACORN FUND</b></a>
Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.
<a name="NASD:TRBS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17163"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TEXAS REGIONAL BANCSHARES</b></a> up to $25 Nasdaq: TRBS
Texas Regional Bancshares (McAllen, Texas) is the largest bank in the Rio Grande Valley, where the economy is benefiting from NAFTA trade, tourism, and immigration (the valley's population is expected to grow 16 percent by the year 2000). In the face of last year's peso plunge and Mexican recession, TRB's loans increased 20 percent while nonperforming assets fell to only 0.8 percent of loans. Acquisitions of neighboring banks in May 1996 doubled TRB's asset size and increased the company's estimated 1997 earnings by 50 percent. TRB, which is probably worth $30 a share to a buyer today, will likely be worth $50 a share after a few years of growth.<p>DONALD A. YACKTMAN
<a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>YACKTMAN FUND</b></a>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.
<a name="NYSE:TMK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11491"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TORCHMARK</b></a> up to $44 NYSE: TMK
Torchmark (Birmingham, Alabama) is a holding company with mostly insurance-related subsidiaries. It has considered spinning off its three major areas of business -- direct life insurance, specialty insurance, and money management (it owns the mutual-fund company Waddell & Reed) -- but might not do so because of legal complications. At roughly ten times 1996 estimated earnings of $4.30 a share, Torchmark's stock is cheap and has a solid growth rate and an excellent long-term record. The stock is trading in the middle of its 12-month price range but is worth a lot more: Its private-market value is at least $65 a share.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

