	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-A Bond Market Adrift</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Clint Willis<p>The bond market continues to reflect professional traders' uncertainty over the direction of the economy and inflation. Individual investors should watch to see if events confirm one direction or another, but shouldn't make big bets now. In early May, inflation fears sparked by delays in balancing the budget and signs of renewed economic growth sent yields on the 30-year Treasury to over 7 percent. Then, in mid-May, reports suggested consumer spending was slackening, reviving hopes that inflation and interest rates would stay low. Long-term Treasury yields subsequently eased to 6.8 percent. The future isn't any more certain. "Consumers are in a lot better shape than people think," says William Dudley, director of U.S. economic research for Goldman, Sachs, who figures the Federal Reserve will raise rates in August. On the other hand, Zane Brown, director of fixed-income investing at Lord Abbett, remains optimistic: Signs of weakness (such as declines in home sales and strong overseas demand for Treasurys) should prop up bond prices. The bond market has already discounted a Clinton victory, he adds. "Any change in that outlook would likely cause yields to decline by reviving hopes for progress toward a modified balanced budget." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Retirement Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

