<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after April 22, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these eight managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends that they conduct their own due diligence.<p>PRESTON ATHEY
<a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE SMALL CAP VALUE</b></a><p>Invests in value stocks 
with market capitalizations under $250 million.
HANCOCK FABRICS  UP TO $13  NYSE: HKF<p><a name="NYSE:HKF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10699"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hancock Fabrics</b></a> (Tupelo, Mississippi) sells fabric, notions, and craft supplies for the home-sewing and home-decoration markets through 500 stores in 33 states under the names Hancock Fabrics, Minnesota Fabrics, and Fabric Warehouse. The company has suffered through a five-year industry recession caused by overexpansion and heavy competition, but its recent results suggest that a turnaround is at hand. The stock sells at 20 times a depressed 1996 earnings estimate of 50 cents a share but at less than 8 times the $1.25 a share I think it can earn when margins recover to normal levels. Meanwhile, a 3 percent yield pays investors to wait.<p>JAMES P. CRAIG
<a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a><p>Invests primarily in large growth companies with 
the idea of preserving capital over the long term.
WELLS FARGO  UP TO $265  NYSE: WFC<p>Banking giant <a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wells Fargo</b></a>(San Francisco) has been successful at boosting its revenues by aggressively going after small business loans. In addition, cost savings from the recent merger with Los Angelesbased First Interstate Bancorp are turning out to be greater than expected. Within the next year, Wells Fargo should also get back to its pre-merger level of return on equity (20 percent) and resume its high rate of share buybacks (10 percent a year). I think the stock will trade within the next 12 months at 11 times 1998 cash earnings (before accounting for goodwill) of $29 a share. At this valuation, the stock would reach $319 a share, a return of roughly 30 percent.<p>SHELBY M. C. DAVIS
<a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a><p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
GENERAL RE  UP TO $148  NYSE: GRN
<a name="NYSE:GRN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10643"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Re</b></a> (Stamford, Connecticut), a world leader in reinsurance, has made a home-run cash acquisition of German-based Cologne Re. The deal increases its percentage of international premiums (a higher growth area than domestic premiums) to over 40 percent of total premiums. I also think American-style reinsurance products are about to gain favor in Europe. General Re, a AAA-rated company, is accounting for the deal conservatively. Now that the company is a true multinational, its price-to-earnings ratio should rise from 12 to 15, giving the stock an 18-month target price of about $180 a share on estimated 1997 earnings of $12 a share.<p>DANIEL B. LEONARD
<a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a><p>Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.
GLOBAL MARINE  up to $12.50  NYSE: GLM<p><a name="NYSE:GLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10662"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Global Marine</b></a> (Houston) is an offshore oil-and-gas drilling company whose operations are focused primarily in the Gulf of Mexico. This has been a good stock, but I think it can do even better in the future. Natural-gas prices, which have risen substantially and should stay at high levels for at least the next year, are leading to a big pickup in drilling. The resulting high utilization of rigs and higher oil and gas prices will benefit Global Marine greatly. I expect the company, which made 23 cents a share last year, to earn 40 cents a share in 1996 and 70 cents a share in 1997. The stock should hit $16 by the end of this year, a gain of roughly 45 percent from current levels.<p>WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ
<a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund </b></a><p>Buys stocks of domestic 
small-cap companies believed to be undervalued.
CROWN BOOKS  up to $10  Nasdaq: CRWN<p><a name="NASD:CRWN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13140"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Crown Books</b></a> (Landover, Maryland) has 178 stores in Washington, D.C., Houston, Chicago, Seattle, and California, 84 of which are SuperCrown warehouse stores. I like the company because of the low price relative to its strong balance sheet: $9 a share in cash, a book value of $16 a share, and almost no long-term debt. Superstores (the most successful format) are increasing as a percentage of total stores, and the new management is impressive. A couple problems: The stock is thinly traded (the Dart Group owns 51 percent), and Barnes & Noble is a tough competitor. Patient investors can buy the stock at about eight times estimated 1996 earnings of $1 to $1.10 a share.<p>ERIC E. RYBACK
<a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a><p>Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.
URANIUM RESOURCES  UP TO $17  Nasdaq: URIX<p><a name="NASD:URIX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17101"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Uranium Resources</b></a> (Dallas), the lowest-cost uranium producer in North America and my pick last November, recently announced the start-up of operations on its Kingsville Dome property. This should help the company produce a total of two million pounds of uranium (U-308) in 1996. Industry analysts expect the uranium spot price, which has risen from $11.75 a pound in June 1995 to a recent price of $15.90, to hit $20 by the end of 1996. Because of the current price of U-308, the company's uranium reserves, and the company's anticipated development of the Churchrock deposit in New Mexico, I think Uranium Resources is worth $25 a share.<p>RALPH WANGER
CHUCK McQUAID
<a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ACORN Fund </b></a><p>Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may 
benefit from favorable economic trends.
KRONOS  up to $30  Nasdaq: KRON<p>Since <a name="NASD:KRON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15715"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kronos</b></a>'s (Waltham, Massachusetts) payroll clocks use microprocessors rather than motors, gears, ink, and paper, they are more reliable and provide accounting data more quickly than old-fashioned models. While broadening its product line to include high-end network versions as well as low-cost models for small businesses, Kronos is also enhancing its software: Its most advanced products now handle payroll data, employee scheduling, and legal compliance. Profit margins are rising. Sales (up 110 percent over the past three years) should hit $145 million in fiscal 1996. At 20 times estimated 1996 earnings of $1.40 a share, the stock is very attractive.<p>DONALD A. YACKTMAN
<a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>YACKTMAN Fund</b></a><p>Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.
DEPARTMENT 56  up to $22  NYSE: DFS<p><a name="NYSE:DFS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16233"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Department 56</b></a> (Eden Prairie, Minnesota) makes handmade ceramic and porcelain houses -- the Heritage Village collection is the best known -- as well as about 2,000 related holiday accessories. The company faces very little competition within its focus markets. Sales are up tenfold over the past five years, though the stock is down from a high of $48 because of flat sales in the fourth quarter of 1995. The company is incredibly profitable: Earnings have risen consistently for five years (going from zero in 1991 to $2.20 a share in 1995), and profit margins are high. Investors in this stock can make five to ten times their money over the next decade.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

