		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-The Smell of Fear</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Why last year's cheerleaders are now so eager to accentuate the negative<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Suddenly wall street is afraid of the future. To understand how spooked professional investors are, look no further than what happened to <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> on April 17.<p>The company announced earnings of $2.48 a share (excluding one-time charges) for the first three months of 1996, surpassing analysts' forecasts of $2.41 a share. The stock began to move up, climbing $5 to nearly $120 in early trading. But even as the stock was climbing, IBM's chief financial officer, G. Richard Thoman, was meeting with analysts. A stronger dollar and tighter profit margins could affect IBM's earnings in the coming quarter, Thoman said. The stock stumbled, closing the day at $105.25.<p>After months of refusing to worry about anything, Wall Street now sees monsters under every bed and disaster in every quarterly report. <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, for example, reported first-quarter earnings of 57 cents a share, a penny less than analysts were expecting. The stock immediately fell two dollars -- it was time, apparently, to start worrying that the stronger dollar would cut profits at multinationals.<p>Even companies with great stories are doing their best to emphasize the negative. <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> reported earnings of 88 cents a share for the quarter ending March 31, an increase of 42 percent over the comparable quarter of 1995, but the company's chief financial officer felt compelled to pour cold water on the market. "My estimation is earnings next quarter will be down a bit," he said.<p>What's behind all this self-conscious negativity? Wall Street and company executives know that growth in corporate profits is slowing, but nobody is sure by how much. Worse yet, the modest growth rate in profits in the first quarter of 1996 is being compared with the explosive growth in the first quarter of 1995. No one wants to get caught being a Pollyanna when earnings fall short. So Wall Street is engaged in one of its least favorite activities: downsizing expectations.<p>Here are the brutal facts that have put analysts on the spot. According to Melissa Brown, director of quantitative research at Prudential Securities, analysts are projecting growth in operating profits of just 7.8 percent in the first quarter of 1996. That's down from 15.2 percent growth in the fourth quarter of 1995 and, worst of all, way below the 23.3 percent growth in the first quarter of 1995. At 7.8 percent, growth would be the slowest since the fourth quarter of 1991.<p>In March, reports Brown, analysts trimmed their estimates 
of annual earnings for the large-capitalization companies she follows by an average of about 1 percent. But that average conceals some abrupt changes in opinion. Last year, for example, profits in many of the so-called basic industries -- chemicals, steel, paper, and trucking -- grew by more than 100 percent. Analysts now expect this sector to show a first-quarter decline in earnings of 4.9 percent. Analysts have lowered their earnings estimates for the year by 5 percent or more for almost 18 percent of the companies in this sector.<p>The consumer-cyclical sector -- the automobile, home-building, tool, and appliance companies that use the materials produced by basic industry -- is facing an even tougher first quarter, 
according to analysts, with profits set to drop by almost 22 percent. Technology companies are expected to post a modest increase in first-quarter sales, but this sector shows a huge decline in 
expectations: Earnings projections for the year have been lowered by 5 percent or more on a full 15 percent of the 201 companies Brown tracks in this sector. Only in the case of energy companies have analysts raised their estimates more frequently than they've lowered them.<p>Earnings uncertainty creates its own logic. Investors need to understand that the same dynamics that lead analysts to excess on the upside also lead them to overreaction on the downside. Just as analysts wind up competing to see how fast they can raise projections when their clients want to buy, buy, buy, so too they compete to cut estimates when the mood sours. It's no fun to be accused of leaving a client exposed to losses because of estimates that are overly optimistic.<p>In this market, investors have to do more than calculate what they believe a company will earn; they must also track the winds of expectation that blow down Wall Street. There's a lesson in the recent case of Motorola.<p>In January, the company announced earnings of just 72 cents a share for the fourth quarter of 1995, far below both the 99 cents a share analysts had expected and the 86 cents a share the company had earned in the fourth quarter of 1994. Analysts felt burned, and they reacted by cutting their ratings on the stock and their estimates for first-quarter 1996 earnings. A company that had earned 61 cents in the first quarter of 1995 would earn just 50 cents a share in the first quarter of 1996, they said.<p>So when <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> reported 63 cents a share for the quarter, it was not a disappointing performance from a company with a five-year annual growth rate of 25.3 percent but, instead, surprisingly good news. The stock rallied to nearly $60 on April 19. Fear, it seems, can be just as easily overdone as enthusiasm.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
