	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>President Clinton has presented Congress with a series of proposals aimed at overhauling retirement plans to make it easier for people to save for the future. The president's Retirement Savings and Security Act would, among other things, allow more middle-income families to deduct contributions to IRAs and would permit IRA holders to withdraw money without penalty during a period of extended unemployment or for first-home purchases, major medical expenses, or education. The plan would also create something called 
a National Employee Savings Trust, or NEST -- a type of 401(k) plan that would allow the employees of small businesses to shelter up to $5,000 a year in tax-free savings. Other measures would make it easier for workers to transfer their retirement plans from one employer to another and encourage employers to lift certain vesting requirements. The act reflects recommendations that have been coming from the private sector for some time. Critics have said the act benefits highly paid workers most, because it relaxes limits on how much such employees can set aside in their 401(k) plans and alters Section 415(e) restrictions on the total retirement benefits such people can receive each year. Some high earners could haul in as much as $100,000 a year extra in tax-free contributions and accruals under the Clinton plan.<p>A group of top mutual-fund executives has expressed concern about the risks associated with the torrent of money pouring into stock funds. The executives, speaking during a panel discussion in New York sponsored by the Mutual Fund Forum, said they are increasingly using bulletins and other forms of communication to warn shareholders against excessively high hopes about the market. Given the long run-up in the market, "we are starting from euphoria," Charles T. Bauer, chief executive of AIM Management Group, told the gathering. "So what happens in the future we have to be careful of." Bauer noted that AIM recently reopened and then closed an aggressive-growth fund because it attracted $1 billion in two days.<p>Morningstar is considering issuing its popular star ratings based on one-year performance figures, in addition to three-, five-, and ten-year numbers. The firm historically has opposed awarding stars for one-year figures, and Morningstar president Don Phillips says he's still against the idea on the grounds that such a short-term horizon is a misleading indicator of performance. If published, one-year ratings would not be factored into Morningstar's overall ratings. The National Association of Securities Dealers has been pressuring Morningstar to add the one-year ratings to make it easier for fund companies to comply with NASD marketing guidelines.<p>Citibank, <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a>, MasterCard, and Visa have announced 
a plan to test-market so-called smart cards -- plastic that can be loaded with electronic cash -- in New York City before the end of the year. Customers will be able to transfer up to $100 to their cards at ATMs. The 500 merchants participating in the test will use special electronic readers to deduct the electronic cash for the amount of each purchase. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Retirement, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
