	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Fixed Income</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Clint Willis<p>The pros draw a bead on the direction of interest rates by checking the yield on Eurodollar futures contracts at the International Monetary Market in Chicago. These contracts are agreements to buy U.S. dollars held in European banks at a fixed price in the future. The 
yield (listed in The Wall Street Journal's "Money & Investing" section under "Futures Prices") on an EFC for a given month in the future reflects what the market thinks the three-month London Interbank Offered Rate will be at that time. (LIBOR is the interest rate banks pay on dollar deposits in London.) Right now the futures are predicting rising rates. For example, on April 19, the yield on the September contract was 5.65 percent, well above the current three-month LIBOR of 5.5 percent. (LIBOR rates appear in the Journal under "Money Rates.") The price on the March 1997 contract suggests a 6.15 percent LIBOR rate__bad news for home buyers but maybe not for bonds. Higher rates are now built into Wall Street's assumptions, so the bond market is likely to shrug off bad news. Good news could even trigger a rebound. "The market is a lot less dangerous now than it was in February, when everyone was counting on lower rates," says John Burgess of Bankers Trust Global Investment Management.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Banking, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
