	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Tree Lawyer</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tree Lawyer</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Tree Lawyer</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> TREE LAWYER  <p> By Mark Ehrman  <p> Randall Stamen knows a lot about trees. And while he's not sure whether one that falls in the woods makes a sound, he can probably tell you if it will make a good lawsuit.   <p> That's because this 29-year-old Riverside, California, attorney and certified arborist deals exclusively in tree litigation --a, er, branch <p>that he calls "green-industry law."  <p> "I wanted to find my own niche," says the aptly named Stamen,who graduated from the University of San Diego School of Lawin 1992. As the son of an arborist, Stamen found litigating cases involving trees, landscaping, and pesticides "the natural thing" to do.   <p> Stamen's garden-variety cases, as it were, involve neighbor disputes. "Usually, they're cutting their neighbor's trees down or cutting the tops off or poisoning a tree to improve their view," he says. In such instances, should malice be proved, California law allows for triple damages.   <p> Trees can be expensive (music mogul David Geffen received $700,000 after a neighbor chopped down some of his), but many of Stamen's clients see their monetary value as secondary. "I felt like I  lost a friend," recalls Jeanne Moore, a former client. She sued her tree trimmer after an 85-year-old eucalyptus died within six months of pruning. Stamen proved that excessive spring pruning made the tree vulnerable to the long-horned borer beetle, turning a real-estate asset into deadwood. The accused arborist settled for a five-figure sum.  <p> Stamen says his expertise fills a need. "First of all, I can recognize that there is a lawsuit," he says. "People can't get anybody to represent them because the first thing an attorney will say is 'You have no lawsuit because it was an act of God,'or 'Go to small-claims court.'"  <p> Thus, after a tree limb fell on a man who was driving through Beverly Hills, Stamen sued the city, arguing that a practice called topping had increased the odds that the tree would drop a branch. In 1995, a judgment was rendered against the city for $36,000.  <p> For Stamen, it was a tough case to argue. "You have the problem that people don't take the tree cases as seriously as they would something else," he says.  <p> Still, after less than two years on his own, Stamen has opened a second office, in the more verdant Sacramento area. "Business has exceeded all my expectations," he says.  <p> Knock on wood. <p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
