	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Overtime Trouble</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Overtime Trouble</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> OVERTIME TROUBLE  <p> By Louis Jacobson  <p> The first law passed by the 104th Congress, the Congressional Accountability Act, requires lawmakers to abide by their own legislation, including the 57-year-old Fair Labor Standards Act, mandating overtime pay for those who work more than 40 hours a week.   <p> Congress, alas, is a deliberative body, not an efficient one-- long, uncompensated hours are the rule. With 38 percent of  representatives' aides and 47 percent of senators' aides eligible for overtime, according to a survey by the Congressional Management Foundation, Congress could owe millions in extra pay. Says CMF's Richard H. Shapiro, "They have to comply, but they have no additional funds." Business lobbyists love it. Congress, learning how the fair-labor act has burdened business, may at last reform it, says Jay Krupin of the Washington-based law firm David, Hagner, Kuney & Krupin.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Legislation, Economy, Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
