	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-No More Running to Catch Plane</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>No More Running to Catch a Plane</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-No More Running to Catch Plane</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> NO MORE RUNNING TO CATCH A PLANE  <p> By Peter Aronson  <p> You can't miss Jo Ann Ussery's home -- just look for the first fuselage on the left. Ussery had wanted to purchase a mobile home until her brother-in-law, an air-traffic controller, gave her a hot tip on a used 727 (well insulated, lots of space, plenty of light).  <p> Ussery, a Mississippi hair dresser, bought her house from the Memphis Group, an aircraft salvage company, which sold it to her for 15 cents a pound -- $2,000. Trucking the 127-foot-long fuselage about 60 miles cost another $4,000, and Ussery projects total costs (including a hot tub in the cockpit) to reach $30,000.  <p> The Memphis Group has sold two other fuselages as real estate: one became an office and the other a hunting cabin, says manager Richard Cordle. But since January, when a report about Ussery's house aired on public radio's Marketplace, inqueries have flooded in from people wanting to turn jets into houses, restaurants, and offices. As for Ussery, neighbors now treat her like a celebrity."I just luuv it," she drawls. <p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners, Real Estate

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
