	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Licensed to Deal</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Licensed to Deal</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Licensed to Deal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> LICENSED TO DEAL  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> In 1983, the Arizona legislature, determined to do something about the state's drug trade, passed a drug tax law requiring a license for "sale of cannabis and controlled substances."  <p> No one actually expected drug dealers to purchase a license; the idea was that those convicted for selling illegal drugs could also be pursued for tax evasion.   <p> Then Peter Wilson, chairman of the Arizona chapter of the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws (NORML), went to the Arizona Department of Revenue and put down $100 for a one-year marijuana dealer's license, plus $17.50 for a sheet of 50 one-gram cannabis tax stamps (similar to the stamps on cigarette packs). <p> Next, the 38-year-old robotics engineer began selling marijuana, and on every bag, he slapped one of his duly purchased tax stamps. After Phoenix narcotics agents busted him on a felony possession charge, Wilson argued in court that the state itself had licensed his activities, which, on that account, could hardly be deemed criminal. The judge agreed and dismissed the charges against him.   <p> "Fair is fair," says Wilson. "I paid $100 for a license to sell pot. What else would I do with it? People know I'm still in business," he adds. Prosecutors, meanwhile, have filed an appeal with the state superior court.  <p> "I'm optimistic that the decision will remain," says Wilson's attorney, Michael Walz, who specializes in marijuana cases. <p>That would be good news to a lot of people, says Allen St. Pierre, NORML's deputy national director, "So many people, from lawyers to pimple-faced teenagers, called to ask, 'Should I be moving to Arizona tonight?'"  <p>
KEYWORDS: Government Legislation
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
