		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Biking Banker</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Biking Banker</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Biking Banker</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> BIKING BANKER  <p> By Ken Kurson  <p> In 1990, Linda Jackson, a vice president at Alex. Brown & Sons, a San Francisco financial firm, injured her leg while skiing and turned to bicycling during her rehabilitation. She discovered that she was remarkably good at the sport, so remarkable that bike racing is now her full-time pursuit. Come July, Jackson will almost certainly be the only investment banker competing at the Atlanta games. <p>At 37, Jackson, a Canadian citizen, is old for a world-class athlete, but last year she won the Canadian nationals. She still sounds like an MBA, however. "Next year will be my last," she says. "I gave up a six-figure income, so the opportunity costs are pretty high." Jackson misses the perks of her old job: "I'd go to Paris [and] stay at the Ritz." Today, she says, it's modest rooms "with toilets down the hall."  <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
