	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-What They're Recommending</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE RECOMMENDING  <p> JIM McCAMANT <p>MEDICAL TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER <p>Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies. <p><a name="NASD:XOMA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15185"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>XOMA</b></a> (Nasdaq: XOMA) Up to $5: After some early disappointments in 1992 and 1993, which drove its stock price way down from a high of $32, Xoma (Berkeley, California) is well on its way to recovery. Neuprex, the company's newest product, is in four different phase-two trials, and I think investors will get very excited when they see the results later this year. One of the trials,which is testing the drug's use with conventional antibiotics in attacking antibiotic-resistant bacteria, has particular promise. Xoma also has a partnership with Pfizer on a drug called E5, which treats sepsis and may get approval in Japan this year.Meanwhile, the company has enough cash to last it a couple ofyears.  <p> MICHAEL MURPHY <p>CALIFORNIA TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER <p>Looks for high-growth high-tech companies. <p><a name="NASD:MTSN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42197"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MATTSON TECHNOLOGY </b></a>(Nasdaq: MTSN) Up to $15: Mattson (Fremont,California) has seen its stock come down sharply with those of the computer-chip makers, even though the economics of Mattson's business are different. Mattson makes the high-speed equipment that companies such as Motorola use to produce semiconductors. In the next three years, roughly 90 new manufacturing facilities worldwide will need this kind of advanced equipment. Mattson's sales grew 183 percent last year, and earnings grew 248 percent. I don't expect to see those kinds of numbers again in 1996, but I am looking for sales growth of 84 percent and earnings growth of 71 percent. My 12-month target for the stock is $25 a share. <p> LOUIS NAVELLIER <p>MPT REVIEW <p>Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks. <p><a name="NASD:ASTF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42224"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ACCUSTAFF</b></a> (Nasdaq: ASTF) Up to $26: The stock of AccuStaff (Jacksonville,Florida), a  temporary-staffing company, is working overtime. Institutional money managers have been aggressively buying the stock, which has great earnings momentum. If the labor market tightens, as recent statistics suggest it might, temporary help will benefit greatly. AccuStaff operates in 26 states and has 20 regional and 123 branch offices. The fundamentals are phenomenal: high sales growth, expanding margins, and explosive earnings growth. The stock has a very high alpha and a negative beta, meaning it is uncorrelated with the market. The stock was scheduled to split three for one on March 27.   <p> DAN SULLIVAN <p>THE CHARTIST <p>Uses technical analysis to identify long-term equity investments.<p><a name="NASD:JLGI"></a><b>JLG INDUSTRIES</b> (Nasdaq: JLGI) Up to $43: JLG (McConnellsburg,Pennsylvania) is a hydraulic-machinery company that has made a habit of exceeding Wall Street estimates. For example, in the most recent fiscal quarter, ended January 31, earnings rose 115 percent to 58 cents a share -- roughly 20 cents a share better than analysts had projected. The company has managed to cut manufacturing costs while raising prices. I expect these trends to continue and earnings to grow at an annual clip of 18 to 20 percent over the next three to five years. Although the stock has had a strong run-up recently and could be vulnerable to some profit taking, I think it is very attractive as a long-term holding.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
