<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE BUYING NOW  <p> Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about  their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after March 25, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these eight managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends that they conduct their own due diligence.  <p> PRESTON ATHEY <p><a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE SMALL CAP VALUE</b></a> <p>Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million. <p><a name="NASD:CULP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13142"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CULP</b></a> (Nasdaq: CULP) Up to $13: Culp (High Point, North Carolina), a home-furnishings and upholstered-fabric company, has a long-term record of exceptional performance in a very difficult industry. I think investors can make a lot of money in the stock. Culp's 33 percent compounded earnings growth over the past six years belies the industry's cyclicity and bodes well for the future; Culp should increase earnings again this year thanks to higher exports and lower raw-material costs. Culp is so cost-efficient that it has been able to increase exports 13-fold since 1989 while improving profit margins abroad. The stock is trading atten times my 1996 earnings estimate of $1.05 a share, and it's a great value.  <p> JAMES P. CRAIG <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JANUS FUND</b></a> <p>Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.  <p><a name="NYSE:LLY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10509"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ELI LILLY </b></a>(NYSE: LLY) Up to $65: The stock of Prozac-producer Eli Lilly (Indianapolis) certainly hasn't been depressed, but I think two new drugs could drive the price even higher. In the same way that Prozac expanded the market for treating depression, the release of Zyprex should increase awareness and demand in the relatively small schizophrenia market. The second promising drug, already released, is ReoPro, an anti-clotting drug made by Centocor; Lilly markets it in exchange for half the revenues. Lilly's earnings, which I expect to be $2.80 a share in 1996, should grow at close to 20 percent for the next several years. I think the stock can reach $80 a share over the next year. <p> SHELBY M.C. DAVIS <p><a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NEW YORK VENTURE FUND</b></a> <p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style. <p><a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>INTEL</b></a> (Nasdaq: INTC) Up to $57: Here's a chance to buy this chip maker cheap. For only 12 times my 1996 earnings estimate of $4.50 a share, investors can own a quality long-term-growth company. The stock of Intel (Santa Clara, California) has come down because of rising inventory and disappointing earnings, but Intel is still the dominant player with the dominant market share. The long-term story is intact; a wave of corporate PC upgrades, using Intel's Pentium Pro and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft's</b></a> Windows NT system, is about to begin. Intel is moving forward in video communications, too, and has a partnership with<a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Hewlett-Packard</b></a> for the next generation of 64-bit chips.  <p> DANIEL B. LEONARD <p><a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>INVESCO STRATEGIC PORTFOLIOS TECHNOLOGY</b></a> <p>Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields. <p><a name="NASD:UEIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UNIVERSAL ELECTRONICS</b></a> (Nasdaq: UEIC) Up to $12: Universal Electronics (Twinsburg, Ohio) makes remote controls that operate up to 12 components at a time. The company had a rocky period some years ago, but has a new CEO and is back on track. The company sells to both component makers and big retailers, and its backlog of orders is building. Universal also has the largest database of infrared codes and faces no real competition because of the difficulty of obtaining these codes from component makers. The company should be debt-free by mid-1996. I'm looking for earnings of 70 cents a share this year, up from 5 cents a share (after a onetime charge) in 1995. This could be a $20 stock within the next 12 months. <p> WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ <p><a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>HEARTLAND VALUE FUND</b></a> <p>Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be under valued. <p><a name="NASD:BOCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15973"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BOCA RESEARCH </b></a>(Nasdaq: BOCI) Up to $21: Boca Research (Boca Raton,Florida) makes products -- mostly circuit boards -- that transmit information among personal computers, networks, and the Internet. Three factors will be pushing the company's earnings up 30 to35 percent a year in the near term: rising demand for faster modems; increasing use of the Internet; and surging growth in the small-office market. The kicker for the stock is Boca's new low-cost video-conferencing product, due out in the third quarter. At 14 times my estimated 1996 earnings of $1.40 a share, Boca is a much better bet than its high-end competitor PictureTel, which trades at 46 times my 1996 earnings estimate.  <p> ERIC E. RYBACK <p><a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LINDNER DIVIDEND FUND</b></a> <p>Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second. <p><a name="NYSE:RSP"></a><b>SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAIL </b>(NYSE: RSP) Up to $27.50: Merger plans between Southern Pacific Rail (San Francisco) and Union Pacificare chugging toward the September completion date. According to the deal, investors will be able to exchange one share of Southern Pacific stock for $25 in cash or 0.4065 shares of Union Pacific. The combined company will benefit from large cost savings. To further enhance shareholder value, the new U.P. will spin of its holdings in its oil-and-gas company, Union Pacific Resources. There has been talk that opposition to the merger may hold it up, but I feel the companies are addressing the concerns fully. Investors should buy at up to 37 percent of the price of U.P. <p> RALPH WAGNER & CHUCK McQUAID <p><a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ACORN FUND</b></a> <p>Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.  <p><a name="NASD:UVSGA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16685"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UNITED VIDEO SATELLITE GROUP</b></a> (Nasdaq: UVSGA) Up to $23: United Video (Tulsa, Oklahoma), which is now 40 percent owned by Tele-Communications, is a satellite-communications company that provides programming to cable franchises and services to the owners of satellite dishes.Its Prevue channel (which features TV listings and clips) has hit critical mass of 40 million homes and will likely add 6 million more. It's selling a lot of advertising, too. Other areas are also turning profits, including Sneak Prevue (for pay-per-view), Prevue International, and SpaceCom (data and audio distribution). Prevue Interactive also has great prospects. Our 18-month target for the stock is $29.50 a share.  <p> DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p><a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>YACKTMAN FUND</b></a> <p>Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion. <p><a name="NYSE:FNQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15674"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FRANKLIN QUEST</b></a>(NYSE: FNQ) Up to $24 <p>Investors in search of solid growth should look at Franklin Quest (Salt Lake City), a company whose annual earnings have grown at an average rate of about 20 percent for the past four years. The stock has stayed flat since I recommended it in January, but all the fundamentals for a strong move are still in place. Franklin makes a lot of money by dominating a very simple business-- it makes day planners -- and is also a growing presence intime-management seminars (its original business) and retail. The company has a high return on assets, and though earnings growth slowed a bit last year, I expect to see strong earnings of $2 a share in 1996.  <p>
KEYWORDS:  Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
