	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> KEEPING UP <p>  <p>By John Fried  <p> *The securities industry does a poor job policing brokers, according to a report jointly prepared by the Securities and Exchange Commission, the National Association of Securities Dealers, the New York Stock Exchange, and the North American Securities Administration Association. The report criticized the industry for failing to adequately monitor broker trades, for slipshod hiring practices, and for willingly overlooking problem brokers.  <p> *Vanguard Group, the nation's second-largest mutual-fund company, plans to offer financial reviews to individuals this year. The check ups, covering such areas as investments, insurance, and trust services, will be provided at what Vanguard says will be a discount rate. At the moment, no other mutual-fund company offers such a service, though it is now more likely that some of the larger fund families will follow suit. The business has traditionally been the province of independent financial planners, private banks, and the networks of advisers employed by full-service financial firms, such as <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>. <p> *Fidelity Investments has reassigned the managers of 26 stock mutual funds. Although Fidelity has ranked among the industry leaders in performance during the past decade, its stock fundsas a group have done less well during the past two years a period when the company's strengths have been out of sync with the market. The management reshuffling which involved 30 percent of Fidelity's equity-portfolio managers was the most sweeping ever at a company that is known for a competitive internal work environment.  <p> *The Securities and Exchange Commission plans to impose new standards on money-market funds, requiring them to reduce their exposure to interest-rate, credit-quality, and currency-related risks. The new rules, scheduled to take effect later this year,encourage greater diversification and prohibit investments in certain derivative securities.  <p> *Hedge funds and other private investment pools may be used in 401(k) retirement plans, the SEC has ruled. Although hedge funds are restricted to no more than 100 investors, the government agency said a self-directed retirement plan even one with thousands of members may be counted under its rules as a single investor. <p> *More workers may be suing their employers in the wake of a U.S. Supreme Court decision that has made it easier for employees to file lawsuits alleging that they were misled about their health and pension benefits. The court's ruling found that a farm-and-industrial-equipment manufacturer in Buffalo, New York, can be held liable for such deceit. A rise in such litigation, however, could make it more expensive for companies to provide benefits.  <p> *Spring Street Brewing will resume operating what apparently is the first-ever system that allows stockholders to buy and sell a company's shares on the Internet. The New York brewer,whose president is a former securities lawyer, halted trading in late March, following a request by securities regulators, who asked for modifications to the system.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Government, Employment, Technology Industry, Retirement<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:AXP">American Express Company</a><br>

					<p>

