<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> GLOBAL MARKETS  <p> By Todd G. Buchholz  <p> Year of the Rat, the Bull, or the Bear? Oliver Stone's film Nixon may have bombed at the box of-fice, but it does remind us of the historic "opening to China," the 1972 renewal of relations with the world's most populous nation, engineered by Richard Nixon and Henry Kissinger.   <p> Of course, no one foresaw that the U.S. would run a $33.8 billion annual trade deficit with China less than 25 years later. Still, companies like <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:CAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10304"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caterpillar</b></a> have done quite well during China's rapid industrialization, and bilateral trade has created about a million U.S. jobs.  <p> So far this trading relationship has been win-win, and it could get better. As Chinese incomes rise, peasants move off the farms and into the cities, and China's need to import food grows. U.S. farmers want to feed all those open mouths, and since China's exports generate lots of foreign currency, its people will not go unfed, as they did in the 1950s and 1960s. And China's remaining farmers will ultimately buy U.S. farm equipment to help meet growing demand.  <p>So why, as of March 25, has the index for Shanghai B stock, which is available to foreigners, fallen 35 percent to 1242 from its May 22, 1995, high of 1913?  <p> There are several plausible explanations. First, the Asian markets are being affected by the Dow Jones average, which looks jittery after last year's spectacular run-up. Second, the Chinese economy has slowed because of a tight monetary policy, which cut inflation from 21.7 percent in 1994 to about 8 percent this year. But whath as really spooked the markets is that U.S.-China relations have slid back to where they were before 1972. The principal reason is that, for most of March, China was lobbing unarmed missiles into the seas off Taiwan in a crude -- and failed -- attempt to frighten the Taiwanese into voting on March 23 against political democratization and against a government that might move toward national independence. In response, President Clinton sent naval vessels to the region, and tense words were exchanged.   <p> The crisis seems to be abating, with China making conciliatory gestures toward Taiwan's newly elected president, Lee Teng-hui. But, nonetheless, 1996 promises to be a miserable year for Beijing-Washington commercial relations. For example, Caterpillar plans on sharing in one of the biggest construction jobs in history, China's Three Gorges Dam, which depends partly on loans from the U.S. Export-Import Bank. Washington may well nix these loans, sending the Chinese elsewhere for financing and equipment (Japan's Komatsu corporation will be happy to oblige).  <p> In addition, the deadline for extending China's most-favored-nation status is June 3, and while the White House would like to extend MFN to help Caterpillar, <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>,General Motors</b></a>, Boeing, and other exporters (and lots of working voters), the president's advisers remember how George Bush was hurt in 1992 by being perceived as "soft" on China.   <p> The U.S. will probably extend MFN but may impose sanctions that target China's piracy of intellectual property (despite a 1995 trade deal, China continues to rip off billions in CD recording sand software) and alleged sale of nuclear technology. Of course, China will retaliate against U.S. firms, to the delight of our competitors. It's no surprise that U.S. investors are growing wary of putting more money into Asian mutual funds in 1996. <p> Contributing editor Todd Buchholz is a managing director of a New York­based international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy. <p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Technology Industry, International Investing 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
