		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-A Buying Opportunity?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Buying Opportunity?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-A Buying Opportunity?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> A BUYING OPPORTUNITY?  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> The recent slump in the bond market has brought long-term issues back into buying range. On March 8, when a report showed an increase in the number of new jobs of more than twice what analysts had expected, bond prices plunged, and yields on 30-year Treasurys jumped from 6.46 percent to 6.74 percent. Yields had already climbed from about 6 percent in early February as hopes for Federal Reserve rate cuts faded and politicians stopped focusing on the deficit. "Republicans started talking about things like flat taxes instead of balanced budgets," says Jim Floyd, a senior analyst at the Leuthold Group in Minneapolis.   <p> Why is this a good time to buy? Many analysts argue that the jobs data were a fluke. Other numbers, such as declining producer prices, point to low inflation and slow growth. "Bonds are very fairly priced right now," says David Rosenberg, a fixed-income manager with Oppenheimer Funds in New York. "Today's real returns of 3 percent or so on intermediate bonds are a good deal" for patient investors. But the moment isn't right to try to make a short-term killing. "The market will react strongly to any economic news," says Floyd. "This probably isn't the time to load up on long-term bonds as a short-term, tactical maneuver." <p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Employment, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
