<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Borrowing Trouble</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Borrowing Trouble</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Borrowing Trouble</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> BORROWING TROUBLE  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> There's something deeply wrong with the bond market. On Friday, March 8, the Dow Jones Industrial Average took a 171-point drubbing. Equity investors howled, and the press put the story on page one. On the same day, the bond market took an even worse beating-- a $1,000 30-year Treasury bond lost $31 in value as long-term interest rates recorded their biggest one-day rise since Iraq invaded Kuwait in August 1990.  <p> The stock market has since recovered from its vapors, but the bond market has sunk into a deeper funk. Not only has it failed to recover any of the ground it lost, but it has continued to punish investors. As of March 22, an investor in the 30-year Treasury bond was showing a year-to-date total return of negative 8.25 percent, according to Ryan Labs Inc.  <p> Exactly what's wrong with the bond market? On March 8, the quick answer was "the economy." Government employment numbers announced that day showed that the nation had created 705,000 jobs in February, almost three times as many as Wall Street expected.  <p> That was terrible news for the bond market, which had been counting on a weak economy to force the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates at its March meeting. The expectation was built into bond yields -- and when the jobs number ensured the Fed's inaction, the market was set to tumble.  <p> But that doesn't explain why it tumbled so far or so fast. To understand the size and speed of the move, you have to look at the market's peculiar structure.  <p> "There are no investors in this bond market," says James Bianco, research director at Arbor Trading Group in Barrington, Illinois."Bonds are being bought by speculators and dealers. Everybody is in the bond market for the short run."  <p> It's easy to see what attracts traders to this market. The short run is potentially far more lucrative for bond traders than for anyone who trades in equities. Regulation T of the Federal Reserve Board requires that equities investors put down at least 50 percent of the price of a stock in cash. Their maximum leverage is two for one.  <p> Bond traders, however, can easily up their leverage by borrowing from the big investment houses that finance the bond trade. When George Soros trades bonds, for example, he often employs leverage  of eight to one. Leverage is great, of course, when bond prices are going up. But it's a disaster when prices tumble. Traders with eight-to-one leverage didn't lose $31 per $1,000 bond on March 8; they lost $248.  <p> Of course, bond traders can't borrow the money to buy bonds on margin for nothing. The banks in this business charge interest, and bond traders are always looking for the cheapest source of money. For a good part of this year and last, that has meant Japan. In order to stimulate the Japanese economy, the Bank of Japan has cut interest rates to almost nothing. International bond traders have been able to borrow yen in Japan at just 0.5 percent and then buy U.S. Treasurys yielding 5 percent.  <p> Leverage like this doesn't come without its dangers. If rates head up and prices go down, the leveraged investor will take a big hit. If the exchange rate between the dollar and yen changes, with the dollar getting weaker so that it takes more dollar profits to repay those yen loans, traders will also feel the pain.  <p> The bond market has been lifted by a sea of borrowed money. There's the money traders have borrowed from banks to buy bonds and the money borrowed from Japan. Bianco estimates the first at around $170 billion and the second at $100 billion. But that's not all. Foreign central banks, which have been buying dollars to prop up the value of the buck, have been recirculating their dollars by buying Treasury securities in the U.S. market. The Fed currently estimates that balance at $552 billion.  <p> All this money has kept interest rates lower and bond prices higher. And it has made equities look like better investments by keeping yields on bonds so low. <p>How long can the situation go on? Bond traders have decided that the Fed is not likely to cut rates soon and have begun to unwind recent positions. But foreign central banks are still buying bonds. How much more they'll hold is anyone's guess. <p>This all adds up to a fundamental change for those who invest-- rather than trade -- in bonds. In this market, bond and bond-fund investors can't buy and forget. They need to be much more active about managing the fixed-income part of their portfolios. "If I'm a fixed-income investor, I don't plan on investing for the long term but for a year or so," says Chip Norton, managing editor of IBC's Bond Fund Report.  <p> Most investors are better off now in bond funds than in individual bonds. Look for a fund family with funds of different maturities-- at a minimum a short-, an intermediate-, and a long-term fund.Then use a number called "duration" -- a measure of a fund's sensitivity to changes in interest rates -- to build a portfolio.(The longer the duration, the more interest-rate sensitivity.) Do some what-ifs that look at combinations of funds with higher and lower yields and different durations. The goal is to find a balance of tolerable potential loss and income.  <p> The whole process should take about an hour. Considering the potential return, that's a pretty good investment -- even without leverage. <p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, International Investing, Bond Investing, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

