<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-10 Stocks to Consider/Avoid</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>10 Stocks to Consider/Avoid</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-10 Stocks to Consider/Avoid</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> 10 STOCKS TO CONSIDER/AVOID  <p> DAVID TICE likes to challenge Wall Street's darlings. As editor of Behind the Numbers, a Dallas newsletter, he advises some 100 portfolio managers on sell decisions, and he recently started a $1 million short-selling mutual fund, the Prudent Bear. To identify stocks with problems that should blow up within a year, he screens for equities at the high end of their trading range and then scours their financial data to identify land mines, such as earnings per share that are growing faster than operating earnings. For example, from the third to the fourth calendar quarters of 1995, <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> spent more than $2.50 in marketing costs to add each dollar of new revenue. Oil-and-gas producer <a name="NYSE:CHK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12049"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chesapeake Energy</b></a> is overstating cash flow because of on going drilling costs to  replenish quickly diminishing reserves. To boost growth, credit-card bank<a name="NYSE:FUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15687"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> First USA</b></a> is taking on higher-risk accounts;  this has led to a 40 percent increase in the delinquency rate. <a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a> faces falling computer-chip prices because of over capacity in the industry. A drop of some 67 percent in the stock's price hasn't really created a bargain: Micron traded below five dollars a share for much of the decade up until there cent memory-chip shortage. <p><a name="NYSE:ALK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10046"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alaska Air Group</b></a> (NYSE: ALK) $9 <p>Industry price wars <p>Hurt by weaker economy <p>Competitors getting stronger <p>America Online (Nasdaq: AMER) $15 <p>Rising costs to add new customers <p>Threat from new technology <p>Cash flow is overstated <p>Chesapeake Energy (NYSE: CHK) $0 <p>High ongoing capital expenditures <p>Building up too much debt <p>Cash flow is overstated <p>First USA (NYSE: FUS) $25 <p>Bad debt is increasing <p>Industry price wars <p>Hurt by weaker economy <p><a name="NASD:MWHS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13013"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micro Warehouse</b></a> (Nasdaq: MWHS) $18 <p>Industry poised for decline <p>Competition intensifying <p>Supply will soon outpace demand <p><a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a> (NYSE: MU) $3 <p>Industy poised for decline <p>Competition intensifying <p>Supply will soon outpace demand <p><a name="NASD:NVLS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14288"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Novellus </b></a>(Nasdaq: NVLS) $15 <p>Industry poised for decline <p>Upcoming order cancellations <p>Supply will soon outpace demand <p><a name="NASD:PAGE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13689"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Paging Network </b></a>(Nasdaq: PAGE) $2 <p>Threat from new technology <p>New service expected to flop <p>Cash flow is overstated <p><a name="NASD:PDCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14827"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Patterson Dental </b></a>(Nasdaq: PDCO) $15 <p>Growth is slowing <p>Competition is intensifying <p>Overvalued versus competitive <p><a name="NYSE:PMA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43119"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PMI Group </b></a>(NYSE: PMA) $20 <p>Bad debt is increasing <p>Industry price wars <p>Hurt by weaker economy  <p>  <p>LAWRENCE AURIANA has done well by investors in the $3 billion Kaufmann Fund he co-manages with Hans Utsch. Up 36.9 percent during the last 12 months, the fund has averaged an annual return of 28.6 percent for the past five years. Auriana buys mostly small-company stocks at initial public offerings -- 17 out of the fund's top 20 holdings were bought as IPOs. He targets companies that can increase earnings by at least 20 percent annually over the next two to three years, that sell proprietary products in multibillion-dollar markets, and that show recurring sources of revenue. Using proprietary software, Altera designs and produces programmable logic microchips that can be tailored to fit customers' needs. While the news of the recent glut in memory chips has driven down the stock prices of all chip makers, Auriana expects earnings growth at Altera to be unaffected: He's looking for earnings to increase 30 percent a year for the next few years. A proprietary information system allows Borders Group's book superstores to tailor 70 percent of inventory to local buying patterns. Diagnostic Products has an ongoing source of profits in the high-margin reagents it developed for use in medical tests. <p><a name="NASD:ACSA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42188"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Affiliated Computer Services</b></a> (Nasdaq: ACSA) $43 <p>Recurring service revenue <p>Growing through acquisitions <p>Benefits from outsourcing trend <p><a name="NASD:ALTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12568"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Altera </b></a>(Nasdaq: ALTR) $65 <p>Proprietary products  <p>Launching new products <p>Strong industry growth <p><a name="NASD:BSST"></a><b>Baby Superstore </b>(Nasdaq: BSST) $40 <p>Leading player in market <p>Plenty of room to expand <p>Growing private-label sales <p><a name="NYSE:BGP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42887"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Borders Group</b></a> (NYSE: BGP) $30 <p>Proprietary technology <p>Efficient inventory management <p>Expanding into new markets <p><a name="NASD:CENT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15905"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Central Garden & Pet</b></a> (Nasdaq: CENT) $11 <p>Dominant market share <p>Broad range of products <p>Strong industry growth <p><a name="AMEX:CYE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12967"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cheyenne Software </b></a>(AMEX: CYE) $27 <p>Value-added distribution <p>Growing through acquisitions <p>Strong industry growth <p><a name="NASD:DANKY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43628"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Danka Business Systems</b></a> (Nasdaq: DANKY) $45 <p>Recurring service revenue <p>Growing through acquisitions <p>Strong industry growth <p><a name="NYSE:DP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10456"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Diagnostic Products </b></a>(NYSE: DP) $43 <p>Proprietary technology <p>High-margin recurring revenue <p>Under followed by analysts <p><a name="NASD:NKOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15814"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nu-Kote Holdings</b></a> (Nasdaq: NKOT) $18 <p>Low-priced products <p>Gaining new economies of scale <p>Strong industry growth <p><a name="NASD:TCNL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13352"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tecnol Medical Products</b></a> (Nasdaq: TCNL) $19 <p>Recurring revenue <p>Low-cost manufacturer <p>Imminent earnings turn around  <p>  <p>UPDATE <p>Last year's market rally was cruel to May 1995's "Ten Stocks to Avoid" selections by Scott Turkel, founder of TCM Partners, a New York hedge fund: His portfolio appreciated 12.5 percent in the past 12 months ended March 15. Most gains came from coffee retailer <a name="NASD:SBUX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15745"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Starbucks</b></a> (up 86 percent) and the surprise success of ValuJet Airlines (up 143 percent). He accurately foresaw bad news for CD-ROM producer Spectrum Holobyte and database-systems company <a name="NASD:SYBS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15350"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sybase</b></a>, down 42 and 36 percent, respectively. <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investment Strategies<p>

