<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>TREND SPOTTER<p>By Monica Corcoran <p>I LAUGHED, I CRIED, I TANNED. How do small-video-store owners boost profits? By bronzing patrons, of course. Thomas K. Arnold, editor in chief of Video Store Magazine, numbers the movie rental outlets offering on-site tanning beds at more than 2,000. "Stores are looking to provide services that cable can't offer," he says.<p>GLOOMY BOOMERS. Fiscal pessimism is especially high among the 30-to-49-year-old set. A study by the Lutheran Brotherhood reveals that twice as many baby boomers expect their family income to drop in 1996 as did in 1995. "When the government closes down, people get nervous about their job security," says Rolf Bjelland, chief investment officer of the Brotherhood.<p>$ILVER $CREEN. The Writers Guild of America, West, reports that screenwriters' earnings have jumped 47 percent since 1991. But don't quit that day job yet. The top 50 film scribes__meaning just 3 percent of all the WGAW's working members__account for as much as 50 percent, or $144.5 million, of last year's overall earnings.<p>LOCATION, LOCATION. A study by the William M. Mercer human-resources consulting firm takes a close look at the impact of your zip code on your paycheck. Using a benchmark $50,000 salary for a middle manager in Yakima, Washington, Mercer gauged the income drop or jump for that job nationwide. Heading to New York increases that $50K by $7,400. But how many cups of joe will that buy in high-priced Manhattan? <p>EVE'S RIB. The scales of justice certainly aren't tipped in favor of female lawyers. The Association of the Bar of the City of New York reveals in a 1995 study of NYC law firms that more women are getting passed over for partnerships. Promotion rates for female associates hired after 1981 have fallen to 5 percent__a third the rate of promotion for female associates hired between 1973 and 1981. Promotion rates for men have dropped slightly, but male associates are still promoted at a rate of 17 percent. <p>RISING DOUGH. Better get cookin' if you're aching to retire. Pillsbury recently upped the grand prize for its perennial Bake-Off from $50,000 to a hot-and-piping $1 million.<p>PASS THE PROZAC, PLEASE. Scott-Levin, a marketing firm for the health-care industry, reports that the number of in-force prescriptions for the ber-antidepressant has soared 65.4 percent, from 10.9 million in late 1992 to more than 18 million by the end of last year.<p>WHY ALL THE JUNK? Because it works. A recent U.S. Postal Service survey discovered that nearly two-thirds of consumers consider all those catalogs, circulars, and coupons useful. That explains why the volume of third-class mail has jumped about 70 percent since the mid-1980s and why it is projected to increase by 6.5 percent a year through the millennium.<p>LET'S MAKE A DEAL. If Uncle Sam won't give you a break next month, try your accountant. The trend among CPAs, who are vying for business with all those tax-preparation computer programs, is alternative billing. "For accountants to make money, they have to adopt different pricing philosophies," says August Aquila, author of Breaking the Paradigm, a book on alternative billing strategies for accountants. Aquila suggests you discuss paying a flat rate or by the form. "Getting billed by the hour is the worst for the customer," he cautions.<p>FOUR LEGS AND A FOUR IRON. Somebody had to find a use for the exploding population of llamas__they've doubled in number, to 75,000, since 1990.  At Minnesota's Elmdale Hills Golf Course, golfers pay $25 to have a llama carry their clubs.<p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry, Taxation, Family Finance, Employment, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
