	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE BUYING NOW  <p> Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. The manager may also have sold the stock after January 22, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these eight managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends that they conduct their own due diligence.  <p>  <hr>  <p>PRESTON ATHEY <p><a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE SMALL CAP VALUE</b></a>  <p> Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.  <p> <a name="NASD:WGOV"></a><b>Woodward Governer</b>  up to $75  Nasdaq: WGOV <p>Woodward Governor (Rockford, Illinois) is the world's leading manufacturer of fuel controls and speed controls for engines. Because of a drop in its defense and commercial-aircraft business, earnings fell from a peak of $10.74 a share in the fiscal year ended September 30, 1990, to a loss of $1.11 a share in fiscal1994. The company underwent a painful restructuring and got earnings back up to $4.11 a share last year. Trading at 1.1 times book value (12 times estimated 1996 earnings a share) and yielding 5 percent, WGOV is a great value. I'm particularly optimistic because a new aircraft cycle is beginning. My target price is $125 a share.  <p> -------------------- <p>JAMES P. CRAIG <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>  <p> Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.  <p> <a name="NYSE:BNI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10250"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Burlington Northern Santa Fe </b></a> up to $80  Nyse: BNI <p>Rail giant BNI (Fort Worth, Texas) is making a single company of Burlington Northern and Santa Fe faster than expected, thanks in large part to Robert Krebs, formerly the Santa Fe chief and now head of BNI. This provides huge cost savings and growth potential. The stock has been hurt by concern over the economy, but booming exports in grain (15 percent of revenue) and a growing demand for low-cost coal (25 percent of revenue) in the Powder River Basin should give the company revenue stability. I think BNI will earn $6.30 a share in 1996 and at least $7.50 a share in1997. The stock should reach the mid-$90s this year.  <p> -------------------- <p>SHELBY M. C. DAVIS <p><a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> <p>  <p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.  <p> <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> up to $88  Nyse: MS <p>With roughly 48 percent of its profit earned outside the U.S., Morgan Stanley (New York) is one of the top global financial-services franchises. It is emphasizing growth of its global money-management and mutual-fund business, and recently acquired Pennsylvania-based Miller Anderson & Sherrerd. The stock is trading at about nine times my 1996 earnings estimate of $9 a share and only slightly above its expected book value of $64 a share. Morgan has a big backlog of mergers and acquisitions and an active share-repurchase program. My 12- to 18-month target is between $110 a share and $120 a share, just less than twice book value.  <p> -------------------- <p>DANIEL B. LEONARD <p><a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a>  <p> Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.  <p> <a name="NASD:LFUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13984"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Littlefuse</b></a> up to $35  Nasdaq: LFUS <p>Littelfuse (Des Plaines, Illinois) is the world's leading designer and manufacturer of fuses; the company makes fuses for cars, for industry, and for electronic equipment. (For electronics, the fuses can be as tiny as a grain of rice.) Littelfuse, which has a market capitalization of $330 million, is also diversifying abroad: It recently acquired land in China to build a manufacturing plant and purchased an interest in a South Korean fuse company. Littelfuse has only scattered competition and is under-followed by Wall Street, which is a big plus. My 12-month target for the stock is $45 a share, well above the recent high of $38.  <p> -------------------- <p>WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ <p><a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund </b></a>  <p> Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued. <p> <a name="NYSE:RIT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>RightChoice </b></a> up to $14  Nyse: RIT <p>RightChoice (St. Louis) is a publicly held subsidiary of BlueCross/Blue Shield of Missouri, the largest provider of managed care in the state. RightChoice is in the midst of launching one of its most successful products ever, AllianceChoice, a hybrid between an HMO and a PPO. It lets members use any doctor and see a specialist without a referral. Employers like this product, and the company will soon be offering it to individuals. RightChoice should earn $1.50 a share in 1996 (up from $1.25 last year) and $1.70 a share in 1997. Though earnings are growing at 15 percent, the price-to-earnings ratio is only nine. The company's buyout value is about $30 a share.  <p> -------------------- <p>ERIC E. RYBACK <p><a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a>  <p> Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.  <p> <a name="NASD:TUBO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12022"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toboscope Vetco INT'L.</b></a>  UP TO $9  Nasdaq: TUBO <p>Tuboscope (Houston), an oil-field service company, is the world's leading supplier of reliability-testing equipment and internal coatings for casings, tubings, and drill pipes used in wells. This spring, Tuboscope, which has a market capitalization of $150 million, plans to merge with Drexel Oilfield Services, another manufacturer of products for drilling and maintaining oil wells. SCF Partners, a shareholder of Drexel, intends to invest an additional $31 million in the combined outfit. After the merger, the chairman of Tuboscope will be SCF Partners' L. E. Simmons, a well-respected industry veteran. I plan to hold the stock up to $15 a share. <p> -------------------- <p>RALPH WANGER <p>CHUCK McQUAID <p><a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a>   <p> Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.  <p><a name="NASD:MTEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14149"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Mobile Telecommunications Tech. </b></a> up to $24  Nasdaq: MTEL <p>Mobile Telecommunications (Jackson, Mississippi) provides nationwide paging service. The subscriber count for its one-way service grew 103 percent to 900,000 last year, so it maintained its dominant market share. The company won a Pioneer's Preference license from the FCC. As a result, it has an 18-month lead over its competition in launching the first nationwide two-way paging service. MTEL also has interests in paging services in 20 countries. The stock is off 45 percent from a 1995 high of $36 a share because of a shortage of pagers, a problem that now appears to be solved. At around $20, we think the stock is extremely cheap.  <p> -------------------- <p>DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p><a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a>  <p> Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.  <p> <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TOYS "R" US </b></a> up to $24  NYSE: TOY <p>Toys "R" Us (Paramus, New Jersey) is the world's largest specialty retailer of toys. The stock had been a steady gainer for years, rising as high as $43 a share in 1993 before tumbling to the low $20s last year. Hurt by a slowdown in the video-game market and a bad retailing environment in general, Toys "R" Us should still be the first to benefit from an easing of competitive pressure. In addition, its product breadth allows it to cross-subsidize its different lines, something mom-and-pop stores and general merchandisers such as Wal-Mart and Target can't do. I think the company can get earnings back up to around $2 a share in 1996. <p>   <p> WHAT THEY"RE RECOMMENDING <p>These four top financial-newsletter writers the most recent additions to our panel of experts identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the author considers a stock attractive. In some cases, the newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages. <p> -------------------- <p>JIM McCAMANT <p>MEDICAL TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER  <p> Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.  <p> <a name="NASD:LGNDA"></a><b>Ligand Pharmaceuticals</b>  up to $14  Nasdaq: LGNDA <p>Ligand (San Diego) specializes in finding small, orally active molecules that interact with the receptors inside cells to mimic or block hormone action. The company is distinguished by its great partners <a name="NYSE:PFE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11175"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pfizer</b></a>, Glaxo, Smith Kline Beecham, American Home Products, and Abbott Labs. This provides a substantial amount of research support and money. The company is currently developing products to treat osteoporosis and inflammation, and to regulatelipid levels. It is also making estrogen-like molecules that don't have the side effects of estrogen. Ligand has no earnings yet, but has $80 million in cash, enough to last three years. <p> -------------------- <p>MICHAEL MURPHY <p>CALIFORNIA TECHNOLOGY STOCK LETTER  <p> Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.  <p> <a name="NASD:IDTI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13785"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>INTEGRATED DEVICE TECHNOLOGY</b></a>  up to $15  Nasdaq: IDTI <p>IDTI (Santa Clara, California) got pummeled in the recent semiconductor sell-off, but it should bounce back in the next year. About half of its revenues come from static random-access memory, or SRAM, which is used as a cache between the fast microprocessor and the rest of a computer, which is much slower. With demand for <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>'s Pentium microprocessor driving PC growth and a new factory in Oregon coming on-line this quarter, IDTI's sales volume should accelerate. The company spends a high 18 percent of sales on research and development, which bodes well for the long term. I think the company can earn $2 a share in 1996.  <p> -------------------- <p>LOUIS NAVELLIER <p>MPT REVIEW  <p> Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.  <p> <a name="NASD:CUBE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17270"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>C-Cube Microsystems </b></a> up to $58  Nasdaq: CUBE <p>C-Cube (Milpitas, California) is a leader in the digital video market. The company provides a wide range of video-compression equipment, such as encoders, decoders, and codecs. Applications for its products include everything from video CD players to digital television systems to video play back on PCs. The stock has very strong earnings-estimate support from industry analysts as well as very strong earnings momentum. What I think is most compelling about this stock from a technical perspective is that it has a high alpha, which means its returns are uncorrelated with the market's. This is a very healthy sign for the stock. <p> -------------------- <p>DAN SULLIVAN <p>THE CHARTIST  <p> Uses technical analysis to identify long-term equity investments. <p> <a name="NASD:AMGN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amgen </b></a> up to $60  Nasdaq: AMGN <p>Amgen (Thousand Oaks, California) develops, manufactures, and markets human therapeutics based on cellular and molecular biology. Two of Amgen's drugs Epogen, for treating renal-related anemia, and Neupogen, for stimulating the production of white blood cells generate 95 percent of the company's revenue. Demand should continue to grow as Amgen develops new uses for these drugs. Revenue for the first nine months of 1995 rose 18 percent while net income increased 25 percent. I expect earnings to come in at $1.95 a share for 1995 (a 25 percent jump) and to grow at around 20 percent for the next three to five years.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Biotechnology Industry, Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

