	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-It's Not Gonna Be Easy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-It's Not Gonna Be Easy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Jubak  <p> You'll probably agree that investors have plenty to worry about already: interest rates, inflation, the budget stand off. And now corporate earnings suggest that deflation should be added to the list. Understanding deflation, in fact, may be the key to success in what is shaping up to be a stock picker's market. <p> When economists talk about deflation, of course, they are describingan economic trend that is the opposite of inflation: when prices fall across the economy. Deflationary periods occur rarely; we haven't seen one in this country since the Great Depression. <p> But the U.S. economy is not on the verge of a general downturn in prices, so let's leave that kind of deflation to the economists and other theorists. What the year's first corporate-earnings reports have begun to reveal is something different: steady downward pressure on the prices that individual businesses can charge for their products. This kind of spot deflation has recentlyled companies as diverse as <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:RBD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rubbermaid</b></a> to deliver earnings far below Wall Street's expectations.  <p> Motorola reported its results for the fourth quarter of 1995 after the market closed on January 8, 1996. The company's sales for the quarter rose 13 percent from the year-earlier period, yet its earnings fell 16 percent. The market knocked $10.63 a share off Motorola's stock the next day.  <p> Both industry analysts and company officials blamed aggressive price-cutting in the cellular-phone industry. In the fall of1995, for instance, Motorola had reduced wholesale prices on its Teletac phone by $15, at least partly in response to an earlier trim by NEC. It's not exactly surprising, then, that Motorola's net-profit margin fell to just below 6 percent of sales from 8 percent.  <p> This kind of price deflation is a well-established fact of life for technology companies: it's only investors who occasionally forget that a computer with today's power and features will cost less tomorrow. <a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a>, the manufacturer of the speedy graphics work stations that made the dinosaurs of Jurassic Parkwalk, was a favorite of investors until Wall Street noticed that competitors such as <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a> and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> had introduced low-end products that were cheaper than those of Silicon Graphics. In early 1996 Silicon Graphics struck back with a new system priced about $1,500 below Microsoft's product.   <p> But the spot deflation that's common in technology has now spread to companies in sectors of the economy that usually escape these pressures. In one of the earliest signs of the trend, in July 1995, Rubbermaid, a producer of such low-tech goods as plastic garbage cans, food storage containers, and children's toys, announced that the soaring cost of resins, the raw materials used to make plastics, had sent its second-quarter earnings tumbling almost 50 percent in comparison with the year-earlier quarter. In normal inflationary times, Rubbermaid would have simply passed those costs along to consumers by raising prices. But the company was already losing shelf space to the cheaper products of competitors at chains such as <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>. So instead of raising prices, Rubbermaid announced plans in December to wring $50 million in costs out of overhead. But that won't fix the company's problems overnight. Net margins have slipped to 8 percent from more than 10 percent in 1994.   <p> Corporations are responding to these product-by-product pressures in very different ways. Some, such as Motorola, have decided to do whatever it takes to hold on to market share, even if that punishes short-term earnings. Others, such as <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> in computer printers and <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> in computer chips, have concluded that they are more production efficient than their competitors and are relentlessly driving down prices to seize market share. Still others, such as <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eastman Kodak</b></a> in copiers, have decided to get out of businesses that they can't dominate.  <p> That gives investors trying to pick stocks new food for thought. Take the auto industry, for example. When <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford Motor</b></a> brought out the redesigned Taurus, it hiked base prices on its four-door GL model by almost 6 percent, apparently believing that the car's innovative styling, added standard features, and quality were more important to consumers than dollars. <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, on the other hand, has priced its Chevrolets and Pontiacs below its competitors' products. The results: Sales of the Ford Taurus fell 35 percent in December 1995 compared with December of 1994, and Ford is now waving $600 rebates at consumers. General Motors' longtime money-losing operations in North America look like they'll be in the black for a second straight year. An even bigger winner,though, may be <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>, which is selling cars with smaller rebates than Ford and has a better product line and lower costs than <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>.  <p> In 1995 declining interest rates and soaring profits lifted almost all stocks in all sectors. In 1996 investors, like the companies themselves, will have to bet on the success or failure of very different corporate strategies for coping with a tough competitive environment. Investors will have to study companies in unfamiliar ways, looking at costs and manufacturing efficiencies, the growth or decline of margins, pricing strategies, and other indicators of competitive position. This year promises to be especially damaging to the second-rate.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Telecommunications Industry, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MOT">Motorola, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:RBD">Rubbermaid Incorporated</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:SGI">Silicon Graphics, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:SUNW">Sun Microsystems, Inc.</a><br>

