	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996  <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> KEEPING UP  <p> By Teri Karush   <p> *Fidelity investments, reverting to an old policy, has told its fund managers to stop talking to the press about individual stocks. The decision follows news reports that Jeffrey Vinik, manager of Fidelity's flagship <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Magellan Fund</b></a>, publicly touted the stock of<a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Micron Technology</b></a> even as he reduced Magellan's holdings in the stock. Fidelity now faces a class-action lawsuit from holders of Micron stock, accusing Vinik of market manipulation. Fidelity denies the charges.   <p> *MONEY magazine has fired columnist Dan Dorfman, saying that the stock tipster wouldn't disclose news sources to the publication's managing editor. Dorfman had been on paid leave from Money since October, when Business Week said federal authorities were investigating Dorfman. The commentator, who says Money erred in its decision, continues his regular broadcasts on CNBC.  <p> *Paine Webber has agreed with the Securities and Exchange Commission to set aside an additional $175 million (on top of the $120 million it has already paid) to settle charges that it misled investors when it sold hundreds of millions of dollars in risky limited partnerships during the 1980s. Paine Webber took a $200 million charge against earnings in last year's second quarter in anticipation of the settlement.  <p> *A task force of securities-arbitration officials, headed by former Securities and Exchange Commission chairman David Ruder, has recommended a total of 70 changes in the way investors and brokerages settle disputes, including a wider pool of arbitrators, substituting the current six-year deadline for filing cases with existing statutes of limitations, and a cap on punitive damages of two times compensatory damages (up to $750,000). The recommendations go to the board of the National Association of Securities Dealers, which handles 85 percent of all arbitration cases. The changes could be in place before the end of the year.  <p> *Banks are doing a worse job of warning novice investors about the risks inherent in mutual funds, according to a survey by Prophet Market Research, based in San Francisco. Prophet says that, during an undercover audit of 400 brokers working at banks, 27 percent failed to caution investors that mutual funds aren't protected by federal deposit insurance. A year earlier, only 20 percent of the brokers surveyed neglected to give the warning to Prophet researchers, who posed as potential customers with $25,000 to invest.  <p> *President Clinton has recently signed a law barring a state from reaching beyond its borders to tax the pension benefits of retirees who earned their benefits while working in the state but have since moved elsewhere. The practice, which Worth reported in the October 1995 issue, had raised the ire of a number of retirement interest groups with the notable exception of the American Association of Retired Persons. The AARP says that it didn't support the bill for fear that it might prompt some states to limit tax deductions for pension contributions. <p>  <p>*Alan S. Blinder has returned to a teaching job at Princeton University after deciding against serving a second term as vice-chairman of the Federal Reserve. Blinder was a champion of lower unemployment and therefore lower interest rates.  <p> *The federal trade commission has given its blessing to a new Funeral Rule Offenders Program, under which funeral homes caught violating federal rules, such as the requirement that they provide itemized price lists to prospective clients would pay a fine to the U.S. Treasury and then undergo supervision by the National Funeral Directors Association.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Banking Industry, Mutual Funds Investing, Ethical Investing, Taxation, Government Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

