<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996   <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> GLOBAL MARKETS  <p> By Todd G. Bucholz  <p> SPAIN & FRANCE <p>A member of the Clinton administration once remarked that he would like to be reincarnated as the bond market, since it has more influence than officials in Washington.   <p> Last year's extraordinary global bond rally was proof that this is true far beyond Washington. The rally was fueled by fiscally conservative governments, from Brazil to Canada, that sought to find favor with foreign investors and big banks bond buyers all by cutting spending and privatizing national businesses. <p> Now it's Spain's turn; its markets have rocketed ahead as traders grow confident that a conservative government will come to power after the March 3 elections. Yields on ten-year bonds (called bonos) dropped from 10.14 percent on December 1 to 9.27 percent on January 18. Meanwhile, the Spanish economy is growing at between 2.5 and 3.0 percent a year, among the highest rates in Europe, and Spain's peseta is rallying against the deutsche mark. Trading at 93.35 in March 1995, the peseta is now valued at about 84 to the mark. It has remained strong even as the Bank of Spain has cut rates.  <p> The key to the Spanish economy lies in keeping inflation, which ended 1995 at a perfectly reasonable 4.3 percent, in check. Can this continue? The stronger peseta makes it easier, and global inflation levels look fairly tame. At the same time, Spain still suffers from 22.7 percent unemployment, so the Spanish public is paying a big price to boost the peseta. Labor laws have made businesses reluctant to hire new workers and hence expand because it can be impossible to fire them. There's lots of room for growth if the government loosens its regulatory grip.  <p> This is one of several economic issues that may be decided by the elections. The conservative leader of the Popular Party, José María Aznar, was expected to defeat incumbent Socialist premier Felipe González in 1993, but the charismatic González pulled off a surprise victory. Even if the Populists win this time around, they may have to form a coalition with the Catalanparty (CiU), which advocates political and financial autonomy for Catalonia. Markets don't like coalitions, which tend to be unwieldy and unstable.   <p> If Aznar wins, he and his party will inherit a fairly strong economy and a government that has already begun the process of economic reform. González sold large stakes in the banking, energy, and telecommunications sectors to the public, and he curtailed public spending as a percentage of gross domestic product. The big savings are yet to come from social security and pensions but it's unlikely the Populists will have the clout or the will to tackle them.  <p> For equity investors in the <a name="FUND:ABUSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ABUSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>U.S., Alliance Capital Management's Spain Fund</b></a> languished at about 8.50 for most of fall 1995, but moved up to 9.50 in mid-January. But keep in mind that González may not yet have exhausted his store of charisma.  <p> NOT SO WILD OATS <p>Last spring, the French elected as president Jacques Chirac, the conservative former prime minister. The Chirac government has struggled inconclusively to convince the financial markets that it has the guts to cut France's huge retirement and social-security programs and  bloated civil service. Because of this, the markets have on occasion punished the French franc and OATs (bonds). Last fall was the low-water mark. In October, the Bank of France ordered emergency rate hikes to defend the franc against speculators, and in November and December, strikes paralyzed the country. Still, the French markets have begun 1996 in pretty good shape. As of late January, the franc had risen about 3 percent against the deutsche mark since mid-October, and the stock market ended last year up about 8 percent.   <p> Now, though, France's economy is weakening with GDP growth around 2 percent and overall demand shrinking. A slower economy meansless money in Treasury coffers, so deficits may rise, not fall,in 1996. French bonds may do well initially, reflecting the growing weakness of other French investments, but by spring the nation's fiscal mess will cause the risks on bonds, too, to rise.  <p> Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz is president of the G7 Group Inc., an international economic-consulting firm, and author of From Here to Economy (Dutton, 1995).  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Bond Investng, International Economy, International Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
