		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-What They're Recommending </title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Recommending Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-What They're Recommending </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE RECOMMENDING  <p> The most recent additions to our panel of experts, these four top financial-newsletter writers identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the author considers a stock attractive. In some cases, the newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages. He also may have changed his opinion after the publishing deadline for this issue.  <p>  <p>JIM McCAMANT <p>Medical Technology Stock Letter  <p> Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.  <p>  <p><a name="NASD:ARRS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16571"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ARRIS PHARMACEUTICAL</b></a> up to $12  Nasdaq: ARRS  <p>  <p>Arris (South San Francisco, California) is a development-stage biotech company focusing on protease inhibition. Its lead product, APC 366-A (for the treatment of asthma), is already in clinical trials. Arris's broad technology base has allowed it to sign deals with quality partners such as Amgen, Bayer, and Pharmacia. Funds committed by these partners (Bayer, for example, has put up $40 million) more than exceed the current market capitalization of Arris and help off set losses. The stock's performance should improve in 1996 as the results of the trials come in over the next year. My 18-month target for the stock is $20.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> MICHAEL MURPHY <p>California Technology Stock Letter  <p> Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.  <p>  <p><a name="NASD:VICL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16150"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VICAL</b></a> up to $11  Nasdaq: VICL  <p>  <p>Vical (San Diego) is the leading publicly traded gene-therapy company. It emphasizes naked DNA technology, which doesn't require a virus to carry a cure, and just started phase-two trials for a melanoma drug called allovectin. If phase two goes as well as phase one (in which there were some cases of complete remission), it may be able to bypass phase three. Vical has invested $40 million in R&D, yet its market value is only $120 million. So the stock is cheap by that measure. <a name="NYSE:RP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rhone Poulenc</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a> are strong partners. My target is $18 a share for 1996 and $100 a share for 1997 or 1998, whenever (or if) allovect in wins federal approval.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> LOUIS NAVELLIER <p>MPT Review  <p> Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.  <p>  <p><a name="NASD:ASND"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41997"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ASCEND COMMUNICATIONS</b></a> up to $40  Nasdaq: ASND  <p>  <p>Ascend (Alameda, California) is ascending because it's one of the few Internet stocks that actually earn a profit. It does so because it supplies hardware for servers and has few competitors. As traffic on the Net builds, the servers that control the traffic will need more of Ascend's hardware. Last quarter, sales were up 289 percent over the like period last year. Improvement in the company's margins have paused recently but should resume in 1996. Following a two-for-one stock split scheduled for early1996, the stock could more than double to $80. It's a great story, but this stock is hotter than hot. This is a risky play.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> DAN SULLIVAN <p>The Chartist  <p> Uses technical analysis to identify long-term equity investments. <p>  <p><a name="NASD:HBOC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>HBO & COMPANY</b></a> up to $92  Nasdaq: HBOC  <p>  <p>HBO (Atlanta) designs, sells, and services information-processing systems for hospitals. Its software facilitates patient care, as well as clinical and financial management. The stock is extremely attractive on a relative strength basis, and profits have consistently outperformed analysts' expectations. In the third quarter, earnings rose 65 percent to 38 cents a share from 23 cents a year earlier. Given the ongoing pressure on health-care costs, we expect HBO's profits to improve about 30 percent annually over the next three to five years. One warning: the shares have experienced an impressive run-up of late; above-average volatility is likely in the short term.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
