<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. The manager may also have sold the stock after December 22, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these eight managers are meant to illustrate a broad range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy any stock, Worth strongly recommends that they conduct their own due diligence.  <p>  <p>PRESTON ATHEY <p><a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</b></a>  <p> Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.  <p>  <p><a name="ASE:SGA"></a><b>SAGA COMMUNICATIONS</b> up to $17  ASE: SGA  <p>  <p>Saga (Gross Pointe Farms, Michigan) operates one television station in Missouri and 24 radio stations in the East and Midwest, including Columbus, Ohio; Norfolk, Virginia; and Milwaukee, Wisconsin. This is a conservative, low-debt company that has been growing at a slower, more deliberate pace than its peers mainly because it hasn't been willing to pay exorbitant prices for acquisitions. If the economy softens, Saga is in a position to scoop up some good deals. Saga's stock currently trades at 10 times its 1995 after-tax cash flow cheap in comparison with the 17.7 average for its industry. This could be a $20 stock by the end of 1996. <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> JAMES P. CRAIG <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund </b></a> <p> Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.  <p>  <p><a name="NYSE:BK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10177"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BANK OF NEW YORK</b></a>up to $52  Nyse: BK  <p>  <p>BK (New York) has a disciplined acquisitions strategy. Instead of acquiring other banks, it has been buying their security-processing departments, such as J. P. Morgan's and Bank of America's. Security processing involves high fixed costs, so BK gains leverage on its margins with each acquisition. It just announced a 16-million-share buyback for 1996. BK is highly efficient: Non-interest expenses are only 49 percent of revenues and heading even lower. (The industry average is over 55 percent.) Equity as a percent of capital is also well above average. We think the stock could trade at 12 times expected 1997 earnings of $5.65 a share within a year, or $68.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> SHELBY M. C. DAVIS <p><a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> <p>  <p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.  <p>  <p><a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WELLS FARGO </b></a>up to $215  Nyse: WFC  <p>  <p>I expect Wells Fargo (San Francisco) to be at the forefront of banking. It has one of the best efficiency ratios in the business and recently signed arrangements to put small banking centers in eight of the ten largest supermarket chains. This will significantly lower its branch costs. Wells Fargo is also at the forefront of electronic banking. Management runs the bank as if it owned it, buying back a lot of stock. If the much-talked-about merger with First Interstate happens, it would create huge savings. The stock, which is selling at around the industry average often times 1995 earnings, could move to $300 a share within the next 18 to 24 months.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> DANIEL B. LEONARD <p><a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a>  <p> Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.  <p>  <p><a name="NYSE:WFR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44021"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MEMC ELECTRONIC MATERIALS</b></a> up to $42  NYSE: WFR  <p>  <p>MEMC (St. Peters, Missouri) makes polished silicon wafers, which are used by companies such as <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> to produce semiconductors.While there's a lot of disagreement about the outlook for semiconductors, wafers themselves are in short supply and will be through 1996. So MEMC is in the driver's seat and should have a very good year. Polycon (material used to make wafers) is tough to get, but MEMC makes two-thirds of its own supply. In addition, there's nota lot of competition in this area. I expect the company, which earned $1.65 a share in 1994, to make $2.57 a share in 1995 and at least $3.20 in 1996.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ <p>HUGH F. DENISON <p><a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund </b></a>  <p> Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued. <p>  <p><a name="NYSE:UNC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11524"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UNC </b></a>up to $6  Nyse: UNC  <p>  <p>UNC (Annapolis, Maryland) is an aviation service company that overhauls jet engines and manufactures and repairs parts. The best way to make money in aircraft is to build them, not fly them. This is our second time in the stock (we hold 1.1 million shares). There's some risk because UNC has more long-term debt ($160 million) than equity ($110 million). But the stock is trading at only four times cash flow. UNC turned the corner in 1995 and should be more profitable in 1996. We're looking for earnings of 20 cents a share in 1995 and at least 50 to 70 cents in 1996.   <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> ERIC E. RYBACK <p><a name="FUND:LDDUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a>  <p> Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.  <p>  <p><a name="NYSE:NOK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41820"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NOKIA </b></a>$40  NYSE: NOK  <p>  <p>Nokia (Helsinki, Finland) is one of the largest global manufacturers of cellular-telephone hand sets and infrastructure equipment. The stock has declined sharply on concerns over slowing growth in the cellular market. My positive stance is based on three things: the company's expansion in overseas cellular markets; strong, shareholder-focused management; and a low valuation for the premier company in a rapidly growing industry. Trading at 10 times 1996 estimated earnings and 8.6 times 1997 estimates, Nokia shares should appreciate into the low $50s. I have owned the stock before and have recently begun buying it again.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> RALPH WANGER <p>CHUCK McQUAID <p><a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund </b></a>  <p> Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.  <p>  <p><a name="NASD:LNCR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15622"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LINCARE HOLDINGS </b></a>up to $32   Nasdaq: LNCR  <p>  <p>Lincare (Clearwater, Florida) provides home health-care services treating respiratory diseases. Because this form of care is relatively inexpensive, the field is growing rapidly. Lincare has a leading market share in a highly fragmented industry and has been growing both internally and through acquisitions. The stock was hurt by the proposed Medicare cutbacks, yet even if the government goes ahead with its latest proposal, Lincare's 1996 earnings will still grow by 10 cents a share to $1.90. We think Lincare's sellout value is more than $40 a share, or 12 times 1995 cashflow. It was the target of a takeover bid by Coram Healthcare and could be a target again.  <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p><a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund </b></a> <p> Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.  <p>  <p><a name="NYSE:RBK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11266"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>REEBOK INTERNATIONAL</b></a> up to $28  NYSE: RBK  <p>  <p>The stock of Reebok (Stoughton, Massachussets) fell in 1995, so investors sold at year's end to capture capital losses. This has driven the stock even lower and created a buying opportunity. This maker of leisure footwear is struggling in the U.S., but its position worldwide versus Nike's is stronger than Pepsi's versus <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coke</b></a>'s. The business has excellent economics: Reebok does the design and marketing, but the shoes are made by foreign manufacturers. Reebok is using excess cash flow to repurchase stock. The shares are cheap, selling at around 8 times our estimate for 1996 earnings of three dollars a share; Nike's multiple is 18. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategeis

					</font>
