	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know/Street Wise  <p> KEEPING UP  <p> By Teri Karush  <p> * Congress has overridden a presidential veto and passed legislation that will make it harder for investors to sue underwriters, corporate officers, and accountants. The measure received intense support from major accounting firms, the brokerage industry, and high-technology companies (which have been vulnerable to shareholder lawsuits because of the extreme volatility of their stocks). Consumer groups and many state securities regulators opposed the legislation. Among other things, the bill protects a company and its officers from being sued over predictions about future corporate performance.  <p>  <p>* The securities industry began lobbying to head off a Treasury Department proposal that would reduce certain tax advantages associated with preferred stock and instruments with maturities exceeding 40 years. These would include instruments known as trust-originated preferred securities (sold by <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> as TOPrS) and monthly-income preferred securities (sold by Goldman Sachs as MIPS). TOPrS and MIPS had been popular among fixed-income investors because they pay dividends as much as one percentage point higher than corporate bonds. With the outlook for TOPrS and MIPS clouded by the Treasury proposal, Merrill Lynch unveiled a new instrument called a "cumulative fixed/adjustable rate preferred stock" (or FRAP). A FRAP offers investors a sweeter dividend if Congress does change the tax law.  <p>  <p>* <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a> has said that it plans to provide online banking over the Internet by the second half of this year. Users will be able to download free software to establish their home banking connection. At the moment, Intuit requires customers to own its Quicken personal-finance software and to dial into a private network in order to bank electronically.  <p>  <p>* The Clinton administration has floated the possibility thatit may seek to close a tax loop hole that involves "shorting against the box." Investors use the hedging technique to lock in profits on stocks while deferring capital-gains taxes.  <p>  <p>* Most mutual funds reveal their investments only twice a year. But GIT Investment Funds of Arlington, Virginia, has begun posting the portfolios of its four equity funds and five tax-free bond funds each day on the Internet. The portfolios appear on GIT's home page at http://www.gitfunds.com.  <p>  <p>* Using an ATM may get more expensive following a decision by Visa U.S.A. to allow its member banks to charge noncustomers for using its Plus system ATMs. Charges could range from 25 cents a transaction to $2.50 starting in April, when the new policy takes effect. MasterCard International, which operates Cirrus, may follow the move. <p>   <p> * <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a> has backed away from its previously reported promise to discontinue paying for order flow on Nasdaq stocks the controversial practice of buying customer orders from other dealers, bundling them together, and reselling them at a profit. Schwab now says such a move would be financially impractical. <p>  <p>* The Internal Revenue Service won't come close to its goal of receiving 80 million tax returns electronically by 2001, according to the General Accounting Office. The GAO also predicted that the number of 1995 electronic returns filed with the IRS will drop about 10 percent to 14.8 million from 1994's 16.4 million. <p>  <p>* Some supermarkets now offer two kinds of cabbage. About 35 banks have installed automated loan machines (ALMs) at approximately 60 locations, including grocery stores, according to Affinity Technology Group. The ALMs provide unsecured personal loans of up to $10,000. Users typically need a driver's license and a major credit card.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Technology Industry, Family Finance, Government, Legislation, Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
