	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-The Dow is Not the Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Dow is Not the Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-The Dow is Not the Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> THE DOW IS NOT THE MARKET <p>Just seven stocks drove the latest surge of the Dow average.What does that tell us?  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> All investors know "the Market" is up, but how much? The Dow Jones index of 30 industrials, for example, climbed from 4755.48 on October 31, 1995, to 5176.73 on December 15 a little more than 8.8 percent. The Standard & Poor's 500 Index didn't do quite as well; it rose 6 percent. The Value Line Index lagged even further behind, with an increase of just 4.1 percent. And then, of course, there's the poor Nasdaq Index, which tracks the over-the-counter market. According to this measure, the market isn't up at all the Nasdaq fell 0.5 percent in the period.  <p> The recent divergence of these indexes is telling investors about a change in the style of this market and signaling its future. To interpret this story, though, it's necessary to understand how each index is constructed.  <p> The Dow is the most frequently cited index when people say the market is up or down, they're usually referring to the Dow but it's also the index least representative of the market as a whole. Despite many changes in its membership, the Dow, which datesback to 1896, is a relic of an earlier America. The index, which is revised by <a name="NYSE:DJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dow Jones & Co.</b></a> when it seems too far out of touch with the current economy, is heavy on old-style industrial stocks and light on consumer and technology companies. Here's the list:<a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:ALD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10062"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Allied Signal</b></a>, Alcoa, <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>, Bethlehem Steel,<a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10304"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caterpillar</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CHV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10328"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chevron</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:DD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10487"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>du Pont</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eastman Kodak</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:XON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exxon</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10668"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Goodyear</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>,<a name="NYSE:IP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10800"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Paper</b></a>, J.P. Morgan, <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>,<a name="NYSE:MMM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11003"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>, Procter & Gamble, <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a>,<a name="NYSE:TX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11458"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Texaco</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:UK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11540"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Union Carbide</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:UTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11559"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Technologies</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:WX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11627"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Westinghouse</b></a>, and<a name="NYSE:Z"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10538"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Woolworth</b></a>.  <p> So why did the Dow accelerate so rapidly toward year-end, leaving other indexes in the dust? Partly because of what the Dow is missing. During that late-1995 period when the market pummeled technology stocks the Pacific Stock Exchange Technology Index fell 3.9 percent in ten weeks it was to the Dow's great benefit that it contained only one pure technology company, IBM. That stock did go down 7 percent in that time.  <p> But even more important is what the Dow includes and how the average is calculated. The Dow is a price-weighted index; it is calculated by dividing the price of one share of each stock by a divisor (currently 0.34599543). This means that a big dollar change in the price of an expensive stock counts for more than a big percentage increase in a cheaper stock. To see the implications of this, look at the movement in two stocks, AT&T and Westinghouse, between October 31 and December 15.  <p> AT&T gained $4 a share during that time and closed at $68. Westinghouse gained $1.88 a share to close at $16. And the impact of each on the Dow? AT&T moved the Dow average by $11.56 twice as much as Westinghouse, even though AT&T was up just 6.25 percent and Westinghouse was up 13.3 percent.   <p> As a matter of fact, just seven stocks Boeing, General Electric, Goodyear, Merck, Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing, Philip Morris, and Texaco account for 44 percent of the Dow's climb from October 31 to December 15.  <p> Specific circumstances fueled some of those stocks 3M announced a restructuring, and Boeing rose on an upturn in orders for jetliners and the end of a strike but the fact that they've thrived as a group testifies to investors' appetite for stocks with solid and predictable earnings and broad exposure to international markets. In comparison, the Nasdaq Index, with its heavy exposure to faster-growing but less predictable technology stocks, went nowhere during the same period.  <p> Looking at another set of indexes helps to flesh out this picture. The Frank Russell Company's Russell 3,000 tracks a universe of 3,000 stocks. The company also breaks that universe into pieces by size (large- and small-capitalization companies) and style (value and growth). After ten months in which growth stocks outperformed value stocks, value stocks surged ahead for companies of everysize to close 1995.  <p> For the short run, at least, the indexes tell investors that the market has entered a new stage. Whereas the first three quarters of 1995 belonged to high technology specifically and growth-at-any-price stocks in general, recent months have rewarded investors in Dow stocks with more predictable growth rates and in purer value plays.  <p> In the longer run, this strategy may not be as safe as it seems, according to another index. In contrast to the Dow, the Value Line Index isn't price-weighted. Instead it assumes that an equal dollar amount is invested in each of the 1,632 stocks that the index tracks. So this index gives a better picture of how a typical stock has performed.  <p> All last year, the Value Line Index underperformed the Dow 35.01 percent for the Dow versus 24.50 percent for Value Line through mid-December and that underperformance has been accelerating.While the price appreciation of the Value Line Index was 70 percent that of the Dow for 1995 through December 15, for just the period of October 31 to December 15 the appreciation of the Value Line Index was only 47 percent that of the Dow.  <p> That divergence has raised warning flags among investors who know that a market in which gains go to an ever-smaller population of stocks isn't healthy. Investors can use these indexes they all appear weekly in Barron's to measure market danger. A rising Dow isn't great news if the real market doesn't follow.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
