	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> FIXED INCOME <p>The Problem With UITs  <p> By Bernice Napach   <p> In the first three quarters of 1995, investors put $2.8 billion into municipal unit investment trusts, or UITs. It's easy to understand why municipal-bond UITs seem to combine the advantages of bond funds and individual bonds. Like a fund, a UIT offers diversification through a fixed portfolio of about seven to ten different bonds. And like individual bonds, UITs have a set maturity, or a specific date by which investors can recoup their principal. <p> But UITs aren't as good a deal as they appear. They carry loads which range from 2 percent of assets for a five-year trust to 4.9 percent for a 25-year UIT and annual expenses of 20 basis points. Compare that with the up-front charge of zero on any no-load muni-bond fund.  <p> Right now UITs are particularly bad news for long-term investors. Although a 25-year UIT will spread the effect of that 4.9 percent load over a long period, it also locks an investor into current low yields for too long. At the end of November 1995, the estimated net long-term return on a five-year muni UIT ranged from 3.7 percent to 4.4 percent (equivalent to 5.4 percent to 6.4 percent for those in the 31 percent tax bracket). The estimated return on a 25-year trust was just 1.5 percentage points higher.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
