	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> TREND SPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> 3   WE'LL TREAT YOU LIKE GOLD. For the first time, banks are peddling gold cards even more aggressively than standard plates, according to the market-research firm Behavioral Analysis. And in case prestige isn't enough, more banks are waiving annual fees and offering low introductory rates on 24K plastic, too. BAI found that 95 percent (up from 84 percent in 1994) of all gold-card offers carried no fees and 80 percent (up from 54 percent) came with special rates.  <p> 3WHAT, NO LOLLIPOP? Ask physicians "Where does it hurt?" and they'll probably point to their wallets. According to the American Medical Association, doctors' annual income dropped 6 percent, to $92,000, in 1994. That's the first time doctors' income has gone any way except up in more than a decade, and it may help explain why the trend among doctors is to cluster in group practices. "A solo physician probably can't afford the latest technology," says Dennis Barnhardt of the Medical Group Management Association. "With group practices, the doctors can divvy costs and reduce overhead."   <p> 3OWNERSHIP ADVANTAGE. A recent study by the consulting and accounting firm Coopers & Lybrand reveals that businesses run by their founders expand faster than those headed by inheritors or new owners. Over the past five years, founder-run companies have grown 66 percent more quickly than businesses in the other two categories.  <p> 3WALL STREET WANTS NERDS. With online banking and financial services so popular, financial firms need techno savants more than ever before. And they're looking in all the right places to recruit them. "More financial firms come every year," says Dianne McLauchlin of the California Institute of Technology, where ten financial-services companies scouted for talent on campus last year. At MIT, the percentage of firms who come calling for future graduates has more than doubled in the past decade.  <p> 3ENGLISH MAJORS WANT JOBS. College graduates with liberal-arts degrees, meanwhile, get less attention. According to a new Michigan State University report on recruiting trends, liberal-arts majors accounted for 7.6 percent of new college grads hired last year, significantly down from 15.6 percent in 1994.  <p> 3DON'T FORGET THE GUEST ROOM. Nearly 25 percent of first-time home buyers (up nearly 5 percent since 1988) now get a monetary gift from kin for the down payment, according to a new study. "Those who do get gifts tend to save less because they anticipate the money from relatives," notes Chris Mayer, economist at the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston and co-author of the study.  <p> 3BOY TALK. Shattering one gender stereotype, a survey by <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> Home Business Resources reveals that of those who work at home, men (82 percent) are more likely than women (70 percent) to make personal phone calls while on the job. Note, however, that women (84 percent) outdo men (72 percent) when it comes to coiffing before work.  <p> 3THE NET HAS EYES. When employees are pleasure-surfing the WorldWide Web on the job, that is. According to a recent survey by new-media market-research firm Jupiter Communications, Web users spend an average of ten hours per week browsing the Net at work. But are they chatting about Baywatch or doing work-related research? Thanks to a monitoring device created by Webster Network Strategies, a privately held Florida-based software company, employers can now find out and even block Net access to time wasters. Webster already counts <a name="NYSE:LMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10903"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lockheed Martin</b></a>, Sikorsky Aircraft, and Northeast Utilities among its clients.   <p> S.H.E., INC. The number of women-owned businesses has jumped 43 percent since 1990, according to the National Foundation for Women Business Owners. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners, Banking Industry, Technology Industry, Small Business Ownership<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

