		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Market Radar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> MARKET RADAR  <p> Market Radar loses its sole positive indicator this month as investment advisers turn optimistic, a traditional sign that a market top may be at hand. The advance/decline line and the bellwether composite continue to show serious weakness. Since the financial markets largely anticipated the December 19 interest-rate cut by the Federal Reserve, the cut won't be enough to turn any of these indicators positive. That will require further interest-rate reductions and a budget deal in Washington.   <p> ADVANCE/DECLINE LINE  The line tracing the broad market has drifted upward but barely matches its October high, an anemic performance compared with the blue-chip indexes. The divergence will be resolved by renewed strength in the broader market or, more likely, by a downturn in the indexes.  <p> COMPOSITE BELLWETHER  This indicator has hit a three-month low. The two components are in a tug-of-war: Utilities are holding up, but many brokerage stocks have lost half their 1995 gains. Are investors in utilities because of optimism about interest rates, or are they just looking for a safe haven?   <p> ADVISORY SENTIMENT Investment advisers have bounced back from a bout of severe pessimism, and that could spell trouble. Advisers stayed skeptical for much of last year's rally; now, with optimism back to the high side of the normal range, this indicator urges caution. Much higher and it would be signaling a market top. <p> YIELD RATIO This is Market Radar's water-torture indicator; this month marks the one-year anniversary of its turning negative, and the numbers just keep getting worse. Again, yields on T-bills hold their own, while the S&P 500 yield slips another four basis points. Will the Fed's December 19 rate cut stop the ratio's slide?  <p> MONETARY EXPOSURE PROFILE Just as in July, the December cut in the Federal Funds rate was a case of the Fed's playing catch-up; market interest rates had already declined to similar levels. Although this move didn't change the MEP reading, a further rate cut by the Fed could turn this indicator positive.   <p> CONSUMER AND CORPORATE DEBT The amount of consumer and corporate debt is still going up, but the rate of increase remains stuck in the steady-as-she-goes 5 percent range. Recent interest-rate declines could spur companies to issue more debt, but they won't impel consumers to borrow more.  <p> ASSET ALLOCATION <p>Cracking On  <p> The U.S. market may be choppy, but none of the four private banks in our monthly survey is trimming its sails. UBS adds stocks: five percentage points domestically and seven points internationally. Bessemer shifts one percentage point from overseas equities to U.S. bonds; Brown Brothers and Northern Trust stay their courses. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, International Investing, Banking Industry, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
