	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE RECOMMENDING  <p> Four top financial-newsletter writers join us this month, each identifying his favorite domestic stock. The price listed is the maximum at which the author considers it attractive. In some cases, the newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages. He also may have changed his opinion after October 23, the publishing deadline for this issue. <p>  <p>Writer: JIM MCCAMANT <p>Medical Technology Stock Letter  <p>Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:AGPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AGOURON PHARMACEUTICALS </b></a>  $30  Nasdaq: AGPH<p>California-based Agouron is the leader in structure-based drug design. Basically, it develops new molecules that attach themselves to specific proteins. The stock has been strong based on early clinical trials of protease inhibitor, a class of AIDS drug. Less noticed is the potential for the company's new anti-cancer drug, which also is showing impressive results in early clinical trials. Agouron also has a pipeline of other excellent products. The company has a total market capitalization $270 million and has a very high level of cash--more than $100 million.  <p>  <p>Writer: MICHAEL MURPHY <p>California Technology Stock Letter <p>Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:EUPH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44511"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>EUPHONIX</b></a>  $10  Nasdaq: EUPH <p>Euphonix went public in August. It makes digital user interfaces for audio mixing boards. Its product helps reduce studio time and is less expensive than the competition's. Three quarters of its revenue comes from music business, 15 percent from film and television postproduction (for such features as Entertainment Tonight, The Lion King, and Crimson Tide). Short-term sales grow this close to 50 percent a year. I expect earnings of 25 cents a share in 1995 on sales of $14 million. I see the stock rising to the equivalent of 30 times projected 1996 earnings, which would get it up to $12 a share early next year.  <p>  <p>Writer: LOUIS NAVELLIER <p>MPT Review <p>Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:ZIGO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15204"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ZYGO </b></a> $40  Nasdaq: ZIGO <p>Zygo, based in Middlefield, Connecticut, makes precison optical equipment for manufacturers. Companies from a variety of industries (Canon accounts for 32 percent of sales) use these measuring instruments to monitor product quality. With Wall Street looking for new technology industries, this is one of the hotter groups right now. It is a very small company with strong sales and margin expansion, so when institutions start biting, it could go up quickly. Right now, there are more buyers than sellers. Profit was 25 cents a share for the second quarter, up from 8 cents a year earlier.  <p>  <p>Writer: DAN SULLIVAN <p>The Chartist <p>Uses technical analysis to identify long-term equity investments. <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NYSE:HPC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10721"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>HERCULES </b></a>  $62  NYSE: HPC <p>So what if chemicals are boring? The profits aren't. Hercules's earnings have increased at an annual clip of 25 percent during the past 5 years. I think this is sustainable. For one thing, Hercules is still finding ways to reduce costs. Second, it is aggressively expanding overseas, especially in Asia and in Latin America. Third, it is continuing to divest non-core businesses. It is using some of the cash it is raising from selling businesses to repurchase its own shares--at a rate of 5 to 6 percent of the outstanding shares annually. The stock buy back program should go a long way toward increasing shareholder value.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
