	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE BUYING NOW  <p> Eight acclaimed mutual fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund, perhaps at a lower price than the one mentioned here. The manager may also have sold the stock after October 23, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these eight managers illustrate a broad range of successful investment styles. The picks on these pages are intended to serve as long-term recommendations.  <p>  <p>Manager: PRESTON ATHEY <p><a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value </b></a><p>
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $250 million.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:UICI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15009"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UNITED INSURANCE </b></a>   $20  Nasdaq: UICI <p>Two things make this company, which sells health and life insurance to small businesses, special. One is Ron Jensen, the founder and chief executive. He's a true salesman, plus he gets paid $1 a year and writes his annual report like Warren Buffett. The other: 60 percent of the outstanding shares of stock is owned by management, employees, and the 5,200 agents who sell the policies. The incentive this provides is an advantage no competitor has, and it shows on the bottom line: Revenue has been rising at 19 percent annually, earnings per share at 41 percent. EPS should maintain this pace in 1995.   <p>  <p>Manager: JAMES P. CRAIG <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund </b></a> <p>Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NYSE:UTX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11559"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UNITED TECHNOLOGIES </b></a>  $90  NYSE: UTX <p>UTX is improving its profit margins by cutting costs at each of its five divisions: aircraft (Pratt & Whitney), air conditioners (Carrier), elevators (Otis), flight systems, and automotive parts. The aircraft unit has captured a big chunk of the market for 777 jet engines, due to delays at <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GE</b></a>. Replacement of air conditioners should increase over the next five to six years due to environmental regulations. UTX is trading at a very low 11 times expected 1996 earnings of $7.60 a share. I think the stock could rise to $110 a share within a year, which would provide more than a 20 percent return on investment.  <p>  <p>Manager: SHELBY M.C. DAVIS <p><a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> <p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NYSE:EQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13307"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>EQUITABLE COMPANIES </b></a>  $24  NYSE: EQ <p>Equitable is a potential growth company disguised as a financial concern. Its stock warrants a higher valuation than that of other insurers because of its diverse business mix, which includes investment banking, money management, and real estate in addition to insurance. Equitable's book value is close to $20 per share, barely below the stock's recent price. Life and annuity sales are picking up. Its Alliance Capital unit is gaining new assets. And Equitable will soon sell stock in its Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette unit. Earnings should exceed $2 a share in 1996. My 18-month target for this stock is $30.  <p>  <p>Manager: DANIEL B. LEONARD <p><a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology </b></a> <p>Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:ITRI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16259"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ITRON </b></a>  $32  Nasdaq: ITRI <p>Based in Spokane, Washington, Itron makes electronic measuring instruments for gas, electric, and water utilities. Its customers include more than 1,200 utilities worldwide. Itron recently signed lucrative contracts with Public Service of Colorado and Puget Sound Power and Light. Annual sales growth is around 35 percent, but earnings are rising at an even faster clip. Net income was 67 cents a share in 1994. I'm looking for 80 cents in 1995 and $1.15 in 1996. No big New York research firms follow the company, but when they catch on, the stock should get a boost. My 12-month target for the stock is $45.  <p>  <p>Manager: WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ, HUGH F. DENISON <p><a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund </b></a> <p>Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued. <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NYSE:URS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14365"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>URS </b></a> $7  NYSE: URS <p>URS Corp., a leading engineering and architectural-services firm based in San Francisco, does design work for infrastructure, environmental, and telecommunications projects. The company's backlog and designations (work that has been awarded but hasn't brought in any money yet) total a record-high $400 million. Despite one of the lowest overhead rates in the business and annual earnings-growth potential of 15 percent, URS is trading at only 8.6 times projected1995 profit of 75 cents a share. The Street is ignoring URS's industry, but we think there's a lot of work out there to keep this company busy.  <p>  <p>Manager: ERIC E. RYBACK <p><a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a><p>Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:GNCMA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11424"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GENERAL COMMUNICATION </b></a> $5.50  Nasdaq: GNCMA<p>This Alaska-based telecommunications company is 30 percent owned by <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI Communications</b></a>. In the wake of <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>'s acquisition of rival Alascom's long-distance assets, we think there's a good chance MCI will eventually buy the rest of GC. Based on strong cashflow, profitable operations, savvy management, and the value of its personal-communications services, a fair takeover price for the stock might be $8 or $10 a share, more than double the current price. GC also recently announced its intention to buyback 100,000 of its shares. This move should provide strong downside support for the stock.  <p>  <p>Manager: RALPH WANGER, CHUCK McQUAID <p><a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a><p>Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NASD:WFSL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15118"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WASHINGTON FEDERAL </b></a> $25  Nasdaq: WFSL <p>Washington Federal is a savings and loan association with 85 branches in five states, including Washington, Idaho, Oregon, Utah, and Arizona. In addition to being well capitalized (13 percent equity-to-assets ratio versus 8 percent for the industry),WFSL is a low-cost lender: Its expense ratio of 24 percent is less than half the industry average. Now that interest rates are going down again, we expect this S&L's margins and earnings to improve. We think the stock should trade at 12 times earnings, which gives us a target price for the stock one year from now of $36 a share.  <p>  <p>Manager: DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p><a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund </b></a> <p> Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.  <p> This Month's Pick: <a name="NYSE:UST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11533"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UST </b></a> $31  NYSE: UST <p>UST stock is like a beach ball being held under water--when it surfaces, it will really pop. This maker of smokeless tobacco is one of the most profitable, if not the most profitable, manufacturing companies in the country. Its brands include Copenhagen, Skoal, and Skoal Bandits. But ongoing worries about the liability of tobacco companies has held the stock down for four years, even though earnings have grown from $1.18 a share in 1991 to $2.15 this year and an expected $2.40 in 1996. Management raises the dividend every year and is buying back shares. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/6pages.gif"><br>About 6 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:UICI">UICI</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:UTX">United Technologies Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:GE">General Electric Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:EQ">The Equitable Companies Incorporated</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:ITRI">Itron, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:URS">URS Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:GNCMA">General Communication, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:MCIC">MCI Communications Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:T">AT&T Corp.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:WFSL">Washington Federal, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:UST">UST Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:PRSUX">T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value </a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:JANSX">Janus Fund </a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:NYVTX">New York Venture Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:FSFSX">Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology </a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:HRTVX">Heartland Value Fund </a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:LDDVX">Lindner Dividend Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:ACRNX">Acorn Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:YACKX">Yacktman Fund </a><br>

					<p>
	
		
