	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> TRENDSPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> * DEPTH OF A SALESMAN. Die-hard peddlers might not sell their own grandmother, but they would consider haggling with Mom and Dad--or misadvising a client. In a recent survey of 2,000 salespeople, 22 percent of used-car sellers and 15 percent of stockbrokers admitted they would out negotiate their parents for a done deal. Even worse, 21 percent of stockbrokers said they would pitch advice to a customer that they would not follow themselves. "Some are so desperate to get clients, they'll do anything to sell," says Robert Shook, who conducted the study. By the way, Shook himself is trying to sell something: his new book, The Greatest Sales Stories Ever Told From the World's Best Salespeople.  <p> * SAY IT AIN'T SO. Baseball fans who think they purchased the late Mickey Mantle's autograph for a steal may have struck out instead. Sweet Spot, a publication that tracks sports collectibles, reports that Mantle forgeries have been on the rise following the famed Yankee's death. "Mick fans who got a signed ball or photo for less than $85 probably bought a fake," says editor and publisher Charles Kaufman. "The market has become less scrupulous as demand for Mantle memorabilia increases."  <p> * TAKE A LOAD OFF. That's what mutual fund investors are doing: No-load funds have grown at more than one and a half times the rate of load funds over the past nine years, according to a recently released study by Goldman, Sachs. Some investors also plan to bypass full-service brokers. A poll by the Investment Company Institute found that while 41 percent of first-time buyers purchased their mutual-fund shares from a full-service broker, only 25 percent anticipate going through a broker next time. <p>  <p>* EXPECT A BIRTHDAY CARD FROM YOUR BROKER. According to a recent study commissioned by Oppenheimer Management Corp. and Registered Representative magazine, 54 percent of financial advisers crave a personal friendship with their clients. Only 24 percent of investors, however, want to buddy up with brokers.  <p> * STICKER AFTERSHOCK. If your new car was expensive to buy, don't expect it to be cheap to drive. When market-research firm Runzheimer International estimated operating costs for selected1996 model cars, it put the annual price of driving a Mercedes 320S at $19,832. That amount reflects fuel, insurance, and other expenses, as well as depreciation. Keeping a 1996 Ford Taurus on the road requires only $8,704 annually, Runzheimer said. <p> * HOUSTON, WE FORGOT THE ASHES. With cremation steadily gaining favor as a funeral option, one company hopes to cash in on the trend: Celestis Inc. of Houston plans to launch a space memorial service. For $4,800, the company will rocket a loved one's ashes into orbit.  <p> * HONEY, GET THE AXE. Although sales of Christmas trees have declined since 1993, the number of cut-your-own-tree farms continues to grow. "A quarter of all tree buyers will head to these farms to chop down their own tree this year," says Joan Geiger of the National Christmas Tree Association. "It's more of a family outing than just getting one from a corner lot." Expect to pay anywhere from $3.10 to $5.65 per foot for a tree this holiday season. <p> * OFF-RAMPS ON THE INFOBAHN. Everyone's plugging in their modems and going online, it seems. But are they staying there? After surveying 10,000 personal-computer users, consulting firm IntecoCorp. estimated that 6.2 million people have tried and later canceled a subscription to one of the top five online services. <p>  * STANDING ROOM ONLY. A recently sold seat on the New York Stock Exchange commanded $950,000, up 14.4 percent from last year's high of $830,000. That's not necessarily a good omen.The record price for a seat on the Big Board, $1.15 million, was paid just a month before the 1987 crash.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
