<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Speculation for the Masses</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Speculation for the Masses</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Speculation for the Masses</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> SPECULATION FOR THE MASSES <p>"Just put that on my card," and other signs that the bubble may burst  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> Have you Noticed that Wall Street is paying more and more attention to the amount of money flowing into mutual funds? That's because the difference between a 7000 Dow and a sickening correction increasingly depends on these cash flows. At 1,834 days and counting (as of October 19, 1995), the current rally is the longest of this century--handily beating the second-place 1,492-day uphill charge of 1942-1946, according to Ned Davis Research. Since 1945, the market (as measured by the Standard & Poor's 500 index) has never risen for this long without a correction of 10 percent or greater. Why should this time be different?  <p> Because of cash from mutual fund investors, say those predicting a continued upward march. In the four weeks ended October 18, investors in stock mutual funds sent $8.2 billion in new capital chasing after a limited supply of equities. And that's after $11.5 billion over the previous four weeks. Every time the market tumbles for a day or two and threatens to correct, the optimists point out, this money steps in to buy the resulting "bargains."  <p> Nonsense, say the gurus of gloom. It's exactly this flood of new money that has prevented the healthy correction that all markets need. Instead we're in the middle of a speculative bubble, with investors willing to buy stocks at almost any price because they believe that some fund manager with money to invest will buy tomorrow at an even higher price. Just wait, the pessimists say, until all these investors head for the door at once.  <p> Financial history is full of speculative bubbles, from tulip maniain 17th-century Holland to the 1929 stock market crash in the U.S. to the real estate and stock euphoria that seized Japan during the 1980s and is still unwinding. Only the greatest pessimists are raising the specter of those financial disasters right now, but it's worthwhile taking the comparison seriously for a moment. Looking for signs of speculation in the stock market of 1995 can tell investors exactly why this market might be vulnerable to a downturn.  <p> Speculative bubbles share two traits. One, assets are bid up to prices far beyond their actual worth. And two, the frenzy of buying is sustained as investors borrow on the inflated value of the assets to buy more. Once the price of the assets used as collateral starts to fall, lenders demand payment (since the collateral behind the loan has just vanished), investors are forced to sell, and the market sinks all the faster.  <p> In 1995, valuations seem restrained--the price-to-earnings ratio on the S&P 500 was recently 16.7, which is historically average. It's leverage that connects today's market to bubbles of the past.  <p> Here's one current sign of leverage. Margin debt--loans made to investors by their brokers, secured by the investors' stocks and used to buy more shares--has risen steadily since 1991. Outstanding New York Stock Exchange margin debt stood at a record $71.4 billion at the end of August. According to Safian Investment Research, August's $7 billion jump was a record increase for a single month.  <p> Mutual fund investors may also be using their credit cards to finance their stock purchases--not directly by calling up a broker and saying, "Put 100 shares of Seligman Communications on my Visa," but by running up debts to pay for current consumption as they "save" for retirement.  <p> Largely because of stagnant incomes, the national ratio of consumer credit plus home-mortgage debt to income (wages and salaries) climbed to a record high of 115 percent in the second quarter of 1995, according to Safian.   <p> As leverage, margin loans and credit card debt seem like mild excesses when compared with mortgaging a house to buy tulips. But today's leverage makes this market especially sensitive to the direction of the economy. In an economic downturn, individual investors already facing high levels of debt would cut back on new investments in stocks and mutual funds. That's not enough to send the market into a tailspin, but it wouldn't help push it higher either. In a more severe recession, households, which currently hold about 33 percent of their financial assets incash--near the low since 1952--might be forced to liquidate some of their investments. That could undermine the market.  <p> So what should cautious investors watch? The standard reports on economic growth aren't useful indicators, because they severely lag events. Instead, try watching delinquency rates on credit card debt. After falling to 1.7 percent in late 1994, the lowest rate since 1969, delinquencies have moved back up to around 2 percent. That's still below 1992's 2.7 percent.  <p> Pay careful attention, also, to the consumer-confidence numbers calculated by the University of Michigan and the Conference Board. Flagging confidence could lead to an unwillingness to assume a greater debt load. That would have negative effects on both the stock market and the economy.  <p> And finally, pay attention to your own household leverage. This is no time to get caught short of cash when life issues one of its own unpredictable margin calls. By all means, follow the old rule that recommends keeping six months' income in cash. But also look out over the next year to 18 months to see what large-ticket expenditures lie in wait. If you were planning to pay for them by liquidating equities, think about what you'd do if the market fell and you still had to meet these obligations. Remember, if the market does correct, the profits will go to those who can buy at the bottom, not to those who had to sell there.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economic Trends, Stock Market Trends 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
