		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> KEEPING UP  <p> By Teri Karush  <p> Securities firms have been falling all over themselves recently to show they care about the small investor--in some cases abandoning practices they once vehemently defended. <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a>took perhaps the boldest step, announcing that by year's end it will stop paying for order flow on Nasdaq stocks--the practice of buying customer orders from other dealers, bundling them together, and reselling them at a profit. Critics believe this behind-the-scenes industry custom undermines open bidding and results in less attractive prices for smaller investors.  <p> <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> meanwhile, said it will quit routing certain orders in New York Stock Exchange issues to the Pacific and Boston stock exchanges, where it has dealer operations. It promised that in the future it will send all orders only to a stock's primary market--where the stock is listed and where, presumably, demand is greatest.  <p> Finally, Dean Witter Reynolds ended its long-time holdout as one of the last major firms to pay its brokers more for selling proprietary products--including mutual funds and initial public stock offerings underwritten by the firm--than for selling outside products.   <p> ----- <p>Congress is weighing a rule change that would allow highly paid employees to contribute the maximum amount to their 401(k) plans regardless of the level of participation by lower-paid workers. Next year, the maximum pretax employee contribution will rise to $9,500 from $9,240 this year. Under current tax law, however, many highly paid employees actually have lower contribution ceilings because of anti-discrimination provisions included in federal rules.  <p> ----- <p>The National Association of Securities Dealers disclosed plans to prohibit brokers from paying referral fees to unlicensed people, including bank tellers. The new NASD rule must be approved by the Securities and Exchange Commission.  <p> ----- <p>Do they know something we don't? According to CDA/Investnet, corporate executives this year are selling shares in their own companies at a rate likely to surpass 1993's record for the dollar value of insider sales. The 1993 mark is about $13.5 billion. <p> ----- <p>Michael Steinhardt, the aggressive hedge-fund manager, will wind down his $2.6 billion in investment partnerships by year's end. Steinhardt, 54 years old, told The Wall Street Journal that investing no longer holds the "psychic rewards" for him that it once did. <p> ----- <p>The Internal Revenue Service has indefinitely postponed its plan to conduct so-called super audits of 153,000 taxpayers, because of budget cutbacks and, according to the General Accounting Office, administrative foul-ups.  <p> ----- <p>Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette plans to begin offering customers access to no-load funds managed by competitors. (Schwab, Fidelity Investments, and Vanguard Group already have similar programs.) Expect Merrill Lynch to follow suit soon.  <p> ----- <p>In 1996, Social Security taxes will be levied on the first $62,700 of workers' income, up from $61,200 this year.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Retirement, Mutual Funds, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
