<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special Issue <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> TREND SPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran   <p> A STATE OF WELL-BEING. For the second consecutive year, New Hampshire tops the list of the healthiest of the United States, as ranked by insurance company Relia Star Financial. The company rated states on 17 criteria and found that, among other differences,Yankees tend to smoke less and have better prenatal care. Downin the Delta, folks aren't so hearty and hale. Mississippi placed last on the list, down a notch from its rank of 49th last year. <p> OPEN THE BANK VAULT DOOR, HAL. Would you rather let your friendly personal computer handle your banking transactions instead of visiting your branch office? Banks hope so, it seems. A recent survey by Forrester Research, a technology consulting firm, found that 79 percent of the commercial banks queried are cyber savvy, with 34 percent currently offering personal-computer banking and 45 percent actively developing a system. Just over a year ago, only 54 percent of banks surveyed either offered techno-banking or planned to do so.  <p> YOUR BOSS WANTS YOU TO RELAX. More companies are providing counseling for modern-day problems. William M. Mercer Inc., a management consulting firm, reports that 92 percent of the employee benefit programs it examined offer services to help employees cope with stress. Sixty-seven percent provide counseling on gambling and education on workplace violence issues.  <p> DON'T CALL THEM SLACKERS. The Lutheran Brotherhood, a financial-services company for Lutherans, reports that those much-maligned Generation X-ers may be good for something after all. In a survey, the group found that 40 percent of people aged 18 to 29 are already providing or expect to provide financial help to mom and dad after their retirement.  <p> GETTING SOAKED AT THE STANDS. Catching your favorite sports team in action is rapidly getting more expensive. According to Team Marketing Report, a newsletter that tracks professional sports, the cost of a ticket for an NBA game has jumped nearly 37 percent since 1991. NFL tickets are up more than 32 percent, while major league baseball fans are paying 23 percent more. And once you've paid for your seat? Philadelphia Eagles fans really suck it up by shelling out $5 for a 14-ounce beer the priciest in pro football. The ticket-price increases must seem easier to swallow for Green Bay Packers fans, who can buy a beer for just $2.75.  <p> SOMETHING'S IN THE AIR. Expect to see those no radio signs propped in car windows amended soon to read no air bag, either. According to Kim Hazelbaker of the Highway Loss Data Institute, a nonprofit insurance research firm, 5 percent of all auto-theft claims are for stolen air bags. "Ripping off air bags is becoming the stereo theft of the '90s," Hazelbaker says. Replacement cost for a driver-side bag: Anywhere from $450 to more than $1,000, with insurance covering all but the deductible.  <p> SCHOOL OF HARD KNOCKWURST? Cheer up next time you write out that tuition check. After all, that college degree might put your progeny in the driver's seat of the Wienermobile, that is.In the past five years, Oscar Mayer Foods has seen a 75 percent increase in the number of college-educated applicants (over 800 in 1995) hoping to spend a year at the wheel of the 27-foot frank. <p> BANKERS BEWARE. The American Management Association says the financial-services sector leads others in the downsizing trend. Job reductions were reported at 61.2 percent of all financial firms last year, up from 51.3 percent in 1990.  <p> ONE MORE REASON TO FEAR A MARKET CRASH. Investors can now trade their way to Hawaii. Bull & Bear Securities, a discount brokerage firm, has become the first brokerage to reward customers with frequent-flier miles for each transaction. Alas, there's no bonus for investing in airline stocks.  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Employment, Insurance
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
