	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special issue <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> KEEPING UP  <p> By Teri Karush  <p> The National Association of Securities Dealers, moving to deflect criticism that it operates the Nasdaq market to the benefit of insiders and to the detriment of the public, has unveiled a plan for a new three-board governing structure that would include more non-brokerage firm members. The reform plan, which requires the approval of the Securities and Exchange Commission, would place a total of 40 governors on the three boards by the first quarter of 1997 with 19 governors selected from within the industry and 21 governors from outside it. Currently, 72 percent of the NASD's governors come from the brokerage business.   <p> The New York Stock Exchange has announced plans to lower transaction charges for smaller orders placed through its Super Dot system as of January, subject to SEC approval.   <p> Mutual Fund Companies now manage a larger share (37 percent) of the $600 billion in 401(k) retirement plans than do insurers (30 percent), according to Cerulli Associates, a Boston-based financial-services consultant.  <p> <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a> plans to offer electronic banking services to the 4 million customers of <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> sometime during the first half of1996. Intuit, the maker of Quicken, currently has 22 banking partners. <p>  <p>An October ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court will allow banks to temporarily freeze the accounts of depositors who defaulton a loan and seek bankruptcy-court protection.  <p> The Federal National Mortgage Association (Fannie Mae) will begin offering reverse mortgages early in 1996. These adjustable-rate mortgages will allow people over age 61 to essentially trade equity in their homes for either fixed monthly payments or aline of credit. Fannie Mae's information line is 800-732-6643. <p> American International Group, the global insurance holding company, has launched its first mutual fund for U.S. investors: the AIG Children's World Fund 2005, aimed at parents saving for their offspring's futures. As a sweetener, AIG said it would guarantee the original investment of shareholders as well as refund the initial upfront sales charges for those who meet certain conditions. <p> Fidelity Investments, sharply expanding its global fund offerings, is opening six new country funds covering established and emerging markets in France, Germany, Hong Kong and China, the Nordic region,the United Kingdom, and small companies in Japan.  <p> The American Homeowners Foundation, a nonprofit organization in Arlington, Virginia, will now investigate loan-payment histories for adjustable-rate mortgages. The group says about 30 percent to 40 percent of its customers find they are entitled to refunds, which average about $1,500. Customers must agree to split the proceeds of any refunds the group obtains as a result of its research. Call 800-489-7776 for further information.  <p> The average 1996 salary increase is projected to reach 4 percent the same as 1995's says Hewitt Associates, following a survey of1,811 employers. The benefits-consulting firm, based in Lincolnshire, Illinois, says other forms of compensation, including bonuses and profit sharing, are expected to rise 7.5 percent in 1996, compared with 7.6 percent in 1995.  <p> Some hotels, led by Westin and Hyatt, have begun charging fees to guests who check out one or more days ahead of schedule. The fees range from $25 to $50.   <p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Mortgages, Homeowners, Banking Industry, Technology Industry
					</font>
