<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-Fin de Cycle?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fin de Cycle?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Fin de Cycle?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special issue <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> FIN DE CYCLE?  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> No one wants to get off the gravy train too soon, but no one wants to be the last out the door, either, if the market's recent exploration of 5000 on the Dow turns into the big blow-off. At the moment the market is populated by fully invested but faint-hearted optimists who have one eye on the exit.   <p> The odds of anyone correctly predicting when to jump are pretty small. Professional economists will probably miss the next turn in interest rates. From 1982 to 1994, the consensus prediction of economists surveyed by The Wall Street Journal got the direction of change in interest rates over the next six months wrong 18 out of 25 times, according to a study by Ryan Labs, a New York money-management firm. Professional stock analysts actually did worse when it came to predicting an earnings turn, accordingto a study by Salomon Brothers. Heading into the recessions of1981 and 1990 and the slowdown of 1984-86, analysts missed the coming earnings downturns completely. In 1981, for example, they were predicting profit growth of 20 percent even as earnings on the Standard & Poor's 500 index were set to fall 15 percent for the year.  <p> The professionals' dismal track record in calling major changes of direction is especially important now. Evidence suggests that the interest-rate and earnings cycles that have driven this market are drawing to a close. The next 12 to 18 months will give birth to a new market, driven by new cycles. Smart investors will change gears now.  <p> For 15 years, the stock market has reaped the rewards of one of the great sustained declines in interest rates of the 20th century. In 1982, the yield on a 10-year Treasury bond hit 14.14 percent. On November 17, 1995, the yield fell to just 5.97 percent. Notwithstanding some temporary blips, rates have been falling steadily for 14 years.  <p> Those years add up to the fourth major wave to roll through the bond market this century. From 1900 to 1920 interest rates rose steadily. From 1920 to 1946, they declined (the yield on the long Treasury went from 5.32 percent in 1920 to 2.08 percent in 1946). From1946 to 1981, bond investors suffered a steady erosion of the price of their bonds as rates rose steadily toward that 1982 high of 14.14 percent.  <p> Partly because of this fall in rates, the past decade has been extremely kind to equity investors. Stocks have recorded annual gains far above their long-term track record of 10.2 percent per year for the past ten years, the annual return on the S & P 500 is 15.5 percent. But bonds have fared even better, far outperforming their long-term track record. For the past ten years, ten-year Treasury bonds have returned 9.91 percent annually just belowthe long-term historical return on stocks and well above the 5.1 percent annual return for intermediate-term bonds.  <p> The interest rate cycle isn't over, but it is nearing an end. The bond market is betting on at least one more rate cut by the Federal Reserve the Fed's discount rate of 5.75 percent is above the 5.6 percent yield on 90-day Treasurys and a series of cuts isn't impossible if Congress takes decisive action to balance the budget and the economy grows more slowly than the Fed expects. But yields on the 30-year Treasury haven't been below 5 percent since 1967, when inflation was consistently below 3 percent.  <p> The same winding down shows up in Wall Street's estimates on corporate earnings. For the third quarter of 1995, preliminary results show that Standard & Poor's weighted earnings measure for the S&P 500 will come to $8.65 about 88 cents below earlier projections, says Arnold Kaufman, editor of S&P's The Outlook. In mid-November, analysts lowered their full-year projection to $36.87, from $37.90 a month earlier. Kaufman says the final number will probably come in at $35.50.  <p> That's certainly not a precipitous dip: If the current $35.50 projection holds, 1995 earnings will still show a 16 percent increase beyond 1994 earnings. But the pattern shows a definite slowing, from a stunning 39.9 percent in 1994 to the expected 16 percent for 1995 to a projected 15.4 percent in 1996.  <p> At the moment, the market is happy playing the end game of these two cycles. Slowing growth is just fine, since it may prompt the Fed to cut rates some more. With modest inflation and growth, interest rates could drop another point and the bond market could continue its rally. If earnings grow at a slower but still steady12 percent in 1996, and if the S&P climbs 10 percent, the market's price-to-earnings ratio would still be a moderate 16.6. And with yields on bonds so low, stocks would remain the investment of choice for baby boomers worried about retirement.  <p> But endgames are dangerous. Investors determined to get the last dollar out of this market could instead get hurt. The risks are especially great and the reward especially small for investors with new money to invest.   <p> Here's one way to handicap the endgame strategies. If the rosy scenario comes true in 1996, new investments will reap a 10 percent return. If instead the Fed raises rates earlier in the year or earnings sink like a stone, the market will correct and that new money might be worth 5 percent less in a year. If new cash is parked in short-term Treasurys until the trends are clearer, it will earn, say, a little better than 5 percent. That may not seem like much, but consider this: An investor who bought into the market at the begining of 1973's major market decline would would have earned just 3.2 percent on his investment annually through the end of 1978. Still feel like plowing that year-end bonus into the market?   <p>
KEYWORDS:Economic Trends
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
