<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> WHAT THEY'RE BUYING NOW  <p> Seven acclaimed mutual fund managers have agreed to tell Worth readers each month about their current favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. Assume in each case that the manager has bought the stock for his fund, perhaps at a lower price than the one mentioned here. The manager may also have sold the stock after September 25, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these seven managers illustrate a broad range of successful investment styles. The picks on this page are intended to serve as long-term recommendations.  <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>Shelby M.C. Davis <p><a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> <p>Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.  <p> PICK: <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> (NYSE: GM) $49  <p> General Motors is the only major organization that has yet to be restructured other than the U.S. government. Can GM turn back 30 years of mediocrity? We think so. It just has to follow the road map provided by <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>. GM's current management is attempting to undertake the streamlining process while business is soft. The automaker is cutting costs and repairing its balance sheet. Some divisions--most notably GM Hughes and GMAC--could be worth more as stand-alone entities. In two to three years, GM could be earning $10 a share--up from about $7 a share this year--and the stock could be at $75.  <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>James P. Craig <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a> <p>Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.  <p> PICK: <a name="NYSE:UNM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11525"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UNUM</b></a> (NYSE: UNM) $56   <p> I recommended this leading disability-insurance provider at $47 a share in July. But now the story looks even better than it did back then. Management has continued an aggressive restructuring, which includes getting out of the tax-sheltered annuity business (only a 7 percent return on equity business). This will free up $150 million in capital, raise the company's overall returns, and speed it toward share buy backs. UNUM's core disability business is also improving faster than I anticipated. Earnings should start beating expectations soon. I think the stock will go to $80 in early to mid-1997. This may be your last chance to buy this stock at an attractive price.   <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>Daniel B. Leonard <p><a name="FUND:FTCHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FTCHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a><p>Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.  <p> PICK: <a name="NYSE:TMO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11473"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Thermo Electron</b></a>(NYSE: TMO) $50  <p> Thermo Electron is in the best growth areas of science. Through its roughly 20 units, this diversified company produces analytical instruments for the environmental, medical, and biomedical industries. It also makes alternative energy systems and environmental products. The company has grown considerably and has enhanced shareholder value by spinning off its subsidiaries while retaining a significant equity interest in each unit. Thermo Electron's net income is growing at well above 20 percent annually. It earned $1.40 ashare in 1994 and should net $1.65 this year. I expect profits to reach $2 a share in 1996. The stock could hit $60 within six months.  <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>William J. Nasgovitz & Hugh F. Denison <p><a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a><p>Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be under valued. <p> PICK: <a name="NYSE:AMV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12572"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AmVestors Financial</b></a>  (Nyse: AMV) $12   <p> AmVestors is an insurance company with annual revenue of about $150 million a year. Its primary product: Single-premium deferred annuities--a business that should benefit as baby boomers begin to save more. The industry is consolidating, and this company could get scooped up. But we like it for its inherent value. Book value is close to $13, there's no debt, and the stock is trading at less than eight times this year's earnings. Even though insurance companies tend to trade at a discount to the market, this low valuation seems unwarranted. AmVestors' revenue is rising by more than 20 percent a year, and it has a rock-solid bond portfolio.  <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>Eric E. Ryback <p><a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a><p>Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.  <p> PICK: <a name="NASD:URIX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17101"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Uranium Resources</b></a> (Nasdaq: URIX) $10   <p> Uranium Resources, the lowest-cost uranium producer in North America, is still a cheap stock, even though it has risen sinceI focused on it in September. An early 1996 start-up of the KingsvilleDome properties should allow the production of 2 million pounds of Uranium (U308) in 1996. The spot price of U308, which usually weakens in the summer, has been holding at $11.90 per pound. It could reach $15 by next year. The company should earn at least 50 cents a share in 1996. Using a 22 multiple (where two direct competitors are trading), Uranium Resources should be at $11. It could go as high $20 by the end of 1996.  <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>Ralph Wanger & Chuck McQuaid <p><a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a><p>Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.  <p> PICK: <a name="NASD:LBTYA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51395"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Liberty Media</b></a>  (Nasdaq: LBTYA) $30   <p> Liberty Media has ownership interests in 71 cable television channels via investments in both public and private companies. It owns part of Turner Broadcasting System, Discovery Communications, and <a name="NYSE:HSN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12024"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Shopping Network</b></a>. The company should benefit as advertising rates for cable television rise and as content flows into other applications, such as direct broadcast satellite, home video, CD-ROM, and international customers. Liberty's investments are worth about $33 per share currently, even though the stock has been trading in the mid-20s. Its value should rise rapidly as existing channels grow and new channels become profitable.  <p>  <p>MANAGER/FUND/STYLE: <p>Donald A. Yacktman <p><a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a> <p>Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.  <p> PICK: <a name="NYSE:FTL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11960"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fruit of the Loom</b></a>(NYSE: FTL) $25   <p> Fruit of the Loom, which commands more than a 40 percent share of the underwear market, has been struggling due to high cotton prices and weak demand for screen-print T-shirts. Yet this is a simple story. In brief, people simply aren't going to stop wearing underwear. Fruit of the Loom has low costs and dominates Hanes in market share. The passage of GATT means it won't locate any more assembly work in the U.S., though it will keep making fabric domestically. This company has the capability of earning $3 a share. The stock sold at $50 a share a few years ago and looks cheap now at $22. There's no dividend, so earnings go toward reducing debt. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Insurance Industry, Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing<p>

