	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> TREND SPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> * Nice house, but where are the biking and hiking trails? So ask nearly three quarters of potential home buyers when they're looking at real estate, according to a study by market-research company American Lives. In fact, proximity to walking and bike paths ranked fourth among important factors that affect house-hunters' buying decisions. The most desirable feature in the study was low traffic density, followed by placement on a cul-de-sac, and having lots of natural, open space. Low-ranking factors included local tennis courts and community golf courses.  <p>  <p>* Madison Avenues finds a new niche. Gay print publications--encompassing both magazines and newspapers--boasted a 16.2 percent surge in advertising revenues for the year ended April 1995. That outpaced both mainstream newspapers, which saw ad revenues grow 6.8 percent, and mainstream magazines, which enjoyed 13.3 percent growth. Meanwhile, ad revenues for Hispanic publications increased 6 percent, while the black print market grew only 3 percent.  <p>  <p>* Family comes before money when moving. That's the trend among workers deciding whether to accept company relocation offers, according to a recent survey by Runzheimer International. The study found that 63 percent of relocation offers rejected last year were vetoed because of family considerations; 27 percent were passed on because of the money factor. Back in 1991, 76 percent of those who declined a transfer did so for financial reasons.   <p>  <p>* Another sign of the 70s revival? Volunteerism in the Peace Corps is projected to reach 7,000 members by the end of this year, the highest level seen since 1978, when 7,072 activists served. Back at its start in 1961, nearly 70 percent of volunteers were male, and the average age of volunteers was 22. Nowadays, women outnumber men--53.5 percent to 46.5 percent--and the average volunteer's age is 30.   <p>  <p>* Attention all turkeys: There's some good news and some bad news. The good news is that Thanksgiving isn't becoming any more dangerous to turkeys; American consumption of the birds at holiday time has been nearly flat since 1990. But any fowl that escapes the dinner table here in the U.S. is likely to wind up on a boat, because Russians and Mexicans have recently developed a taste for turkey. "Exports are skyrocketing, especially the thigh meat and drumsticks," says Stuart Proctor, president of the National Turkey Federation. Indeed, exports of turkey parts have jumped 559 percent in the past five years. According to Proctor, Mexicans favor thigh meat as an alternative to pork in processed foods, while Russians import drumsticks for a cheap source of protein.  <p>  <p>* Wrinkles are in. According to the American Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons, the number of collagen injections (to fill out facial crevices and cavities like laugh lines and brow furrows) dropped to 27,000 last year from 41,600 in 1992.  <p>  <p>* A career change? Head to Atlanta, says economic think tank Cognetics Inc. in a study that ranks the regions with the highest anticipated job growth. Atlanta topped the list, with 161,630 new white-collar jobs expected to be created over the next nine years. Right behind Atlanta were Los Angeles, San Francisco-Oakland-SanJose, Dallas-Fort Worth, and Miami-Fort Lauderdale.  <p>  <p>* Businesses may finally be feeling more generous. The Conference Board, a nonprofit business research firm, asked large and midsize corporations to project their contributions to charitable causes and concluded that giving should rise 3 percent this year and 5 percent in 1996. It's been a while since companies felt so beneficent; for the past five years, the survey had found that giving wouldn't increase. Pharmaceutical companies headed the list of industries expected to ramp up their giving the most.  <p>  <p>* Cruising the Sunset Strip is no cheap thrill. According to Runzheimer International, it costs a typical driver in Los Angeles $8,375 a year to operate a car--more bucks than any other metropolitan area. The figures are based on a 1995 midsize sedan driven 15,000 miles a year and include insurance expenses, depreciation, license and registration fees, taxes, and operating costs such as gas, oil, tires, and maintenance. The least expensive of the 80 cities included in the survey was Burlington, Vermont, at an annual cost of $5,459, followed by Little Rock, Arkansas, at $5,660. <p>  <p>* The line on towing. Last year, the American Automobile Association received 26.8 million calls for emergency road service, the highest volume in AAA's 93-year history. Dead batteries and electrical failures accounted for 32 percent of calls. "Because cars are built better, the average vehicle today is 8.3 years old," says Mike Morrissey of AAA. "That, plus last year's lousy weather, upped the number of breakdowns." Or maybe it was just plain forgetfulness. Thirteen percent of those stranded on the highway had locked their keys in their cars. "We had one call where the woman's dog had locked her out of the car," says Morrissey. "We suggested that she teach Fido to drive so she'd have a chauffeur."  <p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
