	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-The Next Challenge</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Next Challenge</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-The Next Challenge</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> THE NEXT CHALLENGE <p>We've navigated enough dangers to arrive at (of course) another dilemma: What to buy in a slow-growth economy  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> Wall Street has curled up comfortably with the soft landing engineered by Alan Greenspan and the Federal Reserve Board: moderate growth at an annual rate equal to 2 to 2.5 percent and low inflation of between 2.5 and 3.5 percent. So now might be a good time for investors to ask, what kind of stock is best suited to this slow-growth economy ?   <p> The recent gyrations of the market have been sending mixed signals. One week stocks with big consumer names like <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> lead the pack, apparently benefiting from the theory that such companies will perform well no matter what happens in the rest of the economy. The next week, consumer issues fade and cyclical stocks light up the board. Cyclical companies (autos, housing, metals) are those whose earnings ebb and flow in tune with the classic business cycle. A bet on cyclicals is a bet on a strengthening economy.  <p> Cyclical stocks have had a remarkable earnings story to tell this year. In the second quarter of 1995, earnings among cyclical companies leapt almost 50 percent above their year-earlier level, according to Safian Investment Research in White Plains, New York. The achievement marked the sixth consecutive quarter in which the year-to-year profits of cyclical companies grew by at least 40 percent. Analysts who follow cyclical stocks expect the streak to continue.  <p> By comparison, the earnings of blue-chip growth companies have been paltry. The outfits whose stocks compose Safian's Traditional Growth Average Index reported an average earnings improvement of 12.8 percent for the quarter ended June 30, 1995. They weren't expected to do any better in the July-through-September period. <p> These measures, however, don't tell the whole story, according to Kurt Walters, vice-president of Safian. The long cyclical earnings rally, he says, really consisted of three mini-rallies by different kinds of companies. Starting in 1991, the consumer cyclicals such as <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford Motor</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:WHR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11632"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Whirlpool</b></a> began showing big gains on the bottom line. Then, in 1992 and 1993, equipment makers such as <a name="NYSE:CAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10304"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caterpillar</b></a> and Deere began raking in profits. Finally, in 1994, commodity companies such as Alcoa and <a name="NYSE:IP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10800"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Paper</b></a> joined in.  <p> The stages show up clearly in the earnings history of three representative stocks. For the most recent cycle, Ford's earnings bottomed in 1991, when the company showed a loss of $2.40 per share, climbed to $2.28 in 1993, and then more than doubled to$4.97 in 1994. Ford probably won't match that in1995.  <p> Caterpillar bottomed a year later with a 1992 loss of $1.08 per share. Earnings hit $3.36 in 1993, then $4.70 in 1994. Value Line estimates 1995 earnings at $6, but projects 1996 earnings growing to just $6.40.   <p> Alcoa didn't hit its low point until 1993, when the company earned just 40 cents a share. Earnings climbed to $1.08 in 1994 and are projected by Value Line at $4.35 in1995.  <p> Now, this multi-stage pattern is beginning to head in the other direction. Near the end of September, analysts lowered their estimates of Ford's 1995 earnings to $3.96, down 7 cents from their projections a month earlier. And in mid-September Caterpillar executives warned Wall Street that the company's third-quarter earnings probably wouldn't equal those of a year earlier, ending Caterpillar's string of six quarters of record profits.   <p> This leaves just the commodity cyclicals to sustain the sector."You've lost two legs," says Walters. But the third leg hasn't shown any sign of weakness yet, he adds. Year-to-year earnings gains of 100 percent are still possible for the commodity cyclicals for the next few quarters. <p> Just days after Caterpillar threw a bucket of cold water on the market, Coca-Cola rose to the podium with quite a different message. The company confirmed it was "comfortable" with the analysts' third-quarter estimates of 63 to 66 cents a share, compared with 55 cents a share a year earlier. Comfort commands quite a premium these days: Coke's stock jumped $4 a share for the week, hitting a 52-week high of $70.63. That drove Coca-Cola's price-to-earnings ratio to 31, the rarefied atmosphere more typical of a high-flying technology stock. Too much to pay for earnings growth that averaged 17 percent annually for the past ten years? <p> Growth stocks may have relatively stable earnings, but they still go through periods of high and low valuation. There are periods when investors will pay 31 times earnings for Coke, but there also are times, such as 1988, when 14 times earnings seems like a fair appraisal of the soda maker's value. (Since 1980 Coca-Cola's average annual price-to-earnings ratio has been as low as 9.6; it's never been higher than 28.7.) Safian has tracked the valuation of its Traditional Growth Index back to 1959 by contrasting the yield on these growth stocks to the yield on Treasury bonds. When the index is high, growth stocks traditionally are good values (1978-81 and late 1993 were such times). When the index is low, growth stocks often give poor value (1987, for example). Right now the index is neutral. In other words, growth stocks aren't a screaming buy, but neither are they yet overpriced.  <p> Safian's valuation number may slightly understate the attractiveness of blue-chip growth stocks in this market. Changes in the utilities industry have made that traditional safe haven for nervous investors far less attractive. Electric utilities face an uncertain period of deregulation, making profits hard to predict. The regional phone companies face new competition from the long-distance carriers and from cable-television companies. To many investors, convinced that stocks are the only game in town, blue-chip growth stocks,pricey as they are, seem the only alternative.  <p> To us, though, it's no time to be buying growth stocks just to be buying something. At the least investors ought to take a long tough look at how sustainable those blue-chip earnings really are. How many cents a share are dependent on exchange rates? Are margins near historic highs that may be set to contract if the economy slows or competition heats up? Is a brand nameand franchise really one that consumers will pay extra for if the household budget gets a little tight? Remember that Merck, a favored blue chip of the moment, has just recently recovered the $20 a share it lost in the wake of the Clinton administration's health care reform effort.  <p> And where do cyclical valuations fall at the moment? In August, they appeared to be nearing a new high continuing a climb they began from the low valuations of November 1990. That was the best time to buy those stocks, when their valuations were near a bottom. It's hard to find a good reason to load up on cyclicals now. Betting against history is always a risky proposition. <p>
<p>KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Investing Strategies, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
