	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Numbers Turn Trustworthy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>When Numbers Turn Trustworthy</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Numbers Turn Trustworthy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> WHEN NUMBERS TURN TRUSTWORTHY  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> How long does it take before investors can feel confident about a mutual fund manager's track record? Three years may be too short to test a fund against all market conditions. But changes in a management team may render a ten-year record irrelevant. Says Robert Padgette, president of Mobius Group, a software and data provider to professional investors: "A lot of people use five years because it generally will get you through at least one full market cycle."  <p> If that's right, then Michael Gerding, portfolio manager of <a name="FUND:FRINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FRINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Founders Worldwide Growth Fund</b></a>, may just have won his spurs.The fund, which hit its crucial fifth birthday under Gerding's control in May 1995 (the fund itself began operation in December1989), has recorded an average 14.2 percent annual return for the past five years. After adjusting for sales loads, none of the 38 other global funds with five-year track records have performed as well with as little risk. Investors have just started to notice: While still small at $190 million in assets, Founders Worldwide has collected $100 million of that since the start of 1995. <p> There's nothing fancy about Gerding's methods. "I absolutely believe that what makes a stock go up is earnings growth," says the 33-year-old manager, who got his start in international investing ten years ago running money for a bank's trust clients. Gerding cleaves to a growth-at-a-reasonable-price strategy modified to fit the international scope of his fund. (About 75 percent of the fund's portfolio is invested overseas.)  <p> Gerding looks for companies with both sales and earnings growing faster than the average for their industry and home market. He's willing to pay a 10 to 20 percent premium and sometimes more over the price-to-earnings ratio of a stock's home market, but at that price he hopes to find a stock growing at twice the rate of the average stock in that market.  <p> For instance, the fund's largest holding, <a name="NYSE:NOK.A"></a><b>Nokia</b>, a Finnish maker of cellular-phone hardware, sells at 18 times estimated 1995 earnings. That's about a 40 percent premium to the Finnish market's price-to-earnings multiple of 12.5, but the stock is still cheaper than its larger American rival <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>, which trades at a 23.8 multiple and is growing more slowly.  <p> Because his method depends so heavily on forecasting earnings, Gerding met with managers from more than 300 companies last year and spent ten weeks abroad assessing new products, new markets,and management. "If we don't see how the earnings will grow,we can't be confident in the estimates," he says. "Investing is more sweat than art or science."  <p> Gerding's portfolio is concentrated in just 60 to 80 stocks,75 percent of them small- or medium-size companies. Benefon, a Finnish maker of handsets for cellular phones, is typical. With a market capitalization of just $300 million, the company is too tiny for many global managers to bother with. But Benefonis releasing a new digital phone, Gerding says, that has the potential to double company revenues.  <p> Founders Worldwide isn't without risk. Gerding owns fewer stocks than his peers, and they're smaller which could add up to a bigger fall in a down market. And a substantial portion of the fund's gains has come from the dollar's fall versus foreign currencies, which could hurt the fund if the dollar stages a prolonged rally. "A lot of people buy our fund because they want to diversify their own dollar exposure," he says. "For me to hedge that away, I'd have to be very confident that we're in a major dollar bull market."  <p> Accelerating economic growth in the rest of the world outweighs any downside for the dollar, in Gerding's view. "Since the Gulf War, we've had virtually no growth in the developed world outside the U.S.," he says, "and we're beginning to see that change."That will fuel stronger earnings growth, and earnings grow this what this fund is all about.  <p>  <hr>   <p> Fund Briefs  <p> Rebutting Doom: In April 1994, economist Henry Kaufman, known on Wall Street as Dr. Doom for his negative views, proposed a mandatory 60- or 90-day wait before investors could redeem stock and bond funds to prevent a market meltdown. The fund industry's trade association, the Investment Company Institute, wasn't about to let that go. In a new study ICI concludes that's unnecessary since the peso crisis, bond market decline, and bankruptcy of Orange County didn't trigger withdrawals last year. Kaufman's not buying it: "1994 wasn't a real test," he says.   <p> The Big Shakeup: On August 24, Fidelity Investments named new portfolio managers at 21 bond funds, including 6 of Fidelity's12 largest fixed-income funds. Just as significant, since the arrival of Fred L. Henning Jr. as the new director of fixed-income investment, Fidelity has lowered risk by shortening durationand dumping emerging-market debt.  <p> Short form: Eight fund families have begun sending out prospectuses that boil down the typical 20 pages into just three or four. For this year, the families, which include Vanguard and Dreyfus, will send out both forms while the Securities and Exchange Commissiontests investor reaction.   <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
