	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Seven acclaimed mutual fund managers have agreed to tell Worth readers each month about their current favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. Assume in each case that the manager has bought the stock for his fund, perhaps at a lower price than the one mentioned here. The manager may also have sold the stock after August 28, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these seven managers illustrate a broad range of successful investment styles. The picks on this page are intended to serve as long-term recommendations. <p>
James P. Craig <p>
<a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a> <p>
Invests primarily in large growth of preserving capital over the long term.  <p>
 <a name="NYSE:CHA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10317"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Champion International</b></a> Nyse: CHA $60   <p>
 Champion has been raising prices on its main paper products. Unlike the industry's boom-bust pricing cycles of the past, paper companies aren't raising capacity so rapidly this time around so the higher prices should hold, boosting profitability. During the last three months, Champion has repurchased over 10 percent of its outstanding shares, and it just announced plans to buy back another 6 percent. I can see it devoting 30 percent of earnings to buying its own stock about $300-$400 million annually. This will push up earnings per share. I'm looking for earnings per share of $8 this year and $11 in 1996. Barring a major economic downturn, I believe Champion could become an $80 stock in the next 9 to 12 months.  <p>
Shelby M.C. Davis <p>
<a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a> <p>
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.  <p>
 <a name="NYSE:ALL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16182"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Allstate Corp.</b></a>   Nyse: ALL  $33  <p>
 Allstate, with 20 million customers and a broad product base, is one of the top insurance franchises around. <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a> recently distributed its 80 percent stake to the public. As often happens with spin-offs, the management is rethinking its mission: Now it has something to prove. Allstate is reducing its catastrophe exposure by avoiding high-risk places like California, Florida,and Long Island, and it is emphasizing high-growth lines of business such as life insurance and annuities. Barring any large-scaledisasters, Allstate could earn $3.50 per share in 1995 and $4 in 1996. The stock is now selling at six times cash flow and eight times earnings - too cheap. My target is $45 a share in two to three years.  <p>
DANIEL B. LEONARD <p>
<a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Technology Portfolios</b></a> <p>
Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.  <p>
<a name="NASD:LOJN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16551"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LoJack Corp.</b></a>    Nasdaq: LOJN $15  <p>
 Located in Dedham, Massachusetts, LoJack produces a patented detection system that assists the police in tracking, locating, and retrieving stolen cars. After a car owner has installed the $595 radio transmitter and registered with the police, the vehicle can be tracked in any of the 11 states in which the system operates mostly east of the Mississippi. I expect the company to go nationwide very soon. There are no direct competitors. There's only room for one player in this market. And some insurance companies are now offering hefty discounts to LoJack owners. The company reported net income of 16 cents per share in fiscal 1995, up from 2 cents in 1994. I think it will earn 32 cents next year and 55 cents in 1997.  <p>
WILLIAM J. NASGOVITZ <p>
HUGH F. DENISON <p>
<a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a> <p>
Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed  to be undervalued. <p>
 <a name="NYSE:KCN"></a><b>Int'l Colin Energy Corp.</b>   Nyse: KCN   $6   <p>
 This Alberta-based independent oil and gas exploration company has been a real laggard. The company expanded too fast and took on too much debt, which prompted a lot of institutions to lose interest. At $5 a share (down from $20 two years ago), the stock is trading at less than three times 1995 cash flow and at about a 50 percent discount to the value of its assets. It's not unusual for oil and gas companies to trade at six to eight times cash flow and at about 80 percent of asset value. We think this gap will close. Small, independent oil and gas companies have been one of the worst places to be this year so this is a turnaround play. Cash flow per share should be $1.65 this year and $1.75 in 1996.  <p>
Eric E. Ryback <p>
<a name="FUND:LDDUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund </b></a><p>
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.  <p>
 <a name="NASD:MCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Metricom  Inc.</b></a>Nasdaq: MCOM  $22   <p>
 Metricom got its start building systems for the utility industry. Now it installs wireless data networks in large cities (San Francisco, Seattle, San Jose) and on college campuses. Operating in a license-free spectrum, it attaches its small radio units to street lights.This allows it to provide high-speed, two-way communications at a very low cost to subscribers. College students, for example, get wireless modem access from their laptop computers. While Metricom is a viable company on its own, its proprietary technology makes it a likely partner for one of the big boys <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>,or Southwestern Bell. It has no earnings yet but could easily be a $50 stock. Paul Allen, cofounder of <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, is the largest stockholder.  <p>
RALPH WANGER <p>
CHUCK MCQUAID <p>
<a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a> <p>
Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.  <p>
 <a name="NYSE:FAM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15628"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Int'l Family Entertainment</b></a> NYSE: FAM  $19   <p>
 This media company provides programming for cable television. Its core domestic cable channel The Family Channel reaches over 60 million homes in the United States, is very profitable, and has cash flow growth of over 20 percent this year. International Family Entertainment's net income rose 60 percent in the first half of 1995, despite startup costs associated with the new Cable Health Club network and the U.K. Family Channel. Right now, investors who buy stock in this company essentially get these start-up channels for free not to mention a valuable film library, a production company, and live-entertainment assets. If the new channels develop as I expect, the stock could double in a few years.  <p>
DONALD A. YACKTMAN <p>
<a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a> <p>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market  capitalization of at least $1 billion.  <p>
 <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris </b></a> Nyse: MO  $78   <p>
 Philip Morris, of Marlboro, Miller, and Miracle Whip fame, is extremely profitable. New management is focusing on high-return-on-assets businesses. The stock is trading at a very low relative multiple based on expected reported earnings of $6.50 this year (excluding $0.50 of goodwill) and $7.50 next year. At the next meeting, directors will probably raise the dividend to $3.90 a share from the current $3.30. Maintaining a 5 percent yield should get the stock up to $78. It also looks attractive on a technical basis: Once it breaks through its all-time high of $86.6, it should keep going. The big reason we own it, though, is that it sells at a huge discount to its private market value conservatively, $120 billion, or $135 a share.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing, Telecommunications Industry, Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

