<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> TREND SPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran, Elizabeth Macdonald, and Manjeet Kripalani <p> * Paying more for produce doesn't seem to bother consumers, as long as the veggies and fruit display that all-natural glow. Nearly one quarter of all shoppers buy organic products at least once a week, according to the Food Marketing Institute. With sales of organic goods up 23 percent since 1993, it's no surprise to see more farmers getting green. The Department of Agriculture says farms' applications for organic certification have surged this year.  <p> * "Made in America" fever returns. Starting this month, all new vehicles sold in the U.S. will display showroom stickers detailing their foreign and domestic parts content. Will folks actually consider Uncle Sam's feelings before buying? According to a survey by the Dohring Co., 68 percent of car buyers will scrutinize the domestic-content information, and 84 percent of that group will make it a major factor in their purchase decision.<p>  <p>* Meanwhile, car buyers are overlooking good mileage these days, notes the Williams Inference Service. Although gas prices are at their peak since the Gulf War, fuel economy ranked last in a list of 20 factors that affect automobile buying decisions.  <p> * A generation of couch potatoes? A recent study by American Sports Data reveals that frequent fitness participation among teens (between the ages 12 to 17) dropped 10.3 percent from 1987 to 1994. The 45-plus group, however, must be sweating to the oldies; their frequent-fitness activities soared 40.5 percent. But don't expect to hear "Tennis, anyone?" among any ages it's down 21.4 percent. Basketball, on the other hand, is up 22.3 percent.  <p> * Perhaps the tennis industry needs to get its mind in the gutter and take a tip from bowlers. To boost the flat bowling business, Brunswick Recreation Centers now sponsors "cosmic bowling" at19 of its alleys. Glow-in-the-dark pins and fog machines are offered to draw younger crowds.  <p> * The suits who oversee corporate investments, budgets, and forecasts are growing more pessimistic about the economy. According to the Institute of Management Accountants, for the first time in more than two years nearly half of corporate controllers and financial managers believe the economy is in a downturn.   <p> *  Look for better data from the Bureau of Economic Analysis. It spent the last three years overhauling its number-crunching methods so it can deliver a more accurate gross-domestic-product figure. One conclusion:  Last year, annual GDP growth was overstated by half a percentage point. The updated figure is 3.6 percent.  <p> * Crime may be on the decline, but nobody's taking any chances. Among the top growth business categories of 1994 were door- and gate-operating devices (up 32.4 percent) and auto alarms (up 28.4 percent), according to data compiled by American Business Information. Some, however, prefer the ninja approach to personal safety: Martial-arts instruction soared nearly 60 percent. "The trend in security is personal protection," says Albert Janjigian, president of security-consulting firm Stat Resources. "Eventually, we'll see handheld systems that would allow people to locate you anywhere if you pushed a panic button."  <p> * Move over, Robert James Waller. The American Association of Publishers reports that annual sales of Bibles and kids' paperbacks were up 13.2 percent and 39.2 percent, respectively, through June of this year well above adult hardcovers or paperbacks. The Student Bible, published by Zondervan, topped the Bible best-seller list for August.   <p> * Computer buffs can be obsessive about souping up their favorite toys; witness the rush to buy </wam-co NASD:MSFT>Microsoft</wam-co>'s Windows 95 operating system. Of course, new software often demands new hardware to make it work such as additional memory chips, otherwise known as RAM. The old version of Windows required only 4 megabytes of RAM, but Windows 95 demands at least 8. Since it runs better with more, look for devotees to snap up memory upgrades. Advice to nerds: It pays to plan ahead. According to Dataquest, memory prices have jumped 15 to 20 percent since January and aren't expected to drop anytime soon. <p>  <p>* Still paying student loans? According to a study by Louis Harris & Associates, 70 percent of Americans say their parents didn't put away money for their education. Today's parents, however, plan to support Junior's academic endeavors: 80 percent would give up their vacations and 79 percent would work overtime or take a second job to pay these expenses.   <p> * While bank fees keep rising up 22 percent since 1993 more consumers are giving credit unions a try. Membership in credit unions has grown 5.8 percent since 1993, to a total of 69.2 million members. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Technology Industry, Economic Trends, International Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

