	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Market Radar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> MARKET RADAR  <p> Most of the indicators this month are in a holding pattern, as investors  pause to consider whether there's enough energy left in this market for it to scale new peaks. Bellwether utility and brokerage stocks are leveling  off, the monetary environment offers no new fuel, and investment advisors are pulling back from their recent optimism. The Advance/Decline line shows continued momentum, but even that is flagging. In this atmosphere of indecisiveness,the yield ratio's flashing red "Overvalued!" sign stands out. Each indicator gets an arrow indicating its message for stocks this month.  <p> Advance/Decline Line The trend is still decidedly upward, but this indicator, which tracks the market as a whole, is climbing less steeply than  the Dow industrials and the S&P 500. When the broad market follows the indexes instead of leading them, it's a sign that the market is moving upward  more on momentum than on strength. The market and the Dow may be getting winded. <p> Composite Bellwether The scale of our chart masks some recent turbulence. Diverging from the climbing market, these bellwether utility and brokerage stocks have moved mostly sideways in the last month. Should this line start to turn downward, there would be cause for concern; if the line were to break below the plateau of early summer, it could mean trouble.  <p> Monetary EXPOSURE PROFILE This indicator remains firmly rooted in slightly negative territory, showing that this market isn't getting a boost from monetary policy. The sporadic brief dipsare not significant, largely due to banks' end-of-quarter funds-shuffling, and the Fed's most recent quarter-point rate cut didn't even register. The profile is consistent with an aging rally rather than a new upsurge.  <p> YIELD RATIO The S&P 500's yield hit an all-time low last month. It's climbed a smidgen since then while T-bill yields have stayed put, so this ratio looks a tad better. But that's little consolation. Historically, when T-bill  yields more than double the yield on stocks, the market is very overvalued. It would take more than another quarter-point rate cut by the Federal Reserve to turn this indicator around.  <p> ADVISORY SENTIMENT This month a few more investment advisors lost confidence in this market, a positive sign according to this contrarian indicator. But sentiment continues to flirt with the danger zone: This indicator doesn't need to climb too far to reach the 55 percent mark that, historically, has signaled that enough investment advisors have turned optimistic to indicate a market top.  <p> Consumer and Corporate Debt The 5.38 percent jump in private debt compared with the same time last year is the biggest growth in five years, but it's still no match for the double-digit levels reached in the mid-1980s and the late 1970s. Even though consumer credit demand has been picking up, corporations remain cautious about borrowing, keeping overall debt growth moderate. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economic Trends<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
