<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-In Search of Market Leaders</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>In Search of Market Leaders</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-In Search of Market Leaders</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> IN SEARCH OF MARKET LEADERS  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> If you've ever gone backpacking in the mountains with a group of friends, you know something about the way the stock market moves uphill. Early in the morning one hiker, warm with breakfast,perhaps, leads the climb. About mid-morning, he fades, and someone else moves to the front until lunch. Often, a third person takes the pace after the meal, and yet another comes forward toward the end of the day when everyone else has begun to flag. It's an unusual day when the same hiker leads the way from breakfast to dinner.  <p> The stock market climbs mountains in the same way. One sector assumes leadership, soars to remarkable heights and price-to-earnings multiples, suffers a correction, and watches another sector pass it by. In the language of Wall Street, this is sector rotation. Right now, it looks like technology, the sector that took this market to records on the Dow industrials, the Standard & Poor's500, and the Nasdaq Composite Index, is getting pretty tired. And looking around, it's hard to see another sector ready to lead. That should worry investors betting on a continuation of this market's remarkable climb.  <p> This stage of the five-year-long market rise began after the indexes bottomed in late 1994, following a Federal Reserve Board decision to hike interest rates. From its close at 3674 on November 23, 1994, the Dow climbed to a high of 4736 on July 17, 1995 a 29 percent increase before backing off recently. The comparable figures for the S&P 500 and the Nasdaq were 27 percent and 43 percent, respectively.  <p> Historically, leadership in a market like this begins with the financial stocks, passes to growth stocks, moves to cyclical industrial stocks as the market matures, and then finally blows off in a speculative flurry of initial public offerings and mergers. The 1995 market started out as you'd expect: Financials did well, and then technology, a classic growth sector, took over leadership. By the end of May, for example, the S&P Bank Composite index was up 25 percent from its November 1994 low. After starting out slowly, with just a slight rise in December1994 and January 1995, the S&P High Technology index picked up speed to rise 53 percent from its December 14 low through July12.  <p> But then the silicon hit the fan. The big stocks that were carrying the market, such as <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, are all now well off their July highs: Intel is down about 20 percent, Microsoft more than 12 percent. The big semiconductor and PC stocks "are dead for the next three months," says Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock Letter.  <p> Murphy paints a convincingly dire picture for the companies that depend on personal computers and the immediate roaring success of Windows 95. To make sure they wouldn't be caught short of such components as disk drives, microprocessors, and memory chips as the world rushed to adopt Microsoft's new operating system, companies throughout Silicon Valley built up inventories in the first half of this year. But "we've never really had a fast transition to any operating system," Murphy says. He expects the adoption of Windows 95 to be slower than expected, and if he's right, the likely result will be price cutting, slower sales of components, and big hits to profits as companies try to reduce inventories. "We could have a significant sell-off for the next three months," Murphy says.  <p> Then what stocks could lead the market higher? Many of the traditional candidates seem unlikely point men this time. Cyclicals such as automobiles? Auto sales in the U.S. fell sharply in June and July, and looked weak in early August, according to economist David Levy. Retail sales remain weak. The pickup in growth outside the U.S. helped big multinationals such as<a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Coca-Cola</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a> for a while, but the recent strength of the dollar has put adamper on these stocks.  <p> Three other sectors could come to the rescue. Financials, propelled by the wave of mergers sweeping through banking, could reassume the role they played in the early part of this market. The recently proposed union of <a name="NASD:CHFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12961"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chemical Bank</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a>, which would leapfrog the combined company over Citicorp as the biggest U.S. bank, is likely to set off a chain reaction.  <p> Although cyclicals such as auto stocks aren't good candidates for leadership, companies producing more basic raw materials may be. Prices for metals such as copper, nickel, and tin were all up by 4 percent to 12 percent in August, according to Goldman Sachs. Even the price of aluminum, perennially depressed, has stabilized. Investors have started to notice that at these prices,the metals companies can make money. Alcoa is up 59 percent fromits 52-week low; copper producer <a name="NYSE:PD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11176"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Phelps Dodge</b></a> is up 26 percent. <p> And lastly, don't count technology out. The sector is so big that even if PC makers and semiconductor companies tank, other companies can make up the difference. For example, while Intel and Microsoft were retreating from mid-July to the end of August, the Pacific Stock Exchange Index of 100 technology stocks actually climbed 3 percent. Electronics companies probably make up only 50 percent of all technology companies, Michael Murphy estimates, and PC companies make up only about half of that. Some of these companies will thrive whatever happens to Windows 95 and the PC market. For companies making computers that serve as distribution hubs in corporate networks and the related software makers it doesn't make much differerence what PC makers do, says Murphy. His list of such companies includes Sequent Computer Systems,<a name="NASD:ROSS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11793"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ross Systems</b></a>, <a name="NASD:SYBS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15350"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sybase</b></a>, Powersoft, <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>, <a name="NASD:COMS"></a><b>3Com</b>, <a name="NYSE:BAY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15419"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bay Networks</b></a>,and <a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle</b></a>.  <p> The next few months will be crucial for technology and the market. Watch to see if any sell-off in PC and semiconductor stocks starts to spread to other technology shares. Check the S&P financial index, and the Dow Jones aluminum and nonferrous metals indexes, to see if these sectors are taking the lead.  <p> And remember October 29 through November 1. Those are the dates of the American Electronics Association's big fall financial conference. Technology stocks almost always get a bounce from that conference as money managers and analysts start to focus on the good times ahead. If technology stocks don't move up in the wake of the conference, then investors will know the sector is in the throes of more than just a short-term sell-off.   <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Economic Trends, Stock Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

