<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Overview</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Overview</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Overview</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> OVERVIEW  <p> As the Federal Reserve Bank applauds itself for piloting the U.S. economy to a soft landing, politicians and central bankers in Europe, Japan, and Latin America are all too aware that their economies never really got airborne in the first place. Justa few weeks ago, for example, French finance minister Alain Madelin resigned after President Jacques Chirac made it clear he wouldn't slash government spending in the face of 11.5 percent unemployment. The markets reacted immediately by driving down the French franc and French bonds. The next few months will be crucial, not just for France, but for Japan, Germany, Mexico, Argentina and the United States. After all, if our trading partners falter, who will buy our exports?   <p>  <p>Focus On: Japan  <p> Back in the 1980s, pundits predicted that U.S. workers faced a future of flipping hamburgers as Japanese high-tech firms devoured Silicon Valley. Today, the future looks rather different. In yen terms, Japan's exports have been stuck at about the same level for 10 years, while Korea and China have gained market share in electronics. The unemployment rate, officially 3 percent, is closer to 10 percent under U.S. accounting standards, and bad loans at Japan's banks could reach $800 billion, about five times the cost of the U.S. savings & loan bailout. There is, too, a pervasive anxiety among the Japanese about what they call their "donut economy," which is being hollowed out as factory jobs migrate to lower-wage countries, such as China.  <p> Japanese investors are also beginning to leave home. Paradoxically, this may be one remedy for Japan's woes. The yen, which hit a high of 79.75 to the dollar in April, has now slipped to 96.50 as of August 28, which has helped push the Nikkei stock index up more than 22 percent since April (with foreigners doing most of the buying). Why? The overvalued yen has been ruinous to Japanese manufacturers, allowing <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>, for example, to price its Taurus far below <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a>'s Camry. But when investors expatriate yen, they push down the currency's value, making Japanese goods more competitive, Japanese firms more profitable, and Japanese equity markets more buoyant.   <p> In fact, the Ministry of Finance has been encouraging capital flight, lobbying insurance firms and other institutions to buy U.S. Treasury, German, Canadian, and Australian bonds. Imagine Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin strong-arming his old Wall Street colleagues into dumping U.S. securities. He'd be hanged for treason. Yet this trend could pick up dramatically this fall, as Japanese experience "sticker shock." Ma and Pa investors had been receiving 7 to 8 percent returns on five-year bank notes issued amid the bubble economy of 1990. But those notes are now starting to expire, and annual yields on new ones have fallen to around 1.5 percent. In response, for the first time, Japanese investors of modest means are looking to invest elsewhere than with their local banks unless they pay competitive rates. Japanese securities firms, meanwhile, have begun holding nationwide retail seminars on how to buy foreign bonds with higher yields.  <p>  <p>Continental Divide  <p> While Japan scrapes the bottom, Germany has stagnated. Here, too, exchange rates are playing a leading role, with the giant Daimler-Benz company announcing that it cannot earn profits with a superhigh deutsche mark. On August 24, the Bundesbank (Germany's central bank) cut interest rates to get the economy moving. Unfortunately for the bank, bond and equity traders throughout Europe assumed the cut would be the last for some time to come, and they began betting on when the Bundesbank would reverse course and tighten credit, which would force other European central banks to follow suit. So the mark stayed high and the economy continued to stall.  <p> Betting Below the Border  <p> By now it's a cliché to say that emerging markets "pose enormous risks." Still, it's true, especially when investors tie their fortunes to individual policymakers. Everyone knows, for example, that Mexican markets would collapse again if President Ernesto Zedillo tumbled from power. In Argentina, Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo almost singlehandedly defeated speculators during the Mexican crisis by his unwavering commitment to Argentina's "convertibility law," which pegs the Argentine peso at a 1:1 ratio to the U.S. dollar. Cavallo saved the Argentine markets, but he plunged the economy into a deep recession. Now the unions and old guard Peronists are after his scalp. If they get it, they'll plunder Argentina's Brady bonds and the Merval stock index as well.   <p> Good Investment News, Anyone?  <p> Is there any good news? Consider Canada and Colombia. After hemorrhaging red ink for years, Canada's provinces have finally begun tackling their budget deficits, which spells good news for Canadian bonds and the currency. The Quebec separatist movement, meanwhile, looks much weakened. Colombia presents a riskier case. President Ernesto Samper is fighting allegations of ties to drug cartels, and traders have hammered Colombian stocks and American depositary receipts in New York. The underlying economy is in pretty good shape, however, and Colombian equities could bounce back, with or without Samper. Just say "enormous risks" three times before laying your bets.    <p> Todd G. Buchholz is president of the G7 Group Inc., an international economic-consulting firm, and author of From Here to Economy:A Shortcut to Economic Literacy (Dutton, 1995).   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
