	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Build Fiscal Fitness w/Barbells</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Build Fiscal Fitness with Barbells</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Build Fiscal Fitness w/Barbells</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> BUILD FISCAL FITNESS WITH BARBELLS  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> When economic signals are as confusing as they have been of late, simply buy the most attractive bargains in the market. <p> That opportunistic advice is behind the "credit barbell strategy" that savvy fixed-income portfolio managers have begun to employ recently.   <p> The credit barbell is similar to a more familiar strategy, known as the "maturity barbell," used by many bond investors. A maturity barbell calls for investing in a mix of short- and long-term bonds when those issues, taking risk into account, offer moreattractive yields than intermediate issues. The result is a portfolio that looks like a barbell a big bulge on the extreme short-termend, a big bulge on the extreme long-term end, and almost nothing in between. By combining short and long maturities, the maturity barbell aims to create a portfolio with roughly the same riskas an intermediate bond but with a higher payout.  <p> A credit barbell involves a similar strategy, but instead of buying short and long maturities, an investor combines different credit risks. On the safe end, the investor building a credit barbell buys a portfolio of Treasury bonds; on the risky end, he buys junk bonds. The combination captures higher yields thaninvestment-grade corporate bonds the middle of the credit spectrum while taking the same or less risk. "We've been splitting our portfolio between Treasurys and high-yield bonds since May 1994," says Jerry Paul, manager of the <a name="FUND:FBDSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FBDSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Select Income Fund</b></a> (800-525-8085; no load; $1,000 minimum investment).   <p> Why is this strategy so attractive right now? Lately, corporations flush with profits haven't needed to issue bonds to raise money; the resulting scarcity of investment-grade issues has driven the prices        of existing bonds up and their yields down. For example, ten-year A-rated corporate bonds recently yielded only 67 basis points (100 basis points equal one percentage point) more than ten-year Treasurys. Meanwhile, high-yield corporate bonds rated B1 were recently paying around 9.6 percent a full 2.39 percentage points higher than A-rated corporates. "High yields are where the real bargains are," says Paul.  <p> Thomas Ole Dial, manager of the <a name="FUND:NNHBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NNHBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northstar Advantage High Total Return Fund</b></a> (800-595-7827; 4.75 percent load; $2,500 minimum), recommends a mix of 70 percent Treasurys and 30 percent B-rated bonds. One way to follow that advice is to divide your fixed-income money between a pair of funds such as <a name="FUND:VFITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VFITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard F/I Intermediate-Term U.S. Treasury</b></a> (800-662-7447; no load; $3,000 minimum) and <a name="FUND:FHYPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FHYPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco High-Yield</b></a> (800-525-8085; no load; $1,000 minimum).   <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

