<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Who Owns a Fund's Track Record</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Who Owns a Fund's Track Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Andrew Gluck<p>Does Lennon deserve more credit than McCartney? Woodward more than Bernstein? Could Regis make it without Kathie Lee?<p>Should investors buy shares in Carlene Ziegler's first solo fund because the funds she previously comanaged, SteinRoe Special Fund and Strong Common Stock Fund, are among the best performing mutual funds over the last nine years?<p>Ziegler and Richard Weiss, her mentor and longtime coportfolio manager, were a great team, first at the <a name="FUND:SRSPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SRSPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SteinRoe Special Fund</b></a> from 1986 to 1991, then at <a name="FUND:STCSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/STCSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Strong Common Stock Fund</b></a> from 1991 until October 1994. With just a touch more volatility than the market over those nine years, the team averaged a 19.2 percent annual return. No stock fund took less risk and performed better in that period. Late last year, Ziegler, 39 years old, split with Weiss to launch her own investment advisory firm, Artisan Partners of Milwaukee, and her own mutual fund, <a name="FUND:ARTSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ARTSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Artisan Small Cap Fund</b></a>.<p>Investors have poured $130 million into the fund since its March 28 start-up. Are those investors smartly grabbing a good thing before it's gone, or are they overly impressed by the small-cap fund's promise to close to new investors when it reaches just $300 million in assets? That depends on how much credit an investor gives Ziegler for her track record.<p>There's no doubt that Weiss trained Ziegler. In 1980 Ziegler, a French major fresh out of the University of Illinois, responded to a blind ad in the Chicago Tribune for a research analyst. She interviewed with Weiss, then a 29-year-old wunderkind at SteinRoe, who hired and trained her. Five years later, she was comanaging a fund with him. In 1991, Richard Strongwooed the pair to his fund family, where Ziegler worked until her resignation last October.<p>While her departure hasn't caused bad blood between them, both clearly want to claim the team's track record. <p>"Dick and I both had the same number of stocks we were responsible for," Ziegler says. Weiss, who continues to comanage Strong Common Stock Fund, disputes that. "I wouldn't say it was ever 50/50," he says, adding, "I was the senior member of the team." No-Load Fund Analyst, an investment newsletter in Orinda, California, has calculated that Ziegler was responsible for 15 to 25 percent of the stock picks at Strong, a figure Ziegler calls inaccurate.<p>But these attempts at bean counting are really beside the point. A team, built around Ziegler and Weiss but also including analysts, researchers, and traders, created the track record at SteinRoe and Strong. "Carlene can live up to the track record," says Weiss, "but she has another team, and I don't know that other team."<p>That point wasn't lost on Ziegler when she set up Artisan. She hired Millie Hurwitz, a fund portfolio manager at SteinRoe, as a stock analyst at Artisan. Hurwitz was a research assistant to Ziegler and Weiss at SteinRoe from 1986 to 1989.<p>The team's style, a mix of growth and value, could best be described as "growth at a price," similar to the discipline at Strong Common and SteinRoe Special. Ziegler forages for little-known growth companies--half the stocks owned by the fund are covered by fewer than five Wall Street analysts--temporarily buffeted by bad news.<p>To set target buy and sell prices, Ziegler calculates the private-market value of a company. "If you have a target for what you think the business is worth, you're much more likely to buy when the stock is cheap and sell when it's expensive," she says.<p>No one can be certain Ziegler will match her track record with Weiss, but 14 weeks after starting up, Artisan Small Cap was up nearly 20 percent. <p>"Carlene learned the process we use," says Weiss, "and it's proved effective over many years and market cycles. If she sticks to that process, I have no doubt she'll do fine."<p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:SRSPX">SteinRoe Special Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:STCSX">Strong Common Stock Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:ARTSX">Artisan Small Cap Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
