<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-What They're Buying Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Seven acclaimed mutual fund managers have agreed to tell Worth readers each month about their current favorite domestic stocks. The price listed is the maximum at which the manager considers it attractive. It should be assumed that in each case the manager has bought the stock for his fund, perhaps at a lower price than the one mentioned here. The manager may also have sold the stock after July 24, the publishing deadline for this issue. Taken as a whole, the approaches of these seven managers illustrate a broad range of successful investment styles. The picks on this page are intended to serve as long-term recommendations; the managers describe the specific time horizons of their selections below.<p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
James P. Craig
<a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NYSE:CCK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10419"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Crown Cork and Seal</b></a>Nyse: CCK
$55 <p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
When it comes to enhancing shareholder value, this packaging-industry giant specializing in beverage cans is one of the best-run companies I've come across. Right now there's a pending merger with CarnaudMetalbox, a French company that specializes in plastic bottles; this would add $5 billion in sales and hundreds of millions in cost savings. Packaging is a low-margin business, so when you change the margins slightly, there's huge earnings potential. The stock rose $5 when the company announced the merger. If it happens, this thing could go to $80 or $90 over the next one and a half to two years; if not, the downside is limited.<p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
Shelby M.C. Davis
<a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New York Venture Fund</b></a>
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NYSE:SAI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10238"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SunAmerica</b></a>
Nyse: SAI
$54<p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
SunAmerica is led by Eli Broad, one of the first people to spot the demographic shift driving the savings and investment boom. With more Americans buying packaged financial products, the company should earn $4.40 a share this fiscal year (ending in September) and 15 percent more next year. The stock had a nice run last spring but is still attractive. SunAmerica has a multifaceted distribution network for its fixed- and variable-annuity products. Broad is a proven winner; he's also an acquirer with excess cash on the balance sheet, so if we get into a tough market, he could be looking to buy.<p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
Daniel B. Leonard
<a name="FUND:FSFSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSFSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology</b></a> Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NYSE:HRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10689"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>H&R Block</b></a>NYSE: HRB
$50<p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
H&R Block is a diversified service company. It owns CompuServe, the largest service network out there. People think of Block as an income-tax preparer or maybe as a financial-services franchise, but it's really a technology stock. CompuServe now makes more profit than the tax unit does; with earnings and revenues both growing at 35 percent annually, it now accounts for 43 percent of the company's revenues. CompuServe is also the only online company to own its own network; when the market recognizes this, the stock could go to $60 a share.<p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
William J. Nasgovitz
Hugh F. Denison
<a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value Fund</b></a>
Buys stocks of domestic small-cap companies believed to be undervalued.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NYSE:JA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15828"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>John Alden Financial </b></a>
Nyse: JA
$18 <p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
John Alden sells health insurance to companies with fewer than 100 employees. The stock hit a high of $40 a share in 1994 but is now trading at $17. It plummeted because the company reported poor first-quarter earnings, 40 cents a share versus 78 cents one year earlier. This was due to higher claims. The second quarter should also be poor, 45 cents versus 94 cents last year. However, I'm buying the stock on the bad news because it's trading at book value and has earning power of $3 a share or more. The stock should double in two years. <p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
Eric E. Ryback
<a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a> 
Seeks current income first, capital appreciation second.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NASD:URIX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17101"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Uranium Resources </b></a>
Nasdaq: URIX
$7 <p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
This is the lowest-cost uranium producer in North America. It drills a lot of holes in the ground in Texas and New Mexico, then injects water to dissolve the uranium; when the solution is pumped out, the water evaporates, leaving only the uranium. The stock fell to $4 earlier this year when its former chairman filed for bankruptcy. The company received a new cash infusion and has resumed drilling. Demand, which already exceeds supply, is rising. Barring a major drop in oil prices, the stock will certainly go above $20 and probably as high as $30. <p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
Ralph Wanger
Chuck McQuaid
<a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund </b></a>
Holds stocks of small-cap companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NASD:LICIA"></a><b>Lilly Industries Class A</b>
Nasdaq: LICIA
$15 <p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
Lilly Industries, a manufacturer of industrial coatings and chemicals, is gaining market share and making smart acquisitions. It has strong cash flow, a 25 percent return on equity last year, and long-term earnings growth of 15 percent. Raw-materials costs have recently stabilized and lower interest rates should help demand. At 13 times this year's earnings, the stock is cheap--down from a 1994 high of $18. Second-quarter earnings were flat and I don't know when they'll improve, but when they do, the stock should jump; meanwhile, the company is buying its own shares.<p>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FUND MANAGER/NAME/DESCRIPTION:
Donald A. Yacktman
<a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund </b></a>
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.<p>PICK AND TARGET PRICE:
<a name="NYSE:VCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12305"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Valassis Communications</b></a>
Nyse: VCI
$18 <p>THE MANAGER EXPLAINS HIS CHOICE:
Valassis, which prints the coupon inserts in Sunday papers, has an extremely profitable and secure duopoly with a subsidiary of Newscorp. The industry pricing environment, which was hurt when a third company unsuccessfully tried to enter the market a few years ago, is starting to come back. Profit margins are being pinched by the rising cost of paper, but the coupon-insert-business continues to grow. The company also is expanding overseas and diversifying into related fields. With more rational pricing, earnings could be at $1.50 to $2 a share by 1996. I can see the stock reaching the mid-30s.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

