	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Trendspotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>TRENDSPOTTER<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>* Spectators at the summer 1996 Olympic games will carry the latest in currency: smart cards. They look like credit cards, but they're, well, a lot smarter. A microchip embedded in the card allows it to store electronic cash in amounts from $10 up. About a million smart cards will be sold to Atlanta's visitors and residents; the cards will be accepted at fast-food restaurants and grocery stores and by vending machines and pay phones. No personal data will be stored on the cards circulating in this pilot program, but plastic packed with data, such as medical and insurance information, will debut in 1997. <p>* Let us not give thanks: The Kiplinger Washington Letter reports that religious contributions are flat, even though the pews are packed. Episcopalians give the most: $640 per member per year. After that are Assemblies of God, $625; Presbyterians, $610; Baptists, $545; Mormons, $525; Jews, $510; Lutherans, $410; Methodists, $380; and Catholics, $160.<p>* Back in 1970, thieves stole cars to joyride. Today, ripping off autos makes for a lucrative career. According to the National Insurance Crime Bureau, the number of vehicles stolen in the past 25 years has jumped 67 percent while the recovery rate has dropped 26 percent.<p>* Citizens utilities boards--not-for-profit watchdog agencies that fight rate increases proposed by gas, electric, and telephone companies--are getting louder. New York City's CUB attracted 20,000 members last year alone. This surge of consumer advocacy, coupled with the transition to a competitive market, could signal trouble for the utilities sector. "There's a lot of general pressure for the utilities to reduce prices," says Sandford Cohen, utilities analyst at Merrill Lynch. "We believe this group will underperform the market on a regular basis."<p>* Another reason to grouse on the job: A recent study reveals that merit-based salary increases are at a six-year low, with 1995 raises for top and middle management averaging 3.6 percent. Five years ago, top corporate brass pocketed a 5.4 percent raise, and middle managers received a 5.2 percent increase. <p>* A new study finds that 39 percent of Americans put off routine medical care when they're low on cash, with women (46 percent) more likely to do so than men (31 percent). Postponing routine care, of course, can lead to less routine, more expensive care. The study was sponsored by MasterCard, which recommends--yes--that we charge our checkups.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
