<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Great Expectations</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Great Expectations</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Great Expectations</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>GREAT EXPECTATIONS
The biggest danger to the stock market may not be a recession or interest rate hikes, but excessive investor expectations.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Listen and you can hear the stock market changing gears. It's not a pretty sound. The market always insists on accelerating, moving faster and faster until, with a grinding of gears, it abruptly downshifts. No wonder the passengers get whiplash.<p>Everyone knows--well, to be precise, most Wall Street economists agree--that the economy has slowed from the blistering pace that scared the Federal Reserve into raising interest rates seven times between February 1994 and February 1995. Real growth in gross domestic product in the second quarter of 1995 was about 1 percent, for example, Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities, estimated in late July.<p>Logic suggests, therefore, that corporate earnings growth should slow in turn, a supposition that appears to be confirmed by some early numbers. After a 37 percent increase in earnings in 1994, for example, first-quarter earnings for the Standard & Poor's 500 stocks grew 25 percent in the first quarter of 1995, according to Zacks Investment Research. For the second quarter, Zacks projects S&P 500earnings to grow at around 18 to 19 percent.<p>With decelerating economic and earnings growth clearly in evidence, Wall Street has had plenty of time to reduce expectations and earnings projections, and the market could conceivably make its own smooth transition to slower growth.
But that's not the way this market operates. The investment world is so dominated by momentum investors right now that trends are almost guaranteed to go to excess--before making a violent correction. Take the case of  <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>--a technology stock that went from highflyer to road kill in the space of a week.<p>On Tuesday, July 18, after the market closed, the company reported quarterly earnings of 99 cents a share. Revenue had climbed 41 percent and earnings 36 percent. The next day, the stock dropped $8, and it fell another $2.31 by week's end.<p>Why the crash? After all, earnings weren't dramatically off the $1.03 consensus estimate of analysts ($1.10 per share at the upper end). But these official calculations bore little relation to the stratospheric expectations of the momentum crowd. In the days before Intel's earnings announcement, the electronic world was abuzz with excitement. On July 14, at 9:30 p.m., one investor on <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> first guessed that earnings had to come in at $1.10--then, a few lines later in his message, raised that to $1.11. The next morning, another invest-or on the same service started by suggesting $1.25 a share would be a reasonable quarterly figure and wound up predicting $1.32. To this investor, Intel missed projections by a mile, almost 25 percent, not just a few cents. These individual investors weren't alone, obviously. Intel's volume spiked sharply upward on the day of its $8 decline. The big boys sold, too.<p>The disturbing irony to this story is that the biggest danger to the stock market currentlymay not be a recession or inter-est rate hikes, but excessive investor expectations. Certainly the market has little to fear from the economy right now. Earlier signs of a classic "inventory" recession--in which slowing consumer demand causes a buildup in inventories, which eventually leads to a cut in manufacturing activity--have disappeared. Sectors showing faster growth in inventories than in sales on a year-to-year basis have seen sales pick up in recent months, says Nikko's Brusca. For example, retailers--who saw inventories grow at 9.4 percent and sales grow just 6.3 percent year to year--showed sales growing faster than inventories in May.<p>Inflation, too, seems subdued. Capacity utilization, which measures how much of existing manufacturing capacity is in use, hit 85.5 percent in December 1994 but was down to 83.5 percent in June 1995. That's not high enough to lead to serious production bottlenecks, especially because consumer demand isn't likely to heat up fast. Consumers are carrying high debt loads and low savings rates, Brusca notes, which should limit increases in spending to approximately the slow growth rate of consumer incomes.<p>Under these conditions, inflation is likely to creep upward at 3.3 to 3.5 percent this year, and Brusca projects the 30-year Treasury bond will fluctuate between 6.6 and 6.9 percent.<p>How dull: Decent but not great growth; growing but not rapidly accelerating profits; small interest rate fluctations but no multiple rate cuts.<p>Will investors successfully adjust, scaling back expectations to fit this market? There is reason for pessimism. Some of the recent frenzy over technology stocks, for example, occurred because money managers and individual investors, having missed the first-quarter rally, threw their money at the latest winners, whatever the share price, in an effort to catch up.<p>That practice can quickly reach a point of diminishing returns. If some of these highflyers disappoint, investors could start putting their cash on an ever smaller number of stocks. With more money chasing them, those stocks could get bid up to levels that can't be sustained.<p>The hallmarks of this situation aren't impossible to spot. Watch the various indicators of market breadth--the number of rising stocks versus the number falling. In healthy rallies, the market will move up on the back of a large number of stocks. If on the other hand, the overall market gains but on fewer and fewer stocks, that's a danger sign. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:INTC">Intel Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:AMER">America Online</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
