<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-What Numbers Mean When a Fund Evolves</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-What Numbers Mean When a Fund Evolves</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Is there any such thing as a free lunch? In the financial world the answer is occasionally yes. Sometimes an investor can combine better-than-average returns with lower-than-average risk by exploiting an underresearched part of the market. Almost always, however, the advantage is fleeting__other investors, attracted by success, flood in, or the investor gets too big for his niches.<p>Amazingly, the <a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a> has been able to enjoy such a free lunch for more than 15 years. But investors considering the fund as a high-return, low-risk haven in today's volatile market should know that some things about the fund have changed in recent years.<p>The Lindner Dividend Fund has returned 11.92 percent annually over the last ten years__just a tad below the average equity fund. But the fund earned that return with far less risk. Lindner Dividend's standard deviation (a measure of how much any year's return deviates from the average) for the period was just 6.53__making the fund less than half as volatile as the average. Think about the fund in these terms: Lindner Dividend Fund was about as risky as the average bond fund for these years and returned about three percentage points more a year.<p>"I work in my own little world here," says manager Eric Ryback, 43, of the relatively underresearched markets in convertible bonds, convertible preferred stocks, preferred stocks, and junk bonds in which he invests. The junk bonds of troubled apparel maker Hartmarx are a typical Ryback pick. Hartmarx nearly went bankrupt in the early 1990s, but Ryback liked the company's balance sheet. He bought the bonds at a deep discount to yield 11.6 percent and plans to hold them to maturity, thus locking in oversize yields without taking long-term interest rate risk.<p>Lindner Dividend had a tough year in 1994, when it fell 3.31 percent as interest rates rose. But that kind of short-term glitch isn't what worries some analysts.<p>"This fund is different than it was five years ago, or even three years ago," says Erik Witkowski, an analyst at North- field Information Services, a Boston-based investment consultant. After years of zigging when the major indexes zagged, Lindner Dividend's correlation to the Standard & Poor's 500 and Lehman Brothers Aggregate Bond Index has been higher in the last three years. Witkowski frets that if the fund's character has changed so much, its performance will, too.<p>"All funds are different than they were three or four years ago, particularly if they were successful," Ryback says. "But we haven't put on different clothes." Ryback took over the fund in 1983, shortly after he joined the fund company run by legendary investor Kurt Lindner. Assets have soared from $235 million at the end of 1991 to $1.76 billion through March 31, 1995. Still, the fund's 10.84 percent return for the last three years only slightly trails the fund's ten-year record, and the risk is down for the period.<p>As the fund has grown in size, Ryback has broadened the fund's investment universe. In June 1993 the fund's shareholders voted to let Ryback put up to 25 of the fund's assets in private placements, which trade in exactly the kind of inefficient market Ryback likes. On the other hand, these issues could be hard to sell in a sharp market correction.<p>But the biggest change at the fund has nothing to do with the contents of the fund's portfolio. In February 1993, an ailing Kurt Lindner sold his fund company__then consisting of just two funds__to Ryback, who has since opened four new funds. Ryback manages or co-manages all four new funds
.
"We're stretched thin," Ryback says. "I've basically had to play catch-up over the last two years." He has added four researchers and intends to hire two new portfolio managers. All these changes add up to risk of a kind that doesn't show up in past performance. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


