<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-One Down, One to Go</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>One Down, One to Go</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-One Down, One to Go</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> ONE DOWN, ONE TO GO  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> Can we tell you that the market will dive 200 points on Tuesday, or that the Dow Jones Industrial Average will climb straight to 5000 without a hitch? Nope. Over the short haul, the stockmarket is essentially random. No one can predict what will happen tomorrow. But we do believe in the power of fundamentals over the long term. And right now we know that the bond market rally that began at the end of 1994 and accelerated this year has knocked one major support out from under the stock market. That leaves only the hope of growing corporate earnings to sustain stocks at current levels, cold comfort to those who understand the relationship between earnings and stock prices.  <p> Let's start with why a bond rally, at this moment, is bad news for stocks. "The key idea is decoupling," says Bluford Putnam, chief strategist at Bankers Trust Global Investment Management. The bond market rallies that is, the price of bonds goes up and the yield on bonds goes down, when investors believe that interest rates are headed down and inflation isn't a danger. That's exactly what happened beginning last November. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond was 8.11 percent on November 22, declined to 7.71 by January 31, hit 7.40 on March 20, and finally tumbled to 6.9 percent.  <p> Now, often such a rally drives the stock market up too. When that happens, analysts say the markets are coupled. As bonds pay less interest, stocks look more attractive, assuming that earnings aren't falling. If the economy is slowing just enough to keep inflation fears at bay, but not enough to hurt corporate earnings, rising bond prices are good for stocks.  <p> At some point, however, falling interest rates start to signal bad news for the economy and thus for stocks. If rates go too low, that means the bond market expects growth to slow so much that earnings will fall.  <p> The bond market may have reached that point in late May. "We've completely milked the low interest rates and slow-growth story," says Putnam. "The market has completely discounted a safe landing by the economy."  <p> To Putnam, the economy must walk a very fine line to sustain the current combination of stock and bond prices: Inflation has to stay at 3 percent or less, and the economy must grow at a rate between 1.5 and 2 percent. "I don't think we can walk that line," he says, noting the rate of inflation at the consumer level hit 3.1 percent in April, up from 2.9 percent in March and 2.4 percent a year ago.  <p> Putnam sees two possible scenarios. In the first, which he believes has a two-thirds chance of coming to pass, the economy grows faster than expected. If this happens (if the economy grows at, say, 2.5 percent and inflation rises to just 4 percent), Putnam believes the interest rate on the 30-year bond will rise to 7.5 percent and hurt both markets.  <p> Alternatively, the economy could grow more slowly than the market expects, slipping into recession. "I don't think it would be a severe one, but it would take profit growth into negative territory," Putnam says.  <p> It's the little things that worry Putnam. If growth is 2.5 per-cent instead of 2 percent, if in-flation rises to 4 percent instead of 3, if the economy grows less than 1.5 percent, then the stock market suffers. "Risks have gotten to a really high level, and you should be cautious even if you're bullish," he says.  <p> The Wall Street optimists, meanwhile, have turned increasingly to earnings to justify their views. Standard & Poor's is projecting earnings growth for the companies in the S & P 500 of about 21 percent this year, on top of the 37 percent increase in 1994. Despite the market's rally, the price-to-earnings ratio on the S & P is 17.2, down from 20.8 in May 1994. Conventional wisdom says that the market's average price-to-earnings ratio lies between 13 and 18. And another rule of thumb says that a stock is fairly priced at a price-to-earnings ratio equal to its growth rate. Those two formulas suggest that the market, while no bargain, isn't in dangerous territory either.  <p> But this analysis misunderstands the relation between earnings and stock prices. "What is it that moves stock prices?" asks James Stack of InvesTech Research. It is not earnings, he says, but expectations, and everyone still expects strong growth, which is reflected in today's stock prices.  <p> Stack finds little consolation in today's price-to-earnings ratio or next year's projections. "The problem with earnings is they have a poor correlation with stock prices," he says." At 17, the S & P price-to-earnings ratio is down to the level where the 1973­1974 bear market started. In 1991, when this current market blasted off, the p/e ratio on the S&P was near the highest level in history at 26."  <p> Imagining the entire market as one giant stock helps illustrate the difficulties in using a specific ratio to forecast futureprices. A cyclical stock <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, for example, shows its highest p/e ratio when its earnings are lowest, when it's struggling to sell cars. When the company's factories are running full tilt, the p/e ratio plummets. At which point would an investor rather buy? When the ratio is high (before the company recovers and before its price moves up) or after?  <p> Or think about a technology growth stock. An investor who buys <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>when earnings are growing 45 percent a year and its p/e ratio is 37 expects future earnings to grow at that same rate. A dip in earnings to, say, 20 percent would send the stock plunging. You might still want to buy Microsoft, but at a lower price.  <p> This market is coming off what looks like a peak in earnings growth. Profit margins aren't going up in the next year in all likelihood, companies will see their margins fall. Most investors wouldn't jump to buy a stock with those prospects. Why should the entire market be any different?    <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Bond Investing, Economy<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:GM">General Motors Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:MSFT">Microsoft Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
