	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Industry Sectors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Industry Sectors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Industry Sectors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> INDUSTRY SECTORS  <p> By Manjeet Kripalani  <p> Investors, expecting flat or declining interest rates this summer, bid up the share prices of home builders and savings and loans. Pulte Corp. was one of the only two home builders to report increased orders for the first quarter of the year, up 4 percent from last year. Among S & Ls, the primary home lenders, Golden West Financial was a strong performer.  <p> Metals and gold-mining stocks, traditional hedges against inflation, lost luster. The slowdown in auto sales hit the steel industry, and demand for basic metals like copper and aluminum is expected to drop. J. Clarence Morrison, senior metals analyst at Prudential Securities, forecasts a copper surplus of 175,000 tons by 1997. The recently higher dollar hurt gold, and Morrison does not recommend buying gold or copper stocks.  <p> Recent tensions in the Middle East boosted the energy sector. The U.S. trade embargo against Iran helped oil prices rebound from last year.  <p> Health care services continue to do poorly. U.S. Healthcare's announcement of possible price cuts has created fears of an HMO price war and consequent lower growth rates. However, Kenneth Abramowitz, health care analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein, advises investors to stick with stocks like U.S. Healthcare, saying,"Earnings will eventually fall in line with revenues."  <p> Slow growth also dogged the cyclical transportation sector, especially Pittston Services (air freight). But hang tight, says Sam Stovall, editor of Standard & Poor's Industry Outlook: "After an economic slowdown, transportation issues are among the first to recover."  <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
