<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Values the Bond Rally Left</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Good Values the Bond Rally Left Behind</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Values the Bond Rally Left</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> GOOD VALUES THE BOND RALLY LEFT BEHIND  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> On January 24, 1995, the 30-year Treasury bond yielded 7.93 percent. During the next few months, as interest rates fell, the price of the 30-year bond soared. By May 18, the yield on the 30-year bond was down to just 6.9 percent, and the price of a bond purchased in late January had climbed by 15 percent. <p> Those kinds of returns have brought money flooding back into long-term bonds and bond funds. But investors putting money into this part of the bond market now are running to catch a train that left the station months ago. It's unlikely that rates are headed down much further this year, and investors who buy long-term bonds could be setting themselves up for big losses without achance of earning big profits. "Investors aren't getting paid for the added risk at the long end," says Joseph Zarr, managerof <a name="FUND:FLXBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FLXBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Flex-Funds Global Income Fund</b></a>. "Long-term Treasury bond yields could go back from 6.9 percent to 7.5 percent or 8 percent."If that happened, prices could decline10 percent or more.  <p> Rather than chase the last rally, investors looking for income and maybe a little capital gain, should look at bonds that missed the surge.  <p> Intermediate bonds. In late May, seven-year Treasurys yielded 6.5 percent. That's 94 percent of the yield on much riskier 30-year issues. "With intermediates, you can protect yourself without giving up much income," says Walter Frank, chief investment officer for IBC Donoghue's Moneyletter.  <p> Municipal bonds. Munis have lagged the bond market in part because investors expect Congress to slash taxes on investment income, making munis' tax-exempt status less valuable. Yields on tax-exempts recently amounted to around 88 percent of those on Treasurys, up from 81 percent in February.  <p> Mortgage-backed securities. During 1993 and 1994, 7.2 million homeowners refinanced $741 billion in mortgages. That sliced returns for mortgage-backed securities, such as Ginnie Maes, which are in effect bundles of mortgages. Whenever a homeowner prepays a mortgage, there's less in interest income to pass along to the holders of the securities. Concern about additional refinancings has caused these issues to lag this year; as a result, 30-year Ginnie Maes yield 7.56 percent. But these fears are overblown, argues Garitt Kono, manager of the <a name="FUND:DREVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DREVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dreyfus GNMA Fund</b></a>. Even if rates fall further, far fewer homeowners are still looking to refinance.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Banking Industry, Bond Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:FLXBX">Flex-Funds Global Income Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:DREVX">Dreyfus GNMA Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
		<a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  
		<a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  
