	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> GLOBAL MARKETS  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> The U.S. economy has, for the moment, its soft landing. Inflation and growth rates are moderate, perhaps sustainably so. If the Federal Reserve is indeed finished raising interest rates, as Chairman Alan Greenspan hinted last spring, equity markets everywhere are likely to be buoyed by the news. "There was a big sigh of relief heard around the world," says Todd Buchholz, president of the G7 Group, an Alexandria, Virginia, economics consulting group.   <p> Global markets should do well at least through the summer, depending on the U.S. economy. "There are two very distinct schools of thought," says John Trott, the chief international investment officer at Bessemer Trust in London. "Some think we've seen the last rise in interest rates and that everything looks pretty good. Others see the soft landing as an extended pause in U.S.growth and believe that in the third and fourth quarter, interest rates will go back up." A lot will depend on U.S. consumer spending; if it heats up, so will the economy and interest rates.   <p> Clark Winter, president of Global Asset Management, says U.S. politics, not economics, may have the greatest effect on world stock markets. "The rest of the world is paying close attention to what's going on in Washington, D.C., and state capitals such as Albany," he says. Winter says the U.S., by reducing deficits and state spending, could raise confidence in its economy and perhaps inaugurate a global post­cold war reformation of government spending.  <p> HIGHLIGHTS  <p> FRANCE  With Jacques Chirac and the conservatives in power, the time may be ripe to shrink the central government and privatize state-held industry. "The tension is high in the Chirac camp," says Buchholz. "He's conservative, so he should believe in deficit reduction, but he's also a populist, which puts him against unemployment, now at an unacceptable 12 percent. If you're on the side of deficit cutting, financial markets love you. But if you believe in reducing unemployment, that usually means government spending and investors will turn on France."  <p> BRAZIL  Emerging from the "tequila hangover" that struck emerging markets after the Mexican peso devaluation last December, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso is beginning to push some economic reforms through Congress. Says Joseph DeSantis, head of international equities for Chase Asset Management, "The agenda is far from complete, but investors saw enough of a shift in momentum that money started to flow in."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Internatonal Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
