				<font size=5><b>The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> THE BIG PICTURE  <p> "I have heard some intelligent and seasoned stock professionals explain why we really might be entering a new era. U.S. manufacturers are in the best position since WWII; a new wave of politicians will create a fiscally responsible government; the savings of baby boomers are about to expand; advances in technology, science,and communications are more significant than the industrial revolution,etc. Well, it may be intellectually stimulating to speculate on Œnew eras,' but it's a lousy way to invest. In financial history, there have been new eras, but I don't recall any that lasted very long."  <p>  Steve Leuthold, chairman of the Leuthold Group,  <p>an investment-research firm in Minneapolis, discussing optimismin the equity markets.
  <p> <p>

