	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Trendspotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> TRENDSPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran and Ellen Simon  <p> *This might not be the time to play gentleman rancher. Stock cows that went for $1,200 a year ago are worth just $850 now. Range and slaughter cattle are cheaper, too. Greg Sanders, a reporter for a USDA market newsletter, dates the problem to 1986, when farmers sold off huge numbers of cows. The ranges have gotten more crowded every year since, and supply is now growing faster than demand. The winners in this are consumers, who should see "better, more exciting specials or features," says C.J. Valenziano of the Chicago-based Beef Industry Council. "This is one of those big, ugly, cyclical things."  <p> *Safe surfing is the latest buzz on the Net. To protect confidential data, including credit card numbers, companies are learning to firewall and encrypt. Firewalling involves the creation of an impenetrable wall around parcels of top-secret info. Encrypting means translating messages into indecipherable codes that are, of course, decrypted at the other end. The leaders in security software are still small and privately held, but you might want to remember these names: RSA Data Security, <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a>, and Trusted Information Systems.  <p> *How are regulated industries such as cable, telecommunications, and gas and electric utilities planning for the prospect of deregulation and increased competition? First, by playing musical chairs, rushing into industries they know nothing about, and second, by slashing staff, the management panacea of our time. John Siegman, director of utilities and communications at Equifax National Decision Systems, a San Diego marketing company, points to cable operators' eagerness to muscle into telecommunications "despite the fact that cable's customer satisfaction is the lowest inregulated industry."  <p> *Last year, <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> needed the force of the U.S. government to muscle into the Japanese cellular-phone market: Until U.S.trade rep Mickey Kantor got involved, Motorola's Japanese distributor, IDO, refused to increase its purchases of Motorola phones. Well, here's the epilogue: Since the battle, IDO's subscribers have nearly doubled.   <p> *Maybe someday we'll think as much as we drink. But we aren't there yet. While spending on education and research recently surpassed the amount spent on off-premises alcohol, spending on books still looks like a pittance compared with beer: $72.9 billion versus $17.5 billion in 1990.  <p> *Does the workplace bite? Not according to Gen X-ers. A recently released study by the Wyatt Co., a retirement-consulting firm, reveals that it's the over-30 baby boomers who are dissatisfied with their jobs. Of the 4,300 employees surveyed, workers under 30 were more positive about their jobs than any other age group. Paul Sanchez, coauthor of the study, believes the cynical younger set simply has lower standards: "They don't have romantic expectations about their work."          <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Telecommunications Industry, Employment<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
