<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-The View From 400</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The View From 400</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-The View From 400</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> THE VIEW FROM 400  <p> By David S. Liebowitz  <p> Judging from the jubilation at the stock exchanges on February 23, one might have thought the traders had erased the deficit and spotted Elvis on the same day. In fact, that was the day the Dow Jones Industrial Average broke 4000. And when, 60 days later, the Dow muscled past 4300, many of my colleagues on the Street thought they'd died and gone to heaven. Alas, wherever their minds are, they and their investments are still here. <p> It's my opinion that, from any real-world perspective, this market is overvalued. This is not to say it won't go still higher, but that just means it will have farther to fall.   <p> Bear in mind that 4000 represented a psychological barrier, not a measure of the Dow's intrinsic value. And the assault on the last "major resistance level," to use technical language, suggests it may be some time before the 4000 barrier can be decisively overcome. In 1964 the first attempt on 1000 was mounted, only to be aborted in the spring of 1965, when then-chairman of the Federal Reserve Board William McChesney Martin publicly commented on the similarities between the market of the day and that of1929, the beginning of the Great Depression.  <p> The 1000 barrier was actually scaled in 1966 on an intraday basis, but again the market backed off. Indeed, the Dow eventually fell as low as 607 in September 1974. It wasn't until the beginning of the bull market, coming off the August 1982 year low of 784, that 1000 was finally relegated to history's dust bin.  <p> Is this meant to imply that it will take 16 years before we bid a permanent adieu to 4000? Certainly not. Both the market and the U.S. economy have grown far larger and more resilient since then. But the signs augur an imminent correction.  <p> In the first quarter the Dow rose an impressive 324 points, but a number of key indicators are signaling caution. Consider, for example, the advance/decline ratio, the number of stocks trading higher on the day versus the number trading lower. It measures the so-called breadth of the market, or how many issues actually participated in a day's overall rise or fall. At the beginning or in the middle of a bull market, as investor confidence grows, so does the percentage of rising stocks. Over time, this daily pattern can be plotted as a rising advance/decline line, showing more and more of the market climbing. This was the case from January of 1991, when the last bull market kicked off, until the middle of 1993. During this period, advances sometimes outnumbered declines even on days when the Dow fell.  <p> In the present market, according to data compiled by James Stack, editor of the InvesTech Market Analyst newsletter, just the opposite has occurred. Though the advance/decline line has risen somewhat this year, it is down considerably over the last 14 months though the Dow has risen through this period. On two of the last ten new closing highs, decliners actually outnumbered gainers. This suggests investors are losing confidence and are growing more selective in their choice of stocks, a view supported by the fact that the push past 4000, which began in November, was propelled by a rise in 27 of the 30 blue chips making up the Dow.   <p> Never before in the 68 years for which the data is available has the advance/decline line shown a cumulative decline over such a long period at the same time the Dow was setting record highs. Ominously, the only comparable period occurred between1971 and 1973 and ended with the most miserable market in half a century.   <p> Several other fundamental stock market gauges are also sounding the alarm. One that has been doing so for a long time is the market's dividend yield, which measures the average current yield of all the stocks on one of the broad-based market indices. In the past, when that figure fell below 3 percent, it has signaled an overpriced market. Today that figure stands at 2.6 percent, and it has been below 3 percent since November 1992.  <p> Another valuable yard stick is the differential between the market yield and long-term bond rates, which indicates the relative attractiveness of stocks and bonds. The equilibrium point in the spread is approximately 3 percent. A lower rate differential favors stocks, while a higher one favors bonds. At present, the spread is pushing 5 percent.  <p> We also may be within one Fed interest rate increase of an inversion in the Treasury yield curve. During this rare phenomenon, the curve first flattens, narrowing the spread between short-term rates (Treasury bills) and customarily higher long-term rates (usually the bench mark 30-year bond). This is followed by the inversion, during which short-term rates exceed long-term ones. Over the past 50 years there have been fewer than a half dozen inversions; each heralded a market decline and a weakening economy. <p> What will trigger the decline? The continued weakening of the dollar, another rise in interest rates, more potentially inflationary price increases in raw materials such as copper, aluminum, paper, or platinum any, all, or none of these could start the market rolling downhill. So could a crisis in Mexico, China or the Middle East. Don't expect a crash, though. The end of a strong market usually starts with a slow erosion of share prices, before increasing trading causes the momentum to accelerate.   <p> There's a phrase you hear a lot on Wall Street: "This time will be different." Professionals say it as a joke, but it also shows up in articles and analyst reports on cyclical stocks and industry groups, generally as a reason for investors to buy shares that would otherwise seem to have peaked. Problem is: The phrase rarely holds true.   <p> David S. Leibowitz is a managing director at Burnham Securitiesin New York City. <p><p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Stock Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
