<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Overview</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Overview</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Overview</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> OVERVIEW  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> Currency tensions have been the big story lately, but they don't seem to have hurt the international equities markets much. "I'm surprised we have not seen more downward pressure on the markets," says Philip Ehrmann, a London-based investment director for Invesco Capital Management. "But they must've decided that U.S. interest rates are not going up." As David Beckwith, head of the international-equity division at John Hancock, notes, "There's been a long period of turbulence lots of profit taking, a lot of events that hurt the markets. But people are starting to settle down, shake off the effects of Barings, Orange County, Kobe. There are some good earnings numbers coming out; the fundamentals are still attractive. There's a renewed look at the world."  <p> WINNERS <p>POLAND Why Poland? "Bottom fishing after it totally dried up last year," says Ehrmann. Also, because the Polish market is so thin only a dozen or so stocks are traded any buying can cause a "sharp bounce," Ehrmann says. He notes that a conference of U.S. investors recently held in Poland may have inspired just such a bounce.  <p> NEW ZEALAND "A very nice economy," says Rich Lazarchic, a senior portfolio manager for IDS Mutual Fund Group in Minneapolis. "It relies on exports, which means it depends on the rest of the world doing well, particularly Southeast Asia and that's been doing well." Rising paper prices worldwide and <a name="NYSE:IP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10800"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Paper</b></a>'s April acquisition of a 50.1 percent stake in Carter Holt Harvey New Zealand's second largest company and above 15 percent of the market's index help as well.  <p> JAPAN Obviously the dollar's weakness against the yen pumped up this market's dollar gains. But currency values weren't the only factors at work, says Beckwith. The Nikkei 225 Index was hit so hard, falling more than18 percent in the first three months of the year, that valuations have dropped to the point where some find them attractive.  <p> TURKEY Falling interest rates, strong corporate earnings, and recent political stability have encouraged domestic investors, who account for most of the market's capital. "The numbers are flat-out good," says David Edgerly, general manager of Alliance Capital Management in Istanbul, Turkey. Edgerly says that even Turkey's invasion of Kurdish northern Iraq has stirred optimism. The attempt to crush the Kurdish separatist movement is "genuinely popular, at least for the moment."  <p> LOSERS <p>SRI LANKA With negotiations stalled between the government and      rebel Tamils tourism will suffer. And Tom Haslett, a portfolio   manager for Montgomery Funds in San Francisco says manufacturers are concerned that the present pro-labor administration will side with workers' demands for wage increases.   <p> COLOMBIA While the economy remains strong, the market and the producers, says Ehrmann, are "slightly out of step. "The central bank's tight control of the money supply clashed with large corporations' payments of  first-quarter taxes, driving interest rates to nearly 40 percent and pushing the market down to its lowest level in over a year.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
