	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-A Low-Risk Play on the Takeover Craze</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-A Low-Risk Play on the Takeover Craze</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Andrew Gluck  <p> The urge to merge has never been stronger witness <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft's</b></a> months-long pursuit of <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a>. There were more corporate deals in 1994 than ever before, according to Securities Data Corp., and 1995 has started off on a similar pace. But individual investors tend to watch these big-stakes deals from the sidelines, lacking both the expertise and the risk tolerance to bet confidently on whether a particular merger will go through.  <p> There's a better way to get in on the action: a no-load mutual fund called the <a name="FUND:MERFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MERFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merger Fund</b></a>. It's the only mutual fund to invest exclusively in companies that are objects of publicly announced takeover bids or other capital restructurings. The fund makes money by purchasing shares in the target company below what they will be worth upon completion of the merger. (Because of the risk that a deal will fall through, takeover targets always trade at some discount to their announced acquisition price.)  <p> That's risky business, but the Merger Fund has developed an admirable low-risk track record. According to data from Morningstar, the Merger Fund has outperformed the Standard & Poor's 500 Index at about half the risk. The Merger Fund averaged a 10.44 percent return annually for the last three years, compared with 8.56 percent for the S&P.  <p> The Merger Fund keeps its risk low by committing money only when a deal appears certain to pan out. The fund usually has stakes in about 40 to 50 merger deals. Of the transactions the fund has invested in, fewer than 5 percent have fallen through, says Frederick Green, who comanages the fund with Bonnie Smith."We spend a good part of our day analyzing prospective transactions, focusing on key issues affecting whether a deal will be completed," says Green, a former portfolio strategist for Goldman, Sachs. <p> To understand the fund in action, consider its investment in the recently completed acquisition of Western Company of North America by <a name="NYSE:BJS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12054"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BJ Services</b></a> (both are oil-service companies). On September13, 1994, BJ Services announced an offer to pay $18.50 a share to acquire Western. Western insisted it wasn't for sale, but its shares rocketed from $12.50 to $17 on speculation that a deal would eventually be worked out.  <p> The Merger Fund team jumped into action, calling company executives, speaking to Wall Street analysts, and reviewing public filings and financial statements issued by the companies. After all the homework had been completed, Green and Smith decided to passon Western because of the risk that the merger would not take place.  <p> But Western remained on the fund's watch list. On November17, BJ announced it had signed an agreement to buy Western for $20 in cash (or the equivalent in BJ shares) plus a fractional warrant to buy BJ shares. With the merger now looking solid, Green hired an economist and an attorney to study potential antitrust objections.When those consultants reported that antitrust problems were unlikely to kill the deal, the Merger Fund purchased about 200,000 shares of Western at an average price of a little more than $18 each. In the coming weeks, after the Justice Department cleared the deal, the fund added more shares. <p>  <p>When BJ's acquisition of Western was finally completed on April13, the Merger Fund reaped an average annualized gain of more than 26 percent on its Western holdings.  <p> One pitfall of the fund is that almost all its gains are short-term and therefore taxed as ordinary income. But the Merger Fund can strengthen a fund portfolio by diversifying risk. Because the fund spreads risk exposure to another market the takeover trading market its gains and losses are usually independent of the stock market's performance. That doen't make it immune to a crash, but it definitely provides a hedge against the market's usual ups and downs.  <p><p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

