	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-When a Falling Dollar Pays Off...</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>When a Falling Dollar Pays Off for Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-When a Falling Dollar Pays Off...</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need to Know  <p> WHEN A FALLING DOLLAR PAYS OFF FOR INVESTORS  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> The plunging dollar certainly will make your next adventure overseas more expensive. But if you have money in a global income fund, you have less reason to pout. The weaker dollar has made your foreign holdings more valuable.  <p> As of mid-April, the dollar was down 19 percent against the yen and 13 percent against the deutsche mark since the beginning of the year. During that time, the J.P. Morgan Non­U.S. Government Bond Index rose16 percent. Better than two thirds of that ascent is attributable to the plunge in the greenback. "The dollar's fall has been a bonanza for global bond investors," says Ray Goodner, manager of <a name="FUND:IGBFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/IGBFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IDS Global Bond Fund</b></a> (800-328-8300; 5 percent load; $2,000 minimum).  <p> Is the bonanza likely to continue?  <p> Some analysts worry that the dollar could rebound from its recent lows, inflicting currency losses on overseas funds. This is certainly a worry in the short run, and investors concerned about preserving capital in the near term may want to consider switching to funds that hedge against currency risk, such as <a name="FUND:SCIBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SCIBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Scudder International Bond</b></a> (800-225-2470; no-load; $1,000 minimum).   <p> Over the long run, the dollar seems more likely to continue losing value against the yen and the mark. "The dollar's trend has been pretty much consistently downward since 1985," notes Susan Belden, senior editor of the San Francisco­based No-Load Fund Analyst.  <p> Long-term investors should thus steer clear of funds that consistently hedge their currency bets. "When you hedge, your returns will be more correlated with those of the U.S. markets," says John Scarborough of the San Francisco investment-management firm Bingham, Osborn & Scarborough. "That defeats the main purpose of investing overseas."  <p> Scarborough recommends investing roughly 20 percent of a long-term fixed-income portfolio in geographically diversified foreign income funds that do little currency hedging. One pick: <a name="FUND:RPIBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RPIBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price International Bond</b></a> (800-638-5660; no-load; $2,500 minimum). <p> Finally, some analysts think that foreign bond funds remain a good bet under any circumstances. Christopher Leary,  senior vice president at SunAmerica, believes that the risk of currency losses is offset by the chance of further gains in foreign bondmarkets themselves. "Income investors can do better overseas," he says. <p><p>  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:IGBFX">IDS Global Bond Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:SCIBX">Scudder International Bond</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:RPIBX">T. Rowe Price International Bond</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
