<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Trendspotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>TRENDSPOTTER<p>By Ellen Simon<p>First thing we do is have the lawyers kill the CEOs. Lawsuits filed against corporate directors and officers for mismanagement cost insurers more than $1.1 billion in 1994, according to the Wyatt Co., a Boston consulting and actuarial firm. Wyatt surveyed 1,231 companies and found that their insurers paid out an average of $967,000 to defend a mismanagement suit and an average of $4.62 million to settle out of court or pay civil penalties. <p>The building industry raised more roofs last year than in any year since 1988, but demographers see more interest in the ratio of single-family to multifamily homes. In 1988, 32 percent of new building was multifamily; by 1993, only 18 percent was multifamily. Gopal Ahluwalia, director of research at the National Association of Homebuilders, explains that multifamily building has slid since 1988 because it is typically dominated by rental units, and people under 30--those most likely to rent--made up the fastest-declining age group. With the children of baby boomers growing older and moving out, multifamily building should come back.<p>Brawny sport-utility vehicles, like Jeeps and <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> Explorers, now command 11 percent of the car and truck market, up from 9 percent in 1992. Now luxury-car makers such as Lexus and Cadillac have SUVs on their drawing boards, according to Tom Healey, a partner at J.D. Power and Associates, a marketing-information firm that specializes in the automobile industry. The automakers are hoping the mud sloggers will appeal to women who want more room than a sedan affords but "would rather cut off their arms than drive a minivan," says Healey.<p>We're fat and getting fatter. Almost seven in ten Americans are overweight, up from 63 percent in 1991 and 58 percent in 1983, according to the latest Prevention Index. Why the cellulite upswing? Well, we're exercising less: Only 30 percent of women and 45 percent of men work out strenuously three times a week. But we're still tired: 30 percent of adults get six or fewer hours of sleep a night, the highest proportion since the index began keeping track of such things in 1983. <p>Save that sawdust. U.S. consumption of recycled construction materials will increase 4 percent annually, reaching 200 million tons in 1998, according to a study by the Cleveland-based Freedonia Group. Most of the reusables will go toward fill and paving materials.<p>Moviegoing hit a 34-year high last year, with 1.3 billion tickets sold. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Entertainment Industry, Homeowner, Real Estate

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

