	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>THE BIG PICTURE<p>By Dean Robinson<p>OVERVIEW<p>The declining dollar improved the value of stocks held by U.S. investors in every European equities market except Italy. But some European manufacturers are worried about the long-term consequences of having to compete with U.S. firms that can now effectively charge lower prices. "The Europeans are selling off, saying, 'We can't compete,''' says Dan Jacobs, a portfolio manager with the Franklin Templeton Group. "They have to reduce prices and squeeze margins." Of course, not all exporters are so unlucky. Notes Jane Siebels-Kilnes, another portfolio manager with Franklin Templeton, "The low dollar is sort of a godsend for those countries tied to the dollar; it helps exports." South Korea was but one example of this.<p>
WINNERS<p>TURKEY The possibility of increased access to European markets helped excite this small and extremely volatile market. <p>PERU A cease-fire in the border war with Ecuador and an easing of election worries brightened the outlook for Peru, which has a stronger economy than many Latin American nations. Another strength, according to Robert Heisterberg, a global-policy analyst with Alliance Capital: High levels of direct foreign investment, which tends to stick around longer than international capital that arrives via the local stock exchange.<p>SOUTH AFRICA The addition of South Africa to several broad indexes such as <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> Capital International helped stimulate foreign interest in this country. In March, South Africa's dual currencies, the commercial rand and the financial rand, were unified. (They were originally created to keep capital from fleeing the country during apartheid.) The change led to "tremendous appreciation of the currency," says Tom Haslett, a portfolio manager for Montgomery Funds. <p>SOUTH KOREA "A great story," says Haslett. A dollar-linked currency has certainly helped here. "The economy is heavily geared toward exports, so the dollar's 10 percent drop against the yen gives South Korea's export base a tremendous opportunity to expand," Haslett adds. Also, South Korea's restrictions on foreign ownership insulate it from the sudden outflow of funds experienced by so many emerging markets after the Mexican devaluation.<p>CANADA "There was concern Canada might be headed Italy's way [see below]," says Heisterberg, but Canada "passed a budget with much more austerity built into it than the market had anticipated."<p>
LOSERS<p>ITALY The honeymoon for the new administration, which arrived in January, may be over. "The government is going to have to cut spending," says Kelly McDermott, a Dreyfus portfolio manager, "but all it's done so far is raise taxes, and that's not going to fly in the long term. So the market is being penalized now."<p>PAKISTAN The murder of U.S. consular officials doesn't inspire investor confidence. "The issues are almost entirely political--law and order in Karachi, for example," says Haslett. "There's a tremendous amount of political uncertainty. In my opinion, if martial law were declared, you would see a rally of 20 percent." <p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - <p>"People keep wondering how the stock market can go up if the dollar is falling. Well, my answer to them is, what's it been doing since 1985?"<p>--Bartley Blout of Strome, Susskind, a hedge fund in Santa Monica, California<p>
"Kick the IRS out of your wallet and out of your records. Get back to an America free from the IRS in terms of day-to-day micromanagement."<p>--House Speaker Newt Gingrich, suggesting to viewers of CNBC's Talk Live that the size of the IRS would be cut by the imposition of a flat income tax<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
