<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Capitol Gains?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Capitol Gains?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Capitol Gains?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth Magazine/Need to Know<p>CAPITOL GAINS?<p>By James K. Glassman<p>The jaundiced eye wall street traditionally casts on Washington these days often looks like little more than indifference. Big investors, money managers, and traders no longer think that federal decisions on taxing and spending make much difference in a $7 trillion global economy.<p>Beyond that, Contract With America or not, they just don't think politicians will keep their campaign promises. Following November's stunning election, fund manager Martin Zweig's comments were typical: "Republican control (of Congress) is not going to cure the stock market's ills, which include extreme overvaluation, poor monetary conditions, an economy that is too strong, and the hangover from several years of intense speculation."<p>In the four months after the election', the S&P 500 rose about 4 percent--a slight reproach to the bearish Zweig, but the balanced-budget amendment had been defeated, tax cuts were in trouble, and House leaders put off announcing their deficit-reduction plan until May. <p>Still, if skepticism were a stock (possible symbol: SKP), I'd say it's been overbought. This is nothing new. After Ronald Reagan's election in 1980, it took the market two years to recognize that this fellow really wanted to cut taxes and keep a lid on government spending. Then interest rates fell and the S&P almost tripled between mid-1982 and the end of Reagan's second term.<p>That pattern could repeat itself. The current Republican majorities in the House and Senate are too thin to do the things (like replace the current tax code with a flat or consumption tax) that capital markets want. But those majorities could grow after next year's election. Two studies of the 1994 elections--one by Fred Steeper, a partner in Market Strategies, Inc., a Southfield, Michigan, market-research firm, and the other by three scholars from the Hoover Institution and Stanford University--independently concluded that the decisive factor in the congressional elections was voter ideology rather than some vague desire to throw the bums out.<p>Normally, in a swing election, voters of all sorts shift away from the party in power. That is why, as William Schneider of the American Enterprise Institute puts it, "Every landslide carries with it the seeds of its own defeat." But Steeper's recent paper, "This Swing Is Different," showed that in 1994 there was polarization based on policy. Conservatives voted more Republican than usual, liberals more Democratic. As the three Stanford/Hoover researchers--David W. Brady, John F. Cogan, and Douglas Rivers--wrote, "Our most important finding is that the large Democratic Party losses in the House were due to voters' rejecting President Clinton's legislative agenda." That strongly suggests Republicans will retain their gains through 1996.<p>Will they add to them? Quite possibly. In the Senate, where Republicans need another half-dozen seats to break filibusters consistently, it appears far more Democrats will be retiring. Incumbent Republicans also hold more safe seats. Charles Cook's insider publication, The Cook Political Report, currently ranks 11 Republican and only two Democratic senators as safe in 1996. <p>This year, if the market pays any attention to fiscal policy at all, it will probably concentrate on the defeats of key portions of the Republican agenda. But as the prospects for 1996 become clearer, investors may realize that SKP would make a great short.<p>As Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said before the House Budget Committee in March, "The effects [of Congress decisively attempting to balance the budget] I think would be rather startling." In other words, rates would fall and the economy would boom.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

