	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Market Radar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth Magazine/Need to Know<p>MARKET RADAR<p>Sigh. The cautious optimism that our technical indicators showed last month has vanished. Though the Dow Jones Industrial Average has conquered 4000, a lack of participation in the upswing by a wide group of stocks dampens hope for a prolonged run-up in the market. And ominously, our bellwether indicator reversed direction during the latest rally. To make matters worse, investment advisors continue to turn upbeat--and you know how we feel about their reliability. As usual, each of our indicators gets a rating (10 is most bullish) and an arrow (near-term message).<p>
Composite Bellwether (4 this month/5 last month) 
This index, computed by InvesTech, tracks utility and brokerage stocks, which usually predict market turns. Weakness in utilities pushed it down even as the Dow surged; some investors apparently see interest rate hikes ahead.<p>Put/Call Ratio (5/5) 
Based on the volume of equity put and call options traded on the Chicago Board Options Exchange. This contrarian measure is positive if traders bet big against stocks. Optimists fought pessimists to a standstill to keep this indicator neutral for the month.<p>Advance/Decline Line (2/3) 
A moving average of the difference between the number of rising and falling stocks, this indicates if market moves are broadly or narrowly based. Computed by InvesTech, this measure shows participation drooping despite new market highs, a bad sign.<p>Advisory Sentiment (6/8) 
Investment advisors tend to be followers, not leaders: Historically, they're most optimistic at market tops. They've been getting psyched by a record-setting Dow lately; soon they'll be scaring us away from stocks. Compiled by Investors Intelligence.<p>Commodity Index (4/4) 
Supplied by Goldman, Sachs, this measure of raw-material prices remained steady again this month as metal prices continued to fall. The index is down more than 2 percent in 1995 so far, a reassuring sign for inflation hawks.<p>Consumer and Corporate Debt (5/5) 
This aggregate measure of private debt remained steady last month, halting a two-year trend toward more borrowing. A statistical blip or a positive development? It's a little early to say. Provided by Safian Investment Research.<p>Yield Ratio (3/3) 
The ratio between yields of 90-day Treasury bills and the S&P 500, computed by the Leuthold Group. For the first time in more than a year, the ratio didn't increase this month. But it didn't shrink either. Those healthy T-bill returns still look like a safer bet than stocks.<p>Monetary Environment (3/3)  
This model from InvesTech measures how much money is available to flow into the stock market. It remained unchanged from last month, meaning the cash still isn't there for a major, sustained advance in equities.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Bonds

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

