<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Is It Time...Join Move to Junk?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is It Time to Join the Move to Junk?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Is It Time...Join Move to Junk?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>IS IT TIME TO JOIN THE MOVE TO JUNK?<p>By Clint Willis<p>Professional investors have lost billions investing in emerging-markets bonds. Now they're shifting some of their assets into high-yield (or junk) bonds, the riskiest class of corporate bond. Should the rest of us follow? <p>"A lot of investors who got killed reaching for extra yield last year are moving into the high-yield market," says Ole Dial, the manager of the NWNL <a name="FUND:NHYBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NHYBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northstar High Yield fund</b></a> (800-595-7827; 4.75 percent load; $2,500 minimum initial investment). Even characteristically staid pension plans such as the City of New York police department's and employees' funds recently invested a total of $800 million in junk bonds, hoping to profit from the best performing of all bond categories over the last decade.<p>Foolish as that may sound to investors seeking safety after 1994's bond-market meltdown and this year's international-bond debacle, this actually may be a good time to put a modest portion of your fixed-income holdings into a well-managed high-yield bond fund. Rising demand and falling supply are likely to produce capital gains in the months  ahead.<p>Institutional investors looking for some extra yield are providing the demand. On the supply side, redemptions and tender offers took some $2 billion in junk bonds out of play during the first ten weeks of 1995.<p>That has already pumped up prices and lowered yields for bonds with credit ratings near the top of the junk heap. (Junk bonds are defined as those rated BB or lower.) But lower-quality issues remain inexpensive: Some B-rated issues are yielding more than 12 percent, almost five percentage points higher than 30-year Treasurys. "The lower-quality tier of junk bonds is still trading very cheaply," says Clark Stamper, manager of the Venture Income (+) Plus fund (800-279-0279; 4.75 percent load; $1,000 minimum). <p>Of course, such bonds could sink in price. In a recession, junk-bond prices fall as sales and profits decline at the financially challenged companies that issued them. But a serious economic downturn doesn't seem to be in the cards for 1995. And balance sheets at many junk issuers are in much better shape than they have been anytime in the last 15 years. <p>Still, for safety, Ralph Norton, managing editor of IBC Donoghue's Investing for Income, recommends diversified mutual funds. One excellent choice: <a name="FUND:NTHEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NTHEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northeast Investors Trust</b></a> (800-225-6704; no load; $1,000 minimum). <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

