				<font size=5><b>Industry Sectors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Industry Sectors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>INDUSTRY SECTORS<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>As we enter the 50th month of the economic recovery--the average length of an economic expansion--investors are anxious. They worry the business activity may come to a sudden halt. But they also worry business may not slow rapidly enough, prompting the Fed to raise interest rates again. The latter fear caused utility stocks to lose steam in March, even as the falling dollar sent investors in search of safe havens, lifting gold-mining stocks. <p>Other safe harbors included consumer-staple stocks like beverages, tobacco, and health care. Unlike basic materials--metals, chemicals, and forest products--these noncyclical industries do well in up or down markets. Meanwhile, the tobacco industry, vilified by many in the U.S., is expanding aggressively in Europe and Asia and hoping for improved earnings.<p>Sam Stovall, editor of S&P's Industry Reports, notes that, having "drunk 'em and smoked 'em, you have to pay for 'em afterward--with health care." The sector is still benefiting from the failure of health-care reform and from industry consolidation, including the GlaxoWellcome and Columbia/HCAHealthTrust mergers.<p>Computer software and services have outperformed the S&P by 26 percent over the past year. But their gain has been the retail sector's loss. "The consumer has been spending on computer software over apparel," says analyst Jennifer Black Groves of Black & Co. <p>
