<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Going Against the Grain</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Going Against the Grain</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Going Against the Grain</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>GOING AGAINST THE GRAIN<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Martin Whitman, manager of the <a name="FUND:TAVFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TAVFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Third Avenue Value Fund</b></a>, is not one of the crowd. He scoops up stocks that others dump and has gotten into hot water over what some consider his too-cozy relationships with some of the companies in which his fund invests. But his returns--a 14 percent average annual gain for the last three years, versus 6.33 percent for the S&P 500--are hard to argue with. <p>When investors fled Piper Jaffray, a brokerage facing big shareholder suits over derivatives losses, Whitman bought. When <a name="NYSE:DEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10462"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Digital Equipment</b></a> was the pariah of high tech, Whitman kept buying. Now that derivatives are in the doghouse, he's interested.<p>A government-backed mortgage derivative he recently bought is pure Whitman. Worst case--interest rates head higher and stay there--he'd earn 5 percent annually. If rates fall by year end, he could earn 50 percent. <p>Whitman, 70, who started as a Wall Street analyst in 1950, has run Third Avenue--a no-load since it discontinued a 4.5 percent load in February--from its founding in 1990. The fund holds 88 securities, but half its $214 million in assets is in 20 stocks. To make Whitman's list, shares must trade at less than half their estimated buyout worth; assets must exceed liabilities, including offbalance sheet items like lawsuits; a company must be easy to follow from public filings; management must be attentive to shareholder interests. Take <a name="AMEX:FCE.A"></a><b>Forest City Enterprises</b>, for which Whitman paid some $20 a share: The value of its real estate land alone is worth $80 a share.<p>Whitman has been a target of controversy. His fund owns stock in <a name="AMEX:DHC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11180"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Danielson Holding Corp.</b></a>, a financial company in which Whitman owns a stake and which pays him $75,000 a year in director's fees. Also, a partnership he runs bid on a troubled insurance company owned by Third Avenue. <p>Whitman confirms the Securities and Exchange Commission examined his role in both investments last year; the SEC won't comment. But Whitman says he and his family have $4 million invested in the fund, so his interests are the same as shareholders'. "I wouldn't compromise my commitment to fund investors," he says. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:DEC">Digital Equipment Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#AMEX:FCE.A">Forest City Enterprises</a><br>

						<a href="#AMEX:DHC">Danielson Holding Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:TAVFX">Third Avenue Value Fund</a><br>

