	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Rattling the Orthodoxy</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Rattling the Orthodoxy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>RATTLING THE ORTHODOXY<p>By Dean Robinson<p>The minimum wage has been a maximum hot spot ever since President Clinton suggested raising the base pay rate in his state of the union address. David Card, a Princeton economist, has helped fan the fire__and felt the heat, too.<p>"This is very controversial within economics," says Card, the coauthor, along with Labor Department chief economist Alan B. Krueger, of Myth and Measurement: The New Economics of the Minimum Wage. This controversial study debunks the traditional notion that boosting the minimum wage also raises levels of unemployment. "Some colleagues feel it's not right to study the minimum wage. To do research on the subject is like saying, 'I'm going to see if there are bones in this saint's tomb.'"<p>Given the passionate criticism Card has heard, he's beginning to feel like something of a heretic. "One of my colleagues said to me, 'Your work is dangerous,'" he says. "They don't quite realize that makes them sound like they're the Catholic Church in the 1300s."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
