	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Painted into a Corner</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Painted into a Corner</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Painted into a Corner</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>PAINTED INTO A CORNER
Picasso's fingerprint may be the last hope for Mark Harris to prove the art experts wrong<p>By Dean Robinson<p>It is every art lover's dream: to stumble upon what appears to be an unknown masterpiece at a flea market and buy it for a pittance. Usually, of course, the work turns out to be a piece of junk, and that's that.<p>Mark Harris is one dreamer who won't give up. Despite many rejections, the 39-year-old Englishman and former art student refuses to accept that the pen-and-ink gouache he owns isn't an authentic Picasso. As far as Harris is concerned, the failure of any acknowledged expert to support the authenticity of the work says more about the clubbiness of the gatekeepers of Picasso's legacy than it does about the value of his work.<p>Harris believes the work first surfaced about 15 years ago at a house clearance, a sort of English estate sale, in London. About four years ago, a friend of Harris's purchased the work from a Brighton dealer for 25. Soon after, Harris purchased a share in the work (there are now four shareholders in all). He then set out to confirm his belief that he was now part owner of a genuine Picasso.<p>It hasn't gone well. Perhaps the biggest setback came last year, when Claude Picasso, the artist's son, declared that the work had not been created by his father. "You are off on a wild goose chase," Claude Picasso wrote Harris.<p>Harris believes that Claude Picasso's summary judgment has forever ended his chance of a fair hearing among art experts. So, in his latest tactic to authenticate the piece, Harris has offered a $1,000 reward to anyone who can prove that a fingerprint on his drawing came from Picasso himself. This could be his last hope. "The big guys in the Picasso establishment have stopped me all down the line," Harris says.<p>Is there a chance Harris will ever convince the art world to come around to his view? "It looks impossible," says Picasso scholar Robert Rosenblum, a professor at New York University. And a fingerprint match wouldn't necessarily prove anything, Rosenblum adds: "Even if the fingerprint is Picasso's, that doesn't mean it's by him."<p>The disputed painting may never hang in a museum or bring Harris fame or fortune, but it's become a kind of performance art, available for anyone to look at in a high-tech "virtual" gallery. To publicize his fingerprint reward, Harris is displaying the piece on the Internet's World Wide Web. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


