				<font size=5><b>Looking Like a Million</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Looking Like a Million</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>LOOKING LIKE A MILLION<p>Talk about bargains: You can now purchase a million-dollar bill for just $12.50, thanks to the International Association of Millionaires. The Florida outfit mints authentic-looking million-spots as a cutesy corporate giveaway. "Most of our customers are banks and financial types who present them to their employees or clients as a thank-you gift, as in 'Thanks a million,' " says Tari Steward, the owner of the association. Steward shouldn't expect a thank-you from the Bureau of Engraving and Printing, which has been fielding hopeful calls about the funny money. "We've got to tell people that it's not a real million-dollar bill," says a bureau spokeswoman. "But some of them insist that it's redeemable and say they're going to their banks." They'd probably be better off saving their millions for a down payment on the Brooklyn Bridge__there's no such thing as a genuine million-dollar bill.<p>

					</font>
