<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Compulsive in Austin</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Compulsive in Austin</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Compulsive in Austin</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>COMPULSIVE IN AUSTIN
Broker Chris Anderson couldn't stop playing the market. Now he counsels other gamblers.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Losing is a part of life on Wall Street. No stockbroker can expect to best the market all the time, and even the most skilled financial wizards can make costly mistakes with investments that sour. But what about the guy who just can't win? When trade after trade results in defeat and loss, perhaps it's a sign of more than a lack of investment prowess. Maybe that unlucky broker is actually a compulsive gambler.<p>That's what Chris Anderson thinks, anyway. Anderson, 42, blames a betting addiction for ending his career as a broker. "For a long time, I wrote off my bad investments as part of the education," he says of his three years working as a stockbroker in Austin, Texas. "But I kept trading any profits I made so impulsively. I kept looking for a big win."<p>Anderson had never been tempted by blackjack tables or roulette wheels. Instead, he put all his chips on the market. He says he squandered tens of thousands of dollars of his clients' money and roughly $250,000 of his own before he acknowledged his gambling problem. His epiphany came when he resorted to liquidating family assets to support his market-betting habit. "When I sold the property I owned with my wife, put the equity in my account, and lost it in the market in two days, I knew I was in big trouble," he says.<p>It was investments in the notoriously risky options market__what Anderson calls "the greatest gambling casino in the world"__that finally drowned him in debt and forced him to file for bankruptcy. He lost his home, and finally, his wife left him. Looking back, he's most disturbed by how easy it was to get by at work despite the constant losses. "As long as I was generating commissions," he says, "I was left alone."<p>Now Anderson wants to warn other brokers of the potential dangers of getting hooked on the market. With his investment career now permanently behind him, he spends his days as head of the nonprofit Illinois Council on Problem and Compulsive Gambling, counseling stockbrokers who are struggling with the issue. It's not easy to get people to take the idea seriously. Although other former brokers will acknowledge in private that they gambled compulsively on the market, few will speak out openly. "To mention the word gambling in the securities industry is anathema," Anderson says.<p>Fortunately, Anderson has found an ally. Last July, he teamed up with Dr. Marvin Steinberg, a psychologist who heads the Connecticut Council on Compulsive Gambling, to increase public awareness of the problem. Steinberg has been conducting research on the subject but has encountered the same resistance as Anderson. When Steinberg mailed out a survey to 1,000 Connecticut stockbrokers, only 70 even bothered to respond.<p>Anderson isn't surprised by such obstacles__after all, he once considered himself a "speculative investor," not a gambler. Because all investments are at some level a gamble, it can be difficult to gauge the border between a healthy acceptance of risk and a destructive compulsion. "I know firms where some of the biggest producers were compulsive gamblers," Anderson says. "They were labeled as heroes."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

