		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Clipping the Ad Man</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Clipping the Ad Man</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>CLIPPING THE AD MAN
No mere mutual fund manager, David Herro waged war with Saatchi & Saatchi and won<p>By Ted C. Fishman<p>David Herro, the mutual fund manager who ousted Saatchi & Saatchi's chairman and co-founder late last year, relied mainly on support from other shareholders to sack Maurice Saatchi. But Herro looks like he would have been capable of physically tackling the man had it come to that. At 34, Herro is curly-haired, broad-shouldered, and fit__the kind of guy who hasn't let his physique slide from his high school football days in Fond du Lac, Wisconsin.<p>These days, Herro calls the plays for the <a name="FUND:OAKIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OAKIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oakmark International Fund</b></a>, a billion-dollar fund that invests mainly in value stocks overseas__that is, foreign companies that appear cheap relative to their underlying assets. It's a big fund, but far from the biggest, and most people in Herro's position work in relative obscurity. However, thanks to his decision to tangle with Maurice Saatchi, Herro has earned a modicum of fame, especially among investment buffs.<p>He appears to be enjoying it. At a recent investment conference in Appleton, Wisconsin (about 35 miles from his hometown), questions soon turned to his Saatchi-slaying exploits, and Herro seemed happy to oblige the audience with the tale.<p>As Herro tells it, London-based Saatchi & Saatchi's global advertising conglomerate looked like a terrific value, so he began buying up shares and waiting for the stock to rise. When it didn't, Herro focused on Maurice Saatchi and his brother and co-founder Charles as the cause. The Saatchis, Herro believed, were interfering with the executives who averted a collapse at Saatchi & Saatchi in the late '80s__a near disaster brought on by massive debt accumulated in an acquisition binge. To Herro, those executives, and not Maurice Saatchi, were the key to the company's future.<p>"They refinanced the company and got rid of all the gar-bage," Herro says. "They concentrated on the better parts."<p>Herro didn't resort to a public battle immediately. First, he wrote Saatchi & Saatchi's board and told them to rein in Maurice or get rid of him. With Herro's Oakmark International holding 9 percent of Saatchi & Saatchi's shares, that request should have been taken seriously. But the board stalled, and Herro felt he had no other option than to orchestrate a shareholder revolt.<p>"Generally, I wouldn't go hounding a company's management, but this was a special case," he says.<p>So Herro began networking with other investors to rally support. In December, with 70 percent of Saatchi & Saatchi's shareholders behind him, Herro forced the directors' hands. Maurice Saatchi was out.<p>The exit wasn't graceful. Maurice Saatchi announced plans to start a new agency, sparking fears that longtime Saatchi & Saatchi clients__such as M&M/Mars and British Airways__would follow him. Instead of bolstering Saatchi's shares, Maurice's departure sent the company's American depositary receipts down nearly 40 percent, to around $4.50.<p>But Herro has no regrets, even despite being vilified in the British press (accounts ridiculed his Wisconsin roots by tagging him "the Herro from Zero"). And Saatchi's shares have already begun to recover. Eventually, Herro believes, they will prove a winner His confident prediction: "I think the stock still could go to $10."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
