	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>THIS BABY REALLY MOVES<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Janus Capital may have found a new prodigy.<p>In the late 1980s the fund family had James Craig and Tom Marsico, two of the hottest managers in the business. In 1989, Marsico's first full year at the helm, the <a name="FUND:JAVLX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAVLX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Twenty</b></a> fund soared 50.9 percent. Craig's <a name="FUND:JAVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Venture</b></a> fund also turned in stellar numbers, beating the S&P 500 index by an average 5.3 percentage points a year between 1986 and 1991.<p>Warren Lammert, 33, manager of <a name="FUND:JAMRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAMRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Mercury</b></a> since its birth in May 1993, may be continuing the tradition. He produced a 19.8 percent total return in 1993, then followed that with a 15.9 percent gain in 1994, a year in which Lipper Analytical's capital-appreciation category showed a 3.4 percent loss.<p>Among fund managers, however, 20 months isn't a long-term track record. Lammert has stormed out of the gates again in 1995, but he now runs $1 billion, up from $127 million at the start of 1994, and this will be a testing year for Lammert.<p>His strategy at Janus Mercury is solidly within the tradition established in the 1970s by Janus founder Tom Bailey. Janus equity managers combine the Graham and Dodd school of value stock picking with growth-at-any-cost momentum investing. Janus looks at a stock only if its price-to-earnings multiple is lower than its projected earnings growth. Lammert also judges companies qualitatively, looking for consistency of earnings and assessing how well he and his analysts know an industry.<p>Mercury has the most flexible charter of any Janus offering, allowing Lammert to invest in companies of any size or nationality. Foreign-based multinationals, such as Finland's <a name="NYSE:NOK.A"></a><b>Nokia</b>, a manufacturer of cellular phones, make up one fifth of assets.<p>As befits the manager of a fund called Mercury, Lammert moves quickly when the market warrants. In late 1994, he held 46 percent of the fund's assets in cash. By mid-February, after falling interest rates changed Lammert's risk assessment, he had already plunged back into the market, reducing cash to 14 percent. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
