	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-The Big Picture</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>THE BIG PICTURE<p>By Dean Robinson<p>OVERVIEW<p>Two months after Mexico's currency exploded, the fallout is still raining down on markets around the world. According to Gary Thayer, an economist at A.G. Edwards & Sons in St. Louis, "The countries that appear risky [to investors] have to raise their interest rates to defend their currencies. When a country such as Argentina wants to keep its currency stable, that hurts stocks." Investors, however, have started to make distinctions among emerging markets.<p>Although Latin American markets continue to suffer, Asian markets are rebounding from the bout of selling that immediately followed the Mexican blowup and made those markets invitingly cheap. The perception that the Federal Reserve is finished raising U.S. interest rates after February's hike also had a positive influence on the Asian markets, since many of the developing Asian countries link their currencies to the dollar. And finally there's the Chinese New Year factor: "Usually the Chinese New Year kicks off a rally__there's a huge Chinese community entrenched in every Asian market," says William Wilby, director of global equities for Oppenheimer Management.<p>WINNERS<p>MALAYSIA "A very good story," according to Joe Quinlan, senior international economist at Dean Witter Reynolds. "The currency is pretty strong, the economy's doing well. They got some backwash from Mexico, unfairly, but now they're getting a bounce." Thayer adds that the Malaysian government, which has long feared its economically dominant native-Chinese population as a potentially destabilizing force, has recently made overtures to China.<p>HONG KONG Despite concerns about Deng Xiaoping's health and a possible trade war between China and the United States, investors found Hong Kong too tempting a bargain to pass up after the market plunged following the Mexican fiasco. "The market had declined too fast relative to the information out there," says Wilby.<p>UNITED STATES A double-barrel appeal pushed indexes to record highs in mid-February. Woes in the emerging markets have put a new shine on domestic stocks, and U.S. interest rates remain high. "The prospect of higher interest rates brings capital home," says Quinlan.<p>
LOSERS<p>AUSTRALIA A slowing U.S. economy could dampen demand for Australian commodities. "The mining part of the market__roughly 50 percent of the market__is very weak," says Robin Garrow, investment director at Scottish Widows, a pension-management firm in Edinburgh, Scotland. <p>ARGENTINA This is perhaps the best example of the impact of the Mexican financial crisis on other emerging markets. "The most unfair hammering has taken place in Argentina, and to some extent Brazil," says Wilby. "Argentina probably has the best single financial and economic system in all the emerging markets, but it's given no credit for that."<p>POLAND Another market slammed by the Mexican tidal wave, but with some justification. "Poland hasn't worked out a long-term strategy," says Thayer. "It's moving toward economic freedoms, but more slowly than the Czech Republic." <p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - <p>"Quit complaining! It's a wonderful life if inflation is just 3.5 percent."<p>-James W. Coons, chief economist at Huntington National Bank in Columbus, Ohio, on speculation that inflation could go beyond 3 percent this year<p>
"It's going to be the greatest intergenerational struggle of our times. [It will pit younger workers against] the Greedy Geezers of America Amalgamated."<p>-Senator Alan Simpson on the future of Social Security, to the Institute for Research on the Economics of Taxation and the Tax Council, Washington, D.C.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
