	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Limits of Certainty</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-The Limits of Certainty</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth Magazine/Need to Know<p>THE LIMITS OF CERTAINTY<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Physical scientists call it inertia. Economists call it lag. Either way, investors cannot make sense of today's economy without an understanding of this concept.<p>Physical inertia proposes simply that bodies at rest tend to stay at rest while bodies in motion tend to stay in motion, tracking a straight line unless some new force intervenes.<p>If the economy were a physical object__say a 1988 Saab__speeding along too fast and heading toward inflation, it likely would continue in this direction__unless the Federal Reserve Board intervened to slow the car down. To do this, the Federal Reserve indeed applies a force: It raises or lowers interest rates. <p>Sadly, though, the economy doesn't respond like a car. First, there's a delay, a lag, between pushing or braking and the economy's response. Second, this lag is longer for some parts of the economy than others. So a change in rates doesn't have an immediate__or even__impact.<p>During the 12 months beginning in February 1994, for example, the Fed raised interest rates seven times, but the economy is only now beginning to show signs of slowing down. On February 16, the Department of Commerce announced that January housing starts slumped 9.8 percent, the second straight monthly decline since the revised numbers for December. An 8.6 percent drop in building permits issued also suggested a building slowdown.<p>Housing starts are among the most widely followed economic indicators because the loans home buyers usually require are highly sensitive to interest rates.<p>But what portion of the braking force applied by the Fed is reflected in January's housing slowdown? Home buyers, presumably, didn't put off signing a contract after the first quarter-point rise in rates a year ago. Nor did builders cancel their lumber orders. Perhaps the housing market didn't believe that the Federal Reserve was serious about inflation until after four or five rate hikes.<p>Meanwhile, the government also recently reported that the country's factories ran at 85.5 percent of capacity in January, the highest level since 1979. No slowing there.<p>So just how much of an effect have the Fed's rate hikes had? Knowing the answer would tell us a lot about the future of the economy. If the housing declines were a response to early rate hikes, then the economy may slow considerably or even slide into recession. If the numbers reflect a reaction to most of the hikes, then the Federal Reserve may reach its goal of steady, sustainable growth. Alternatively, the economy could continue to expand at an inflationary rate. No one can know for sure.<p>At the moment, the humble investor concentrates on what he can know__the quality of a company's management, its prospects for growth, and the strength of its balance sheet. He or she remembers that no economic scenario is a good one for a bad company.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
