	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Muni Bonds Aren't Bargain Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Muni Bonds Aren't Any Bargain Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Muni Bonds Aren't Bargain Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>MUNI BONDS AREN'T ANY BARGAIN NOW<p>By Clint Willis<p>Last year, municipal-bond investors took a terrific beating as interest rates rose and rose, lifting yields and squashing prices. This year, muni advocates insist, the bonds are due for a comeback.<p>"There will be unheard-of scarcity in the municipal-bond market this year," says Robert Dennis, head of the municipal fixed-income department at Massachusetts Financial Services. "For the first time ever, there could be a significant decline in the number of issues." <p>The decline is a result of cutbacks in state and local government spending, as well as bond refundings, redemptions, and scheduled maturities totaling $150 billion in 1995. In theory, that should give a boost to the prices of tax-free bonds as investors in the top tax bracket fight over the diminished supply.<p>Of course, investors heard the same arguments early last year. That didn't prevent the average muni-bond fund from suffering a 6 percent loss in 1994, according to Morningstar.<p>This time it will be different, the optimists argue. Last year's municipal-bond market was a victim of higher interest rates, which battered every sector of the bond market. As the economy slows down, the Fed isn't likely to push rates much higher__and the muni market will rally in response to tight supply and heavy demand. <p>Trouble is, the rally already occurred. "There was a brief buying opportunity in late '94, but right now the municipal-bond market stinks," says Joe Mysak, editor of Grant's Municipal Bond Observer. Experts commonly judge the attractiveness of munis by comparing their yields to Treasury bond yields. "Yields on municipal bonds in mid-February were only 81 percent of Treasury bond yields, versus 88 percent last November," says Mysak.<p>And the Orange County debacle suggests that investors must tread carefully to avoid credit problems. "Few investors are qualified to build a diversified portfolio of munis on their own," says Ralph Norton, managing editor of IBC Donoghue's Investing for Income. <p>People who do invest in the municipal market should choose a mutual fund with 80 percent or more of its portfolio in issues rated investment grade or higher. Norton recommends <a name="FUND:VWITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Municipal Intermediate-Term</b></a> (800-662-7447; no load) and <a name="FUND:SCMTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SCMTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Scudder Medium-Term Tax Free</b></a> (800-225-2470; no load). "It used to be easy to invest in munis," he says. "These days, you need a pro."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
