<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Market Radar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth Magazine/Need to Know<p>MARKET RADAR<p>We officially leave the ranks of the pessimists this month. But that doesn't mean we think the market is about to blast skyward. True, our indicators have improved a lot since hitting a bottom late last fall. But we'd like to see more stocks participate in rallies, as measured by our Advance/Decline Line. And the pesky Yield Ratio continues to make Treasury bills look better than equities. As usual, each of our indicators gets a rating (10 is most bullish) and an arrow (near-term message).<p>
Composite Bellwether (5 this month/4 last month) 
This index, computed by InvesTech, tracks utility and brokerage stocks, which usually predict market turns. The index is gaining steam__but it's moving in lockstep with the market, which blunts its predictive power.<p>Put/Call Ratio (5/5) 
Based on the volume of equity put and call options traded on the Chicago Board Options Exchange. This contrarian indicator is positive if traders bet big against stocks. It's been in limbo lately, possibly awaiting a signal on the direction of the economy.<p>Advance/Decline Line (3/2) 
A moving average of the difference between the number of rising and falling stocks, this shows if market moves are broadly or narrowly based. Computed by InvesTech, this measure continues to improve but remains at a discouraging level.<p>Advisory Sentiment (8/9) 
Investment advisors tend to be followers, not leaders. Historically, they're most pessimistic at market bottoms__and they hit the depths in December. Now they're warming up to stocks, but not enough to scare us. Compiled by Investors Intelligence.<p>Commodity Index (4/4) 
Supplied by Goldman, Sachs, this measure of raw-material prices remained steady this month, thanks to a decline in the cost of metals such as lead and tin. Commodity prices are off almost 3 percent so far this year, a reassuring sign for inflation worrywarts.<p>Consumer and Corporate Debt (5/6) 
This aggregate measure of private debt keeps inching upward, a bad sign. Fueled by higher use of credit cards, the index recently reached a four-year high. But it isn't dangerous quite yet. Provided by Safian Investment Research.<p>Yield Ratio (3/3) 
The ratio between yields of 90-day Treasury bills and the S&P 500, computed by the Leuthold Group. This spread keeps widening, albeit slightly. As long as this is so, those healthy T-bill returns will siphon prudent investors away from the stock market.<p>Monetary Environment (3/2) 
This model from InvesTech measures how much money is available to flow into the stock market. It made a positive move in the last month but remains vulnerable to any further interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
