		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Industry Sectors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Industry Sectors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Industry Sectors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>INDUSTRY SECTORS<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>The latest industry-sector rankings from Standard & Poor's show automakers down (again) and toy makers up__prompting the question: How come Wall Street is favoring playthings for kids over playthings for adults?<p>The answer has to do with the business cycle. Now that most analysts are expecting higher interest rates to slow economic growth, the Street has lower expectations for heavy industry, especially big cyclicals like autos, steel, and aluminum. "It's the fear of going into a recession that creates the pullback from these sectors," says Robert Schenosky, steel analyst at Smith Barney. On the other hand, if these worries prove exaggerated, the stocks in these sectors may soon stabilize.<p>That apparently has already happened in the home-building and building-materials sectors, among the first to get clobbered when interest rates began rising last year. Sam Stovall, editor of Standard & Poor's Industry Report, thinks these sectors both offer good buys. <p>Industries less sensitive to interest rate changes are also doing well. They include, beside toy makers, restaurant chains and entertainment companies. Among the last group, <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walt Disney Co.</b></a> (NYSE: DIS) was a standout as The Lion King became the second-highest grossing film of all time after Jurassic Park.<p>Health care stocks also did well as it became clear that government reform efforts were unlikely and merger activity might increase. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:DIS">The Walt Disney Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
