	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> TREND SPOTTER  <p> By Ellen Simon  <p> * Want a raise? Go to the Northwest. Idaho, South Dakota, Utah, Oregon, and North Dakota led the country in income growth between1990 and 1993. Idaho led the pack, with 10 percent growth. A record wheat crop in '92 boosted wages in the Plains States, which reached an annual $30,856 in Idaho. High-tech jobs are growing out West,  though not in California, where personal income dropped almost 15 percent. Meanwhile, income slumped throughout the Northeast.  <p> * The down payment and closing costs for a first home now represent 58.5 percent of the annual income of first-time buyers, according to Harvard's Joint Center for Housing Studies. That's a gloomy number for renters looking to buy. Renters have a median net wealth of $2,203, compared with the average $14,036 for 20 percent down plus closing costs. With 10 percent down, costs average $7,426.  <p> * One third of adults in the U.S. have saved nothing for their retirement, and about 19 percent "are almost deliberate in their refusal to deal with retirement," according to a Public Agenda report. Where to turn? Forty-nine percent of those surveyed by Lutheran Brotherhood Reports say they've prayed for financial guidance.  <p> * The number of civil-rights cases brought annually to federal court has more than quintupled, from 5,138 in 1971 to 27,655 in 1993. Much of the increase results from the Civil Rights Act of 1991, which made jury trials available in civil-rights cases. Personal-injury lawyers have stopped chasing ambulances and started advertising for discrimination suits from those laid off at work. <p> * Carpoolers are becoming an endangered species. From 1980 to1990, their percentage among commuters dropped from 20 percent to 13 percent.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners, Retirement, National Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
