		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Now What?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Now What?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Now What?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> NOW WHAT?  <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> Investors took such a pounding from rising interest rates in 1994 that they may be excused a little euphoria now that interest rates look like they may top out soon.  <p> But an end to the Federal Reserve's rate hikes wouldn't guarantee a bull market. In fact, in 1995 investors could go from interest rate anxiety to recession depression.  <p> Stock bulls say investors ignored terrific earnings last year in their obsession with rates. While profits for the Standard & Poor's 500 rose an estimated 38 percent in 1994, the S&P managed a total return of only 1.32 percent. Faced with climbing interest rates, investors devalued the favorable news about earnings. The price-to-earnings ratio on the S&P 500, about 23 at the beginning of 1994, fell to 17 at the end.  <p> In 1995, however, the bullish case argues, the Fed will raise rates just once or twice, not six times as it did last year. Investors will be willing to focus on earnings--and pay more for companies with healthy bottom lines.  <p> What could go wrong with this scenario? Inflation could be tougher to subdue than expected, which could force the Fed to keep tightening. For example, one leading indicator of inflation, the CRB Spot Raw Material Price Index, was up a worrisome 38 percent in the 15 months ended mid-January.  <p> Or the Fed could wind up stopping the economy dead in its tracks,which could hurt corporate earnings. After all, only twice in nine tries over the past 40 years has the Fed managed to raise interest rates just enough to slow the economy without creating a recession, according to James Stack, president of InvesTech Research in Whitefish, Montana.  <p> Even absent a recession, the bulls could be thwarted. Earnings growth for 1995 will probably peak in the first quarter, so by the time the Fed has signaled an end to its interest-rate boosts, quarter-to-quarter earnings growth will begin to slow.   <p> In 1995, as in 1994, alert investors will be watching inflation and economic growth.  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
