		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>March Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-March Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> MARCH TIP SHEET  <p> * In a universe of 7,000 mutual funds, a "fund of funds'' where a manager picks a portfolio of the best mutual funds sounds appealing. But most require large minimums or charge high fees. Markman MultiFund Trust offers conservative, moderate, and aggressive funds, all investing in no-load funds so there's just one management fee--capped by Markman at 0.95 percent annually. The trust has been open only since January, but over the last five years, the investment advisor to the funds, Markman Capital, with $300 million under management, has outperformed Lipper Analytical's indexes in its three risk categories using no-load funds. The minimum initial direct investment is $25,000 (800-2DAISY2), or $3,000 through <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> Mutual Fund Marketplace.  <p> * Mutual funds that invest in emerging-market bonds crashed following Mexico's December peso devaluation, but bonds of some emerging nations, particularly Brazil and Argentina, may now be bargains. Mark Headley, director of international investment at Litman/Gregory, recommends <a name="FUND:FNMIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FNMIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity New Markets Income</b></a> (no-load,10.9 percent yield, $2,500 minimum initial purchase; 800-544-8888)and <a name="FUND:SCEMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SCEMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Scudder Emerging Markets Income</b></a> (no-load, 12.5 percent yield,$1,000 minimum; 800-225-2470), which hold less than 10 percent Mexican debt and are weighted toward Brazil and Argentina. Remember, says Headley, "The short term could still be rough."   <p> * Recently, mutual fund companies Fidelity Investments and Neuberger & Berman began offering personal trust management, long the preserve of banks. Fidelity and Neuberger require minimum accounts of $400,000, below the usual threshold: Laird Norton Trust Co., for example, requires a minimum of $1 million. Fidelity Personal Trust Services' (800-448-0538) minimum annual fee is $3,000; Neuberger's (800-223-6448) is $7,500.  <p> * Investors burned by rising interest rates have been buying variable-rate CDs. In the fourth quarter of 1994, LaSalle National Bank sold $250 million of ten-year "multi-step" CDs whose yields rise at a set annual rate. Currently, the ten-year CD starts at 7.70 percent and rises to 11.25 percent. If interest rates drop after one or two years, the bank has the right to call the issue, in which case you get back your principal and accrued interest. Multi-step CDs,  also in five and 12-year maturities, are sold through brokers and require an initial investment of $5,000.  <p> * South Africa, once a pariah market, will be added this spring to Morgan Stanley Capital International's and International Finance Corp.'s emerging-market indexes, adding to the impressive sums already flowing into the country. Vahid Fathi, senior vice president for minerals and mining research for Kemper Securities, says the potential is "enormous for investors." Fathi says home-building, heavy-equipment, and food-distribution companies will all take advantage of President Mandela's infrastructure-building program. Investors can participate through vehicles such as the Morgan Stanley South Africa Fund. 
 <p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
