	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Consistency Pays</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Consistency Pays</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> CONSISTENCY PAYS   <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> Donald Yacktman and the <a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a> are back in style. After a dismal 1993, the 53-year-old fund manager staged a comeback in 1994, gaining 8.8 percent while the average growth fund lost 2.1 percent. And with a slowing economy on the horizon, the big, undervalued growth stocks in Yacktman's portfolio could well outperform the market again in 1995. "The market is moving in his direction," says Robert Markman, a Minneapolis investment advisor who recently put his clients in Yacktman's fund.  <p> For Yacktman, the comeback is particularly sweet. From 1983 to 1991, as the manager of Selected American Shares, he delivered annualized gains of 18.2 percent, above the 17.2 percent realized by the S&P 500 stock index. But in1992, Yacktman shocked investors and the industry by quitting the fund after a bitter dispute with Kemper Financial Services, the owner of Selected Asset Management. <p> The Yacktman Fund, started in July 1992, got off to a terrible start, dropping 2.17 percent in its first 18 months while the S&P 500 shot up 18.19 percent. "Everything I touched turned to lead," Yacktman says.  <p> Yacktman stubbornly waited for the market to come to him. He kept buying large companies that had earnings of at least $100 million and above-average earnings growth and that also offered good relative value. This approach gave him a portfolio of companies whose collective earnings growth is nearly twice the S&P 500's and whose price-to-earnings ratio is 20 percent below the index. <p> In 1994, as investors started to worry about slowing economic growth, the market shifted away from cyclicals toward Yacktman's kind of stocks: companies that can keep growing earnings even if the economy slows. The fund's largest holdings include <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:SLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11410"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Student Loan Marketing Services</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:BMY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10232"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bristol-Myers Squibb</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:FTL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11960"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fruit of the Loom</b></a>.  <p> "If you buy good, high-return businesses at low prices and have patience, then it will work out," Yacktman says. "The concept is relatively easy, but the execution is not."   <p>  <p>Name: Yacktman Fund <p>Manager: Donald Yacktman <p>Phone: 800-525-8258 <p>Minimum initial investment: $2,500 <p>Load: None <p>1995 return as of 1/19:1.5% <p>1994 return: 8.8%  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
