		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bargains in Print</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Bargains in Print</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>BARGAINS IN PRINT<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>Newspaper stocks are cheap just now. And their value is unrecognized, says Lauren Fine of <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>: The industry has rallied after the recession. On the average, the sector's revenues grew by 7 percent in 1994.<p>Yet investors remained obsessed with falling circulation and rising newsprint rates. Newspaper stocks underperformed the S&P by nearly 9 percent in 1994.<p>But most analysts say higher newsprint prices are always eventually offset by higher ad rates. And it's becoming less and less likely that on-line services will replace newspapers as more and more enter the online world.<p><a name="NYSE:TRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11508"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tribune Co.</b></a> (NYSE: TRB) has a formidable franchise. It owns the Chicago Tribune, the Chicago Cubs, and 14 television and radio stations, and it recently launched a news service, Chicago On-Line. Or consider <a name="NYSE:GCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10623"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gannett Co.</b></a> (NYSE:GCI), which owns USA Today and 134 community papers, 20 radio and television stations, and an outdoor-advertisement display company.<p>In December, Warren Buffett acquired 4.9 percent of Gannett__a move that drew new interest to the newspaper sector. <a name="NASD:AMPC"></a><b> American Publishing </b> (Nasdaq: AMPC), the country's second largest newspaper group, bought the Chicago Sun-Times in March and went public in May. The company is cutting costs, and earnings for 1995 are expected to grow by 12 percent. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
