	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Trendspotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>TRENDSPOTTER<p>By Ellen Simon<p>* The people of cyberspace love Star Trek. For eight weeks Prodigy offered online images from the latest Trek flick, Generations; subscribers downloaded them more than 100,000 times. Compare that with about 10,000 downloads of pictures from the much-hyped hoop-skirts-and-heartbreak TV movie Scarlett. <p>* Cheap stuff and lots of it--that's the retail formula that's working now, according to the U.S. Department of Commerce. Sales at warehouse clubs, the fastest-growing places to shop, were up 221 percent between 1987 and 1992. Discount department-store sales grew 62 percent. The biggest regional surge occurred in eight northwestern and mountain states. The District of Columbia was last nationwide.<p>* As go (or went) Richard Nixon, Jacqueline Onassis, and Oregon, so goes a well-prepared chunk of the nation. Nixon and Jackie had prepared living wills: instructions about what care they wanted and didn't want at the end of their lives. Usually about 100 people call New Yorkbased Choice in Dying each day for information on living wills. In the weeks after Nixon's death, 2,000 called each day; after Jackie's, 3,000. After Oregon voters passed a "death with dignity" act, which permits the terminally ill to obtain prescriptions for lethal drugs, 12,000 people called daily.<p>* It's like love--the harder they try, the less we want them. Credit card companies stuffed mailboxes with a record 1.2 billion solicitations in the first half of 1994, and the recipients threw out a record 98.4 percent of them.<p>* Death-penalty states pay a lot to kill a few. A Duke University study found that one in every ten North Carolina capital cases ends in execution. Adding up the extra trial costs for all capital cases, that means each execution costs taxpayers $2 million. <p>* Now who would pay 35 cents extra per directory-assistance call just to have the phone company dial the number? In the <a name="NYSE:NYN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11044"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nynex</b></a> service area, about 3.5 million callers a month, or 9 percent of all information customers. And the service isn't yet available everywhere in NYNEX's calling area. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry, Banking Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

