	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Catch a Star That Stumbled?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Time to Catch a Star That Stumbled?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Catch a Star That Stumbled?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>TIME TO CATCH A STAR THAT STUMBLED?<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>"We're having a lousy year," acknowledged Earl McEvoy, lead manager of the $6 billion <a name="FUND:VWINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard/Wellesley Income Fund</b></a>, in late December. At the time, the fund was down 4.3 percent since the beginning of the year. "This is the worst kind of environment for us," McEvoy said. Fund comanager John Ryan was equally blunt: "With rising interest rates and rising inflation, the fund is relatively disadvantaged." <p>Mutual fund managers normally aren't so quick to admit to subpar performance. But McEvoy and Ryan know they have nothing to be ashamed of. Over the last ten years, their fund, which invests in a mix of bonds and equities, has averaged an annual return of 12.3 percent. It has done so with far less volatility than the average bond or stock. Also, 1994 was just the second time in 20 years that the fund posted a loss. The decline occurred mostly because the fund was heavily invested in bonds with long maturities. As interest rates rose, the underlying value of these bonds declined, creating principal losses.<p>Nevertheless, the two managers believe 1995 could be a rebound year for their fund. "When newspapers are filled with stories about the threat of inflation and when there seems to be no end to economic expansion, that's when this fund will be a good choice," said Ryan.<p>Once long-term interest rates flatten or even decline, these same long bonds will appreciate while continuing to provide high yields. Pressed for a forecast, McEvoy said the 30-year Treasury is likely to close 1995 at 7.85 percent. That would help put Wellesley Income back on track with a total return of 8 or 9 percent. <p>If the economy contracts and corporate profits slow, as Ryan and McEvoy expect, the stock market will slump. But the stocks that this fund buys for the 30 to 40 percent of the portfolio it keeps in equities tend to drop less than the broad averages because of their high dividends. A value investor, Ryan, who runs the stock part of the portfolio, looks to buy dividend growth on the cheap by snapping up out-of-favor blue chips. Right now, the average yield on the fund's stocks is 5.5 percent, and he expects dividends to grow 7 percent annually. <p>Said Ryan, "We're laying the foundation for that future period where our style comes into play."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
