	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Listening to Sweet Seoul Music</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Listening to Sweet Seoul Music</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>LISTENING TO SWEET SEOUL MUSIC<p>By Gary Hector<p>Sequels are rarely as good as the originals, but South Korea could be the exception. South Korea was the bright spot for investors in Asia last year. In dollar terms, stocks rose some 20 percent in 1994 as corporate profits soared more than 40 percent. With reduced political tension taking the worry out of the market, continued growth is likely to push the market even higher in 1995. And the government's tight control on capital flows could keep the market from being battered if the U.S. Fed hikes rates in 1995.<p>Exports drive South Korea's growth. With a boost from the transcendently expensive yen, South Korea's muscular chaebols, the country's industrial conglomerates, are picking up business from high-priced Japanese competitors throughout Asia, especially in China. South Korea's export sector, in turn, drives construction and equipment spending at home, as exporters modernize to offset rising labor costs. All told, GDP is likely to grow 7.5 to 8 percent this year, and corporate profits should climb 17 percent. <p>Despite the recent downing of a U.S. helicopter across the North Korean border, political risks have declined over the last six months. North Korea, eager for American aid to shore up its ancient, inefficient economy, has agreed to scale back nuclear plans--a major source of international tension.<p>Investors have several options. The best bet is the 11-year-old <a name="NYSE:KF"></a><b>Korea Fund</b> (NYSE: KF), a closed-end mutual fund heavily invested in South Korean blue chips. While the fund once sold for a stiff 150 percent premium to its net asset value, it recently traded at $23.38, slightly above its net asset value of $21.09. The fund approached the end of '94 down some 1.5 percent. Two other closed-end funds, the <a name="NYSE:KIF"></a><b>Korean Investment Fund</b> (NYSE: KIF) and <a name="NYSE:KEF"></a><b>Korea Equity Fund</b> (NYSE: KEF), date back only to 1992 and 1993, respectively. (The <a name="FUND:MAPTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MAPTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Matthews Korean Fund</b></a>, the first open-end South Korea fund, has an even shorter track record--it opened in January 1995. It is managed by Paul Matthews, former president of G.T. Capital Holdings.)<p>Players can also invest directly in major companies. The <a name="NYSE:KEP"></a><b>Korean Electric Power Corp.</b> (NYSE: KEP), the nation's biggest power producer, should benefit from the booming domestic economy. Pohang Iron & Steel (NYSE: PKX), a large, efficient steel producer, should get a boost from both domestic and export growth.<p>
Name: <a name="FUND:VWINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard/Wellesley Income</b></a>
Manager: Comanaged by Earl McEvoy and John Ryan
Phone: 800-662-7447
Minimum initial investment: $3,000
Load: None
1994 return as of 12/19: -5.4%
1993 return: 14.65%<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
