<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-February Tip Sheet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>February Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-February Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>FEBRUARY TIP SHEET<p>* TAKE A LOAD OFF: Putnam Investments has launched what may be a trend-setting fee plan for 15 of its funds--Class M shares, which carry lower front-end loads (up to 40 percent lower than regular shares) and tie brokers' fees to performance. Putnam will extend the new pricing option to all its funds in 1995, says senior vice president Chris Meyer, who brags of putting brokers "on the investor's side of the table." Don't cheer yet: Putnam will raise trailing fees to offset these cuts. The annual bite on Class M shares is 0.65 percent of assets for equity funds and 0.4 percent for bond funds. That's up from 0.25 percent on regular shares. "They're shuffling fees so investors think they're getting a deal," says Don Phillips, publisher of Morningstar. In fact, Class M shares favor short-term investors; in the first year, a stock-fund buyer saves nearly two points. If you have a horizon of more than five years, however, the regular front-end load will be a better deal.<p>* FOR GREENSPAN WATCHERS: One bond-fund category was spared from last year's slaughter--loan-participation funds, also know as prime-rate funds. Since they invest in high-quality bank loans whose rates track the Fed's moves, such funds weren't hammered by rising interest rates. They returned an average 5.92 percent through November, according to Lipper Analytical Services. Getting into a prime-rate fund--smart if you're skittish about interest rates--takes timing. Most offer shares only via quarterly tender offers. Most also levy a fee on investors who cash out after less than a year. The names: Eaton Vance Prime Rate Reserve, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> Senior Floating Rate Fund, Van Kampen Merritt Prime Rate Income Trust, Prime Income Trust, and Pilgrim Prime Rate Trust.<p>* HAZARD PAY: Global investors who can tolerate risk should look at Venezuela. Once-solid Caracas has been a basket case since two attempted coups in 1992. Hopes for a recovery were dashed in 1994 when President Rafael Caldera instituted state controls on banks and foreign exchange. Investors have fled, waiting for Caldera to see the light. But investors who want to play the turnaround shouldn't wait for this to happen--Venezuela is almost certain to roar back so fast that no one will be able to jump on board once the train is moving. "It's like Peru in 1992, when nobody would invest a dollar," says Jose Gonzales of Credit Lyonnais. "Whoever got in then made major profits a few months later." Want to gamble? Venezuela's Brady bonds sell at 50 cents on the dollar, but potential investors will need the help of a private banker. A few closed-end mutual funds have decent exposure to the country; check out Alliance World Dollar Government I and II, Latin America Dollar Income, <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> Emerging Markets Debt, Morgan Stanley Global Opportunity Bond, and Worldwide Dollarvest. And six Venezuelan stocks are available to U.S. investors as ADRs.<p>* CLEAN AIR COSTS: Now's the time to buy lawn mowers, outboard engines, and other motor-driven gizmos. Because of new environmental rules, upcoming models will have lower emissions but higher prices--perhaps 30 percent higher, say some boat-engine makers. The Environmental Protection Agency says the hike should be 15 percent, but that's still $750 on a $5,000 outboard.<p>* DON'T GET TAKEN FOR A RIDE: Beware the economics of auto leasing, warns consumer crusader Ralph Nader. Although many people grasp the basic buy-or-lease calculation, he says, few protest leasing fees that can add over $1,000 to the price of a car. The problem: Dealers don't do the leasing--they sell cars to a finance company that leases them to customers. But, Nader says, dealers often charge leasing companies a cushy 15 percent over the sticker price, a rip-off that's passed along to lessees. Along with the Consumer Task Force for Automotive Issues, he's developed a "reality checklist" for consumers to assess the deals they're offered. Write Checklist, P.O. Box 7648, Atlanta, GA 30357, for a free copy.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Internatonal Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
