		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Cheap is Relative</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Cheap is Relative</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> CHEAP IS RELATIVE   <p> By Jim Jubak  <p> Without doubt the stock market was cheaper at the end of 1994 than it was when the year began. Only the Dow, the narrowest of the major stock indexes, eked out a gain, 1.6 percent. But the question is, could equities get cheaper still?   <p> The most popular measure of whether stocks are cheap or dear is price-to-earnings ratios. These have been falling all year, thanks to strong corporate profits produced by a hot economy. Earnings on the S & P 500 surged from $20.42 at the end of 1993 to $27.33 by December 16, an increase of 34 percent. As earnings rise and stocks stand still, p/e's decline.  <p> Such was the case for both large- and small-capitalization stocks, according to numbers run by Frank Russell Co. From year-end '93 through November '94, price-to-earnings ratios of large stocks fell from 19.6 to 15.8; for small stocks, ratios dropped from 24.2 to 19.4.  <p> Lower ratios signal a cheaper market, but they don't necessarily mean the market is cheap. So says Rolf Agather, product manager for the Russell indexes. Investors instead must juxtapose current p/e ratios with historic valuations. Such a comparison shows that while the market as a whole is fairly inexpensive, growth stocks, the current darlings of the Street, are not.  <p> Russell compared valuations at the end of November--the month prior to the market's year-end rally, when prices were lowest--with average valuations of the past eight years. In November both large- and small-cap stocks overall traded below their average past valuations. For large-cap stocks, this hadn't occurred since1991.  <p> But large- and small-cap growth stocks are another story. The market normally charges a premium for growth, but the premium in November exceeded the historic average, Russell calculated. It was richest for small-cap growth stocks: The p/e ratio premium on small growth stocks reached 27 percent last year, far above the average 16 percent premium of the past.   <p> Message: Joining in the current mania for growth is more expensive--and riskier--than it looks.  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

