	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Best Investments for ‘95</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Best Investments for ‘95</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Best Investments for ‘95</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> BEST INVESTMENT FOR '95  <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> The year just ended was the worst on record for investors in long-maturity bonds--the worst, that is, since 1948. That's as ancient as data compiled by Richard Suttmeier gets. He's the yield curve strategist at Smith Barney in New York. If you bought 30-year Treasurys at the beginning of the year, you lost 13 percent by year end. That decline is double the next two worst performances over the past 46 years, which took place in 1973 and 1987. During both times, long bonds fell roughly 7.3 percent.   <p> Note that those declines immediately preceded horrific markets in stocks. Will 1994's bear market in bonds prove to be yet another precursor to stock market blues? Nobody knows. You can certainly make a very good case for moving money out of stocks and into Treasurys with one- to three-year maturities paying better than 7.5 percent.   <p> That's exactly what many small investors did at the end of the year. During the late-December auction of $17.25 billion in two-year notes, the noncompetitive bid for those notes--an indicator of small-investor participation--amounted to $2.4 billion. That demand--almost 14 percent of the auction--was the largest since January 1984. Says Suttmeier: "The small investor sees value in the short-term maturities with yields of 7 to 7.75 percent." <p> Investors know a good thing when they see one. The question is, are Treasurys the right place to be in '95? Absolutely, says Suttmeier, who believes real rates of return of 3 to 3.5 percent are mighty compelling. He thinks yields will drop significantly this year, and projects the long bond to trade between 6.5 and 7 percent by the end of 1995. Suttmeier goes out on this limb: "The top-performing asset in 1995 will be Treasurys. They will outperform if rates decline and will perform less badly than any other asset if rates go up." The risk, meanwhile, is minimal. <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
