	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>TREND SPOTTER<p>By Carla Koehl<p>-> If industry forecasts can be trusted, revenues for all computer magazines will soar from $1.8 billion last year to $5 billion in 2000 and $8.1 billion by 2005. "There is a lot of money in demystifying computers," says Arthur Gruen of New York-based Wilkofsky Gruen Associates, the authors of the study.<p>-> National sales of hair-color products have risen by a steady 8 percent since 1984. From 1992 to 1993, though, sales jumped 10 percent, and in 1994 they're up 12 percent. In ten years, coloring products are expected to account for half of all salon sales. Why? "Baby boomers are finally going gray," says Mary Atherton of Modern Salon magazine. "We've waited years for this."<p>-> Two years ago the National Committee for Quality Assurance of Washington, D.C., unleashed its clipboard-wielding inspectors on America's 541 HMOs. Just 30 percent of the 133 HMOs inspected so far have met NCQA's 50 standards in areas ranging from consistency in record-keeping to encouraging preventive testing to sniffing out old malpractice suits involving prospective physicians. <p>-> Bitter over missing the chance to buy Manhattan for $24? The Mineral Policy Center of Washington, D.C., says the U.S. government is now selling $34 billion worth of mining rights on public lands to mining firms -- for the bargain price of $800,000.<p>-> Barbara Levy, an editor at Footwear News, proclaims, "Women's shoes are ten times more comfortable now than they were a decade ago." A recent study for the American Podiatric Medical Association, however, finds exactly the same percentage of women complain of painful shoes as did ten years ago.<p>-> Crime has been on the decline since 1981. But the cost of it -- losses from theft, damage, medical costs, and lost pay -- is up 38 percent, says the U.S. Justice Department.<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
