	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Stalking Category Killers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Stalking Category Killers</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Stalking Category Killers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>STALKING CATEGORY KILLERS
Take care that your superstore investment isn't battling in an overpopulated niche.<p>By Ellen Simon<p>Category killers, stores that sell everything in a specific niche -- be it bedding, babies, or home improvements -- have been one of the hottest concepts in retailing. Investors who got in early on <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a> or <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a> carted home bags of goodies. And the beat goes on. <a name="NASD:BSST"></a><b>Baby Superstore Inc.</b>, a late-September offering slated to sell for $15 to $18 a share, was expected to be a hot IPO in a cool market. <p>But while crowded stores are great, overpopulated niches are not. A category may be big enough for one killer, but investors in others could end up dead. "`There seem to be one or two winners" per niche, says Steven Kernkraut, retail analyst at <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear, Stearns</b></a>. "The rest eventually seem to fail."<p>Winners know how to cater to their customers. For instance, male shoppers seem overwhelmed by the too-huge selection at Today's Man clothing stores, contributing to the company's rocky bottom line. Competitor the Men's Wearhouse has fewer racks, more manageable stores, and consistent 30 percent earnings growth in recent years. Home Depot simply has a much better assortment than the competition, says N. Richard Nelson, analyst at Duff & Phelps. The prospects for Baby Superstore? Too early to tell. Stick with the old standbys, says Nelson: Home Depot, Toys "R" Us, and Sports Authority. "From an investment standpoint, it's still really early in their growth cycle."<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
