<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-On the Record</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>On the Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-On the Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>ON THE RECORD
Here's what experts think could shake up the market.<p>We asked six market professionals: What event would be most likely to rock stocks in coming months? We also asked for an overall market outlook and a rating of their sentiment from 1 to 5, with 5 the most bullish.<p><p>LOUIS NAVELLIER, MPT REVIEW, INCLINE VILLAGE, NEVADA: "The bottom line is, if interest rates go up another percentage point, it will probably take 12 to 15 percent out of the market. Earnings growth could counterbalance some of that, but the stock market could be very vulnerable." <p>Market Rating: 3<p><p>DAN SULLIVAN, THE CHARTIST, SEAL BEACH, CALIFORNIA: "An unexpected rise in the discount rate would really spook the market. The Fed has been raising it about a half percent at a time, and the Fed Funds rate is three quarters of a percent above the discount rate, so we're due for another raise. If they raise it one percent instead of one-half, the market could go down a couple hundred points."<p>Market Rating: 1<p><p>JAMES STACK, INVESTECH RESEARCH, WHITEFISH, MONTANA: "Any factors that confirm a stronger-than-forecasted economy will have a negative impact on the market as investors realize that more interest-rate hikes lie ahead. Most critical will be consumer confidence and capacity utilization, which is bumping against a 14-year high."<p>Market Rating: 1<p><p>GERALD APPEL, SYSTEMS AND FORECASTS, GREAT NECK, NEW YORK: "Treasury-bill yields getting to be twice the dividend payout of the S&P 500 would constitute a serious sell signal. The current T-bill-to-dividend ratio [90-day bill yields divided by the S&P dividend payout] is about 1.7; it would have to get above 2.1 to become bearish. This has been an excellent predictor of bear markets since 1969."<p>Market Rating: 2<p><p>ROBERT BOWKER, THE BUSINESS CYCLE MONITOR, DALLAS: "If economic growth figures are significantly strong so that Greenspan will be forced to raise short-term interest rates above 5 percent, pushing long-term rates over 8 percent, the stock market, which is already overvalued, must fall."<p>Market Rating: 2<p><p>MARIEL CLEMENSEN, CLEMENSEN CAPITAL ACCESS, NEW YORK CITY: "The Federal Reserve relies on movement in gold prices to set interest rates. Therefore, a breakout in gold through the psychologically important $400-an-ounce level may presage a correction in the stock market as interest rates adjust upward. But the correction should be short-lived as the stock market decouples from the bond market and focuses on strong earnings growth in the economy rather than interest-rate levels." <p>Market Rating: 3<p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
