<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-November Tip Sheet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>November Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-November Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>NOVEMBER TIP SHEET<p>-> SPLITSVILLE: Some high-priced stocks may soon be the best deals on the Street. Sixty or so companies listed on the NYSE are poised to split shares in the next 6 to 12 months, according to the Standard & Poor's newsletter Outlook. A company's decision to split shares is usually a thumbs up for investors, with healthier dividends and a positive earnings report often accompanying the split. Whom to watch for a split soon? The following candidates carry a buy ranking from S&P's analysts: <a name="NYSE:AIG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10095"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American International Group</b></a> (AIG), recently $90 a share; <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler Corp.</b></a> (C), recently $44; <a name="NYSE:CB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10335"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chubb Corp.</b></a> (CB), recently $70; and <a name="NYSE:NWS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41816"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>News Corp.</b></a> (NWS), recently $49.<p>-> TAXING NEWS FOR MUNI INVESTORS: Recent changes in federal income-tax laws have taken a little bit of the appeal out of municipal bonds for anyone above the 28 percent tax bracket. Those same investors buying municipal-bond funds will feel the pinch as well. On 1994 tax returns, any appreciation of the principal value on munis bought at a discount to par value on or after May 1, 1993, will now be taxed as ordinary income, as with ordinary bonds. (This tax applies to the difference between the discounted purchase price of the bond and the bond's par value.) Those higher taxes will, of course, lower effective yields. Before the change, if a bond with a face value of $10,000 was bought for $9,200, the $800 appreciation was taxed as a capital gain, at the capital-gains rate of 28 percent. Now that gain is taxed as ordinary income, at up to 39.6 percent. <p>-> IS THE END NEAR FOR IRA FEES? <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> started offering no-fee IRAs in the spring of '92 for anyone with an account value of $10,000. Since then, IRA fee schedules have been adjusted across the industry -- though the terms are rarely simple. Prudential started waiving its $35 per IRA fee last March for anyone who has had a fund for at least a year and contributed to it in the last year or who has Prudential mutual funds in the IRA. For top clients, Smith Barney waives its $40 annual custodial fee on IRAs if their household average commission on their Smith Barney accounts is $100 per account per year. Fidelity charges $10 for each mutual fund in an IRA if the balance in each fund is less than $5,000. There's no charge for funds with a balance greater than $5,000, and a maximum charge of $60. Dreyfus charges $10 for each IRA, with a maximum total of $25 per customer. <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> doesn't offer no-fee IRAs, but it periodically reviews the issue. If Merrill follows the competition, a fee-free future can't be far off. <p>-> WHERE THE MONEY COMES FROM: Have you wondered why the interest banks pay on savings accounts and CDs hasn't gone up faster, given the Fed's five hikes in short-term rates (totaling 175 basis points) this year? It's because banks aren't terribly interested in your dough -- they can get money cheaper somewhere else. As the economy expands and loan demand increases, banks typically raise capital by luring new deposits. This time, they're moving away from consumer deposits toward riskier, uninsured, but less costly borrowing. "A bank can borrow from the wholesale market and save a lot more money than if it raised deposit [interest] rates above current levels," said Tom Brown, a banking analyst with brokerage Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing, Retirement Investing, Bond Investing, Banking Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
