		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>
MARKET RADAR
A monthly look at the outlook as told by our eight market indicators.<p>
Our technical indicators have suddenly headed south again, while fundamental measures remain fairly stable. The message for equity investors: There's sentiment for a correction. As usual, we give each indicator a rating (10 is most bullish).<p>
BEARISH: INVESTOR SENTIMENT (2 this month/2 last month). Fidelity Investments says small-investor enthusiasm for stocks is inching closer to its all-time high -- a bearish sign, since small investors often get excited at market peaks.<p>
BEARISH: COMPOSITE BELLWETHER (2/3). Last month's upturn had raised the prospect of a bullish move for this index, which tracks the movement of utility and brokerage stocks, historical predictors of market turns. Falling utilities have trashed that hope, says InvesTech, which computes the index.<p>
BEARISH: ADVANCE/DECLINE LINE (2/3). A moving average of the difference between the number of rising and falling stocks, computed by InvesTech. This indicator is now flashing a classic bearish signal.<p>
NEUTRAL: PUT/CALL RATIO (4/5). Based on the volume of put and call options traded on the Chicago Board of Options Exchange, this indicator swung sharply negative but then bounced back slightly. A mixed signal.<p>
NEUTRAL: COMMODITY INDEX (4/3). Supplied by Goldman, Sachs, this measure of raw-materials prices has gotten a bit sunnier, but mostly because the Nigerian oil crisis was resolved. Other prices remain on an upward trend.<p>
NEUTRAL: YIELD DIFFERENTIAL: (5/5). Comparison between yields of 90-day Treasury bills and the Standard & Poor's 500, computed by the Leuthold Group. Fairly steady, but T bills still look a bit more attractive than stocks.<p>
NEUTRAL: CONSUMER AND CORPORATE DEBT: (6/6). This aggregate measure of private debt continues to edge upward, but still not enough to be called a negative signal. Provided by Safian Investment Research.<p>
BEARISH: MONETARY ENVIRONMENT: (3/3). This model from InvesTech measures how much money is available to flow into the stock market. It remains steadily bearish and shows little likelihood of moving into bullish territory by the end of the year. <p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Stock Investing, Bond Investing, Economy, Mutual Funds Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
