		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Drought Warning</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Drought Warning</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Drought Warning</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>DROUGHT WARNING
Is the world's supply of cash drying up?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Maybe the world is running out of money. While almost everyone on Wall Street is worrying about too much growth setting off inflation, a few analysts have started to worry about the world's supply of cash, knowing that a liquidity crisis would send interest rates up and markets tumbling. Sound far-fetched? Consider that those worrying about liquidity don't belong to a single Wall Street camp and are finding their evidence in very different sets of numbers.<p>David Shulman, chief equity strategist at Salomon Brothers, takes the macroeconomic view. Early in the current economic cycle, Shulman says, when business activity was slow and loan demand weak, the economy had excess cash: "There was a lot of liquidity, and most of it was going into the financial markets." Now that the economy has picked up, Shulman says, "it's Main Street's turn" to need money for inventories and capital equipment. That puts the productive sector in competition with the financial markets for cash.<p>Analysts who watch the domestic money-supply numbers have come to a similar conclusion. Recently M1 and M2, two measures of the amount of money in circulation, have shown slower growth. Over the last 12 months, M1 has grown at an annual rate of 5.1 percent; during the last 3 months the annualized rate is just 3.5 percent. "From an investment standpoint, it would be a lot better if M1 weren't slowing down," says James Stack, president of InvesTech Research in Whitefish, Montana.<p>And finally, Wall Street has started to worry that higher interest rates on CDs will draw money out of the stock and bond markets. After looking at the last 20 years, Katherine Hensel, chief investment strategist at Lehman Brothers, recently concluded that the rate on short-term CDs would have to climb another 2 percentage points before individuals would completely stop putting money into stocks. Of course, that implies that some investors have already found CDs an attractive alternative.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Bond Investing, Banking Industry, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
