		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Buying a Better CD</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Buying a Better CD</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Buying a Better CD</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994-
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>BUYING A BETTER CD
Consider shopping at a brokerage instead of a bank.<p>By Deborah Pont<p>Why would anyone buy a simple financial product like a CD from a brokerage house? That's what banks are for, aren't they? Don't brokerages charge commissions for everything and require big minimums?<p>All good questions, but investors still ought to consider brokerage CDs. For one thing, brokerage-offered CDs yield 1 to 1.5 percentage points more than CDs from leading banks. And for another, brokers sell CDs without commission with minimums that range from $1,000 to $10,000.<p>Here are two examples: In September, branches of <a name="NASD:CHFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12961"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chemical Bank</b></a> offered a one-year CD yielding 3.9 percent. At the same time, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> offered a Chemical one-year CD at 5.4 percent. A Bank of New York CD yielding 4.3 percent at branches yielded 5.35 percent through Merrill. <p>But front-end gains aren't the only reason to look to a broker. Brokers can often resell CDs before their term -- an important option if rates climb sharply.<p>Pay close attention to the yields on brokerage CDs: Premiums often reduce the coupon. For example, Smith Barney's true yield on a six-month 7.65 coupon is 4.90 percent -- still okay when banks average 3.83. <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Banking Industry, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:CHFC">Chemical Financial Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
