		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Bag Global Profits at Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bag Global Profits at Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Bag Global Profits at Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>BAG GLOBAL PROFITS AT HOME<p>By Jim Jubak<p>The recovery that the U.S. economy has been enjoying for the past 22 months is finally beginning to spread to the rest of the world -- as most economists said it would. But next year may turn out quite differently than these same economists expect.<p>In 1993, U.S. real growth of 3 percent far outstripped the rest of the developed world's. That year the U.K. grew 1.9 percent, Japan broke even, and Germany fell 1.2 percent.<p>Forecasts for 1994 show our economy in overdrive -- 3.8 percent real growth -- with the rest of the world playing catch-up. Germany should grow by 2.8 percent, the U.K. 3.0 percent, Japan 0.9 percent.<p>That sets the scene for 1995, the year the U.S. is supposed to slow down and be overtaken by the countries following in the recovery cycle. Things may not happen that way. Estimates have U.S. growth slowing to 2.6 percent, but the rest of the developed world doesn't look as if it's set to zoom ahead. German growth should stay at 2.8 percent, U.K. growth will likely drop to 2.7 percent, and Japan should inch up to 1 percent.<p>Why no surge? David Munro, chief U.S. economist at High Frequency Economics in New York, explains that European economies have natural growth rates about 1 percentage point lower than the U.S.'s long-term growth potential of 2.5 percent. "Europe tends to run into inflation before we do [in its growth cycle]," he says. Low birth rates and aging population help keep its growth modest too.<p>But investors can still play the European recovery. So says Jeffrey Applegate, chief investment strategist for CS First Boston. Corporate profits have been growing faster than their historic trend line in the U.S. and lagging in Europe. As U.S. growth slows, he's projecting only a 5 percent bump in domestic profits in 1995, but a 20 percent rise in profits overseas. U.S. multinationals with strong European sales could get a nice boost just as the U.S. economy begins to level off.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Economy, International Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
