	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Bad News for Telemarketers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bad News for Telemerketers</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Bad News for Telemarketers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>BAD NEWS FOR TELEMARKETERS<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Pencil sets. Penny stocks. Swampland in Florida. Fraudulent telemarketers hawk everything imaginable. And until now, the minute they sniffed legal trouble, they had only to flee the state, set up shop, and start all over again. But a new law, enacted August 16, makes scheming telemarketers a federal concern--and could save investors more than $10 billion a year. <p>The Telemarketing and Consumer Fraud and Abuse Prevention Act gives state attorneys general the right to ask federal courts to seize the assets of telemarketing-fraud suspects, then chase them across state lines. "These boiler rooms are built to move," says Scott Cooper, legislative aide on the House transportation subcommittee, where the bill originated. "They use rented phones, rented coffee machines, rented people. By the time attorney generals can go looking, they're already gone."<p>The principal federal agency charged with carrying out the law, the Federal Trade Commission, has until August 1995 to decide on the specific rules it will develop to prohibit such practices. The Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodities and Futures Trading Commission will have six months after that to add their own rules. The North American Securities Association estimates one quarter of the $40 billion that consumers lose each year in fraudulent telemarketing schemes involves phony investment ploys.<p>John Barker, director of the National Fraud Information Center, praises the law but adds, "There's an easier way, of course: Don't go shopping--or investing--on the phone."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
