	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-A Change of Strategy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Change of Strategy</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-A Change of Strategy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994-Worth Magazine
Worth magazine/Need To Know<p>A CHANGE OF STRATEGY
Want to reach your short-term goals?  Then don't buy stocks or equity mutual funds.<p>By John Koten<p>Are you saving for a second home? Your children's education? Or a retirement that's only a few years away?<p>Then don't try to do it by buying stocks -- or, for that matter, by buying mutual funds that invest in stocks. If your goals are short-range, stay out of the market. Buy Treasury bonds or CDs instead.<p>Strong advice? Yes, indeed. And it may just turn out to be wrong.<p>No one can ever say for sure what stocks will do next. There's certainly a chance that short-termers who plunge into equities now will be laughing at us skittish types a year -- or even a few months -- hence. They'll be camping out in their new beach houses; we'll still be sleeping in our tents.<p>At the moment, though, the odds appear stacked in the opposite direction. Our Market Radar feature (see "Market Radar Shows Bearish Signs" further down in this file) tells part of the story: Stocks are overvalued in comparison with their historic levels. Concerns about liquidity, inflation, the dollar, and trade talks also have placed the market on precarious footing of late.<p>At the same time, the rises in interest rates have made fixed-income investments a more attractive option. Short-term investors can now earn returns on bonds and CDs that are extremely competitive with anything they might hope to get from stocks. Better still, the risks associated with these investments are much lower.<p>We're so convinced about the importance of this change in the investment climate that we've dropped short-term ratings from our mutual fund listings this year. As far as we are concerned, no equity fund offers enough promise to justify its near-term risk.<p>None of this, of course, applies to investors with more distant horizons. In the long run, the only way to be assured of getting the higher returns that stocks offer is to remain invested at all times. Nothing about this has changed.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing, Bond Investing, Investing Strtaegies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
