		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-The Whining CEO</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Whining CEO</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-The Whining CEO</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Ocotber 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>THE WHINING CEO
Be wary if a company's chief is denouncing the Fed.<p>By John Koten<p>If you own stocks, this is a good time to pay attention to what your companies are saying about rising interest rates. Is the chief executive angrily denouncing the Federal Reserve Board or demanding Alan Greenspan's scalp? If so, there's reason to be wary as an investor.<p>This isn't to say that some amount of executive-suite disappointment isn't in order. After five straight interest-rate hikes this year, economic growth is certainly bound to slow down. What's more, given the nation's increasingly tight industrial capacity, some companies out there must have been looking forward to making some easy money. There's nothing like reduced competition when it comes to enhancing the bottom line.<p>This, of course, is exactly what the Fed has been trying to avoid -- unearned price increases that lead to inflation. In raising rates, its message to business is this: You can earn more money only if you improve productivity and invest in new capacity. Tough medicine, yes, but it's also fair.<p>In this way, you might say the Fed is practicing its own brand of supply-side economics. Yet whereas Ronald Reagan offered up a carrot in the form of lower tax rates, the Fed is brandishing a stick in the form of higher interest rates. This time, industry must either respond or get clobbered.<p>The companies that will do well in this environment are those that can cut costs, raise productivity, and build modern new factories. Industries that help manufacturers achieve these goals -- such as the suppliers of computers and other labor-saving devices -- should benefit as well.<p>Of course, higher interest rates also can make the cost of capital improvements prohibitive for marginal outfits. If your company's CEO is wailing on about the evil Fed, you might want to make sure that's not the real reason.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Employment, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

