		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>TREND SPOTTER<p>By Carla Koehl<p>-> Not since 1982 has the Federal Reserve ordered the U.S. Mint to make such a big chunk of change: 19 billion new coins for 1994. That's 25 percent more than the average made over the past 11 years. "You have to mint more coins when the economy's better," says Mint spokesman Michael White. "There's more business out there this year. And a whole lot more next year."<p>-> At last count, women in the workforce with children under age six numbered 9.6 million. The estimated number of spaces at licensed child-care centers? Just 4.2 million, says the National Association for the Education of Young Children.<p>-> National Park Service rangers counted up 28 percent more backcountry overnight stays in the first half of 1994 than for the same period last year. That's more campers than the parks have seen since 1983. "It's pretty damn many is what it is," gruffs Ken Hornback, NPS chief of socioeconomic studies. Hornback chalks up the rise to rampant consumer optimism. "Must be," he says. " 'Cause the weather's been awful."<p>-> Given the choice between figuring taxes and killing Nazis on computer screens, America is choosing Nazis. Says PC Data of Reston, Virginia, 11.8 million software games were sold last year, compared with 4.2 million personal-finance packages.<p>-> From the "It May Mean Nothing, but..." Department: A NYSE seat sold in June 1994 for $830,000. The last time the price of a seat was in that neighborhood (on its way up in value, that is) was April 1987, when it hit $850,000. In September of that year a seat went for $1.1 million. A month later came Black Monday.<p>-> Alarm systems now protect 10 million American homes. That's great for alarm owners, who'll save $500 million this year by fending off would-be burglars. The rest of us, though, will blow $700 million paying police to answer bogus alarms, says Lee Jones, president of Support Services Group in San Clemente, California. In 1995, 20 percent more homes will be armed -- and you can count on 20 percent more false alarms. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Government Adgency, Taxation, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

