		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Is Steel a Deal?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is Steel a Deal?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Is Steel a Deal?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>IS STEEL A DEAL?
These are the best of times for big steel. And that's what worries investors, who know this industry has a history of squandering good fortune. <p>By Ellen Simon<p>It's hard to imagine a better scenario. The bitter cuts that big, integrated steel makers made in the '70s and '80s, reducing manufacturing capacity by one third, are paying off. Now, thanks to heavy demand for consumer durables such as appliances and cars, steel makers can dictate price hikes. A weak dollar has kept offshore competitors from undercutting domestic steel makers' prices. A revitalized U.S. auto industry has provided steady contract work. Good times are even letting big steel adequately fund pensions for the workers it laid off way back when. <a name="NYSE:BS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10210"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bethlehem</b></a>, for instance, used its $355 million spring stock issue to fund pensions. <p>But steel is exactly the kind of cyclical industry that worries some analysts. Hard times lie ahead, many say. Karlis M. Kirsis of New York's World Steel Dynamics is looking for the steel market to rise over the next two years but thinks a "death spiral" will hit in the late '90s. "Those companies that have not vigorously attacked their cost structures between now and then will find themselves in great distress," he says. New competition looms: Five new plants coming on line will give low-cost mini mills the capacity to capture 25 percent of the flat-sheet steel business, a bread-and-butter segment for the biggies. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
