<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Time to Sift Through the Rubble</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Time to Sift Through the Rubble</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Time to Sift Through the Rubble</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>IT'S TIME TO SIFT THROUGH THE RUBBLE<p>By Gregory Millman<p><a name="NYSE:HTT"></a><b>Hyperion 1999 Term Trust</b> was last year's frog, but it may be this year's prince. The trust, which dropped in price from $10 a share in January 1993 to $6.88 a year later, is now a bargain-priced way to profit from rising interest rates.<p>The term trust is a species of closed-end mutual funds. Managers sell shares in the trust, then use the money to buy assets. Shares trade like stocks and pay dividends. At a pre-established time (hence term trust) management liquidates the assets and distributes them.<p>Few investments got hammered harder by falling interest rates last year than Hyperion 1999 (NYSE: HTT). Betting that interest rates would rise, the fund's managers put 30 percent of capital into derivatives called IOs. (These are created by breaking up the stream of payments from a mortgage. The term stands for interest only.) IOs gain in value as interest rates rise and lose value when interest rates fall.<p>In 1992 and 1993, interest rates fell and Hyperion took a beating. Over the past year, as rates have risen, IOs have performed well; the trust's net asset value increased by 9.4 percent in the first seven months of 1994.<p>But the share price has not reflected the improvement. At $7, shares trade at a discount of about 9.1 percent to NAV. Analysts figure the trust could return as much as 13.1 percent annually by the time investors get their 1999 distribution. The downside return, they calculate, is 6.73 percent annually -- roughly the current yield on a three-year treasury note. As for the distribution, management remains committed to returning the $10 a share original investors paid in 1992. Analysts think that's extremely unlikely, but investors have a good chance at getting a distribution of more than the current share price.<p>Of course, Wall Street bargains come with risks. The fund manager and its original underwriters face a possible class-action lawsuit for last year's debacles. And if rates go down again before 1999, Hyperion will once again head south fast. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
