<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-The Return of the CD</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Return of the CD</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-The Return of the CD</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>the return of the cd<p>By Deborah Pont and Jim Jubak<p>It's not a flood yet, but money is starting to flow back into those small-denomination time accounts known as certificates of deposit. According to the Federal Reserve, the amount of money held in CDs rose from $769.1 billion in May to $770.4 billion in June. In July, the sum crept up to $772.5 billion. Those levels are still far below last year's (the total in May 1993 was $832.4 billion), but the turnaround in CD deposits is certainly significant. Higher interest rates are the driving force. In July, Southern Pacific Thrift and Loan in southern California offered 5.13 percent on a six-month CD. In August, the rate hit 5.44 percent.<p>The recent move in CD rates has raised yields to levels at or above those paid by Treasury bills with comparable terms. On August 19, one-year T bills were paying 5.63 percent. Top rates on one-year CDs ranged from 5.5 to 5.8 percent. "When rates were going up in February, the Treasury bill and note were higher than even the top CD rate in the market, which was historically an aberration," says Norbert Mehl, president of MasterFund/BanxQuote, a firm that tracks national interest rates. <p>How far will CD rates climb? James Fry, the chief financial officer of Southern Pacific, says increases in CD rates could outpace the Fed's efforts to push interest rates higher -- assuming loan demand improves.<p>Another factor that could drive CD yields higher: "The banks will see an enormous opportunity to recapture funds that have fled to mutual funds," says Mehl. If that's the case, count on aggressive hikes in CD rates in October, a traditional time to launch marketing campaigns.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

