	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-How Rate Hikes Hit Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>How Rate Hikes Hit Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-How Rate Hikes Hit Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>HOW RATE HIKES HIT HOME
When credit tightens, younger consumers may feel the pinch.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Higher interest rates will slow the economy. That, of course, is the entire premise of recent Federal Reserve policy. Raise rates, slow growth, keep inflation in check. But the Fed's moves have another effect. Each time it changes interest rates, the Fed shifts income from one age group to another. <p>Consider consumer credit. The latest numbers from the Fed show no letup in Americans' pursuit of debt. Outstanding consumer installment credit -- everything from automobile loans to credit card debt -- grew by 1.3 percent in June, or $10.9 billion. That follows an $11.5 billion jump in May.<p>This may not be as ominous as it seems. Now that almost every form of consumer credit has been turned into income-bearing securities, one man's interest owed is another's interest income. Peter makes a payment on his mortgage; Paul gets an interest payment from the collateralized mortgage obligations in his government bond fund.<p>The numbers used by the Department of Commerce to measure personal interest income and interest expense (including mortgages) show that interest income fell right alongside rates. It hit bottom -- $628 million -- in the fourth quarter of 1993. Then, as rates began to climb in 1994, income again tracked right along, rising to $644 million in the second quarter of 1994. Interest expense also rose from $366 at year end to $377 million in the second quarter of this year.<p>The bottom line? Because Americans in aggregate own more than they owe, individuals are making more in interest than they are paying out. The differential was $261 million in the fourth quarter and $267 million in the second quarter of this year.<p>This doesn't mean consumers are going to keep on getting richer as rates rise, or that all consumers will prosper equally. That's mostly because mortgage rates lag changes in Fed policy. Despite five Fed rate hikes this year, effective mortgage rates averaged 8.02 in the second quarter of 1994, just 1 basis point higher than at the start of the year. As mortgage rates catch up, younger consumers may feel the pinch -- and spend less. Their parents, who have already paid off their mortgages, will collect bigger payments on the investments they hold. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

