	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-On The Record</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>On The Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-On The Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>ON THE RECORD
Here's what experts think are  the most promising foreign markets.<p>We asked five global market experts to tell us what foreign arena looks most promising. We also sought their views on the U.S. market, plus a near-term rating from 1 to 5, with 5 the most bullish outlook. <p><p>J. MARK MOBIUS, PORTFOLIO MANAGER, <a name="FUND:TEDMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TEDMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TEMPLETON EMERGING MARKETS FUND</b></a>: "Brazil is finally beginning to bring inflation under control and is moving toward a more logical economic system. A new currency seems to be taking hold. We've taken a long-term bet on Brazil, and it's paying off. I'm concerned about the U.S. because of generally declining competitiveness vis-a-vis other countries in the world." <p>U.S. Market Rating: 3<p><p>MATTHEW WILSON, ECONOMIST, OLLIFF & PARTNERS, LONDON: "I'm a bull on Taiwan for capital growth. Although its interest rates went up earlier in the year, Taiwan's fairly independent monetary policy makes it an alternative to U.S. interest rate uncertainty. I'm neutral on the U.S. It's very defensive, stands up well to knocks. I just don't think it's a very aggressive market. "<p>U.S. market rating: 3<p><p>MARTIN MARMOLEJO, CHIEF EXECUTIVE OFFICER, MMA CAPITAL MANAGEMENT, MEXICO CITY, MEXICO: "The Mexican market is in an excellent expansionary phase. I think in the next year or two it could well be up in excess of 30 percent in dollar terms. For the U.S. market to be stagnant is about the healthiest thing for it because the U.S. economy is still growing at a vigorous pace. Eventually the U.S. market will be more in line with rational valuations. Looks like we'll see a soft landing of prices without major damage to investors."<p>U.S. market rating: 3<p><p>LEAH ZELL, PRINCIPAL, WANGER ASSET MANAGEMENT, CHICACO: "I like the U.K. market of all the European markets. It's come down a lot and seems to be holding.The economy is in pretty good shape; U.K. stocks are more reasonably priced than U.S. On the U.S. I'd be neutral; give it a three on price and fundamentals."<p>U.S. market rating: 3<p><p>CHRISTOPHER H. BROWNE, GENERAL PARTNER, TWEEDY, BROWNE, NEW YORK CITY: "France has really underperformed other European markets this year; first six months of '94, it was down 11.2 percent, compared with all Europe down 5.7 percent. Its price-to-earnings ratio looking out to '95 is under 16, cheaper than some other European markets. The market is at two times book value; U.S. is three times. The U.S. market is not going anywhere until earnings start justifying valuations. It has discounted the future, but there's no reason for it to fall off a cliff." <p>U.S. market rating: 2<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

