	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-October Tip Sheet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>October Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-October Tip Sheet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>OCTOBER TIP SHEET<p>* CORPORATE COST CUTTING IMPROVES PERFORMANCE, BUT BY HOW MUCH? 
A new study by Mercer Management Consulting of Lexington, Massachusetts, finds that investors can achieve much higher returns by focusing on companies that boost earnings through higher revenue rather than lower expenses. The Mercer study analyzed the performance of 1,000 companies versus their peers from 1989-1992. It found that while cost-cutters improved shareholder value by an average of 12 percent annually, companies with above-average revenue growth returned an average of 21 percent annually to shareholders.<p>* NEARING THE CLOSE OF THE TWENTIETH CENTURY: 
Twentieth Century Funds have always been marketed as friends of the small investor. Until January 1, 1993, the fund family didn't even require a minimum investment. Now, however, investors not only need $2,500 to open an account (a fairly common figure in the industry) but also can't let the value of their account fall below that figure. If it does, Twentieth Century will liquidate the account even if the cause is poor performance by a fund. With <a name="FUND:TWCUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TWCUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Twentieth Century Ultra Investors</b></a> fund down 8.93 percent for the seven months ended July 29, that's a very real possibility for some people. "We want to leave the door open to small investors," says company spokesman Gunnar Hughes, "but we need a really tight handshake from them." Investors have two choices: They can either meet the minimum by December 10, 1994, or they can sign up for Twentieth Century's monthly investment plan with its own $50 minimum.<p>* TALK LIKE A PRO: 
"The stock market has returned an average 10.3 percent a year since 1926." That and other oft-quoted statistics on the financial markets are available in the just-published 1994 Stocks, Bonds, Bills, and Inflation (SBBI) Yearbook, a compendium of market research from Ibbotson Associates in Chicago. A financial wonk's dream reference, the $90 SBBI tracks returns and index values for asset classes such as large- and small-cap stocks and long-term government bonds back to 1926. To order, call 800-758-3557.<p>* BEEN DOWN TOO LONG: 
For the first half of 1994, short-selling was the most successful "alternative" equity strategy, reports the Frank Russell Co. With the mean short-selling fund up 19.2 percent, the group substantially outperformed three other categories of funds that posted double-digit returns in 1993: hedge funds (down 1.6 percent through June), controlled-risk funds (down 2.9 percent) and "event-driven" funds (up 1.7 percent). That's quite a turnaround from 1993, when the mean short fund was down 8.2 percent. So have investors responded to this turn of events? According to Don Hardy, director of Russell's Private Investment Services, the answer is a resounding no. Hardy, who tracks 350 investment managers who pursue alternate strategies, says he continues to detect more investor interest in hedge funds, which play both sides of the market, as well as in event-driven funds, which attempt to profit from corporate mergers and acquisitions. Controlled-risk funds, which play anomalies in interest-rate swings, are holding about even, he adds. <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
