<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Market Radar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>MARKET RADAR
A monthly look at the outlook as told by our eight market indicators.<p>With four of our signals now flashing neutral, things look less gloomy for equity investors than last month. Still, no bullish signs yet. This month we've given each indicator a numerical rating (10 is most bullish). The arrows represent each indicator's near-term message.<p>THE INDICATORS:<p>BEARISH: INVESTOR SENTIMENT (2 this month/2 last month). Fidelity Investments says small-investor enthusiasm for stocks remains near an all-time high -- a bearish sign, since small investors often get excited at market peaks.<p>NEUTRAL: COMPOSITE BELLWETHER (3/2). This index, computed by InvesTech, tracks utility and brokerage stocks -- which historically predict market turns. It has moved ahead of its five-week average -- a good sign, but it's too early to call this a bullish move.<p>NEUTRAL: ADVANCE/DECLINE LINE (3/2). A moving average of the difference between the number of rising and falling stocks. This indicator, computed by InvesTech, appears to have bottomed out after a bad stretch.<p>NEUTRAL: PUT-CALL RATIO (5/4). Based on the volume of put and call options traded on the Chicago Board Options Exchange, last month's only non-bearish signal remains neutral -- but it's edging the right way.<p>BEARISH: COMMODITY INDEX (3/3). Supplied by Goldman Sachs, this measure of raw-materials prices has been buffeted by the political crisis in oil-rich Nigeria. Overall, the numbers still show upward pressure on prices. <p>BEARISH: YIELD DIFFERENTIAL (5/6). Ratio between yields of 90-day Treasury bills and the Standard & Poor's 500, computed by the Leuthold Group. It currently suggests that stocks are a bit overpriced.<p>NEUTRAL: CONSUMER AND CORPORATE DEBT (6/6). This aggregate measure of private debt continues its upward trend -- a warning to bears. Provided by Safian Investment Research.<p>BEARISH: MONETARY ENVIRONMENT (3/2). This model from InvesTech measures how much money is available to flow into the stock market. Although it has inched back from a three-year low in July, it remains bearish.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
