	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Bargain Hunting All Over World</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bargain Hunting All Over World</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Bargain Hunting All Over World</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>BARGAIN HUNTING ALL OVER THE WORLD<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>Tweedy, Browne Co. believed in staying close to its customers long before the phrase became a management mantra. In the early 1940s, it even moved its New York headquarters just down the hall from the office of Benjamin Graham, the father of value investing and a treasured brokerage client of the firm.<p>Maybe it's Graham's spirit that has enabled the <a name="FUND:TBGVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TBGVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tweedy, Browne Global Value Fund</b></a> to rack up a year-to-date 9 percent return by mid-August while its mutual fund rivals in Morningstar's world stock group were hovering around breakeven (up 1.9 percent for the year to date). The blue-blooded firm has moved its offices again since Graham's days, but it still follows his approach to value investing.<p>Graham believed in paying less for a stock than the company's assets were worth. About half of the 180 stocks in the Global Value fund reflect this strategy; these issues sell for an average of 72 percent of book value. Since many of these companies are in the midst of turnarounds, or have no earnings at all, their price-to-earnings ratios are misleadingly high. The other half of the fund's portfolio is selected on the basis of low price-to-earnings ratios, which collectively average about 10.<p>Co-managers Christopher Browne, William Browne (both sons of a founder), James Clark Jr., and John Spears have done well this year largely by avoiding hard-hit Asian and Latin American markets; nearly two thirds of the fund's money is in 132 undervalued companies spanning the recovering economies of Western Europe, with strong concentrations in Switzerland and the Netherlands. Another 25 percent of the fund is split evenly between the U.S. and Japan, with the rest in Hong Kong, Australia, Canada, and cash. The fund leans toward smaller companies, but does hold some name brands, including Heineken, Nestle, and Fuji Film.<p>The greatest threat to the fund's continued success could be its own rapid growth: Started in June 1993, the Global Value fund already has $477 million under management. But Tweedy, Browne's management team is convinced that the world's equity markets are full of undervalued companies. So convinced, in fact, that the four managers have roughly $8 million of their own money in the funds. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

