	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Is There a Yield Problem?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is There a Yield Problem?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Is There a Yield Problem?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
October 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>IS THERE A YIELD PROBLEM?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Yields on CDs are up. With a little shopping, investors can find one-year certificates paying more than 5 percent. One-year Treasury bills pay 5.6 percent now, up from 3.6 percent in January. And the stock market? The dividend yield on the Standard & Poor's 500 is at 2.78 percent, a measly 6-basis-point increase from the 2.72 percent yield in January. Is this a sign that the market is overvalued? <p>In the past, Wall Street analysts have used dividend yield as an indicator of the market's direction. "For 13 or 14 years I've been in the market, dividend yield has been a pretty good indicator of the market's direction," says Eric Ryback, president of Lindner Funds. The thinking is that if the market's yield drops significantly below that offered by competing investments, investors will buy bonds or CDs instead of stocks, sending the market lower. That says the market's yield gap is a bearish sign.<p>But things may be different this time. Not because analysts expect the market to catch up with higher yields elsewhere, but because changes in the economy have made dividend yield a less useful indicator. Companies are simply not passing good earnings along to investors as dividends to the extent they did in the past.<p>"Traditionally, there's been a big lag before the market catches up," says Ryback. "Corporations will eventually raise their rates -- if they can." <p>But this time the three traditional big dividend-paying sectors -- drug companies, utilities, and oil-and-gas companies -- all face competitive pressures that make dividend hikes unlikely. Cost containment is now the driving force.<p>"Corporate America is focused on getting leaner and meaner, and there's more emphasis on staying competitive than on paying out that dividend," says Jim Floyd, senior analyst at the Leuthold Group. Floyd calculates that dividends on the S&P came in at $12.90 a share in 1993. For 1994, he's forecasting $13.50. If Floyd is right, dividends will grow by 4.7 percent this year, beating inflation. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
