	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Time for a Tantrum?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Time for a Tantrum?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Time for a Tantrum?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>TIME FOR A TANTRUM?
The gloom on the horizon doesn't have much to do with whether equities represent a good value.<p>By John Koten<p>Optimism about the markets isn't easy to come by at the moment.<p>Not with the dollar in the dumpster. Not with inflation still looming as a threat. And not with the prospect of further interest rate hikes this fall.<p>Those who think otherwise should take a look at our Market Radar feature (further down in this file). Of eight technical indicators, seven bespeak extreme caution, while the eighth merely suggests mild caution.<p>At present, the gloom on the horizon does not have much to do with whether equities represent a good value. The more pressing concern is whether or not there's any money left out there to buy stocks.<p>President Clinton's policies promise little help in this regard, either in creating more wealth here at home or bringing it in from abroad. Back when the market was steaming along on its own power, this wasn't regarded as a huge problem. Better not to risk him mucking things up. Now, however, it may be necessary to get his attention.<p>Teenagers issue a plea for help by staging a crisis. Given Wall Street's sometimes adolescent tendencies, we wouldn't be surprised to see it resort to this subconscious tactic sometime soon.<p>Investors watching from the sidelines may do well to distance themselves emotionally from the goings-on. If the market does tumble, it's likely the damage will be short-lived. <p>For those who can remain circumspect, this is a good time to do some shopping. Look for companies with strong fundamentals and solid growth prospects. Then, settle on a price that represents a good value -- and wait for the stock to drop to that level. Chances are that it will. <p>In the current investment environment, there's little risk that the highfliers will take off before you can get on board. There's no excuse for not taking the time to complete thorough due diligence. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
