	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Perfect Stock Market Hedge</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Perfect Stock Market Hedge</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Perfect Stock Market Hedge</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>THE PERFECT STOCK MARKET HEDGE<p>Looking to diversify some of your holdings out of stocks? You're not alone. In search of the perfect hedge, investors have rushed to gold, real estate investment trusts, even commodities in recent months. <p>New data point to an even better stock market hedge, one that gives investors consistently high returns with substantially lower risk than commonly found in hard assets. It's a balanced long and short stock portfolio created by Michael Long, a money manager and general partner of Rockbridge Partners in Charlotte, North Carolina.<p>Short-selling of any kind is risky, but the structure of this so-called hedged portfolio -- 62 percent long and 38 percent short, rebalanced quarterly -- removes much of the downside associated with short-selling.<p>Long says that investors have been scared away from shorts since 1991, when they made some bad bets against stocks of money-center banks; the Nasdaq composite -- a favored hunting ground for short-sellers -- rose 57 percent in 1991.<p>Even cautious investors can be comfortable with the long/short portfolio thanks to its high returns and relatively low volatility. Investors looking for a short manager can try one of a couple of mutual funds that use short-selling or try to find an individual money manager who shorts stocks. <a name="FUND:RYURX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RYURX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rydex Ursa Fund</b></a>, for instance, is 100 percent short the S&P 500; <a name="FUND:RSCOX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RSCOX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Robertson Stephens Contrarian Fund</b></a> has one quarter of its portfolio in shorts. Be advised that neither of these achieve the balance in the hedged portfolio. Long (704-543-4880) also tracks money managers who short stocks. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:RYURX">Rydex Ursa Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:RSCOX">Robertson Stephens Contrarian Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
