<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-The Bad News About Earnings</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Bad News About Earnings</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-The Bad News About Earnings</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>THE BAD NEWS ABOUT EARNINGS
Why isn't the market rewarding companies with higher profits?<p>By Jim Jubak<p>"Earnings are coming in better than expected," says Melissa Brown, director of quantitative research at Prudential Securities. "That's the good news." The bad? "The market just doesn't seem to care."<p>Take the action in two stocks on July 21. <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq Computer</b></a> reported a doubling in earnings, beating analysts' estimates by two cents a share. In response, its stock fell more than 5 percent. <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> announced quarterly earnings of 59 cents a share, above analysts' estimates and up 37 percent from the year-earlier quarter. The stock edged 1 percent percent lower. "It's a paradoxical quarter," says Brown.<p>But not inexplicable. The problem, Brown says, is that a bulk of the gains in corporate earnings are coming from tighter controls on costs rather than more goods being sold. Investors love companies that run lean and mean, but earnings increases that come from cutting costs aren't sustainable. Company after company, says Brown, "is coming out and saying that we don't expect this [earnings growth rate] to continue." Economists now say the economy is slowing. Corporate executives determined to manage the expectations of Wall Street analysts are vocally seconding the motion.<p>Investors are listening hard. Suddenly, everybody wants to look beneath the surface of earnings reports. If earnings are growing, what about sales and inventories? Rising inventories at Compaq in the second quarter signal trouble down the road to investors. If both sales and earnings are up, what about profit margins? The market slammed Intel recently: Even though its earnings had risen, profit margins had slipped.<p>The market may also be looking further ahead and saying that big gains in earnings are history in this business cycle. According to Standard & Poor's Compustat, quarterly earnings for the S&P 500 hit $6.93 during 1994's first quarter. That's way up from the low of $2.55 recorded in the fourth quarter of 1991. Which may be precisely the problem. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:CPQ">Compaq Computer Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:MSFT">Microsoft Corporation</a><br>

