	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Sector Funds' Slow Death</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sector Funds' Slow Death</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Sector Funds' Slow Death</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>SECTOR FUNDS' SLOW DEATH<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>Are mutual fund families fed up with sector funds? An increasing number of these laggards are walking the plank. Since 1992, ten have been liquidated or merged into other funds. Recent kills: Vanguard Specialized Technology and Service Economy funds, Fidelity Select Electric Utilities, and Rushmore Precious Metals Index Plus. Says John Rekenthaler, editor of Morningstar Mutual Funds, "Sector funds are very dangerous animals [that] have played into investors' worst instincts. The more dead sector funds, the better."<p>Investors should beware merged slackers with shiny new labels. Oppenheimer Management now wants to splice its Global Bio-Tech and Global Environment funds to form a new global emerging-growth fund. The two have lost 24 percent and 10 percent, respectively, of their net asset value so far this year. "We're getting out of the sector-fund business," says Robert Doll, director of equity investments at Oppenheimer. Not quite -- biotech stocks would still compose 25 percent to 30 percent of the new fund. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

