<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-One Fund's Roller-Coaster Ride</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>One Hot Fund's Roller-Coaster Ride</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-One Fund's Roller-Coaster Ride</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>ONE HOT FUND'S ROLLER-COASTER RIDE<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>When investors and the press get the scent, a hot-performing mutual fund can pull in close to a half-billion bucks in just one year. Gary Pilgrim's <a name="FUND:PBHGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PBHGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PBHG Growth Fund</b></a> did just that. The eight-year-old fund dumped its fat 4.75 percent load in July 1993 and then racked up a red-hot 1993 total return of 46.6 percent. As a result, the fund, which had just $8.1 million in assets in July 1993, boomed to $466 million in assets a year later.<p>However, before you invest, take a look past the champagne and confetti. The fund has a record of high volatility, including a 29 percent drop in the third quarter of 1990. In the past the nimble fund was quickly able to overcome such setbacks by running up even bigger gains in bull markets. But this isn't a tiny fund anymore. With 60 times more money, will Pilgrim still be able to run with the bulls when they return?<p>Winning in up markets is crucial to PBHG. Pilgrim plays the turbulent earnings-momentum game, which means he picks volatile companies, sometimes initial public offerings, with projected annual earnings growth of at least 20 percent. In down markets, such highfliers exact a heavy price. Two Pilgrim picks, IDB Communications and <a name="AMEX:CYE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12967"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cheyenne Software</b></a>, recently shed half their market value, and Pilgrim sold both at a loss. By midsummer, the fund's year-to-date total return was a negative 13 percent. The IPO market, which added a hefty 16 percent to 1993's return, has since cooled considerably. That market's "opportunity," he recently told shareholders, "is clearly behind us." <p>Of course, Pilgrim has been down before. After the fund lost 9.7 percent in 1990 (with that 29 percent third-quarter plunge), it rebounded to return 51.6 percent in 1991.<p>Finding enough small undiscovered stocks to fuel a rebound like that is tougher with $466 million than with $8 million. To cast a bigger net, Pilgrim has recently added several members to his portfolio team.<p>So should you invest? The outside experts and Pilgrim are in surprising agreement. Sheldon Jacobs, editor of The No-Load Fund Investor newsletter and who recently dropped PBHG from his best-buys list says, "It's a very good fund if you have a high tolerance for a lot of volatility." If you can't stand the heat, says the pragmatic Pilgrim, "move on." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#AMEX:CYE">Cheyenne Software, Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:PBHGX">PBHG Growth Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
