<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-On The Record</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>On The Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-On The Record</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>ON THE RECORD
Here's what strategists think is driving the market.<p>Six highly regarded strategists talk about what's driving the market right now. Each also rates the prospects for stocks for the rest of the year on a scale of 1 to 5, with 5 reflecting the most bullish outlook. <p><p>LOUIS NAVELLIER, MPT REVIEW, INCLINE VILLAGE, NEVADA:  "The market's been dying a liquidity death on light volume since early April. Interest rates have gone up so much, stocks should fall 20 percent to 30 percent. I think it's a good time to get in. As soon as earnings take hold, they'll probably drive  stocks higher." <p>Market rating: 4<p><p>GERALD APPEL, SYSTEMS & FORECASTS, GREAT NECK, NEW YORK:  "The expectation of higher interest rates is getting everyone panicky. I think rates are going to go up, but not dramatically. The market is going to stay under some pressure. It would not be at all surprising to see [the market] go down a few  percentage points by the end of the year and have trouble advancing."<p>Market rating: 2<p><p>DAN SULLIVAN, THE CHARTIST, SEAL BEACH, CALIFORNIA:  "The breakdown of the daily advance/decline line [the difference between the number of new highs and the number of new lows] indicates the [performance of the] Dow is masking the internal weakness of the market. We're in the early stages of a bear  market. The market will make zero progress through the rest of the year."<p>Market rating: 1 <p><p>MARIEL CLEMENSEN, CLEMENSEN CAPITAL ACCESS, NEW YORK CITY:  "The stock market is inexorably linked to the Fed short term. It is impossible to see forward momentum until investors get the higher rates they fear. [Long-term, however], due to the recovery in Europe already in sight and Japan's behind that, we  face the delightful prospect of a long economic expansion period. The stock market will eventually value securities on earnings growth rather than interest rates. This is a good time to pick those securities."<p>Market rating: 5<p><p>ROBERT NATALE, STANDARD & POOR'S EMERGING & SPECIAL SITUATIONS, NEW YORK CITY:  "Right now inflation expectations are around 2.6 percent. By year end, I think it's going to be 3.5 percent. If it comes in over that, the Fed will have to act more than it has. The market will drop."<p>Market rating: 3<p><p>JAMES B. STACK, INVESTECH RESEARCH, WHITEFISH, MONTANA:  "With interest rates now in an uptrend, investors must keep a watchful eye on the underlying pressures on the Federal Reserve. The deteriorating monetary climate and poor technical strength raise the odds that we are in a bear market, where broad  averages may eventually lose 20 percent or more."<p>Market rating: 2<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

