		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>MARKET RADAR
A monthly look at the outlook as told by our eight market indicators.<p>With seven of our eight indicators bearish and the other neutral, it's a good time for investors to be extra cautious in the financial markets. Indeed, at press time several indicators were hovering near all-time bearish levels. The bottom line:  Hold off on that stock-buying spree.<p>THE INDICATORS:<p>BEARISH: INVESTOR SENTIMENT. Fidelity Investments' measure of small-investor enthusiasm for stocks is a contrarian signal. High is bad; lots of cash is already in the market. Still very bearish after an all-time high in January.<p>BEARISH: COMPOSITE BELLWETHER. This index, computed by InvesTech, tracks utility and brokerage stocks (both of which historically move down before the rest of the market does) to predict market turns. The only times it's been more bearish were before the  corrections of 1974 and 1987.<p>BEARISH: ADVANCE/DECLINE LINE. A moving average of the difference between the number of rising and falling stocks. This indicator, computed by InvesTech, kept falling even during July's brief rally -- a bad sign.<p>NEUTRAL: PUT-CALL RATIO. Based on the volume of put and call options traded on the Chicago Board Options Exchange, this contrarian indicator remains officially neutral but appeared to be moving bearishly in July.<p>BEARISH: COMMODITY INDEX. Supplied by Goldman Sachs, this measure of raw-materials prices has been rising steadily this year, showing upward pressure on the inflation rate. Upward moves have been stronger lately; that means bad news for prices -- and possibly  the market -- later this year.<p>BEARISH: YIELD DIFFERENTIAL. Gap between yields of 90-day Treasury bill and Standard & Poor's 500, computed by the Leuthold Group. High yields on T bills and low dividend yields argue for a market correction.<p>BEARISH: CONSUMER AND CORPORATE DEBT. This aggregate measure of the country's private debt continues to increase ever faster from year-ago figures -- a likely harbinger of higher interest rates.<p>BEARISH: MONETARY ENVIRONMENT. This model from InvesTech measures how much money is available to flow into the stock market. Bearish since the first quarter, this summer it reached its lowest point since 1990.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

