	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Gurus in Flux</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Gurus in Flux</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Gurus in Flux</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>GURUS IN FLUX
Investment tip sheets experience reverses from agitation in the market.<p>By Jim Melloan<p>This year's market turmoil has carried over into the world of investment newsletters. Many of the newsletters with the best long-term records for their model portfolios have lagged recently, according to Hulbert Financial Digest, while some tip sheets that were throttled by the bull market are finally turning around. <p>The top two tip sheets for the first half of 1994, Futures Hotline/Mutual Fund Timer (up 50.1 percent) and P.Q. Wall Forecasts (up 26.8 percent), had both performed miserably, losing 29.7 over five years and 64.8 percent over three years, respectively. Meanwhile, OTC Insight rode the bull market to a 432 percent gain from '89 to '93; it was down 28.2 percent through June '94. <p>The message seems to be that a jumpy market rewards strategies that can short stocks. Three of the top five gurus were advising futures and options plays. "Futures traders love that kind of volatility," says Digest editor Mark Hulbert. "They don't do well during stagnant markets." This doesn't surprise Hulbert, who thinks it may be easier to beat the market on the short side than the long.<p>The first-half winners: Futures Hotline/Mutual Fund Timer, P.Q. Wall Forecasts, Short on Value (up 20.9 percent), The Timing Device (up 16.4 percent), and Stockmarket Cycles (up 9.4 percent). The first-half losers: Wall Street Generalist (down 48 percent), Medical Technology Stock Letter (down 41.5 percent), Granville Market Letter (down 37.5 percent), The Princeton Portfolios (down 28.9 percent), and OTC Insight (down 28.2 percent).<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
