<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Fed Up With the Fed</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fed Up With the Fed</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Fed Up With the Fed</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>FED UP WITH THE FED
Wall Street ponders the meaning of the central bank's inconsistencies.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Robert Brusca, economist at Nikko Securities, is disgusted with Alan Greenspan. "The markets above all want consistency," says Brusca. "[Greenspan] hasn't provided us with the consistency that we need."<p>Brusca points to the Fed chairman's congressional testimony of July 20, where he argued that a weaker dollar, shortages of truck drivers, and lengthening delivery schedules at some manufacturers were danger signs of possible inflation ahead. Just a week before, however, Greenspan had posited a very different view: that we were in the best of all possible worlds with slow, steady growth and low inflation. <p>The market was expecting more reassuring testimony from Greenspan in his July 20 testimony. No such luck. Greenspan opened the door for another rate hike, and the bond market headed south. Yields on the 30-year Treasury climbed to 7.54 percent, up from 7.46 the day before. That's almost back to where rates were when Clinton defeated Bush in the 1992 election.<p>The recent jump in rates has more to do with traders' fears of Fed confusion than it does with Greenspan's case that inflation is looming. The problem: The markets simply have no idea what benchmarks the Fed is currently using to set monetary policy. <p>Now that the Federal Reserve has decided the traditional measures used to manage inflation -- M1, M2, and M3, which measure the money in circulation -- are no longer reliable, its members seem to be watching everything and anything. One week it's truck drivers, the next it's housing starts. One minute Greenspan discounts the inflationary impact of a weak dollar; the next he worries publicly about it. <p>The folks at the Fed may indeed have a theory behind their choice of indicators and what they mean for the economy. But no one in the bond market is sure what it is. Meanwhile, Wall Street is left to wonder whether the Fed's inconsistencies are a sign of increasing disagreement among Federal Reserve Board members or just evidence of a weak chairman. Neither possibility sits comfortably with traders.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Politics<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

