<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-The Big Picture</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-The Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Large-format TVs:  The best of the beasts.<p>By Edmund Cadigan<p>My wife and I didn't bother with a prenuptial agreement; but if we had, I have no doubt that aside from length of in-law visits, the major point of contention would have been a nugget of technology that I have long longed for -- the big-screen television. While other guys are sneaking trips to strip bars or renting hotel rooms by the hour, I can be found wandering electronics stores, fantasizing about an interminable late night with a really big screen.<p>When you're choosing a set in the big-screen arena -- which includes both direct-view and rear-projection TVs and tops out with monstrous home-theater setups -- you are initially faced with some relatively inexpensive choices. If, for instance, you are not interested in redecorating your entire home -- this would definitely be in my prenuptial agreement -- then you might choose from dozens of large-screen direct-view models. In essence, these are basically just very big TVs.<p>One of my favorites, the 35-inch Toshiba CF-35C40, has 800 lines of resolution, about twice as much as a regular set, and costs about $1,700. Although I'd never admit to my wife that I can be this easily satisfied, I also have my eye on a 27-inch <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a> KV-27V55 that has better sound than the bigger Toshiba and runs only about $900. Big-screen purists seem to think that big screen-ness doesn't begin until around the 31-inch mark, but for a lot of people 27 inches is enough. My friend James, who is more into sports than landscape-sweeping motion pictures, tells me that he doesn't want a home movie theater. "I like my TV to be a TV,'' he says, and he has a point.<p>Somewhere between these large tabletop TVs and the even larger home-theater models lie TVs like the Sony KPR-41EXR96, about $2,700. This particular Sony has a 41-inch screen, but it's not as bulky as most televisions with screens this size. It's one of the slimmest models out there, in fact, and its well-apportioned speakers are designed sleekly and slipped into the bottom of the console. (As you notch up the big-screen-TV wish list, you quickly realize that you want the size of the sound to match the size of the picture.) This Sony has a rear-projection screen, which means that the colors tend to be more subtle in comparison to the relatively rigid colors of a direct-view screen. Like all rear-projection TVs, this model's screen generally works best in a darkened room, a feature that takes you one step closer to that more drastic home-theater environment. Also, unlike some of the more inexpensive rear-projection screens I've seen, the picture on the Sony is crisp, tight, never muddy. I recently watched a laser disc of Top Gun on it. Rarely are films so lacking in narrative substance, and yet, given how those dogfights looked and sounded, if I hadn't had something of a life to live, I would have watched it again.<p>Next on the list of big-screen philosophies is the issue of nonconventional aspect ratios. When considering aspect ratios, you are considering the shape of your screen. The aspect ratio of the traditional television is 4:3, which gives you an almost square picture. Certain sets are now able to play elongated pictures filmed in the Cinemascope ratio of 16:9 without placing black bars across the top and bottom of the screen; it's more like being in a movie theater. And what might seem merely artsy is actually a way to bring back a huge percentage of the picture that was lost when it was hacked down for TV size. I recently saw the difference between the two ratios while watching Adam's Rib. In one scene, on 4:3, I could see only Katharine Hepburn; in 16:9, watching the same scene, I could see Spencer Tracy quietly making faces at the edge of the frame. In this category, RCA makes a 34-inch direct-projection model, the ProScan CinemaScreen, which costs about $5,000.<p>There is a caveat to wide-screen, however. The backlog of TV history is in 4:3, as is what you might watch tonight. As a result, Pioneer has a series of sets that have an aspect ratio of 16:10.7, which is a little closer to the current standard. Pioneer's thinking is that most people will be forced to zoom up their images from 4:3 to 16:9 (the sets do so on command), and the 16:10.7 ratio makes this leap with significantly less distortion. At the top of the Pioneer line, the rear-projection Pro-107 Elite has a 55-inch Cinema Wide screen; it costs $5,550, a price that includes something called a digital comb filter that gives it 830 lines of horizontal resolution (great for such a big screen). The rear-projection Pioneer SD-P5071, at about $2,473, is a cheaper version of 16:10.7 and, though I haven't lived with it, looks almost as good.<p>From here on up the price list, it probably pays to hire a home-theater designer. (For that matter, it may pay to wait two years for the initial launch of high-definition television). I saw a system in Video magazine last year that -- when you added up the Altec Lansing subwoofers, the center-channel speakers, the surround speakers, the Acoustic Research M6 auxiliary speakers, the Kenwood amplifier and tuner, and the $1,000 Mitsubishi VCR -- was priced at about $12,500. <p>A system like that is definitely home theater, and when I think about a system like that, I think about building a whole new room onto my house, which pains me, not to mention a whole new marriage, which pains me even more. Come to think of it, I love our little 13-inch Trinitron.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry, Technology Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:SNE">Sony Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
