		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Market Radar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 
<p>
Worth magazine/Need To Know  
<p>
 MARKET RADAR  
<p>
 Most of our indicators are now giving off neutral signals, meaning
the market may be headed for a period of stabilization. Last
month's scary lurch in the commodity index didn't repeat itself‹heartening
news for inflation worriers. Still, it's hard not to wonder about
an all-time low yield on the Standard & Poor's 500. Is it a sign
that stocks are overvalued, or just that more companies are hanging
on to their cash or reinvesting it in their business? As usual,
each of our market indicators gets a historical rating (10 is
most bullish) and an arrow (message for this month).  
<p>
 <->Composite Bellwether (5 this month/5 last month) This index,
computed by InvesTech, tracks bellwether utility and brokerage
stocks. It has risen consistently since December but is lagging
broader indexes because of underperforming utility stocks.  
<p>
 <->Put/Call Ratio (6/4) Based on the volume of equity put and
call options traded on the Chicago Board Options Exchange. This
contrarian indicator turns positive when traders are feeling
gloomy‹which they were even as the Dow and S&P indexes were achieving
new highs.  
<p>
 <->Advance/Decline Line (4/3) A moving average of the difference
between the number of rising and falling stocks, this shows whether
market moves are broadly or narrowly based. The measure has surged
but is still playing catch-up with the overall market. Computed
by InvesTech.  
<p>
 <->Advisory Sentiment (5/6) Investment advisors tend to be followers,
not leaders. Historically, they get most excited at market tops.
For the fifth straight month, more advisors have gotten optimistic.
It scares us a little more each time. Compiled by Investors Intelligence.<p>
<p>
 [down] Commodity Index (3/3) Supplied by Goldman, Sachs, this
measure of raw-material prices‹an inflation precursor‹edged up
only slightly this month after a 4 percent gain the month before.
For the year so far, the index is up a net of 1.8 percent, slightly
above most expectations.  
<p>
 <->Consumer and Corporate Debt (5/5) This aggregate measure
of private debt continues its upward drift, a bad trend driven
by increases in real estate lending. Only an economic slowdown
will keep it in our comfort zone. Provided by Safian Investment
Research.  
<p>
 [down] Yield Ratio (3/3) The ratio between yields of 90-day
Treasury bills and the S&P 500, computed by the Leuthold Group.
At about 2.6 percent, the stock market's dividend payout is now
the lowest since 1926. Only declining T-bill yields have stopped
this indicator from falling considerably.   
<p>
 [down] Monetary Environment (3/3) This model from InvesTech
measures how Federal Reserve Bank policy affects credit availability,
interest rates, and other factors that encourage money to flow
into the stock market. It remains stable in negative territory.<p>
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
Copyright 1995 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership.  All rights
reserved. 
<p>

