	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Giving Credit to Teenagers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Giving Credit to Teenagers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
By Monica Corcoran<p>If you've got high schoolers in the house, watch your mailbox this summer: Banks may be trying to tempt them into starting a credit card account. This growing practice is a way for card issuers to get a jump on all the offers students receive in college. But it's condemned by consumer advocates because many teens just can't handle credit. "We're seeing more young people getting into debt at an early age -- and it's just because the credit card industry is desperate for new customers," says Ken McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action.<p>"I can't think of one good reason why a high school kid needs a credit card," says Ruth Susswein, executive director of Bankcard Holders of America, an industry watchdog agency. But banks are pitching them nonetheless, buying mailing lists from companies such as American Student List of New York, which can provide statistics on 1.7 million college-bound high school seniors.<p>Most card issuers admit the practice but say it's a tiny part of their business. McEldowney says it's fairly widespread. Either way, here are some tips for avoiding disaster when your teen pesters you for plastic:<p>-> Educate. Use your own bills as teaching tools. Note that interest may start piling up as soon as a purchase is made; only 30 percent of college kids know this basic fact.<p>-> Don't cosign on a new card for your child -- add a second card to your own account. Get the bill sent to you, and agree on a payment plan.<p>-> Talk to your card issuer about setting the credit limit on your child's card much lower than on your primary card.<p>-> If you must unleash your child by cosigning, look into a "secured" card backed by the child's own bank account.<p>-> Consider a Visa or MasterCard debit card as an alternative. They're accepted most places but deduct money directly from a checking account. The party's over when the money's gone.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
