	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Funds Move Into Real Estate</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Funds Move Into Real Estate</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1994
Worth magazine/Need to Know<p>FUNDS MOVE INTO REAL ESTATE<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>As real estate continues its upswing, real estate equity mutual funds are trying to lure new players into gambling on the market. In April, both Columbia and Crabbe Huson introduced such funds, pushing the total to more than a dozen. Fully half these funds are newcomers, and at least three more await approval from the Securities and Exchange Commission.<p>Investors clearly are being tempted. Two years ago, only six real estate funds existed -- and none had $100 million in assets. By the end of the 1994 first quarter, however, total assets for the group topped $1.3 billion. Is it time to join the stampede? Perhaps. Robert Tracinski, an analyst at Morningstar, the mutual fund-watching company, praises the liquidity and diversification offered by real estate funds -- advantages that are harder to find in more traditional real estate plays.<p>Most real estate funds hold a portfolio of shares in real estate investment trusts, companies that invest in property or mortgages. This market has been booming: REITs raised more than $8.6 billion in public offerings during 1993, just 17 percent less than the total raised during all 31 previous years REITs had been around. "These are longstanding, reputable companies that are going public," says Barry Vinocur, editor in chief of Realty Stock Review newsletter. And they've been performing well. REITs offered an average 3 percent return for the year through April. That compares to a 4.2 percent  drop for the Standard & Poor's 500.<p>But not all real estate funds are created equal. <a name="FUND:CSRSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CSRSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cohen & Steers Realty</b></a> returned 6.8 percent for the year through April, for example, but DFA Group's fund was down 4.2 percent, according to Lipper Analytical Services. Such spotty results are typical in the real estate market, which fluctuates widely depending on region and type of property. When deciding on a fund, analysts say, it's smart to look beyond current yields for a manager with lots of experience in this capricious area.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

