<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-A Trendy Way to Make Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-A Trendy Way to Make Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Dean Robinson<p>Jim Williams doesn't make his living as a stock picker, but he sells advice to those who do. For nearly 30 years his firm, Williams Inference Service, has looked for long-term cultural trends that are powerful enough to move markets. Whenever he spots such a trend, Williams tries to identify the companies that will be affected -- for better and for worse.<p>Take the color black: Williams noted late last year that people are embracing all things black, from high-fashion clothes to sports merchandise. He figures it's a symbol of self-denial and says we're headed for a decline in consumer spending. That's bad news for retailers like <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears Roebuck</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:LTD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11471"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>The Limited</b></a>, Williams predicts.<p>Spotting trends is a broad-brush approach that's catching on at some brokerage houses, in part because such "themes" make stock picks easier to explain to customers. Wall Street's Kidder Peabody, for example, now has a five-person team busily reading cultural tea leaves.<p>Of course, several trends can be underway at the same time. Lately Williams has been focusing on what he calls a "meaning void." Americans are trying to combat the sense that their lives lack purpose, he says. He believes this helps explain the rise of hangouts such as microbrewery pubs, coffee bars, cafe bookstores, and other "watering holes" where people can find company and support.<p>What's good for the soul can also be good business. Here are a few stocks Williams thinks may benefit as people search for meaning.<p><a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> (AMER): Like pubs and cafes, electronic chat services allow users to reach out and make contact with others.<p><a name="NYSE:HRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10689"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>H&R Block</b></a> (HRB): Sure, helping people get tax refunds is meaningful. But Williams likes the company mostly because it has another on-line service, CompuServe, where people can come together.<p><a name="NYSE:LLY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10509"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eli Lilly</b></a> (LLY): With the loss of meaning often comes depression. And these days depression means Prozac, the blockbuster drug made by Eli Lilly.<p><a name="NASD:TNEL"></a><b>Thomas Nelson</b> (TNEL): Those who don't turn to medicine may fill their void with religion. Nashville-based Thomas Nelson is a huge publisher of Bibles and other inspirational literature.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:S">Sears, Roebuck and Co.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:LTD">The Limited, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:AMER">America Online</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:HRB">H&R Block, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:LLY">Eli Lilly and Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:TNEL">Thomas Nelson</a><br>

