<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Weathering the Monsoon</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Weathering the Monsoon</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>The guru who invented new financial products such as air-pollution futures, catastrophe-insurance futures, and Treasury-bond futures is looking overseas for his next innovation - to India, in fact, where U.S. mutual funds and celebrated investors such as George Soros are already playing.<p>What's Richard Sandor's spin on the subcontinent? Monsoon futures, a new way to bet on India's often devastating weather patterns. Not a bad idea: India's $175 billion economy depends heavily on the June-to-August rainy season, and agricultural futures are at best a once-removed way to play the weather.<p>The 52-year-old former finance professor is short on specifics - "proprietary at this point" - but says the new product will hedge against the unpredictability of the monsoon. To play all possible outcomes, he describes a sketchy combination of flood-insurance futures and crop insurance.<p>If the rainfall is torrential, Sandor's product would be hurt by flood-damage claims but would benefit from good harvests. If the monsoon is mild, crops would do badly but flood insurance should be profitable. Investors likely would buy monsoon futures as a supplement to other Indian investments. Sandor won't say when his new product may be rolled out, but it won't be in time to play the 1994 monsoon.<p>Sandor has been interested in India since the 1960s, but his latest passion was triggered two years ago while he was vacationing there. At the time, he had been preparing a United Nations report on using financial markets to improve the environment. Traveling by road to see the Taj Mahal, he was impressed by two things: "The Taj was unbelievable, but so was the traffic and pollution. I saw the opportunity."<p>Indeed, Sandor thinks India may ultimately be a good market for his air-pollution futures. But for now he says he's focusing on the monsoon. If he succeeds, it'll mark a comeback of sorts. Although he gained lasting fame at the Chicago Board of Trade as the inventor of the T-bond future - now a $50 billion market - Sandor hasn't been at the forefront of the financial markets recently. His effort to create a derivatives group at Kidder, Peabody, for example, ended in failure after two years.<p>Shortly after leaving Kidder last year, Sandor started a small New York -  based firm, Centre Financial Products, an affiliate of the giant Zurich Insurance Group. Centre is a likely vehicle to launch the new monsoon futures, but Sandor says he'll also consider doing it through the Commodities Board of Trade.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
