<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-New Standards for 401(k)s</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-New Standards for 401(k)s</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
By Kevin Caliendo<p>In recent years, workers at several major companies have sued their employers for failing to run 401(k) retirement plans properly. Settlements in some cases - <a name="NYSE:HON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10742"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Honeywell</b></a> and CenTrust Savings Bank, for example - have run into the millions of dollars.<p>But in recent months, the issue of bad 401(k) management has heated up even more. New federal guidelines make it clear that lots of companies aren't acting appropriately - by limiting investment choices, for example, or not keeping employees informed. One national survey showed that only 52 percent of companies comply with the new rules, which aren't mandatory but will become an industry standard in 1995.<p>It isn't just the big boys that are falling down: Smaller companies may be even riper for complaints because they don't have enough resources to meet the new standard. "Employees must be vigilant," says Tom Schlossberg, president of Diversified Investment Advisors, a big retirement-investment firm.<p>Meanwhile, although the federal guidelines were designed to cut down on lawsuits from employees in 401(k) plans, they may have the opposite effect.<p>The regulations, dubbed 404(c) standards after the section of a law that established them, essentially spell out the steps a company should take if it doesn't want to be sued for bad management of a 401(k) plan. But some recommendations are vaguely worded, allowing for arguments over whether they've been met. And compliance requires lots of tedious work, which employers will inevitably shirk on occasion.<p>"I don't think anyone really understands all the little subtleties of 404(c)," says Michael F. Seidenburg, a principal with William M. Mercer, a consulting firm.<p>As a result, Seidenburg and other experts say 404(c) should actually make lawsuits easier, by establishing a code of conduct that's well accepted but hard to meet.<p>"No one is going to sue if he's getting a good return," says Howard Pianko, chairman of employee benefits at Epstein Becker & Green, a law firm. "But if one guy is getting 5 percent and his buddy is getting 15 percent, that first guy is going to want to know why he isn't in his buddy's fund." Indeed, the first man could easily claim he hadn't been educated about the other fund - and sue his company for the difference in returns.<p>Of course, suing your employer is probably a last resort, even if it runs a truly lousy 401(k). But the 404(c) standards give all employees a good look at the kind of service they should be getting:<p>-> A 401(k) plan should offer at least three investment options, each with a different level of risk.<p>-> A company-stock purchase plan doesn't qualify as one of the recommended three options.<p>-> Prospectuses must be handed out, where available.<p>-> Employers must educate employees on investing principles, as well as on the funds they offer. A stack of pamphlets in the office almost certainly isn't enough.<p>-> Employers must reeducate employees if conditions change.<p>-> Employees should be allowed to adjust their mix of 401(k) investments at least quarterly - and at any time during a quarter, not only on a specified day.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
