<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The Merits of Debit Cards</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Merits of Debit Cards</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
These credit-card alternatives keep you in control of debt, but shop around for the best plan<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Debit cards, which deduct purchases directly from users' checking accounts, may finally be taking off. Transactions have more than doubled in the past three years, to nearly 675 million in 1993. Even some New York prostitutes now accept debit-card payments.<p>Time to catch the wave? Sure, if you love the ease of credit cards but worry about debt getting out of control. When you use a debit card, you're spending money you already have--not borrowing, as with credit cards.<p>Debit cards come in two flavors, on-line and off-line. The difference is how fast payments are deducted from your checking account: An on-line card takes it out instantaneously, just like spending cash. An off-line card is really another sort of check, with a float period of two to five days.<p>Because they don't depend on high technology, off-line debit cards are accepted in far more locations. In fact, the Visa and MasterCard versions are taken wherever those credit cards are accepted, since they're processed the same way by merchants. This makes off-line cards a nifty alternative to checks, which are awkward to carry and cause hassles anyway.<p>An on-line debit card is exactly like an ATM card, but it's used to make purchases. In fact, many big-city cash cards now function as on-line debit cards too. The cost for a transaction usually equals the fee for using a cash machine, if any. The downside of on-line cards is that they require merchants to link to a computer that knows how much money each customer has. Because of this, the cards aren't yet widespread--though they're now accepted by many supermarkets, gas stations, and fast-food joints.<p>If you already have a cash card that works as a debit card in local stores, do you need an additional on-line debit card? Only if you travel much: Unlike local cash cards, the Visa or MasterCard on-line cards are accepted nationwide and should also be accepted in some foreign locations by the end of the year.<p>So, on-line or off-line? Or no debit card at all? The key points to consider:<p>-> What are you trying to replace? An on-line card is better than cash but isn't accepted many places yet. An off-line card is handier than a checkbook and accepted pretty widely. Neither performs as a credit card, which allows borrowing and can have a far longer float than an off-line debit card.<p>-> Fees. Few banks charge more than 25 cents per transaction for debit cards, and annual fees, if any, rarely top $24. If you plan to use a debit card a lot, opt for an issuer with a flat annual fee. And shop around: Deals vary.<p>-> Do your favorite merchants charge extra for debit transactions? Amazingly, some merchants do, resulting in a doubled fee that makes credit-card interest rates look good. The only way to find out is by asking.<p>-> Liability. As with credit cards, if you report a missing card within two days, you'll be out a maximum of $50. But if you wait any longer, you could be forced to pay up to $500. And after 60 days, you might even have to absorb a thief's entire spending spree.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
