<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Leveling the Playing Field</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Leveling the Playing Field</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Back in March, the "Full Disclosure" column reported on a shadowy but increasingly popular practice by which U.S. companies sell shares of their stocks to overseas investors at discounts of 30 - 40 percent of what American investors pay. Unfair as the tactic is to U.S. investors, it is technically legal, because Securities and Exchange Commission rules on sales of shares to foreigners are less rigorous than the laws that apply in the U.S. The rules governing these types of foreign stock transactions are known as Regulation S. Under these rules, foreign buyers of discounted shares are not supposed to sell their holdings for 40 days and are not supposed to dump them back into U.S. markets. <p>But foreign investors have been doing just that, and American investors are being put at a great disadvantage. Hundreds of millions of dollars have been raised through these offerings, yet few U.S. investors know they may be paying big premiums to buy shares from canny Reg. S investors. <p>Our warning about the uneven Reg. S playing field had an effect in Washington. The March 15 issue of The SEC Today, a publication that summarizes SEC discussions and activities, reported that the commission staff is "reviewing the use of the (Reg. S) rule." <p>According to SEC deputy director Elisse Walter, "The staff will look closely at such offerings where the market for the securities has been solely in the U.S. but the company makes a substantial placement, purported abroad, at a significant discount of 20 percent to 40 percent off the market price." She says that the commission will revisit Reg. S if it is being abused and that it cannot be used to evade registration requirements. William McLucas, SEC enforcement director, says his staff will look at the deals "with a fairly skeptical eye." <p>Couldn't have said it better ourselves.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
