<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Time to Catch a Rising Rate?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Time to Catch a Rising Rate?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Ilyce R. Glink<p>The recent hike in interest rates is pushing reluctant home buyers off the fence: After an upswing in buying at the end of 1993, followed by a weather-damped first quarter, 1994 is shaping up better than any other real estate market in recent memory.<p>The prod is the near certainty of future rises. Even former optimists such as David Lereah, chief economist for the powerful Mortgage Bankers Association, have changed their view. After predicting last year that 30-year fixed rates would hold the line at about 7.5 percent, Lereah now believes rates will top 8 percent by year end--and may not level off until mid-1995. Still, despite the prospect of higher mortgage rates, buyers shouldn't get panicked. It's always a mistake to buy a house on national stats: Real estate is local, and many markets have room to fall yet.<p>Assess the momentum in your market, and try to remember that a house is mostly a place to live. Rising rates won't cost much if you're waiting for just the right place. On a fixed-rate 30-year loan of $100,000, the difference between 7.5 percent and 8 percent is only $35 a month.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Mortgages

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
