<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Transferring Airline Discounts</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Transferring Airline Discounts</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Deborah Pont<p>Got a great discount voucher for one airline, but a fat frequent-flier account at another carrier? It's not such an agonizing choice: When it comes to airline discounts, you can often have it both ways.<p>Few people know it, but for competitive reasons many carriers accept coupons issued by their rivals. And with airlines now offering a flood of lucrative promotions through supermarkets, credit cards, and the like, this knowledge is more valuable than ever.<p>The offers can be substantial and easy to get. For example, <a name="NYSE:DAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10448"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Delta</b></a> recently gave a $100 discount to customers who collected a mere $100 worth of receipts from the Stop & Shop supermarket. You prefer to fly on USAir? No problem--that carrier accepted Delta's voucher. United currently offers up to $50 off tickets for customers of Midwest Rocky Mountain Bank. You like American better? Again, no problem.<p>Transferring discounts takes a little work. For one thing, no reservation agent will suggest using another airline's promotion. But most carriers keep a database with details on all the rival offers they've decided to match. The key here: Always ask.<p>Suppose your coupon isn't in the database of your preferred airline? Well, that doesn't mean the carrier won't accept it, says a USAir spokeswoman: With so many discounts available nationwide, the airline just may not know about the offer. Her suggestion: Call the carrier's marketing department and ask it to add your deal to the approved list. That's how USAir hears about many of its rivals' offers, she says.<p>
A few more tips:
--Note the code number that accompanies any offer you want matched. That's how airlines keep track of discounts on their databases.
--Be aware of all the restrictions on your offer; airlines will match most of these if they decide to match the discount.
--Take note of some not-so-obvious advantages of transferring coupons. Some airlines may fly direct to a destination, for example, while the coupon issuer requires a connection. Some airlines might honor a MasterCard payment, while the coupon issuer requires <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>.
--Keep track of which airlines are better about matching rivals' offers; it may be worth changing your preferred carrier. United, for example, has a reputation for being accommodating.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
