				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Carla Koehl<p>In the municipal-bond market, some cities are more fashionable than others as a destination for investors<p>IN:
Los Angeles; Charlotte, North Carolina
Don't let January's tremors or last year's debt downgrade fool you: Los Angeles isn't a complete basket case. A resilient economy and declining reliance on defense make it a chic (if risky) muni bond buy. Charlotte's bonds are already triple-A rated, but the city is bolstering its hot reputation by building a convention center and emerging as a banking-industry powerhouse.<p>OUT: 
Houston; Portland, Oregon
Despite an expanding economy and strength in the health-care industry, Houston's not home free yet: Its bondholders are still unconvinced of the merit of a recent debt restructuring. Meanwhile, despite a triple-A debt rating, Portland could have difficulties if its revenue is hurt by new state-imposed limits on property tax.<p><p>

