	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Another Sort of Market Timing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Another Sort of Market Timing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>Glance a moment at those newspaper charts that show the minute-to-minute movements of the Dow Jones Industrial Average. These days, there's often a big upswing in the index right before the stock market closes--a fact that was confirmed recently in a study by Robert Exler, a trader in Pittsford, New York.<p>According to Exler, moves in the last ten minutes of trading tallied a net gain equal to 89 percent of the Dow's entire gain during his seven-month study. "From 3:50 p.m. on, it's like clockwork," he says. Market watchers say the last-minute gains have been pronounced lately and agree they're caused by computer-controlled stock buying and large institutional traders. But is there any lesson for individual investors?<p>Well, investors who have already decided to sell a stock--especially a stock that's a component of the Dow--should think about instructing their brokers to make the trade "at the close." This doesn't guarantee a sale at the exact closing price, but "unless there's a market crash and the system is shut down, the trade will almost always be executed during the last few minutes," says Michael Grenon, a broker at PaineWebber.<p>Of course, big downdrafts in share prices sometimes happen at the end of the day, too, and could make this strategy a loser. But in the current bull market there have been more upswings than drops. For now, the odds seem to favor late-afternoon sellers. Exler thinks this may reverse whenever the market turns: Then, he says, late-day buyers may have an edge.<p>One caveat, echoed by market vets: Only trade "at the close" if you're going to trade anyway. The aim, says Laszlo Birinyi of Birinyi Associates, should be to get a better price or a better value--not to second-guess the big traders.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

