	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Investing in Onetime Enemies</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Investing in Onetime Enemies</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>With the collapse of castro's Cuba apparently near and pressure growing for the U.S. to drop restrictions on investing in Vietnam, investors face new options as timely as the headlines.
Already, several Vietnam funds are poised to accept American investors whenever the embargo is lifted. And a Cuba fund is promoting itself in the U.S., even though it can't make direct investments in Cuba.<p>Is it time to think about betting on soon-to-be-former foes? Most observers say the bigger Vietnam is also the better prospect, with a stabilizing economy and good trade potential. Despite Cuba's onetime status as a go-go U.S. satellite, its post-Castro future is still far from certain.<p>But even with all restrictions lifted, neither country will rival the hottest foreign markets anytime soon. "Investors should realize that [Vietnam and Cuba] are not Mexico," says Mark Ahern, who manages the International Investment Group at SEI, a financial-services company in Wayne, Pennsylvania. "After the hoopla is over and markets are in place, investors can make intelligent decisions. These first funds, however, have nothing to invest in."<p>So far, that's almost literally true: All four existing Vietnam funds are almost totally in cash because virtually any investment in Vietnam amounts to outright speculation. Prospects may brighten when a stock market emerges as planned.<p>Cuba isn't even open to capitalist-style investing yet. But the country is tantalizing to investment types who remember it as a big U.S. trading partner before the 1959 revolution. Thomas J. Herzfeld & Co. in Miami, which manages the new Cuba-oriented Carribean Basin Fund, is buying into U.S. companies it thinks will prosper when the embargo is lifted--particularly in construction and transportation. It also helps fund expatriate Cuban businesspeople who plan to return when Castro is out of power.<p>Another risky but legal play is to buy pre-Castro Cuban bonds, which might be honored by a new government. A series of 1937 bonds has been in default since it came due in 1977. As Castro looks more vulnerable, trading in the bonds has warmed up on the New York Stock Exchange. But they still go for less than 50 percent of face value.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
