	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Funds That Go the Extra Mile</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Funds That Go the Extra Mile</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Dean Robinson<p>Airlines are battling to woo customers by offering frequent-flier miles for everything from hotel stays to flower purchases. This year the fight may expand to another forum--investing.<p>So far, only American Airlines has made the link by offering one frequent-flier mile for every $10 invested in one of three money market funds. But other carriers, currently noncommittal, may follow. InsideFlyer, a publication that tracks the frequent-flier market, says miles for money should be catching fire by the end of 1994.<p>American's plan performs respectably enough: Last year, its AAdvantage Money Market Fund ranked 15th of more than 200 funds in its class, according to Lipper Analytical Services. But mileage-conscious investors won't be happy until competition boosts the range of investment options and number of miles offered. Says Randy Petersen, editor of InsideFlyer, "This will be a win-win-win situation--for airlines, funds, and individuals." <p>American's funds, which are managed by an arm of parent AMR, require an investment of $10,000, a lot for a low-return vehicle. And at current rates, it takes a huge investment (or a long time) to earn free flights. Michael Lipper of Lipper Analytical thinks other frequent-flier tie-ins may emerge but raises some unresolved questions--whether the miles are taxable, for instance.<p>American recently pushed its funds by offering double miles. But investors may want to watch instead for the airline's competitors, which generally don't have parents with investment services, to hook up with major banks or mutual fund companies. Within two or three years, says Petersen, frequent-flier deals for investing will be as common as they are now for credit cards or long-distance calls.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
