<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Bread Making Recipe</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Bread Making Recipe</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
You can trade features without eating any losses - if you have an ear for fashionable grain.<p>Soft red winter wheat
Ready to be harvested at a tasty price on the Chicago Board of Trade this month. Despite a potentially soggy spring, July futures on this Midwestern wheat should be a great deal compared with competing strains, which haven't produced a decent harvest in two years. A good buy at $3.10 a bushel, says Patrick O'Connell, an analyst at Chicago's Refco Group.<p>Hard red winter and spring wheat
The wheat that makes bread and pasta is likely to trade at ridiculous premiums over the next few months on the Minneapolis and Kansas City commodities exchanges. Even blending last year's disastrous grains with potentially healthier 1994 crops won't push prices below $3.25 a bushel--and analysts say investors shouldn't buy any higher than that.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
