<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-How To Rate a Low-Rate Card</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-How To Rate a Low-Rate Card</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Deborah Pont<p>While most interest rates dally in the single digits, credit cards still carry an average annual rate of 17 percent. And though many issuers are waiving annual fees or offering incentives, those high rates still hurt. Small wonder that consumers are snapping up a new breed of bank cards with rates as low as 6 percent from institutions such as Wachovia, Citibank, and Signet.<p>But unlike the last card rush--toward no-fee plastic such as <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>'s Universal Card--this new category has hefty entry requirements. Because they can't afford bad credit risks, low-interest cards accept only 20 percent of applicants, making them twice as picky as their high-rate brethren. Even some card users with an unblemished record from a credit bureau such as Equifax may get shut out. And those who are approved may get a measlier credit line than they expect (often less than $1,000), limited services, or a low interest rate that's good only for the first year or two.<p>Still, low-rate cards can save lots for anyone with revolving debt. How to qualify:<p>--Cut your debt-to-income ratio, a key figure calculated by low-rate card issuers. Add your monthly credit-card and housing costs. If the sum is 45 percent or more of your pretax income, you probably won't get approved--so throttle back on spending for a while. High-interest card issuers, by contrast, may accept ratios as high as 75 percent.<p>--Consolidate your credit. Don't keep more than four credit-card accounts active at a time. And if you opened more than two new accounts in the last six months or so, you're unlikely to get a low-rate card. <p>--Get well below the credit limits of your other cards--and always pay at least the minimum payment on time. Don't use more than 80 percent of any revolving credit line.<p>--Apply to an easy mark. According to Gerri Detweiler, executive director of Bankcard Holders of America, national issuers such as Wachovia, Signet, and AFBA Industrial Bank may accept people who have been rejected by other low-rate cards.<p>--Haggle. If you're rejected, it's likely the work of a computer. Get a human on the line. Many credit managers are willing to listen to arguments, and they must tell you why you were rejected. It may be something that's easily fixed, such as having one credit card too many.   
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:T">AT&T Corp.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
