<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Trading On Your Goodwill</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Trading On Your Goodwill</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
 <p>Beware of so-called 19c3 trading. The strategy, most recently being touted by Smith Barney Shearson, steers investors' trades away from the cost-effective New York Stock Exchange--and sends them to more expensive arenas.<p>The term 19c3 comes from a rule that allows certain NYSE stocks to be traded over-the-counter. There's little reason to do this, however: The Big Board's transaction costs are among the lowest around. What's more, the NYSE often pairs buyers and sellers who specify a share price other than the market's quoted price, allowing better deals. Except for Smith Barney, 19c3 trading is a relative rarity on Wall Street. Dean Witter uses it to some degree, for example, but <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> apparently quit some time ago.<p>Internal Smith Barney documents claim the practice results in better executions for customers. That's unlikely, since Smith Barney pays brokers an incentive to use the company's 19c3 desk, which may in turn increase costs by tapping an outside firm to execute orders. That's not disclosed to customers. Nor do many customers know that their NYSE-stock trades may not be made on the NYSE--a virtual guarantee that they'll pay "ask" price rather than getting a shot at the lower "bid."<p>So why is Smith Barney pushing it? Non-Big Board trades carry a higher markup and generate more revenue for the firm, but Smith Barney's passion is mostly a holdover from its acquisition of Shearson, a big believer in 19c3.<p>It's hard to prove that 19c3 trading is always more expensive. But those Smith Barney incentives must come from somewhere and --one way or another--it's likely from the customer's hide. How to avoid 19c3? Always specify that NYSE trades must be executed on the NYSE. If you don't get such a promise, yank your account.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
