<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Dealing With Retroactive Tax</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Dealing With Retroactive Tax</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Dean Robinson<p>for high-income earners, the budget passed in August didn't just increase taxes for 1994--it applied the hike all the way back to the start of 1993. The result: Come April 15, rich folks may find that a hefty extra payment is due.<p>Now is the time to deal with this. The retroactive tax can be paid in equal chunks over the next three Aprils. Everyone should take this option: In effect, it's an interest-free loan from the Internal Revenue Service. To raise the yield of the "loan" while ensuring you don't get caught short, tax planners recommend setting aside money now for all the extra tax. Hand over a third in April and put the rest somewhere safe, such as CDs that mature in time for the other two payments.<p>There are a few caveats. If you'll be subject to the alternative minimum tax, you can't pay in installments: Start putting away money now. Also, if you're likely to file an extension, do at least enough planning to make sure you overpay the first installment. If you undershoot by too much, the entire amount comes due.<p>Finally, remember the psychological aspect. Financial planner Jack Blankinship says he's advising clients to pay in three chunks but will write only one check himself. "To hell with it," he says. "I'll pull the bandage off quickly. I just don't want to deal with it."<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
