				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Bearing Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Andrew Gluck<p>They missed the bull run of the last three years, and their predictions of economic Armageddon have been wrong. But the trio of brainy money managers known as Comstock Partners remain locked in their bear cage.<p>Lately the pessimism has been paying off. Comstock's $540 million Strategy Fund was up 12.6 percent in the first nine months of 1993, for example--five points better than the showing of the Standard & Poor's 500.<p>"We think the wind is beginning to blow our way," says Stanley Salvigsen, Comstock's chairman. Perhaps the nation's most articulate bears, Comstock's principals think a crisis will eventually trigger a 40 percent drop in stock prices.<p>Among their current plays:<p><a name="NYSE:TGT"></a><b>Tenneco</b> (TGT). The company wants to deliver more value to shareholders. Salvigsen thinks it'll succeed by unloading a farm-equipment unit.<p><a name="NYSE:SFX"></a><b>Santa Fe Pacific</b> (SFX). Santa Fe plans to sell off its gold-mining division, and Salvigsen says the price it'll fetch isn't yet reflected in the company's shares.<p>Gold stocks. If financial markets break, investors will flock to gold. Comstock owns big-name miners such as <a name="NYSE:ABX"></a><b>American Barrick</b> (ABX), L<a name="NYSE:NEM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11076"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Newmont Mining</b></a> (NEM), <a name="NYSE:PDG"></a><b>Placer Dome</b> (PDG), and <a name="NYSE:HM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10739"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Homestake Mining</b></a> (HM).  
 <p>

					</font>
