	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-The Credit-Card Shuffle</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-The Credit-Card Shuffle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Emanuel Howard<p>In an effort to prop up credit-card profits, banks are finding new ways to wring extra interest from customers without raising rates. The latest ruse:18 of the 25 biggest card issuers--including, most recently, Mellon Bank and BankAmerica--now backdate interest charges to the moment a purchase was made. Previously, interest was charged starting when the card issuer was notified of a sale, usually two or three days later.<p>The change doesn't matter much if you're among the 29 percent of credit-card users who pay their full balance every month. But if you're less dutiful, it's important to know that the meter is now ticking from the moment you reach for your wallet.<p>For an average card user who spends $200 a month, the new policy adds $1 to each bill, according to Cardholder Management Services, a consumer group. That's probably not enough to force you to switch cards, but it's certainly annoying.<p>By backdating interest, card issuers can earn money on your debt even before they take possession of it. Here's how it works:When you buy something on credit, the store gets reimbursed by its own bank. Then the store's bank gets paid by the card's issuer. The process takes an average of 2.5 days--and the card issuer doesn't have an out-of-pocket expense until the very end.<p>Card issuers argue that once they've authorized a sale, they've guaranteed that debt, so they're entitled to interest from the time of the transaction. But such moves have prompted ire on Capitol Hill. Congressman Charles Schumer is sponsoring a bill that would require issuers to make little-noticed policy changes far more obvious. "If we can raise consumer awareness about the real costs, it will be more effective than regulating rates and charges,"says Randolph Harrison, a legislative aide at Schumer's office. "Credit-card companies are very creative at undermining regulations." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

