	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Medicaid Moves the Posts</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Medicaid Moves the Posts</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>If you want to take advantage of Medicaid--for yourself or for a parent--better get moving. New rules make it harder to finagle the help that can be a key to affording long-term medical care, and President Clinton's health-care plan may prompt further changes by 1995. One thing hasn't changed so far, however:Those who plan ahead can still qualify for government aid while protecting their nest eggs.<p>Medicaid was designed to help people with minimal assets. But the program can be a money saver even for wealthy folks. To get coverage, claimants give their assets away, usually to family members who'll allow use of them. The government frowns on such maneuvers, so officials check to see if applicants have met the low-asset rule throughout a "look back" period. If you transferred property recently, you can't get benefits.<p>Until August, the government looked back 30 months. Now it's 36 months. Setting up a trust fund to transfer assets is also tougher: The look-back period for this rich person's trick has doubled to five years, and some trusts don't protect assets anymore. Another new rule means your house can be seized if you don't transfer it properly.<p>Even attorneys find this stuff confusing; get lots of advice. But in general, these Medicaid planning tools should still work:<p>- Gifts to family members.<p>- Irrevocable trusts.<p>- Family limited partnerships.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
