	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Bargain Hunt</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Bargain Hunt</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Only a few retailers pitched their stocks just right at a recent consumer-sector conference: Most issues were either too cold (<a name="NYSE:ANN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14959"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ann Taylor Stores</b></a>, with more trouble ahead)or too hot (Bombay Company, already a Wall Street darling). The true bargains convincingly combined two themes --efficient operations and financial strength:<p><a name="NYSE:BBY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10209"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Best Buy</b></a> (BBY), an electronics discounter based in Minneapolis, is poised for a profit breakout as it takes advantage of the troubles of other retailers. The company's ability to grab 17 percent of the Chicago market in just one year shows strength that will help it grow beyond the Midwest.<p><a name="NASD:SFWR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43235"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Software Etc. Stores</b></a> (SFWR) is another survivor set to capitalize on the woes of rivals such as Egghead. The company, which sells software and video games, is riding an explosive market:It projects industry-wide sales of 70 million high-end video-game cartridges in 1993, up from 30 million in 1992.<p><a name="NASD:QRSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16312"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quickresponse Services</b></a> (QRSI) is a good way to play the retail industry's drive for efficiency. Its database and electronic "highway"allow retailers and suppliers to exchange orders, invoices, and product information. Conference host Robertson Stephens thinks the company, which recorded revenue of just $13.3 million in fiscal 1992, will break into the black in fiscal 1993.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
