<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Prepaying Your Mortgage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Prepaying Your Mortgage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>Conventional wisdom says prepaying your mortgage is smart: Owning a home free and clear is a true status symbol for the 1990s.<p>But while prepayment can be shrewd for some, the strategy is no longer a sure thing. With fixed mortgage rates hovering around 7 percent, there are probably better things to do with your money.<p>However tempting it seems, don't focus on lopping years from your payment schedule. The key fact is this:When you prepay a fixed-rate mortgage, your pretax return is always equal to the mortgage rate.<p>That's good and bad. On one hand, your 7 percent return is guaranteed. On the other, 7 percent won't get you very far.<p>Some people should prepay, mainly those who have already funded most of their financial goals. And anyone who's risk averse may appreciate the psychic reward of paying off a mortgage--no small consideration in uncertain economic times.<p>But you can't take a psychic reward to the bank. Here are five things to do before prepaying your fixed-rate mortgage:<p>*  Pay off other debts. They're usually more expensive than mortgages and probably aren' tax deductible.
*  Create and fund a retirement plan.
*  Create and fund a college-tuition savings plan.
*  Build up some liquid reserves (but don't go overboard).
*  Buy disability insurance.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mortgages, Homeowner, Real Estate Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

