		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-It Doesn't Pay to Prepay</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-It Doesn't Pay to Prepay</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Jim Jubak<p>"Value" investing--looking for stocks with unrecognized value--has been hot for a year now, and the big-name stocks are pretty picked over. But don't despair:Plenty of less-familiar issues still trade far below their basic worth, says value vulture Scott Black, founder and president of Delphi Management.<p>At Delphi, Black manages $550 million for more than a dozen big institutions. He's shown an 18.5 percent annualized return since 1980 and notched 8 percent in the first half of 1993.<p>Black buys only stocks that trade well below the average price-to-earnings ratio of the S&P 500. He looks for companies that sell near the book value of their assets, have little debt, and show rising earnings. Three of Black's current favorites:<p><a name="NASD:ACCMA"></a><b>Associated Communications A</b> (ACCMA) Owns valuable cellular franchises and a 16-million-share chunk of cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. Black sees value of $30 a share--50 percent higher than recently.<p><a name="NASD:HDCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13618"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hadco Corp.</b></a> (HDCO) A circuit-board maker, Hadco is trading at just nine times 1992 earnings. With the stock trading near book value of $7, there's little downside.<p><a name="NASD:SERF"></a><b>Service Fracturing</b> (SERF) As oil rigs multiply again, this debt-free service company is back in the black. Shares trade at $5.25, not far above book value. Black sees a move to $8.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
