		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-At Ransom to the Rich?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-At Ransom to the Rich?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Jim Jubak<p>In a few months, we'll know whether the rich will slam the U.S. economy into reverse.<p>President Clinton's economists have already knocked a quarter point off their anemic forecast of 2.5 to 3 percent growth for 1994. But that tiny notch was likely just the first of many downward revisions prompted by the budget bill.<p>One reason: Although the tax increases were widely expected, few wealthy people have increased their withholding or made higher estimated-tax payments. That means 1994 will be unusually tough for the upper-bracket set. The rich will face higher withholding, 1993's retroactive taxes, a 2.9 percent Medicare payroll tax, and a possible health-care levy.<p>Such burdens may stall economic growth:The top 5 percent of taxpayers account for more than a quarter of all taxable income. If they slice spending to pay their extra tax, rather than dipping into savings, the effects will be felt throughout the economy.<p>Economists are split about whether this will happen. Allen Sinai of Economic Advisors Inc. has trimmed his estimates but isn't panicking. Believing the rich won't cut back much, he predicts the economy will eke out 2 percent growth for three years.<p>Others are far less sanguine. "I call [the budget] the recession act of 1994," says Lacy Hunt of HSBC Holdings, the banking giant. Hunt notes that many high earners are actually small businesses, which won't hesitate to cut costs. He looks for two quarters of decline at the end of next year--a real-life recession.<p>Tax advisors, who know high earners best, are closer to Hunt's view. William Clapp of Bessemer Trust believes his clients will cut back rather than dip into capital.<p>All this suggests a strategy for investors:Watch the rich and get set to buy bonds. There's almost no chance that growth will beat the official forecast for 1994. But if high earners start cutting back more than the government expects--which seems likely--the downside surprise could shock the Federal Reserve into cutting interest rates, a plus for bonds.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Government, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
