	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Investing: The Bargain Rack</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elif S. Armbruster<p>
Last year's overhyped offerings from designers <a name="NYSE:DK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42555"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Donna Karan International</b></a> , Guess?, and <a name="NYSE:MGX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47767"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mossimo</b></a> are now selling at steep discounts to their initial-public-offering prices. But the punishment handed out to most of the group has put one gem on sale. <a name="NYSE:DSH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51178"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Designer Holdings</b></a> (NYSE: DSH), which markets Calvin Klein sportswear under a 40-year licensing agreement, soared from $18 a share to $34 within ten days of its May 1996 offering. Since then the shares have dipped to a recent price of $18.13. Selling at only 14 times estimated 1997 earnings, the company has a solid balance sheet and recently won the license to market Donna Karan jeanswear. Ryan Jacob of IPO Value Monitor expects earnings to grow 40 percent in 1997, which could send the price to $28. Take that, Donna.	<p>
KEYWORDS:fashion, retail, public offering

					</font>
