<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Investing: Taking the Lies Out of Earnings</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Investing: Taking the Lies Out of Earnings</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						As growth slows, companies are tempted to manipulate earnings<p>
By Gregory Millman<p>
Earnings. investors rely on no other number as much. It's the starting point for valuing a stock and has become the most important indicator of a company's short-term performance. Falling earnings can set off a stampede of selling. Rising earnings can send a stock soaring. Earnings momentum -- a strategy that says to buy stocks when the underlying corporate earnings are growing at a faster and faster rate -- is probably the most popular investment technique in today's market.<p>
But earnings are becoming an increasingly less reliable tool for investors as changes in executive compensation and accounting practices give corporate officials both a reason to bend the rules and greater leeway in doing so. "The informativeness of earnings has clearly gone down over the past three decades," says Baruch Lev, a professor at New York University's Stern School of Business. Add in the current pressure on corporate officers to keep earnings climbing even as the economy slows, and investors would be smart to put all earnings numbers under a microscope. "We're seeing a deterioration in the overall quality of earnings," observes Robert Olstein, who manages the <a name="FUND:OFALX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OFALX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Olstein Financial Alert Fund</b></a> in Purchase, New York.<p>
Some of what Olstein calls "deterioration" is tantamount to outright fraud. The greatest concentration of problems, says George Diacont, chief accountant for the Securities and Exchange Commission's Division of Enforcement, seems to be in the high-growth, high-technology companies, exactly the industry sector favored by earnings-momentum investors. The methods range from creating fictitious sales to keeping the books open a day or two after the end of a quarter to record additional revenues.<p>
But outright fraud is only a small part of the problem, according to Martin Fridson, chief high-yield strategist at Merrill Lynch. Most of the accounting used to massage earnings is legal and, indeed, conforms to accepted accounting practices. Nonetheless, says Fridson, the result is widespread distortion. He regularly sees financial reports from companies that have lengthened depreciation schedules to minimize write-offs for aging equipment or that force inventory on distributors and count those transactions as sales. "A prime candidate would be a company with an extended record of high earnings growth that is now going to find it more difficult to maintain that momentum. Those are the companies that will resort to accounting gimmickry," explains Fridson.<p>
The current problem with earnings extends far beyond high-tech high-fliers and companies that issue new stock. <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, for example, was able to make its earnings projections for the quarter ended September 30 only by incorporating extraordinary asset sales into operating revenues. <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a> have both pursued aggressive accounting policies in recent years, according to Olstein.<p>
Why all of this monkeying around with earnings now? It's the result of two trends. First, many corporations have moved to a pay-for-performance system that ties managers' compensation to higher earnings. Says Fridson, "There is a direct interest on the part of management to have earnings go up. Their contract is tied to the number, no matter how phony it is, no matter how much trickery is involved in producing it." The SEC's Diacont agrees. "Any time you create an incentive for management to falsify the financial statements, you will see increases in falsification," he says. <p>
Second, the recent slowdown in corporate earnings has put pressure on executives to match the heady profits of the past few years. Earnings increases for the third quarter of 1996, for example, were the lowest since 1992. The result: more manipulation, predicts Fridson. "Analysts are already getting poised for this," he says. "At this point in the cycle, you really have to be on your toes."<p>
Yet investors are to blame as well. In their single-minded focus on earnings growth, they have been entirely too accepting of the accounting tricks used to deliver that growth. Fred Speece, a partner in the Minneapolis-based money-management firm Speece, Lewis and Thorson is more blunt, saying, "Investors have been ignoring quality of earnings."<p>
All this has led some experts to conclude that earnings reports are losing relevance as a measure of corporate performance. <p>
Part of the problem is with the earnings number itself. Accounting was designed for the days when most assets were tangible. Now the most important part of many businesses is intellectual. "The accounting system simply cannot deal with change," says New York University's Lev. For example, the common practice of drug and technology companies' expensing research and development -- that is, charging long-term research against current earnings -- makes future earnings look better because the expense of producing the income is not properly matched against the revenues. "In the early years of a project," says Lev, "because of all of this expensing of R and D, you get very low, sometimes even negative earnings. Then later, when those investments start to pay off, you get inflated earnings and an overstated picture of profitability." <p>
The quality of corporate profits can make a big difference to investors. In a recent study, Richard Sloan of the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business examined 30 years' worth of data on the differences between reported earnings and operating cash flow. Sloan found that, although it takes an average of three years for the market to catch on, the price of a stock with manipulated reported earnings will ultimately fall to the level predicted by that company's cash flow.<p>
Sloan came up with a handy rule of thumb that investors can use to determine if a company's earnings reflect financial reality or the CEO's fantasy. <p>
Sloan's quality-of-earnings ratio rates a company by first calculating the difference between reported earnings and operating cash flow -- the actual flows of cash in and out of the company unadjusted for such non-cash costs as depreciation of a building or equipment. He then adjusts the figures for a company's relative size by dividing this figure by the company's total assets. Companies with the smallest difference between reported earnings and cash flow are at the top of Sloan's list, while those with the widest differences are near the bottom. Historically, a portfolio that bought the stocks of the 10 percent of companies at the top of the quality-of-earnings ranking, and that sold short the stocks of the 10 percent of companies at the bottom of the ranking, produced a 10 percent annual return -- with virtually no market risk.<p>
Can investors use Sloan's study to select better investments? Absolutely. Obtain the latest quarterly earnings report from a company you're interested in, or retrieve the report electronically on the Internet from the Security and Exchange Commission's Edgar Database (<a HREF="http://www.sec.gov/cgi-bin/srch-edgar">www.sec.gov/cgi-bin/srch-edgar</A>?). Find the number for total net income on the income statement. Then go to the cash-flow statement, where you'll find a line for net cash used in operating activities. Subtract that number from the net-income figure to get cash earnings. Then divide the result by the company's total assets to get the earnings-quality ratio.<p>
Sloan advises investors to look for stocks that have a ratio near zero. Such a company is reporting earnings honestly, since it shows almost no difference between reported earnings and cash flow. The higher the ratio, the more likely it is that the company's reported earnings are giving a misleading picture of the enterprise. Sloan's study shows that a quality-of-earnings ratio of 0.15 is enough to put a company in the bottom 10 percent of all companies. Any company with a quality-of-earnings ratio of 0.20 or higher should be treated with extreme suspicion.<p>
KEYWORDS:
earnings report, quarter, profit, loss

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:KO">The Coca-Cola Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:DIS">The Walt Disney Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:S">Sears, Roebuck and Co.</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:OFALX">Olstein Financial Alert Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
