				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Investing: The Power of the Employer Match</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The cash that an employer puts into your 401(k) provides a remarkable cushion against market crashes. Even during the worst 5-, 10-, 15-, and 20-year markets in history, a 50 percent match would have ensured that an investor fully committed to stocks did better than an investor on the sidelines in safe three-month Treasury bills.<p>
Period
Total personal contribution
After-tax net portfolio
After-tax annual return
Pre-tax annual return on Treasury bills<p>
5 years (1928 to 1932)  
$3,600  
$3,948  
4.62%  
2.54%<p>
10 years (1929 to 1938)  
$7,200  
$10,331  
7.80%
1.02%<p>
15 years (1929 to 1943)  
$10,800  
$17,001 
6.19%
0.73%<p>
