	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Investing: Wired for a Rebound</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Investing: Wired for a Rebound</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Do cable TV's copper wires offer investors a golden opportunity?<p>
By Paul Davies<p>
Scorned by consumers, vilified by regulators, and weakened by a massive debt load, the cable-TV industry was ill-equipped to face a frontal attack by fast-growing direct-broadcast satellite TV. No wonder Wall Street, smelling blood, has driven cable stocks down 23 percent over the past year, reducing cable-company shares to valuations virtually unseen in a decade. Now, however, prices are so low that the smart money is looking among cable stocks for bargains. <p>
"The fact of the matter is cable companies are not going out of business," says Mark Boyar, a New York money manager and principal of Mark Boyar & Co. "Yes, there is going to be more competition. And yes, they have to spend a lot of money to upgrade their systems. But when push comes to shove, cable is going to be on top. And with the stocks trading at ridiculously low levels, the patient investor can make a lot of money."<p>
It's not that cable companies don't have real problems. Their traditional markets are mature, cash flows don't cover interest payments at many companies, and upgrading to digital service is both pressing and expensive. It's just that the competition is not quite as formidable as many investors fear. <p>
Consider the threat from direct-broadcast satellite services -- the companies that deliver 200 channels over an 18-inch, $399 dish. Despite an initial surge in orders, customers are beginning to recognize satellite's limitations, including high cost and the lack of local programming. Worst of all for heavy TV users, each dish delivers only one program at a time, forcing two-TV homes to buy two dishes. Nor can satellite effectively compete in offering interactive services, such as Internet access or home banking. As a result, sales have slowed to the point that one retailer in Dallas offers the dish for one dollar if the user commits to a year's worth of programming at $400. <p>
As for the rivalry between cable companies and other telecom providers, "the competition is [also] somewhat overblown," says Tom Wolzien, an analyst at Sanford Bernstein & Co. in New York. The telephone companies (both local and long-distance) are distracted at the moment as they try to invade one another's turf.<p>
Cable's competitive advantage is simple: It offers vastly superior capacity and speed compared with its wired and wireless competitors. And by the end of this year, many companies will have begun implementing digital-system upgrades that add more channels through digital TV-set-top boxes, that provide Internet access using cable modems, and that pave the way for offering telephone service. About half of the 65 million cable subscribers should be connected to upgraded systems by 1998, according to a recent report by Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette. Time Warner plans to spend $4 billion between 1996 and 1999 to upgrade its equipment, while analysts estimate that TCI's cost to upgrade will be $10 billion. "They are not spending this kind of money on a hunch," says A'isha Ajayi, a professor of information, technology, and telecommunications at the Rochester Institute of Technology.<p>
So which stocks should an investor pick? The best bets are those companies that own both cable and non-cable assets, including satellite, wireless communications, and programming. <p>
<a name="NYSE:COX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43269"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cox Communications'</b></a> (NYSE: COX) aggressive equipment upgrade -- 36 percent of its system -- makes it the most attractive stock (and one of the most expensive) for investors who believe cable companies will profit from the rollout of new services and increased channel capacity. Part of the company's upgrade includes adding telephone switches; analysts estimate Cox can capture 20 percent of the telephone markets in which it operates. Unlike most other cable operators, Cox makes a profit, has a healthy balance sheet and an excellent customer-service record, and serves high-density areas, allowing the company to reach the most customers with the least expense.<p>
<a name="NASD:CMCSA"></a><b>Comcast</b>, the fourth-largest cable operator (Nasdaq: CMCSA) in the U.S., also owns stakes in QVC's home-shopping network; in Sprint Spectrum, a provider of personal communications services expected to debut in 1997; in the Teleport Communications Group, a telecommunications venture; and in professional basketball and hockey teams in Philadelphia. Growth in cash flow -- 42 percent in the first nine months of 1996 -- enabled the company to spend $300 million to upgrade systems and deliver new services as well as repurchase $186 million worth of shares. At $16.50 a share, Comcast is trading at 45 to 50 percent of its estimated intrinsic value, according to Mark Boyar. Value investor Michael Price purchased 617,100 shares during the third quarter of 1996.<p>
<a name="NASD:TCOMA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14891"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tele-Communication-TCI Group</b></a> (Nasdaq: TCOMA) is the riskiest -- and therefore the cheapest -- of these three stocks. CEO John Malone recently cut capital spending on existing systems from $2 billion to an estimated $750 million for 1997. Although this will slow the effort to upgrade the system to digital, the increase in cash flow should help TCI lower its $14.5 billion debt. Revenues will also benefit from TCI's 30 percent stake in Sprint Spectrum. In September, TCI began offering the @Home Network, which provides Internet access using a high-speed cable modem for $35 a month.<p>
KEYWORDS:cable, television, industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

