<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Investing: Regaining the Edge</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Investing: Regaining the Edge</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						After 30 years, the world has caught up to Value Line's original system<p>
By Michael Peltz<p>
At an age when most of his peers have headed to Florida to clip coupons, Samuel Eisenstadt remains in New York, researching cutting-edge computer technologies, such as neural networks and genetic algorithms. The 74-year-old statistician is seeking to improve the Value Line stock-ranking system, which he created more than 30 years ago under the direction of the investment-advisory firm's late founder, Arnold Bernhard. The system -- which has more than 100,000 subscribers but is a bible to many times more investors, who use its one-page reports when researching stocks -- has been slipping of late.<p>
As the 1980s began, a portfolio of the 100 stocks awarded the number-one ranking by the Value Line Investment Survey outperformed the Russell 1000 Index five out of six years, but in the past ten years it has beaten that index just three times, according to Mark Hulbert, publisher of The Hulbert Financial Digest. Although research chairman Eisenstadt maintains that Value Line should work in all markets, the system -- which, by looking at such factors as earnings surprises and price momentum, ranks 1,700 widely traded stocks on a scale of one to five, in terms of their expected 6-to-12-month performance -- has lagged in exactly the kind of momentum-driven market in which it should excel.<p>
"When it was first introduced, it was a bold, brilliant stroke, but the insights captured in the ranking system are no longer unique," says <a name="FUND:GPAFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GPAFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Guardian Park Avenue Fund</b></a> manager Charles Albers, who began his career at Value Line in the mid-1960s. A growth investor, Albers prefers the stock screens of Guardian's computer models. In fact, professional investors now have access to analytic tools that track the same factors Value Line uses to rank stocks. Eisenstadt admits the competition has caught up. "The system probably worked better in the early years," he says, "and we're looking at ways to improve it."<p>
Bernhard began research during the depression to develop what his daughter and current Value Line CEO Jean Bernhard Buttner calls "a rational approach to the evaluation of stocks." Bernhard initially performed the analysis by plotting company earnings by hand on a transparency and superimposing the transparency on a price chart to create a "value line." In 1946, Eisenstadt joined the firm as a proofreader and introduced Bernhard to statistical analysis, which enabled Value Line to consider multiple variables (dividends, book value, interest rates, price lags, market yields) to predict whether a stock was under- or overvalued. The system, however, was better at picking when to buy or sell a specific stock than at determining which stocks were the best to own. "Each stock had its own formula, but they were not necessarily comparable," says Eisenstadt. Then, in 1965, Eisenstadt fashioned one formula -- using the ten-year trend of relative earnings, price performance, and recent price and earnings momentums -- that worked across all stocks. (Earnings surprise, the degree to which earnings exceed or fall short of analysts' estimates, was added in 1968.)<p>
Part of Value Line's appeal has been its simplicity. "If you can count to five, you can use the system," says Buttner. The 100 stocks rated one for timeliness should outperform the 300 rated two, which should in turn do better than the 900 threes, 300 fours, and 100 fives. A portfolio of ones, however, tends to have much larger price swings than the overall market. "This greater volatility explains why Value Line's lead over the market shrinks when its gains are adjusted for risk," wrote Hulbert last fall. <p>
Eisenstadt says this is because the system favors stocks with dynamic earnings. It's also why the flagship firm's mutual fund, the Value Line Fund, doesn't simply mimic the Value Line ranking system, but actively selects holdings from issues ranked one or two (or occasionally even three).<p>
The decline in the system's performance is unlikely to mean that investors will begin to drop their Value Line subscriptions. Most subscribers don't use Value Line as a formal stock-picking system. "It's a valuable research tool," says David Dreman, manager of the Kemper-Dreman Funds, who worked as an analyst at Value Line in the mid-1960s. "It's a quick down and dirty on a company. You can't buy a stock on what they tell you, but you can dismiss one."<p>
Eisenstadt wouldn't entirely disagree. "Just get rid of the fours and fives from your portfolio and you'll do well," he says. "The system almost does better at signaling the poor stocks than at picking out the winners."<p>
But he's not satisfied with that answer either. Value Line hopes to recapture the success of the survey's early years with an expanded edition, introduced in March 1995, that ranks 1,800 more companies. "The inefficiencies, and the potential opportunities, are greater in the expanded survey," says Eisenstadt, because the companies tend to be smaller and not as widely followed. Unlike the original, the new survey doesn't include forecasts and comments from analysts. And since earnings revisions are not meaningful for many  small-company stocks, the new survey depends on price and earnings momentum, earnings acceleration, and relative cheapness to estimate performance.<p>
The initial results seem promising. According to Eisenstadt, a portfolio of the 100 stocks ranked one in the expanded survey was up 76 percent from inception through November 1996 (although Hulbert estimates commissions would cut that return by about half).<p>
Eisenstadt expects that fans of the original survey, even those who can't afford to buy all 100 stocks ranked one, will continue to use the system to build portfolios. Eisenstadt, who has tried unsuccessfully for years to reduce the number of top-ranked issues to a more manageable size, offers a simple compromise. Pick any 12 to 15 stocks from the group of one-ranked issues. "Unless you're really unlucky," he says, "your performance should match that of the larger group -- but only if they're selected totally at random. <p>
"I'd almost say throw darts at a list of the group ones," he adds, the twinkle in his eyes revealing, for him, the limits of scientific research.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
mutual fund, rate, rating

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:GPAFX">Guardian Park Avenue Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
