				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Cover: Number Two</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						His Heart Is in His Trees<p>
By Monica Corcoran<p>
When the second-largest landowner in America surveys his property, he sees trees. Douglas firs, sugar pines, and cedars, to name a few. "I don't think of land in terms of acres," says Archie Aldis "Red" Emmerson, 67, who just happens to own 1.2 million of them. "It's what those acres do for us." Grow plenty of trees for Sierra Pacific Industries, is what.<p>
SPI is the timber company Emmerson founded with his father, Curly, in 1949. The two Emmersons began by leasing a sawmill to cut Douglas firs. Today, SPI is the third-largest U.S. lumber producer and owns more land than any other timber company in California. Red's desire to own tree-producing land is the reason. "My father didn't believe in land," he says in his Douglas-fir-paneled corner office at SPI's headquarters in Anderson, California. "He was from the old school, and he didn't think that far ahead." In timber-industry lingo, "far ahead" means 40 to 50 years into the future, because trees don't grow overnight. <p>
The acreage didn't grow that fast either. "Buying land was always a priority, but I never had any money to do that," he says, recalling the leaner years. The company acquired its first tract of timberland in 1958: 2,500 acres dotted with Douglas firs in Cappel Creek, California. Emmerson liked its potential for reforestation. His largest purchase took place in 1987 when SPI bought 522,000 acres for $460 million. To finance the huge acquisition, he borrowed the money from a consortium of 11 banks. "I hocked my heart and soul to buy land," says Emmerson.<p>
Emmerson's willingness to shoulder onerous debt has paid off and even ensured his company's survival. In the past decade, as environmentalists have fought against timber interests and pressured the U.S. government to restrict logging, many smaller timber companies have been swallowed by larger ones or disappeared altogether, especially those that didn't own a lot of land. Because Emmerson does not depend on access to Uncle Sam's acres, he can be sure the next generation of Emmersons will be timber barons, too.<p>
"One of the main reasons for buying the land is my family," says Emmerson. His children own 68 percent of SPI. Emmerson's son Mark serves as a corporate director and a vice president of the company; his daughter and other son also hold positions within SPI. "I hope the family business will perpetuate," says Red. Like the trees.<p>
KEYWORDS:
people, property, land, real estate, environment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
