	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Why Pay Retail?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						While the Dow sets new highs, closed-end funds sell at record discounts.<p>
By Joanmarie Kalter<p>
Everyone loves a bargain, so why are investors ignoring fire-sale prices on closed-end mutual funds? <p>
Big markdowns (when a fund's market price drops below the value of the assets it holds) currently exist even among the most attractive closed-end funds. One example: <a name="NYSE:GHS"></a><b>Global Health Sciences</b> (NYSE: GHS), a biomedical fund. It returned 67 percent in 1995, yet currently sells for a 23 percent discount to its net asset value, or NAV.<p>
The flood of new closed-end funds that came on the market from 1992 to 1994 -- nearly 230 of the 567 now in business -- undoubtedly is one reason for the bargain prices. Also, many investors who bought shares at initial public offerings didn't realize that they would start off underwater -- Wall Street takes about 6 percent off the top for underwriting an issue. Adding injury to insult, closed-end-fund returns were pitiful in 1994: Foreign funds experienced negative net returns, averaging 19.7 percent that year, and bond funds tumbled 13.5 percent, according to Morningstar, the mutual-fund research firm based in Chicago. <p>
In 1995, when the U.S. stock market exploded, says Donald Cassidy, closed-end analyst for New York–based Lipper Analytical Services, disgruntled investors gave up on closed-end funds to chase the red-hot returns that were available in open-end funds.<p>
Of course, all of this may mean that "it's a great time to buy closed-end funds," says Michael T. Porter, a fund analyst for Smith Barney. "They're selling at fantastic discounts to their intrinsic worth." Tricia Rothschild, an associate editor at Morningstar, adds, "When everyone is throwing up their hands on an investment is exactly when you should be looking at it."<p>
As a matter of fact, discounts in certain closed-end funds have become so compelling that they have attracted the vulture investing crowd. Take famed value investor Michael Price, who is credited with helping to persuade an undervalued Chase Manhattan Bank to merge with Chemical in 1995. According to Securities and Exchange Commission filings obtained through the CDA/Spectrum research database, Price has been snapping up substantial stakes in at least six closed-end funds: <a name="NYSE:OST"></a><b>Austria Fund</b> (NYSE: OST), <a name="NYSE:CEE"></a><b>Central European Equity Fund</b> (NYSE: CEE), <a name="NYSE:CLM"></a><b>Clemente Global Growth Fund</b> (NYSE: CLM), <a name="NYSE:BTO"></a><b>John Hancock Bank & Thrift Opportunity</b> (NYSE: BTO), <a name="NYSE:NAF"></a><b>New Age Media Fund</b> (NYSE: NAF), and <a name="NYSE:GF"></a><b>New Germany Fund</b> (NYSE: GF). Porter speculates that Price may wait for the discount to narrow or else try to force the managers of those funds to narrow the discount through share buybacks or by converting the funds to an open-end format, which would eliminate the discounts.<p>
To reap profits from closed-end funds, investors need to understand exactly how they differ from their more familiar open-end cousins. Like an open-end fund, a closed-end fund is a portfolio of stocks or bonds -- either concentrated in U.S. securities or invested around the world. But that's where the similarities end. Investors buy and sell shares in an open-end fund directly from the fund, which issues new shares as new money flows in. A closed-end fund, on the other hand, issues a fixed number of shares in an IPO. After that, investors buy and sell shares on the market (usually the New York Stock Exchange) just as if they were trading a company stock. Unlike an open-end fund, which is always sold at the net asset value of the stocks and bonds it owns, a closed-end fund may be priced higher than the NAV (a premium) if demand is strong. When investors shun a closed-end fund, its shares trade below the NAV (a discount). <p>
This creates some interesting possibilities for someone who likes to purchase a dollar's worth of assets on the cheap. Let's say an investor buys a closed-end fund that has posted some disappointing returns lately. With an NAV of $10 per share, that fund could be trading at $8 -- a 20 percent discount. If the investments in the fund perform well and the NAV increases, the fund's shares should rise in value (as long as the discount remains the same). But a fund that's doing well is also likely to attract other investors. This, in turn, should narrow the discount, as more investor money seeks a limited number of shares. Say the fund's NAV rises to $12 a share -- a 20 percent increase. And suppose the markdown also narrows so that a share sells for $11. In this case, an investor would reap the increase in net asset value and get a boost from the narrowing discount as well -- for a total return of three dollars on an initial eight-dollar investment, or 38 percent.<p>
Historically, that's how savvy investors have profited from closed-end funds. They buy an out-of-favor issue that's ready for growth, hoping to capture the increase in its net asset value and be doubly rewarded as its discount narrows. Even if things don't work out and the NAV stays flat, an investment in a closed-end fund could be profitable as long as the discount narrows.<p>
Seth Anderson, professor of finance at the University of North Florida, has found that closed-end funds trade in bands, rising and falling but trending back toward an average near their NAV over time. He says an investor can buy at a 20 percent discount, sell when the discount narrows to 10 percent or 15 percent, and, after commissions, reliably outperform the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index by two percentage points a year.<p>
Still, in today's market for closed-end funds, an investor can't buy just any fund that sells at a discount and expect to make money. But lately, the discounts have actually been getting wider rather than narrower. The <a name="NYSE:GCH"></a><b>Greater China Fund</b> (NYSE: GCH), for example, sold for a 3 percent discount at the end of 1995. Although its net asset value rose 16.6 percent in the first nine months of this year, the share price actually fell by half a percent because the discount widened to nearly 17 percent.<p>
Instead of looking for just any discount, investors should "find a fund that's selling at a bigger discount than it usually does," says Smith Barney's Porter. In fact, investors should concentrate on funds selling near their record discount. Within that group, look for funds with features that could cause the discount to shrink -- for example, a manager with a sterling track record. In some cases, great managers who run open-end funds (and charge a load) also run closed-end funds that sell at a discount. That's the case with the highly respected team at Templeton; its closed-end <a name="NYSE:TDF"></a><b>Templeton Dragon Fund</b> (NYSE: TDF), which invests in Asia, currently sells for a 19 percent markdown. Another choice is the <a name="NYSE:UKM"></a><b>United Kingdom Fund</b> (NYSE: UKM), which is managed by Mercury Asset Management. United Kingdom has outperformed its benchmark for the past five years and now sells for 14 percent off its NAV.<p>
Investors shouldn't have any trouble finding funds that are selling at historically wide discounts. If, for example, a fund usually sells at 15 percent below its NAV but now sells for 20 percent off, that fund might be a good buy -- as long as similar funds are not selling at even higher discounts, of course. For a list of funds that are currently trading in the bargain basement relative to past discounts, see "A Value Buyer's Shortlist," on page 124.<p>
According to Morningstar, the average domestic-stock fund today is trading at a discount of 10.9 percent --  compared with 5.8 percent at the end of 1992. Foreign funds are currently selling at an average discount of 12.2 percent and bond funds at 9.4 percent. "The number of funds trading at more than a 15 percent discount is as large a list as we've seen in the last ten years," says Adam Shapiro, the president of Advantage Capital Management in Philadelphia.<p>
Another potentially profitable strategy: Ride the coattails of predatory buyers like Michael Price and hope they succeed in forcing the discounts to narrow. Because closed-end funds are selling at such large discounts to their intrinsic values, Smith Barney's Porter says, "I think you're going to see a new wave of buyer, a hostile type of shareholder who will come in and say, 'I want to see this discount closed.' In fact, we may be seeing signs of it already in the Austria Fund and the <a name="NYSE:SHF"></a><b>Schroder Asian Growth Fund</b> (NYSE: SHF), which have provisions allowing them to buy back shares or ultimately go open-end."<p>
The prices and the net asset values of closed-end funds are printed on Saturdays in Barron's and on Mondays in The Wall Street Journal. To compare a fund's current discount to its historic discount, either call the fund directly or check out Morningstar's Principia for Closed-End Funds (800-735-0700), which is available on computer disk or CD-ROM. Another resource is the Miami-based Thomas J. Herzfeld Advisors phone service -- Herzfeld Closed-End Funds on Call (305-274-5333) -- which gives daily prices, approximate discount/premium data, and addresses and phone numbers for more than 250 closed-end funds.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/6pages.gif"><br>About 6 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
