<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Tips</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Tips</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						PROCRASTINATION PAYS
Thinking of buying shares of a mutual fund before year-end? Think again. Most funds pay out the capital gains they realized during the year in November and December; this could leave you with a big tax bill. Call the fund company to find out the date you can buy into a fund ex dividend and move those gains into next year.<p>
GOOD TIMING
Now may be a good time to buy stock in time-share companies -- while other investors are still focused on the $5.5 billion industry's sleazy past, says Brian Thorkelson of the <a name="FUND:LUOGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LUOGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lutheran Brotherhood Opportunity Growth Fund</b></a>. An industry shakeout that favored well-capitalized and better-managed companies has benefited <a name="NYSE:FFD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10545"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fairfield Communities</b></a> (NYSE:FFD ) and <a name="NASD:SIGR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Signature Resorts</b></a> (Nasdaq: SIGR). Thorkelson says Fairfield's 1997 earnings are projected to reach $1.52 a share, but may rise as high as $1.75. Signature recently doubled its size with the purchase of Avcom International and could earn $1.15 a share in 1997.<p>
THE 9.5 PERCENT SOLUTION
Although the 30-year bond yields 7 percent or less, there's an A-rated closed-end fund that pays 9.5 percent. <a name="NYSE:CSP"></a><b>The American Strategic Income Portfolio III</b> (NYSE: CSP) sells at a 14.4 percent discount to net asset value (see "<A HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9701I07.html">Why Pay Retail?</A>" ). The portfolio has been cleaned up since derivatives caused losses in 1994, says Michael Brilley, head of fixed income for Sit Funds. It's invested in quality diversified residential mortgages.<p>
BRIEFS
A recent study from Ibbotson Associates found that most so-called enhanced-index funds add little value. "Are Enhanced Index Mutual Funds Worthy of Their Name?" appears on Ibbotson's World Wide Web site (<A HREF="http://www.ibbotson.com">http://www.ibbotson.com</A>), or call 312-616-7883....The new no-load Loomis Sayles High Yield Fund (800-633-3330) will be run by Daniel J. Fuss, who also manages the Loomis Sayles Bond Fund, which is rated five stars by Morningstar.... The National Council of Individual Investors now provides information on more than 94 discount brokers. Their World Wide Web site: <A HREF="http://www.ncii.org/ncii">http://www.ncii.org/ncii</A>.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

