<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-The Call of the Wild</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-The Call of the Wild</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						At the other end of the extreme is CGM Realty -- a fund that hopes big risk equals big reward.<p>
By Paul Davies<p>
While Cohen and steers perfect a tried-and-true buy-and-hold strategy, a newcomer to equity real-estate investment trusts is standing conventional wisdom on its head. Kenneth Heebner, the 56-year-old manager best known for his high-octane <a name="FUND:LOMMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LOMMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CGM Mutual</b></a> and <a name="FUND:LOMCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LOMCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CGM Capital Development Funds</b></a>, seems determined to break every rule of real-estate investing to get outsize returns from equity REITs for shareholders in his <a name="FUND:CGMRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CGMRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CGM Realty Fund</b></a>.<p>
Timing is everything, says Heebner. Take his latest position in hotel REITs: "I would expect to be there for six months, but you can't be sure." And don't even think of diversification: Heebner maintains just a handful of stocks. "By selecting a shorter list of stocks, I can add more value. If I needed 150 stocks to hedge against my own poor judgment, I should be in a different business."<p>
But there's no arguing with success. Launched in May 1994, his CGM Realty Fund rose nearly 20 percent in 1995, putting it among the top-returning REIT funds. In the first nine months of this year, the fund has returned 19 percent.<p>
Riding with Heebner may not be for everyone. His funds are famous for their outstanding performance and daunting volatility. CGM Capital Development Fund, for example, was up 99 percent in 1991, but down 23 percent in 1994. "Four out of five years he will be up -- but that fifth year will be real ugly," says Lou Stanasolovich, president of Legend Financial Advisors in Pittsburgh. Yet, over 20 years, CGMCapital Development has produced an average annual return of 21 percent, six percentage points better than the average U.S. growth fund.<p>
In REITs, Heebner says he looks for high-growth prospects. "If I think the cash flow is going to grow very rapidly, I can have a high dividend three years from now -- versus one that yields 8 percent today but isn't going to grow." <p>
Critics abound. Cohen, for one, calls Heebner's high-risk investing style "irresponsible." Heebner's retort: "I guess [Cohen] hasn't seen my results."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:LOMMX">CGM Mutual</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:LOMCX">CGM Capital Development Funds</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:CGMRX">CGM Realty Fund</a><br>

