<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Good for What Ails Them</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Good for What Ails Them</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Recruiting healthy seniors is one key to future HMO profits<p>
By Leland Montgomery<p>
After a decade of rapid growth, managed-health-care companies have been quarantined in the sickroom of late. The industry's symptoms include rising costs, flagging profits, and wobbly stock prices. <p>
But some relief may be in sight. The tonic: a big push by health-maintenance organizations to enroll the 37.5 million (and counting) senior and disabled citizens covered under Medicare. At the moment, only 4.5 million Medicare recipients are signed up with a managed-care provider; the rest use private doctors, who are reimbursed by the federal Medicare system. This leaves a vast market -- one HMOs have found they can tap by offering low deductibles and other incentives. In just the past two years, the number of Medicare recipients enrolled in HMOs has swelled 34 percent.<p>
The new strategy comes at a welcome time for investors with a stake in the industry's fortunes. According to a survey of more than 200 HMOs conducted by InterStudy Publications, a health-care-research firm based in Minneapolis, only 61 percent earned any money in 1995. That compares with 88 percent in 1994. The problem is that HMOs haven't been able to raise prices enough to keep pace with increases in the cost of care.<p>
HMOs, in fact, have become one another's worst enemies. For a time, these businesses were able to expand rapidly by siphoning off business from fee-for-service health-care providers. But as HMOs have grown, they've begun bumping up against one another in the battle for new (and even existing) customers. The result is a squeeze on profits.<p>
Seeking to maintain the growth rates the market has come to expect, some HMOs have also compounded their difficulties by purchasing the health-care operations of traditional insurance companies. This tactic, pursued with the idea of converting the acquired business over to the HMO model, has proved both cumbersome and expensive. <p>
Last year, for instance, United HealthCare, an HMO based in Minneapolis, paid $1.7 billion to buy the 4.6-million-member MetraHealth organization, a joint venture between Travelers Insurance and Metropolitan Life. Similarly, Healthsource, an HMO based in Hooksett, New Hampshire, shelled out $231 million for the 2.4-million-member health-care unit of Provident Life and Accident Insurance. Both of the acquiring companies were optimistic about driving down costs. But those hopes were quickly dashed in 1996, when expenses at the insurance-based plans quickly exceeded the acquirers' rosy forecasts. Healthsource saw its medical-loss ratio (which measures direct health-care costs as a percentage of premiums) rise from 76.6 percent in 1995 to 78.4 percent in the first quarter of 1996. As a result, its stock got pummeled, falling 75 percent in the following months. Reality caught up with United HealthCare in July, when expenses rose from 79.7 percent in 1995 to 84.8 percent in the second quarter of 1996. News of this caused its shares to fall 30 percent in a single day.<p>
Going after the Medicare market looks much more promising for the HMOs. The idea is far from new, but early attempts by HMOs to serve Medicare patients proved frustrating because of government restrictions and fluctuating reimbursement levels. By 1991, few HMOs offering Medicare plans were left. Only in the past few years has the Health Care Financing Administration offered rates attractive enough to draw the HMOs back into the business. <p>
Now companies like PacifiCare Health Systems, based in Cypress, California, and Oxford Health Plans, based in Norwalk, Connecticut, are among the faster growing HMOs, largely because of their emphasis on Medicare. "It's a tremendous opportunity for the HMOs," says Clifford Hewitt, a health-care analyst with the New York–based brokerage firm Sanford Bernstein & Co.<p>
Senior citizens do pose a challenge for HMOs. Few are inclined to give up a long-term relationship with a trusted family doctor, and many are skeptical that an impersonal HMO will provide high-quality care.<p>
But HMOs have economics on their side, because traditional Medicare requires both an annual deductible and a 20 percent co-payment. In contrast, efficient HMOs are finding that it is possible to offer plans with no deductibles and with per-visit charges as low as five dollars. Some include free vision and dental care. <p>
Even with these kinds of incentives, Medicare customers can be highly profitable, according to InterStudy. HMOs collect an average premium of $1,764 a year for non-Medicare patients, while the average Medicare customer brings in $5,280 a year. So while the profit margins for the two groups are required by law to be identical, the Medicare member still brings in three times as much raw profit as the non-Medicare member. Thus, as long as an HMO doesn't attract a disproportionately large number of the oldest (and thus costliest) Medicare clients, it can reap big profits. <p>
At least for the moment, Washington appears content with this arrangement, according to Jack Rosen, CEO of Continental Health Affiliates, a provider of home health-care services based in Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey. Rosen notes that, because the large profits are helping to convert Medicare recipients to lower-cost HMOs, the government still saves money. "If you asked the people at Health and Human Services," says Rosen, "their response would be: 'We need to allow enough profit so that, as the older, sicker population signs up, there will be enough incentive for HMOs to serve them.'" <p>
<img src="/imgs/GRAPH1127b.GIF" width=475 height=210><p>
Not every HMO will succeed, however. "We've seen a huge increase in the number of providers," says Craig Schub, head of marketing for PacifiCare Health Systems. "But there are a lot of risks there that aren't immediately apparent." That's why investors should focus on companies experienced at controlling costs.<p>
One company to look at: <a name="NASD:PHSY"></a><b>PacifiCare</b> (Nasdaq: PHSYB). Already the largest and most experienced Medicare HMO in the country, PacifiCare is in the process of acquiring <a name="NASD:FHPC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13348"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FHP International</b></a> (Nasdaq: FHPC), a California HMO  with a large Medicare membership. The transaction should enable PacifiCare to achieve both greater efficiency and increased marketing clout in its primary base of California, Oregon, and Washington. The company is also slated to receive a 6 percent rate increase in Medicare premiums covering its operations in southern California in 1997. <p>
Another front-runner is <a name="NYSE:UNH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15007"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United HealthCare</b></a> (NYSE: UNH), which recently leaped aggressively into the market by winning a coveted $4-billion-a-year contract with the American Association of Retired Persons to insure approximately 5.7 million of AARP's 33 million members. Despite its recent problems with the MetraHealth operation, United historically has been one of the most profitable HMOs in the nation, and analysts are expecting it to regain that status. Eleanor Kerns, an analyst at Baltimore-based broker Alex. Brown, also believes that United has a good chance of raising its commercial rates in January, when nearly half of its contracts are up for renewal. <p>
<a name="NYSE:AET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10039"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Aetna</b></a> (NYSE: AET), which sold off its property-casualty business last year to focus on health care, may be the company with the most turnaround potential. Analysts admire the efforts initiated by Aetna's management to transform the old-style health insurer into a cutting-edge HMO. To do this, Aetna bought U.S. Healthcare, one of the most profitable HMOs, and is seeking to apply U.S. Healthcare's more aggressive culture and business approach to managing the 12 million members in Aetna's HMO plans.<p>
In the short term, HMOs may continue to report disappointing earnings. But because Wall Street has battered virtually the entire industry, this may be a good time for investors to snap up shares of industry leaders on the cheap.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:PHSY">PacifiCare</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:FHPC">FHP International Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:UNH">United HealthCare Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:AET">Aetna Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
