<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-At the Top of Their Game</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-At the Top of Their Game</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Can hard work and experience keep Cohen and Steers at the top of the heap?<p>
By Paul Davies<p>
Martin Cohen gleefully recalls the moment three years ago when a jealous investor accused him of practicing "voodoo real estate." At the time, real-estate prices were still tumbling in the wake of the go-go 1980s. Yet the fund run by Cohen and partner Robert Steers, which buys real-estate investment trusts, was surging ahead at a rate of 15 to 20 percent a year. "I don't understand it," the rival investor said. "I can't believe the returns you're getting. This must be a Ponzi scheme." <p>
Cohen and Steers, however, are hardly witch doctors or bunco artists. During the past five years, they've consistently outperformed their peers by displaying a better understanding of the market's dynamics than anyone else. Since its inception in 1991, their open-end mutual fund, Cohen & Steers Realty Shares, has bested all its competition and even beaten the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index -- by an average of 1.5 percentage points a year. This year, the fund has continued its surge, returning 17.1 percent through mid-October, compared with the S&P 500's 15.4 percent.<p>
The success enjoyed by Cohen and Steers also parallels the resurgence of REITs as investments. As a class, REITs -- basically, listed securities that pool investors' money to buy property -- have done even better than stocks during the past five years, earning an average annual return of 13.8 percent versus 13.6 percent for the S&P 500. The subgroup of equity REITs -- those that invest in property as opposed to those that hold mortgages -- have also been extremely attractive as income investments. In the past ten years, they've paid an average annual yield of 7.8 percent, edging out both the 7.7 percent yield on ten-year Treasury bonds and the average 6.95 percent yield offered by the stocks that compose the Dow Jones Utilities Average. "I keep telling everybody, 'It doesn't get any better than this,'" says Cohen.<p>
The two partners rely mostly on hard work, discipline, and their uncanny talent for spotting new trends. "Cohen and Steers really understand real estate," says Robert Frank, director of research for the Baltimore-based brokerage firm Legg Mason. "They were in this business early. They know where all of the bodies are buried, and they have a good knack for picking stocks." <p>
Investors with long memories should be forgiven any lingering skepticism about REITs. In the 1970s, most REITs were run by "out-and-out crooks," says Lou Stanasolovich, the president of Legend Financial Advisors in Pittsburgh. Cebra Graves, an equity-fund analyst with Chicago-based Morningstar, notes that REITs were "badly structured in the '70s, and there were lots of hucksters running the funds. Then in the late '80s, real estate collapsed." Cohen and Steers began managing real-estate investments together in the 1970s, first at Citibank and then at National Securities & Research. By the time they established their own firm in 1986, many of the players in the field had gone broke or were in the process of doing so.<p>
Exercising the strict discipline necessary to succeed amid this troubled environment, Cohen and Steers focused on fundamentals, not fads. The selection process they developed then and have since refined is "90 percent science and 10 percent art," explains Cohen, 47, the president of the firm. (Steers, 43, serves as chairman.) <p>
Like other real-estate analysts, the two pore over appraisals and perform on-site surveys when evaluating the properties held by REITs. But success, says Cohen, a Brooklyn native who has an MBA from New York University, also involves picking the right sector of the market in which to target their investments. "You have to be early," he says. The fund's big move into retail REITs last fall -- shopping centers and strip malls -- is a typical example of how such a sector-oriented approach can pay off.<p>
"The world was totally gloomy about retail," recalls Cohen. "All the major retailers were struggling. Kmart was rumored to be going bankrupt, and even Wal-Mart was struggling to post any growth in same-store sales. Our analyst who follows retail companies was despondent.<p>
"But," he says with a grin, "they were the cheapest stocks in the entire industry. You were getting 8 to 9 percent dividend yields -- far above yields in the private real-estate market -- at a price-to-earnings ratio of only ten. Furthermore, the Federal Reserve had loosened monetary policy that July, and there's anywhere from a 9-month to a 15-month lag between a Fed action and its effect on the economy. We decided to overweight the sector." With retail REITs up over 14 percent in 1996, the gambit has already paid off handsomely for the fund.<p>
Cohen and Steers constantly tinker with the fund's weighting in different sectors, such as offices, apartments, and shopping centers. Yet they still manage to maintain a low portfolio turnover of 23 percent a year, thereby helping to minimize their expenses.<p>
"Marty's great strength is his ability to be a pure thinker," says Steers, who lives in Rye, New York, and whose hobby is playing ice hockey. "He is constantly coming up with unique ways to look at the industry."<p>
Recently, the fund has reduced its holdings in the retail arena -- to 30 percent of its portfolio (which reflects a normal market weighting) from its onetime high of 45 percent. They used the proceeds from selling retail REITs to up their stake in office REITs (to a weighting double that of the industry index). <p>
"We like offices because there is no new construction. Rents are rising and will continue to do so irrespective of the economy," Cohen says, adding that offices also offer a layer of protection that other real estate can't. "They will do well in a recession because, with long leases, the rents are locked in." Steers agrees and adds, "The [office sector] valuations are probably fair, but the growth prospects looking out three to five years are so solid in our view, and there is so little risk associated with them, that it makes our holdings worth keeping."<p>
Steers generally focuses more of his efforts on picking which individual REIT stocks are best for the fund to buy. While the 16-person firm operates out of modest offices in midtown Manhattan, they spend lots of time evaluating the major properties of the REITs the fund owns. The firm also maintains close ties to property managers and developers. <p>
When selecting property, Cohen and Steers look for strong management and well-structured deals. Contrary to popular belief, good real estate has less to do with "location, location, location" and more to do with "people and money," Cohen says. "To me, a class-A property is one that flows cash like crazy."<p>
That thinking is what prompted Cohen and Steers to dump their holdings in the Rockefeller Center Properties REIT two years before financial problems sent Rockefeller Center into bankruptcy. The financial structure of the deal that formed the REIT, Cohen says, was designed "to make money for the Rockefeller family but not for investors." The firm sold its holdings at $18 a share -- before they plummeted to as low as $4 a share in 1994. <p>
Cohen insists that their style isn't overly risky: "I hope we are criticized for being too conservative." <p>
The industry, too, has changed radically since its troubled early years. Today's property managers, argues Cohen, are interested more in increasing shareholder value than in merely obtaining higher management fees. And for investors worried that the bull market is nearing its end, REITs are an attractive defensive play because they often behave differently from stocks or bonds. Over the past ten years, the returns on equity REITs have correlated with the S&P 500's performance only 65 percent of the time, according to accounting firm Ernst & Young. When stocks took a beating in July, for example, REITs were up 5 percent. <p>
As REITs have worked their way back as credible mainstream investments, the amount of assets managed by Cohen and Steers has ballooned -- to $2.9 billion of the $61.6 billion invested in all equity REITs. Their flagship fund, Cohen & Steers Realty Shares, manages $1.4 billion.<p>
Fortunately for Cohen and Steers, the REIT market has grown along with the size of their fund. Since 1991, the total market capitalization of publicly traded REITs has increased 160 percent to more than $100 billion, according to the National Association of Real Estate Investment Trusts, a nonprofit industry association based in Washington, D.C. Overall, there are now more than 300 REITs. One reason for this revival: REITs can provide higher income to investors than other equity investments. Unlike corporate profits, which are first taxed and then paid out as dividends, REITs are not taxed as long as they pay out a minimum of 95 percent of their rental income each year. (These dividends are taxable income to REIT investors.) <p>
Despite its grown-up appearance, however, trading REITs is still a game suited more to small, nimble funds than large institutions. The average daily trading volume for the top 200 equity REITs is a mere 54,000 shares a day, but the normal-sized position for a fund like Cohen & Steers Realty Shares is ten times that amount. As a result, trading in and out of sectors, as is Cohen's preferred method, has to be accomplished over several weeks to avoid jostling share prices. <p>
Ken Gregory, publisher of No-Load Fund Analyst, worries that the burgeoning size of Cohen and Steers's fund could eventually hamper the ability of its two managers to invest in some of the smaller sectors of the REIT industry. The fund's largest shareholder, Kaspick & Company, a Palo Alto, California, asset-management firm for colleges and universities, has also shown some concern. It is considering shifting some of its investments into other REIT funds. "This is nothing against Cohen and Steers, but we like to be broadly diversified in every asset class and by portfolio-manager styles," says managing director Scott Kaspick. <p>
<img src="/imgs/GRAPH1127a.GIF" width=475 height= 210><p>
Cohen and Steers are also facing more and more competition. Since the end of 1991, the number of funds investing in REITs has grown from 6 to 51, according to Morningstar. Many of these funds are small enough to navigate the market more nimbly. They include <a name="FUND:CREEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CREEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Columbia Real Estate Equity</b></a> ($30 million in assets), <a name="FUND:Crabbe"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/Crabbe"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Crabbe Huson Real Estate Investment</b></a> ($14 million), <a name="FUND:LLREX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LLREX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Longleaf Partners Realty</b></a> ($41 million), and <a name="FUND:CGMRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CGMRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CGM Realty</b></a> ($86 million). In fact, CGM, which tends to dart in and out of thinly traded REITs (see "<A HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9701I04.html">The Call of the Wild</A>") has lately outperformed Cohen & Steers by a solid margin. <p>
"You'll see a more competitive environment going forward," says Cohen. Yet he insists that the size of the firm can also be an advantage. "Go to almost every one of our competitors," he says, "and you'll see, at most, one manager and an analyst trying to cover 300 REIT issues. We have an investment staff of eight -- we simply start out with a better chance of success."<p>

