	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-At the Center of the World</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Egypt, the linchpin of ancient empires, is the key to the Middle East and its oil<p>
By Walter Russell Mead<p>
The most important country at President Clinton's October summit on the Middle East was the one that didn't come. Egypt, the largest and strongest Arab nation, was the first to make peace with Israel. As long as the Egyptian army stays in its barracks, Israel faces no serious military challenge to its security. And as long as Egypt gives political cover to the Saudis and Kuwaitis, oil will flow from the Persian Gulf to gas pumps in Cleveland and Atlanta. Congress knows Egypt's importance: Egypt is, after Israel, the largest single recipient of U.S. foreign aid.<p>
Negotiations between Palestinians and Israelis are Egypt's great chance to escape its own poverty. Peace in the Middle East can bring the billions from private investors necessary to create jobs for the millions who live in Cairo's slums. It will keep a stream of tourists climbing the pyramids, booking hotel rooms, and hiring guides. It could make the land bloom, just as the summer floods that washed down the Nile for millennia turned the desert green.<p>
But peace is a fragile dream in the Middle East. In 1995, an Israeli extremist murdered Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin for making peace with the Palestinians. In 1981, Muslim fanatics assassinated Egyptian president Anwar Sadat for making peace with the Israelis. Today in Hebron, Jewish settlers proclaim it a holy duty to drive all Arabs out of the land God promised to the Jews. In Cairo, terrorist groups wage a campaign to build a revolutionary Islamic state.<p>
Time is not on the side of the peacemakers. Egypt's population is projected to double to 120 million by the year 2026. Only a massive influx of American foreign aid -- $2.2 billion in 1995 -- has kept inflation under control and allowed the country to invest in some of the infrastructure its exploding population requires. Unfortunately, the U.S. now looks set to cut back on its foreign aid, even to major recipients like Egypt.<p>
Egypt's economy must grow at 7 percent a year -- the kind of growth produced by the economic miracles of East Asia -- simply to keep living standards from falling, and it must create approximately 500,000 new jobs to keep unemployment stable. With per-capita gross domestic product at a miserable $2,400 a year, there isn't much room for error.<p>
Unfortunately, after a trip to the country, I have to conclude that the best-intentioned efforts of U.S. and other international economists and planners aren't working very well. We have encouraged the Egyptian government to apply the same economic cookie cutter -- privatize government enterprises, reduce inefficient workforces, bring in international capital -- that experts have applied from Buenos Aires to Moscow. Such a program will not work in Egypt.<p>
This does not mean that I've returned a total pessimist. Egypt has muddled through for centuries, and the country has strengths that aren't fully appreciated in the West. In our fixation with Iran, where a radical Islamic regime overthrew an American ally and turned the country from one of America's most reliable friends to one of its most bitter foes, we tend to ignore the unique character of Egypt's Islamic tradition -- and the way that it is shaping a specifically Egyptian response to 20th-century capitalism.<p>
The streets of Cairo may be as close as human beings can come to creating absolute chaos. In and around the great Khan al-Khalili bazaar, the medieval streets are narrow and twisted. But that doesn't stop taxis, cars, and delivery vans from trying to make their way past mounds of exotic, sharp-smelling spices, heaps of beans and rice, piles of tourist bric-a-brac (tiny pyramids, sphinx figurines, reproductions of ancient inscriptions on papyrus, hand-carved chess sets, and, of course, T-shirts), crowds of shopkeepers, heavily burdened laborers, and stunned, bewildered tourists. Trucks, pedestrians, and bicycles try to thread through the camel market, where camels are sold for food as well as transportation. In other parts of the city, great concrete overpasses try to move the traffic over the crowded ancient streets, but nothing affects the constant congestion of this dust- and smog-choked city of almost seven million.<p>
Nobody thinks much about lanes; Egyptian drivers seek open space either in their own lane or on the opposite side of the street. Car horns -- what locals call the Egyptian brake pedal -- blare constantly. Obeying traffic lights is optional.<p>
You could, I suppose, argue that this is the triumph of pure laissez-faire. Without all those government regulations, every driver uses private initiative to maximize his speed. The result, theory tells us, is that the invisible hand guides Cairo's traffic better than policemen and stop signs ever could.<p>
I had had quite enough of watching the invisible hand by the time I arrived at the Finance Ministry. But the minister's office was cool, quiet, and civilized. His secretary brought me a cup of hot, sweet coffee -- and didn't make a sound as she carried it over the lush Oriental carpet. I sank back into my comfortably upholstered chair and sighed with contentment. By the time the eloquent finance minister, Mohieddin Elghareeb, began to explain government policy, I was ready to consider the possibility that Western economic theory wasn't laughably irrelevant.<p>
American diplomats and Egyptian leaders think that the country's problems are economic and demographic. Egypt's population is growing at 2.3 percent a year -- a horrendous problem for a country where 95 percent of the land is uninhabitable. "We have two basic problems," Elghareeb explained to me. "First, we need to attract more investment. Our savings rate is too low, and too many Egyptians send their savings abroad." Like rich Latin Americans, who spend their money and often educate their children overseas, rich Egyptians have been famous for decades for their spending sprees in the casinos and fleshpots of Europe.<p>
"In 1995," he continued, "we made some progress in bringing Egyptian capital back into the country, but we have not yet attracted enough foreign money." He said that Egypt needs to double or triple foreign investment from the 1993 level of about $453 million and pointed to the success of Malaysia, which, with a much smaller population, attracted almost ten times that amount.<p>
"The second problem," Elghareeb told me, "is the legacy of the past." State socialism in the 1950s and 1960s has left the Egyptian economy crippled and driven some of the most energetic and creative businesspeople out of the country. Since the mid-1980s, the Egyptian government has been laying the foundation for economic reform. The role of government planning in the economy has been scaled back: Regulations on foreign-capital investment have been liberalized, the banking sector has been opened up, and many controls over prices have been abolished. Key industries such as tourism have benefited the most from liberalization, and the foreign exchange that tourists bring to Egypt has become an engine of growth.<p>
Now the government is looking to privatize some of the industries that former president Gamal Nasser nationalized in the 1950s and 1960s. Politicians have stuffed state industries with their relatives, in-laws, and old friends from the village. Turn these industrial turkeys over to private industry, figure Egypt's strategists, and government spending will shrink, productivity will rise, and foreign investment will pour in.<p>
It won't work. Don't take my word for it -- just read the centuries-old history of Egypt as a "developing" country evident in the buildings of Cairo. For example, the 12th-century Citadel, originally built by Saladin, the famously chivalrous Islamic ruler who waged a jihad against the Crusaders, rises above the graveyards and housing developments of the eastern part of the city. By the time Napoleon's army occupied Egypt in 1798, much of the Citadel had fallen into decay, but it was extensively repaired and rebuilt by the great Muhammad Ali, the first of Egypt's modernizing rulers.<p>
Ali is a key figure in Egyptian and world history. He was one of the first rulers of a non-Western country to understand that, to survive, his country had to import ideas and technology from the West. As I wandered through his carefully preserved palace, I saw the heavy, elaborate wood furniture he imported from France, and I marveled at the tapestries, clocks, and other Western novelties he introduced.<p>
The three-year French occupation opened a period in which Britain and France competed for influence and economic control. At the opening of the Suez Canal 127 years ago, the empress Eugénie of France and the Prince of Wales attended a glittering series of receptions and balls, capped by a performance of Verdi's Aida, which had been commissioned for the occasion.<p>
Since Napoleon's time, the  Egyptian ruling elite -- headed at times by khedives, kings, or presidents -- has tried to do two things: adopt enough Western technology and techniques to strengthen Egypt against outsiders, and spread enough money around domestically to keep everybody happy. Over and over again, Egypt's relationship with the West concentrated power and money in the hands of small, privileged groups of elites -- even as those elites changed. Government officials and members of the aristocracy learned foreign languages, studied in foreign schools, and acted as intermediaries between foreign investors and governments and the Egyptian economy. Modern Egyptian politics has revolved around a struggle between the "ins" at any given moment -- the people with access to Western capital and connections -- and a powerless majority. Nationalism has been the rallying cry of the impoverished, as have socialism and Islam.<p>
Egypt's dilemma today isn't new -- centuries of contact with the developed West have thoroughly defined the problem. Opening the country to foreign investment tends to concentrate wealth. Commercial agriculture pushes peasants off the land and into the cities. A drive for economic efficiency reduces employment opportunities in the short run. The biggest danger, of course, is that economic reform will do just enough to loosen the repression that keeps the lid on in Egypt, but not enough to prevent the rise of some radical political regime. Today, we call that the Iran scenario. In the 1950s, it produced the radical pan-Arab regime of Nasser.<p>
Cairo, like all big cities in the developing world, is a magnet for the ambitious, who want a better future than their rural villages can offer, and for the desperate, who cannot earn a living from the land. I wanted to see the place where all these people had come from. A driver I met in Cairo came from a large family headed by a lay Muslim religious leader in a village outside of Cairo. It was a chance to see rural Egypt and make my first contact with the country's Islamic traditions.<p>
As my Mercedes passed the last of Cairo's straggling cement-block suburbs and reached the rich farm country south of the city, the land turned shockingly green. In the village itself, scores of children flocked around our car as we slowly negotiated the narrow dirt road that ran between tightly packed two- and three-story houses, shops, and mosques. My guide, born and raised in the village, was eager to show me the glories of the place. Our parade went past cow barns and thatch-roof donkey stalls that looked like something out of a Christmas manger scene. I admired the ancient rusty and complicated irrigation pumps and the intricate network of channels through the fields. The pump that brings Nile water up to the farmland is now electrified, and chemical fertilizers are used in the fields to grow new strains of crops. But the labor in the fields hasn't changed much from the days when Cleopatra passed by in her barge.<p>
My guide invited me into the spotlessly clean (the floors were all dirt, but they had been rigorously swept) though spartan home. The kitchen and fireplace were outside, in a courtyard behind the house. His mother was baking bread over burning dung in a traditional brick oven. His father, who appeared to be in his mid-60s, offered me tea as we sat on the low wooden chairs and iron-framed cots in the largest room in the house. I tried not to think about how dangerous the water must be and offered cigarettes all around, smoking one myself to be sociable -- my sixth in 20 years.<p>
The problems the village faces, he said, are simple. Taxes are too high, and the young people can't find work, so they leave for the city.<p>
On the other hand, because a high-ranking government official was born in the village, it has been able to get electricity. According to my host, the people of the village are extremely pious and have built dozens of mosques.<p>
At this point, we were joined by the bearded fortysomething muezzin -- a Muslim crier who calls the hour of daily prayers -- of one of the mosques, and the discussion turned to religion. We talked about how life without God isn't worth living, how all of us must look to God's mercy on Judgment Day, and how important it is to raise children with a strong religious faith. The sunset call to prayer sounded, but with exquisite courtesy, my host and his friends continued our conversation. They wanted to know how Americans felt about God and Egypt and were happy to hear that, in general, we have a positive impression of both. A few more cigarettes and glasses of hot, sweet tea and it was time to go.<p>
As we wandered the dirt roads around the village searching for Cairo in the moonlight, I had plenty of time to think about the implications of what I'd seen in city and town for the plans of the bureaucrats. Consider privatization, for example. Where were the people who were leaving the village going to find jobs? Mass layoffs in privatized state firms would destabilize Egypt. But from the government's perspective, the starving peasant who would no longer find work as a tea boy in an Egyptian office, the underemployed assembly worker, and the day laborer aren't the biggest problems. The unemployed university graduate, a potential professional revolutionary, is much more dangerous -- which makes reducing the bloated ranks of middle management in the state sector politically explosive. <p>
The Egyptian government's approach to these problems combines a modicum of economic liberalization and tourism promotion with political crackdowns. Economic liberalization is intended to stimulate investment but cannot be permitted to cause mass layoffs. The political crackdown aims to crush the more violent opposition. But one policy inevitably contaminates the other. Take the telecom industry. One of the most effective methods anywhere in the world for opening up an economy, reducing costs, and bringing money into government coffers for social programs is to privatize the telecommunications system. In Chile and Argentina, telephone privatization was a major element in economic-reform programs. This would, in theory, work in Egypt, but politics gets in the way. As one cabinet minister told me, Egypt can't privatize its phone system because its security forces depend on wiretaps for the suppression of terrorism.<p>
I wondered how foreign investors felt about this mixture of economic reform and political constraint. From their point of view, the whole world is begging for investment. I could imagine them asking, Why should we get ourselves tangled up in Egypt's political problems? I thought a visit to the stock exchange would give me a quick read on investor attitudes.<p>
Even the grit and grime that blows in from the desert to coat the buildings and surfaces in Cairo can't hide the elegance and solidity of the 84-year-old stock-exchange building, a reminder of the time when Egypt was one of the world's favorite emerging markets. Briefly after World War II, the Cairo Stock Exchange was actually the third largest in the world.<p>
But then came the revolution of 1952 and 40 years of Arab socialism. The best companies were nationalized and key industries brought under state control; the stock exchange became a sleepy place, with few shares traded and little money made or lost.<p>
Now Egypt wants to wake up the stock market. Government-owned companies are being spun off and sold to private investors through stock offerings: The number of shares has grown from 76 million in 1981 to almost 500 million today, and the number of companies registered on the exchange went from 63 in 1981 to about 700 in 1994.<p>
But all this hasn't restored the stock market to its old glory. Inside the imposing building, more traders seemed to be playing video games than trading securities. The office of the president is a dusty, badly maintained room; his secretary has a desk that would have been at home in a thrift shop.<p>
But like stock-exchange officials everywhere, those on the Cairo exchange were optimistic. I could see their point. Investors might or might not make money on the deals as privatization continued, but investment houses certainly would. <p>
The director was enthusiastic for another reason as well -- one that I admit I hadn't considered. Privatization would actually make Egypt's economy more acceptable to Islamic fundamentalists, he felt. The Koran condemns lending money at interest -- commercial banking -- but praises ventures in which the partners put up shares in equity and participate in the division of profits and losses. In other words, investment banking and stock markets are, when properly administered, very Islamic. The Prophet Muhammad came from a merchant family, and Mecca was the most developed trading city of its region during the Prophet's lifetime. Islam is not necessarily an anti-business ideology.<p>
Anyone who wants to begin to understand Egypt needs to study not just Islam in general but the Egyptian tradition of that religion. The 14th-century Sultan Hasan Mosque, widely considered the greatest Egyptian architectural achievement of its time, is a good place to start. Part house of worship, part house of study, the Sultan Hasan Mosque has a cool courtyard that is an oasis from the noise, heat, and dust of the city. Flanking its distinctive mihrab -- the recess in a mosque's walls that indicates the direction of Mecca -- are four serene halls, each built for the use of one of the four principal schools of orthodox Sunni Muslim thought: the Hanafi, the Shafii, the Maliki, and the Hanbali. Egypt's traditional tolerance is the theme of the Sultan Hasan Mosque, where the four great halls stand for peaceable coexistence among rival theologies. It's as if Saint Peter's Basilica in Rome had four chapels: for Roman Catholics, Lutherans, Presbyterians, and Baptists.<p>
Most Egyptians are Sunnis, not Shiites, and for most of Muslim history Egypt has been a center of scholarship and high Islamic culture. This counts. Unlike the chip-on-their-shoulders Shiites who currently run Iran and think history went horribly wrong soon after the death of the Prophet, Egypt's Islamic theologians have a tradition of subtle and sophisticated attempts to relate Islam to the wider world.<p>
Ibn Khaldun, a 14th-century scholar who spent much of his life in Cairo and one of the world's great historians, typifies the thoughtful, rational approach to Islam that runs like a river through Egyptian culture. In a controversy over whether doctors should rely on medical science or on religious traditions to treat their patients, Ibn Khaldun wrote: "The Prophet (peace be upon him) was sent to teach us the religious law, not medicine or any other ordinary matter." The Koran, in other words, is a guide to religion, but observation and scientific study are necessary to understanding the world around us.<p>
More recently, Muhammad 'Abduh (1849–1905) worked to reconcile Islamic faith with Western ideas. For 'Abduh, the Koran lays out the guiding principles of life, but these must be adopted to special circumstances before they are codified into laws. Islamic societies, he taught, should not be restricted by traditional interpretations of shari'a -- Islamic law. Instead, shari'a must be constantly updated to fit the circumstances in which Muslims live.<p>
While 'Abduh remains a controversial figure, the belief that shari'a and the modern world do not have to be at war with each other is a key idea throughout much of the Islamic world and especially in Egypt. Most of the Egyptians that I talked with do not want to do away with traditional Muslim laws and customs altogether, but neither do they favor narrow interpretations of shari'a that leave no room for the realities of the contemporary world.<p>
The effort to reconcile religion with the modern world is not just an Islamic problem, of course. When ultra-Orthodox Jews stone cars in Jerusalem's streets on the Sabbath, or when Christian fundamentalists seek to block the study of evolution in American public schools, I see parallels to Egypt's struggles with the meaning of Islam. All three great faiths of the family of Abraham took shape before the birth of modern science, and all have struggled and still do struggle to adjust to it.<p>
It is by no means certain that Egypt's traditional brand of cosmopolitan and tolerant Islam will win out. The radical and violent wing of Islamist opposition in Egypt includes two main groups: the Gamaat Islamiya and the Jihad. These groups have roots in Egypt's poorest region -- the south -- and they attract substantial support at the lower end of the social scale. In southern Egypt and among the slums of Cairo, a combination of poverty, suspicion of government, and alienation from Egypt's traditionally moderate Muslim establishment have produced a violent movement responsible for 920 deaths since 1992. Most of the victims have been Egyptian, and the causes often have as much to do with local feuds as with abstract ideologies, but there is no doubt that Egypt is the unwilling host to murderous campaigns of terror aimed at revolutionary social change under the banner of Islam.<p>
Egypt has another type of Islamic opposition grouped largely around the Muslim Brotherhood, which includes many of the well educated but underemployed or unemployed. It was founded in 1928 and declared illegal in 1954. Driven underground, the Brotherhood did not disappear, and despite recurring crackdowns, it has gradually reinserted itself into Egyptian politics. It is committed to bringing Egypt's laws into conformity with its interpretation of Muslim legal norms, but this does not necessarily mean the violent overthrow of the government. Many Egyptians both inside and outside the government hope that economic progress plus political liberalization will lead to the integration of the Brotherhood into "normal" politics.<p>
Before I visited Egypt, like most Westerners I assumed that radical Islamism in Egypt would be the voice of economic protest against the regime. In part, that's true. But the picture is much more complicated. Some of the government's most unpopular reforms -- a land reform, for example, that shortened rural leases, forcing peasants to pay higher rents for their plots -- have actually been backed by some of Egypt's most conservative Islamic groups. The indefinitely long leases that Nasser's socialism introduced, said the sheikhs of Islam, were contrary to Koranic practice.<p>
How do these forces balance out? Egypt could go the way of Iran. Economic misery could increase the size of the small but well-financed Islamic extremist groups.<p>
But I don't believe that has to happen. To an extraordinary degree for a developing country, Egypt's Western-educated officials and traditional Islamic leaders aren't locked into knee-jerk opposition. Intellectuals from both camps operate within a centuries-old debate about how to accommodate Western science and economics to Islamic thought and religion. Unless the current regime of Hosni Mubarak tightens the screws of repression too forcefully (either through miscalculation or out of economic necessity), it is hard to imagine a replay of Iran, where the Shah and his Western-educated government were disdainfully distant from the country's religious powers. <p>
Once, Egypt was the greatest power and center of civilization west of China. It was the breadbasket of the Roman Empire, the source of the grain with which the Caesars fed their people. Its conquest by the warriors of Islam established the new religion as a world power; the defeat of the Crusaders here signaled the end of their dream of rebuilding Christian kingdoms in the Muslim Near East.<p>
Today, Egypt is as important to the U.S. as it ever was to any of our imperial predecessors. It is in our self-interest to create an economic miracle on the shores of the Nile, and for that we need peace in the Middle East. A real peace between Israel and the Arab world could unleash forces of economic growth and investment in the Middle East that could transform the economic condition of millions of ordinary Egyptians. Anything less is unlikely to be enough.<p>
KEYWORDS:
global, international, society

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

