	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-The Value of Cash</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-The Value of Cash</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Clint Willis<p>
Investors have no business holding cash. At least that's Wall Street's current mantra, learned by rote during a decade-long market rally. But there are good reasons to have some ready money (90-day Treasurys, money-market funds, and the like) in your portfolio.<p>
The most important: diversification. Stocks and bonds often move together -- both markets frequently slump when interest rates spike higher. And even some individual international markets and some specific international stocks zig and zag with the U.S. market. That leaves cash as one of the few mainstream investments that provide reliable diversification.<p>
Sure, cash offers lower long-term returns -- but not as much as some investors fear. According to data provided by Ibbotson Associates, since 1950 a portfolio of large-company stocks that matched the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index delivered annual returns of 12.5 percent. By contrast, a portfolio composed of 80 percent large-company stocks and 20 percent cash gained 11.2 percent.<p>
And in exchange for giving up some return, an investor was rewarded with lower risk. The portfolio with cash was 21 percent less volatile. <p>
The results were similar for two small-company stock portfolios -- one all stocks and one with a 20 percent stake in cash. The cash portion reduced returns modestly, from 15 percent to 13.3 percent -- but it also reduced the investor's risk (as measured by standard deviation) from 22.4 percent to 17.5 percent. <p>
An investor who holds cash as part of a portfolio can create new combinations of risk and reward. Note that the portfolio composed of 80 percent small-company stocks and 20 percent cash not only outperforms the cashless large-stock portfolio (a 13.3 percent return versus a 12.5 percent return) but does so with less risk than the cashfree small-stock portfolio and only slightly more risk than the cashfree large-stock portfolio (a standard deviation of 17.5 percent versus 15.7 percent).<p>
True, a genuine long-term investor with the stomach to withstand market gyrations doesn't need cash to smooth out those bumps. He could hold a portfolio of small-company stocks through thick and thin and reap the higher returns that come with the added volatility. But even such a paragon of patience might want to hold cash to take advantage of bargains when they appear -- in a general market downturn, say, or when a sector crashes, as technology stocks did this summer. <p>
In the race to keep pace with the market quarter in and quarter out, professional investors often don't have the luxury of holding cash. Individual investors who worry more about meeting long-term goals than about falling behind an index month to month can afford to be more flexible.<p>
KEYWORDS:Eight Ways to Beat the Pros, strategy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
