<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-The Pros Are Always Watching the Clock</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-The Pros Are Always Watching the Clock</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Clint Willis<p>
Professional money managers are quick to scoff at market timers, who shift large sums of money from stocks to cash when they think a market downturn is due. But the scoffers themselves often engage in more subtle and insidious forms of investment timing designed to improve their job security -- often at the expense of their portfolios' long-term returns.<p>
Most of the timing behavior revolves around quarterly performance evaluations. Just as an unscrupulous chemistry student will falsify his lab book near semester's end, managers spend considerable energy touching up their portfolios before they disclose them to clients. <p>
The most common ploy is to dump shares of a stock that has inflicted losses on the portfolio. "When December approaches, you might want to blow out of a bad stock you'll soon have to show clients you're holding," says Samuel Hayes, Jacob H. Schiff Professor of Investment Banking at Harvard Business School.<p>
Such late-year selling used to result in a January rebound for stock prices as managers moved in to snap up bargains among the discarded shares -- the so-called January effect. But the calendar has moved up: "The selling starts earlier now -- in September or early October," says Michael Metz, chief investment strategist at Oppenheimer & Co. in New York. "Most of the dumping is over by late October, because all the guys who window-dress are trying to beat the other guys to the trade. That's why you see the January effect in early December now."<p>
Another reason for the hurry: Clients now closely watch trades that occur near the end of the reporting period, and if managers sell in the middle of the quarter, clients aren't as likely to notice the transaction.<p>
If the anecdotal evidence is unconvincing, consider a 1991 study by Josef Lakonishok and three of his colleagues at the University of Illinois that confirmed the tendency among managers to sell laggards near the end of the year. They found that during the first three quarters of the year the average fund sells 32 percent more of its big losers (relative to its holdings of those losers) than it sells of all stocks. That percentage rises to 42 percent in the fourth quarter. <p>
Other kinds of even more dubious timing take place at the end of a reporting period. Example: At the end of a quarter, a manager might buy 5,000 or so shares of a thinly traded stock that's already in his or her portfolio. That action alone might be enough to temporarily boost its price. <p>
Finally, Metz notes that timing issues play out differently in different market sectors. For example, if you run a small-company fund, you can keep some losers in your portfolio -- because nobody will recognize their names. Large-company and balanced funds, on the other hand, have to be especially careful about holding losers near quarter's end. "People invest in those funds because they want to limit their risk," says Metz. "They won't tolerate it if you own cats and dogs."
KEYWORDS:Eight Ways to Beat the Pros, strategy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

