<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Don't Try This at Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Don't Try This at Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Clint Willis<p>
Before you start feeling too sorry for the pros, please remember that their sheer size and financial resources do give them the edge in a few areas. And because of those advantages, they can profitably pursue strategies -- most involving short-term trading opportunities -- that individual investors can't. The pros have most of us beat hands down in the following areas:<p>
Access to hot IPO's. Most of the gains in initial public offerings come right out of the box, and the pros know that. That's why they line up -- in order of size and financial clout -- to snap up the most exciting offerings while they're still hot. Brokers use the shares to reward their biggest clients, leaving most individual investors out in the cold. <p>
Trading costs. Portfolio managers can trade at so-called crossing networks, which arrange transfers between large-scale buyers and sellers at a reduced cost: around four to six cents a share on a 100,000-share transaction. That compares with 30 to 35 cents a share if you're trading 100 shares of a $30 stock on your own. The crossing networks also let the pros buy at the median between the bid and asked quotes. Individual investors often pay the higher quote when they buy and receive the lower when they sell. <p>
Information. Every investor is supposed to have the same access to information about public companies, but that isn't how it works. "An analyst's most recent report may say a company will earn $3 -- but as the announcement gets nearer, he may 'whisper' to money managers that he thinks earnings could be closer to $2.90," says Dan Cardell of Weiss, Peck & Greer in Chicago. "There won't be a surprise on the institutional side, but there will be a surprise for individual investors."<p>
Help. Most pros are backed up by traders who can sit in front of their screens all day watching for short-term opportunities. Even money managers who take a long-term approach to investing use that information to make quick buy and sell decisions. Say a company's share price takes a temporary dip for no apparent reason. The trader can quickly phone analysts, who will call up information about the firm and report back to the manager with a buy or sell recommendation. All this happens before you even know the stock has taken a hit. That's one reason an investor like Michael Price of Mutual Shares -- hardly a day trader -- sits in the same room as his trading staff.<p>
That said, immediate access to information tends to encourage short-term trading and second-guessing. Fact is, the pros often abuse their resources -- and given the chance, individual investors would probably do even more damage to their own portfolios with these tools. Maybe we're better off sipping our coffee over The Wall Street Journal. <p>
KEYWORDS:Eight Ways to Beat the Pros, strategy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
