http://www.worth.com:80/articles/Z9701C01.html 204.141.48.165 19970209110307 text/html 38149
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 11:03:28 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=2062700855486208962; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Eight Ways to Beat the Pros</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Eight Ways to Beat the Pros</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Wall Street's money managers earn millions working for America's biggest investors -- which is exactly why you can beat them at their own game<p>
By Clint Willis<p>
When Pensions & Investments magazine ranked the 250 largest money-management firms last spring, the smallest firm on the list, Brandywine Asset Management, oversaw $4.7 billion in assets. The biggest, <A HREF="http://personal.fidelity.com/funds/fund_data/fund_data.html">Fidelity Investments</A>, controlled $431.3 billion. The fees for managing all this money pay for a lot of information and people. Fidelity, for example, claims a research and trading staff of 323.
How can a small investor like you even hope to compete with these titans? <p>
Actually, it's pretty easy. <p>
The reason is that professional money managers at the big investment firms are handicapped when it comes to achieving the highest possible returns. They have to worry about keeping their jobs. And keeping their jobs isn't about maximizing performance. It's about meeting the varied demands of pension trustees, 401(k) sponsors, shareholders, and other clients. <p>
Money managers at the big firms must put huge sums to work every day, yet they can buy only readily saleable assets (in case a big customer wants its money back). They must avoid hard-to-explain investments (no matter how attractive). And they need to steer clear of anything that might cause a short-term surprise (even when the long-term prospects are solid and bright). These requirements mean constant compromises that can reduce the potential for maximum returns.<p>
To keep their jobs, professional money managers typically invest in assets that are popular with other money managers, that get good press, and that are easily explained to folks who know just enough about stock picking to be dangerous. In other words, the pros end up buying expensive investments and shunning cheap ones. <p>
Is it any wonder, then, that 80 percent of these highly paid professionals underperformed the market during the past decade? There are exceptions -- Warren Buffett comes to mind, as well as...hmm....<p>
Of course, the important thing to remember in all of this is that your situation as an individual investor is quite different. As someone with no clients to please and no policy guidelines to meet, you have a huge advantage: You can choose the best investments you can find and hold them until they fulfill the expectations that led you to buy them in the first place.<p>
The good news doesn't stop there. The so-called amateur investor who studies the institutional biases of the professionals -- such as when the big guys overpay and what investments they won't touch -- can use this knowledge to beat the giant institutions at their own game. <p>
Before you can chop down the beanstalk, though, you have to know something about how the big guys really operate. But don't fret -- we're here to help.<p>
We discussed our thesis with 50 money managers, analysts, academics, and investment consultants. We asked each one to tell us about the constraints that hem in even the savviest of pros. Our plan from there was fairly straightforward: Develop a list of these handicaps and then turn them topsy-turvy -- convert the pros' nightmares into positive strategies that individual investors can easily adopt. Along the way, we also inquired about specific investments the pros would dearly love to own but, for one reason or another, just can't (more on this later).<p>
The first thing the experts told us (which we'll call Constraint Number One) is that most money managers have such huge sums to invest that they can't bother with really small companies. As a rule, major institutions won't look at a company with a market capitalization (stock price times number of shares outstanding) of less than $500 million. Lance James, a portfolio manager with mutual fund <a name="FUND:BAETX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BAETX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Babson Enterprise II</b></a>, explains: "You have so much money to put to work that in order to buy a meaningful position you have to buy a significant percentage of the outstanding stock -- which could knock the price up [in a small-company stock] before you even finish buying." <p>
Constraint Number Two: The pros are obsessed with the short term, because their clients are. "When I was running pension money, we'd sit down quarterly with a client who had a stack of papers ranking each of my holdings by performance," recalls Michael Murphy, chief investment officer at Murphy Investment Management in Half Moon Bay, California. "It was really painful. When they saw a loser, they'd say, 'Why do you own this?' And when they saw a loser you'd defended the last quarter, they'd say, 'Why do you still own this?' Rather than explain yourself, you might just sell the thing and take a loss."<p>
Some managers respond to this pressure by buying the stocks or sectors that are hot now -- hoping they'll stay that way at least through the end of the quarter. "When <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a> was selling at 10 times earnings in the '70s, no one was interested," says Jim Crabbe, co-founder of Crabbe Huson Group, a money-management firm in Portland, Oregon. "Now that it's at 40 times earnings, everyone wants it in their portfolios." <p>
Bill Fleckenstein, president of Fleckenstein Capital, a money-management firm in Seattle, adds: "It's like a beauty pageant where you're not trying to find the prettiest contestant -- instead, you're trying to find the one that the judges think is the prettiest."<p>
Other managers try to cope with short-term pressures by sticking close to the indexes. "You won't be criticized if the index goes down and you're invested in the index," says Michael Metz, chief investment strategist at Oppenheimer & Co. in New York City. "If you make picks that go against the benchmark, you'd better be right."<p>
In short, the pros can't afford to overweight anything that isn't already hot -- or about to be. International stocks look cheap? Tell it to your pen pal. "Owning too much international is what we call a CLM -- a career-limiting move," says Dan Cardell, director of quantitative strategies at Weiss, Peck & Greer in Chicago. "It might even be a CEM: a career-eliminating move." <p>
Constraint Number Three for the pros: Cash is trash. Holding cash (90-day Treasurys or commercial paper) means being out of the stock market -- these days an even bigger sin than being wrong. Can't find enough bargains right now? Better put your money to work anyway.<p>
Oh, sure, money managers give lip service to the notion that they'll "take advantage of downturns in the market by purchasing shares at attractive valuations." They use exactly those words all the time in their quarterly reports to shareholders. But, says Bill Fleckenstein, "I don't know how that's possible. The fact is that money managers cannot hold cash because they might fall behind in a bull market -- grounds for dismissal. At my old job at a money-management firm, we all got tremendous pressure about it. I got letters from clients telling me not to hold more than a certain percentage in cash. One client got on me at every single meeting if I held any cash at all."<p>
Appearances also count for a great deal among the pros, a problem we'll call Constraint Number Four. "Being an institutional manager is like living in a small town," says Samuel Hayes, the Jacob H. Schiff Professor of Investment Banking at Harvard Business School. "You're under constant scrutiny. You can't just follow your convictions; you have to worry about how your actions will be perceived." <p>
This situation leads to some bizarre behavior. A 1992 study by three professors found that, as a group, stocks with terrible five-year performance records returned an astonishingly high 13 percent in the month of January. <p>
Why? Because money managers tended to dump their riskiest holdings in December and buy blue chips. "Managers will always move toward the benchmark near the end of the year," says Cardell. "They start heading toward the <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GM</b></a>s and <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>s and <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>s." This helps to lock in the returns they've earned over the course of the year and prevents nasty last-minute surprises from blowing their year-end bonuses. In January, the managers were free to sell the blue chips and look for bargains -- so bargain stocks regained support. This is called the January effect, and since 1992 it has crept into December.<p>
Almost nobody wants to own an individual stock that's been trashed in the press. The stock has become a "loser." You own it? Then you're a loser, too. There's a bias now toward what money pros call quality stocks, says Paul Greenwood, senior research analyst at Frank Russell Co., an investment-consulting firm in Tacoma. These are the dependable stocks with big names. "You can't go before a committee and say, 'Last quarter, two of my holdings went bankrupt,'" Greenwood says. "As a result, very few money managers are true contrarians -- people who buy really down-and-out ugly companies."<p>
"It can get mean, even among clients who are very long-term oriented," adds Babson's James. "Usually, you're at these meetings with a marketing guy from your firm. Later, he asks, 'Why didn't you just dump the thing so we wouldn't have to go through that? Let's not do that again.'" <p>
The final handicap on our list -- Constraint Number Five -- is time. The typical money manager must juggle a portfolio loaded with scores or even hundreds of stocks that fit his fund's style and other strictures -- all the while dealing with bosses and clients. "Because a money manager's time is so short, he has to depend on other sources to filter ideas," says Marc Robins, editor of The Red Chip Review, a Portland, Oregon, newsletter that tracks small companies. "When I was a money manager, I didn't have time to talk to companies, which is how you really find the best stocks." <p>
Time constraints encourage the trend toward closet indexing. Stocks, bonds, and other securities that compose a benchmark index -- the yardstick by which a manager's performance is measured, such as the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index, the Lehman Brothers Aggregate Bond index, or the Morgan Stanley European and Far East index -- become an easy default pick when the manager doesn't have time to come up with better ideas. <p>
Analysts are another cop-out. The very best analysts' reports contain new information or insights about a company, forcing people to rethink their stand on the stock. But reports of such quality are rare because few analysts are willing to venture out on a limb. An analyst who dumps on a company makes it less likely that company will hire his investment-banking department to do its next stock issue. Just as bad, the company might not answer his phone calls when it comes time to update earnings estimates.<p>
That's why so many analysts' reports tend to use very similar numbers and look very much alike. "Analysts feel safety in numbers," says Keith Wibel, president of Foothills Asset Management in Tempe, Arizona. "It's better to be wrong conventionally than right unconventionally." <p>
When a company announces financial results that are higher or lower than the hallowed consensus, the analyst pack rushes to change its estimates -- without giving much thought to what has actually changed. "There's a lot of overreaction," says Andy Ratkai, president of Praxis Advisory Group, a money-management firm in Inglewood, Colorado. "After a negative surprise, analysts tend to reduce their estimates too dramatically -- and the reverse happens after a positive surprise."<p>
Money managers don't necessarily believe analysts' buy recommendations. They may even have their doubts about the earnings estimates analysts grind out every quarter. But watch how quickly managers move to sell a stock when a company falls short of those projections.<p>
Feeling thankful you never considered a job as a professional money manager? You should. More importantly, you should also be feeling a little bit better about your own chances of operating successfully in the market -- right alongside this herd of hobbled equines. Instead of having to worry about clients or quarterly results, you're in the enviable position of being able to focus on what really matters.<p>
We'll outline eight ways to go about this -- each a discrete strategy investors can use to beat the pros. In the process, we'll also reveal 15 specific investment opportunities. You can take these picks either as recommended buys or simply as examples of the kind of deals that are out there for the plucking. But know this: There are plenty more where these came from -- and the guy who runs your pension money probably can't touch them.<p>
Strategy 1: Buy Small<p>
This is so obvious it's embarrassing -- yet almost no one does it. "Even if microcaps are the next big thing, you can't run a billion-dollar microcap fund," says Frank Russell's Greenwood. <p>
Too bad. James O'Shaughnessy's book What Works on Wall Street points out that stocks with market capitalizations under $25 million delivered 20.4 percent annual returns from 1951 through 1994, versus around 11 percent for larger issues. According to Ibbotson Associates, shares of firms with market caps between $86 million and $171 million have gained 15 percent annually since 1950.<p>
Choosing truly small stocks for your portfolio will require some sleuthing on your part (see "<A HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9609C01.html">Going Small</A>" in the September 1996 issue). Hold out for companies with reasonably strong finances and a solid market niche that can't easily be stolen away by larger firms. Also focus on firms with low institutional ownership -- say 15 to 20 percent or less of a firm's shares -- but be aware that such neglect isn't always a plus. "Some neglected companies will always be neglected, and for good reason," says Cardell of Weiss, Peck & Greer. "What you want is a company with low but growing institutional ownership." <p>
Also check out which institutions hold the shares. You can do that by subscribing to Thomson MarketEdge (<A HREF="http://www.marketedge.com">http://www.marketedge.com</A>); the basic monthly fee is around eight dollars. If the shares are owned by managers you admire, then at least you know you're in good company.<p>
Marc Robins of The Red Chip Review likes <a name="NASD:NZYM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46270"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Synthetech</b></a> (Nasdaq: NZYM), which recently traded at $7.75 a share. This small biotech firm -- its recent market capitalization was just $107 million -- is the world's leading provider of peptide building blocks, which have fewer side effects than amino acids and proteins in treating diseases. "I'd say 198 of the 200 big pharmaceutical companies in the world want this technology," says Robins. <p>
Unlike most biotech companies, Synthetech is profitable -- it's earned money every year since 1991. It has no debt, and cash flow is sufficient to finance a doubling of the company's production facilities this year. Institutional investors own only 9 percent of the stock -- but that will likely change as the company's market cap increases. <p>
For similar reasons, Dick Perkins Jr. of Perkins Capital Management has his eye on <a name="NASD:BAGL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47192"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BAB Holdings</b></a> (Nasdaq: BAGL), a bagel franchiser. BAB's strategy of targeting small towns has helped it open 70 stores in two years. A pair of acquisitions will boost that number to 360 by the end of 1997, making BAB, with a market cap of just $57 million, one of the three biggest players in a fragmented industry. And a recent agreement with the Mrs. Field's cookie chain will get BAB's bagels into hundreds more stores. "People aren't impressed by restaurant stocks, but I think this is going to be a big company," says Perkins. The stock recently sold at $8.13 a share.<p>
If you don't have the time or money to put together a diversified portfolio of small fry, consider a fund that will do it for you. Only a few equity funds -- 12 to be precise -- have median market caps below $100 million. One long-term pick: Dick Perkins's <a name="FUND:POFDX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/POFDX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Perkins Opportunity Fund</b></a> (800-366-8361; $2,500 minimum; 4.75 percent load), which invests in small companies in the health, technology, and services industries. Many of the fund's holdings are shares of companies in the upper Midwest. It has gained 34 percent annually since its inception in 1993.<p>
Another choice: <a name="FUND:HRSMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRSMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Small Cap Contrarian Fund</b></a> (800-432-7856; $1,000 minimum; no load), run by William Nasgovitz, who built his reputation racking up 22 percent annual gains over five years at the fund's older sibling, <a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value</b></a>, which is closed to new investors. The new fund gained 36.9 percent during its first 12 months (through April 1996), and its portfolio recently had an average market cap of only $89 million.<p>
Strategy 2: Buy what's out of style<p>
"Find the companies in a down-and-out industry with the ability to improve profit margins and earnings," says Babson's Lance James. <p>
Take retail stocks, which trailed the market for each year from 1993 through 1995. "No one wanted them, so valuations were low," says James. "The number of stores was shrinking. That told me competition was going to decline, and profit margins would grow from their depressed levels." The retail group climbed 18.2 percent for the year through September, compared with 13.5 percent for the S&P 500. <p>
Some retail stocks still look good, but you'll make more money if you find an industry that hasn't yet turned the corner. The mail-order business, for example, has been battered for the past 18 months, with some stocks falling 70 percent or more. Rising paper and postage costs, too many catalogs, and a poor retail environment account for the slump. But Mark Boyar, a respected New York value investor, reckons that, as shopping via the Internet and cable grows, Internet and cable companies will buy mail-order firms in order to control the distribution of products sold in cyberspace. <p>
One pick: <a name="NASD:SPGLA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14773"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Spiegel </b></a>(Nasdaq: SPGLA), which recently traded at $7.25. Boyar calculates that if you bought the entire company you'd get a firm with $3 billion in sales for less than $1 billion -- a tiny price-to-sales ratio of 0.3. German mail-order giant Otto-Versand owns 80 percent of Spiegel and is working to increase Spiegel's sales in Europe, where mail-order retailing is in its infancy. Boyar figures the company could earn around $1 a share in 1997 and trade at $18 to $22.<p>
Strategy 3: Do hold cash <p>
"As a money manager, you've got to invest cash as it comes in," says Lance James. "But individuals can act like Warren Buffett: They get to pick their shots."<p>
This is an especially good time to have some extra dough around. "At some point in the next two years, investors who have cash on hand will have their best buying opportunity in ten years," says James Stack, president of InvesTech in Whitefish, Montana. Other managers stress that short-term market moves are unpredictable, but they recommend holding a 10 to 20 percent stake in cash to snap up bargains when they appear.<p>
Or find one of the rare managers who will do it for you.<p>
SoGen International (800-334-2143; $1,000 minimum; 3.75 percent load) invests in out-of-favor sectors of the world's financial markets. The portfolio recently included a 21.9 percent stake in domestic stocks, 33.7 percent in foreign stocks, and more than 15 percent in dollar-denominated bonds. And manager Jean-Marie Eveillard makes a point of holding a big chunk in cash, as much as 35 percent of fund assets and never less than 10 percent. "When Napoleon went into battle, he didn't send all of his troops," he says in his too-French-to-be-true accent.<p>
James Craig typically keeps 10 percent of his <A HREF="http://www.janusfunds.com/cgi-bin/genobject">Janus Fund</A>'s assets in cash. "I keep cash to take advantage of the opportunities fear creates," he says. "I've gotten flak about it in the past, and I just say, 'If you don't like it, get another fund.'"<p>
Strategy 4: Buy what they can't<p>
Often, managers' investment policies restrict them from investing in the securities of bankrupt or otherwise financially troubled companies. As a result, sophisticated investors can often buy a chunk of a struggling firm's debt for considerably less than it will be worth when the company reorganizes. <p>
Marty Whitman's <a name="FUND:TAVFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TAVFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Third Avenue Value Fund</b></a> (800-443-1021; $1,000 minimum; no load) can hold up to 15 percent of its assets in non-marketable securities -- an absolute no-no for most mutual funds, pensions, and other pooled accounts. "Whatever you do, don't buy a troubled company's common stock," he advises, because stockholders have a relatively weak claim to the assets of a bankrupt company. <p>
Instead, Whitman buys senior secured debt -- securities that give him strong claim to a firm's assets in a reorganization. In 1992, for example, he purchased senior secured debt issued by Eljer Industries, a plumbing company that some investors worried was about to file for bankruptcy. Whitman figured he'd recover his investment whether that happened or not. Eljer avoided bankruptcy, and the debt has paid Whitman a yield of 16.4 percent, along with a 15 percent capital gain -- for a total return of more than 20 percent annually.<p>
Michael Price's Mutual Shares (800-553-3014; $5,000 minimum; 4.75 percent load) is another way to invest in unloved securities. The fund typically invests 40 percent or so of its portfolio in securities of bankrupt companies and other special situations. (See "<A HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9701I07.html">Why Pay Retail?</A>")<p>
Too risky? Price notes that prices of securities backed by bankrupt firms generally move according to the progress of the issuers' reorganizations -- which typically have little to do with broad stock-market movements. Thus, these seemingly high-risk issues can reduce stock-market risk through diversification without sacrificing growth potential. That helps explain why both Whitman's and Price's funds have outgained more traditional funds while remaining less volatile than the typical equity fund. <p>
Strategy 5: Buy embarrassing stocks <p>
The hardest stocks for professional money managers to buy are shares of companies that have endured well-publicized disasters -- lawsuits, accidents, financial stress, and the like. As a result, these stocks often represent great values.<p>
Before you buy such a stock, you need to understand why it is likely to recover. In the case of <a name="NASD:VJET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42104"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Valujet</b></a>, which plummeted from more than $17 a share to $6.50 after the discount airline's Flight 592 crashed in the Everglades last May, it's possible that the company may not ultimately survive Federal Aviation Administration scrutiny. Thus, many smart investors have stayed clear of the stock.<p>
George Putnam, editor of The Turnaround Letter in Boston, likes <a name="AMEX:TWA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TWA</b></a> (ASE: TWA), which declared bankruptcy in 1993, reduced its debt, modified its operations -- and then went bankrupt again in 1995. "This time they drastically changed their operating plan, shifting to regions where they have a competitive advantage," Putnam says.<p>
After the firm emerged from its second bout with the banks, shares rose from $6 to $22 -- and then plummeted to $9.50 after TWA Flight 800 went down over Long Island last July. (It recently traded at $9.) No one blamed the airline for the tragedy, but this is a stock that would take some explaining to a pension trustee. "Cash flow is up, demand is up, and costs are down," says Putnam. "I can easily see this stock in the low $20s again" within the next few years.<p>
Jim Crabbe recently held shares of <a name="NYSE:FLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10587"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fleming</b></a> (NYSE: FLM), a food distributor that caters to small supermarket chains. Low inflation has crimped the firm's ability to raise prices. Worse, a supermarket chain in Texas filed a lawsuit that alleged Fleming had overcharged it. A judge awarded the chain $211 million, and Fleming's stock fell to $11.50 last April, down from its peak of $40 in May 1991. <p>
Wall Street worried that other customers would sue as well. But the ruling has since been thrown out, and the company has rewritten almost 90 percent of its contracts to reduce the risk of future litigation. The firm's profit margins are increasing, along with its market share. Crabbe figures earnings could climb 40 percent, to $1.50 a share in 1997, and thinks the stock, which recently sold at $17.75, could go as high as the mid-$20s within 12 months.<p>
Strategy 6: Buy orphaned stocks <p>
Money managers often dump a perfectly good stock for reasons that have nothing to do with its fundamentals. <p>
Take spin-offs, which are born when a company decides to divest itself of one or more divisions that don't fit with its long-term plan. Often, the firm simply distributes shares in the spin-off to its own shareholders -- and many of those shareholders immediately dump them. <p>
Why? For starters, spin-offs usually have small market capitalizations, so the size constraint kicks in. Further, there's often little information about the spin-off: Why would beverage analysts follow Anheuser-Busch's bakery operation, Earthgrains, which it spun off in March? They don't know baking, and Earthgrains isn't likely to be throwing around big investment-banking fees. <p>
What's more, spin-offs don't usually make the index that includes their parents -- the S&P 500, say, or the Dow. In that case, indexers have to dump them. If a growth company spins off a value stock, strict growth managers have to drop it as well. "There's tremendous selling pressure on these stocks," concludes Peter Doyle, an analyst with the newsletter The Spin-off Report.<p>
Guess what: Spin-offs often turn out to be better investments than their parents (see Peter Lynch's column "<A HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9508E01.html">Free at Last</A>" in the July/August 1995 issue). The spin-off's new management often consists of employees who are getting  their first shot at running the show, and typically, they have strong financial incentives tied to performance. A study by Horizon Asset Management, an investment-management firm in New York City, found that spin-offs generate 77 percent better returns in the first three years than other companies in their industry -- and their shares are less volatile.<p>
Doyle advises investors to buy spin-offs that are selling at low price-to-earnings ratios compared with the stocks of similar firms. His recent picks include <a name="NYSE:TUP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=48028"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tupperware</b></a> (NYSE: TUP), which Premark International spun off in May. Approximately 85 percent of Tupperware's sales are overseas -- increasingly in India and China, where the company's door-to-door distribution system is an advantage over competitors like <a name="NYSE:RBD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rubbermaid</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:MMM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11003"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing</b></a>. The stock, which was recently priced at $48.38 a share, traded at 17 times expected 1996 earnings, versus around 21 times expected 1996 earnings for comparable stocks. <p>
Strategy 7: Buy the business, not the earnings estimates<p>
When an analyst lowers the earnings estimates on a stock, most money managers sell it. No excuses. "When it comes to earnings, there's a tremendous herd instinct in this business," says one pro, who asks not to be named. "We'd all rather be wrong together than wrong alone. That's why we'll dump a stock that has even a small earnings shortfall -- and companies that haven't seen a significant fundamental shift will drop 10 percent or more."<p>
That manager warns against buying right after such a decline. Instead, take it as a cue to look more closely at the company. Focus on fundamentals (especially sales growth) that will drive future earnings. Jim Crabbe likes <a name="NYSE:HHC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10746"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Horizon/CMS Healthcare</b></a> (NYSE: HHC), which provides nursing-home care and other medical services. Thanks partly to a botched acquisition attempt in January 1995, the company lost 56 cents a share in the quarter ended in August 1995 -- a huge decline from its 27-cent profit a year earlier. The stock declined from a high of $28 to $9.75 in July before recovering slightly. It recently traded at $11.13.<p>
But Crabbe thinks earnings will rebound sharply as Horizon makes other acquisitions, boosting revenues and profits. "They remain one of the best low-cost-care providers in the country," he says. "At this price, I would not be surprised if someone acquired them." He figures the stock could hit $17 to $20 in the next 12 months. <p>
Initial public offerings that have plummeted from their peaks are another place to hunt -- carefully -- for value. Typically, the momentum buyers have moved on to the latest hot issues, without realizing that (for once) they actually owned shares in a real company. Look for a firm with a two- to three-year history of profits from its operations and a p/e ratio below its expected earnings growth rate.<p>
Ryan Jacob, director of research at The IPO Value Monitor, likes <a name="NASD:DOCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51636"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DecisionOne Holdings</b></a> (Nasdaq: DOCI), which went public in April at $18 a share. Its stock price, recently $15.50, peaked at $30 before falling 47 percent when technology stocks plunged last June. The firm provides support services for more than 15,000 computer and other technology products made by almost 1,000 manufacturers: It'll send someone to fix your <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq</b></a> computer, <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> printer, and <a name="NASD:USRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15388"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>U.S. Robotics</b></a> modem. Some 85 percent of the firm's $540 million in revenue comes from long-term contracts, and Jacob projects 20 percent annual earnings growth over the next several years.<p>
Strategy 8: Invest with independent money managers <p>
Go with investment pros who run their own shows, says Craig Litman of Litman/Gregory & Co., an investment-research firm in Larkspur, California. "We like money managers who are principals of their own firms," he says, "guys who can afford to be independent thinkers." Litman cites Shelby Davis of Selected American Shares (800-243-1575; $1,000 minimum; no load) and Foster Friess of Brandywine (800-656-3017; $25,000 minimum; no load). <p>
Independents are stubborn, and their funds occasionally trail the market for months, or even years. If that bothers you, they don't care. And that's why you should hire them.<p>
Then again, none of them is perfect. What you really want is a money manager who identifies totally with your interests. One who can buy small stocks, hold offbeat investments of every stripe, completely ignore quarterly rankings -- basically do whatever he or she feels like doing. <p>
Yes, there are some arenas where attempting to compete with the professionals doesn't make a whole lot of sense (a pro-hockey rink, for example). But investing in stocks and bonds is different -- so long as you know how to play the game. This is one field where even the mightiest players have no better odds of success than the little guy who does his homework. This arena is big enough for everyone.<p>
Additional reporting by Carol Pickering and Mark Klimek.<p>
KEYWORDS:mutual fund, invest, profit, investor, basics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
