	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-The Limits of Protection</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Good news on limited-liability companies -- but watch your step<p>
By Roy Furchgott<p>
Limited-liability companies have been a boon for investors who want the tax advantages of a partnership and the liability protection of a corporation. Family businesses, owners of rental properties, and professionals with their own practices have discovered the benefits of these vehicles. Thanks to proposed tax regulations, they'll soon be a lot easier to set up. <p>
But just because it's easier doesn't mean you should sign on the line. LLC laws (and laws for limited-liability partnerships, which are substantially the same) may not always offer the protection they were designed to provide. "Limited-liability companies are different state to state," says Carl Polsky, an accounting professor at the Wharton School of Business. "Somebody might sue you in another state, and you might be liable." Polsky says it could require a huge court case just to determine which state's rules will be heard in a suit.<p>
Wyoming introduced the concept of LLCs in 1977, but they didn't take off until 1988, when the IRS ruled that an LLC would get the tax treatment of a partnership -- which is preferable to that of a corporation -- if it passed a four-point test. The test identified four key characteristics of a corporation (such as transferability of interest in the company) that would endanger an LLC's status. The IRS is expected to approve a rule by 1997 that would do away with the test and allow LLC owners to decide their status on their own. "You just check the box if you are a corporation or a partnership, and that's it," says Mark Luscombe, a tax analyst at tax-law publisher CCH.<p>
There may also be good news ahead on the interstate front. The National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Law have proposed a standard for LLCs that would apply throughout the U.S. Not all states have accepted the standard, though several have made liability law compatible in other ways. But LLCs aren't out of the legal woods yet. "There is some uncertainty," says Larry Ribstein, a professor and LLC authority at George Mason University School of Law. "For example, we don't know how LLCs will be treated under bankruptcy law, securities law, employment-discrimination law, or workers' comp." One issue: Of the LLC "members," as owners are called, who is employer and who is employee?<p>
In the meantime, there are other options. Baltimore-based financial planner Patrick Horan suggests forming a limited partnership with a corporation as the general partner. Though complex, it provides the advantages of an LLC -- without the legal questions.<p>
KEYWORDS: LP, IRS, taxes

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
