<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Strictly Top Shelf</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Strictly Top Shelf</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Owning a wall full of books about money isn't the same thing as having a first-rate investment library. Check out these classic texts.<p>
By Fredric Smoler<p>
You've got money in the markets, and, of course, you're skimming the financial press, when suddenly it occurs to you: Despite the conventional wisdom of your friends and the musings of journalists, there are serious gaps in your knowledge. Too much of what you've come across, you realize, is designed to make you wealthy, and too little is intended to make you smart. So you decide to read a few good books.<p>
Yet it turns out that the local chain store's financial section is a wall full of books, each claiming that if you read only one book about investing this should be the one -- and you know instinctively that books that boast like this are fish wrap. A knotty problem, not least because you suspect that one major alternative -- putting complete trust in the expertise and disinterestedness of a broker during a boom -- may not be the smartest thing you have ever done.<p>
The annotated list that follows is an attempt to loosen this knot by outlining the core of an investor's library. It's based on the premise that most people who lose money on their investments are neither peculiarly unlucky nor particularly stupid; in fact, most people who manage their own investments are smarter than average, though almost all active investors who trade for a profit will not make as much money in the long run as they should. When you think about this, it seems odd, because people whose investments simply track the Dow Jones Industrial Average or the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index make money -- over the long haul, they make a lot. So it seems that intelligent people confronting the markets are simply prone to a few intellectual mistakes, have a certain amount of misinformation, or succumb to psychological pitfalls.<p>
The books I've chosen address these human failings. It's a selective list, of course, and as an academic I have my biases. There are, for example, no mass-market how-to titles; I'd prefer that readers delve deeper into the foundations that underlie the practice of investing. Because the psychology of investing is where so many people come a cropper, a number of these selections explore this problem. And because a knowledge of financial history is invaluable when it comes to fighting one's irrationality -- or the pseudo-rationality that seems to make so much sense -- several are historical. Some convey a general sense of how investment strategies fare in the markets over a longish span of time -- the span an investor should be concerned with. There are general and specialized reference works, too, because finance includes both a technical vocabulary and terms of art, and something you think you understand but don't can cost you a lot of money. Finally, there are a couple of novels thrown in.<p>
These subjects overlap a great deal, and the categories are necessarily  loose. "Market Mechanics," for one, here means how the markets actually behave, which is part history, part psychology, and part technical explanation, so titles in this category could have perhaps been placed in another. Be advised that these books are mostly skeptical and rather conservative. They argue (and, I think, demonstrate) that, while prudence and discipline do pretty well in the long run, there are many more interesting, dramatic, and intellectually attractive approaches -- all of which will eventually bankrupt you. In short, these works are most valuable for people who are not specialists in economic history and who are living through an intoxicating bull market. Which is to say, you.<p>
MARKET MECHANICS
Start with Benjamin Graham's "The Intelligent Investor." It never grows old and is the one classic almost everyone has heard of -- which may be why it has never gone out of print when most investment primers are on the remainder tables before a year is out.
For most of us, the arcana of investing are far more compelling than any practical advice or commonsense approach, perhaps because the urge to make a killing leads us into a subliminal conviction that there is some swift and subtle technique that, once mastered, will make us obscenely rich immediately. An investor who has Lawrence G. McMillan's "Options as a Strategic Investment" (see below) on his shelves will strike most of us as enviably sophisticated, while a man with a copy of Graham by his bedside will seem at best pleasantly old-fashioned, and more likely timid and stodgy. Foolish impressions: Graham averaged a 17 percent annual rate of return over a career that began before the 1929 crash and continued through the Great Depression, and The Wall Street Journal has described him as one of the greatest investors of all time. On the other hand, men who master the most technical approaches and trade for a profit are, as Graham repeatedly points out, doomed to die broke if they persist in their folly long enough.<p>
Graham -- a hugely talented man who, a month before graduating from Columbia University in 1914, was offered teaching appointments in its mathematics, English, and philosophy departments -- distinguishes sharply between the speculator, defined as a man who trades for a profit, and the investor, who buys and generally holds, seeking to accumulate wealth patiently. The investor does this with a scrupulous attention to what Graham insists are underlying values, and he moves from overpriced to underpriced sectors of the markets more to escape risk than to chase super profits. His approach sounds old-fashioned, seems to confuse moral and economic categories, and deploys terms a modern economist would reject out of hand, but only one thing can be said for it: It works.<p>
Charles P. Kindleberger, the most famous chronicler of the Great Depression and the author of "Manias, Panics, and Crashes" and "The World in Depression," knows that financial crises are perennial and have a standard anatomy; he is also keenly aware of the limitations of regulatory authorities. For those young enough to "know" that nothing can go disastrously wrong for long in modern financial markets, for those who believe that financial crises can be contained within their own sector and are of necessarily limited duration, and for those who think anyone fathoms the links of the world economy, money spent on Kindleberger's books may be the best investment they could ever make.<p>
The stuff of financial history need not be all that old to offer immense value, as James P. O'Shaughnessy's "What Works on Wall Street" shows. O'Shaughnessy was the first outsider given complete access to S&P's Compustat, the largest, most comprehensive database of U.S. stock-market information available. There are only 44 years of financial history -- from 1950 to 1994 -- but that's enough to destroy lots of conventional wisdom. Against this longitudinal data, O'Shaughnessy tests popular investment strategies and the conventional wisdom on price-to-earnings and price-to-book ratios, small-company versus large-company stocks, cash flow, one- and five-year earnings-per-share ratios, return on equity -- indeed, most of the formulas investors have come up with for determining value.<p>
O'Shaughnessy finds there's a tendency to irrationality even among the most skillful investors: Individuals invent intricate patterns that at first only they can see but that, once seen, become immensely persuasive. But the failure of money managers to see through and beat market indexes does not mean random-walk theories win the day either. O'Shaughnessy argues that the portfolios studied by random-walk academics are inconsistently managed or run by more than one adviser and so never reflect the true possibilities of rational analysis. By testing test investors' intuitions against the universe of U.S. stocks over nearly 50 years, he demonstrates that the disciplined use of statistical evidence is possible -- or at least technically possible, if psychologically improbable.<p>
For a generous dose of drollery with your economic wisdom, you won't go wrong with Martin S. Fridson's "Investment Illusions: A Savvy Wall Street Pro Explodes Popular Misconceptions About the Markets." Fridson's is the most immediately engaging book on my list. His simple demonstration of the utility of probability theory in assessing financial journalism (say, the tendency to select some flavor-of-the-month fund manager) is as valuable as most investment guides. He is devastating, and very funny, in critiquing what passes for sophistication among many investors.<p>
If Graham's sobriety is palatable, look for Richard Brealey's "An Introduction to Risk and Return from Common Stocks." For a more specifically historical perspective, consider John D. Brown's "101 Years on Wall Street: An Investor's Almanac." Both of these books may be out of print by now, but they're worth grabbing if you find them in a used-book store. One book that repeated generations are rediscovering is Edwin Lefèvre's classic, "Reminiscences of a Stock Operator."<p>
PSYCHOLOGY
Since the financial markets include vast numbers of people in an amazing variety of institutions and subcultures and since these multitudes are often invoked by the optimistic as proof of the markets' infallibility, a little knowledge about how large numbers of people behave when money is at stake can be helpful. Charles Mackay's "Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds" remains the classic account of this subject. Tulipomania and the South Sea bubble never grow old. The great and recurring illusion of the markets is that there's something new under the sun -- that the rules are changing in fundamental and beneficent ways and that the skill, sophistication, and psychology of one's own generation of financial wizards make financial history a matter of purely antiquarian interest. Believing this can easily be the most expensive mistake you'll make; on the other hand, Mackay's book -- simultaneously funny and grimly sobering -- is often on remainder tables. You'll never learn cheaper.<p>
If you enjoy Charles Mackay, consider another classic work often mentioned in the same breath, Gustave Le Bon's "The Crowd: A Study of the Popular Mind" Take a look, too, at Henry Harper's "The Psychology of Speculation." And though drabber in tone than Fridson's work, Martin J. Pring's "Investment Psychology Explained" is worth checking out.<p>
TECHNICAL ANALYSIS
In the words of a great investor, never buy anything you don't understand. If you work your way through Lawrence G. McMillan's "Options as a Strategic Investment" (it assumes some sophistication and mathematical training but may usefully be read without either of these), you will be able to honor this rule while buying a butterfly spread, trading LEAPS and CAPS, and talking knowledgeably about the gamma of the gamma. In other words, if you're going anywhere near options, McMillan is a must-read. Whether in fact you ought to do any of these things is another question, one that Graham addressed many years earlier.<p>
Other valuable volumes with narrower foci and more practical approaches are Martin J. Pring's "Technical Analysis Explained," Stephen J. Brown and Mark Kritzman's "Quantitative Methods for Financial Analysis," and Frank Fabozzi and Frank Zarb's "Handbook of Financial Markets: Securities, Options, and Futures." And if you ignore the sobrieties celebrated in these books, you will eventually need every bit of comic relief you can lay your hands on (see Fridson above).<p>
PERIODICALS
Should you subscribe to journals? If you are determined to read what the pros read, consider getting The Journal of Portfolio Management, Institutional Investor, The Journal of Financial Economics, and Financial Analysts Journal. The danger of actually reading these publications is that they may delude you into thinking you are not an amateur -- which you are. Your strategy as an investor should be to avoid market timing, since in the long run market timers almost always fail. However, unless you're a pure chartist, you are going to need some sense of where the world is heading, whether you are going to be a value investor or a market timer. Since television is profoundly inefficient -- fatuities at 100 words a minute -- and news radio scarcely better, you'll need to read something, and it had better be The Economist. Competing mass-market weeklies are hopelessly outclassed: The Economist is lively, intelligent, global in its coverage, economic in its orientation, and shrewd about politics. It has its own sane politics -- deregulation and free trade -- but it is almost perfectly free of ideological cant (which cannot be said of The Wall Street Journal). It publishes regular reports on developments in economics that are relevant to investors; it has periodic special sections on regional developments; and its technology coverage is excellent. Even if you read specialist publications, you will want The Economist for the many areas in which you are going to remain a generalist.<p>
REFERENCE
Whether you're reading The Economist or one of the aforementioned books, you're bound to encounter unfamiliar terms. Don't know what a "contango" is? Look it up in Barron's Dictionary of Finance and Investment Terms, a handy, compact guide. For a general reference work, more essayistic in style, consider Palgraves, which is essentially a specialized encyclopedia. There are now several New Palgraves, including one for economics and one for finance (with considerable overlaps in coverage between them), though some folks prefer the older editions. Still, this is a major work and, if money is no object, well worth owning. <p>
When Sidney Homer arrived at Salomon Brothers in 1961, he organized the first in-depth research department devoted strictly to fixed-income markets. After looking in vain for anything dispositive on the subject of interest rates -- even though it's an ancient subject and interest rates are demonstrably older than money itself -- Homer filled the absence himself and in 1963 published A History of Interest Rates. The book, which has been revised many times, most recently by Richard Sylla, is more than a lengthy data series going all the way back to ancient Sumer; it's an attempt to understand interest rates in the multiple dimensions of time, space, quality of loans, marketability, size of loans, redemption terms, tax status, class of debtor, class of creditor, and a complex legal history. How do we stack up? If, as a fin de siècle economist observed, a country's cultural level is inversely proportional to its free-market rate of interest, not very well -- although perhaps it is some comfort that in this decade Argentine banks at one point offered depositors 1,000 percent a month. Homer and Sylla provide an invaluable frame of reference for investors who need a broad and textured sense of the determinants at work in the credit markets.<p>
FICTION
Lots of fiction has treated the topic of money, but the list of great novels written about investing is small. William Gaddis's "JR," one of the finest postwar American novels and a viciously funny high-modernist triumph composed almost entirely of dialogue, is surely at the top of the list. (Honorable mentions must include Theodore Dreiser's "The Financier" and "The Titan" and Louis Auchincloss's "The Embezzler.") Gaddis's book belongs in any investor's library: JR is an 11-year-old who, using his hapless music teacher as a front, pyramids a class project's share of stock into a highly leveraged sham conglomerate nominally worth hundreds of millions. The novel resonates with the later rise and fall of James Ling and the hideous efflorescence of tax-avoidance-driven investing since muted by the 1986 code revisions, but JR's comic brilliance is undimmed by the passing of the fads it mocks so savagely.<p>
Fredric Smoler teaches at Sarah Lawrence College and is an editor-at-large at Audacity, a journal of business history.<p>
KEYWORDS:
book, reading, literature

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

