	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01S-Promises to Keep</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Promises to Keep</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						New Year's resolutions are hard to follow through on, but some of America's best financial planners have come up with ten that are well worth the willpower<p>
By Paul Davies<p>
1. Investor, Know Thyself: David Diesslin
The first step in investment planning is to determine exactly where you stand now, yet most people in the U.S. can't estimate their net worth within 5 percent, says David Diesslin of Diesslin & Associates in Fort Worth, Texas. To arrive at a dollar figure, add all your assets -- cash, IRA, mutual funds, stocks, real estate, cars, and collections like art or coins -- then subtract liabilities, like a home loan, car loans and leases, and investment liabilities, such as a margin loan with your broker. Don't forget to factor in deferred-income taxes on stocks and compensation packages; these are liabilities, too. <p>
This exercise will help you decide how fast you need your wealth to grow to meet whatever your long-term financial target is -- a retirement home, four years of tuition, start-up money for a business. By knowing your goal, you can determine if your savings and investment strategies are too conservative to get you where you're trying to go or riskier than necessary. Setting a bottom line "forces you to be proactive," Diesslin says. <p>
2. Reduce Your Tax Withholding: Kathleen Stepp
The goal for most taxpayers is to get a refund on April 15 rather than owe the government. In reality, it's better to reduce your withholding and invest the money rather than let Uncle Sam hold on to it, says Kathleen Stepp, president of Stepp & Garrett in Overland Park, Kansas. "Most people think they win if they get a big refund, when they've really lost," says Stepp.<p>
Consider a taxpayer who receives a $2,400 refund from the federal government. The taxpayer would do better to reduce withholding and invest the $200 a month over 12 months at 8 percent. By the next April, the investment would be worth $2,557, or $157 more than the tax refund. Even after paying 33 percent in tax on the $157, the gain would be $105. "Most people would jump at the chance to keep $100 rather than give it to Uncle Sam," Stepp says.<p>
3. Put Your Trust in Real Estate: Carol Wilson
Real estate has been a tough sell in recent years, but now that the stock market may be overvalued, it might be the time to consider it again, says Carol Wilson of Wilson Financial Advisors in Salt Lake City.<p>
Wilson recommends that investors place 10 percent of their portfolio in real-estate investment trusts, which are basically listed securities that pool investors' money to buy property. She likes REITs because they can be bought and sold like stocks. Through October, REITs outperformed the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index for the past five years, earning an average annual return of 13.8 percent, versus 13.6 percent for the S&P. In addition, REITs are an excellent hedge against stocks. "I use REITs as a bond substitute," Wilson says.<p>
Wilson likes the two largest REIT mutual funds, Cohen & Steers Realty Shares and Fidelity Real Estate Investment, which have been among the industry leaders over the past five years. Some smaller funds -- such as Columbia Real Estate Equity, Crabbe Huson Real Estate Investment, Longleaf Realty, and CGM Realty -- have been posting impressive returns, but Wilson avoids funds that have not been around for at least five years. One safe bet, however, is the Vanguard REIT Index Portfolio, which started in May.<p>
4. Review Your Asset Allocation: Wayne Starr
The start of a new year is always a good time to review your portfolio's asset allocation, says Wayne Starr, a certified financial planner at Neill & Associates in Kansas City, Missouri. Each investor's asset allocation varies according to age, financial goals, and taste for risk, but a conservative split would be 60 percent in a basket of equities and 40 percent in a combination of short- and long-term bonds and cash. An aggressive 25-year-old investor may want 100 percent of her investments in stocks, while a conservative investor in his 70s may want 70 percent in fixed income. <p>
A well-balanced portfolio can get out of balance in a year's time, especially in a year with a strong equity market like 1996. Your stock investments may have increased from 60 to 80 percent of your portfolio, while your bonds dropped from 40 to 20 percent. If so, consider selling some stocks to get back to your desired allocation.<p>
Starr says investors might also consider tactical shifts to take advantage of political and economic changes. He is urging his clients to consider natural-resource commodities, particularly oil and gas. Fears of a recession or inflation could send commodity prices climbing. Three funds that provide excellent exposure to commodities are the <a name="FUND:PRNEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRNEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price New Era Fund</b></a>, the <a name="FUND:RSNRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RSNRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Robertson Stephens Global Natural Resources Fund</b></a>, and the <a name="FUND:VGENX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VGENX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Specialized Energy Fund</b></a>.<p>
5. Give the Gift That Keeps on Giving: Mary P. Merrill
Many investors are unnecessarily wary of charitable trusts, says Mary P. Merrill of M. P. Merrill & Associates in Madison, Wisconsin. "People will give old coats to Goodwill, but they have to be confident they are not going to run out of money before they consider charitable trusts," she says. But you don't have to be rich to enjoy the tax benefits of charitable giving.<p>
There are three basic kinds of charitable trusts, each of which pays off in a different way. A charitable-remainder annuity trust provides a guaranteed fixed annuity, which is a percentage of the value of the trust's assets at the time of the donation. By comparison, a charitable-remainder unitrust provides annual income payments that are a percentage of the value of the trust's assets; the annuity varies since the trust's assets are revalued each year. A third option is a pooled-income fund, which pools gifts with those of other donors. The donor is paid income depending on the fund's earnings performance.<p>
As an example, consider a couple in their late 50s who donate $100,000 in equities to charity. They avoid the capital-gains tax, and by donating the stocks through a charitable-remainder annuity that pays 7 percent, the couple will receive annual income of $7,000 for the rest of their lives. <p>
6. Stay Current in Estate Planning: Patricia F. Raskob
Estate documents deserve a thorough review once a year, says Patricia F. Raskob of Raskob/Kambourian Financial Advisors in Tucson, Arizona. Raskob recommends reviewing your will and life-insurance beneficiary designations every January. In addition, estate documents should be updated following any major life event, such as a birth, death, or divorce.<p>
Living wills and health-care powers of attorney should be reviewed annually as well. Banks and doctors prefer the updating to ensure that clients haven't changed their minds. Raskob says that another will option worth considering is a gift clause, which allows for your assets to be given to your heirs in the event you become incapacitated. Without one, there's no guarantee that your wishes will be followed.<p>
7. Get in the Market: Victoria F. Collins
In a perfect world, all investors would buy at the bottom of the stock market and sell at the top, says Victoria F. Collins of Keller, Coad & Collins in Irvine, California. But it's very difficult to time the market on a regular basis. Of 90 market-timing strategies touted in newsletters, only 3 outperformed the market over the past five years, according to Mark Hulbert of Hulbert Financial Digest in Alexandria, Virginia. "If so-called experts can't do it, no wonder it's frustrating for individual investors," says Collins.<p>
The important thing is to be in the market. Collins tells of a former client  who was made anxious by the Dow's reaching 3000 in 1991. The client sold $100,000 in stocks and put his money in certificates of deposit. The Dow has doubled since then. Had the investor left $100,000 in an S&P 500 index fund, he would have more than doubled his investment to $201,407 through August. The $100,000 in CDs has grown to only $124,136.<p>
8. Hedge Your Bets Against Inflation: Peggy Ruhlin
The Treasury department plans to issue new inflation-indexed bonds in January. The interest rate paid will be set by auction, as with regular Treasury bonds, but the principal will increase along with the consumer price index, and interest is earned on the adjusted principal. <p>
Investors may want to shift the traditional bond portion of their portfolio to inflation-indexed bonds, but they shouldn't sell equities to do so, says Peggy Ruhlin of Budros & Ruhlin in Columbus, Ohio. "Nobody in a million years should consider selling stocks and putting the money into these things," she says. "These bonds will be a crummy investment if inflation stays low." The advantage of the new bonds is that they don't lose value if inflation spikes up -- the principal increase covers that. But they'll carry lower coupon rates than regular bonds. If inflation is low and the adjustment never comes into play, you'll wish you hadn't got fancy. <p>
9. Embrace Cultural Diversity: Alan Weiss
With the U.S. stock market seemingly overvalued, investors should look for opportunities overseas, says Alan Weiss, president of Regent Retirement Planning in North Haven, Connecticut. Europe is beginning to rebound, and emerging markets offer increased opportunities. "There is no time in our history when it has been easier to conduct business on a global basis," Weiss says.<p>
Weiss recommends that growth investors put 30 percent of their portfolio in foreign and emerging-markets stock funds. This diversification provides a hedge against downturns in the U.S. market. He suggests putting 20 percent in a large-company foreign fund, such as the <a name="FUND:
         VWIGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard International Growth Fund</b></a> or Ivy International A, and 10 percent in a small-company emerging-markets fund, such as <a name="FUND:CNTAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CNTAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Colonial Newport Tiger A</b></a> or <a name="FUND:TEDMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TEDMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Templeton Developing Markets</b></a>.<p>
10. Know Your Mutual Fund -- Again: Frank Butterfield
Investors can spend months shopping for the right mutual fund. But after choosing one, they often send in their money and never think about the fund again. This is a mistake, says Frank Butterfield of Homrich & Berg in Atlanta. "Several things can happen to a great fund after you buy it," he says. "The manager who built the track record can depart. The assets can balloon and cause the manager to dilute his or her investment ideas. The style of the fund can change."<p>
Butterfield points to the <a name="FUND:GSCQX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GSCQX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Govett Small Companies Fund</b></a>. Under Garrett Van Wagoner, its average return for the three years ended December 1995 was 52.1 percent. Then Van Wagoner left, and through the first nine months of 1996, the fund returned 1.47 percent under Jeff Bernstein. "The new manager could not find Van Wagoner's shoes, let alone fill them," says Butterfield. He urges investors to read their funds' quarterly reports and watch for shifts in the amount of assets and the number and types of stocks.<p>
KEYWORDS: advice, idea

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
