<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-The Bruising Browsers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-The Bruising Browsers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman<p>
The battle between the browsers -- software programs that make World Wide Web access possible -- is much like presidential politics this year: two big opponents duking it out with claims and counterclaims of superiority, but with few real differences of substance to separate them. <p>
Both <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a>'s Navigator 3.0 (available as shareware for $49
for Windows and Macintosh) and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>'s Internet Explorer 3.0 (free for Windows 95 and Windows NT only) display the Web in all its multimediated, interactive glory; both make E-mail painless and offer connections to Internet newsgroups. Each is easily acquired (at <a HREF="http://www.netscape.com">www.netscape.com</A>
 and <a HREF="http://www.microsoft.com">www.microsoft.com</A>
, for those already connected), easily installed, and easily mastered. Last summer's bugs have been fixed. Both help users edit and organize the chaos of 10,000-plus newsgroups, the Internet's equivalent of cocktail-party chatter. And neither program will affect what users see -- of the hundreds of thousands of Web pages out there, only a handful will look different in these two browser programs.<p>
In short, although the stakes are great for the firms struggling to control the market, selecting a browser may be the most risk-free computing decision you'll ever have to make. But since you still have to choose -- keeping both browsers on a system is a good way to compare them, but in the long run it invites confusion and double work thanks to the functions that archive personal information -- there are reasons to prefer one to the other.<p>
**Navigator's advantages over Microsoft**<p>
In spite of cleaner and more elegant graphics from Microsoft that evoke modern book design -- Navigator is still gray and hogs too much of the computer screen -- Netscape's is the better product.<p>
Right now, Internet Explorer 3.0 runs only on Windows 95 or Windows NT, whereas Netscape, the dominant choice of all browser users, works on many more computer systems. Also, Navigator takes a fraction of the hard drive needed to install Explorer, which requires 25 megabytes of a hard drive to set things up (the memory needed shrinks afterward).<p>
Explorer does have advantages, maybe the most significant being that many of the biggest Internet providers, such as AT&T Worldnet, Netcom, and America Online, have deals with Microsoft to offer Explorer as the default browser, making the program a natural choice for those who sign up with them. Explorer is always free, too; Navigator, when not given away by an Internet provider, is free for 90 days, after which Netscape requests (though in truth it doesn't expect) a onetime charge of $49.<p>
**Navigator is better at moving Web content through E-mail.**<p>
But Navigator is clearly better when it comes to moving Web content over the Internet via E-mail. Navigator allows users to send and display E-mail that incorporates materials formatted in HTML, the coding language in which Web pages are written. HTML makes possible the blending of text, graphics, sound, and the "hot links" that move users from site to site. This means that if someone sends you an audio file -- a recording of a press conference, let's say -- you can hear it by merely clicking a button inside the E-mail application. <p>
Or imagine you want to coordinate travel plans with a friend: You can call up a hotel's Web site and send that page directly to the friend as E-mail. The hot links are immediately accessible, too. Several media groups are taking advantage of this feature to disseminate news and entertainment. The New York Times, for example, can send its World Wide Web version as E-mail, permitting subscribers to retrieve the online paper and read it offline without racking up phone charges.<p>
**User-friendliness can also be the curse of these programs.**<p>
What now makes Explorer and Navigator so attractive, especially the latter, is that they integrate into one package all sorts of capabilities that formerly required a piecemeal collection of arcane programs. (An example is the browsers' incorporation of "phone" packages, which allow users to communicate long-distance at local rates over Internet connections -- though in neither program is this feature easy to configure, nor does either yet offer great sound or smooth two-way conversation.) <p>
This, in turn, can't help but hasten the Internet's destiny, which is to move everything -- from movies to money -- onto a person's desk. Alas, such user-friendliness is also the curse of these programs: One problem they help create but can't solve is increased Internet traffic and, therefore, more bottlenecks. Indeed, in the few days after each new browser was released, heavy use nearly ground the companies' sites to a halt.<p>
KEYWORDS:
Internet, WWW

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
