<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-When All the World's Your Stage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-When All the World's Your Stage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Investors won't pick winners in a global economy if they study only U.S. stocks<p>
By Paul Davies<p>
A U.S consumer trying to find the best buy in a car or a cellular phone would kick the tires on U.S. <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fords </b></a>and Japanese <a name="NYSE:"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46940"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hondas</b></a> and flip open phones by America's <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> and Finland's <a name="NYSE:NOK/A"></a><b>Nokia</b>. Why should investors be any less global when they buy stocks?<p>
Only an estimated 29 percent of U.S. mutual-fund shareholders currently own an international or global fund, and when it comes to choosing individual stocks, U.S. investors remain chauvinists. Often investors trying to cash in on a global trend begin and end their analyses with companies based in the United States.<p>
But that kind of thinking can mean settling for second best when it comes to capitalizing on a trend or industry turnaround in today's global economy. For example, according to Standard & Poor's Compustat, over the past ten years, the big three automobile stocks, ranked by virtue of their total return to investors, were not <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, Ford, and <a name="NYSE:"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46940"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> but Ford (262 percent cumulative return), <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a> (244 percent), and Chrysler (240 percent).<p>
Right now, the cellular-phone industry offers a classic case study of the dangers of thinking domestically when investing in a global market. Dataquest, a technology research firm in San Jose, California, projects that through the year 2000 the number of cellular subscribers will grow by more than 20 percent in the U.S. and Europe and by 57 percent in East Asia. U.S. investors who want to play this trend by buying shares in a maker of cellular-phone handsets but who are determined to keep their heads stuck in U.S. sands are limited to one stock, Motorola. A global analysis, however, would put Sweden's <a name="NASD:ERICY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41776"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ericsson</b></a> and Finland's Nokia at the top of the list of companies currently best positioned to take advantage of the global boom.<p>
**Look for international companies with the best mix of competitive advantages.**<p>
Picking winners and losers from a worldwide list may seem daunting, but it's no more difficult than analyzing a purely domestic industry. Just look for the company with the best mix of competitive advantages.<p>
For example, in the auto industry, manufacturers interested in  competing globally must do three things: make cars as efficiently as they can, bring out new models faster than their competitors, and build the best-quality cars for the money. The one automaker preeminent in these three areas, according to industry sage Maryann N. Keller, managing director at New York–based institutional brokerage Furman Selz, is Toyota. "No one else even comes close," says Keller.<p>
According to auto-industry consultants Harbour and Associates, while General Motors takes an average of 29 hours building each car and Ford 25 hours, Toyota's average car is built in only 20. And while it takes GM approximately 40 months to bring a new car model to market, Ford does the same in 31 months and Toyota in just 30.<p>
Nor does all this efficiency come at the expense of quality. Of the top three models picked by J. D. Power and Associates' 1996 quality study in 11 product categories, Toyota made the cut in 9 categories, while GM earned a place in 6 and Ford in only 3.<p>
**Motorola dominated the U.S. cellular-phone market for years -- but the market is evolving.**<p>
A similar checklist of competitive factors for the cellular-phone industry needn't be any longer, even though the industry is much more dynamic than the automotive sector. The number of cellular-phone users in the U.S. alone climbed from 1 million in 1987 to 33 million last year, according to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association in Washington, D.C. The world cellular population is expected to grow from 68 million subscribers today to over 251 million by the year 2000, according to Dataquest.<p>
For years, Motorola dominated the U.S. cellular-phone business with handsets that were sturdy, functional, and -- thanks to an aggressive cost-cutting strategy -- lower in price than competing phones. Consider that 11 years after its introduction the ubiquitous dark-gray Motorola DPC 550 -- the original "flip-phone" -- remains the most popular handset sold in the U.S. <p>
But the cellular world has changed. Motorola's low-cost, high-volume approach left a hole in the marketplace big enough for a competitor to drive through. And two competitors -- Oy Nokia (NYSE: NOK.A) and L. M. Ericsson (Nasdaq: ERICY) -- did just that. The two used their competitive strengths to outmaneuver the established industry leader in the same way that Toyota outmaneuvered General Motors and Ford.<p>
For years, Motorola set the technological pace, and it remains an industry leader with a world-market share of 30 percent, followed by Nokia's 24 percent and Ericsson's 10 percent. But while Motorola was focusing on the U.S. market and following its aggressive low-cost strategy, Nokia and Ericsson were building handsets and cellular systems for the global industry. Taking advantage of Motorola's reliance on older models and its concentration on the U.S. market, Nokia and Ericsson aimed at the global "sweet spot" by producing phones with more features. The result was huge sales to a worldwide audience.<p>
**Nokia slipped into the cellular market by developing more advanced telephones.**<p>
Nokia let Motorola continue to dominate the low end of the market, while it developed advanced telephones that appealed to users at the high end. The top-of-the-line phones -- like Nokia's hugely popular 2100 model, which sells for about $550 yet costs only $234 to make -- feature much higher profit margins than the low-end models that are given away by service providers in an effort to drum up additional business. The newest models, some of which weigh as little as three ounces -- compared with six to nine ounces for most phones -- sell for more than $1,000 and boast even higher margins.<p>
Those feature-laden products appealed to customers in Europe and Asia, helping Nokia and Ericsson to build market share outside the U.S. and thus spread their research-and-development costs over many markets, giving them a decisive cost advantage. Nokia was the biggest winner in this race, rising to second-place status in an astounding three years.<p>
Nokia owes much of its current success to its prowess in getting new products to market fast, enabling the company to alter new phone models quickly for constantly shifting consumer tastes. While the industry average for rolling out new phones is three to four years, Nokia can introduce a new product in 18 months. <p>
**Ericsson took the lead last fall when new technology failed to take off for Nokia.**<p>
But the marketing-savvy company stumbled badly last year on the technology front -- as did Motorola -- letting Ericsson grab the initiative. While the old analog system for sending phone calls still dominates in the U.S., four out of five European phones are based on newer digital technology, which can carry three times as many calls as analog, with better quality to boot. As digital was introduced to the U.S. over the past year, the price of analog phones plummeted 40 percent, causing massive headaches for all three manufacturers. At the same time, Nokia cost itself a lot of money when it bet last fall that digital would become an overnight hit -- when it didn't, the company was forced to offer big discounts on loads of unsold digital handsets. <p>
"They dropped the ball there," says Ajay Diwan, wireless-equipment analyst for Goldman Sachs. "They really misjudged U.S. market demand."<p>
**The industry is split between two competing technologies: TDMA and CDMA.**<p>
A battle between two competing digital standards -- a proven technology called TDMA (time division multiple access) and a promising but experimental one called CDMA (code division multiple access) -- makes judging the growth rate for digital phones extremely tricky. With a single standard yet to emerge, many cell-phone makers are jockeying for position. Motorola and <a name="NYSE:LU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46656"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lucent</b></a>, the <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T </b></a>spin-off, have invested billions in CDMA, while Ericsson is banking on TDMA. Because CDMA is proving far more difficult and expensive to implement than initially thought, Ericsson seems to have made the smart choice, at least for the next few years.<p>
"For a while, everyone was saying, 'Where's Ericsson?'" says Albert Lin, an industry analyst with New York– based institutional broker Cowen & Co. "Now it seems like they have emerged almost overnight." Credit the company's research-and-development budget: In 1995, Ericsson spent nearly 20 percent of sales on R&D, versus Motorola's 9 percent and Nokia's 6 percent.<p>
**While Ericsson retains top position in the field, Japanese firms are edging in on the market.**<p>
Ericsson is well positioned to put that research edge to work when the industry makes its next great technology leap into the mass-market personal-communications services business. Dataquest estimates that the market for PCS handsets will be $3 billion a year by 1998 in the U.S. alone. Ericsson has a commanding lead in both PCS handsets and the underlying infrastructure that provides the service; this should let the company win far more business than either Motorola or Nokia.<p>
If only Ericsson can keep the field to itself. With stakes this high, the market is also attracting the Japanese electronic giants <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41873"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Matsushita</b></a> (the maker of Panasonic phone equipment), and <a name="NYSE:NIPNY"></a><b>NEC</b> -- each of which has approximately a 3 percent share of the market currently -- as well as Dutch-based <a name="NYSE:PHG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41823"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philips</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:ALA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41751"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alcatel Alsthom</b></a> of France.<p>
Even with all these new players flooding the field, investors in the industry's next stage should be able to apply the same kind of analysis that has shown Ericsson to be the cellular-phone market's current leader. Look for the company best able to get the technology and features sought by consumers quickly to market. Look for the cost-efficient producers who can use their marketing and technological savvy to keep their profit margins higher than those of their competitors. Thinking globally isn't as hard as it looks -- and it's a whole lot more profitable than the alternative.<p>
KEYWORDS:cellular phone, cellular telephone, communications, automotive, international, global, worldwide, foreign, high-tech

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
