	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Losers Out of the Gate </title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Losers Out of the Gate </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Simply put, government-bond-fund managers can't beat a five-year treasury<p>
By Scott Burns<p>
Let's be blunt: government-securities mutual funds don't deserve to exist. <p>
Of the 634 funds (with nearly $130 billion in assets) dedicated to investing in the various types of United States government securities, all but a handful have been a disappointment -- sometimes a bitter disappointment -- to their shareholders. Thousands of investors, many of them retirees, fled the meager yields of bank CDs only to discover that government-bond funds themselves produced low yields and often took a bite out of an investor's capital as well. These investors would have done better if they had simply bought Treasury bills, notes, and bonds and held them to maturity. In this part of the fixed-income market, coughing up fees for active management almost never pays off. <p>
Except for the fund managers, that is. These same funds have provided very nice revenues to their management companies and generated millions in marketing fees for their sales forces. <p>
To see just how miserably the government funds have performed as a group, compare them with passive indexes for the same pool of securities. In the five-year period ended July 31, for instance, the average government mortgage fund provided an annualized return of 6.16 percent, according to data from Morningstar, while the Lehman Brothers mortgage-backed-securities index returned 7.46 percent. That's quite a gap.<p>
Similarly, funds categorized as Government General by Morningstar returned 6.52 percent annually during the period while the Lehman Brothers Government Index returned 8.01 percent. The figures in the table on page 136 show that a performance gap existed for every major time period from 1 to 15 years. <p>
What we are talking about here is a massive failure to deliver the goods.<p>
Let's turn these bloodless figures into the actual results investors experienced. Suppose, for example, that you had invested $10,000 in Putnam U.S. Government Income A shares five years ago in August. This fund, sold through many brokerage houses, has $2.6 billion in assets and is one of the ten largest government funds. <p>
If you were retired and instructed the fund to send you all interest income but to reinvest any capital gains, your $9,525 investment (after the commission) would have declined in value to $8,979, and you would have received some $3,372 in interest income.<p>
An investment in a simple five-year Treasury at the same time would have produced a 7.43 percent yield, creating $3,715 in interest income. It also would have returned your original $10,000 at maturity. You could, in other words, have had more income, less risk, a real guarantee that your original principal would be returned, and no sales charge. Somehow, during a period when interest rates declined -- which sent the prices of bonds up -- the actively managed fund lost more than a tenth of this investor's principal and paid less in interest, too.<p>
The point here is not to pillory Putnam U.S. Government Income (among large funds, Federated Fund for U.S. Government Securities A shares and Colonial U.S. Government A shares did worse). While one or two of the funds beat the five-year Treasury, they are the exceptions that prove the rule. The real point is that this entire mutual-fund category can't cut the mustard. As they say in Texas: They ain't worth shooting.<p>
Kind of a broad-brush statement, you say? Let's see.<p>
To test the idea, I assembled a list of the 20 largest government-securities funds as a portfolio -- since the 25 largest government funds account for half the assets in the category, the sample is representative of what most fund shareholders experienced. Then I examined their performance in every five-year span since January 1988 -- a total of 44 60-month time periods. Treating the group as a portfolio and counting anything that exceeded the original $10,000 investment as a return on investment -- just like investing in a CD -- I calculated the average performance in each of those time periods and compared it with that of a simple five-year Treasury obligation purchased at the same time.<p>
Guess what?<p>
The five-year Treasury beat the average in 34 of the 44 time periods. Averaging all 44 time periods, I found that a $10,000 investment in a five-year Treasury would have produced $442 more in income, even though interest rates, when averaged, fell a whopping 2.23 percentage points during the study. <p>
At best, the $10,000 Treasury investment outperformed the average fund by $1,142 (between January 1990 and December 1994). At worst, the Treasury bond lagged the index of funds by $337 (between September 1988 and August 1993). <p>
Although the past three years have sent interest rates on a roller-coaster ride, surprisingly there wasn't a single five-year period during which interest rates hadn't declined. If bond-fund managers can't beat a simple Treasury purchase in periods of declining interest rates, how will they do if interest rates actually climb? In that environment, buying a five-year Treasury and holding it to maturity -- which produces slightly less income but guarantees a return of principal -- will look just that much better.<p>
How difficult is it to buy a U.S. Treasury with a five-year maturity? Not very. The Treasury auctions five-year notes each month, and you can participate -- at no cost -- through the Treasury Direct program (202-874-4000) or through a broker-dealer for  about $50. The minimum purchase amount is $1,000 -- which is less than for many mutual funds. So what are you waiting for?<p>
<center><strong>EVEN THE BEST BARELY CUT IT</strong></center>
<img src="/imgs/9611I02-chart1.gif" width=475 height=210><p>
Among the largest government-bond funds, only two of the ten best performers beat a humble five-year Treasury note. A version of this table listing the 20 biggest funds is updated monthly on the World Wide Web at <a HREF="http://www.scottburns.com.">www.scottburns.com.</A><p>
<center><strong>GOVERNMENT FUNDS FAIL TO MEASURE UP</strong></center>
<img src="/imgs/9611I02-chart2.gif" width=475 height=210><p>
Over all time periods, actively managed government funds -- whether they specialize in mortgage-backed securities or invest in the full range of government issues -- fail to beat the passive indexes. An investor is better off buying and holding a Treasury.         

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
