<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Diversity in a Limited Menu</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Diversity in a Limited Menu</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Our picks for 401(k) portfolios limited to one fund family<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
Wait a minute, you say. My 401(k) plan limits me to funds from one family. Can I still build a diversified portfolio?<p>
Well, pretty close, though it may take some juggling. The 401(k) plans are offering more fund choices in their menus, and the biggest names now almost routinely offer lots of options. But none of the families below offers funds that are open to new investors in all five categories. For example, none offers an open small-cap value fund. It will also take creativity to add the right global mix to several of these menus. Here are our recommendations for four single-family portfolios. The asset classes are indicated in parentheses; all returns are average annual figures.<p>
**<A HREF="http://personal.fidelity.com/funds/fund_data/fund_data.html">Fidelity</A>**<p>
Fidelity. Worldwide (GLO), $$$$, 12.2 percent five-year return, low risk; Low-Priced Stock (SCG), $$$$$, 19.3 percent five-year return, low risk; Contrafund (LCG), $$$$, 17.5 percent five-year return, high risk; Equity-Income II (LCV), $$$$, 16.2 percent five-year return, moderate risk. <p>
**<A HREF="http://www.troweprice.com/">T. Rowe Price</A>**<p>
T. Rowe Price. For GLO, combine equal amounts New Asia ($$$$$, 12.7 percent five-year return, moderate risk) and European Stock ($$$$, 12.4 percent five-year return, low risk); Over-the-Counter Securities (SCG), $$$$, 17.1 percent five-year return, low risk; Growth Stock (LCG), $$$$$, 14.0 percent five-year return, low risk; Capital Appreciation (LCV), $$$, 12.5 percent five-year return, low risk.<p>
**<A HREF="http://www.putnaminv.com/">Putnam</A>**<p>
Putnam. For GLO, combine equal amounts Europe Growth A ($$$$, 14.2 percent five-year return, moderate risk) and Asia Pacific Growth A ($$$, 12.37 percent five-year return, high risk); New Opportunities A (SCG), $$$$, 26.2 percent five-year return, high risk; Vista A (LCG), $$$, 18.2 percent five-year return, high risk; for LCV, use Equity Income A (an LCG fund moving toward LCV), $$$, 13.4 percent five-year return, moderate risk.<p>
**<A HREF="http://www.vanguard.com/">Vanguard</A>Vanguard**<p>
Vanguard. International Growth (GLO), $$$$, 11.6 percent five-year return, low risk; Index Small Cap Stock (SCG), $$$$, 15.5 percent five-year return, low risk; Index 500 (LCG), $$$$, 13.4 percent five-year return, low risk; Windsor II (LCV), $$$$, 14.7 percent five-year return, moderate risk.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
