<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Using Asset Classes as Building Blocks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Using Asset Classes as Building Blocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Jubak<p>
Diversifying a portfolio by investing in different asset classes not only can reduce risk but also has been shown to enhance performance. What's an asset class? Actually, it's just a useful abstraction -- a way of describing a group of investments with similar performance characteristics. To build an effective portfolio, we divided the universe of qualified equity funds (those with five years of history and assets of $50 million) into the five asset classes shown below. Our system features minimal overlap but broad reach. Each category also offers a different level of risk, as measured by standard deviation over the past three years. (Standard deviation is a measure of the variation of a fund's performance over time.) Risk decreases as you go from the top of the list (global funds) to the bottom (large-cap value). In addition, the classes have different performance characteristics in relation to one another and to the market as a whole.<p>
Global Funds. 
<img src="/imgs/WP1028A.gif" width=352 height=240><p>
These 116 funds all have at least 40 percent of their assets overseas. Of our five categories, this one shows the greatest standard deviation and therefore the highest risk. The funds in this category are the least likely to track the U.S. market -- making them a key element in a diversified portfolio. This class is most likely to be overlooked or underweighted.<p>
Small-cap Growth Funds. 
<img src="/imgs/WP1028B.gif" width=352 height=240><p>
These 114 funds try to buy the stock of small companies soon to become big companies. Earnings of the companies in these portfolios are growing at 28.8 percent annually. These risky funds show the highest beta, the highest price-to-earnings ratio, and the highest standard deviation among our four domestic categories.<p>
Large-cap Growth Funds. 
<img src="/imgs/WP1028C.gif" width=352 height=240><p>
These 396 funds seek big companies that are still growing rapidly. The companies in these funds average an annual earnings growth rate of 20.8 percent. Big companies tend to grow more slowly than small ones, but they're also less risky: The price-to-earnings ratio averages 23.2 and the standard deviation 10.3.<p>
Small-cap Value Funds. 
<img src="/imgs/WP1028D.gif" width=352 height=240><p>
The managers of the 19 funds in this group try to limit their risk and maximize their gains by purchasing the stocks of smaller companies at bargain prices. On average, they pay less than twice book value for a company's shares. The category's beta is just 0.63, far below the beta of 1.0 for the market as a whole. <p>
Large-cap Value Funds. 
<img src="/imgs/WP1028E.gif" width=352 height=240><p>
The managers of the 74 funds in this group try to spot the stocks of big companies that, for one reason or another, may be sharply undervalued by the market. The average price-to-book ratio of a stock in these portfolios is 2.5. With a standard deviation of just 8.9 and a beta of 0.79, these funds are extremely low risk. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
