<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Picks from the Past</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Picks from the Past</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						If you've taken our advice, you've prospered.<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
We developed our system for picking mutual funds two years ago, choosing the first set of five recommended funds in our November 1994 issue and our second set of five in November 1995. We've continued to refine and improve the system since then, but the underlying methodology is essentially unchanged.<p>
So how have our earlier picks fared? And should readers who followed our advice in 1994 or 1995 jettison any of the funds they bought then in favor of the latest crop?<p>
The short answer to both questions: We're reasonably content with our earlier selections. Seven of the ten look as solid to us today as when we picked them. We're somewhat concerned about two of our other past choices. And in a third case, we have definitely concluded that investors should abandon ship in an orderly fashion.<p>
<img src="/imgs/CH360240.PICT.gif" width=360 height=240><p>
So far, we haven't picked the same fund twice to appear in our top five, but that generally has little to do with the performance of any of our picks. For example, two of our top five funds from last year, <a name="FUND:PRNHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRNHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price New Horizons</b></a> and <a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</b></a>, are now closed to new investors. Their 12-month returns as of August 31, 1996, were 22.04 percent and 17.09 percent, respectively -- both well above the performance of their benchmarks (the Russell 2000 Growth and Russell 2000 Value indexes). <a name="FUND:HRTVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRTVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Value</b></a>, a 1994 top pick, also remains closed. Heartland matched its benchmark, the Russell 2000 Value index, during our most recent 12-month measurement period, earning a 12.12 percent return.<p>
It doesn't surprise us a bit that Mutual Beacon and Mutual Qualified, our top picks in the large-cap-value category in 1994 and 1995, respectively, earn $$$$$ ratings again this year. Neither, however, was selected for one of our top five spots this time around. Portfolio manager Michael Price recently sold the fund's parent company to the Franklin Templeton Group, which, in turn, will impose a 4.5 percent sales charge on new investors beginning October 25. That was all we needed to hear -- even considering Beacon's 12-month return of 14.86 percent and Qualified's 13.87 percent. Respectable, yes, but not enough to justify an exorbitant sales charge.<p>
Last November, we were worried about the performance of <a name="FUND:WIETX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WIETX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus International Equity Fund Common Shares</b></a>, our 1994 choice for best global fund. This year, we're pleased to say that Warburg has proved the danger of putting too much weight on one-year returns. Although the fund trailed its benchmark, the Morgan Stanley EAFE index, in our 1995 ratings, it bounced back smartly in our most recent rating period, returning 9.87 percent. That handily beat the EAFE. Meanwhile, our 1995 global pick, <a name="FUND:FWWGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FWWGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Founders Worldwide Growth</b></a>, did even better, returning 11.44 percent. Our top global choice this year, though, outflanked these two because it is better suited to our new asset-allocation model.<p>
We do think that the performances of two funds from the 1994 and 1995 group bear continued close scrutiny. Spiros Segalas's <a name="FUND:HACAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HACAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harbor Capital Appreciation</b></a>, a 1995 pick, returned just 7.77 percent during the latest 12-month period -- the result of last summer's rout in technology stocks. Segalas has shown an ability to ride out such short-term volatility before, so we think investors should hang on. <p>
We also aren't jumping for joy over the fact that <a name="FUND:WAAEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WAAEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wasatch Aggressive Equity</b></a>, a 1994 pick, returned just 3.21 percent for the recent 12-month period, about six percentage points below its benchmark, the Russell 2000 Growth Index. It looks to us as though portfolio manager Samuel S. Stewart Jr. took just enough risk to get clobbered last summer but wasn't aggressive enough to have built up a cushion in the momentum-driven market of 1995 and early 1996. We think this fund is worth sticking with, however, especially since it's now closed to new investors.<p>
The one fund pick we'd definitely like to have back is <a name="FUND:FDEQX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FDEQX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Disciplined Equity</b></a>, our 1994 choice for best large-cap growth fund. This year, it dropped to a $$$ rating and returned just 6.46 percent during the most recent 12 months. That's well below its five-year average annual performance of 13.89 percent.<p>
What frightens us now is that manager Brad Lewis seems to have revised the elaborate software model he uses to pick stocks. Our worry is that Lewis may be giving too much weight to the kinds of stocks that have been winners lately, rather than sticking with the style that earned him his early success. That on top of a big drop in the fund's predictor rating in 1995 means the fund just doesn't have the consistency we require for inclusion in our model portfolio.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:PRNHX">T. Rowe Price New Horizons</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:PRSVX">T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:HRTVX">Heartland Value</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:WIETX">Warburg Pincus International Equity Fund Common Shares</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:FWWGX">Founders Worldwide Growth</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:HACAX">Harbor Capital Appreciation</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:WAAEX">Wasatch Aggressive Equity</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:FDEQX">Fidelity Disciplined Equity</a><br>

