<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Making It Personal</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Making It Personal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Rated: 719 equity funds. Picked: the best five. Built: a series of model portfolios. All to suit your real-world finances.<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
The ideal mutual-fund selection system would do four important things. It would offer a rational, defensible system for identifying which among the best-performing equity funds are likely to maintain a stellar record. It would enable investors to build a portfolio of such funds based on an effective asset-allocation model -- one that would improve returns and reduce risk. It would allow investors to customize their portfolios to suit their specific needs and objectives. And it would provide a framework that would easily accommodate people who own other investments, such as a portfolio of individual stocks or employee stock options.<p>
Such a system is exactly what we set out to construct this year as part of our annual review of mutual-fund performance. In the tables following this story, you'll find our usual dollar-sign ratings for more than 700 funds -- from $$$$$ for the best to a single $ for the worst. Along the way, we'll also reveal our top fund in each of five categories. <p>
We'll also explain how readers can take advantage of our methods to make the best choices in assembling a truly personal investment portfolio.<p>
As a guide, we've developed a basic portfolio model to meet the needs of the typical long-term investor -- plus five additional portfolios modified to fit life as Americans really live it. Investors need to send children to college, they own small businesses, they receive compensation in the form of company stock. Some of us can stand to be aggressive with our investments; others need steady current income or just don't have the stomach for a wild ride. All these factors change the way an investor should allocate investments in their portfolios. We've also included advice on how to assemble the best portfolio within the limitations of the typical 401(k) plan.<p>
Our models use the five fundamental asset classes we introduced two years ago: large-capitalization growth, large-cap value, small-cap growth, small-cap value, and global. Together, these groups not only cover the widest possible range of proven investing strategies but also offer the best-known combination for enhancing return while limiting risk. These categories also allow investors who own individual stocks to calculate their exposure in each group -- and to adjust their overall holdings of funds and stocks accordingly.<p>
This general approach, derived from modern portfolio theory and most commonly referred to as asset allocation, has recently become the hot trend in the financial-services industry. One by one, the biggest mutual-fund families -- those that have garnered the lion's share of the 401(k) business -- have begun shifting their marketing campaigns away from the cult of the superstar fund manager. The new emphasis, promoted in the educational programs that are offered through employers to 401(k) participants, is on providing investors with a selection of funds that can be clearly distinguished from one another, that offer clear and consistent styles, and that can be easily combined in a portfolio that is relatively stable.<p>
Brokerage companies, along with the rapidly growing financial-adviser industry, are preaching the gospel, too. What are they offering to justify their fees? Basically, it boils down to asset allocation. <p>
Why Asset Allocation Works<p>
Asset allocation actually seems a strange tool to seize upon as a marketing edge because it isn't all that complicated to execute once you understand the basic principles. It's based on research, begun in the 1950s, that shows how an investor who combines assets with different characteristics in a portfolio can achieve optimal results over the long term.<p>
Asset allocation, for example, lies behind the oft repeated recommendation to blend international equities with domestic stocks to increase performance and lower risk. At first blush, that might seem a mistake. By themselves, foreign stocks are historically riskier than U.S. equities. Yet when an investor adds a mix of international equities to a domestic-stock portfolio, overall risk does decline. According to calculations by Bankers Trust Global Investment Management, for example, from 1971 through 1995, a portfolio of 60 percent U.S. stocks and 40 percent non-U.S. stocks returned about one percentage point more annually and had a standard deviation about 2.5 percentage points lower than a portfolio of 100 percent U.S. stocks. (Standard deviation is a commonly accepted way to measure risk.)<p>
It's actually not the risk level of each asset class that's important; it's how the asset classes work together. Asset allocation reduces risk because some investment classes zig when others zag. Markets that move in the same direction most of the time are said to be highly correlated. There's not much point in building a portfolio around two highly correlated assets. But putting together two assets with a low correlation can give a portfolio quite a pop.<p>
Nor do investors have to go overseas to find assets with low correlations. Inside the U.S. market, different segments move out of step at times. For example, in 1977, the large-company stocks of the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index lost about 7 percent. Small-company stocks, on the other hand, climbed 25 percent. Value and growth stocks also move out of step as they respond differently to the cycles of economic growth.<p>
The needs and goals of an investor dictate which combination of asset classes is most appropriate. The goal of good asset allocation is to get the most return for the acceptable risk in each situation.<p>
To see how this works, look at the model portfolios "The Optimist" and "The Cautious Investor." Each lies along what is called the efficient frontier, a theoretical line that shows the amount of return an investor should aim for at any given level of risk (and vice versa). Badly designed portfolios diverge from this line either by taking on more risk than they need to or by returning less than they should for the risk they take. Well-designed portfolios are those that show the best trade-off between risk and reward.<p>
For example, our Optimist portfolio is projected to return a compounded 13.4 percent a year, according to historical returns for equities as calculated by Ibbotson Associates, a Chicago investment-research firm. (This, like all financial calculations, assumes that the future will resemble the past.) But this portfolio's standard deviation is 17.9 percent -- which means that about two-thirds of the time its return will fall between 31.3 percent and negative 4.5 percent. Quite a ride.<p>
Our Cautious portfolio, on the other hand, is projected to return an average annual 12.1 percent with a standard deviation of 7.3 percent. Two-thirds of the time, this portfolio's return will fall between 4.8 percent and 19.4 percent. That's certainly a lot less risk -- but look at the difference in return. Over 20 years, $10,000 in the Optimist portfolio would grow to $123,669. In the Cautious portfolio it would reach just $98,200. Is one of these models better than the other? Not at all. But one is certainly more appropriate for a given investor.<p>
Asset allocation can get pretty arcane at this point, as investors try to determine whether to carry, say, 23 percent or 24 percent of their portfolio in small-cap value stocks. This kind of precise optimization -- along with constant updates -- is what the institutions and advisers are peddling. We believe, though, that this degree of accuracy is best suited to institutional investors who can afford to fine-tune a portfolio daily. Most individual investors can do very well with the kind of basic allocation shown below and the modifications shown in the box on pages 102 and 103.<p>
Having made the fundamental decisions about asset allocation, the investor should then identify an investment vehicle or vehicles for each asset class. In the case of a fund portfolio, an investor needs to be able to select a mutual fund that invests effectively in each category. Buying a fund that wanders all over the block, investing in small caps one minute and in Dow Jones Industrials the next, would subvert an investor's model. Fidelity's popular Magellan Fund, for instance, altered its investing strategy so drastically in the past year that we had to move it from our large-cap-growth category into large-cap value. Funds that do this force asset-allocation investors to keep readjusting their portfolios to bring them back into balance.<p>
This is one reason many people favor funds tied to certain stock-market indexes. By definition, these funds must remain consistent in the way they invest. Index funds make a lot of sense for another reason, too: They outperform most active fund managers. By buying an index fund, an investor gets stylistic consistency and returns that are likely to beat as many as three-quarters of all managers.<p>
But index funds also have drawbacks. They work best in efficient sectors of the market like large-cap growth, where the Vanguard Index 500 fund earns $$$$ in our ratings. The fund's five-year average annual return of 13.44 percent ranks it above the 75th percentile in the range of returns of all funds in this category.<p>
In the less efficient category of small-cap growth, the Vanguard Index Small Cap Stock fund doesn't do quite as well. It still earns a $$$$ rating, but its 15.53 percent average annual five-year return puts it in only the 61st percentile in its category. What's more, there are no index funds at all in the small-cap- and large-cap-value categories. Nor does any broad-based index fund appear on our global list. <p>
We use actively managed funds in our system because we believe we can identify managers who have demonstrated substantial expertise in choosing stocks in specific segments of the market -- enough to give them an edge over an index, where one exists -- and who are willing to stick to their guns even when their particular style may be out of favor with the broader market. <p>
How We Pick the Best Funds<p>
Each year, we search for such mutual-funds managers by dividing the universe of funds into our five asset classes. We start with recent data provided by Morningstar in Chicago but rely on our own research to fill holes in the numbers and to verify the accuracy of the information. We look only at equity mutual funds with track records of at least five years and assets of at least $50 million. Sector funds -- those that invest only in a specific industry -- don't fit our definition of an asset class, so we do not include them. This year, 719 equity funds meet our minimum requirements.<p>
Next, we split out the global and international funds (this year there were 116), giving us one of our five asset categories. Domestic funds are then divided into four groups through a two-step process.<p>
First, we divide the funds on the basis of whether they invest primarily in small- or large-cap stocks. ("Cap" here refers to the median market capitalization of the stocks in the fund's portfolio.) We designate a fund as large cap if its median market capitalization is more than $1.8 billion. Small-cap funds fall below that level.<p>
Second, with the help of index analyst Kevin Maloney at Frank Russell Co. in Tacoma, Washington, we classify domestic funds based on whether they are more apt to buy stocks for their growth potential or for their instrinsic value. To do this, we look at the median price-to-book ratio (the relationship between the price of a stock and its underlying asset value) for the stocks in each fund's portfolio. Among large-cap funds, a median price-to-book ratio above 2.96 puts a fund into our growth category; anything below that goes into value. For small-cap funds, we use a median price-to-book ratio of 2.23 as the dividing line.<p>
These two steps do most of our work for us. To double-check our choices, we go back through the funds, looking at such things as the average price-to-earnings ratio and the average growth rate of the stocks they hold. In many cases, we also look at a fund's top stock holdings -- all this to make sure we place each fund in the appropriate investing category. <p>
The five categories give us the building blocks of an effective, diversified portfolio that balances large-cap funds against small-cap, value against growth, and domestic funds against those that invest around the world.<p>
But we also want to know which funds in each asset category do a good job and which are no better than mediocre. So we rate each for return, risk, and predictability.<p>
We score for return (total investment return minus the effect of sales charges) by comparing each fund's performance against that of its peers during the past five years. Our tables list this score for each fund as well as its raw one-, three-, and five-year results. (We treat global funds a little differently, dividing the category into two peer groups for the purpose of scoring -- one for funds with more than 75 percent of their assets outside the U.S. and one for funds with at least 40 percent overseas.)<p>
To calculate risk, we focus on three measures: standard deviation (which shows the degree of variance in a fund's performance over time); beta (a measure of a fund's volatility in relation to the entire stock market); and turnover (the percentage of stocks in a fund's portfolio that are bought and sold over the course of a year). We give each fund a high-, medium-, or low-risk rating based on how it stacks up against its peers for each of the three measures.<p>
Our predictor rating, a feature found in no other fund-ranking system, assesses how likely a fund is to repeat its past performance. To arrive at this score, we check the tenure of a fund's manager during the five-year study period, look at the rate of growth in a fund's assets since 1993, and compare current ratios such as beta and price-to-book with the same measures three years ago. In each case, we check for big changes that could signal shifts in a fund's style.<p>
Our final overall rating, expressed by dollar signs, rates each fund based on its level of return, risk, and predictability. Only funds with scores in the top 5 percent of their peer group earn our highest $$$$$ rating. <p>
An investor wouldn't go wrong using any of our $$$$$ funds to construct a portfolio. Some suggestions on how to do this can be found in the box on pages 102 and 103.<p>
To identify our favorite in each category, Worth editors take a close look at each of the top scorers. At this point, the process does become somewhat subjective. What do we know about the manager? What do we think of his or her overall strategy? Do we agree with his or her top stock picks? Do we have reason to believe that this fund will continue to perform in the future as it has in the past? <p>
We selected the five funds that appear in the profiles below. As you read about these funds, you'll note that each has a clear, distinct investing style, one that its manager has stuck with over the years and one that has served it exceedingly well. Each fund has been on top of its game for some time, and we see no reason why it shouldn't stay there in the years ahead. <p>
Best Small-Cap Growth Fund<p>
ACORN
We like Acorn because we like senior manager Ralph Wanger and the way he picks stocks. He's a classic small-cap investor who uses a disciplined, beat-the-bushes approach to uncover small companies that stand a chance of one day becoming large companies. His objective is to find small companies that he can hold over the long term. (The annual turnover rate of the 350-odd stocks in Acorn's portfolio is a skimpy 29 percent.) <p>
Wanger has a couple of firm rules about stock picking. First, stay away from short-term investing because it costs shareholders money when a fund realizes capital gains and because trading costs on small-company stocks can push up expenses.<p>
The second Wanger rule: Pay for growth, but don't overpay. The average price-to-earnings ratio of stocks in Acorn's portfolio is 25.6 -- not low but well within reason for a fund focusing on small growth stocks.<p>
Wanger does fundamental research on each company he owns and also insists that he or one of his researchers personally interview the company's executives, suppliers, and competitors. "That's very basic," he says. "We always check on a company ourselves." Harley-Davidson, the motorcycle manufacturer, has become a Wanger favorite. So has Carnival Cruise Lines. "The company has to have some sort of theme or a niche that allows you to think they will have a special franchise," says Wanger. <p>
Investors who own Acorn can expect consistency -- in the types of companies in the fund's portfolio and in the manager's style, for Wanger has run Acorn essentially the same way for 26 years. "We've traditionally been a small-cap fund," he says. "We try to stay in more secondary companies, where we think there is more value." <p>
Since mid-1995, Wanger and his longtime partner, Chuck McQuaid, have been sharing their favorite investment ideas in this magazine's regular "What They're Buying Now" column. Worth readers who own this fund can follow along as the pair seeks out new prospects. Wanger also plans to share his long experience next year in a book he's titled A Zebra in Lion Country. "Zebras are good-looking and agile," Wanger says, explaining the title, "but they have to be careful not to get eaten by the lions." <p>
Best Small-Cap Value Fund<p>
<a HREF="http://mjwhitman.com/third.htm">THIRD AVENUE VALUE</A>
Third Avenue Value may well be the best of the so-called vulture funds. Manager Marty Whitman's mission is about as clear as it gets: to identify assets he can buy for 50 cents on the dollar -- with little or no risk. "We want 'em safe and cheap," says Whitman.<p>
The emphasis on safety is critical because, as Whitman explains in his latest report to shareholders, "every security in which TAVF invests has something wrong [with it]." So, once he and his team of researchers identify an opportunity, they generally spend far more time analyzing the ways it might turn sour than the ways it might soar.<p>
Cautious and yet aggressive at the same time, Whitman's approach has produced an average annual return of 15.97 percent since 1991. Throughout this five-year period, the fund's risk level -- as measured by its standard deviation -- has stayed in the bottom quarter of the industry.<p>
A recent Whitman coup: At the end of last year, Third Avenue began investing in Kmart debentures. They were available at 74 cents on the dollar, partly because rumors were circulating that the big retailer might soon be forced to file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. Whitman's analysis, however, showed that the credits would not only yield 18 percent annually to maturity but hold their full dollar value even in the event of a bankruptcy.<p>
Third Avenue's most recent plays involve companies that supply equipment to semiconductor manufacturers. "All these companies -- the Silicon Valley Group, for example -- have cash flow far in excess of total liabilities," he says. "All are selling at 6 or 7 times their latest 12-month earnings, while the overall market's at about 19 times earnings."<p>
Of course, as with all technology stocks, these companies carry the added risk that their products could suddenly become outmoded. Whitman hedges by "buying across the entire manufacturing process," he explains. "We figured that out of the eight stocks we picked two might go sour, but six will be big winners."<p>
Whitman wouldn't deign to refer to this strategy as diversification. "Diversification is a poor surrogate for knowledge," he declares. In this case, he's banking on semiconductor chips' continuing to be in heavy demand over the next two to five years, as applications increasingly move from computers to more mainstream uses, such as credit cards, telephones, and automobiles.<p>
Whitman's objective is to earn an annual return of 20 percent, and by mid-September he was only halfway there. Patience, however, is critical when it comes to owning Third Avenue. Whitman's plays can take time to develop, but there's no one with a better reputation for turning 50 cents into a dollar.<p>
Best Large-Cap Growth Fund<p>
<a name="FUND:OAKMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OAKMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>OAKMARK</b></a>
Robert Sanborn isn't what you would call his own best salesman. He scoffs at the importance of past performance in picking a fund -- though Oakmark, which he co-founded in 1991 and manages, has returned a remarkable 27.1 percent annually over the past five years. <p>
Sanborn buys a stock only when he'd like to own the whole company -- the Warren Buffett approach to investing. He also puts the bulk of his fund's portfolio (over 70 percent) into a short list of 20 big-company stocks. <p>
Oakmark takes a position in a company when it's selling at 60 percent or less of what Sanborn calculates as the price a rational buyer would pay for it as a whole, i.e., its takeover value. That strategy has spread Oakmark's portfolio across the economy, with some concentration in financial and consumer stocks. Current favorites include <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:BDK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10214"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Black & Decker</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:BUD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Anheuser-Busch</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10983"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mellon Bank</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:FUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15687"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First USA</b></a>. These companies are "all very high-quality, high-return, high-barrier-to-entry businesses with dominant market positions, very loyal end-users, and tremendous international opportunities," Sanborn wrote in a recent shareholder report.<p>
Sanborn makes a point of not having an opinion on the short-term prospects for the market. "I really don't," he says. "At today's valuations levels, I think people should be buying the fund for five years at least and should be able to tolerate a 20 percent decline in their investment value without affecting their lifestyle."<p>
Sanborn and his staff pick stocks one by one. It's a bottom-up process that involves seven analysts, each of whom comes up with ideas that then must compete against those of the other analysts. For a stock to make it into the portfolio, it has to oust one of Oakmark's current top 20 stocks. Turnover this year is below the fund's historically low 18 percent rate.<p>
Best Large-Cap Value Fund<p>
<a name="FUND:DODGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DODGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DODGE & COX STOCK</b></a>
Dodge & Cox Stock is kept on the straight and narrow in two ways: It adheres to a strict investment philosophy, and it's run by an eight-person committee whose newest member joined 12 years ago. The fund itself dates back to 1965. "We all started at Dodge & Cox in a research capacity," says Ken Olivier, a committee member and senior vice president of the San Francisco–based fund.<p>
Team members say that an emphasis on research, combined with the group dynamic, helps maintain the fund's focus. "It really gives us the persistence to stick with companies," says Olivier. "Too often you buy a stock and it doesn't immediately perform. If a stock's not working, but we're still convinced on the fundamentals, we'll even add to our position in small increments." That's reflected in the fund's turnover rate -- a minuscule 13 percent. Says John Gunn, the fund's president and chief operating officer, "We're enormously persistent. We try to distinguish that from stubborn."<p>
An example: Back in 1989, Dodge & Cox took a hefty position in <a name="NYSE:CCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Citicorp</b></a> at about $30 a share. Then, says Gunn, "we got caught by the real-estate debacle." The stock dropped to $10 a share. "We looked at it and compared the assets and holdings. We looked at past bank debacles and knew we were looking at a lot of quarters without earnings." Still, Dodge & Cox stuck with its pick. Today, Citicorp is trading at around $87 a share.<p>
At first glance, this fund looks a lot like a Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index fund in disguise. More than 95 percent of its 85 stock holdings, in fact, are included in the index. But there are differences. For one, the average price-to-book ratio of the Dodge & Cox portfolio is close to half that of the S&P 500. For another, the fund has consistently outperformed the S&P 500, returning an average 15.33 percent annually for the past five years, compared with 13.58 for the index.<p>
Dodge & Cox's success also stems from serious cost-consciousness. The fund doesn't advertise, and it often achieves a portfolio turnover rate as low as 10 percent. "In running our firm, one of the goals is to keep expenses as low as possible," says Olivier. "Go back to 1986–1990. Our ratio of expenses to average net assets was in the range of 65 to 69 cents per $100 of assets. Last year we were at 60 cents."<p>
Best Global Fund<p>
<a name="FUND:USIFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/USIFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>USAA INTERNATIONAL</b></a>
You don't get where David Peebles has gotten by shying away from the unfamiliar. "The thing I like most about the fund is we're not dealing in efficient markets," says Peebles, manager of USAA International. "I don't find it as interesting to make a decision on buying or selling two or three stocks in an industry where everything is known about the company and everybody has the same information, like choosing between <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> versus <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>. The global market isn't efficient yet, because the information is not well-known. So you have greater odds of making a lot more money by selecting the right stock."<p>
What does that say about risk? "I think that being diversified in 40 countries, with over 150 stocks in the fund, the fund has relatively low risk," he says. "Because we have so many stocks, we have no real big bets in any one stock, so we've spread the risk out. Because it's low risk we tend to have good performance in down markets."<p>
Peebles and his two portfolio managers, Travis Selmier and Al Sebastian, begin their company analysis with country analysis: They give great consideration to a country's macroeconomic factors and government policies. Then they get down to some very basic stuff. "If you're working in one market, like the U.S., you can develop one style and be pretty successful," Peebles says. "But when you're working in 40 countries, all of which are in various stages of development, you can't rely on a single style. So you not only have to look at things like standard ratios -- p/e, cash flow, book value -- but you have to look at them in relation to, say, accounting principles of various countries." <p>
Twice a year Peebles, Selmier, Sebastian, and the fund's three analysts each make a two-week overseas trip, stopping in as many as five countries apiece. They visit targeted companies and talk to management and also drop in on central-bank officials and meet with analysts and researchers at local brokerages. All this work has produced average annual returns of 13.01 percent for the past five years, which puts USAA International among the top 10 percent of funds in our global category.<p>
Additional reporting by Dave Califano, Paul Davies, Ken Kurson, Elizabeth Macdonald, Leland Montgomery, and Michael Peltz.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

