				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Well-Spent Youth</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>
Perched on the edge of his bed, Arthur Bochner bounces excitedly as he discusses his portfolio. "Last week, I hit $100,000, if you count the maturity of my bonds," he says. "It's pretty wild."<p>
But for this 14-year-old, who stashes *Disney coupons in his bedroom safe and scans the Net for prospective buys, investing is elementary. He bought his first stock at age nine. That was two years before he co-wrote (with his mom, a stockbroker and financial planner) The Totally Awesome Money Book for Kids and Their Parents.<p>
"I was in Venezuela on a country road, and all of a sudden I saw a *Blockbuster," Bochner recalls of his very first investment insight. "There was nothing else there." Returning home to South Orange, New Jersey, Bochner bought 100 Blockbuster shares at $17 each. A few months later, he unloaded the shares at $30 apiece. "I was, like, wow!" he says.<p>
Bochner grabs his latest brokerage statement from a shelf lined with chess trophies -- he's ranked eighth in his age-group nationwide -- and reads off some of his current holdings. "*Kyocera is a Japanese company that makes ceramic housings for computer chips," he explains. "It's very volatile because you're investing in the yen." He's got *British Petroleum, because "there's one down the street and I like to stick close to home," and *Mark Twain Bancshares, which sells CDs in foreign currencies.<p>
As an investor, Bochner's got a bundle of confidence. "I'd like to take more risks," he says. "Maybe do puts and calls." As a teenager, though, he's no stranger to adolescent angst. He just started high school. "That's  scary," he says with a nervous bounce.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

