	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-10 Stocks To Avoid/Consider</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-10 Stocks To Avoid/Consider</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						10 STOCKS TO AVOID:
Michael Murphy began his newsletter for short-sellers, Overpriced Stock Service, in 1983, when he was struck by glaring discrepancies in the quality of technology companies going public. "There were a lot of junky stocks, and I thought there ought to be a newsletter warning people," he says. Murphy, 54, predicted the breakdown in oil prices in the 1980s and made money shorting savings-and-loans before the industry’s collapse. To identify stocks to short, he looks for companies flashing such danger signs as low cash flow, insider selling, and ballooning inventories. His average short position lasts seven months. Murphy sees little joy at Toys "R" Us this holiday season: The Federal Trade Commission is investigating the company for pressuring toy manufacturers not to sell to less expensive warehouse chains. A bet on an inferior cellular-phone technology could be the downfall of Qualcomm, a stock Murphy has shorted in his own fund. Terms of the partnership between International Paper and IP Timberlands, which harvests timber for paper, will shift in three years and sharply reduce the dividend to shareholders. And Evergreen Media has doubled its debt acquiring radio stations, where growth, says Murphy, will be slow at best. <p>
<a name="NASD:BMET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12777"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Biomet</b></a> (Nasdaq: BMET) $10<br>
* Losing business to competition<br> 
* Outdated technology<br>
* Forecast of declining earnings<br><p>
<a name="NASD:COPY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13105"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CopyTele</b></a>(Nasdaq:COPY ) 0<br>
* Developing outdated technology <br>
* Unsuccessful joint ventures<br>
* No revenues<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:DNA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10459"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Diana</b></a> (NYSE: DNA) 10<br>
* Meat-delivery company trying to market Internet switches<br>
* Intense competition<br><p>
<a name="AMEX:EPT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11809"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Epitope</b></a> (AMEX:EPT) 0<br>
* Increased competition<br>
* Losing market share<br>
* FDA approval didn't buoy stock<br><p>
<a name="NASD:EVGM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16034"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Evergreen Media</b></a> (Nasdaq: EVGM) 30<br>
* Massive debt<br> 
* No earnings<br>
* Slow growth in market<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:IPT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10769"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IP Timberlands</b></a> (NYSE: IPT) 7<br>
* Income will drop in three years<br>
* Overvalued, given scheduled fall in future dividends<br><p>
<a name="AMEX:NVX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41944"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>North American Vaccine</b></a> (AMEX:NVX ) 5<br>
* Posting losses<br> 
* Competitors getting FDA approval<br> 
* Abbott to get big part of profits<br><p>
<a name="AMEX:ORG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12209"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Organogenesis</b></a> (AMEX: ORG ) 0<br>
* Questionable product tests<br> 
* Delay in FDA approval<br>
* No earnings<br><p>
<a name="NASD:QCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11436"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Qualcomm</b></a> (Nasdaq: QCOM) 23<br>
* Inferior cellular technology<br>
* Potential loss of some contracts<br>
* Lack of support for technology<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a> (NYSE: TOY) 20<br>
* Sluggish sales<br>
* Pending FTC investigation<br>
* Potential need to cut prices<br><p>
10 TO CONSIDER: 
Helen Young Hayes is first and foremost a stock picker. "At Janus, we build portfolios stock by stock," says Hayes, who runs the firm’s $3.7 billion <a name="FUND:JAWWX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAWWX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Worldwide Fund</b></a> and $484.8 million <a name="FUND:JAOSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JAOSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Overseas Fund</b></a>, up 22.3 percent and 23.3 percent, respectively, for the 12-month period ended July 31. (Compare that with 9.3 percent and 3.8 percent increases for the Morgan Stanley Capital International World and EAFE indexes.) Hayes -- part of a nine-person international investment team that seeks to identify companies with the potential for strong earnings growth -- argues that Janus’s rigorous bottom-up investment approach "works even better outside the U.S. because the markets are less efficient." Pharmaceutical giants Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline Beecham, for example, are cheap compared with such U.S. drug companies as Merck. Hayes also likes U.K. pest-control company Rentokil Group and Dutch publisher Wolters Kluwer. Although their American depositary receipts are thinly traded on the pink sheets, she says, "I could imagine owning them for ten years." She also advises investors in Grupo Casa Autrey, Grupo Televisa, Telebras, and Telefonica del Peru to be very patient because emerging markets are extremely volatile.<p>
<a name="NASD:DBRSY"></a><b>De Beers Consoldtd. Mines</b>     (Nasdaq: DBRSY) $29<br>
* Global diamond sales picking up<br>
* Cartel has strong monopoly<br>
* Russian diamond supply dwindling<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:GLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41781"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Glaxo Wellcome</b></a> (NYSE: GLX) 30<br>
* Low p/e for drug company<br>
* Great new-drug pipeline<br> 
* Underappreciated in U.S.<br> <p>
<a name="NYSE:ATY"></a><b>Grupo Casa Autrey</b> (NYSE: ATY) 23<br>
* Major drug distributor in Mexico<br>
* Getting into food/office supplies<br>
* Great management team<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:TV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51043"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Grupo Televisa</b></a> (NYSE: TV) 30<br>
* Dominant TV network in Mexico<br>
* Valuable Spanish-program library<br>
* Direct-TV venture in Latin America<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:GUC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46896"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gucci</b></a> (NYSE: GUC) 62<br>
* Rejuvenated brand name<br>
* Tight management of expenses<br>
* Strong sales growth<br><p>
Rentokil Group (OTC: RTOKY) 67<br>
* Top U.K. management team<br>
* Recent acquisition spurs growth<br>
* Low-tech, high-margin business<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:SBH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41844"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SmithKline Beecham</b></a> (NYSE: SBH) 55<br>
* Great new-drug pipeline<br> 
* Growing free cash flow<br>
* Diversity of earnings<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:TBR"></a><b>Telebras</b> (NYSE: TBR) 77<br>
* Huge telephone demand in Brazil<br>
* Possible privatization<br> 
* Operating-cash-flow growth<br><p>
<a name="NYSE:TDP"></a><b>Telefonica del Peru</b> (NYSE: TDP) 24<br>
* Rate reform will stabilize earnings<br>
* Chance to rapidly build network<br>
* Large personnel reduction<br> <p>
Wolters Kluwer (OTC: WTKWY) 121<br>
* Major Dutch specialty publisher<br>
* Moving into electronic media<br>
* Recent acquisition boosts margins<br><p>
UPDATE:
The October 1995 "10 Stocks to Consider" selections by John L. Keeley Jr., president of Keeley Asset Management in Chicago, gained 13.4 percent (compared with the S&P 500's 19.3 percent gain) in the 12 months ended August 20. <a name="NYSE:RON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44237"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cooper Cameron</b></a> rose the most, appreciating 117 percent. The "10 Stocks to Avoid" picked by Howard Schilit, editor of Monthly Research Compendium, dropped 17.4 percent. The fall was led by <a name="NASD:CLST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41895"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CellStar</b></a>, which plunged 77 percent, and <a name="NASD:DSPG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16944"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DSP Group</b></a>, down 63 percent. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

