	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Market Psychology by the Numbers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Market Psychology by the Numbers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Heavy number crunching can give quantitative funds an edge in tough markets.<p>
By Michael Peltz<p>
On July 10, money managers John Bogle Jr. and Mark Engerman were at their computers early. Outside the Cambridge, Massachusetts, offices of their firm, Numeric Investors, the gentle flow of the Charles River was in stark contrast to the turbulence on Wall Street. The day before, <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> had announced second-quarter earnings of 54 cents a share, a staggering 20 percent below analysts' estimates. Like many investors, Bogle and Engerman were trying to decide what to do as Motorola opened down more than nine dollars a share.<p>
As quantitative investors, Bogle and Engerman looked to the numbers for guidance. Quantitative analysis -- as distinguished from qualitative analysis, which focuses on hard-to-measure factors such as the quality of a company's management -- usually begins with fundamental numbers like sales and profits. Bogle and Engerman, however, use the numbers on their computer screens to grasp changes in the psychology of the market. In the case of Motorola, "we saw the analysts' [future] earnings estimates falling dramatically after the announcement," says Bogle. This market favorite had so disappointed analysts that investors were dumping shares. This was no time to buy in hope of a rebound, the partners decided. Instead, they shorted the stock, betting that it would tumble further.<p>
This was all a normal day's work for the partners at Numeric Investors -- Bogle, Engerman, and founder Langdon Wheeler. Numeric's quantitative computer models routinely crunch through revisions in analysts' estimates of future corporate earnings to find stocks that will outperform -- or underperform -- the market. The models have certainly worked in the current market: From October 1991 through June 1996, the firm's $500 million institutional small-cap growth portfolio, for example, had an annualized return of 26.7 percent, versus the Russell 2000 growth index's 15.2 percent return for the same period.<p>
The bulk of the more than $2 billion in assets the firm manages has come from institutional investors who understand the value of the quantitative method's almost antiseptic approach to investing. "Focusing on earnings surprises and earnings growth is a tried-and-true method of picking the winners and avoiding the dogs," says Bluford Putnam, chief strategist at Bankers Trust. And focusing on the numbers also helps control risk by preventing the firm from paying too much for stocks in an overheated market. "When markets are down, risk-management controls become more important, and quant strategies are just excellent in that area because they have no feelings," says Putnam.<p>
The average individual investor has been much slower to embrace quantitative shops like Numeric. According to Lipper Analytical Services research coordinator Jon Teall, there are no more than a couple dozen purely quantitative funds among the 6,000-odd mutual funds tracked by his company. Part of the blame for the scarcity goes to the short-short rule, which basically prohibits a mutual fund from having more than 30 percent of its capital gains come from positions held less than 90 days, a not insignificant hurdle for quantitative funds, which depend on high turnover. Mostly, though, it's a matter of marketing. "The mutual-fund business is more of a marketing than investment business, and quant techniques tend to be esoteric and not easily articulated in a few sentences," says Robert Arnott, CEO of quantitative money-management firm First Quadrant.<p>
And some of the money managers marketing quantitative mutual funds have hurt their own cause, too. Until recently, for example, retail investors had access to Numeric's strategies only through two no-load mutual funds marketed by Quantitative Group of Funds of Lincoln, Massachusetts. One of these, the small-cap <a name="FUND:QBNAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/QBNAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quantitative Numeric Fund,</b></a> closed to new money at $100 million, and the other, the mid-cap <a name="FUND:QNIIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/QNIIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Quantitative Numeric II Fund</b></a>, charged investors a hefty 2.34 percent for expenses -- including a 50-basis-point 12b-1 marketing fee (see box on page 140). Last March, frustrated over high fees, Bogle, Engerman, and Wheeler ended that agreement with the Quantitative Group; in June, they introduced three retail mutual funds of their own: <a name="FUND:NIMCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NIMCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>n/i Micro Cap</b></a>, <a name="FUND:NISGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NISGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>n/i Growth</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:NIGVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NIGVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>n/i Growth & Value</b></a> (800-686-3742).<p>
Wheeler, 49, developed what would become Numeric's system while managing his own money from his Shaftsbury, Vermont, farmhouse in the early 1980s. Using an Apple II computer to crunch through earnings forecasts and prices for 300 stocks, Wheeler studied the effect of changes in analysts' earnings estimates on stock prices. Companies with upward changes in earnings expectations often outperformed the market, and those with downward changes usually underperformed. The hard part was predicting the revisions.<p>
By early 1985, Wheeler had built a successful model, but he was out of money. "I was nearly 40, with two young kids, so I decided to find a respectable job," he says. That year he joined <a name="NYSE:STT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14795"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>State Street Bank and Trust</b></a> in Boston, where he showed how his earnings-estimate-revisions model could be run alongside the bank's value model. The resulting Matrix Synthesis product, later modified by current State Street chief investment officer Peter Stonberg and others, is used today by the bank to manage $7 billion. In 1989, Wheeler left the bank and founded Numeric to continue refining his investment models.<p>
State Street's and Numeric's earnings models are based on behavioral psychology as much as on statistical analysis. "Analysts tend to cluster their forecasts," says Engerman, who came to Numeric in 1994 from BARRA, a stock-market-software developer in Berkeley, California, to head up its research. "They don't like to be perceived as being too dramatically different from the rest of the Street." Analysts tend to revise their estimates incrementally rather than all at once. These small revisions then embolden other analysts to update their estimates. "You get this leapfrogging going on with analysts following one another, and the numbers creep up [or down] over time," explains Bogle, who is the son of Vanguard Group chairman John Bogle and who joined Numeric in 1990 after spending three years at State Street, where he got to know Wheeler. Numeric tries to anticipate the "creep" by looking at not only the size and direction of earnings revisions but also the number of analysts changing their estimates and the degree to which optimistic analysts are getting more upbeat or pessimistic ones more gloomy.<p>
The model works best for smaller stocks because a change in just one or two earnings forecasts has a larger impact when only a few analysts are covering a company. "Small stocks with unique products can also sometimes avoid cyclical shifts in the economy," says Wheeler. "The trends for them can be longer lived." Most of the names in Numeric's portfolios are followed by fewer than ten analysts each.<p>
For all its skill in stock picking, Numeric could've chosen a better date to launch its new family of funds, which debuted under the "n/i" name on June 1, just a few days before the tech sector began its summer descent. Unfortunately, the firm's models had it overweighted in technology. "When you get a major sea change in a sector, the estimate-revisions model doesn't allow you to make a smooth transition," says Richard Bernstein, head of quantitative research at <a name="NYSE:MCO"></a><b>Merrill Lynch</b>. This year Numeric's Micro Cap, Growth, and Growth & Value Funds lost 7.6 percent, 6.1 percent, and 7 percent, respectively, through the end of July.<p>
Actually, Numeric may have more to fear from a directionless market than from one headed determinedly downward. Quantitative funds depend on turning over their portfolios frequently -- their success comes from being right more often than not, rather than on picking a handful of big winners. "We're probably right only 53 or 54 percent of the time," says Bogle. "We rely on the law of large numbers." <p>
That results in a lot of trading, especially in a choppy market. "The transaction costs can eat up a quantitative investor if he's not careful," says Merrill's Bernstein. Numeric's annual turnover is a high 250 to 300 percent, but the 19-person firm keeps a tight eye on every trade. "We're absolute hawks on trading efficiency," says Wheeler. <p>
A falling market, however, would be just fine with Bogle, Engerman, and Wheeler. "It doesn't matter if earnings are all down," says Bogle. "We're buying companies where earnings are decreasing the most slowly." And avoiding those stocks where the numbers on Numeric's computer screen show that investors' love has turned to hate.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

