<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10/-Finding Quality Stocks On Sale</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10/-Finding Quality Stocks On Sale</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Lots of stocks are trading far below their 52-week highs -- a few are good buys now.<p>
By Amy Barrett<p>
The stock market's decline this past July made some stocks look like haute couture gone bargain basement.<p>
For example, <a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a>, one of the country's largest makers of computer memory chips, climbed as high as $94.75 a share last September. In July, it hit $18 a share.<p>
Or consider <a name="NASD:BROD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11907"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Broderbund Software</b></a>, which traded at $31.50 a share on July 25, down from its 52-week high of $78.75; <a name="NYSE:ODP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Office Depot</b></a> ($13.50 on July 25, down from $32.13); and <a name="NASD:RAYS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16239"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sunglass Hut International</b></a> ($13.25, down from $36.94). Even though stocks in general have moved upward from July lows, many issues are still trading at half their recent highs.<p>
Not all of these stocks are bargains. Some have been unfairly savaged by investors who overreacted to fleeting bad news or who fled a solid stock when an industry peer soured. But other stocks have suffered exactly the punishment they deserved as investors suddenly noticed decaying balance sheets, slowing sales, and declining profit margins. So how does an investor decide if a beat-up stock is a good deal?<p>
Wall Street's perception of what next year's earnings will be is a good place to start. A Wall Street rule of thumb says that an investor should be willing to buy a stock if it trades at a price-to-earnings ratio at or below its earnings growth rate. (But for some caveats on this approach, see "Gauging the Price of Growth," May 1996.) So an investor who believes chip maker <a name="NYSE:LSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13932"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LSI Logic</b></a> will make $1.71 a share in the next four quarters and grow by 20.5 percent annually over the next few years, as Wall Street analysts project, can reasonably value the stock at $35.06 a share, well above its August 6 price of $22.75.<p>
But Wall Street has been known to be wrong about earnings. LSI Logic has traded at a price-to-earnings ratio as low as 13 within the past five years. If analysts are wrong and earnings are headed further downward in the future, the stock could trade at just $22.23 instead of $35.06.<p>
Still, weighing the best-case against the worst-case values demonstrates that LSI isn't a bad bet. At worst, it has a fair value only about 50 cents a share below its current price. At best, its value is about $12 above that price. And, of course, the stock has more upside potential if investors get overly enthusiastic about technology stocks again and send LSI soaring above fair value.<p>
To apply this method to stocks that have recently taken a beating, we first asked Standard & Poor's Compustat to sift through the rubble. The result was a list of the 200 stocks -- each with a market capitalization of at least $500 million -- that, as of July 25, had fallen the most in percentage terms from their 52-week highs.<p>
We also asked Compustat to provide us with the consensus estimate of Wall Street analysts for each company's earnings per share for the next four quarters and the estimated three-to-five-year earnings growth rate for each. To get an idea of how each company's future compared to its recent past, we asked Compustat for the actual earnings growth rate over the past three years and the most recent actual earnings per share. (The 15 best and worst "bargains" are listed in the table to the left.)<p>
Our study showed that earnings for many of these beat-up companies are projected not only to fall but to fall steeply. At Micron Technology, earnings per share, which were $3.96 in the four quarters ended May 1996, are projected at $1.08 for the next four quarters. Actual earnings could be lower. Estimates "are under constant revision," says Ben Zacks, executive vice president of Zacks Investment Research in Chicago. "Only the economy will tell."<p>
When we apply our methodology, Micron Technology doesn't look like much of a bargain, even if that $1.08-a-share estimate holds up. Multiplying Micron's estimated $1.08 a share in earnings for the next four quarters by the consensus estimate of 22.9 percent annual growth rate over the next three years values the stock at just $24.70.<p>
But that $24.70 is by no means guaranteed. A flood of chips flowing into the market from new semiconductor plants could drive Micron Technology's earnings even lower. "For the most part, the semiconductor stocks still have the threat of negative earnings and losses as more capacity comes on stream," says Lary Aasheim, a technology analyst for CoreStates Investment Advisors in Philadelphia, which oversees some $10 billion.<p>
So how low could Micron go? Within the past five years, the stock has traded at a price-to-earnings ratio as low as 7.3. That gives the stock a worst-case value of just $7.88 a share, well below its recent price of $22.25. With a fair value on the upside just $2.45 above its recent market price and a downside more than $14 below the current price, Micron doesn't provide an investor with much potential in exchange for all that risk.<p>
Other fallen stocks, in contrast, look like real bargains. <a name="NASD:HLYW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16431"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hollywood Entertainment</b></a>, a video-store chain, plans to open 210 stores next year -- the same as this year's target. That should provide the impetus for growth, says Michael Legg, an associate analyst at Alex. Brown & Sons. Also, the company has cut costs by evaluating each store's business before ordering new videos to sell and rent. Legg expects the company's earnings per share next year to jump by almost 50 percent. The consensus estimates peg the next four quarters' earnings at 59 cents a share, up from 37 cents. Our method gives Hollywood Entertainment an upside value of $23.60 a share and a downside value of $11.80. The stock recently traded at $14.75.<p>
Bargain-hunting investors should know it's extremely difficult to pick the absolute earnings bottom for a company. At first glance, for example, <a name="NASD:NVLS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14288"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Novellus Systems</b></a> looks like a steal with an upside value of $146.20 a share, a downside value of $70.74, and a recent price of $39.50. But earnings will probably come in far below current projections because demand for semiconductor equipment has slowed, says Jeff Middleswart, an analyst at David W. Tice & Associates. While analysts have already begun trimming their projections, "earnings have a lot further to decline," making it a bad time to buy, he says. The same may be true for other equipment makers, such as <a name="NASD:LRCX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13941"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lam Research</b></a>, <a name="NASD:KLAC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13881"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>KLA Instruments</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:AMAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12647"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Applied Materials</b></a>, says Middleswart.<p>
Analysts seem to believe that the chip makers on the list, however, have reached the bottom of their earnings cycle. If analysts are right, <a name="NASD:ALTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12568"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Altera</b></a> should rebound from earnings of $2.35 a share to $2.53, and <a name="NASD:VLSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15037"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VLSI Technology</b></a> should record earnings of $1.19, up from 98 cents.<p>
Of course, the fact that the turnaround at chip makers is more certain means that, although these stocks don't carry the risk of the semiconductor-equipment makers, they don't have anywhere near the upside potential either. Sadly, in looking for bargain stocks, as in 
other kinds of investing, there is really no such thing as a free lunch.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

