		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-The Market Made Me Do It</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-The Market Made Me Do It</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Twelve weeks of anxious and improbable brilliance<p>
By Colin Harrison<p>
When a savvy investor friend called to recommend a high-tech small-cap Nasdaq stock last May 3, little did either of us know how bad his recommendation would be nor how much money it would soon make for me. Only recently had I gone on the Internet at work, and even as my pal, a former commodities trader, extolled the company, I realized that if I bought some shares I could check their price hourly. Hopping around the Internet, I'd already found the sites where one can get a stock quote for free on a 20-minute delayed basis (I like <A HREF="http://www.pcquote.com/">http://www.pcquote.com/</A>, where I also check the Dow), and so the prospect of tracking the value of my own shares was an idea that slid into my consciousness like a needle into a willing vein.<p>
But this wasn't what sold me. The company, <a name="NASD:VSNR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47703"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Visioneer</b></a> (VSNR), made inexpensive desktop scanners -- called PaperPorts that plugged into PCs. "They're terriffic!" my friend said. "I have one." The stock price had tumbled in the previous three days from $15 a share to $10.75, and this, he ffigured, was a buying opportunity. Soon, by visiting price-graph sites and the company's home page (<A HREF="http://www.visioneer.com/>http://www.visioneer.com/</A>), I knew Visioneer had gone public last December at $12 a share and seen its price zoom to a high of $23 before falling. It had only $18 million in revenue the previous quarter, with no earnings per share and no dividend. Licensing agreements with <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> boded well, however. Perhaps Visioneer was a solid long-term buy. Or merely one of the tech IPOs that had blossomed in the rains of speculation.<p>
My last question for my friend: "Did you buy it?"<p>
Yes, he said, at $10.125, and so, with a call to <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a>, I jumped in, too: 3,000 shares at $11.<p>
On margin, no less. Oh, hell -- I had made some money in the tech run-up. I had a feeling. I liked the buzz here. The company made a new, useful product. I'd sit back and dispassionately watch the stock grow.<p>
I'd do nothing of the sort. Within minutes of the completed order, I was obsessively checking the price and volume on my computer, greedily watching those little <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a> comets flickering with possibility. In the pauses at work. While I dialed the phone. Before lunch. After lunch. Fifteen times a day. It took, what, three seconds to flick up the price? If I could check it this often, I wouldn't lose a lot of money, right? Even if, against the advice of my friend, I hadn't put in price stops?<p>
Meanwhile, I found a chat room (<A HREF="http://www.talk.techstocks.com/proffiles/VSNR.html">http://www.talk.techstocks.com/proffiles/VSNR.html</A>) where Visioneer junkies consoled one another on the recent price drop, floated dubious analysis, and made fervid predictions about the future glory of the stock's price: $18, $20, even $30. The prevailing mood was religious, potentially ecstatic. The jargon and insiderish comments comforted me, and my faith soon proved rewarding. On May 9, the stock hit $13. I was up 18.18 percent in six days. Sell or wait? I remembered the famous words of Joseph P. Kennedy: "Only a fool holds out for the top dollar." I sold, moving 1,000 shares at $13.125, 1,600 at $13.25, and the last 400 at $13.375. After commissions, a proffit of $6,295.<p>
I called my friend. Was he still holding the stock? I asked slyly. "Nah," he said, "I was out at 11 and a half."<p>
Seduction takes many forms. Over the next eight trading days, here was Visioneer lap dancing before me. Down to $12.875. Up to $14.50. Down to $11.50. Up to $12.50. Somebody, the market maker presumably, was making serious money. How much could I make? I put together an Excel spreadsheet to figure theoretical proffits and losses after commission and margin interest. And I watched -- like a kid nervously following a jump rope, waiting to time it right, get inside the action. On May 22, I jumped -- in for 1,000 shares at $11.125. Two days later, on May 24, even as doomsayers predicted market carnage, the stock popped up to $13.50, then started to drop. Was I too late? Jump. I sold the 1,000 at $12.375. Proffit: $1,018.09. <p>
It won't get easier than this, I warned myself. I was right. On June 4, I jumped back in for 3,000 shares at $11.125. The price dropped immediately. By June 6, it was below $10. Worried, I consulted the on-line chatter: "The rumor was that they had to recall some PaperPorts in Q1 because of a potential mechanical problem." My friend called me. "Visioneer!" he said. "Yes, yes!" I answered anxiously. He made sounds of commiseration. "You know..." I mused, then repeated some of the arguments for a higher price that had appeared on-line. "And," I concluded, "with that logic I should buy more now." My friend agreed mine was a pretty theory, adding that he would be much impressed if I bought more stock now. I ended the conversation thinking he was a fine fellow indeed for not pointing out what a fool I might soon prove myself to be. But I watched the stock. The volume slowed. The bounce is coming, I thought -- do it. And I did -- 1,000 more shares at $9.75. Now I was in for 4,000 shares, on margin.<p>
On June 7, the stock hit nine dollars, equal to the record low. My proffits were gone. I was, I knew now, an irresponsible fool, a lout, a self-cheat, an unworthy father and husband, a dead dog on the road. But on June 10, the stock ratcheted back up over $10. It closed at $10.75. I kept plugging the numbers into my spreadsheet. The next day, $11.50. I had moved back into the black. The next day, the price popped over $12. I sold 3,000 shares at $12 and the last 1,000 at $11.75, for a proffit of about $4,085.<p>
I had now made seven calls to Schwab (four buys, three sells) and was up more than $11,000. As they say in certain New York City neighborhoods, botta-boom, botta-bing.<p>
Next came a vacation in Tuscany. I told my friend I thought I'd leave a buy order for Visioneer at nine -- in case the price bounced way down for a moment. "Don't!" he warned. "You won't be able to check the market!" "But that would be a record low," I said. "Don't," he responded. "You'll be taken out of your game!" On the last day of my vacation, in a café in Sienna reading the International Herald Tribune, I was able to appreciate his advice. Back in the States, the technology sector was crumbling. The Dow had dropped 115 points. Visioneer had fallen to nine.<p>
On July 8, now home, I slipped into the office early. The day before, I had signed up for Schwab's Internet trading service, and in addition to cheaper trading commissions, I had visions of lightning-fast trades made from my own desk. Zorro of the Internet, thousand-dollar bills on the end of my foil. But, as it turned out, either my computer or the office's server couldn't handle the memory requirements. Nor could I use Schwab's slick e.Schwab service, because I had a Macintosh and not an IBM compatible. Alas, I would have to trade the old-fashioned way, over the phone, while looking at my screen. I clicked off the Internet, discouraged. What a piece of luck. That day, Visioneer sank from $9 to $7.50, a 21 percent drop -- and, let it not be forgotten, a heart-stopping 46 percent drop from the highest price I'd sold at back in May.<p>
The next day, July 9, I logged on to see if there was any particular explanation for Visioneer's drop, perhaps in a news story or a chat room. I found none. But, intriguingly, a Visioneer press release had been carried on the PR Newswire that morning: Visioneer, it said, had just received three patents "covering technical innovation in paper management device design." Maybe this was corporate hype to counteract a sinking stock price. But maybe not! Perhaps the market, which had opened 25 minutes earlier, would bounce upward on bargain hunting. I checked Visioneer's price.<p>
I'd been right and had already missed the move. Visioneer was at $8.50 -- a 13 percent jump. I could have cried. I called Schwab anyway. The clerk gave me a quote of $7.50. "Really?" I asked. This seemed impossible. "Yes," came the answer. Maybe there was some pricing discrepancy, I thought. Better to ffind out later. I took 1,500 shares at $7.50 and waited for the clerk to ffill the order. He did, and then I realized my mistake: The price on my screen was on 20-minute delay. The stock had moved to $8.50 and was falling. Suckers like me were buying it now. Would it go down further?<p>
No -- it stayed at $7.50 awhile, then bounced. Within two hours it was vibrating between $8.50 and $9. I called Schwab. "The last trade was nine," the clerk said. "Put in a sell at nine," I instructed. "The bid is now 8.50," she said. I worried a few seconds. "Take the bid," I responded. <p>
The order went through. A 13 percent jump in two hours. After commission, a proffit of $1,265.65. I was up $12,000 and really didn't know what I was doing.<p>
When my friend, the retired trader, called again to check my progress, he seemed both irritated and amazed at my success, especially in such a wild week. "Let me get this right," he said. "Do you know what Visioneer makes?" <p>
"Scanners."<p>
"Right. What's their main product?"<p>
"Something called PaperPort."<p>
"Where is it sold?"<p>
"I don't know."<p>
"You've never seen it?"<p>
"Right."<p>
"Who is their president?"<p>
"I don't know. Some guy who came from another place."<p>
There was a pause while he calibrated my ignorance. "Who are their major competitors?"<p>
"I forget. I knew, but I forgot."<p>
"What's the next estimate on their earnings?"<p>
"I don't know."<p>
"Amazing," he said. "You're actually trading."<p>
My next attempt came a few days later, and if bad luck was a wall that I was destined to hit, I yearned, strangely enough, for that to happen soon, to bring this terrifying exercise to a humiliating close. What a relief it would be to finally get burned, then swear off this foolishness forever.<p>
Visioneer had moved from $8 to $7, just off its recent 52-week low of $6.75. Stocks had fallen broadly, kicked down by Hewlett-Packard's announcement that its earnings would be disappointing. How bad could it get? I wondered. If Visioneer's price could be imagined as a drunken braggart in a bar, it had been dragged out to the alley, beaten, stabbed, and then shot. It was down 69 percent from its high! And, no great surprise, both trading volume and Internet chatter had slowed to a trickle -- the wounded hiding in silence. I decided to put in a clever little order at $6.75 -- exactly at the all-time low. Maybe I'd snag an early sell, and the stock would vibrate back upward, as it had a tendency to do after a weekly low. I promised myself I'd sell at $7.375, a move of just 62.5 cents but, multiplied by 3,000 shares, a proffit after commissions of about $1,685. With the price so far down, I was forcing greater volume into a narrower bet. Gambling, in other words.<p>
The next day, Tuesday, July 16, lives now in infamy. That was the day know-nothing, jerk-weed speculators like me were said to have finally seen God -- when hundreds of billions of dollars of market capitalization vanished then reappeared. That was the day the Dow jumped up 45 points, then plunged (with the index off 167.19 at the lowest), then rocketed upward 219 points, and finally fell back to close 9.25 up -- on a volume of 695.83 million shares, the most ever. The Nasdaq also broke its volume record, trading 877.33 million that day.<p>
But I knew none of this yet -- only that we seemed to be having an office-wide problem getting on the Internet. Frustrated, I called Schwab to get a price. It was taking longer than usual to be serviced, and a recorded voice asked for my patience. Then I got through. Visioneer was at $7.25, said the clerk. How was the market? I asked. "Well, it was up," he said casually, "and now it's down 50." <p>
I could tell from his voice something was afoot, but I hung up having done nothing. I still had the buy in for 3,000 shares at $6.75. But I couldn't get on-line all morning. I tried 10, 20 times. Then, down the hall, I heard that the market was down 160 points. I felt sick. I didn't want to buy into a dropping market, and I couldn't be calling Schwab every ten minutes -- I had work to do. There was no way to track the price. I called. My buy for 3,000 at $6.75 hadn't gone through. What a relief! I canceled the order. Now I'm cool, I told myself.<p>
Bad move. <p>
The stock dropped to $6.50 then closed back up at $7. I had missed -- perfectly. By the following Friday, the stock was up over $7.50, closing at $7.625. If I had stayed in the game, filling at $6.75 and then, say, selling at $7.50, I'd have been up another $2,060.<p>
With the resolve of the ignorant, I put in an order the next Monday to buy 3,000 shares at seven dollars -- which would represent a drop of 8.2 percent from the Friday close. I figured the market had been so bloody that the stock couldn't drop much further. I was right, unfortunately. The Dow lost another 36 points and the Nasdaq another 16, but Visioneer closed back up at $7.50.<p>
Two days later, July 24, the price had dropped to $6.625. I called to see if my order had gone through. It hadn't -- which puzzled me until I realized that I had set an "all or none" order, which, ironically, had worked in my favor. Now the price was lower. This is luck, I told myself, the cheapest and stupidest luck. Make your last play and get out! I changed the order so that the 3,000 could be broken up into pieces. All 3,000 went through in blocks at $6.625. Visioneer closed at $6.50. It had been down here before. I set the sell at $7.25 and waited.<p>
But not long. On July 26, the sell went through, for a proffit of $1,495. After commissions, I was up $14,159.59, and, for now at least, out of the game. Six plays, all for a proffit. I felt like a man who had escaped from a burning building, scorched but exhilarated. Had I been reckless? Absolutely. But what a roll. Botta-boom, botta-bing.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
