<html>
	<head>
		<title>96/10-Balancing Act</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/whitebarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Balancing Act</b></font><br>
		</center>
				
				
					<font size=4>
						When is a rising market cause for concern? The answer may be in your portfolio's asset mix.<p>
By Susan Lee<p>
There are a couple of bad things about a stock market that keeps going up. The first is that investors begin to confuse the market's stellar performance with their own. Convinced that they possess hot hands, investors become sloppy, overconfident. They start ignoring the advice of schoolmarms like me. To be specific: They disdain the notion that they should keep their eggs in more than one basket.<p>
The second is that even people who believe in spreading risk over several types of markets often end up with radically unbalanced portfolios. As the market shoots up, the percentage of their asset value devoted to stocks rises along with it. So, too, does their exposure to stock-market risk.<p>
True portfolio diversification comes from holding assets in more than one basket, or, to use the current phrase of choice, asset allocation. The thing about this type of diversification, though, is that you have to keep working at it.<p>
This isn't easy. It requires a steely heart, so most people flop: Who doesn't want to cleave to the winners and punish the losers? <p>
Nevertheless, rebalancing your portfolio is what demonstrates that you have the discipline (more schoolmarmishness) to be a world-class investor. This, by the way, is not the same as something called tactical asset allocation, in which investors move money into one asset class or another depending on forecasts of market conditions -- trying, say, to take advantage of the prospect of lower interest rates by beefing up the bond portion of a portfolio. In my opinion, this is just market timing by another name, and it's a loser's game. <p>
The strategy I am talking about starts with the assumption that your investment strategy is tailored to meet your needs. And unless your needs change, your strategy should remain the same. You can't let changing market conditions dictate to you. <p>
The concept of asset allocation, of course, is far from new. The investment pooh-bah of all time, Benjamin Graham, for example, recommended a 50-50 rule for dividing holdings between the stock and bond markets. The theory is that when some markets are falling, other markets will be rising, and thus overall returns won't suffer quite so absolutely. <p>
Serious asset allocators, especially those who manage giant portfolios like pension plans, put money into a wide range of categories, including real estate (like commercial property and undeveloped land), foreign stock and bond markets, derivatives, venture and mezzanine capital, timber, oil and gas, gold, and art and antiques. But this takes huge bucks and huge amounts of time. <p>
Failing that, your approach needs to be driven by your temperament, needs, and situation. Consider:<p>
**How much risk do you want to be exposed to?**<p>
The majority of us are risk averse. We are willing to give up some potential return in order to avoid unpleasant surprises. <p>
Those who are terrifically averse to risk, for example, might concentrate on relatively safe categories and be happy to divide assets more evenly among riskless and risky categories (Benjamin Graham's advice); for them, U.S. Treasury bills or stock-market-index funds are attractive. For those who love risk, on the other hand, small-cap stocks and options, as well as distressed and long-term medium-grade bonds, make sense.	<p>
**How close do you want to be to your cash?**<p>
Some people have an urgent need for cash flow or like to be one fast step away from converting assets into cash. They should concentrate allocations in more-liquid categories like money-market funds and blue-chip stocks. Others, however, can afford to lock investment money away for a while; they can spread their allocations over a wider range, like real estate or arts and antiques. <p>
**How long is your time horizon?** <p>
Investors who are 30 to 40 years away from retirement can afford to be more aggressive about chasing returns, because they have more time to ride out depressed markets and make up for individual bombs. <p>
For those with long horizons, growth stocks and zero-coupon bonds might be desirable -- although the longer the time horizon, the more alert investors have to be to the danger that inflation will erode the value of their cash and debt holdings. Those with more immediate goals, however, have a much shorter time line and should stick with a smaller number of more-liquid categories. <p>
**How phobic are you about taxes?** <p>
Pretty much no one is fond of paying taxes, but for investors in high marginal brackets, avoidance is crucial. <p>
Tax avoiders ought to focus on a few tax-favored categories, while investors who are more neutral can broaden their reach. Committed tax averters, for instance, might cleave to triple-exempt muni bonds or index funds and shun the practice of short-selling stocks and buying stock mutual funds that have high turnover rates.<p>
Obviously, some of these considerations are overlapping and harmonious, and others can contradict one another and drive you to utter distraction. (You are a young pup, but you detest risk; you adore risk but need liquidity; and so on and so forth.)<p>
I can't tell you -- in the space of a magazine column anyway -- the best way to customize your portfolio. One thing I can tell you, however, is that the decisions you make in this regard will have a greater impact on the performance of your portfolio -- long term -- than anything you do in the way of individual stock selection or market timing. <p>
A 1987 study of big pension plans by Roger Ibbotson and Gary Brinson showed that decisions on asset classes accounted for 93.6 percent of the difference in total returns -- far more than the manager's choice of securities or market-timing maneuvers. Other studies have since confirmed that asset allocation is the single most important determinant of performance. <p>
After you have sweated over your allocation and, presumably, got it just right, then what? <p>
Well, first of all, you can relax -- knowing that the schoolmarms will be pleased. You are following the wisest course. You can't control what the markets will do, but you have done the most sensible thing.<p>
You can sleep at night and ignore what's happening day to day. In fact, you can sleep for a year. But then you need to wake up and look at your portfolio afresh.<p>
Presumably your needs haven't changed -- but your asset allocation most certainly will have. It's time to rebalance your portfolio.<p>
You may find, for instance, that a gangbusters stock market and a low-down bond market have thrown your division out of whack; in other words, your 55 percent stock position may now represent 70 percent of the total value of your portfolio, while your bond position has dwindled to only 20 percent. <p>
Should you sell off some stocks and buy some bonds in order to rebalance your portfolio? Your evil twin -- the greedy one -- will say no. But the answer is yes. <p>
Note: The only time you should consider varying your allocation is when you experience a change in personal circumstance -- for instance, you win at Lotto and are feeling lots more frisky and risky. <p>
There are, by the way, mutual funds that will allocate assets for you by varying the distribution of stocks, cash, and bonds within a single vehicle. Some of these are true strategic funds in the sense that the allocations rarely vary significantly, while others are just market timers in disguise, sending great chunks of their portfolios into one or another hot market. <p>
Ignore both types. You don't really need the former, and the latter will doubtless get you into hot water rather than hot returns. 
Smart asset allocation is not all that difficult. The true difficulty is hewing to it. (Okay, school's out.)<p>
Contributing editor Susan Lee writes “Mind Your Own Business” monthly. She is an economist and the author of Hands Off: Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health, just published by Simon & Schuster. E-mail her at sclee12@aol.com.<p>

					</font>
