	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Captains of Industry</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Captains of Industry</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Yacht-management services help keep skippers afloat<p>
By James Gorant<p>
Once a month, Kurt Campbell packs up his flip-flops, flees Columbus, Ohio, where he runs a small hedge fund, and heads for Key West, Florida. There he heads out on a boat for five days and does nothing but fish and soak up the sun. Since charters cost up to $600 a day, such monthly outings could cause financial strain, but not for Campbell -- he owns the boat.<p>
Actually, Campbell owns two boats, which he has set up as a business so that he can charter them out when he's not using them. With Key West's year-round tourist traffic, some boats see action 52 weeks a year and not only pay for themselves but even turn a profit. "I'm always looking for a business opportunity," Campbell says, "and this looked like a good way to make some money and have fun."<p>
In almost all cases, success depends on treating a boat as a business, not a toy. "A lot of it is accounting and management," says Campbell. "I set all the budgets, take care of the insurance and proper licenses, and make sure to account for maintenance and improvements. A lot of these small owner-operators just don't do that."<p>
For those without Campbell's business savvy, help is available in the form of charter brokerage and management companies. These outfits generally offer three levels of service. The most limited, called clearinghouse, places your vessel in a series of listings available to yacht brokers internationally. Charter marketing includes all the clearinghouse functions plus the presentation and booking of the yacht. With yacht management, the most complete service, the company takes care of everything from business plans and budgets to distributing payroll and buying fuel.<p>
"Building any business takes a long time, and building a yacht business is pretty hard," says Nigel Henderson, president of Newport Yacht Services in Newport, Rhode Island. "But there's a lot of things I can do in a consulting format that can shorten the learning curve."<p>
Henderson estimates that a 65-footer costs $350,000 to $850,000 to buy and $180,000 a year to operate. Against that, the yacht earns about $5,000 a week and, in the relatively cool climes of Newport, will likely be booked up to 20 weeks a year. "If you're talking about bottom black-line profit, I don't think I've ever made it," Henderson says. "If you're talking about satisfaction that an owner has reached a point where he wants to use his boat and offset his costs, we've reached that point many times."<p>
It's the smaller, self-managed sector that fares best in the chartering world. Campbell bought his first yacht, the 43-foot Lethal Weapon, three years ago for $135,000, with 20 percent down and the rest financed over five years at 9.5 percent. He estimates his yearly expenses -- things such as equipment, docking fees, and insurance that includes a million-dollar liability policy -- at $60,000. At $600 a day, the boat needs to book 18 to 20 days a month to break even. So far he has surpassed that number enough to see a 20 to 25 percent annual return on his investment.<p>
As a fund manager, Campbell knows that's on par with some of the hottest mutual funds around. And when was the last time you escaped from an Ohio winter to sip piña coladas and chase sailfish on your mutual fund? <p>
Full-service yacht-chartering firms: 
Bob Saxon Associates, Fort Lauderdale, FL (954-760-5801)
Interpac Yachts, San Diego, CA (619-222-0327)
Newport Yacht Services, Newport, RI (800-234-7720)
Sacks Yacht Charters, Fort Lauderdale, FL (954-764-7742)
Yachting Partners International, Brighton, England (800-626-0019).

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
