<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Letters</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Letters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Down on downsizing<p>Peter Lynch and John Rothchild make a strong case for corporate layoffs and downsizing ("In Defense of the Invisible Hand," June). They even admit the pain and fear, at least in theory. But I think they miss the point of much of the criticism. Al Dunlap was CEO of Scott Paper for 20 months, during which time he fired 11,200
employees, arranged for the company to be taken over by Kimberly-Clark, and in the process made a personal gain of $100 million. A photograph in the Mobile (Alabama) Press Register showed 19 workers in the Mobile plant -- all fired by Dunlap__who had an average of 23 years each with the company and whose combined annual salaries equaled just five days' compensation for Dunlap. And he is proud of what he's done at this company! If the financial bottom line is the only responsibility of boards of directors and managers of corporations in our capitalist system, with no regard for the welfare of the workers, then the system is doomed to destruction.
George M. Murray
Fairhope, Alabama<p>"In Defense of the Invisible Hand" is described on your cover as the upside of downsizing, but its supporting evidence leads to the opposite conclusion. The table on page 90 purports to show that 25 large companies have demonstrated the link between leanness and the ability to compete by shedding 363,000 jobs since 1985.This, however, is a net figure made up of 589,000 jobs eliminated by 11 companies and 226,000 jobs created at the other 14 companies. If we compare the performance of the downsizers with the performance of the upsizers, the upsizers did better in the decade ended April 1996. If we look at the decade ended 1985, the recent upsizers also outperformed the downsizers. This suggests that the critical influence is less the invisible hand of market forces than the visible hand of corporate management and planning.
Raymond Frost
Coral Gables, Florida<p>
Flat Fixation<p>Hats off to Elizabeth Macdonald for her insightful and straightforward article on the flat tax ("Let's Fix the Flat Tax," June). Granted, there are some problems with a flat tax, but the intelligent handling of those problems would certainly give us a tax system far superior to the jungle we have now. Until then, perhaps we should change the name of the House Ways and Means Committee to the House Give and Take Committee. 
G. P. Karle Jr.
Miami, Florida<p>"Let's Fix the Flat Tax" manages to advance the debate not at all. For instance, that enormous 1.7 billion hours we spend doing taxes each year: Doesn't Macdonald have a clue as to the size of the economy? Think of how much more productive I'd feel if I could spend my share, about two minutes a day, finishing that cure for cancer I've been meaning to get to! Then there's the matter of asking Jack Kemp for his definition of a "fair" tax. Jack Kemp is a politician (whom I respect), not an ethicist. Perhaps next we should ask Fidel Castro for the definition of a fair return on equity. Let's cut to the ethical principle on this one: The last dollar of a family that earns__and spends__$1 million a year pays for niceties like a trip around the world, not necessities. The last dollar of $100,000 a year pays for important, but not vital, expenses like college tuition or car payments. And the last dollar (and every dollar) of $10,000 a year pays for vital expenses, like food. Fair tax rates reflect this. 
Joel Macauslan
Nashua, New Hampshire<p>
Too Speculative<p>Ted C. Fishman writes in "Speculating 101" ("Review," June), "Selling call options against stock, for example, is portrayed as a low-risk hedging strategy, when in fact it's the practical equivalent of selling puts outright__the riskiest strategy of all." I must be nuts. A put is a mirror image of a call. How can selling calls be the same as selling puts?
Donald P. Cohen
Boynton Beach, Florida<p>Ted C. Fishman replies: a number of readers have raised this question. Strange as it may sound, my statement is a well-established truth, although it usually takes even professional options traders several months to see the relationship between puts and calls. Indeed, this arbitrage relationship is the cornerstone of professional option trading. Retail customers love the covered-call strategy, and professionals routinely accommodate them by buying calls at (relatively) inflated prices, then hedging their risk by buying puts and selling stock. For those interested in how combinations of stocks and options align into equivalent positions, I recommend the book Options as a Strategic Investment, by Lawrence G. McMillan, published by Prentice Hall. <p>
Follow-up<p>Darrell Zimmerman, the former bond-futures trader whose misadventures were detailed in the December/January 1994 issue, has lost his legal battle to remain in Canada, where he fled after a grand jury indicted him for masterminding a 1992 scheme to create a downturn in Treasury-bond prices that ended up costing his clearing firm more than $7 million. According to the Chicago Sun-Times, Zimmerman has reached a nonbinding plea agreement with the U.S. Attorney's Office that would cap his potential eight-year sentence at four years if he surrenders quickly and pleads guilty to all six counts of wire fraud that he faces. Zimmerman's trading partner, Anthony Catalfo, was convicted of all six counts against him and received a 42-month sentence in June 1994.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
