<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-The Web's New Wave</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-The Web's New Wave</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
It's about time: Finally, investors have a good reason for signing on to the Internet<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Until recently it has been no contest. An investor armed with two old-fashioned print guides -- The Value Line Investment Survey for stocks and Morningstar Mutual Funds -- had far better information at his fingertips than anything one could find on the Internet. The Internet's World Wide Web was often hard to navigate and painfully slow. But that wasn't the worst of it. Once an investor found a page and waited for it to download, the information was dated, shallow, or a disguised ad -- sometimes all three.<p>But recently, several new Web pages have closed the gap. Now investors are rewarded with current quotes, breaking news, and alerts of changes in earnings estimates for stocks in their personal portfolios -- all for at most $20 a month. It's too soon to cancel subscriptions to paper guides, but an investor who uses the Internet will have a significant edge over one armed only with paper.<p>Quote.com (www.quote.com) is a good example of the Web's new prowess. For $9.95 a month, the cost of a basic subscription, an investor can set up two portfolios, each tracking up to 100 securities. While portfolio trackers abound on the Net, this one packs more punch. At the end of each day, Quote.com delivers a portfolio updated with prices and volume to an 
investor's E-mail address. (Updates are available during the day, too.) Users can customize the format to show a table listing such fundamentals as trailing earnings per share, price-to-earnings ratio, and the 52-week price range.<p>Quote.com also links news from Reuters, MarketScope, BusinessWire, PR Newswire, S&P News, and Newsbytes to the portfolio. Investors who don't subscribe to these services get headlines on each portfolio stock and the overall market with each end-of-day update. (Full stories can be ordered  la carte for a dollar.) Signing up for a news service (an extra $9.95 a month for Reuters, for example) puts breaking news in investors' E-mail. An advanced subscription ($19.95 monthly) adds news on insider trading in portfolio stocks from Vickers Insider Trade Reports and on earnings estimates from Zacks Investment Research.<p>Investors who want to follow revisions in earnings estimates more closely can go straight to Zacks Analyst Watch on the Internet (www.zacks.com; $150 a year or $29 a month). Like Quote.com, Analyst Watch works from an investor's portfolio. The user enters a list of stocks he wants to follow, and Analyst Watch delivers an end-of-day report on each security by E-mail. It offers more than the price and volume data of Quote.com. Analyst Watch lists the Zacks rank for each portfolio stock as well as individual revisions in earnings estimates made in the past week, changes in brokerage recommendations, earnings surprises, and dates of upcoming earnings reports.<p>Analyst Watch combines this data into a report on each company, which graphs all analyst recommendations, lists recent earnings and current earnings estimates (mean, high, and low), details the company's history of earnings surprises, and compares its forecasted and actual earnings to those of its industry as well as to the total earnings of the S&P 500 Stock Index. Finally, investors can screen Zacks's database on 81 items, such as recent price changes and rankings. Sadly, it's hard to combine such criteria into more complex screens.<p>Both Quote.com and Analyst Watch are light on fundamental data -- but either MarketEdge from Thomson Financial Services (www.marketedge. com) or Market Guide (marketguide. com) will take up the slack.<p>For $7.95 a month, MarketEdge offers unlimited quotes on stocks and mutual funds with 15-minute delays, 25 company reports, 25 mutual-fund reports, 50 historic-price charts, 5 detailed industry reports, company and mutual-fund screening, real-time market-news updates, stock and fund alerts, and fund reviews. In July, MarketEdge introduced MarketEdge Tracker, which tracks portfolio value and provides high and low prices, volumes, and earnings announcements and forecasts. <p>The company report alone is worth the price of admission. In three pages, it sums up a firm's most recent full-year and quarterly income statements and balance sheets, lists performance ratios such as return on sales and three-year earnings-per-share growth, and recaps the earnings estimates and insider-trading data from Vickers and Zacks, albeit in less detail than Analyst Watch.<p>Market Guide isn't as far along in developing its Web page or lowering prices to match its rivals. Most of its information is priced  la carte and isn't cheap. But Market Guide lets investors choose how much to buy. A snapshot report is free. A more detailed company profile, adding quarterly and annual income as well as balance-sheet and cash-flow data, costs $2.50 (for $9.95 a month you get unlimited reports). The most detailed profile, the only one on-line that shows data exactly as reported by the company, costs five dollars. (StockQuest, which will screen 8,200 stocks on over 70 variables, is due soon.)<p>Buy-just-what-you-want pricing is carried to its logical conclusion by INVESTools (www.investools.com). It provides impressive features -- such as mutual-fund reports from Morningstar and evaluations of newsletters by Mark Hulbert, editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest -- but the most interesting and, indeed, revolutionary feature is a search engine that lets investors type in a ticker or stock name and generate a list of research reports, newsletter articles, educational materials, and news stories. A simple click delivers it to the investor.<p>For example, a search on ERTS, the symbol for software maker <a name="NASD:ERTS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14059"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Electronic Arts</b></a>, yields reports from Morningstar and Zacks and six stories from Reuters in headline form. For 25 cents, an investor can download a Reuters story about Cowen & Co.'s revision of its earnings estimate for Electronic Arts. INVESTools' library of 21 newsletters works the same way: If a search turns up an article on a stock of interest, investors can buy just that piece.  INVESTools gives a five-dollar credit to those who sign on, so investors can try it out for free. Items are clearly priced, and confirmation is requested, so an accidental purchase is unlikely.<p>INVESTools is a new model for delivering information, one made possible by the Net's structure. Buy just what you need when you want it -- for a reasonable price. And those prices are falling. Intuit, the software company behind Quicken, launched Quicken Financial Network in June. QFN (www.qfn.com) isn't very useful yet, but it does offer a glimpse of the future. QFN lets investors set up and track portfolios and download quotes for free -- advertisers and financial-services providers pay the freight. Such price competition should spur information providers to lower prices and add services, augmenting the armory of information-hungry investors.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Technology Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

