<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Looking for Lasting Profits in IPOs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Looking for Lasting Profits in IPOs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Warburg Pincus has a strategy that should work even if the IPO bubble pops<p>By Tom Saler<p>Wonder why funds such as <a name="FUND:DGVAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DGVAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dreyfus Aggressive Growth</b></a>, up 68 percent for the first five months of 1996, <a name="FUND:VWEGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWEGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Van Wagoner Emerging Growth</b></a>, up 57 percent, and Oberweis Micro-Cap, up 49 percent, have soared so far above the overall market, which gained just 9 percent? Give the credit to IPO fever. In those first five months, the average initial public offering gained 20.9 percent on its first trading day. Six IPOs actually doubled in price. Many new small-cap funds have loaded up on IPOs to supercharge their returns.<p>Over the long term, most funds that bet their portfolios on IPOs fall as fast as they climb. History shows that the new-issues market can go from red-hot to stone-cold almost overnight. In fact, a cool breeze blew through the market in June. The average first-day gain on an IPO dropped from 25 percent in April and May to 12.4 percent in June -- just slightly above the historical average of 10.4 percent since 1980. Newly public stocks tumbled -- <a name="NASD:LCOS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=48044"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lycos</b></a> and <a name="NASD:XCIT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47307"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Excite</b></a>, for example, fell 28 percent and 48 percent, respectively. It's no wonder that redemptions from emerging-growth funds totaled $113 million in the week ended June 19, according to AMG Data Services -- the first outflows since last October.<p>But are all the new funds specializing in the risky but potentially rewarding stocks of extremely young growth companies destined to disappoint investors over the long term? One, <a name="FUND:CUEGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CUEGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus Post-Venture Capital</b></a>, could be different. The track record of its parent firm, the experience of its managers, and a unique vantage point for finding the best new companies could give the fund a long-term advantage.<p>Warburg Pincus Post-Venture Capital's short-term returns make it clear this isn't a fund for the faint of heart. Started last September 29, it rode the IPO bubble to a 79 percent return in its first eight months, beating the average aggressive-growth fund by a staggering 59 percentage points. However, the fund didn't escape the June correction -- it was down 6.3 percent for the month.<p>But the reason to consider the Post-Venture Capital Fund doesn't lie in the short-term numbers; it's in the long-term record of the fund's managers and its parent company. Co-manager Elizabeth Dater, 51, came to Warburg Pincus as an institutional portfolio manager in 1978 after a stint as vice president of research at Fiduciary Trust. She is now one of five senior managing directors at New York based Warburg Pincus. Using her expertise in researching small growth firms for institutional clients, she began the company's first equity mutual fund, the $1.3 billion <a name="FUND:WPVCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WPVCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus Emerging Growth</b></a>, 
in 1988. That fund has earned an average annual return of 18.57 percent from its inception through June 30, 1996, versus 14.84 percent for the Russell 2000 small-cap index.<p>Co-manager Stephen J. Lurito, 33, joined Dater on the emerging growth fund in 1988 as a research analyst, after two years at money-management firm Sanford C. Bernstein & Co. He now co-manages that fund as well as Post-Venture Capital. "She's like the CEO, and I'm like the chief operating officer," says Lurito. While Dater sets the market and business strategies of the fund, Lurito focuses on the day-to-day research activities of the fund's three other analysts.<p>Since 1989, the team has worn another hat as well -- one of a fashion well suited to its new venture. Although Warburg Pincus is a relative latecomer to the mutual-fund business, the company has a solid reputation as an institutional money manager dating back to the early 1970s. Its venture-capital arm, Warburg Pincus Ventures, has been financing start-ups since 1971. For sister company Warburg Pincus Counsellors, Dater and Lurito, since 1989, have been advising pension funds, endowments, and high-net-worth individuals about what to do with shares in young companies received as a result of venture-capital investments. In the process of managing $1 billion in distributions from 400 venture-capital pools, the team has examined thousands of post-venture companies. "As a result of the research that we did on behalf of clients, we've developed an inventory of what we believe will be the great growth companies of the future," says Dater. (The fund can't buy stock in companies in which Warburg Pincus Ventures has an interest.) "Over the long run, we expect that venture-backed companies would have better-than-average returns than non-venture-backed companies."<p>A comment like that is what any skeptical investor would expect from the manager of this fund, but history seems to support Dater's conclusion. Companies backed by venture capital do perform better after going public than their non-venture-backed cousins. According to Securities Data Corp., a financial-information company, venture-backed IPOs issued from the start of January 1986 through the end of June 1996 returned an average of 126 percent, compared with just 39.2 percent for non-venture-backed IPOs. And venture-backed IPOs beat other new issues by 29.9 percent to 10.4 percent in the year subsequent to going public. <p>What gives venture-backed companies the advantage? First, venture capitalists buy equity in the start-ups they fund, resulting in less debt on corporate balance sheets. Second, in general, venture capitalists don't cut corners on funding critical research and development. Third, "when venture capitalists decide to commit capital, they will also typically act in an advisory capacity," says Dater.<p>Finally, the nature of the venture-capital industry acts as a form of quality control. With thousands of start-ups vying for limited funds -- in a typical year, the typical venture-capital partnership invests only $2 billion to $4 billion in all their deals -- companies that ultimately receive backing have already survived an arduous screening process.<p>And venture capitalists aren't short-term investors -- they usually stick around even after the company goes public. Securities and Exchange Commission rules prevent venture capitalists from selling shares in their companies to the public for two years after they invest, and agreements with underwriters keep them from selling for four to six months after the IPO. One important result: Venture capitalists often insist their companies follow conservative accounting practices. "Long before thinking about going public, venture-backed companies are already doing financial accounting and strategic business planning as if they were public," says Robin Bellas, a general partner in Morgenthaler Ventures. "We do that so we can measure the progress they're making against the strategic plan."<p>Dater and Lurito admit they aren't always long-term players in their own fund. Part of Post-Venture Capital's stellar performance ("probably a couple of percentage points," says Lurito) is from flipping hot IPOs. Flipping -- or buying stocks at the IPO price and selling them a day or two later -- can add to short-term returns. But it's not what Dater and Lurito are after. "We have flipped to a degree if we can't get a significant position in a company," says Lurito, "but by and large, we are looking to hold."<p>To pick stocks for their portfolio, Dater and Lurito combine venture-capital experience with solid growth discipline. To make it past the first cut, a company must show backing not just from any venture-capital firm but from the "ablest VCs" -- those that have the best track records of building successful companies. Then the team looks for earnings growth of at least 25 percent -- they sell at the first signs of slowing growth. The two managers expect to hold the average company for about a year. But since there's no market-cap restriction on stocks in the fund, Dater and Lurito can hold them as long as the story doesn't change.<p>To figure out if a stock is reasonably priced, they estimate a company's earnings growth rate over the next three years. Take the stock of McAfee Associates, a maker of software to detect viruses and manage personal-computer networks. "We've estimated growth rates for networks and PCs around the world and looked at how penetrated that market is," says Lurito. "We think the earnings growth rate at McAfee is 35 percent a year for the next three years. The company is only trading at 27 times our future earnings estimate. So for us, that's an attractive proposition." <p>As June demonstrated, a market downturn would hurt the high-flying fund. But Dater and Lurito believe that, over time, owning companies that grow faster than the economy will reward investors. Those with a long-term horizon can even turn the highly volatile market to their advantage: Warburg Pincus Post-Venture Capital is just about perfect for dollar-cost averaging.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
