	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Passion Play-Transaction Costs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Passion Play-Transaction Costs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Susan Lee<p>At auction houses, both buyers and sellers participate in transaction costs. A buyer at Christie's pays a "premium" of 15 percent of a final price up to $50,000 and 10 percent on any amount over $50,000. Sellers pay a "commission" based on a sliding scale: 20 percent of a final price of less than $2,000, 15 percent of a final price between $2,000 and $7,499, 10 percent of a final price between $7,500 and $99,999, and so on, until the commission falls to 2 percent of a final price of $5 million and above. Sellers also pay percentage points for insurance, administrative fees, and miscellaneous charges for framing, restoration, and whatnot, as well as a flat fee for catalogs. It all adds up.<p>Dealer markups are an inky area -- for both seller and buyer. For instance, dealers who represent works for which there might be only a few dozen possible buyers know those buyers will bargain and must set prices without an auction record. Before they settle on a price, dealers ask themselves a bunch of questions, like whether they need the money to buy something else or whether they paid too much and should be willing to accept less. <p>New York City dealer James Goodman runs through a little monologue in his mind that goes like this: "What! Is he kidding? I am not going to sell it to him. How much of a profit is there in it? Does this mean he's going to write out a check right now? Can I replace it? Do I want to make a sale? How has my business been this week?" <p>Dealer Max Davidson says that in a typical show he will sell half the works at list and the other half at a 10 percent discount. <p>Overall, some say dealer markups average 10 to 15 percent; others say 20 to 50 percent, although markups as high as 300 percent are not unheard of. Generally, the more "difficult" the artist (young, untested) or the cheaper the work (less-than-sensational prints), the higher the markup. When collector Dave Williams decided to focus on African-American printmakers of the 1930s and 1940s, he told dealers he would buy anything they could come up with. Was he afraid of getting gouged? "No, I was confident that they would treat my wife and me fairly, and they did," he says. "We bought nearly all of what they brought to us."<p>Most collectors agree that sometimes it's cheaper to buy from a dealer, but no one says it's cheaper to buy at auction. Also, dealers provide services not available from auction houses, such as pre-selection based on the dealer's expertise and allowing potential buyers to take something home and live with it before deciding to buy. (Dealers also offer discretion. Some people prefer to buy or sell without the world knowing about it -- or, sometimes, without alerting the IRS if, say, their dealer sells in London and deposits the proceeds in a Swiss bank.)<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
