<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Passion PLay-Buy Well and Hold</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Passion PLay-Buy Well and Hold</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Susan Lee<p>Okay. So you know that you should buy something only if you absolutely love it. But what happens if passion fades? There are straightforward disciplines that buyers can follow if they also want to be successful investors.<p>
Feel comfortable with the word "quality"<p>"Quality" is a favorite adjective in the art world. Essentially, something is considered to have quality if it has (or has the potential to have) enduring aesthetic value. Quality is something that most experts recognize and agree on but that eludes most novices, who often cleave to works that are immediately enjoyable yet won't hold their appeal. <p>To recognize quality, you must educate yourself -- tiresome as it might be -- by reading about art, looking at art, and listening to experts talk about art. <p>
Beware of fads<p>This is a bit more than a restatement of the above. Fads are endemic to the art world, where hype is part of the business. Since people want to be seen buying the right thing, it's easy to get caught up. <p>
Buy quality<p>Once you're comfy with the notion of quality, this is simple. As dealer Max Davidson says, "You make your money when you buy. It's a truism of retailing that goods bought right are goods half-sold." <p>
Buy for the long term<p>Which means nothing shorter than ten years. Rachel Adler of Rachel Adler Gallery in New York City says, "Each transaction involves profit for the seller, so it takes a while for prices to rise above that profit." Patience is especially needed if you buy something that has made the rounds at auction: It will be considered stale, and you may have to wait ten years before the art world considers it fresh and enticing again. Of course, for true collectors, long term means forever (or until their heirs sell).<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
