<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Passion Play-Getting Started</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Passion Play-Getting Started</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Deborah Jermanok<p>Before investing in the art market, "educate your eye, educate your brain, go to the best galleries and museums," says Peter Falk, publisher of Sound View Press. Then "arm yourself with two kinds of information -- market information, like a good annual art price index, and biographical information." <p>Each book, on-line service, and CD-ROM has its own strengths. Here are some guides to consider.<p>BOOKS
Art Price Index International (published by Sound View Press in Madison, Connecticut) has more than 200,000 entries of paintings, watercolors, drawings, prints, sculptures, posters, photographs, animation works, and installations. The annual, two-volume set sells for $195. Call 800-ART-4API. <p>Details provided by art price indexes vary from publisher to publisher. An Art Price Index International entry for a Georgia O'Keeffe painting is as follows: "O'Keeffe, Georgia [American, 1887
1986] + $321500 204796 White hill and black [406 x 508 mm - 16 x 20 in] s, i, oil on canvas, 1928. Sotheby's NY, 25 May 95, #117    P (DM461353)."<p>To translate: The artist, Georgia O'Keeffe, was an American who lived from 1887 to 1986. The plus sign indicates that the sale price in dollars ($321,500) and in pounds (204,796) includes the auction house's premium. The painting is titled White Hill and Black; its dimensions are listed in millimeters (406 by 508) and inches (16 by 20). The "s" indicates the work is signed and the "i" that it is inscribed; the medium is oil on canvas, and the work was executed in 1928. Sotheby's auctioned the painting on May 25, 1995, in lot 117. The square means the work was illustrated in the auction catalog, and the "P," for provenance, means the previous owner is documented. The price is also listed in deutsche marks (DM 461,353). <p>
Mayer International Auction Records ($190), published in Switzerland, is one of the oldest guides. It has about 120,000 entries for paintings, watercolors, sculptures, drawings, and prints (914-297-1312). <p>
Art Sales Index, published in England by Duncan Hislop, is in its 27th edition. The two-volume set ($185) lists 108,000 works and includes paintings, sculptures, photographs, watercolors, drawings, and prints (011-44-1932-856426).<p>
ADEC, published in France, covers paintings, watercolors, sculptures, prints, photographs, and drawings. Price: $170 plus shipping (800-527-3501). <p>
Leonard's Annual Price Index of Art Auctions ($219) includes prices for paintings, drawings, and sculptures but cites auctions in North America only (617-964-2876).<p>
Gordon's Print Price Annual focuses on prints and contains over 37,000 entries. It sells for $225 (941-434-6842).<p><p>ON-LINE SERVICES 
Artnet, the only on-line service that provides images, claims to have the largest electronic archive of art-auction records in the world. To access, you need a PC, a modem, and ArtNet software; the rate is $1.25 per minute in North America (800-4-ARTNET). <p>
ArtQuest was launched in 1983 by Hislop's Art Sales Index. ArtQuest provides auction-price data for fine arts at a cost of $250 a year and $1.20 per minute (011-44-1932-856426).<p>
Thesaurus, based in London, has data on over 600 auction houses and historical pricing going back to 1820. It is the only on-line service that includes decorative arts. For a cost of $150 to $500, Thesaurus also provides pre-sale notification. On-line price information costs about $12 an hour (800-491-FIND).<p><p>CD-ROMs
ArtFact is an auction-price database (made up of ten CD-ROMs) for fine and decorative arts and is the only CD-ROM that provides images. The ten CD-ROMs cost $1,995 for the first year and $1,550 every year to update (800-ARTFACT).<p>
Art Sales Index's disc lists sales from 1990 to 1995 for 528 auction houses in 32 countries. It costs $595 and is distributed by ArtFact (800-ARTFACT).<p>
ADEC provides a CD-ROM that documents the sales of 750 auction houses, including paintings, sculptures, prints, drawings, and photographs. The cost is $495 for the first year and $295 for yearly updates (800-ARTFACT).<p>
Mayer International Auction Records CD-ROM has over 600,000 sales records of paintings, prints, drawings, gouaches, pastels, watercolors, and sculptures ($199 plus shipping; 888-MAYERCD).<p>
Leonard's Combined Price Index of Art Auctions CD-ROM database goes back 15 years and lists prices for paintings, drawings, sculptures, prints, posters, and photographs ($995; 617-964-2876).<p>
Gordon's Print Price Annual CD-ROM has information on more than 385,000 print sales and also includes a database of print dealers as well as a bibliography of publications about prints. The base subscription is $595; annual updates cost $295 (941-434-6842).<p>
Now what? Gayle Skluzacek, an appraiser and the president of Abigail Hartmann Associates, suggests using a combination of price indexes and CD-ROMs; most good art-reference libraries carry both. For general introductory books on art, consider H. W. Janson's History of Art, Robert Atkins's Art Speak and Art Spoke, which are guides to the buzzwords and players of the 19th and 20th centuries, and Susan Theran's Fine Art Identification and Price Guide. Also consider taking a basic art-history or art-appreciation course.<p>One last piece of advice, this one from Stephen Abt of ArtFact: "Buying art information is exactly like buying art itself. Buy the highest quality you can find in your budget, and your purchase will eventually justify itself."  -- Deborah Jermanok<p>
Okay. So you know that you should buy something only if you absolutely love it. But what happens if passion fades? There are straightforward disciplines that buyers can follow if they also want to be successful investors.<p>Feel comfortable with the word 
"quality"
"Quality" is a favorite adjective in the art world. Essentially, something is considered to have quality if it has (or has the potential to have) enduring aesthetic value. Quality is something that most experts recognize and agree on but that eludes most novices, who often cleave to works that are immediately enjoyable yet won't hold their appeal. 
To recognize quality, you must educate yourself -- tiresome as it might be -- by reading about art, looking at art, and listening to experts talk about art. 
Beware of fads
This is a bit more than a restatement of the above. Fads are endemic to the art world, where hype is part of the business. Since people want to be seen buying the right thing, it's easy to get caught up. <p>Buy quality
Once you're comfy with the notion of quality, this is simple. As dealer Max Davidson says, "You make your money when you buy. It's a truism of retailing that goods bought right are goods half-sold." <p>Buy for the long term
Which means nothing shorter than ten years. Rachel Adler of Rachel Adler Gallery in New York City says, "Each transaction involves profit for the seller, so it takes a while for prices to rise above that profit." Patience is especially needed if you buy something that has made the rounds at auction: It will be considered stale, and you may have to wait ten years before the art world considers it fresh and enticing again. Of course, for true collectors, long term means forever (or until their heirs sell).  -- S.L.<p>
At auction houses, both buyers and sellers participate in transaction costs. A buyer at Christie's pays a "premium" of 15 percent of a final price up to $50,000 and 10 percent on any amount over $50,000. Sellers pay a "commission" based on a sliding scale: 20 percent of a final price of less than $2,000, 15 percent of a final price between $2,000 and $7,499, 10 percent of a final price between $7,500 and $99,999, and so on, until the commission falls to 2 percent of a final price of $5 million and above. Sellers also pay percentage points for insurance, administrative fees, and miscellaneous charges for framing, restoration, and whatnot, as well as a flat fee for catalogs. It all adds up.
Dealer markups are an inky area -- for both seller and buyer. For instance, dealers who represent works for which there might be only a few dozen possible buyers know those buyers will bargain and must set prices without an auction record. Before they settle on a price, dealers ask themselves a bunch of questions, like whether they need the money to buy something else or whether they paid too much and should be willing to accept less. 
New York City dealer James Goodman runs through a little monologue in his mind that goes like this: "What! Is he kidding? I am not going to sell it to him. How much of 
a profit is there in it? Does this mean he's going to write out a check right now? Can I 
replace it? Do I want to make a sale? How has my business been this week?" 
Dealer Max Davidson says that in a typical show he will sell half the works at list and the other half at a 10 percent discount. 
Overall, some say dealer markups average 10 to 15 percent; others say 20 to 50 percent, although markups as high as 300 percent are not unheard of. Generally, the more "difficult" the artist (young, untested) or the cheaper the work (less-than-sensational prints), the higher the markup. When collector Dave Williams decided to focus on African-American printmakers of the 1930s and 1940s, he told dealers he would buy anything they could come up with. Was he afraid of getting gouged? "No, I was confident that they would treat my wife and me fairly, and they did," he says. "We bought nearly all of what they brought to us."
Most collectors agree that sometimes it's cheaper to buy from a dealer, but no one says it's cheaper to buy at auction. Also, dealers provide services not available from auction houses, such as pre-selection based on the dealer's expertise and allowing potential buyers to take something home and live with it before deciding to buy. (Dealers also offer discretion. Some people prefer to buy or sell without the world knowing about it -- or, sometimes, without alerting the IRS if, say, their dealer sells in London and deposits the proceeds in a Swiss bank.)  -- S.L.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

