<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Passion Play</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Passion Play</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
One difference between buying art and buying stock: Love. Others: Liquidity, volatility, risk, rates of return. An economist looks at art as a market.<p>By Susan Lee<p>Bump. Flutter. Liftoff. <p>These three words tell the story of the art market since its crash in 1990. The question now is, Will the last two years of liftoff become soar? Is it, in other words, time to buy? <p>Well, some experts think so. Consider the signs. <p>Collectors, who had pretty much dropped out of the market by 1987, have returned. One of them, John Stewart of Sagaponack, New York, is back and putting his couch-price rule to work. He explains: "When you can buy great paintings by very good artists for less than it takes to buy a couch at Bloomingdale's, then art is undervalued. Prices for normal, young artists are back to competing with Bloomingdale's." <p>Bidding at auction is in a rational phase, too. Christopher Burge, chairman of Christie's Inc., says he now sees buyers trying to stop bidding at the same price point. "When they all start cutting their bids at the same time, that means there is a consensus on value," he says. "It's an orderly market now -- a perfect market." <p>Finally, it's an auspicious time in the broader art-market cycle. Burge has lived through four cycles in his 27 years in the business. He figures the average cycle takes about seven or eight years. "Following any spurt is a falling back, a loss of confidence," he says. "A lot of supply is withdrawn, and the supply that does come onto the market is not the best, causing a higher rate of unsold lots at auction. These things fuel uncertainty." <p>According to Burge, downturns last 18 to 24 months 
before the market finds a price level -- that is, before sellers adjust to new prices. Then follows a period of consensus. That is followed by the inevitable run-up. Burge pegs major bottoms in 1969, 1975, 1981, and 1990, which coincide roughly with economic slumps. (The last cycle was extended by the Japanese, who started a buying surge in 1988 and then, when their economy tanked, vanished from the market.) <p>So if the market is coming off a major bottom, does that mean we are in for a major top -- like the glory days of the 1980s? Days when Ivan Karp of O. K. Harris in New York could turn over inventory at breathtaking speed and at eyebrow-raising profits? "We had concluded a sale for a painting and accepted a down payment," Karp recalls. "Then a dealer came in and said he'd give us 25 percent more. I gave the buyer a $10,000 bonus not to buy. That's how it was." <p>But before you rush out with a pocketbook over your arm, step back and consider the nature of the art market. It has characteristics that make it at once comforting and dangerous. <p>As a market, the art market satisfies some of the criteria for efficiency that are attractive to investors. There are, for instance, no big price gaps among markets. Dealer Max Davidson used to buy in Paris and sell in New York; now, he says, "price differences are insignificant." Indeed, buyers can bid at auctions from halfway around the world, making former barriers like geography inconsequential. <p>Information aboundeth, too: Auction houses churn out catalogs, and publishers spew out art magazines. Price information is especially accessible. <p>The market also has a decently diverse product mix with different price and risk ranges. Its three major categories -- the biggest is decorative (furniture, rugs, silver, etc.), which is followed by painting and work on paper and then by sculpture -- account for somewhere between $20 billion and $50 billion in annual sales. In each category, good works can be bought for anywhere from a couple hundred dollars to a couple hundred thousand dollars. Risks also vary widely: In painting, for example, old masters probably carry the least risk, contemporary living artists carry the most, and impressionists and 19th-century artists are somewhere in between.<p>But the art market also has other characteristics that make it unattractive to investors.<p>First and foremost, it's almost impossible to determine if risk-adjusted returns compare favorably with those of other markets. Indeed, it's a little tricky to determine what, exactly, returns are. Price changes can be measured only for works that endure and are brought to market. Since most art is deemed worthless and thrown out, estimates of returns capture only the survivors and are, thus, overstated. Moreover, it's hard to estimate the nonpecuniary component involved in owning art -- the value attached to the enjoyment gained from the simple act of viewing. <p>Tricky as it is to figure rates of return, economists have gone right ahead anyway. William Grampp, professor emeritus of economics at the University of Chicago, reviews some of the better empirical studies in his 1989 book, Pricing the Priceless. Estimates of rates of return, gleaned from looking at price changes for a broad range of paintings, vary enormously. The highest real return was 8 percent annually from 1946 to 1968, and the lowest real return was .55 percent annually over 300 years (1652 to 1961). Such a wide range, created by honest and skilled people, should alert potential investors to the fact that investing in art is akin to flying blind.<p>Yet even if it were possible to obtain sound estimates of returns, it's still a mug's game to view those returns in terms of risk. Is the risk attached to an investment in a Picasso unusually high or abnormally low? Unlike other financial markets where risk is routinely measured -- such as with a beta for stocks, duration for bonds, and BlackScholes for options -- the risks in the art market are not that transparent.<p>There are two types of risk: market and nonmarket. Market risk stems from changes in income and wealth. Since the demand for art is income elastic, more wealth and higher incomes will mean greater demand for art, but a sudden economic or financial crunch will cause demand to evaporate and prices to crater.<p>As for nonmarket risk, on the demand side art investors are always subject to broad changes in taste. For example, Nicholas Hall of the Colnaghi gallery in New York says, "English portraiture was devoured in America at the turn of the century. In 1915, Henry Frick bought The Ladies Sarah and Catherine Bligh, by John Hoppner, for $100,000. It would now sell for $150,000. But the same year, he bought for $28,000 less a portrait by Bronzino, Portrait of Ludovico Capponi, that would now be worth about $25 million." Similarly, 10 to 20 years ago, strong Italian religious paintings, such as works by Guido Reni and Mattia Preti, were popular. Today, Italian view paintings by Canaletto and landscapes by French artists such as Hubert Robert are considered more stylish.<p>There are also smaller shifts. The art world is vulnerable to fads in which certain schools or artists can go from being wildly popular to totally shunned almost overnight -- Julian Schnabel comes to mind. Ian Kennedy of Simon Dickinson in New York says, "These days, people don't want to be challenged. They don't want pictures of difficult subjects, too dramatic or emotional. They want a picture that is easy to live with, something a bit bland and decorative." <p>Risks can come, too, from the supply side. For instance, a huge sale of an artist's works or a corporate dumping of a particular period can flood the market and drive down prices. Nor does the art market offer opportunities for hedging risk. There is no futures market or organized options market. <p>Transaction costs, too, leave a lot to be desired. They are, well, on the high side. <p>When looked at beyond these specific good and bad aspects, the art market is a puzzle -- it exhibits characteristics that are a bit like more familiar investment markets yet unlike them as well.<p>For instance, the art market resembles the stock market; it comprises certain brand names that convey known attributes. The name Rembrandt is similar to the name <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> (a blue-chip category), while a Jean-Michel Basquiat is like <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a> (a growth category). Yet works by brand-name artists aren't fungible; not all Rembrandts are alike the way all Ford shares are.<p>Prices can experience wide and rapid swings, as they can in the commodities and foreign-exchange markets, but the art market itself is hardly as liquid as the commodities and foreign-exchange markets. Also, while the art market is global, like the bond market, it is not nearly as deep or as wide; it doesn't have a lot of ready buyers and sellers. It can surely be said -- and is with annoying frequency -- that works of art resemble pieces of real estate because they are unique and relatively illiquid, although, of course, most art is portable and real estate is not.<p>And, last, like other financial markets, the art market is subject to -- ahem -- speculative excesses. Consider what happened in the 1980s. <p>For starters, prices zoomed. The Daily Telegraph's price index for modern European painting rose at an average annual rate of 23 percent between 1980 and 1990; its index for old masters went up at an average annual rate of 15 percent. (During that time, stocks logged a 17 percent annual increase, and bonds registered a 13 percent annual rise.) <p>Speculators, drooling over the potential for fast profits, all but crowded collectors out of the market. Turnaround sales were lightning quick and generated delicious profits. One Florida dealer sold a Larry Rivers drawing in January 1989 for $19,000 only to see it auctioned off in New York at <a name="NYSE:BID"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12331"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sotheby's</b></a> ten months later -- before the check arrived -- for $88,000. "When we finally got the check," she says, "it came with a thank-you note and a bottle of champagne."<p>At auction houses, the doings were also red-hot: The 1987 sale of van Gogh's Irises for almost $54 million and the 1989 sale of Picasso's Pierrette's Wedding for close to $52 million merited international TV coverage. Christie's Burge recalls the moment just after the enormously successful 1990 auction of van Gogh's Portrait of Dr. Gachet. The place was packed, the crowd tense and silent. But at the fall of the gavel, the room burst into thundering applause. "They were not clapping for van Gogh but for themselves," says Burge. "The sale price of $82.5 million suggested their investments were secure." <p>Not to put too fine a point on it, but the art market of the 1980s had many of the markings of a financial bubble. Everybody and his sister-in-law were slurping up art -- the usual assortment of newly rich Americans as well as the Japanese, along with the Scandinavians, the French, the British, and the Swiss.<p>Why were they slurping? Well, surely some of it was motivated by a genuine interest in art. But surely some of it was driven by social climbing. "Take a fellow who has just made a couple of hundreds of millions of dollars," says Milton Esterow, publisher of Art News. "Who knows him? But let him buy a van Gogh for a couple of million, and suddenly everybody knows his name."<p>Consider the story told by collector John Stewart. In 1989, he was selling a work by pop artist Richard Artschwager. In the several years since he purchased it, Stewart had come to find the piece "atrocious." He told dealers he had an Artschwager for sale, but he was totally unprepared for what happened next. "A dealer asked if he could bring over a couple from Chicago," Stewart says. "Apparently, they were having a party, and they absolutely could not leave New York City without an Artschwager -- not my Artschwager, but an Artschwager -- to hang on a wall." (P.S. The couple returned to Chicago with Stewart's Artschwager for $165,000 -- four times what he had paid.)<p>And, finally, some of the buying was propelled by greed, pure and simple. As with all things financial when prices seem to skyrocket ever upward, buying art sure looked like easy money. When the market tanked in 1990, prices dropped 30 to 50 percent overall; 80 to 90 percent was not unusual for contemporary living artists. "Everyone disappeared at the same time," says dealer James Goodman. The result was several years of an abnormally thin and illiquid market.<p>Now, however, it looks like the art world has solidified the turnaround that began last year. Prices for certain things are coming back. Impressionists, for example, are now up to three-quarters of their top prices. Works of the modernist movement -- 1910 to 1950 -- are selling at 20 percent below their high-tide mark. Six years' time has meant that the two mighty engines of supply -- death and divorce -- have released a lot of fresh, quality stuff, and demand is once again broad based. Everyone, including the Japanese, is coming back. And there is a crop of new buyers: Americans, of course, in the form of new faces from Silicon Valley and small industrial firms, as well as new groups of English, French, Swiss, Koreans, South Americans, and Southeast Asians.<p>But the fact remains: Investors in the art market are tromping around in a lot of uncharted territory. Perhaps this is why almost everybody with any experience says art is not a good investment. Don't buy something, say the voices of wisdom, unless you love it. (Because, the voices imply, you'll be stuck looking at it forever.) <p>Indeed, the word "passion" crops up over and over again. Buying art should be a form of passion -- an exercise in passion, an expression of passion. And buyers who become collectors speak convincingly of their desire to acquire art not for profit but for the happiness of bringing significant cultural artifacts into their lives. Martin Margulies of Grove Isle, Florida, is one of those. When he started collecting contemporary art over 20 years ago, he says, he did so "for deeply personal reasons; it was something beyond business, more satisfying and illuminating."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
