<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Home and Away</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Home and Away</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Summer Reading<p>ECONOMICS
Hidden Order: The Economics of Everyday Life, by David D. Friedman (HarperBusiness, $25).
Of the millions who've forgotten their one semester of college economics, thousands wonder whether -- in this globally competitive age of ours -- they ought to try again. For them, David Friedman -- the son of conservative economist Milton Friedman -- has produced Hidden Order.<p>Friedman's apparent view is that, for years, market theory has just needed breezier expositors and snappier illustrations to win back those lost hearts and minds. Thus, Friedman tells us that economic rationality isn't just for "Mr. Spock" and other "calculating... Vulcans"; instead, it can help us save "a hero with a broken sword (Conan, Boromir, or your favorite Dungeons and Dragons character)."<p>As a relatively math-free field guide to traditional (and some recent) textbook concepts, Hidden Order does a cleverly decent job. We revisit Victorian-era principles and encounter newer approaches, such as rational expectations. We're cheerfully introduced to such modern figures as Gary Becker, James Buchanan, and Gordon Tullock and their applications of economics to new fields like crime, voting, and divorce. (The book notably omits any mention of John Maynard Keynes or his descendants, though, which is a bit like teaching American history sans Roosevelt, Kennedy, and Johnson.)<p>Even for readers inclined to Friedman's libertarian views, this book won't knock John Grisham off the beach; nor for sheer literacy and humor can Friedman rival his father's old nemesis, John Kenneth Galbraith. But for those who want to review their Samuelson (or McConnell or Lipsey and Steiner) through the partisan eyes of the University of Chicago, Hidden Order offers an offbeat -- and sometimes amusing -- introduction. <p>--Richard Parker<p>
WORLD AFFAIRS
Market Unbound: Unleashing Global Capitalism, by Lowell Bryan and Diana Farrell (John Wiley, $27.95).
Like Prometheus, financial markets, once bound by stabilizing international covenants, such as Bretton Woods, have now shaken off their chains. If the authors -- senior consultants at McKinsey & Company, which advises blue-chip clients around the world -- aren't the first to argue that governments are losing the ability to control the operation of capital in domestic markets, what distinguishes them is how heartily they celebrate the phenomenon.<p>The book is best at tracing the liberation of the global market, showing, for example, how the invention of simple derivatives (say, interest-rate swaps) provided the building blocks for a global financial stock marketplace worth $41 trillion by 1994. Bryan and Farrell take every opportunity to lay out clearly the interrelationships among bond, currency, and world stock markets.<p>For those who live and breathe the markets, the increasing liquidity and wealth of international financial markets can seem the most salient aspect of late-20th-century economic life. Such a view, however, has little to do with how most national economies operate. As financial markets become ever larger, the volume of money whirling through them reflects productive activity less and less. Not even one dollar in five that trades on the international-currency market is tied to a player outside the financial industry -- to someone who isn't a trader, in other words -- and over 80 percent of all U.S. productive economic activity still takes place in the domestic market. These conditions won't stop the growth of global financial markets, but they should comfort those who think the world is destined to be ruled by them. <p>-- Ted C. Fishman<p>The Challenge From the East and the Rebirth of the West, by Michael Spicer (St. Martin's Press, $22.95).
In this 200-page stump speech, Spicer claims that the nations of the East, led by China, are destined to overrun the West militarily and economically and, in the end, trounce all challengers in the age-old contest for prestige. A return to the forceful advocacy and practice of free trade is the West's only hope for peaceful coexistence with the aggressive East. Spicer's general conclusions about the merits of trade are sound enough, but he neglects to consider that the U.S. is increasingly an Eastern, as well as a Western, nation and that some Asian countries, such as Japan and South Korea, are as happy to ally themselves with Western interests as to embrace the democratic principles Spicer says are unique to our heritage. <p>-- Ted C. Fishman<p>
CRIME
Hot Blood: The Money, the Brach Heiress, and the Horse Murders, by Ken Englade (St. Martin's Press, $23.95).
Candy heiress Helen Brach vanished in 1977, leaving an estate then worth an estimated $30 million. Her body has never been found. Hot Blood tells the bizarre story of the investigation into Brach's disappearance. Penetrating the horsey set, the investigators discovered a dazzling array of lowlifes, from a Mafia hit man, to a check-forging crack addict, to a hired killer of show horses. Fun stuff for a book. One drawback, however, is that Englade writes with all the artistic subtlety of Joe Eszterhas. Nevertheless, true-crime aficionados will enjoy the book. Those tempted to buy a horse might want to think twice before reading it, though: They may end up suspecting that their trusted horse dealer would happily charge a 400 percent commission on a psychotic donkey. <p>-- William Green<p>
POINT OF VIEW
The Day Before Yesterday: Reconsidering America's Past, ReDIScovering the Present, by Michael Elliott (Simon & Schuster, $24).
An editor friend at The Economist once told me the secret of the magazine's style. Nothing to it, he pronounced: "First simplify, then exaggerate." In The Day Before Yesterday, Elliott (an Economist veteran now at Newsweek International) displays the merit -- and liabilities -- of this British approach. Expanding on an Economist article he wrote some years ago, he revisits America's last half century to examine our current complaints.<p>"Americans whine," he begins sternly. We misread the late 1940s, 1950s, and 1960s; that hazy "golden age" of American prosperity and power concealed all sorts of fissures and failures. Always a nation of immigrants, plagued by cultural wars and uneven prosperity, we were lucky, as well as energetic, after World War II -- and wrongly took this historical moment as a new norm. We still possess an entrepreneurialism and ambition that can move us forward -- but only if we stop whining.<p>A tad long on this sort of Methodist uplift, the book lacks the depth that David Halberstam, Martin Walker, and Daniel Bell bring to their work. Yet as an easily digestible blend of anecdote, data, and (partisan) judgment, it's a worthy tour d'horizon of our rightfully contested recent past. For those who favor the Newsweek castor-oil-and-spinach school of analysis (think Robert Samuelson, Meg Greenfield, and Joe Klein), it's ultimately good "vacation history."              -- Richard Parker<p>
Business as a Calling: Work and the Examined Life, by Michael Novak (Free Press, $22.50).
This is a thought-provoking but tricky book -- one that shouldn't be read blithely by those who want to believe Peter F. Drucker's claim that it's "nonsense" to judge an "economic action" by yardsticks other than profitability.<p>True, Novak endorses Drucker's remark with great enthusiasm. But he then contradicts it by arguing, somewhat unctuously, that CEOs and entrepreneurs can lay claim to moral virtues as well as economic ones. Why? Simply because business entails obedience, on pain of ruin, to morally significant obligations: providing products of "real value" and creating new wealth, new jobs, and a "reasonable" return on investment.<p>But Novak, not surprisingly for a Roman Catholic "theologian on capitalism" at the American Enterprise Institute, is a closet paternalist. As such, he believes that business folk have obligations to society beyond the obligation to prosper. For example, they must foster a strong sense of community, condemn the "animal-like" sex and violence of popular culture, and battle constantly against the forces of envy and despair.<p>This is a daunting moral agenda, requiring a quixotic resistance to such market-driven imperatives as corporate downsizing, competitive marketing, and CEO remunerations that are 200 times those of the average worker. Here, sadly, Novak falls silent. Communism's ruin has left free enterprise in the ethical catbird seat, but also under intense ethical scrutiny. So buy Novak's book for a rather smarmy exhortation on behalf of the system, but look elsewhere (if only to Drucker) for a more persuasive defense of it. <p>-- Nelson W. Aldrich Jr.<p>
FICTION
The Zero Hour, by Joseph Finder (William Morrow, $25).
If the Oklahoma City and World Trade Center bombings have taught us anything, it is this: When it comes to terrorism in the U.S., expect the unexpected. Of course, those incidents taught terrorists a lot, too. So the details of atrocity are what make The Zero Hour so hair-raising. Finder plots his entire scenario at the apex of the terrorist learning curve. The provocateur, for example, isn't a political ideologue; instead, he's a fugitive tax evader eager to get back at America by bombing Wall Street's most powerful computer network. Finder, an internationally renowned expert on the CIA, massages his material with great skill. This is one of those books that will inevitably be dismissed as a great beach read -- and it is that -- but anyone interested in how modern technology makes world finance vulnerable will find a lot more here than that. <p>-- Greg Critser<p>
The Vulture Fund, by Stephen W. Frey (Dutton, $23.95).
Mace McLain, a hotshot investment banker, is tapped to head a $2 billion "vulture fund" to buy real estate in a market crash rigged by the head of the CIA. Unless, that is, Mace and his bosom buddy from the orphanage (!), Slade, can save the day. Beach literature requires such a plot. Other essential elements are also here: venal bankers, presidential shenanigans, nuclear terrorism, a few rolls in the hay. But to be a good beach read, a book must satisfy certain commandments. No putting laughable dialogue straight off the cutting-room floor of Oliver Stone's Wall Street into the mouths of cardboard characters stuck in boardrooms. Action shall take place before book's end and not read as if slapped together by teenagers. Plausibility shall not be repeatedly stretched by suspending logic. Alas, The Vulture Fund violates them all. So instead of being entertaining and disposable, it's simply disposable. 
-- Rob Spillman<p>
MEMOIRS
Benjamin Graham: The Memoirs of the Dean of Wall Street, by Benjamin Graham (McGraw-Hill, $27.95).
The Wall Street Journal recently described Graham as one of the greatest investors of all time, ranking him with George Soros, Peter Lynch, and Graham protg Warren Buffett. Graham averaged a 17 percent rate of return over a career that saw both the Crash and the Great Depression, yet it's somewhat miraculous that he became an 
investor at all: A month before graduating from Columbia University in 1914, he was simultaneously offered teaching appointments in the school's departments of mathematics, English, and philosophy. Instead, he took a job as a Wall Street runner and apprentice bond salesman.<p>His memoirs are for those who want a look into the inner life of a notoriously private and wonderfully playful man. Some material covers his experiences and techniques as a financier, but mostly the other facets of his many-sided brilliance are on display. Not least of these is the insight of one who can criticize himself for being aicted with Horace's mens sibi conscia recti -- a mind conscious of its own rectitude (this from a person memorably described 
by another as one who "leaped from blonde to blonde like an alpine goat springing from peak to peak").<p>A fair number of other Latin tags dot the book. Makes sense, though:
Graham translated not only Latin poetry, but French and German poetry, too. He also, despite never having formally studied Spanish, translated a Uruguayan novel, Mario Benedetti's La Truega. You won't find his kind on Wall Street (or anywhere else) anymore; it's amazing you ever could. <p>-- Fredric Smoler<p>
BUSINESS
The Critical Path: Inventing an Automobile and Reinventing a Corporation, by Brock Yates (Little, Brown, $24.95).
On a Clear Day You Can See <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> exposed the piranha-like atmosphere within GM, and Iacocca the back-stabbing egomania at <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>. Now The Critical Path gives us the history of <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a>'s minivans in riveting detail -- and, in so doing, provides behind-the-scenes close-ups of the auto industry's warts and executive foibles.<p>Those who put Lee Iacocca on a pedestal, for example, will want a pillow to cushion their idol's frequent falls. Iacocca, credited as the "father of the minivan," initially vetoed the project in favor of developing a pickup truck. (Chrysler's sales and marketing staffs had no more foresight: They laughed at the suggestion that minivans might replace station wagons.) When the first van finally rolled off the assembly line, the power door locks failed, and Iacocca, at the wheel for a photo op, was briefly trapped inside.<p>The minivan's story may be the glue that holds the chapters together, but the book is also a litany of Chrysler travails, from Frank Sinatra's misadventures at Iacocca's Vegas farewell party, to Chrysler executives' dodging Inside Edition cameras that were pursuing a recall story, to Kirk Kerkorian's hostile-takeover attempt.<p>Don't be put off by the dry title. Yates, a noted automotive writer, columnist, and Cannonball-race instigator, uses a detective-like style and fascinating detail to produce an enjoyable, quick read. -- Jim Mateja<p>
Hit and Run: How Jon Peters and Peter Guber Took <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a> for a Ride in Hollywood, by Nancy Griffin and Kim Masters (Simon & Schuster, $25).
> Motion-picture market share held by Columbia in 1989: 9.4 percent.
> Amount, including debt, Sony paid to buy Columbia in 1989: $5 billion.
> Yearly salaries paid to Jon Peters and Peter Guber: $2.75 million each.
> Academy Awards won by Guber and Peters: zero.
> Amount spent on rugs for Guber's office: $67,124.40.
> Amount spent on chairs for the office of Lynda Guber, a producer: $11,420.
> Amount spent to charter a plane for Bruce Willis when the corporate jet was filled with flowers and sent to Peters's girlfriend instead: $50,000.
> Amount Peters spent on Mike Medavoy's 50th-birthday party: $100,000.
> Number of handicapped-parking places appropriated for Peters and Guber: two.
> Number of times Sony CEO Norio Ohga, on going to the john, had to chase away Peters by saying, "Tiger-san! We make pee-pee now! Go outside!": one.
> Minimum amount paid by Sony to "make Jon Peters go away": $30 million.
> Production costs on Hudson Hawk: at least $50 million.
> Net loss on Hudson Hawk: more than $42 million.
> Number of LifeCycles in Guber's home: 20.
> Size of the revolving fund given to Guber to produce movies after his "resignation": $275 million.
> Motion-picture market share held by Columbia (now Sony) in 1994: 9.4 percent. <p>-- Greg Critser<p>
ALSO OUT
Traders' Tales, by Ron Insana (John Wiley, $24.95). 
This charming book by the host of CNBC's Inside Opinion captures the quickly disappearing sensibility of Old Wall Street, a place, Insana writes, where "emotional extremes" fused with "a fraternal order" to create an original American culture. 
-- Greg Critser<p>The Dilbert Principle, by Scott Adams (HarperBusiness, $20). Cartoonist Scott Adams brings to his potato-headed hero a frustration with management that will resonate with anyone who's ever been passed over, unappreciated, bossed by an incompetent, or relegated to silly projects -- in short, anyone who's ever worked in an office. 
-- Ken Kurson<p>"This Business Has Legs," by Peter Bieler with Suzanne Costas (John Wiley, $24.95). 
A saga as passionately told as anything by Joan Collins; Suzanne Somers herself couldn't do better. The subtitle says it all: How I Used Infomercial Marketing to Create the $100,000,000 ThighMaster Exerciser Craze. 
-- Hillary Johnson<p>Leo Melamed: Escape to the Futures, by Leo Melamed with Bob Tamarkin (John Wiley, $27.95). 
Anyone in business knows futures markets are critical to a true international economy. What people probably don't know is that, if one man invented these markets, that man is Leo Melamed. His memoir is a lively, unpretentious account of how the Chicago Mercantile Exchange came to be what it is and how he created some of the key underpinnings of a world economy running on pure fiat money. 
-- Fredric Smoler<p>The Complete Guide to Offshore Money Havens, by Jerome Schneider (Prima, $29.95). 
This ridiculous mess of grand promises and contradictions is the dark side of the boom in global investing. Its biggest problem is that almost all of the treaties that created offshore tax havens have been revamped, and U.S. citizens have almost no advantages in moving their investment base abroad. 
-- Ted C. Fishman<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Publishing Industry, Education

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
