		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Tallying Total Return</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Tallying Total Return</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Investor, know thy return. Appreciation is only half the picture.<p>By Kathleen Pender<p>Most investments offer two sources of profit: income (dividends or interest) and capital gains (an increase in the security's market price). Together, they make up total return.<p>Some investors fixate on capital gains, forgetting that dividends fatten returns and cushion losses. Others focus on yield, forgetting that a decline in the price of a stock or bond can wipe out years of dividends or interest payments.<p>Total return is the only way to measure an investment's performance and the only meaningful way to compare returns on two investments -- a stock with no dividend but plenty of price appreciation, say, and a high-dividend equity with some gain in price. It's easy to figure total return on a security held for a full year: Start with the total value of the shares or bonds in a portfolio at year-end, and add interest or dividends received but not reinvested. Subtract the value at the start of the year, and divide the difference by the starting value. Convert to a percentage.<p>For example, say each of 100 shares you own of a stock worth $12 a share on January 1 pays $2 in annual dividends and appreciates to $16 by year-end. The year-end total value is $1,600 ($16 times 100) plus $200 ($2 in dividends times 100 shares), or $1,800. The beginning value was $1,200. So total return for the year is 50 percent -- $1,800 minus $1,200 (or $600) divided by $1,200, then multiplied by 100 to convert to a percentage.<p>The calculation isn't usually that simple, however. Adding or withdrawing cash from a portfolio during the year changes the basis of the calculation. Dividends that are paid on different dates further complicate matters.<p>"Brokerage houses could do this for people, but they don't," says John Markese, president of the American Association of Individual Investors. Fortunately, investors have two do-it-yourself choices. Software such as Quicken, Simply Money, and Managing Your Money calculate total return with a click of the mouse after the investor enters buy and sell prices and dividends or interest payments.<p>Paper-and-pencil investors don't have to throw up their hands, either. The formula below will calculate an approximate total return for any portfolio. The approximation will be most accurate if an investor does the calculation at the end of a quarter or year and if additions or withdrawals are in fairly equal amounts and at regular intervals. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
