<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Tactics of the Next High-Tech</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Tactics of the Next High-Tech</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Some currently cheap high-tech stocks aren't exactly bargains<p>By Jonathan Butler<p><a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a>, the maker of the high-end computer systems that brought the dinosaurs of Jurassic Park to life, did a good job of animating investors as well for most of last year. Its stock rose 35 percent in the first eight months of 1995. <p>But then came the technology rout. By the end of April 1996, the stock had lost all its gains, trading within three dollars of its January 1995 price. That was common for technology stocks: After rising 45 percent in the first eight months of last year, the Pacific Stock Exchange technology index treaded water in the last quarter -- while the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index climbed another 6 percent. The first quarter of 1996 didn't go any better: The Pacific Stock Exchange index fell 0.3 percent, and the S&P rose 5.4 percent.<p>Suddenly, hot performers from 1995 -- like <a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a> (down 64 percent as of May 15, 1996, from its 1995 high), <a name="NASD:MACR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16658"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Macromedia</b></a> (down 36 percent), <a name="NASD:LLTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13973"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Linear Technology</b></a> (down 32 percent), and even <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a> (down 23 percent) -- look cheap. But investors shouldn't assume this pullback is a buying opportunity for every fallen highflier. Some of these stocks are victims of changes in technology that have cut profit margins or made key products obsolete. Many could actually fall further. Experts believe that the next technology rally will differ from the 1995 boom: This time, the rising tide will not lift all boats.<p>It's as important to know which stocks to avoid as it is to find great stocks to buy. One or two flops can annihilate a portfolio's gains. Witness the <a name="FUND:MBTCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MBTCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch Technology B Fund</b></a>. When its biggest holding, software maker <a name="NASD:AKLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10544"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acclaim Entertainment</b></a>, fell 35 percent on December 5, the fund, which held 25 stocks at the time, declined 5 percent in one day.<p>How does an investor identify stocks threatened by potential downdrafts? At this stage in the technology revolution, avoid companies marketing technology in danger of becoming outdated, those with a small market share and narrow product lines, and those whose profits depend on high-margin products that are facing competition from lower-margin products.<p>OUT WITH THE OLD
Every technology investor knows what the introduction of the PC did to companies that made mainframe computers. As PCs and networks of PCs became powerful enough to do many of the tasks that only mainframes could once perform, sales of mainframes fell as a percentage of total sales. At <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, for example, sales of mainframe computers and related products have declined from 42 percent of sales in 1992 to 25 percent in 1995, according to Daniel Mandresh, vice president of research at Merrill Lynch. That decline has had an immense impact on the bottom line even at companies that have kept their sales climbing in total dollars: Mainframes and related products have profit margins of at least 60 percent, four times more than the 15 percent profit margin for PCs.<p>That story is now being replayed among computer companies whose fortunes are tied to the Unix operating system. The group at risk includes such stellar performers as Silicon Graphics (NYSE: SGI) and <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a> (Nasdaq: SUNW), up-and-comers such as the <a name="NASD:SCOC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15227"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Santa Cruz Operation</b></a> (Nasdaq: SCOC) and <a name="NASD:BNYN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15842"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Banyan Systems</b></a> (Nasdaq: BNYN), and old-line mainframe makers such as <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Unisys (NYSE: UIS). "The companies to be most worried about are the ones that are dependent on Unix and are not open to other systems," says Larry Eakin, a senior technology analyst at Federated Investors in Pittsburgh. "The key is that those old proprietary systems carry terrifically good profit margins compared to the new stuff," says Michael Murphy, editor of California Technology Stock Letter. For example, although revenues at Unisys, which provides computer systems to governments and businesses, have certainly headed south, falling from $8.4 billion in 1992 to $6.2 billion in 1995, earnings have plummeted even faster, dropping from $362 million in 1993 to $43 million last year.<p>Unix is one of the oldest and most versatile operating systems, the intermediary software that enables applications, such as databases and graphics, to run on a computer. PCs running a new operating system from <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> called Windows NT still can't match the power of Unix-based systems, but they have recently narrowed the gap. And they cost much less. For example, a high-end workstation and software from Silicon Graphics can't be beat for its graphic modeling capabilities. Using such a workstation, an engineer can see how the sun would reflect off different paints on a car or let a client "sit" in the interior. But such machines cost more than $100,000. Users who don't need the ultimate in graphics capabilities can approximate the power and versatility of such machines using an NT-based PC system for about $20,000. To compete, companies like Silicon Graphics have introduced new products at the low end of their product lines. That has kept sales growing, but profit margins fell from 53.5 percent at the end of 1994 to 50.7 percent in the last quarter of 1995.<p>SIZE MATTERS
The obvious example of how heft makes a difference is <a name="NASD:SQNT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14698"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> (Nasdaq: AAPL). Its Macintosh line of personal computers, which uses an operating system that's incompatible with Microsoft Windows, controls roughly 7.3 percent of the domestic personal-computer market. That's enough to make Apple one of the world's largest computer makers, but not enough to keep software makers producing new applications for the Macintosh. Many program updates for the Macintosh get to market months after the Windows version has already been installed in users' computers. Increasingly seen as a niche player by investors, Apple finds its very survival threatened. The stock has plunged 50 percent in the past year.<p>The same problem bedevils other technology companies in less obvious ways. <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sequent</b></a> (Nasdaq: SQNT), a Beaverton, Oregon, firm that makes multiprocessor-computer systems for financial and retail transactions, is too small and specialized to challenge companies that offer customers one-stop shopping for everything from PCs 
to electronic measurement systems. "There's no way Sequent [with revenues of $535 million] can compete against the breadth of companies like <a name="NASD:BNET"></a><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> [with $31.5 billion] and Digital [with $13.8 billion]," says Nicholas Moore, an analyst at Franklin Funds. Sequent stock has lost half its value since last summer.<p>The lesson hasn't been lost on companies in such competitive industries as networking. The big four networking companies -- <a name="NYSE:CS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10276"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bay Networks</b> (Nasdaq: BNET), <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cabletron</b></a> (NYSE: CS), <a name="NASD:COMS"></a><b>Cisco Systems</b></a> (Nasdaq: CSCO), and <a name="NASD:LNOPF"></a><b>3Com</b> (Nasdaq: COMS) -- which have an average market cap of $12.6 billion, so dominate the market for hubs, routers, and switches that the likes of <a name="NASD:ODSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15698"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LanOptics</b> (Nasdaq: LNOPF), with a mere $55 million market cap, <a name="NASD:NPIX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42199"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Optical Data</b></a> (Nasdaq: ODSI), with $400 million, and <a name="NASD:STRM"></a><b>Network Peripherals</b></a> (Nasdaq: NPIX), with $170 million, can't reach critical mass. And the big companies are determined to keep size working for them. Cisco Systems, for example, is set to complete a merger with <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>StrataCom</b> (Nasdaq: STRM) in June.<p>Why is size so important? It's related to the increasing pressure on margins in industry after industry in the technology sector. Size makes it possible to create manufacturing or marketing efficiencies that will let one 600-pound gorilla dominate the playing field. No company illustrates this principle better than Intel.<p><a name="NYSE:AMD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10037"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a> controls three-quarters of the market in microprocessors, the chips that direct computer functions (as opposed to memory chips, which merely store information). Its economies of scale let Intel pummel wanna-bes like <a name="NASD:CYRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16430"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Advanced Micro Devices</b></a> (NYSE: AMD) and <a name="NYSE:TXN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11462"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cyrix</b></a> (Nasdaq: CYRX). For example, AMD, the number-two microprocessor maker, spends more to manufacture its chips and, with a gross profit margin of 32 percent in 1996, earns less on them. (Intel's gross margin for the first quarter of 1996 was 47.9 percent.) "AMD can't get the volume and can't get anywhere near the prices of Intel," says Bob Finch, a money manager at Aeltus in Hartford. Intel has relentlessly plowed its extra profits into new factories and into creating new products in shorter and shorter cycles. For example, as AMD was releasing its answer to the Pentium, Intel was unveiling the Pentium Pro.<p>A DIME A DOZEN
Intel's size lets it control the market for its product. Other technology companies aren't so lucky. For example, companies that make the computer chips that store memory, called DRAMs, are actually in a commodity business: Customers don't care whether they buy from Micron Technology, <a name="NASD:DELL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13193"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Texas Instruments</b></a>, or Samsung.<p>Three years of tight supply and high prices led DRAM makers around the world to build new factories. When overstocked customers slowed their purchases in the first quarter, prices dropped 50 percent, and DRAM makers like Boise, Idaho based Micron (NYSE: MU) were stuck with excess capacity. After sinking $400 million into a new $2.5 billion plant in Utah, Micron put the project on hold. Its stock has fallen 60 percent in the past seven months.<p>PCs are quickly becoming a commodity, too. Profit margins in that industry have fallen by 50 percent since 1990 as customers have realized that machines from most manufacturers are virtually identical. That left computer makers to compete on price alone.
PC companies now vary primarily in their ability to manage inventory and get their products on the shelves. Companies like <a name="NASD:GATE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dell</b></a> (Nasdaq: DELL) and <wam-co NASD:GATE>Gateway</b></a> (Nasdaq: GATE) use just-in-time delivery to gain an edge in managing inventory. But dealers and re-sellers account for 80 percent of sales in the $100 billion PC industry. Once again, size counts. Big manufacturers have the clout to win shelf space at retailers and the broad product lines that give dealers an edge in selling to their customers. It's no accident that Hewlett-Packard, the most recognized name in computer printers, has been the fastest-growing seller of PCs recently -- or that AST, a relatively narrowly focused company, has been one of the most troubled. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

