	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Angles</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Angles</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						These are the folks who rush in where other investors fear to tread. Their ranks are swelling, and would-be entrepreneurs are grateful for it. <p>By Nick Ravo<p>Near dawn, deep in the New Hampshire woods, a half dozen lumberjack look-alikes pull up in their four-wheel-drives outside the not-as-posh-as-it-sounds Nashua Country Club.<p>Ignore the plaid shirts and work boots. "We don't wear suits, but the people who come to see us do," says Morton Goulder, a physicist-turned-investor and a longtime host of this informal gathering, which has met here irregularly for ten years and calls itself the Breakfast Club. Goulder and his friends aren't just here for bacon and eggs -- they're wealthy men prospecting for business, as their guests, many too nervous to eat, are entirely aware. These nicely dressed pilgrims are inventors and entrepreneurs in search of an angel, someone who will bestow some cash and perhaps some worldly wisdom on their embryonic businesses.<p>There are roughly 250,000 angels in the United States. ("We prefer to think of ourselves as zero-stage venture capitalists," Goulder jokes.) In 1995, they gave an estimated $10 billion to $20 billion in financing to 30,000 to 40,000 ventures -- about four times as much as the better-known venture-capital funds, according to the University of New Hampshire's Center for Venture Research.<p>Mark Conant, president and chief executive officer of Built on Technology in Derry, New Hampshire, is one of the many supplicants who have made the journey to the Breakfast Club. Last May, he met with Goulder and asked for $80,000 to help expand his fledgling company, which makes toner-dispensing units for laser printers.<p>Conant presented his business plan to Goulder and scheduled a second meeting with him and another Breakfast Clubber. He projected that investors could triple their money in three years and has found two other angels who have kicked in $10,000 each. He also has three more backers who have been with him two and a half years and who have helped him with patent applications and prototypes.<p>Firms like Built on Technology are the engines of new-job creation in the nation's economy -- the computer-software and -hardware, health-care, and consumer-product start-ups that often begin with a lone inventor's stroke of inspiration. But neither the banks nor the deep-pocketed venture-capital firms can be relied on to fund such small, vulnerable operations, especially when they need just a few thousand dollars to stay alive or get under way. Angels have rushed in to fill the gap, becoming "one of the most important and least recognized parts of the business world," says William E. Wetzel Jr., director emeritus of the Center for Venture Research and the nation's preeminent authority in the field.<p>This seed money can bear rich fruit. For example, in 1978, C. Richard Kramlich, today a managing general partner at the California-based venture-capital firm New Enterprise Associates, gave a couple of Bay Area computer geeks $22,500 out of his own pocket. The investment grew to $5 million over the next decade; the geeks were Steven Jobs and Steve Wozniak; the start-up was <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a>.<p>"I was just plain lucky as an angel," Kramlich says. Perhaps, but he got a chance to be lucky because New Enterprise Associates was just starting up at the time, and Jobs and Wozniak wanted a piddling $45,000 -- but the deal was too small. Kramlich's partners said, "Yes, it's a great company, but we are a $16 million partnership," he recalls. "So I took it myself and split the $45,000 with someone else." (Only later did Apple receive venture-capital financing.)<p>This ability to take a flier is one reason Ralph Wagner, a former owner of a chain of computer stores who now spends most of his time as an angel, believes that angels "are the seed money for most of the companies that start up in America today." Recently, Wagner put $37,500 into PureSpeech of Cambridge, Massachusetts. "It's a company that makes a voice-recognition system that recognizes the meaning of what you say contextually -- by how you say it," he says. "It hasn't gone public yet, but it will. It looks like a potential big hit."<p>Wagner has been doing this for about ten years, ever since he invested "around $100,000" in <a name="NASD:NMSS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17026"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Natural Microsystems</b></a>, a small company in Natick, Massachusetts. It sold its first shares to the public in February 1995 and "is doing very well," he says. "But that one took a long time to pay off, so the overall annual return was probably only about 15 to 20 percent."<p>Angels make private placements of as little as $10,000 and rarely more than $500,000. In this respect, they are unlike federally regulated Small Business Investment Companies, which seldom invest less than $300,000 to $500,000, or venture-capital funds, which almost never kick in less than $1 million. While venture-capital firms are structured as eight- to ten-year limited partnerships, angels are often willing to stay invested for longer periods. Of course, this is the highest trapeze of the investing circus; there is no greater overall risk and no greater potential profit. Think <a name="NASD:BOST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16244"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boston Chicken</b></a>. Think <a name="NASD:PIXR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46451"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pixar</b></a>.<p>Now think Vanguard Environmental.<p>What is Vanguard Environmental? Ronnie Raben knows. He's an angel in Austin, Texas, who lost $200,000 in the company, which consisted of little more than a few Waco University professors who, in response to tougher clean-water standards in Texas, had developed a new type of treatment system for businesses.<p>"It turned out the government was more flexible than we thought they would be, and companies didn't need it," says Raben, a former tax attorney, who estimates he has invested half a million dollars in about 20 deals over the past ten years. Overall, he says, he's made "over $5 million" on his original half-million-dollar stake.<p>Morton Goulder has invested several million dollars in 100 businesses over the past 20 years. He's won some and lost some. "Some of these companies do take a long time before you make any money," he says. "On the whole, though, I've probably done better than your average trust fund."<p>Of course, the prospect of a higher return means higher risk. Angels generally don't fund more than one or two budding businesses at a time, and the odds of earning huge profits on a given deal are probably one or two in ten. By comparison, venture-capital funds, which always have numerous bets on the table in order to spread the risk, hit a home run once or twice out of ten tries, fail two or three times, and are marginally successful with the remaining investments.<p>"The best angels are people who have been successful entrepreneurs themselves and feel a sense of obligation to help others get started," says Neil Rodberg, former director of operations at Technology Capital Network, a service in Cambridge, Massachusetts, that seeks to match angels with entrepreneurs. Angels often invest in areas where they have substantial experience or long-standing interest.<p>Goulder, for example, has a background in engineering. Decades ago, he worked for <a name="NYSE:RTN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11261"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Raytheon</b></a>, maker of the Patriot missile, and, in 1951, he helped start an electronics company, Sanders Associates, that was bought by <a name="NYSE:LMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10903"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lockheed</b></a> in 1986. The buyout netted Goulder around $10 million. Not bad for an initial investment of $5,000 that came from taking a second mortgage on his home.<p>"We sold stock to anyone who walked in the door," Goulder says. "There were no venture capitalists in those days."<p>In 1993, he invested $50,000 in <a name="NASD:SIMC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=50100"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Spacetec</b></a>, a company in Lowell, Massachusetts, that makes a three-dimensional mouse (or "spaceball") for CAD-CAM workstations used by architects and engineers. He also took a seat on the board and later invested another $70,000. "It was a good match for what I could contribute, and what they needed," he says.<p>Last December, to raise funds to enter the video-game market, the company sold shares to the public. Since then, the stock has bounced between $10 and $15 a share, and Goulder's stake -- worth a few million dollars -- has bounced right along with it.<p>Angel interest these days is concentrated in similar high-tech start-ups. Investment sectors that have gone cold include biotechnology ("The specter of FDA regulation scares some angels away," says Rodberg) and environmental control ("Too many consulting, engineering, and planning labs," says Bob Fuller, an angel in Milwaukee).<p>There are, however, many no- or  low-tech companies that benefit from angels. "We had a candy-bar manufacturer, Paris Chocolates," Rodberg recalls. "The angel tried the candy, said it was the best damn candy he had ever had, and cut a check on the spot."<p>Until recently, locating an angel was often a matter of 
hitting up a rich uncle. In the past few years, however, several nonprofit "dating services" have sprung up. The best known is the 11-year-old Technology Capital Network, which is affiliated with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and has a database of about 150 investors and 300 cash-starved companies. Its angels must have a net worth of at least $1 million or gross income of at least $200,000 for the past two years.<p>Another prominent service is the Capital Network (http://test.webtek.com/vcf/investor/tcn.htm) in Austin, Texas, which was started in 1989 by George Kozmetsky, co-founder of Teledyne. Small companies and inventors pay $450 to be listed for six months with the network; angels pay $450 for a one-year listing and receive summaries of ventures that might appeal to them. Around 80 percent of the organization's investors are angels, 15 percent are venture capitalists, and the balance are corporate investors commonly looking for a strategic alliance.<p>"The angels are usually successful entrepreneurs, but we also have doctors, lawyers, and dentists who will invest in small start-up companies, as well as some people in upper management at larger corporations and people who inherited money," says David Gerhardt, executive director of the Capital Network.<p>Several smaller nonprofit networks have also been born in recent years. Some have niches, like the computer-industryoriented Silicon Valley Venture Network (http://www. svi.org/jointventure/) in Sunnyvale, California; the year-old Environmental Capital Network (http://www.bizserve.com/ environmental.capital.network/) in Ann Arbor, Michigan; and the Investors' Circle in West Chicago, which describes itself as a socially responsible angel network.<p>"We do companies involved with health, education, energy efficiency, the environment, community development, women, and minority businesses," says Susan E. Davis, executive director of the Investors' Circle, which, since 1992, has put $16 million into 43 companies.<p>"We also have entrepreneur fairs twice a year and select a variety of different companies and show them to our investors," Davis adds.
One recipient of Investors' Circle money is Wild Planet Toys in San Francisco, a maker of educational nonviolent and nonsexist toys. "There is a real role for this type of angel," says Daniel C. P. Grossman, the company's president and chief executive officer. "In the Bay Area, most of the angels are technology-oriented and looking for <a name="NASD:NSCP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42472"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Netscape</b></a>- or <a name="NASD:YHOO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=48043"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yahoo</b></a>-type returns. We felt that it was more important to have angels tuned into our philosophy. I sleep better at night knowing that they share our values and share our vision."
Several for-profit firms have recently sprung up on the Internet to act as matchmakers between angels and investors.
"We have designed our listings into a database format that allows investor angels to search for ventures and markets that interest them," says John Dick, president of DealFlow (http://www.dealflow.com/index.html), a World Wide Web based angel-search service. "They can download details of ventures, for five dollars each, right onto their screen, where they can then save it, print it, or E-mail directly to the entrepreneur to request a detailed business plan or other information."<p>Gerhardt warns that angels aren't always a blessing. "There are angels that can be too controlling, try to take over the business," he says. "But that can happen with any type of partnership or investment."<p>For their part, angels look for entrepreneurs who, along with a good product and a market for it, have their own money at risk. Eighties-style OPM (other people's money) deals don't fly in the 1990s. Angels also want a fast-growing company, with sales eventually increasing 15 percent a year, minimum. And they want high returns, at least 20 percent. After all, investors can get that in the stock market most years if they have a top-drawer money manager.<p>Would-be angels should recognize that, though brainy, inventors can be so obsessed with their work that they may lack the most basic social skills and business knowledge. "They can't understand why you can't call at 11 p.m. when you have a great idea," Rodberg says. "Or they don't know the difference between debt and equity."<p>He adds that the Technology Capital Network has started a "charm school" to teach entrepreneurs how to deal with investors. It will also offer classes in finance fundamentals.<p><p>
COMPANIES SEEKING ANGELS
Just to give a sense of the breadth of the deals available to angels, here are a few taken from Private Investors Network in Baltimore, 
Environmental Capital Network in Ann Arbor, Michigan, and Investors' Circle in West Chicago, Illinois.<p>Clockwork Designs, Austin, Texas
Produces cost-control software for corporations. Seeking $1 million, $100,000 minimum. A two-and-a-half-year-old company with current annual sales of over $1 million, it's projected to grow to $50 million in five years. Estimated annual return from now until 2001, when the company hopes to go public: 35 percent.<p>Superior Pasta, Annapolis, Maryland
Take-out restaurant chain tentatively named Expressly Pasta. Seeking $2 million, $50,000 minimum, less for someone with investment-banking expertise. The seven-month-old company plans to develop two restaurants in the Washington, D.C., area modeled after the Boston Market chain. The first is scheduled to open this fall. Projected sales: $50 million by 2000. Estimated annual return on investment in four and a half years: 85 percent.<p>Adventure Learning Club, Vernon Hills, Illinois
Computer-education store. Seeking $500,000, $10,000 minimum investment, to open retail stores that sell lessons and time on computers. The 20-month-old company has one store open, $250,000 in annual sales, but no earnings yet. A second store is scheduled to open in September and a third next winter. The company plans to start franchising by January 1998. Aiming for a 10 percent annual return on investment over three years.<p>Cary Medical, Great Falls, Virginia
Medical-research-acquisitions company. Seeking $500,000, $50,000 minimum, to buy dormant pharmaceutical patents from the National Institutes of Health's Office of Technology Transfer. The 18-month-old company has three pending applications to license patents, including one for gossypol acetate, an old drug (used as an oral male contraceptive in China) that may 
be useful for treating breast cancer. The company expects to have nine or ten applications approved within three years. Projects an initial investment will grow 20 to 30 times if the company goes public or is bought by a large pharmaceutical corporation.<p>The Greener Cleaner, Chicago
Environmentally safe, chemical-free alternative to dry cleaning. Seeking $2 million, $50,000 minimum if part 
of a group investment totaling $500,000. The company operates one store and will soon open a second. Projects sales of $267,000 this year, up from $150,000 last year, but no earnings yet. Hopes for an annual return on investment of 47 percent over seven years.<p><p>
EARNING YOUR WINGS
How to Become an Angel<p>Q: How much money do I need?
A: Lots. You should be what the Securities and Exchange Commission calls "an accredited investor." That means having a net worth of $1 million or more, excluding your home, or earning more than $200,000 ($300,000 if investing as a married couple) in each of the past two years and expecting to do so again this year. Most angel networks require that their investors be accredited. Most legitimate entrepreneurs avoid the unaccredited or try to keep their number to a minimum. "This isn't for widows and orphans," says Jeffrey E. Sohl, director of the Center for Venture Research at the University of New Hampshire's Whittemore School of Business.<p>How much should I invest?
No single investment should ever take more than 10 percent 
of your investment assets. Investing in start-ups is a high-risk proposition, with the odds of hitting a home run somewhere around 10 percent, which is right up there with other long shots like buying pork-belly futures. A prudent angel might take the 10 percent of his investment portfolio allotted to start-ups and invest in ten separate deals. That works out to about 1 percent of your portfolio per deal, which, if you have $1 million in investment assets, will get you into ten companies for $10,000 each, the minimum investment you are likely to find. Many companies require $25,000 to $50,000 minimums.<p>What kind of return should I expect?
Out of ten investments, according to David Gerhardt of the Capital Network in Austin, Texas, probably three or four deals will fail, four or five will break even, and one will make substantial money -- perhaps 300 percent in three or four years (or an annual return of about 40 percent). Perhaps much more, if the company goes public or is bought.<p>How hard is it to get my money back?
That depends on the deal's terms and conditions, or T&C. The entrepreneur may decide to buy back the angels' shares at a mutually agreeable price. Sometimes, the particulars of a buyback -- the price and timetable -- are detailed in advance in the T&C. The price is generally based on the growth and value of the company. A buyback can be a good security blanket for an investor, but it can also force a company to spend too much time raising cash when it should be focusing on growth. There are, of course, companies that don't attract suitors and that aren't strong enough to go public, and for which a buyback isn't practicable. These are called the "living dead," and there are firms that specialize in buying their shares. At a discount.<p>Is the investment insured or guaranteed?
No. A buyback option written into the T&C is as close as you will get to a guarantee. Angel investments can also be structured as debt, which can be converted to equity if the company succeeds. <p>What do I get instead of a stock certificate?
A contract stating how many shares (or, in some cases, warrants, which are similar to stock options) you own in the company and their value. An investor making a $10,000 minimum investment, say, might buy 10,000 shares at a dollar a share. This would also be called one unit -- the number of shares a minimum investment buys.<p>How do I track my investment?
Financial reports, such as income statements, should be, but often aren't, sent out quarterly. These reveal the company's sales and earnings but not the approximate value of your shares if the company were sold or offered to the public. It is not difficult, however, to learn from bankers and analysts in your company's industry, or even from the company officials, what similar businesses sell for (generally, it's a multiple of annual earnings or sales). With an estimated value of the company, simple math will tell you what your shares might be worth.<p>Where do I find a company in need of an angel?
If you have enough money to be an angel, you probably mingle with others who know about these kinds of deals. Lawyers and accountants are good sources, and state business-development offices can be useful. You might also try the venture-capital networks. Forget the classified ads in newspapers under "Capital Wanted" or "Investment Opportunities."<p>Do I need a lawyer?
Yes. Seek someone who knows about early-stage equity investing. "Otherwise, the clock is running while the lawyer is learning," Sohl says.<p>Do I need financial advisers to peruse business plans?
Probably not. But if you don't fully understand the investment, it's not for you, at least not as the sole or lead investor. "A good way to start is to partner with some other investors, one of whom is the lead investor," Sohl says. "Angels tend to invest as a group and in areas they know something about."<p>Who does the due diligence?
You or your lead partner.<p>What kind of relationship will I have with the owner of 
the company?
Close. Very close. "You should be able to pick up the phone 
at any time and call him and get straight answers," Sohl says.<p>Should I ask for a seat on the board?
Maybe. If you're investing more than the minimum and more than most of the others, a seat is a reasonable request, as it is if you bring some unusual expertise to the venture. Keep in mind, though, that not every investor can be on the board, and if you're part of a group, only the lead investor should seek a seat. "There is no magic number for getting on a board," Gerhardt says. "It all depends on the company's size, the size of the board, the number of investors, and your contribution." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
