	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Speculating 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						SELF STUDY GUIDES
Chicago Mercantile Exchange
Free<p>AN INTRODUCTION TO FUTURES AND OPTIONS
Chicago Mercantile Exchange 
$10<p>OPTION TRADING SERIES
Chicago Board of Trade
Free<p>HOW TO OPTIMIZE YOUR STOCK PORTFOLIO WITH OPTIONS
The Options Industry Council
Free<p>By Ted C. Fishman<p>The temptation to play the passive investor is great. Today's conventional wisdom says that markets do better than individual stocks and that buying lots of different stocks and holding them forever beats trading. Plus there's an entire mutual-fund industry that promises to make everyone's investment decisions for them.<p>That's fine for most people most of the time, but let's say you want to get active. First you need some smarts -- and not merely about markets, but about trading them. Adding futures and options to your portfolio will teach you more about trading than a lifetime of buying and holding. It's fun, too, pitting yourself against the major economic trends. (Think the dollar's heading up? The bond market sideways?) What's more, introducing a small speculative element can fine-tune a portfolio by adding either risk -- and the chance for higher returns -- or stability, which is important in a volatile market.<p>Still, because futures and options have a reputation of burning investors, it's smartest not to start buying them blindly -- or from the next cold-calling futures broker. So, where to turn for some learning? Try the temples of speculative investment, the nation's top futures and options exchanges. The Chicago Mercantile Exchange and the Chicago Board of Trade offer a wide range of educational materials aimed at retail customers and professional brokers.<p>The Merc, perhaps the nation's most aggressively marketed exchange, produces the most approachable materials for beginners, much of it available for free (312-930-8210). The Merc's Self Study Guides on livestock futures and options, for example, are concise yet thorough introductions to the mechanics of trading agricultural contracts. They cover much of the same material found in the basic futures texts, and they're particularly good at explaining the most vexing strategy in trading, the short play. Other valuable materials from the Merc cover its currency and bond markets. The best aid, however, may be the manual An Introduction to Futures and Options ($10, but free for schools). It contains ten chapters (with quizzes), which are pitched at beginners, so you'll learn to tell a future from an option and a put from a call. More-advanced concepts, such as hedging and arbitrage, are also made comprehensible.<p>The Merc's crosstown rival, the Chicago Board of Trade, has its own free series of magazine-style brochures, including the Option Trading Series (800-THE-CBOT). These works assume that readers have a working vocabulary when it comes to futures and options, so they're a good follow-up to the Merc's begin-ner guides. A typical CBOT work is the Financial Option Strategies Menu, with approaches for various risk profiles, from the conservative hedger who wants to reduce portfolio risk to the crapshooter willing to take a flier.<p>Futures and options trading is often simplistically depicted as gambling. It's not. In fact, few financial instruments are more varied or can be fine-tuned more readily to meet specific investment objectives. In forging a bond-trading strategy, an investor has thousands of combinations of futures, puts, and calls of varying prices and expirations to choose from. The CBOT booklet warms up with a few straightforward, easily managed scenarios -- such as the long straddle, in which puts and calls are bought together -- and then moves on to more involved combos.<p>Don't forget to learn the math: Judging risks requires it. This is where one of the Board of Trade's booklets, Trading Ag Option Volatility, can help. It presents a step-by-step introduction to the mathematical measures of option value, such as vega (the sensitivity of option prices to changes in market volatility) and delta (the measure of how option prices change in relation to changes in their underlying contracts). It also suggests approaches on how to base trades on market volatility as well as price.<p>One caveat: Avoid the video called How to Optimize Your Stock Portfolio With Options, produced by the Options Industry Council. To the council's earlier, stilted production, The Options Tool, new material on using stock options to boost returns on equities has been added. Oversimplification is the chief fault here. Selling call options against stock, for example, is portrayed as a low-risk hedging strategy, when in fact it's the practical equivalent of selling puts outright -- the riskiest strategy of all. That's a long-standing misrepresentation of how options work. It should be struck for good. <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
