	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Is Time on Your Side?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Is Time on Your Side?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Does Time cut the risk of owning stocks? No, says a Nobel-winning Economist. <p>By Jim Jubak<p>The common wisdom is that market risk decreases if an investor holds stocks for the long term. But Paul A. Samuelson, the 1970 winner of the Nobel Prize for economics, disagrees. In articles stretching back to the early 1970s, he says, "I have debunked the usual arguments for the so-called long-term case for equities." Normally, investing in stocks will be the best strategy, says Samuelson, but the common wisdom makes it all too easy to become complacent about risk.<p>The basic argument for holding equities long term has two parts. First, although a stock investor can lose money in any one year, the historical record, as calculated by Ibbotson Associates, shows that since 1926 no 15-year period has produced a loss. Ergo, holding for the long term reduces risk. Second, statistics show that a coin flip has a 50 percent chance of producing either heads or tails. A short run of flips -- say, ten -- can result in this 50-50 outcome or an aberration, such as ten heads. As the number of flips rises, the distribution comes closer to 50-50. Hence, an investor who stays in the market long enough has a statistical guarantee of making the long-term average annual return: 10.5 percent, according to Ibbotson. <p>Neither part is true, according to  Samuelson, professor emeritus of economics at MIT. "Risk, properly measured, does not go to zero over long periods," he says.<p>Consider the cost of insuring against loss in the shipping industry. Insurers know that most ships don't sink, and they collect precise numbers on the chances of a ship's going down. But a policy's cost doesn't drop when a shipowner buys insurance for a longer period. Instead, rates rise to cover the greater uncertainty of a longer time frame.<p>That's partly because the world could change so that the old probabilities of a ship's sinking are obsolete. That increased uncertainty should worry investors more than underwriters. Solid financial data is available for no more than the past 100 years, and the oft cited numbers from Ibbotson date back to 1926. Is that period representative of the entire history and future of the markets?<p>Insurance premiums -- and market risk -- also rise as time increases because, statistically, "events in these arenas are not equivalent to coin tosses," says Samuelson. A coin toss has only two outcomes of equal magnitude. The market not only rises and falls but can swing by 20 or 100 points. A few outcomes are catastrophic, such as the crash of 1929. The chance of such a fiasco is small -- 
but it doesn't fall to zero over time. <p>What's an investor to do? "Most of the time, the investor who blithely ignores risk and buys lots of stock will fare better than the person who doesn't," says Samuelson. But never 100 times out of 100. That's why investors diversify or otherwise insure themselves against catastrophe. It will cost them in performance, but it assures that if the ship sinks, they won't go down with it.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
