<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-How to Stay Cool in a Hot Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-How to Stay Cool in a Hot Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Studying the financials can reveal a stock about to stumble<p>By Clint Willis<p>Last February 26, shares of <a name="NASD:BSST"></a><b>Baby Superstore</b> fell 29 percent when the fast-growing retailer alerted analysts that it would miss its targets for the year just ended. The culprit, the company said, was a problem in the financial report it had issued in November. The company had understated expenses and overstated its cash on hand. When it finally reported results for the 12 months ended January 1996, earnings (at $11.7 million) trailed Wall Street's hopes by about 14 percent.<p>Wall Street analysts were blindsided by the announcement. Six of the eight who covered the stock had recommended it as a buy in January. But the trouble at Baby Superstore (Nasdaq: BSST) shouldn't have been a total surprise. A study of the public financial documents would have shown a company under pressure: As competition forced Baby Superstore to lower prices, its gross profit margins fell, from 36.8 percent in January 1991 to 28.2 percent in January 1996. <p>In a market where investors seem to think that every stock is destined to hit a new high tomorrow, it's hard for analysts and individual investors to remain focused on the figures that can signal potential trouble at a company. "When stock prices are rising, people don't question things as much as they ordinarily would," says Jack Ciesielski, owner of the Analysts' Accounting Observer, a Baltimore advisory service. "Investors aren't as diligent as they were two years ago__and as a result, there are going to be some big disappointments," says Howard Schilit, author of Financial Shenanigans. In the last quarter of 1995 and the first quarter of 1996, the stocks of companies such as <a name="NYSE:KM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10830"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kmart</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CNF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10393"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Consolidated Freightways</b></a>, <a name="NASD:CRUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cirrus Logic</b></a>, <a name="NASD:JUNO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13877"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Juno Lighting</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MTEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14149"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mobile Telecommunications Technologies</b></a>, <a name="NASD:PSIX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43405"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PSI Net</b></a>, System Software Associates, and <a name="AMEX:THP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14886"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Thermo Power</b></a> have all surprised Wall Street by reporting disappointing earnings, and all their stocks have declined.<p>As investors bid up prices for companies that promise above-average growth, the risk increases. "Some corporate managers feel they have to deliver the right numbers," says Hugh Evans, an analyst at T. Rowe Price in Baltimore. "It's a very dangerous situation." 
It doesn't take an accounting degree to identify when corporate earnings are likely to slip. Getting access to the relevant numbers from a company's annual 10-Ks and quarterly 10-Qs (the more detailed versions of the familiar annual and quarterly corporate reports) is easy: Just call the company's investor-relations oce. The trick lies in knowing which numbers to study and how to put them together. We enlisted 20 financial analysts to guide the way; they suggested zeroing in on five areas. <p>Inventories. A rising inventory (the supply of unsold goods that a company keeps on hand to fill customer orders) can be a positive sign. It could mean a company is planning to meet growing customer demand for its products. But a growing mountain of goods in the warehouse could also signal that a company can't sell its products. Take <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> (Nasdaq: AAPL). In September 1994, the company built up inventory in expectation of brisk sales for the Christmas season. But computer stockpiles remained sky-high at the end of December__and continued to rise in 1995. Price slashing by competitors had cut into Apple's sales, and many potential Apple buyers were waiting to check out computers with the Windows 95 operating system. Apple's stock peaked on June 21, 1995, at $49.375; it recently traded at $23. <p>To tell the difference between a company with healthy inventory growth and one that's setting the stage for a gigantic garage sale, track a company's inventory-to-sales ratio. Find the inventory figures on the 10-Q's consolidated balance sheets and the sales figures on the income statement. To calculate the ratio, divide the value of the company's inventory by the dollar amount of its sales for the quarter. Do the same for the comparable quarter of the previous year. An acceptable inventory-to-sales ratio varies across industries, but by comparing the ratio from year to year, an investor can spot a company with a growing burden of unsold merchandise. Apple was clearly in trouble last year: Its inventory-to-sales ratio was higher than those of its rivals__and rising fast. 
It climbed from 68 percent at the end of 1994 to 81 percent on June 30, 1995, just before the stock began its slide. <p>Accounts receivable. Receivables, found on the balance sheets, represent the money a company is owed for products or services it has sold. "If a company's accounts receivable are growing faster than sales, there's probably a down quarter ahead," says David Tice, a Dallas money manager who runs the Prudent Bear Fund. It's easy to see why. If receivables have grown 50 percent from the previous quarter and sales only 5 percent, that might suggest a company is so anxious to sell its goods that it's extending the deadlines for receiving payment in order to keep its product moving out the door. Customers who may be buying more than they really need take a long time to reorder. Even worse, the firm might be recording sales when there's still a chance customers will return their purchases for refunds.<p>In late 1994, <a name="NASD:APCC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12609"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Power Conversion</b></a> (Nasdaq: APCC), a maker of backup PC power supplies, clearly suffered from the first problem. Its sales had climbed 51 percent in 1994, but receivables had risen 81 percent, a sign that in the face of rivals like <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>, American Power Conversion was offering customers more-lenient payment schedules. The stock fell from its peak of $30 in March 1994 to $10.625 in April 1996 <p>Cash flow. This figure shows the net flow of real money into or out of the firm. Unlike earnings or profits, cash flow factors out the effects of paper debits (such as depreciation) that get charged against earnings but don't require the company to spend actual dollars. It also reflects the costs of building a new plant or buying equipment at the time of the expenditure rather than charging them against future earnings. Cash flow shows if a company is generating dollars that can be used for building the business or if it's devouring funds that must be raised from outside sources. <p>Compare cash flow from operations, which appears on the 10-K and 10-Q statements of cash flow, to net income at the bottom of the income statement. "If a company's net income is rising but its cash flow is falling, you don't want to invest in it," Schilit says. If the firm isn't increasing cash flow, it will eventually have trouble financing growth.<p><a name="NASD:TLXN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14901"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Telxon</b></a> (Nasdaq: TLXN), which makes portable and interactive computer systems, reported profits of $7 million for the second half of 1995, but cash flow from operations was negative $56 million. A closer look reveals that Telxon was piling up inventory and receivables. "If the cash-flow problem persists, they'll need an infusion from other sources," says Schilit.<p>Expenses. Accounting rules give companies the choice of 
expensing a cost (charging it against this year's profits) or capitalizing it (charging it against future profits). Expenses are recorded on the income statement. Capitalizing costs that should be expensed can be seductive. Say a company spends $1 million in 1996 on direct mail to find subscribers to its on-line service. It could record that $1 million as an expense and charge it all against current earnings, or it could argue that this $1 million should be capitalized, since it was spent to acquire future revenue. Spreading the $1 million over a number of years increases current earnings.<p><a name="NASD:BARE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Barefoot</b></a> (Nasdaq: BARE), a lawn-care company in Worthington, Ohio, with $93.4 million in 1995 sales, capitalized its direct-mail expenses until recently. Reportedly after discussions with the SEC, Barefoot changed its accounting methods this year to record those expenses as current costs. That added over $3 million to 1995 costs, reducing the firm's profit from 96 cents a share to 84 cents. The stock recently traded at $10, off a high of $15 last August.<p>Profit margins. Profit margins reveal how much money the company makes on a dollar of sales. Profit margins can be stated in many ways. Gross profit, for example, is total sales minus the cost of goods sold, while net profit is sales minus the cost of goods sold, general and administrative costs, interest, and taxes.
Falling gross margins are often bad. <a name="NYSE:RBD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rubbermaid</b></a> (NYSE: RBD), a maker of plastic and rubber products, saw its gross margin drop (from 34 percent in late 1993 to 29 percent in 1995) as the cost of resins it used rose. The stock fell from $37.125 in late 1993 to $27.75 recently.<p>When gross profits fall, net profits commonly go with them. When they don't, look closer. A rising gross margin and falling net margin may even be a positive sign, indicating that a company is investing in the future by adding to general and administrative costs in order to build a sales force. But investors should be wary when the gross margin is falling and the net is rising. "There are a lot more costs that go into net profit__such as taxes and research-and-development costs__that they can play with to make the net look good," says Tice. <p>In short, the bottom line on a company's income statement__the one that reports its profits__isn't always the final word on a company's prospects. Investors who remember that fact stand a good chance of being on the sidelines the next time Wall Street takes a company out back and shoots it for missing an earnings estimate.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/7pages.gif"><br>About 7 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:BSST">Baby Superstore</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:KM">Kmart Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:CNF">Consolidated Freightways, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:CRUS">Cirrus Logic, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:JUNO">Juno Lighting, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:MTEL">Mobile Telecommunication Technologies Corp.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:PSIX">PSINet, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#AMEX:THP">Thermo Power Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:AAPL">Apple Computer, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:APCC">American Power Conversion Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:HWP">Hewlett-Packard Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:TLXN">Telxon Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:BARE">Barefoot Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:RBD">Rubbermaid Incorporated</a><br>

