	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Gauging the Price of Growth</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Gauging the Price of Growth</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Gauging the Price of Growth</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> GAUGING THE PRICE OF GROWTH <p>Companies with speedy earnings increases often can't go the distance <p> By Jonathan Butler  May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> GAUGING THE PRICE OF GROWTH <p>Companies with speedy earnings increases often can't go the distance <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> Which of these two  growth stocks is a better investment: drug giant <a name="NYSE:PFE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11175"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pfizer</b></a> or <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>, a maker of hardware that supports the Internet?  <p> The decision is a no-brainer, according to one time-honored Wall Street rule of thumb. When it comes to calculating a reasonable price for a growth stock, the rule goes, look for a stock that's trading at a price-to-earnings ratio lower than the rate of growth in the company's earnings. Pfizer recently traded at a price-to-earnings ratio of 27 times earnings per share, but the company's earnings grew just 18 percent in 1995. So the stock is selling at a premium of roughly 50 percent to its earnings growth rate. Cisco showed a much higher price-to-earnings ratio of 41, but the computer company's earnings rose 45 percent last year. It's reasonably priced for a stock growing so spectacularly. Buy Cisco, shun Pfizer. What could be simpler?   <p> Nothing, and that's exactly the problem. When it comes to determining the value of fast-growing, high-p/e stocks, the traditional wisdom can lead investors astray by steering them into high-risk stocks and away from dependable growers. "The rule of thumb becomes  particularly irrational at higher rates" of growth, says Chris Davis, co-manager of the <a name="FUND:NYVTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NYVTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Davis New York Venture Fund</b></a> and <a name="FUND:SLASX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SLASX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Selected American Shares</b></a>.   <p> In trying to figure out if a stock is a bargain or an overpriced bauble, most investors rightly start with the p/e ratio and the rate of earnings growth. The p/e ratio shows how much the market is willing to pay for one dollar of past earnings. (The ratiois calculated by dividing the 12 months' trailing earnings per share into the current stock price.)  <p> Not all stocks trade at the same p/e ratio, however, because the market anticipates growth, too. Two stocks with earnings of one dollar per share over the past 12 months might trade at p/e ratios of 12 and 20, respectively, because the market is expecting the second company to increase earnings much faster than the first. In general, the faster the earnings growth, the more investors are willing to pay for a stock.  <p> The tough question is, how much more is too much?  <p> It's impossible to provide an answer without understanding why a share of stock is worth anything at all. To some investors, a stock certificate is simply a lottery ticket, says Davis. As long as some other investor might be willing to pay more tomorrow, the true worth of a share never troubles them.  <p> But stock certificates represent an ownership stake in a real business. The value of that stake depends on many factorsÐhow well the managers keep costs under control, how well they anticipate demand, and more. But to an investor in a growth company, nothing is more important than the company's ability to increase earnings over the long term. "The question that no one asks is how long the current growth rate is sustainable," says Davis.  <p> Imagine that instead of buying a share of stock an investor pays $1 million for a business that produces earnings of $33,333 a year. The investor is paying a p/e ratio of 30 for that income. <p> Is this a wise investment? That depends on how fast the business can increase its earnings and how long it can sustain them. To evaluate this deal, investors should also compare it to what could be earned by putting the money into other businesses or a low-risk security such as a government bond. And because a dollar next year is worth less than a dollar today, the investor must also adjust these estimates to reflect inflation.  <p> It's possible to apply this thinking to a share of stock. Consider a $30 stock with earnings of one dollar a share and a growth rate of 30 percent a year. In unadjusted terms, it would take nine years for the stock to generate earnings that add up to$30. But when one takes inflation and the potential return on alternative investments into account, this stock would actually have to maintain its annual 30 percent growth rate for more than13 years before the investor could collect the equivalent of his original $30 in profit.  <p> "The bet that a company can continue to grow at 30 percent is not a winning bet on average," says John Spears, a general partner at Tweedy, Browne, a New York money-management firm. According to Compustat, Standard & Poor's Denver-based statistics division, not one company managed to do this for all of the past 13 years. Over time, growth rates tend to revert to the mean. Even great companies have trouble maintaining rapid earnings growth as they get larger.  <p> This fact will ultimately be reflected in a stock's p/e. A 1978 study by William Beaver and Dale Morse in Financial Analysts Journal shows that the highest p/e's fall by more than one-half over one year and by roughly two-thirds over two years. So the chance of picking a high-p/e stock that can maintain its growth rate over the long term is pretty slim.  <p> Worse yet, when the earnings growth of a high-p/e stock falls, the market often trounces the p/e it's willing to pay. Look at what happened to the stock of <a name="NYSE:GIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15718"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Instrument</b></a>, a maker of cable-TV boxes. In 1993, its earnings leaped from a deficit of 42 cents a share to a profit of 74 cents a share, propelling the stock price from a low of $5.75 in 1992 to a high of $30.13 in 1993 and a p/e of 56. Earnings more than doubled in 1994, but the rise in stock price slowed as the p/e contracted to reflect concern that future earnings would be weak. When earnings subsequently fell short of analysts' expectations by a few cents a share in the third quarter of 1995, the p/e and the stock price plummeted. The investor who piled in when the stock traded at $30.13 with a p/e of 56 was left holding a stock worth less than $20.  <p> How does this analysis help an investor choose between Cisco and Pfizer? An investor who buys a share of Pfizer at the recent p/e of 27 is buying a piece of a business that will justify its current price after roughly 18 years of 18 percent growth. Meanwhile,at a 45 percent growth rate, it will take a share of Cisco only about a decade to justify its recent price.   <p> But how likely is it that Cisco will grow at 45 percent for that long? With $3.3 billion in projected fiscal 1996 sales, Cisco will be about the same size in June 1996 that <a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems</b></a>, another well-managed computer maker, was in 1991. Sun increased earnings 18 percent a year over the next four years, an impressive achievement for such a big company. If Cisco matches that rate instead of growing at 45 percent a year, it would take about 25 years to justify the current priceÐsignificantly longer than it would take Pfizer.  <p> All this evidence doesn't mean it's impossible to make money buying high-p/e stocksÐfund families such as Twentieth Century (800-345-2021), AIM (800-347-4246), and PBHG (800-433-0051) have been doing it successfully for years. But these funds don't buy and hold. Instead, they sell as soon as the legions of number crunchers they employ spot the first sign of a slow down in the earnings growth rate.   <p> No individual investor can match these funds' data bases of earnings information or pay as little to move in and out of the market. "This approach is too risky to try with only two or three stocksÐthere are too many bombs out there. If you're trying to make money, you should buy a fund," says Stephen Barney, a senior vice presidentat Twentieth Century.  <p> Alternatively, an investor can buy and hold growth stocks that have more modest expectations and less stratospheric price tags. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
