	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Finding the Buys in Retail Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Finding the Buys in Retail Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> FINDING THE BUYS IN RETAIL STOCKS <p>The "little things" will ultimately determine which chains will thrive  <p> By Pamela J. Black  <p> Even the giants are stumbling. In early January, when <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>, the country's leading retailer, announced a slow down in fourth-quarter earnings after 99 successive quarters of increasing earnings, it was emblematic of how tough the retailing terrain has become. Jamesway, <a name="NYSE:CLD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12896"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caldor</b></a>,<a name="NYSE:BLE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11253"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b> Bradlees</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:EBS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10504"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Edison Brothers</b></a>, all major retail chains, filed for bankruptcy protection in 1995. Analysts estimate that the bad times aren't over, either: The huge shakeout may have at least two more years to run.  <p> That makes this a good time for patient investors to go shopping for retail stocks. Picking the right ones, however, will take a discriminating eye; it's more important than ever to understand what makes and breaks these companies.   <p> Why did an entire industry go bad at once? Blame it on the excesses of the late 1970s and 1980s. Shopping seemed to be the recreational sport of choice. Consumers, especially baby boomers in their peak spending years, were willing to build up credit-card debt to stay in the game. Retailers responded with a giant building spree, adding hundreds of stores and introducing new concepts such as the superstore and the category killer. Retailer after retailer showed stunning growth in sales.  <p> The recession of 1990 sobered up a mall-happy populace: Suddenly, saving for retirement and children's college funds became more important than keeping up with the latest merchandising fad. Retailers, though, were slow to catch on. Their sales growth slowed from 7 percent a year in the1980s to 4.5 percent in 1995, but companies continued to expand at a breakneck pace, often in marginal locations or in the face of intense competition. Some continued to open new stores even as they slouched toward bankruptcy. For example, Bradlees, a northeastern discount chain now in Chapter 11, opened ten new stores in 1994.   <p> In 1996 investing in retailers that previously increased sales by expanding is out and buying stock in companies that earn high profits on their sales is in. In the current environment, those retailers that stick by the business basics will ultimately benefitas the competition falls by the wayside. There is no special trick to it. "Retailing just comes down to how well you execute," says A. G. Edwards & Sons analyst Donald Spindel.  <p> To see what a difference execution can make, look at two department-store companies, J. C. Penney ($21 billion in sales) and May Department Stores ($11 billion in sales). Both have around $800 million in net profitsÐwhich makes May's profit margin 6.4 percent versus 4.1 percent for J. C. Penney. Why is May more profitable? Inventory turns over slightly faster at May, 3.8 versus 3.7 times a year, and May's expenses are significantly lower: 19.8 percent of sales versus 23.8 percent for Penney's. The result for investors: In1995, May's earnings per share rose 7.4 percent, while Penney's fell 17.8 percent.  <p> An investor can actually tell a lot about how well a company executes by visiting its stores. Are a wide range of quality goods attractively displayed and reasonably priced? Are the employees helpful and knowledgeable about the merchandise? Is the store conveniently located and easy to get in and out of? Execution is "a lot of little things like listening to the customers," says Spindel.  <p> Contrast the experience of visiting two well-known category killers. <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a> has become the country's largest home-improvement retailer in part because the company hires employees skilled in home-repair and building projects. "The one thing that clearly sets Home Depot apart is the level of service it provides," says David Presson, an analyst at Edward Jones in St. Louis. "It doesn't try to sell a product but to build a relationship with customers, and that will give the company a clear advantage." With 408 stores in 31 states, Home Depot has a good shot at increasing its 12 percent share of the $134 billion home-improvement market to 25 or even 30 percent by the turn of the century, Presson believes. He expects earnings to continue growing at a pace of 20 to 25 percent a year.  <p> On the other hand, at <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a>, the country's leading toy retailer, cold, undifferentiated aisles stuffed with a seemingly random and bewildering selection of products discourage return visits. Despite carrying some 4,000 kinds of toys, storesÐoften unbeknownst to their employeesÐare out of some products. "More than anything else they need to overhaul the look and design of their stores," says A. G. Edwards analyst Greg Simpson. "The warehouse look they were using in the '70s and '80s doesn't work anymore." The company's net profits fell 21.6 percent last year, and earnings per share dropped 18.4 percent, from $1.85 in 1994 to $1.51 in 1995.  <p> A retailer's ability to execute also shows up clearly in a company's financial statements. For example, last year <a name="NYSE:ANN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14959"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ann Taylor</b></a> piled on merchandise to fill new stores. "They were building inventory, and then sales slowed," says Oppenheimer analyst Dorothy Lakner. At the same time, shoppers were snubbing the fashions at existing stores. A statistic called same-store sales, which segregates the sales at stores that have been open for a year or longer from total sales, eloquently captures that story. After climbing an impressive 22 percent in 1994, same-store sales fell 13.8 percent in 1995. To move all that inventory, Ann Taylor had to cut prices. Gross margins consequently dropped 8.5 percent, and net income fell by $32.6 million. Earnings per shareÐwhich had doubled to $1.40 in 1994Ðtumbled to negative four cents in 1995. <p> Meanwhile, the <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a> raised net profits by 10.5 percent from 1994 to 1995 by "running the business with very lean inventory," says Lakner. That solid execution is reflected in a figure called inventory turnover, which measures the number of times a company fills its shelves with merchandise, sells it all, and then re-stocks each year. The Gap's inventory turnovers have been rising for the past four years to 6.3 times in 1995, according to estimates by Value Line, while Ann Taylor's have fallen to 4.4. Add in the Gap's new Old Navy chain and it's easy to see why Gap stock has rallied from a low of $30.13 in 1995 to $56.75 on March 13. <p> But even managing inventory so that merchandise moves won't make a retailer profitable if the cost of buying and selling those goods is too high. "Sales figures can be misleading," says analyst Presson. "The most important thing is if the company is generating cash flow above and beyond its expenses."   <p> That's why investors should look at a figure called selling, general, and administration (SG&A) costs. For example, even though <a name="NYSE:KM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10830"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kmart's</b></a> same-store sales increased 5.5 percent in December of1995 versus only 1.1 percent for Wal-Mart's, Kmart went from a profit of $1.04 billion in 1994 to a deficit of $490 million last year, while Wal-Mart increased profits from $2.68 billion to $2.74 billion.  <p> To see one reason why this happened, look at SG&A as a percentage of sales at the two chains. Wal-Mart has an SG&A of 15.59 percent compared with 21.97 percent for Kmart. This means it costs Wal-Mart just $15.59 in salaries and overhead to produce every $100 of sales versus $21.97 at Kmart. "That gives Wal-Mart a great pricing advantage," says Presson. "Kmart can't undersell that without losing money."  <p> From its start, Wal-Mart "offered low prices and good service,and paid attention to all aspects of retailing; they really watched every penny," says A. G. Edwards' Spindel. "They're more efficientat distribution and information systems. And now that they're so large they are able to buy extremely well."  <p> But with 2,000 stores in the U.S., 131 in Canada, and 126 in Mexico, Wal-Mart is now so bigÐsales recently hit $94 billionÐthat it probably can't maintain its historic 20 percent growth rate. Its fourth-quarter drop in earnings is a sure sign it "suffers from the law of large numbers," says Prudential analyst Wayne Hood. "It's difficult to grow off that base."  <p> In an effort to keep growing, though, Wal-Mart management is tackling a new market with supercenters that sell groceries as well as general merchandise. Wal-Mart plans to add 100 new supercenters this year to the 245 it currently operates. While food is a low-margin business, the hope is that it will pull in enough new customers to increase sales of Wal-Mart's more lucrative general merchandise. So far, according to Spindel, this has worked. Spindel points out that Wal-Mart currently has about 45 percent of the discount market, which is roughly a $185 billion industry, but the grocery business is a $400 billion market, and the largest company in that industry has only a 6 percent share of it. Presson and Spindel therefore think Wal-Mart can increase earnings 10 to 15 percent annually for the next three to five yearsÐbelow the company's historic 20 percent rate, but still higher than the growth rate for the average company in the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock IndexÐwhich Presson calculates at 6 to 7 percent annually.  <p> That's the plan anyway. Now it's up to Wal-Mart, just like anyother retailer in this tough environment, to execute.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS:  Retail Industry, Stock Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
