	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Bonds Away!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bonds Away!</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Bonds Away!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Columns  <p>  <p>BONDS AWAY!  <p> Move aside coupon clippers. Bondholders are finding aggressive ways to make serious money.  <p>  <p>By Susan Lee  <p>  <p>Bonds are boring. bonds are for fuddy-duddies. Bonds are dead!  <p> Long live bonds!  <p> Huh?  <p> Many people--including me--look at bonds for risk control and current income; we plunk them into our portfolios and then forget about them. That's quite okay, but we are missing an opportunity for optimizing. Well, here's a strategy that will zip us out of the fuddy-duddy category. It's called investing for total return, and it can be at least as rewarding as stocks and just as exciting.  <p> Total return has two components: interest, or what the coupon pays, and any appreciation or depreciation in the price of the bond. If you have a bond paying a coupon rate of 3 percent a year and if the price of that bond goes from $10,000 to $11,000 over a year, for a gain of 10 percent, then your total returnis 13 percent.   <p> Of course, if the price falls from $10,000 to $9,000, that is a price depreciation of 10 percent. You would still have $300 from the interest payment, but your total return would be negative7 percent. (To be absolutely accurate, you should subtract transaction costs and taxes from the total return. And to be academically accurate, you should also subtract any inflation to get real total return.)  <p> Last year, when long-term rates fell 2 percent, the total return on 30-year Treasurys was 34 percent. On investment-grade corporates,total return averaged 22 percent. Not bad.  <p> A total-return strategy requires two things. First, you have to start looking at bonds more like they were stocks and less like, well, bonds. Just as dividend payments are not the only reason to buy stocks, so with bonds. You have to buy them with an eye to price changes. That means you should evaluate the potential for the price to go up--or down. The good news here, of course,is that changes in bond prices are bounded. If you let the bond's maturity run out, the price returns to par--its face value. That's bad if you allowed a big, fat run-up in the value to go unrealized, but good if you experienced a big, fat loss in value. And that brings me to the second key to the total-return strategy: Simply put, you have to be prepared to trade your bonds to realize gains--to look at bonds not as security but as an opportunity.  <p> As Eduardo Haim of E H Capital Group in New York says, "The point is to buy bonds that really produce for you--where the after-tax yield is high enough to provide a cushion against rising interest rates and where you have the potential of price appreciation." <p> So where can you go to get higher-yielding, price-popping potential in a market where interest rates are already pretty low? One suggestion is to focus on out-of-the-way markets--and really increase the thrills-and-chills factor.   <p> Take, for instance, the darkest side of a dark market--distressed securities. These bonds lurk on the bottom of the junk market. They either aren't paying interest or are about to stop paying it, because the issuers are in or are sliding into bankruptcy.These bonds are cheap, trading well below par. When the issuing company comes out of bankruptcy, however, there will be a recapitalization. Bondholders will be able to sell their bonds or convert the minto equity. In other words, the action comes from price appreciation. If the issuer recovers, there is a swift price kicker.  <p> Martin Sass of M. D. Sass Investors Services in New York has$400 million in distressed securities. "We love them," he says. He buys bonds of firms that have a strong core business but are either just going into or emerging from bankruptcy. "There are temporary, dramatic dislocations in this market because of the panic when a firm defaults," says Sass. "I can buy a dollar for 30 cents."  <p> The market in foreign bonds is another out-of-the-way place--way out, though, which means investing in new emerging-markets countries, not Western European or established emerging-markets countries. Lisa Hess of Zesiger Capital Group in New York likes Polish and Czech bonds. She expects Polish bonds to give an annual total return of 20.5 percent in local currency and 10 percent in dollars,and Czech bonds to deliver 10 to 11 percent in dollars.  <p> A nifty total-return strategy can also be built around convertible bonds. These are securities that pay interest like bonds but are convertible into stocks at a price--usually much higher than current market value--promised by the issuing company. As the stock price rises, approaching the conversion price, the value of the bond increases. Hess likes convertibles issued by small companies, because she expects small caps to out perform the market, and while she waits for that price appreciation, she receives current income in interest payments--something you might not get from small-cap stocks, which usually don't pay dividends.  <p> And finally, Fred Quirsfeld, senior portfolio manager for IDS Mutual Fund Group in Minneapolis, offers the following total-return strategy for bond funds. Put 60 percent of your bond money in a fund with shorter or "controlled" duration (duration is a wayof re-adjusting the maturity date to account for the size andtiming of cash flows--the shorter the duration, the less volatility).For example, suppose you invest in mortgage-backed securities with a duration of 3.5 years. "Given the flattish yield curve [short-term yields are close to long-term yields], you will get competitive returns with good credit--they're backed by the U.S. government--and stability," says Quirsfeld. Then combine that position with 20 percent in junk bonds and 20 percent in global bonds--two more-volatile sectors that could give you double-digit returns from both current income and price appreciation and that will diversify your exposure.  <p> The trick in total-return investing is, of course, to find bonds whose risk-return trade-off favors return. That means staying away from popular securities, where information is so good and so accessible that pricing is efficient.  <p> One place not to look would be the bonds in the various bond indexes, such as the <a name="NYSE:LEH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41936"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lehman Brothers</b></a> T-Bond Index, the Ryan Labs Treasury Composite, and the Salomon Brothers Broad Investment-Grade Bond Index. Many players feel that big institutional bond manager sare "closet indexers," so the demand for these securities is large and constant, keeping upward pressure on prices.  <p> Before you decide to add some thrills and chills to your bond portfolio, however, consider the risks--and I do mean risks.The standard array applies in capital letters. Distressed bonds,for example, are particularly subject to credit risk--the possibility that bondholders will never get back their principal--especially if the economy goes into a recession; foreign bonds are sensitive to currency and political risk; and even high-yielding bonds are, at some point, vulnerable to interest-rate risk.  <p> There are also some barriers to investing. Money, for example.If you are buying individual bonds instead of fooling around with bond funds, it takes at least a half million dollars to get good diversification. And transaction costs can be killers; typically, buying bonds is a lot more expensive than buying stocks.  <p> Also, this stuff is not for amateurs. Every bond manager I talked with agreed with Eduardo Haim, who said, "I know this sounds self-serving, but it's almost impossible for nonprofessionals to do well on their own." This is one part of your portfolio you should strongly consider running through a professional manager. <p> And speaking of portfolios, if you have allocated a lump of money to bonds as a sleep-at-night precaution, don't touch it. Total-return ploys belong in the high-risk lump, along with, or instead of, those nifty micro-cap stocks your brother-in-law tipped to you.   <p> As Kevin Johnson of Aronson + Partners, a money-management firm based in Philadelphia, points out, "It's a question of degree and kind. On the degree side, there's a lot more money to be made on bonds that have a double-digit total-return potential, but on the kind side, you are taking on an enormous amount of risk."  <p> In other words, fasten your seat belts. You could be in for a bumpy ride.  <p> Contributing editor Susan Lee writes "Mind Your Own Business" monthly. She is an economist and author of Hands Off! Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health, just published by Simon & Schuster. E-mail her at sclee12@aol.com.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Global Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

