<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-So You Think You're Diversified?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-So You Think You're Diversified?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A new technique called style analysis shows more detail about how a fund earns its returns  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> Smart investors know that diversification can not only enhance the safety of a portfolio but also improve its performance. Example: The best growth-and-income fund of 1990, <a name="FUND:GATEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GATEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gateway Index Plus</b></a> earned a total return of 9.3 percent over the past five years. But an investor who shared the same bet among the top three growth-and-income funds of 1990 --  Gateway, <a name="FUND:AAGFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AAGFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AIM Charter</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:CAPEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CAPEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Capital Exchange</b></a>--  would have earned a return of 13.5 percent annually over the past five years.  <p> Something, though, has gone wrong with the methods that many investors rely on to diversify fund portfolios.   <p> Consider inves– tors A and B. Investor A uses the traditional approach, attempting to diversify by buying funds from three of the categories listed in The Wall Street Journal or one of the mutual-fund newsletters. So A purchases a growth fund, <a name="FUND:BENOX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BENOX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berger100</b></a>; a growth-and-income fund, <a name="FUND:OMSBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OMSBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oppenheimer Main Street Income& Growth</b></a>; and a world-stock fund, <a name="FUND:SMCWX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SMCWX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Smallcap World Fund</b></a>. Investor B knows nothing about diversification and  buys three funds listed in the growth category by Morningstar Mutual Funds: <a name="FUND:BCHYX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BCHYX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Benham Equity Growth</b></a>, <a name="FUND:BRWIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BRWIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Brandywine</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:FDVLX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FDVLX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Value</b></a>.   <p> It sounds crazy, but investor A is actually less diversified than investor B. According to data from Morningstar, investor A's three funds behave like the Russell 2000, an index of small-company stocks. Investor B's three growth funds differ distinctly from one another: One is correlated with a large-company index, another with a small-company index, and the third with a foreign index.  <p> "The labels applied to mutual funds are generally misleading, "says Robert Ludwig, director of investment strategy at SEI Asset Management Group, a financial-services firm in Wayne, Pennsylvania."They don't really explain what a fund does."  <p> Some fund companies --  knowing that investors measure a fund against its peers in a category --  mislabel funds, calling a growth fund a growth-and-income fund, for instance, so that it's ranked in a category in which it's likely to rise to the top during some periods. <p>But even the categories created by mutual-fund data providers, such as Lipper Analytical Services and Morningstar, can cause confusion. The data providers begin with the funds' descriptions of themselves and then adjust each description after examining the portfolios funds report to the Securities and Exchange Commission twice a year. A fund that describes itself as growth and income, for example, might be moved into the growth category after ananalyst studies such  portfolio fundamentals as price-to- earnings ratios.  <p> Funds, however, report their portfolios just twice a year, so fund analysts get only a snapshot of what the fund held on 2 days out of 365. And few funds restrict their holdings to just one category. A fund in the domestic small-cap group, for example, might own a few big-company stocks and some foreign securities, too. Yet the system forces that fund into just one of these categories. And some investment strategies, oddly, aren't represented at all. Morningstar, for example, doesn't include a value classification among its investment objectives, even though there are hundreds of value-oriented funds.  <p> "When you take a growth fund that may really be a small-cap fund and put it together with an equity-income fund that may have high-yield bonds in it, and you throw in a portfolio with a small-company fund that actually is  a small-company growth fund, you end up with things that you probably did not want to own," says Ludwig.  <p> The solution: Diversify a portfolio based on style. Most fundmanagers have a process of investing that leads them to pick certain kinds of securities. That's their style.  <p> Three factors --  growth, value, and company size --  determine a fund manager's technique. Growth managers, for example, buy stocks in companies because the companies' earnings are growing rapidly. Value managers are bargain hunters, seeking stocks with low prices compared with the value of the underlying companies. Finally, some fund managers specialize in small companies, and others buy large ones.  <p> A style may seem as vague and hard to define as a category, but thanks to Nobel Prize–winning economist William Sharpe, investors can now apply precise techniques to reveal a fund's style. In a 1992 water shed article in the scholarly Journal of Portfolio Management, Sharpe presented evidence that 85 percent to 90 percent of a fund portfolio's returns is determined by style. Just 10 percent to 15 percent of returns, he found, is attributable to securities selection. In other words, it matters more that a fund has chosen to focus on small-cap value stocks than it does which small-cap value stocks it buys.   <p> Sharpe developed software that identifies the investment styles from fund returns. Basically, his techniques look at the way a fund performs month to month --  not at its semi-annual reports--  and tries to match its performance to that of two or more indexes, such as the Russell 2000 for small-cap stocks or the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index for large-cap stocks. The mix of indexes that best matches a fund's performance defines its style.  <p> Creating a portfolio based on this  type of analysis "gives you a greater degree of precision so you can be sure the funds you invest in are different from each other," explains Andrew Rudd, chairman of BARRA, a Berkeley, California, investment-software firm. "You'll be able to construct portfolios that are better diversified."   <p> The fund universe can be divided into six basic styles. Domestic-stock funds account for four: small-cap growth, large-cap growth, small-cap value, and large-cap value. Foreign funds and fixed-income funds are the other two styles. Each has distinctly different characteristics. <p> "Style investing is accepted by academia as a useful way to create a portfolio, and it's been the investment mode for professional money managers for years," says Bob Barry, a New Jersey investment adviser. "Now it's starting to be used by advisers to create fund portfolios for wealthy clients." These advisers often employ style-analysis software that sells for $5,000 to $15,000. (See the sidebar below for more on style-analysis software, including one package designed for individual investors.)  <p> But individual investors can also design a style-based portfolio or check the styles of an existing portfolio without software.Two pieces of data from Morningstar Mutual Funds, a biweekly newsletter available at most libraries, are all an investor needs. <p> Morningstar provides a "style box" on approximately 1,500 stock and bond funds. This box shows if a fund is oriented toward small-,large-, or medium-sized companies and if its style is growth, value, or a blend of the two. Morningstar also provides historical information, showing how consistently a fund has adhered to its style.  <p> The style box has some limitations. A fund that invests only in medium-sized companies, for instance, will be listed in the style box as owning medium-sized stocks. But so will a fund that invests equal amounts in small-, medium-, and large-cap stocks.  <p> Morningstar's "Best Fit Index" will help investors get a more precise style reading. Morningstar compares funds to 27 different equity and fixed-income indexes and lists the index a fund most closely resembles --  its best fit. Statisticians call this correlation "R-squared." On a scale from 1 to 100, if a fund has an R-squared of 75 or more versus an index, then it is closely correlated to that index.   <p> For example, Smallcap World Fund is categorized by Morningstar as a world-stock fund, but has an R-squared of 85 against the Russell 2000, a domestic index of small companies. According to Morningstar's December 8, 1995, issue, Smallcap World's top holdings include <a name="NASD:FPNX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15805"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Pacific</b></a>, <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>, and <a name="NASD:WCLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10584"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wisconsin Central Transport</b></a>. An investor who buys Smallcap for foreign diversification is in for a surprise.   <p> An investor seeking a small-cap fund would look for an R-squared of 75 or more compared with the Russell 2000. An investor seeking a large-cap fund would look for a high R-squared versus the S&P 500. Foreign-stock funds will have a high R-squared versus the <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> Europe Austral-Asia and Far East Index (EAFE) or any other diversified foreign-stock index. To get the fixed-income style of investing in a portfolio, look for a fund that has a high R-squared versus a bond index, such as the <a name="NYSE:LEH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41936"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lehman Brothers</b></a> Intermediate Treasury Index.   <p> With the style box and R-squared data, fund investors can create a truly diversified portfolio. After all, if the markets turn disagreeable this year, you won't want to be caught with a portfolio that's not your style.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
