	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Search for World's Highest Yield</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Search for the World's Highest Yields</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Search for World's Highest Yield</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Cover  <p> SEARCH FOR THE WORLD'S HIGHEST YIELDS <p>Who needs penny stocks when some Russian bonds yield 125 percent? Or course, there may be a little risk...  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> It seemed like a simple question: What's the world's highest-yielding fixed-income investment? "You're talking about truly treacherous territory," warned the first investor I talked to, the manager of a $500 million bond fund. "A lot of the people who deal in this stuff are real scum." Then he referred me to two guys he knew who specialized in such deals.  <p> So began a chain of sometimes grudging referrals that would take me from jumbo certificates of deposit to Russian Obligatsii Federalnie Zayomni. Before I was through, I would talk to more than 60 brokers, analysts, and money managers in the United States, Europe, Latin America, and Russia. Some refused to help such investments were too risky, they said even though I swore that my hypothetical investor could afford to lose the $100,000 he had to invest. Others simply didn't know they were content with instruments with lower yields and less risk. But from a few I learned how a person willing to take modest risks can boost the yield on his fixed-income portfolio and I found out just how incredibly high the yields can get for someone with a telephone, a fax machine, and a hypothetical $100,000. (Would you believe 200 percent?) Before I share the results the best of class ineight categories from low-risk CDs to the highest-risk foreign bonds I'll pass along three general lessons I learned about the planet's yielding-est fixed-income investments.   <p> First, the highest-yielding instruments aren't just risky. They are very, very, very risky. Most income investors know about credit risk, the chance that an issuer won't be able to pay. Most investors also know that climbing interest rates will slam an income investment especially one with a long time horizon. Such mishaps can cause prices of plain-vanilla corporate or government bonds to fall 5 percent to 10 percent, as many did in 1994. Big deal. Prices of the highest-yielding issues can easily plummet 50 percent or more if rates rise sharply or even decline to zero when a company (or an entire country) goes belly up. Fraud, revolution, currency devaluations, or government default can render these holdings worthless.   <p> Second, analyzing these deals is very complicated. If you think yield-to-maturity is a knotty concept, wait until you meet your first GKO; that's short for Gosudarstvenii Kratkasrochnii Obligatsii, a Russian security modeled on United States Treasury bills. High-yield investors spend their time calculating debt coverage on junk bonds, hedging for currency risk, and trying to predict how the next swing in interest rates will affect the balance of payments in Ecuador. I don't know how to do those things, I'm not sure that all the brokers, analysts, and fund managers I talked to do, either.   <p> Third, many of these instruments are hard to buy. Broker after broker told me that $100,000 would barely get me a seat at the table. Still, nagging phone calls usually turned up at least one broker who could tell me how to get what I wanted, or at least something close to it. Of course, I didn't know any of this when I began my search. All I had was a hypothetical $100,000 in my pocket and a burning desire to find the world's highest-yielding investments. Here's what I found.  <p> I START CONSERVATIVELY WITH CDs  <p> I started at the low-risk end of the scale, trying to get just a little more yield than that offered by the average one-year bank CD an annual payout of 4.89 percent. I quickly discovered that I could bump that up to 5.26 percent if I could cough up the $90,000 to $100,000 required for a jumbo CD.  <p> I figured I could do better. Some brokerage firms offer a selection of CDs from around the country. The yields are often higher because brokers buy in bulk. BanxQuote, the research division of fixed-income broker MasterFund in Fairfield, New Jersey, cited average yields of 5.18 percent on one-year brokered CDs. You might do a bit better by calling around; start with <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> (800-637-7455), Prudential Securities (212-406-3380), and Smith Barney (212-816-6000).  <p> TIME AS RISK:  ZERO-COUPON BONDS  <p> Bored with 5 percent yields, I turned up the risk meter. Like CDs, zeros are often sold to conservative investors but unlike CDs, they can be astonishingly volatile.   <p> Here's why: Wall Street creates zero-coupon bonds by buying U.S. Treasurys and then separating the coupon (the interest payments) from the principal payment due at the end of a bond's life. So zeros pay no interest; instead, they are sold at deep discounts from their maturity value. For example, by paying $13,470 now for a 14-year Treasury zero, I could receive its $30,000 face value in the year 2009.  <p> But an investor is locked into the zero's imputed interest rate (the interest rate that it would take to make $13,470 grow to $30,000 by 2009) 6.1 percent in the case of my Treasury zero. If inflation climbs and interest rates rise, the projected purchasing power of my future $30,000 will shrink dramatically. I can try to get out of the deal by selling, but I'll take a big hit: The value of a 15-year zero coupon bond will decline roughly 15 percent if interest rates rise just one percentage point.  <p> A DASH OF SAUCE:  OVERSEAS BONDS  <p> Going overseas didn't automatically up the yield, I found unless I was willing to take on currency and political risks. Jean-Marie Eveillard, manager of <a name="FUND:SGENX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SGENX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sogen International Fund</b></a> (212-278-5800),urged me to check out New Zealand government bonds: Apart from sheep and great scenery, the Kiwis have a growing budget surplus. That, of course, means that the bonds carry small risk and bonds, for example, recently paid 7.05 percent.  <p> Things got racier when I spoke to Bill Kaeli of Noyes Partners, a New York investment firm that specializes in South African debt. His pick: BAA3-rated (by Moody's Investor Service) Eskom13.5 percent coupon bonds maturing in 2020, which recently traded on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange at a 14.63 percent yield-to-maturity.Eskom, the fourth-largest producer of electricity in the world, provides 97 percent of South Africa's electric power. "Eskom would be a triple-A credit if it were in the United States," says Kaeli.   <p> But, of course, it isn't. Investors in Eskom take on the risk that South Africa could implode or devalue its currency, therand. Kaeli doesn't think the first is likely, and he expects the rand to bounce back from its recent 28-year low. Noyes Partners (800-433-0129) will arrange the trade for a $10,000 minimum purchase. <p> DEEP DISCOUNT:  CLOSED-END FUNDS  <p> Not many garden-variety mutual funds offer double-digit yields, but things are different in the closed-end arena. Closed-end funds issue only a limited number of shares, which then trade on stock exchanges often, as investor sentiment swings one way or the other, at discounts or premiums to the value of their investments. Out-of-favor funds with big discounts can easily sprout double-digit yields. No fewer than 62 of the 510 closed-end funds on the list I got from Chicago's Morningstar fund-rating service were yielding 10 percent or better as of December 1.  <p> Morningstar's Carolyn Whitfield warned me not to get too excited. "Some people chase yield in these funds, and that's fine," she said. "But make sure the fund isn't using your principal to pay the dividends." Excuse me? It turned out that three of the four highest-yielding funds were doing just that. <a name="FUND:AADBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AADBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Opportunity Income fund</b></a>, for example, showed a 15.7 percent payout. In 1994, manager Worth Bruntjen had almost 50 percent of the fund in mortgage derivatives, which led to a 28 percent decline in the fund's value when interest rates climbed early that year. This year, even though he's trimmed the fund's dividend, he's kept the yield up by making some payments out of the fund's "dividend reserve." For new purchasers, that amounts to a payment from shareholders' principal.   <p> But investors looking for truly higher yields based on higher risk can find them among the closed-end funds invested in emerging markets. Morgan Stanley Emerging Markets Debt fund (13.9 percentyield) offered the highest payout of this bunch. Manager Paul Ghaffari uses borrowed money (loans equal about 9 percent of the fund's assets) to load up on securities issued in places such as Mexico, Morocco, Nigeria, and Bulgaria. That leverage pumps up shareholders' yield as well as their risk.   <p> Like most emerging-markets funds, this one has a short and bloody history: Launched in July 1993, it rose 36 percent that year, fell 26 percent in 1994, and staggered to a 17.6 percent return, early this year the fund was trading at a 0.2 percent discount to its net asset value. But the discount has been as high as 12.8 percent. It seemed like a good time to wait on this one.   <p> TRAWLING FOR TRASH:  JUNK BONDS  <p> It's hard to make a huge score with a diversified portfolio. The same safety in numbers that makes a diversified portfolio an investor's friend prevents a single good call from really raking it in. Hence my next step: Buying junk bonds directly. These are bonds rated below investment grade (Ba or worse by Moody's; BB or lower by S & P). Issued by companies with dinged-up balance sheets, they're the used cars of the bond market.   <p> Like my 1988 Taurus (whose previous owner put 104,000 miles on it), junk bonds are cheap; the average bond rated CCC and CCC+ by Moody's yielded almost nine more percentage points than Treasurys in early November. And like my car, those bonds probably can go the distance though it's never quite sure they will. <p> Analysts Michael Graves and Jeff Aurigemma of Northstar told me I'd need to invest at least $25,000 to get decent commission rates. Graves liked BB-rated California Energy 10.25 percent coupon bonds maturing on January 15, 2004, trading on the New York Bond Exchange and paying a 9.6 percent yield-to-maturity. The firm is the globe's second-largest provider of geothermal power: Basically, it uses volcanoes to boil water. California Energy has a strong presence in the Philippines as well as Indonesia, which Graves called "the Saudi Arabia of geothermal energy. "The bonds' double-digit yield reflects concern about those two countries' stability.   <p> Somewhat superstitious about making money off volcanoes, I asked for another pick. Aurigemma offered me B3-rated Ralphs.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Bond Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
