<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Capitalize on the Cut</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Capitalize on the Cut</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Capitalize on the Cut</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> CAPITALIZE ON THE CUT <p>As the GOP works over the tax code, the most significant change for investors is the capital-gains cut  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> Does it seem like 1986 all over again? Do you sense in the air major changes in the tax law? Well, your instincts are right. For the first time in ten years, elected officials are serious about passing major tax cuts. Although Congress is still battling vehemently over many of the changes, some stand a good chance of surviving the fight--most significantly the long-anticipated, much-debated capital-gains reduction.  <p> In mid-October, Senate Finance Committee Republicans signed off on a $245 billion tax-cut package, which was headed for inclusion in a combined House and Senate omnibus budget reconciliation package. President Clinton threatened to veto the entire package because of his objections to Medicare cuts.   <p> Tax breaks for families with children and for investors, however, are articles of faith among most Republicans in Congress. That's why the tax pros at several Big Six accounting firms who are plugged into the two congressional tax-writing committees say three measures face a good chance of eventually becoming law:a $500-per-child tax credit, an expanded IRA, and a reduction in the capital-gains tax rate.   <p> The most meaningful measure for investors would be the capital-gains cut, which would cost the government an estimated $31.9 billion over five years. The version most likely to pass would let taxpayers deduct 50 percent of their net long-term capital gains when determining taxable income, thereby lowering the top capital-gains rate of28 percent to an effective 19.8 percent. To take advantage of the cut, investors who sell or exchange assets would have to hold on to these appreciable assets for longer than one year. <p> There are still several disagreements between House and Senate tax-writing committees' versions of a capital-gains cut. The Senate version retains the alternative minimum tax, while the House bill does not. The House also wants an indexing component, meaning investors would be taxed only on gains that exceed inflation, which the Senate flatly rejected. What's more, the two tax-writing committees are at odds over the cut's effective date. The House wants it to take effect as of January 1, 1995, while the Senate is pushing for October 13, 1995. Tax experts say, however, the effective date may end up being January 1, 1996.  <p> Few tax rules change as often as the capital-gains tax rules. And few cause as many migraines and busted calculators. To figure out long-term net capital gains, taxpayers must first subtract long-term capital losses and net short-term capital losses. For assets held one year or less, investors must pay a capital-gains tax equal to their ordinary income tax rate, which could shoot to 39.6 percent or even higher with the phase out of exemptions and certain deductions for high-income individuals.   <p> The differences between the two rates produce hefty financial incentives to invest for long-term capital gains. For example, say an investor in the 39.6 percent bracket receives $100,000 in long-term capital gains. Today, that taxpayer would pocket $72,000 after federal taxes. The new law would let him or her take home $80,200.   <p> If the capital-gains cut passes, unexpected taxpayer breaks will flow from it, says Janice Johnson, tax director at the accounting firm Coopers & Lybrand in New York and a member of the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants' Capital Gains Task Force. Johnson says that when taxpayers sit down to do their returns, they'll see that their long-term capital gains deductionis done as an above-the-line computation to produce their adjusted gross income. Taxpayers use AGI to calculate their limitations on certain deductions. So if AGI will be reduced by the capital-gains deduction, taxpayers will face a lower threshold for writing off miscellaneous and medical deductions, which are restricted to 2 percent and 7.5 percent, respectively, of AGI. If Congress makes the cut effective in 1996, says Johnson, taxpayers "may want to put off paying miscellaneous costs such as fees for investment advisory services, tax preparation, and elective medical costs until 1996, because they may get higher itemized deductions." <p> To take best advantage of a capital-gains cut, taxpayers must keep close track of their recognized (actual) and unrecognized (potential) gains and losses. Taxpayers "recognize" gains or losses when they sell or otherwise dispose of an asset; the date of disposal determines what tax year the gains and losses apply to.   <p> Shoving more capital gains into the long-term category, and picking the right holdings to sell, takes some work. Taxpayers who own various lots of the same security purchased at different prices can control the amount of gain or loss recognized on a sale by identifying the lots to be sold. If this isn't done in writing to the broker executing the sale, taxpayers will be considered to be selling the first lot they bought. If the stock has consistently appreciated, that lot will have appreciated the most and its sale will produce the greatest tax.   <p> Other lots of stock will produce different results. Selling a lot that hasn't been held for more than 12 months yields a short-term gain, usually the most expensive gain of all. Given the probable drop in the capital-gains rate, taxpayers might want to sell those lots in the long-term category that offer the least overall gain (after January 1, 1996, if a retroactive measure is not approved). When selling these shares, choose those in which the cost basis (the original cost plus out-of-pocket expenses, like broker commissions) is highest--this will shave the capital gains down as well.  <p> Regardless of a rate cut, there are several moves taxpayers can still make to reduce their 1995 capital-gains taxes. First, look for stock lemons on which to take a loss in 1995, say the tax gurus at the accounting firm KPMG Peat Marwick. Taxpayers can fully deduct net capital losses against capital gains, and if losses exceed gains, they can write off the excess dollar for dollar from ordinary income, up to a maximum of $3,000 in any one year. For example, a taxpayer with $10,000 in stock losses can offset $7,000 in capital gains and then deduct $3,000 of the losses from ordinary income.  <p> Net capital losses that exceed $3,000 can be carried forward indefinitely until they are exhausted. Capital losses carried over to future years should be first used to offset any short-term capital gains in that year, which might otherwise be taxed at higher rates.   <p> Taxpayers who have significant capital-gains income can also try a tax swap, but they need to be careful. Tax swaps involve dumping assets that are currently worth less than the original purchase price and replacing them with similar assets. This action converts a paper loss into an actual loss, which is used to offset taxable gains. However, if a taxpayer pulls the plug on an ailing security to create a loss, he or she cannot buy the same or what the IRS considers a "substantially identical" security within 30 days of the sale. Losses from such so-called wash sales are not deductible. Taxpayers who sell a stinker must wait at least 30 days after the original sale before purchasing the same security. <p> Bond swaps, though, can help reduce taxes without the 30-day wait, says Johnson, so long as investors buy slightly different bonds. Bond swaps work better than securities swaps because it's easier to find other bonds that have different characteristics, such as interest rates and maturity dates, but basically represent a comparable investment. Whether the value of a taxpayer's portfolio has increased or decreased this year, in a bond swap, taxpayers can recognize tax losses without altering their fundamental investment positions. Taxpayers can sell sufficient bonds to achieve a loss, which they can then use to reduce their total net capital gain for the year. They can use the proceeds of the sale to purchase bonds of similar quality, maintaining their desired position.  <p> Taxpayers can also try what's called selling short against the box. This strategy can be used to defer capital gains to the following tax year, an attractive strategy if a capital-gains cut takes effect next year. Taxpayers can lock in capital gains by short-selling borrowed securities equivalent to those they already own and then delivering their own securities to close the sale after year's end. In this manner, the gain is locked in this year but there's no taxation until 1996. Be aware, however,that this tactic limits the upside potential of the securities used to lock in the gain.  <p> Strategies like these can easily become too esoteric for taxpayers without degrees in accounting. The reasoning behind them, though, is based on simple rules that all taxpayers should abide by when doing their year-end tax planning: Realize income when the tax rate is low; lump together deductible expenses in one year to surpass tax thresholds; postpone tax whenever possible (taxes paid this year "cost" more than those paid next year); and finally, remember that a capital gain is, for the most part, better than ordinary income. These tenets are likely to remain valid no matter how the tax code is patched back together this time.   <p> ALSO NEW FOR 96  <p> Along with the capital-gains cut, tax pros at Deloitte & Touche, KPMG Peat Marwick, and Coopers & Lybrand say the $500 child-tax credit and an expanded IRA will likely pass. At press time, Senate Finance Republicans had greenlighted a $500 tax credit for each child under 18 in single-parent households earning up to $75,000 annually and two-income households earning less than $110,000. The House bill kicks the income limit up to $200,000. The fortified IRA would raise income limits and let all taxpayers, including nonworking spouses, invest a full tax-deferred $2,000. It would also allow penalty-free withdrawals to pay for items like medical or college expenses, or a first home. Another proposed savings account would allow taxpayers to withdraw interest tax-free after five years.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Taxation, Family Finance, Investment Strategies<p>

					</font>
