	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Keep the Faith</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Keep the Faith</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> KEEP THE FAITH <p>Foreign bonds may have taken a big hit recently, but they still offer high yields and diversification  <p> By Clint Willis  <p> Most U.S. investors have ignored international bonds for the past decade. Too bad: Overseas bonds outpaced domestic and foreign stocks as well as U.S. bonds during the five- and ten-year periods through last June. That run included strong gains early this year, when foreign issues stayed well ahead of U.S. bonds.  <p> This glittering record is largely the result of the prolonged slump of the dollar, which has fallen 9 percent versus the deutsche mark and 39 percent versus the yen in the past five years. That's made foreign bonds worth far more in dollar terms.   <p> But now some investors fear the dollar is reversing course. "Currencies in Germany, Japan, and Switzerland are overvalued against the dollar," says James Stack, editor of InvesTech Mutual Fund Advisor in Whitefish, Montana.   <p> Central bankers in the U.S., Germany, and Japan appear to agree with Stack--at least for the moment. In August, the bankers joined forces to push up the money, causing U.S. investors to lose 11.3 percent in Japanese bonds and 5 percent in German bonds.   <p> The central bankers have at least two reasons for pursuing this strategy. First, by making imports cheaper in the U.S., a stronger dollar reduces inflationary pressures here. Second, it increases exports for U.S. trading partners such as Japan. "The Japanese economy is in such bad shape that central bankers fear global growth could be affected," says Les Nanberg, manager of the <a name="FUND:MWGTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MWGTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MFS World Governments Fund</b></a>.  <p> Nevertheless, even if the dollar rally continues over the next six months or so, it probably won't last. The long-term outlook for foreign bonds may be brighter than it seems right now. Why? Because in the long run, the U.S. needs a weaker buck to encourage exports and thus correct--or at least control--the yawning U.S.trade deficit. Meanwhile, any setback in plans to reduce the budget deficit will hit the dollar hard. "A country cannot continue to run a balance-of-trade deficit and a high budget deficit without seeing its currency weaken," says Stack.   <p> Discord over European monetary unity should also boost the mark and the Swiss franc against the dollar. German officials recently expressed doubts that plans for a central European currency after 1999 will succeed. As a result, investors are flocking to those currencies from marginal European ones such as the Italian lira.  <p> Beyond short-term currency changes, investors who add foreign bonds to their holdings generally increase their returns while reducing the overall portfolio volatility. "Historically, bond markets in different regions tend to move in very different patterns from each other," says Nanberg.  <p> Overseas markets also offer bargains. "As more countries issue bonds, many overseas credits are mispriced," says Shirish Malekar, manager of the <a name="FUND:SIBVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SIBVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Strong International Bond Fund</b></a>. "If you do your homework, you can get significantly higher yields, without taking much more risk than you'd take with U.S. issues."   <p> Studies of asset performance show that investors who committed10 to 15 percent of their fixed-income holdings overseas in the past eight years got the best trade-off between risk and reward. But only trained international-bond analysts should buy individual securities. Most people should invest through professionally managed mutual funds.   <p> Avoid funds that use sophisticated hedging techniques to eliminatethe impact of currency fluctuations on their portfolios. "Hedging costs money that comes out of your return," says Malekar. "It also eliminates much of the diversification benefit that makes the bonds attractive."   <p> Choose funds that hedge little or not at all. Andrew Lohmeier, an analyst for Morningstar Inc. in Chicago, recommends <a name="FUND:RPIBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RPIBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price International Bond</b></a>, which rarely hedges. Its exposure to the U.S. dollar recently stood below 5 percent, and it leads foreign bond funds with a 12 percent five-year average annual return through September. More conservative investors should consider <a name="FUND:ICPHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ICPHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Franklin Templeton Hard Currency</b></a>, which invests in short-term bonds overseas and has less than 1 percent exposure to the dollar. The fund has not recorded a calendar year loss since its launch in 1989.  <p> MFS World Governments Fund (800-637-2929);  <p>Strong International Bond Fund (800-368-1030);  <p>T. Rowe Price International Bond (800-638-5660);  <p>Franklin Templeton Hard Currency (800-342-5236). <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Bond Investing, International Economy, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
