<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Retain Your Gain</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Retain Your Gain</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Retain Your Gain</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> RETAIN YOUR GAIN  <p> By Susan Lee  <p> Hey! it's perfectly normal. Who wouldn't be worried every time the stock market lurches down? At some point, of course, anxiety will turn into raw fear and you will decide to sell. If you are at that point now, I have a better suggestion: hedge.  <p> The virtue of this approach is twofold: You can protect some of your gains from a washout if the market does indeed tank, and you get to hold on to those little babies if the market makes new highs. The drawbacks--and they're nothing to sneeze at--are that hedging costs money, takes time, and requires a certain amount of attention.  <p> Given those drawbacks, review your stocks to determine whether the paper gains in your portfolio are large enough to justify the cost of hedging. For example, if you've been holding stocks since after the market crash in 1987, you'll likely have triple-digit gains--the market is up around 130 percent since then. If you've been holding since 1990, you'll probably have fat, double-digit gains--the market is up about 65 percent. Appreciation numbers like those are important enough to want to preserve. Also, realize that if you sell now, you'll lose 28 percent of your profit to taxes and that you'll be doubly aggrieved if Congress passes, as expected, a reduction in the long-term capital-gains tax toan effective rate of about 20 percent.   <p> Another consideration: What percent of your stock position do you want to hedge? If you think the market is only in for a 10 percent slide, then you don't really need to be guarding against utter calamity.  <p> Two popular ways of hedging a potential decline in the market are to sell call options and to buy put options. Let's first examine the strategy of selling call options; that is, selling the right to call away some of your shares. Say you sell a contract with an exercise price that reflects the current market value of your stock. If the stock price then falls, the buyer will let the option expire unused, because it makes no sense to buy your shares at a price that is now higher than the market price.The money you made on the sale of the option will cushion the loss in your actual stock. (Of course you will owe short-term capital-gains tax on your sale, but since you are not hedging your entire position and you still have considerable gains left in your actual shares, the comparative tax bite will be more like a nibble.)  <p> Such an outcome would certainly be attractive, and that's why selling call options is so appealing to investors--and to brokers. Unfortunately, these sales folks often neglect to mention the downside, which is pretty steep.   <p> What's that? Well, think about what will happen if things don't go as planned and the price of your stock actually goes up. Now, you are faced with the gloomy possibility of having your (now cheap) shares called away by an option buyer. In that case, you will not only lose your stock, you will be liable for the capital-gains tax. Not so attractive, after all, eh?  <p> One way around this problem is to tell your broker that if your option contract is exercised, you don't want one share of your inventory of existing stock touched, and that he or she should go into the market and buy fresh shares to settle your contract. This works under certain circumstances, but you'll have to pay a premium.   <p> Consider, too, another slightly trickier way: If you have big capital gains in a stock like <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, you could sell call options in another "proxy" stock that tends to move in tandem with  GM, like <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a>. Since you don't own Ford stock to cover the option, you'll be selling what's known as a "naked" call. Then, if the price of both stocks falls, you will at least be ahead the money from the option sale because the buyer will let it expire unexercised.   <p> If both GM and Ford go up, on the other hand, an option holder might wish to buy your (nonexistent) shares of Ford. Then you will have to go into the market and buy them at their increased price. This is expensive and unpleasant, granted, but not only will you get to keep your GM shares and keep your gains safe from taxes, your option position will have generated a short-term tax loss. And the (paper) appreciation of your GM shares will make you feel better about your option loss on Ford.  <p> The danger of course, is that GM could go down while Ford goes up. In that case, you will still have a short-term tax loss, but without the appreciation in GM to cheer you up--and that could be really unpleasant. Moreover, this strategy, while it may make you sound clever around the watercooler, really only works if you have just a few stocks with really big gains--you certainly don't want to root around searching for a bunch of proxy stocks to write naked options on.  <p> But maybe all of this call writing sounds too fancy, too sweaty-palms to bother with. If so, consider the comparatively vanilla strategy of buying put options on your stock; that is,  buying the right to put the shares to the seller. Since you are buying, rather than selling, a contract, you are out the cash initially.   <p> Again, assume for simplicity's sake that you purchase options around the current price of the stock. If your stock drops like a stone, your put options become valuable and you can sell them for cash (and for a higher price than you paid for them). That's the preferred approach, although you could exercise your options by buying the now-cheaper stock and putting it to the buyer at the higher option price.  <p> If, on the other hand, the price of your stock goes up, your puts will be worthless and you will allow them to expire unexercised. The loss on your puts will be cushioned by the appreciation of your actual shares.   <p> Buying puts, while admittedly less exciting than selling calls,would be my strategy of choice for two reasons. First, it carries only limited and known risk (the price you pay for the puts). Second, it ensures that you will retain your stock, allowing you to benefit from any future price increases and avoiding the immediate payment of the capital-gains tax.  <p> Okay, so far so good. But what if you have a well-diversified portfolio and are holding lots and lots of stocks? Selling calls or buying puts on each of them individually could require a great deal of time and attention. Indeed, it could take on the aspects of a rather pricey hobby. If that's the case, you may want to consider hedging a market fall with options on a stock market index. It's the same general idea, except that it is simpler and cheaper than using individual options, and since index options are settled in cash, you sidestep the danger of paying taxes on capital gains in your portfolio.  <p> Say you sell call options on the Standard & Poor's 100 index at about the current price of the index. If the market plunges, the buyer will let the option expire unexercised, and the money you made on the sale will cushion the loss in your stock portfolio. If the market spikes up, however, the buyer will require you to settle the option in cash--at a price that reflects the new, higher value of the index option. Your portfolio will have increased in value, but you will have lost money on your option.  <p> Buy puts on a stock market index, on the other hand, and you can exercise them for cash if the market tanks, thereby dampening your portfolio loss. Or, if the market moves up, you can let the put options expire worthless--but the money you lost on the options will limit the gains in your portfolio.  <p> As you have probably realized by now, using options is not forsissies. For starters, it requires investors to stay absolutely alert to what's happening in the market. You must not only be current on the price of your stock, but since most options run for three months, you have to pay attention to expiration dates in order to maintain your hedges. More important, although hedging will soften your losses if the market falls, the flip side is that it will dampen your gains if the market goes up.  <p> Susan Lee is an economist and a contributing editor to Worth. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

