<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-A Mug's Game</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-A Mug's Game</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Ignore the Wall Street swamis and your brother-in-law. Here's how to do your own economic forecasting.  <p>
 By Susan Lee  <p>
 Everybody but everybody knows that economic forecasting is a mug's game. Even the forecasting swamis know it. So why then do they continue to make predictions, why do business publications continue to run articles based on those predictions, and why oh why do we all keep reading them? Partly because every so often, mostly in a totally random way, a forecast will be correct. And, for investors, those chance occurrences become a form of entrapment. Think back: If, on October 15, 1987, your tea leaves had foreshadowed the following week's market crash, would you ever drink coffee again?  <p>
 Of course, most people face less dramatic circumstances. Consider: if you are sitting on a little pile of cash, you don't want to pump it into stocks just when economic growth is peaking and then, as company earnings slide, spend the next two years watching your capital diminish in a slow and sickening way while you listen to your stick-in-the-mud brother-in-law, who bought bonds, crow. Nope. You want to invest when the economy is at a bottom, not a top. Who doesn't?  <p>
 So short of reading the swamis or listening to your brother-in-law, what's a person to do? One harmless way to quench your thirst for prophecy is to make your own forecasts. Many people do watch their own personal indicators. I know one former member of the Fed who used to drive around suburban Detroit before Christmas, checking the parking lots of the big shopping malls. If the lots were packed, this was a favorable economic portent. Some rules to follow:  <p>
 Rule No. 1. Base your outlook on long-term trends. The economy--andits constituents--will always wobble around a trend. Wobbles happen weekly, monthly, and quarterly. Trends take place over a year or two. Wobble numbers are untrustworthy in two ways. First, they can be expressions of random occurrences rather than reflections of actual events. Second, the data can change as the government gets more complete numbers; figures that indicate whatever is being measured shot up in October may be revised in November to show that whatever was being measured actually slumped. Trust me: This happens all the time.  <p>
 Rule No. 2. Be alert to forces other than beltway politics. Currently, the fashionable way to forecast is to focus on what policy makers are doing in Washington. Witness the huge industry of Wall Street swamis who foretell the future by following Alan Greenspan's tennis game or listening to congressional tax debates. They volley back and forth--one week Greenspan is hailed as a master manipulator who is keeping growth on a steady climb, the next week he's guilty of pushing the economy over a cliff. One day the economy is said to be surging on the promise of tax cuts, the next day the economy is weakening ahead of those very same cuts.  <p>
 Sure, monetary and fiscal policies are important, but so are energy prices, the weather, labor strikes, the rate of growth in productivity, changing global trade flows, and so on. For any move made in D.C., there are half a dozen other forces that can nullify it. For example, the weather: Congress can cut thecapital-gains tax, but a boom from a surge in investment could be dampened by serious floods or a widespread drought that zooms food prices. And I haven't even mentioned really powerful forces like war and pestilence--or investors who get burned by a nation's sudden devaluation.  <p>
 I'm not saying Washington isn't worth paying attention to. Indeed,many of the factors that propel economic growth are now in place: energy prices and the rate of inflation are both on the low side and stable, productivity is up, and the benefits of NAFTA and the new GATT trade pacts beckon. Nonetheless, economic growth has been disappointing. Why? Because the big and potentially disruptive legislative agenda in Washington is creating a lot of uncertainty. And uncertainty dampens spending and investment.  <p>
 Rule No. 3. Don't ignore the consensus. You may need to know what it is in order to know what not to do. There are plenty of investors who owe their success to rejecting conventional wisdom. Since business publications usually declare a trend just when that trend taps out, watch them closely.  <p>
 Rule No. 4. Focus on several broad measures. Official Washington spews out hundreds of numbers that track economic health, but many are too narrow to be useful, especially when viewed alone. You could, for example, interest yourself in consumer spending, which is the biggest driver of economic activity, constituting two thirds of gross domestic product (the mother measure of thevalue of goods and services in the economy). That would mean keeping an eye on how much money consumers have to spend by looking at personal disposable (after-tax) income. You would also want to know how likely it is that consumers will spend their money, so you should factor in consumer confidence and unemployment rates. And, since folks are also inclined to borrow in order to spend, you should watch levels of consumer debt and interest rates on consumer credit.  <p>
 Thus, if income is strong, confidence high, unemployment under control, debts reasonable, and credit interest rates low, it's pretty even money that the economy will grow.  <p>
 Of course, the proof of the pudding is in the eating, so a nice exercise is to determine whether those indicators tracked the slowing of economic growth that occurred in the second quarter of this year.  <p>
 The Bureau of Economic Analysis, which is part of the Department of Commerce, publishes monthly figures on personal disposable income, unemployment rates, consumer debt, average bank primerates, and consumer sentiment. As the table above demonstrates, weakness was already apparent in April, the first month of the second quarter. Disposable income, which grew decently during the first three months of this year, shrank in April and didn't recover until June. Unemployment, which was moving down in the first quarter, bounced up. Meanwhile, the ratio of outstanding consumer credit to personal income also took a big step in the second quarter. The prime rate, on which many banks base variable credit-card rates, moved up in February and held its new higher level throughout the second quarter. Consumer optimism, which fell in February, had not recovered its January mark by June. Thus, if you had been tracking these monthly numbers, you would have known something was up (or down, in this case) well before the second quarter GDP figure confirmed it.  <p>
 Now, if your eyes are still tracking, you will be saying, "Wait! The author has ignored Rule No. 1 by focusing on wobbles, not long-term trends." And you would be right. My excuse is that I am following Rule No. 4 and looking at several variables as part of a broad category, and when all those numbers wobble in an unfavorable direction, it is reasonable to assume that something real and unpleasant is happening.  <p>
 In retrospect, we know that something real was happening because growth slowed from 2.7 percent in the first quarter to 1.1 percent in the second. But that begs another question: how can you tell if what you see is part of a trend? Well, you can't. You have been alerted to the possibility that the economy is at a turning point, but you won't know for sure until results for another quarter or two are logged. Which brings me to:  <p>
 Rule No. 5. Don't get too wedded to your own forecast. If something happens to throw your prognostications in doubt, be prepared to pull an about-face. As the seesawing swamis demonstrate, flexibility is essential. In other words, not only can you forecast to your heart's content, but the more you do it, the better your forecast will be.  <p>
Susan Lee is an economist and the author of the forthcoming book Hands Off: Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health (Simon & Schuster). She will write M.Y.O.B. monthly.   <p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends, Investment Strategies, Government, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

