	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Technical Analysis:  A Primer</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Technical Analysis:  A Primer</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Technical Analysis:  A Primer</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> TECHNICAL ANALYSIS: A PRIMER <p>What to buy, when to buy it, and when to sell it these are the basic questions facing every investor. The pros have two answers: fundamental and technical analysis.   <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> Fundamentalists scrutinize balance sheets, talk to chief financial officers, and evaluate product lines to predict a company's performance and, by extension, its stock price. Technicians, on the other hand, don't care whether a company builds cars or roasts coffee or whether its bottom line is red or black. Instead, they use historical statistics of investor supply and demand to extrapolate future stock-price patterns. "I can put my feet up on my desk while all the analysts are out there digging away because I don't need to know what the story is," says Justin Mamis, chief market technician at Hancock Institutional Equity Services in New York." All I care about is how people feel about those particular stocks as shown by their putting money in and taking their money out." <p> Few people are as faithful to a single approach; most market professionals use both fundamental and technical analysis daily and recommend that amateurs do the same. "The individual has to use them both in common," says Edward Nicoski, director of technical research at Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis. "Because the market is an anticipatory device, you're typically going to see the turns in stocks more quickly looking at charts than by being a fundamentalist and reading the front page. However, if there's really something fundamentally wrong that nobody knows about yet, the chart's not going to help you."  <p> Entire books have been written on the subject of technical analysis, and some people spend their lives learning the trade, but there is a basic core of information and tools accessible and intelligible to the individual stock picker and 401(k) participant that no investor should be without.  <p> Technical analysis dates back to the rice markets of 17th-century Japan. It tries to reduce the apparently random character of markets to statistical patterns predictive of future price trends among individual stocks, industry sectors, and market averages (it also applies in other markets, such as bonds, currencies, and commodities). The technician's premise, say Robert D. Edwards and John Magee in Technical Analysis of Stock Trends, the industry's bible, is that "prices move in trends and trends tend to continue until something happens to change the supply-demand balance." <p> While the ultimate goal of technical analysis is to identify changes in the direction of stocks, Mamis notes that investors don't need to pick the absolute highs and lows to make a lot of money. "If you've made a Faustian pact with the devil to get out within 10 percent of the high all the time, that's all you need," he says.  <p> CHART WORSHIP <p>The technician's most important tool is the chart, which allows him or her to identify trends and patterns in a single stock or average, as well as to compare the two.  There are three ways to graphically represent stock-price movement.  The familiar line chart uses one number usually the closing price to reflectthe day's price movement. The bar chart, perhaps the most frequently used, shows the high, low, and closing prices within a given time frame, usually a day, week, or month. Most bar charts also include corresponding trading volumes along the bottom.  <p> Both of these charts plot the price at specific time intervals, whether or not prices have changed. The third type of chart, the point-and-figure chart, records a price only when it fluctuates by a predetermined amount, usually one point or more. Upward movements are plotted using the letter x, while downward movements are denoted by the letter o. This is a good way to track price momentum, but since point-and-figure charts disregard time and volume and are difficult to interpret, professionals recommend that amateur investors focus on lines and bars.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
