<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Dowsing Water Utility Stocks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Dowsing for Water Utility Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Dowsing Water Utility Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995   <p>Worth  magazine/Advisor  <p> DOWSING FOR WATER UTILITY STOCKS  <p> By Nick Ravo  <p> When industry analysts talk about the stodgy world of utility stocks, they usually mean electricity producers or natural gas distributors. But there is a tiny subsector of utilities that virtually escapes Wall Street's notice: water companies. You practically need a dowsing rod to find them in the financial pages.  <p> "Many people don't even know about them because they are so few in number and most are very small regional operations," says Steven D. Seibel, editor of Water Investment Newsletter in Halstead, Kansas, which follows the industry. "They're not glamorous, either, even by utility standards."  <p> There are roughly 59,000 water systems in the United States, collecting, treating, and selling water to residential and commercial users. Almost all of them are owned by municipalities or private investors. Seventeen, however, mostly in California and the Northeast, are publicly traded and are, as the saying goes, generally considered safe enough for widows and orphans. United Water Resources in Harrington Park, New Jersey, for example, has paid dividends every year since 1886. The Middlesex Water Co. of Iselin, New Jersey, has been selling water since 1897.  <p> The median dividend yield on water stocks is 6.5 percent, versus 6.6 percent for electricity stocks (and 2.4 percent for the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index), but they are the most stable of all utilities because they attract little institutional interestand hence rarely trade in large blocks. (The average beta, a measure of market volatility, is 0.4 for the water industry, 0.6 for electric utilities, and 1.0 for the S&P 500.)  <p> "These are stable long-term stocks for income-oriented investors and perhaps also for people who feel the market is too high and who are looking for something defensive," says J.C. Whitfield, publisher of Whitfield's Utilities Letter in Houston. "You're not going to be making a quick buck here.  <p> That doesn't mean growth-seeking investors should ignore these companies. "If you look at the total return the share-price growth and the dividend some of these companies have done really, really well and with little risk," says Robin M. Rather of St. Louis brokerage Edward D. Jones & Co. She is one of the few water-stock analysts in the nation.  <p> Rather notes that the total return of Voorhees, New Jersey­based American Water Works, the nation's largest investor-owned water utility with 1.7 million customers in 21 states, has averaged12.7 percent annual growth over the last five years. This utility has expanded rapidly of late, Rather says, and so might other water companies, as rising costs and tougher water-quality standards force municipalities to leave the business to the nimbler, more entrepreneurial private firms. She also sees United Water Resources and Philadelphia Suburban Corp., based in Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania, as good growth candidates.  <p> "The water industry also looks like something of a safe haven in the utilities sector because of volatile natural gas pricesand with electric utilities' concerns over nuclear-power decommissioning costs and competition because of deregulation," says Rather. <p> In addition, investors can boost their returns in many water stocks by buying shares (at discounts of up to 5 percent) through shareholder-investment and dividend-reinvestment plans. (See "The Poor Man's Arbitrage," July/August, for more on discount direct-purchase plans.)  <p> The risk with these stocks is a sharp rise in interest rates. Indeed, when the Federal Reserve Board upped rates six times in1994, the total return for the 14 stocks that compose the Edward D. Jones Water Utility Index was minus 6.8 percent, compared with minus 7.9 percent for the Standard & Poor's Utility Index. <p> If interest rates stay put or drop in 1995, however, share prices of water utilities should increase. Utility stocks have historically risen about 15 percent for each percentage-point decrease ininterest rates.  <p> Weather, too, can affect a water company's earnings; either too much or too little rain can dampen profits. Environmental regulations, which usually cause costs to rise, are also of some concern. There is little price competition in the industry, however, and demand for the product is growing. Perhaps more important, rising demand can almost be taken for granted, a situation not found in most industries. As J.C. Whitfield puts it, "Water is in many ways more important than oil."  <p> So far this year, with one rate increase and one decrease by the Federal Reserve, most water utility stocks have risen. AmericanWater Works has led the way; as of August 9, its share price was up 11.5 percent in 1995.  <p> Nick Ravo is a reporter at The New York Times. He can be reached by E-mail at nravo@aol.com.  <p>  <hr>   <p> Company      5-year return* <p>  <p>Offering Direct Purchse Plan  <p> <a name="NYSE:AWK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10104"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Water Works</b></a> (NYSE: AWK)  18.6 <p>609-346-8200 <p><a name="OTC:CTWS"></a><b>Connecticut Water Service</b> (OTC: CTWS)  14.4 <p>203-669-8636 <p><a name="OTC:IWCR"></a><b>IWC Resources</b> (OTC: IWCR)     11.4 <p>317-639-1501 <p><a name="NYSE:PSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11178"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philadelphia Suburban Corp.</b></a> (NYSE: PSC)  13.7 <p>215-527-8000 <p><a name="NYSE:UWR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11561"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Water Resources</b></a> (NYSE: UWR)   7.6 <p>201-767-2811  <p> Not Offering Direct Purchase Plan  <p> <a name="NYSE:WTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Aquarion</b></a> (NYSE: WTR)     7.6 <p><a name="OTC:ARTN"></a><b>Artesian Resources</b> (OTC:ARTN)   N/A <p><a name="NYSE:CWT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12878"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>California Water Service</b></a> (NYSE: CWT)  9.8 <p><a name="OTC:CONW"></a><b>Consumers Water</b> (OTC: CONW)   11.0 <p><a name="OTC:DOMZ"></a><b>Dominguez Services</b> (OTC: DOMZ)   6.0 <p><a name="NYSE:ETW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13251"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>E'Town Corp.</b></a> (NYSE: ETW)    10.7 <p><a name="OTC:MSEX"></a><b>Middlesex Water Co.</b> (OTC: MSEX)   12.7 <p><a name="OTC:PNNW"></a><b>Pennichuck Corp.</b> (OTC: PNNW)   N/A <p><a name="AMEX:SJW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12296"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SJW Corp.</b></a> (AMEX: SJW)    13.3 <p><a name="NYSE:SCW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14756"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>So. California Water</b></a> (NYSE: SCW)   11.3 <p><a name="OTC:SWWC"></a><b>Southwest Water</b> (OTC: SWWC)   -7.8 <p><a name="OTC:YORW"></a><b>York Water Co.</b> (OTC: YORW)    N/A  <p> * Annualized. Source: Edward D. Jones & Co., DRIP Investor. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
